</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPEECH-1STLD-WRITETHRUHRU-ART-TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARING THE SPEECH OF HIS LIFE, GORE WROTE, AIDES WHITTLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs with additional quotes/details and general smoothing
throughout; story grows by about 250 words and is now 2 takes)  
 (ART ADV: Photos CVN9 through 22 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Al Gore sat down at his laptop to write _ no
pressure, but everyone said it had better be the speech of his life
_ he began by raiding some of his favorite speeches past, culling
some material that had been written for him and some of his own
stuff, like the eulogy he wrote for his father's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   He threw in everything he might even conceivably want to mention
_ 12,000 words in all, then let his speechwriters edit and polish,
tinker and tweak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in the speech reflects what he wanted in the
speech, if you know what I mean,'' said his top consultant, Carter
Eskew, one of three aides who helped edit Gore's acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   The top-down approach is not only the perfect reflection of the
way Gore operates, but the mirror image of the way his Republican
opponent, Gov. George W. Bush, worked on his recent acceptance
speech. Bush, as is far more typical of presidential nominees, left
the writing to the professionals and then fiddled with the text,
asking for certain changes and adding some personal touches.
</P>
<P>
   That Gore would make the highly unusual decision to write his
own words surprised no one who knows him well. After all, he wrote
his own book, ``Earth in the Balance,'' and before running for
office was a reporter for The Tennessean in Nashville, where his
former editors fondly recall having to tear copy out of his hands
as he kept right on reporting past deadline, never satisfied that
he had all the information.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday afternoon, he was still asking his staff for
documents he might want to draw from.
</P>
<P>
   For such an important speech, Bush put his writers through 17
drafts.
</P>
<P>
   But a few hours before Gore was to deliver his address, an aide,
Laura Quinn, joked, ``It's in draft 625'' _ and not necessarily in
final form even then.
</P>
<P>
   Of this much, though, Quinn was positive: ``It won't be short,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore's first draft ran 12,000 words, he never intended to
deliver a speech of that length, Eskew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process was to gather a lot more material than he knew he
could use,'' Eskew said. ``He enjoys the editing process, and
that's how he likes to work. That helps him decide what's
essential.''
</P>
<P>
   What was essential? He wanted to explain why he is running and
what he has learned from listening to voters, and told several
stories of people he had met in the last year, like a parent who
lost a child at the school massacre in Columbine, Colo., and
whispered in his ear, ``Promise me that these children will not
have died in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to introduce himself with some good biographical
stories, telling about how his father, Sen. Albert Gore, grew up
poor in Possum Hollow, Tenn., and after living through the
Depression ``entered public service to fight for the people, not
the powerful.'' And how his mother, Pauline LaFon Gore, put herself
through law school waiting tables in an all-night coffee shop. Yet
he also wanted to get into policy details that he thought Americans
ought to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does love to talk about policy and specifics,'' said Gore's
oldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, ``and he has the attitude
that if people don't like that they should still know that's what
they're getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also felt strongly that he wanted to use the speech to look
to the future. ``He didn't just want to talk about the successes of
the administration,'' Schiff said. ``He thinks people are not as
interested in hearing what he did as vice president as they are in
hearing what he would do'' if elected.
</P>
<P>
   After taking his initial, 12,000-word crack at the speech, he
handed a computer disk with that first draft on it to a consultant,
Robert Shrum, and a speechwriter, Eli Attie, who whittled it to
7,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took that version with him on his recent vacation in North
Carolina. He kept putting various chunks that his aides had taken
out back in _ again in contrast to Bush's impulse to pare down his
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to include a foreign policy section,'' for example,
Eskew said. ``Some of us felt that might be a place to cut, but he
said it's an important part of the job and I want to talk about it
and explain how the threats facing our country have changed over
the last 20 years. That's very much him.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked, recently, whether he regretted anything he had
written in ``Earth in the Balance,'' a book that proposed phasing
out the internal combustion engine, and has been widely parodied,
he said he still regretted some sections that were edited out.
</P>
<P>
   As a senator, he not only wrote his own op-ed pieces, but in the
early 1980s once turned up at the office of The New York Times and
announced, ``I pulled an all-nighter on this one,'' and hung over
an editor's shoulder as his piece on arms control was being edited.
</P>
<P>
   Where he did make cuts in his acceptance speech, though, was in
streamlining wording that speechwriters had inserted that did not
feel comfortable for him. His aides, for example, had come up with
the line, ``We're for the people; they're for the powerful.'' His
team wanted him to repeat the line about a half-dozen times
throughout the address.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not feel right to him, he told his team. Eskew
said, ``He said, `Well, that's true, but I only need to say it
once.' Ms. Schiff said he also took out a number of anecdotes that
he has been using on the campaign trail. ``He scrapped that,'' she
said. ``He wanted it to be fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
