u p BC-GORE-SPEECH-1STLD-WRI     08-18 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPEECH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: be fresh.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the final version, he quoted his high school headmaster:
``Sometimes, you have to be willing to spend your popularity in
order to pick the hard right over the easy wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He was self-deprecating, as he often is in private, saying, ``If
you entrust me with the presidency, I know I won't always be the
most exciting politician.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked in one of the fun facts he loves, mentioning that
``there is more computer power in a Palm Pilot than in the
spaceship that took Neil Armstrong to the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   And, voicing his personal reaction to the discussion of honor
that he heard at the Republican convention, he talked about his own
definition of honor: ``Getting cigarettes out of the hands of kids
before they get hooked is a family value . . . A new prescription
drug benefit under Medicare for all our seniors, that's a family
value.'' His second daughter, Kristin, who works as a comedy
writer, contributed a joke at the last minute, not a side-splitter
but a play on words on why he opposes a Republican-size tax cut:
``You would get 62 cents in change, but that's not the change I'm
seeking in America.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his youngest daughter, Sarah, who will be a senior at
Harvard in the fall, who of all his family worked most closely with
him on the speech, and spent much of the family vacation helping
him edit and rewrite.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did practice his speech the last couple of days before he
was to deliver it, trying parts of it out on his family, members of
his staff and that of his wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday afternoon, Eskew said the speech _ now down to
5,700 words, about 1,800 more than Bush's _ was finally more or
less finished, except for ``a few little word things.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew insisted that Gore did not feel pressured by expectations
and the perception among some pundits that he had to hit a homerun
to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a speech he's been waiting to give for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
