<HEADLINE>
GORE ASKS VOTERS TO PLACE NATION'S FUTURE IN HIS HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seizing the moment that could make or break his
presidential ambitions, Al Gore asked skeptical voters Thursday to
place the nation's future in his hands, assuring them that ``I
stand here tonight as my own man'' and promising a path to a
``better, fairer, more prosperous America.''
</P>
<P>
   The 50-minute speech, in which Gore accepted his party's
nomination and brought the Democratic National Convention to a
rousing climax, was universally viewed as the most important of
Gore's life. It offered the vice president a unique opportunity to
imprint himself _ and his policies _ on voters who remain
unimpressed by his candidacy, to declare his independence from
President Clinton and to gain ground on front-running Republican
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who high-fived cheering delegates as he walked through the
packed convention floor to the podium to begin his speech, wasted
no time. He painted himself as an experienced leader who is the
best choice for protecting the nation's galloping economy,
improving education, expanding health care and protecting Social
Security, while restoring values and ensuring that the less
advantaged are not left behind.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to spend more money to find a cure for cancer,
finance the hiring of 50,000 police officers and pass campaign
finance reform and hate crimes legislation. And underscoring one of
the biggest differences between himself and Bush, Gore said: ``Let
there be no doubt: I will protect and defend a woman's right to
choose,'' drawing some of the loudest and most prolonged cheers of
the speech.
</P>
<P>
   With his 87-year-old mother, Pauline, wife, Tipper, and children
looking on, the 52-year-old Gore cloaked himself as a populist.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so here tonight, in the name of all the working families
who are the strength and soul of America _ I accept your nomination
for president of the United States,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to talk seriously about the issues. I believe people
deserve to know specifically what a candidate proposes to do. I
intend to tell you tonight. You ought to be able to know, and then
judge for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech laden with policy details, partisan jabs, personal
asides but few rhetorical flourishes, Gore promised to advance
limited tax cuts, to protect the environment and to improve the
quality of life for time-stressed workers.
</P>
<P>
   If elected president, Gore promised, he would stay connected to
the nation by ``holding open meetings in the places (people) live
and work. ... I'm going to go out to you, the people, because I
want to stay in touch with your hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   And he mocked the centerpiece of Bush's campaign _ a major tax
cut _ as fiscally ill-advised and unfair to all but the wealthiest.
``Let me say it plainly,'' Gore pledged, ``I will not go along with
a huge tax cut for the wealthy at the expense of everyone else and
wreck our good economy in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, let's make sure that our prosperity enriches not
just the few, but all working families. Let's invest in health
care, education, a secure retirement and middle-class tax cuts,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore's attempts to present a more personal side may have
succeeded, his effort to escape Clinton was more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that ran 13 pages, Gore mentioned Clinton by name
only once.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's presence was tangible. Only hours before Gore
stepped onto the stage at the Staples Center came news that
independent counsel Robert Ray has impaneled a new grand jury to
hear evidence against Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reacted quickly and bluntly to the report,
dismissing the probe and questioning the timing. ``The timing of
this leak reeks to high heaven,'' White House spokesman Jake
Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Clinton committed perjury or obstructed
justice when he denied an affair in sworn testimony in the Paula
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, Gore cast himself as a devoted father and an
unfailing friend of working families who will stand as a barrier
between them and the monied interests favored by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the difference in this election. They're for the
powerful, and we're for the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big tobacco, big oil, the big polluters, the pharmaceutical
companies, the HMO's. Sometimes you have to be willing to stand up
and say no _ so families can have a better life,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So often, powerful forces and powerful interests stand in your
way, and the odds seemed stacked against you _ even as you do
what's right for you and your family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How and what we do for all of you _ the people who pay the
taxes, bear the burdens and live the American dream _ that is the
standard by which we should be judged. And for all of our good
times, I am not satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has served as vice president for the past eight
years, Gore portrayed himself as an underdog who will safeguard the
interests and future of Middle America, proclaiming that his
``focus is on working families'' who often feel powerless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know this,'' Gore said to an adoring and
overflow crowd in the Staples Center and the millions more watching
on TV. ``I've taken on the powerful forces. And as president, I'll
stand up to them, and I'll stand up for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was preceded on stage by his wife, Tipper, who introduced
him as ``a decisive leader with strong values, deeply held
convictions, and an unwavering commitment to making the American
dream a reality for all our people.''
</P>
<P>
   There also were testimonials from friends and family members and
a 13-minute film of his life, tracing his path as a child born in
Tennessee to his Army tour in Vietnam through his early career as a
newspaper reporter and a politician.
</P>
<P>
   The segment was designed to add depth and color to Gore's image,
to present him as an everyday guy who is little different from the
average American and not a stiff, distant, waffling politician.
</P>
<P>
   One of the testimonials came from Jim Frush, a Seattle attorney
and mountain climber who guided Gore and his son Albert to the
summit of Mount Rainier last summer in extraordinarily harsh
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough climb,'' Frush told the Democrats. Temperatures
dipped into the 20s, and much of the mountain was shrouded in near
white-out conditions. But, Frush said, Gore ``was grace under
pressure and perseverance. ... Al was our spark plug on that climb.
... I'd follow him anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the glowing praise, Gore admitted, ``I know my own
imperfections. I know that sometimes people say I'm too serious,
that I talk too much substance and policy. Maybe I've done that
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the presidency is more than a popularity contest,'' he
said. ``It's a day-by-day fight for people. Sometimes, you have to
choose to do what's difficult or unpopular. Sometimes, you have to
be willing to spend your popularity in order to pick the hard right
over the easy wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore delivered the speech trailing Bush by about 10 points in
most polls and with his campaign struggling to find a chord that
will energize the undecided voters that will determine the
election.
</P>
<P>
   He structured his speech to address issues important to them and
to amplify the centrist positions that those voters are most likely
to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it will work remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   But he reminded voters, ``The power should be in your hands. The
future should belong to everyone in this land. We could squander
this moment _ but our country would be the poorer for it. Instead,
let's lift our eyes, and see how wide the American horizon has
become.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Gore left with vice presidential nominee Joe Lieberman
for Wisconsin, where they are to begin a campaign boat trip down
the Mississippi River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
