<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-GORE-REACT-1STLD-     08-18 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, CENTER STAGE AT LAST, REVELS IN EMBRACE OF CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs grafs 4, 5, 7 and 10 for wording changes; adds 9 grafs at
end)  
 (Eds.: This is now an added starter on N.Y. Times Page 1)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Bill Clinton's backstage walk to valediction on
Monday was a heavyweight champion's last indulgent moment in the
sun, Al Gore's arrival in the Staples Center on Thursday night was
a dogged contender's first chance to enter the arena alone. He
strode through a sea of pennants down a side aisle with a posse of
seconds trailing humbly in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Gore had climbed the gray-carpeted steps of the
podium and wrapped his wife, Tipper, in a sweeping embrace and a
long kiss, the giant arena was shaking as if in a California
earthquake, strobe lights flickered, tears streaked delegates'
faces, and the crowd was utterly his.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking unusually quickly (faster, one of his writers said,
than he ever did in rehearsals), confidently, even ebulliently at
times, Gore seemed determined to shake the plodding pace and tone
of condescension that often mark his formal speeches. He virtually
raced through a litany of causes and issues dear to the core
Democratic constituencies, from health care to civil rights,
affirmative action, public education, and abortion rights, with
perhaps the biggest applause line of all that ``the last thing this
country needs is a Supreme Court that overturns Roe vs. Wade.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of loyal service to a consummate, intuitive
political performer, Mr. Gore left no doubt from the start tonight
that he was determined to present himself without Mr. Clinton's
shadow darkening his center stage. When he said, ``I stand here
tonight as my own man, and I want you to know me for who I truly
am,'' his young speechwriter, Eli Attie, and his image-meister,
Carter Eskew, watching from just below the podium, slapped a
high-five in satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 minutes later, at the end of his speech, Gore even
found his own formulation of Clinton's 1992 pledge to stay with the
voters of New Hampshire until the ``last dog dies,'' by vowing:
``If you entrust me with the presidency, I know I won't always be
the most exciting politician. But I pledge to you tonight: I will
work for you every day and I will never let you down.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast with the disappointment that Clinton's personal
conduct has caused Democrats was unspoken, but perfectly clear.
</P>
<P>
   But as they climbed the aisles to the press section afterwards,
Gore's aides took particular satisfaction at the way he had defined
his identity and delineated his argument for election, by saying:
``This election is not an award for past performance. I'm not
asking you to vote for me on the basis of the economy we have.
Tonight, I ask for your support on the basis of the better, fairer,
more prosperous America we can build together.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's aides also expressed surprise that Gore had
finished his speech far faster than in any of his repeated
rehearsals with a teleprompter.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, for a candidate with proven skill at cut-and-thrust,
Gore made not a single direct mention of his Republican opponent,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, and very few indirect ones.
</P>
<P>
   About the closest he came to a direct attack was his vow to
fight against tax cuts for the wealthy, and fight for prescription
drug benefits for the elderly. ``And that's the difference in this
election,'' he said. ``They're for the powerful, and we're for the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a convention week in which conventional wisdom held
that Gore needed to knock one out of the park Thursday night. Only
time will tell how he touched the television audience, which
matters the most, but many delegates here, perhaps in reflection of
the glittery, giddy high of the moment, said he had done just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my gosh, I was moved to tears _ I'm so proud of him,''
said Dianna Johnson, a delegate from Virginia who grew up in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Whalen, a Massachusetts delegate, said: ``He kept right on
the issues, and the issues are what will help him win in November.
His style was great. He absolutely was not wooden. As Tiger Woods
would say, he brought his A game.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Hale, a longtime Clinton aide who came back this season
to help manage the convention for Gore, flashed a thumbs-up sign as
she passed journalists on deadline. ``I think he showed his own
persona,'' she said, ``and he told his own story and he said it
clearly and with emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, as star-shaped mylar balloons, and red, white and
blue rubber ones, and gold and silver confetti fired from air
cannons filled the air, the newly minted nominee was joined on
stage by a pantheon of the Democratic family, winners and losers,
past and present alike, from his primary rival, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, to John J. Sweeney, the president of the AFL-CIO. When
Gore finally made his way through the tunnel off the speaker's
platform, delegates were straining to shake his hand or snap his
picture, and a new aura surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   From late afternoon on, the energy in the hall had built
steadily. Souvenir stands that were all but deserted on Wednesday
suddenly had long lines. Aisles that had been passable were filled
to overflowing. Air-conditioning that had been icy seemed just a
bit less cold. By 5:30 p.m., the stage was groaning with a gaggle
of party leaders and dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Gore's daughter Kristin introduced his wife an hour
later, there was pandemonium. Mickey Hart, the old Grateful Dead
drummer, beat a tom-tom on stage, and Mrs. Gore, radiant in powder
blue, shook and boogied, clapped and high-fived. What seemed like
an ocean of round red, white and blue signs reading ``Tipper
Rocks'' bobbed in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore, an accomplished amateur photographer, narrated
pictures from a family album interspersed in a video that paid
tribute to Gore's service in Vietnam, his journalistic career and
his virtues as a family man. She concluded over stirring music,
``To me, for all the past accomplishments and future promises, he's
still the man I fell in love with in high school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
