<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA DENIES REPORT DODGERS FIRED HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia strongly denied
a story in Thursday's Los Angeles Times which cited unnamed sources
in the Los Angeles Dodgers organization who claimed he was fired
after managing at Triple-A Albuquerque last season.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone fired
Scioscia ``because his staff didn't think he could manage.'' The
report also quoted Malone saying Scioscia wanted to be at the
major-league level but they didn't have room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true,'' Scioscia said. ``I was not fired and I did
not ask for a spot on the major-league staff. I had meetings with
(assistant GM) Bill Geivett and Kevin Malone, really long-range as
to what my role in the organization would be and what my input
would be. But there couldn't be any clear-cut plan because they
were still in transition. The organization was still being
reshaped.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers announced that Scioscia resigned during the first
week of September, right after he guided the Dukes to a 65-74
record in the Pacific Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I know what happened,'' he said. ``I resigned to pursue
opportunities I knew would be out there. . . . I don't know where
the perception (he was fired) came from. The first week of
September my feeling was this gives me a jump on other positions
and allowed me to lay the groundwork for getting this job.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Pitching update: Troy Percival (inflamed elbow), Seth
Etherton (shoulder tendinitis) and Jarrod Washburn (stress fracture
in shoulder) all played catch Thursday and were encouraged by their
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today he gave it an enthusiastic thumbs up,'' Scioscia said of
Percival. ``It's not like he stepped it up to any appreciable level
to say, hey, he's ready to get on the mound. But the sensations he
had before are not there and that's encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Etherton is eligible to come off the DL on Sunday. The club
didn't expect him back by then, but Etherton hopes to show them
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great,'' he said. ``I can come off in four days.
Hopefully I can make sure they know I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn's recovery is monitored by the pain he feels, and
Thursday he said he felt no pain.
</P>
<P>
   __ Back in the lineup: Tim Salmon was in the lineup Thursday,
one day after being hit on the left thumb by a line drive hit by
Troy Glaus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
