r f BC-POLITICAL-PRODUCTS-KA     08-18 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-PRODUCTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN FINDS SUCCESS SELLING POLITICAL PRODUCTS ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHVILLE, Mo. _ The speeches have been delivered, the confetti
swept away, the lights dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   Now the stumping begins in earnest for presidential candidates
Al Gore and George W. Bush, their running mates and their
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   And John and Jane Q. Public _ itching to trumpet their loyalty
for their candidate on a T-shirt, button or bumper sticker _ can
click onto www.politicalshop.com, which sells a wide array of
political products.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site is an outgrowth of one started by Sharon Clemons of
Smithville in 1996. The year before, she got her first taste of the
Internet and was in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is one of the most earth-shattering things
developed in the last century, and I think it will continue to be
well into this century,'' Clemons said. ``It is just so
fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   PoliticalShop.com is an outgrowth of an entrepreneurial class
that Clemons took in 1992 while pursuing a master's degree in
business administration at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to come up with something where you start your own
business, so I started selling novelty items, souvenirs and
political items, and I've never stopped,'' Clemons said.
</P>
<P>
   So caught up was Clemons in her venture that she never returned
to finish her MBA, which she regrets.
</P>
<P>
   But selling political buttons, T-shirts, bumper stickers, coffee
mugs and more has kept her busy.
</P>
<P>
   After her first foray into the world of Web sites connected
through technology, Clemons set up shop on the Internet. Along the
way, she registered Web site domain names, including AlGore.com,
Gore2000.com and variations thereof.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Clemons got a call from Gore's staff. Could Gore, they
asked, get the AlGore.com and Gore2000.com domain names?
</P>
<P>
   After haggling over a price for the names, Clemons gave the vice
president AlGore.com but kept the others for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Clemons said Gore's camp offered less than five figures, while
she thought the names were worth nothing less than six figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we just ended up giving it to him,'' Clemons said.
``After all, Al Gore is his name, but we felt we had a right to
keep {www.gore2000.com} because we were speculating a long time ago
he was going to run. We'd been selling Gore items since 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Gore, who once said he invented the Internet, wasn't
too on top of snagging domain names. In the end, she cut him some
slack. After all, she said, she is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But she said her site is strictly nonpartisan. There are as many
Bush-Cheney items as there are Gore-Lieberman ones.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she was a bit worried about the expected drop-off
in business after the election but that she immediately will begin
a Campaign 2004 push and branch out into other areas. That includes
an eBay auction-type site for which Clemons has registered the name
PoliticalAuction.com. Her current site sells political
paraphernalia going back to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Clemons' personal favorites on PoliticalShop.com are Ella the
elephant and Demi the donkey, plush collectibles she spent more
than a year designing. They can be bought separately or in a set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them the most because they're collectible, like Beanie
Babies, and they're, well, just cute,'' Clemons said.
</P>
<P>
   Each come with hangtags with sayings such as ``I promise to work
my tail off,'' ``I promise to keep my nose clean'' and ``I won't
take you for a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemons said many of the Web sites offering political
paraphernalia are partisan, although there are direct competitors
such as PoliticalGifts.com.
</P>
<P>
   She said her site was getting about 1 million different visitors
each month. Many of those visitors click on from overseas, Europe
and Asia in particular.
</P>
<P>
   She said the site generates revenue of more than six figures
each year and is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wouldn't want to say how far into the six figures for
competitive reasons,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And the best seller on the site?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Clemons said, ``that would have to be the T-shirts
that say, `Read My Lips _ No New Texans.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
