<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-1STL     08-18 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PANEL PROBES LEWINSKY AFFAIR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Editors: tightens and updates 
 
By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Robert Ray has impaneled a
federal grand jury to review President Clinton's efforts to conceal
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, raising howls from Democrats about
a political sneak attack on the day Al Gore accepted the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury was sworn in more than a month ago, sources
outside the independent counsel's office said. The panel is
positioned to help Ray fulfill a promise to announce, once Clinton
leaves office, whether he can be indicted on charges of perjury or
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who replaced Clinton nemesis Kenneth Starr last October,
has quietly continued the investigation into the president's affair
with Lewinsky, at the center of his impeachment by the House and
subsequent acquittal by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of the leak of this information reeks to high
heaven,'' said White House spokesman Jake Siewert. ``But given
their (the independent counsel's office) track record on this, it
is hardly surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   As Vice President Gore was preparing to give perhaps the most
important speech of his political career Thursday evening, his
staff reacted angrily to the reports of the resurrection of
scandals plaguing the administration in which he is top deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is highly suspect,'' said Doug Hattaway, a Gore
spokesman. ``People are sick and tired of the judicial system being
manipulated for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Hattaway added, Gore was not concerned that the reports
might mar his acceptance speech. ``We believe the voters are
focused on the future.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Gore's November opponent, George W. Bush's campaign
spokesman Ray Sullivan said, ``Americans are sick and tired of
investigations and scandals. The best way to change the tone in
Washington is to change the administration in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's office refused to confirm that a grand jury had
been impaneled, but at the same time denied any link to reports
that a grand jury was meeting. ``The source of these reports is not
within the office of the independent counsel,'' said Lynda Flippin,
spokeswoman for Ray.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as this spring, Ray said he had not ruled out
indicting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Legal bombshells dropping near important political events are
not new in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Iran-Contra independent counsel Lawrence Walsh
issued an amended indictment of Caspar Weinberger, President Bush's
defense secretary, on the weekend before the 1992 election. It was
the first indictment in the scandal to make specific references to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's political advisers pounced on that and within hours of
the indictment issued a statement headlined: ``New Iran-Contra
Evidence Released By Prosecutor Shows Bush Flatly Lied.'' Bush
loyalists claimed the court filing halted his momentum before the
1992 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But some Clinton advisers and friends think that Thursday's leak
could actually end up helping Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is no doubt this leak is designed to deprive Al
Gore of his moment tonight, but you know what, I think it will
boomerang,'' said Lanny Davis, a former Clinton administration
official.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six months, Ray's office has issued statements
noting the hiring of several new attorneys and assistants in his
office, indicating that at least some aspects of the Clinton case
had not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Ray has been in Nova Scotia on vacation for several days and was
out of touch with his staff during the critical hours before
initial reports of the new grand jury, associates said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a panel of federal judges overseeing independent
counsel investigations reauthorized Ray's inquiry for another year.
In a brief statement, the judges said it is ``not currently
appropriate'' to end the investigation begun in 1994 into Clinton
involvement in Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   Starr told Congress in September 1998, when he filed his
impeachment referral with the House, that he believed there was
``substantial and credible'' evidence that the president had
committed perjury, first during a sworn deposition during the Paula
Jones sexual harassment case, and then when he testified via
closed-circuit television to Starr's original grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was Clinton's claim to Jones' lawyers that he had not
had sexual relations with Lewinsky when he was asked that as part
of Jones' lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also alleged that Clinton had obstructed justice in his
efforts to cover up the Lewinsky affair, action he eventually
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright, who oversaw
the Jones case, ordered Clinton to pay about $90,000 to the Jones
legal team, finding the president in contempt of court for giving
false testimony about his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Ray has said that he would bring no charges in
two other cases _ the misuse of classified FBI files to the White
House and the firing of White House travel office workers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
