<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      08-18 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON AND UNION NEGOTIATORS KEEP TALKING AFTER MIDNIGHT
DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Negotiators for more than 86,000 striking workers and
Verizon Communications continued to talk early Friday, past a
midnight deadline that some union representatives had set to end
formal talks.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared likely that talks between high-level representatives
of the unions and Verizon would continue through the night and
perhaps longer, regardless of what midlevel union negotiators did
at midnight, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   That was made possible after the unions' three main bargaining
units, which were divided on Wednesday, agreed to draw up a unified
proposal Thursday night, a person close to the talks said. The main
sticking points are now job security and mandatory overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperation would probably mean that the unions' concern
about the movement of work after Bell Atlantic's recent acquisition
of GTE Corp., a transaction that formed Verizon, would eclipse the
concern about mandatory overtime, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the highest-level negotiators on each side,
Lawrence T. Babbio Jr., Verizon's vice president and co-chairman,
and Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of
America, were exchanging details of the proposal by fax Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared to stay all night,'' Bahr said near the midnight
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The CWA represents about 72,000 striking employees, while the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers represents about
14,000. The walkout affects a region stretching from Virginia to
Maine that has more than 25 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, representatives for the CWA in New York and New
England and representatives for the IBEW said they would break off
talks if an agreement was not reached by midnight Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   That would have left a CWA bargaining unit representing striking
employees in several mid-Atlantic states alone in bargaining with
Verizon. That bargaining unit's main priority was gaining
concessions on mandatory overtime.
</P>
<P>
   That has been an important issue throughout the strike region
but perhaps more so in the states where the reluctant bargaining
unit is strongest, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Virginia.
Customer service representatives in those states _ unhappy with the
amount of overtime they work _ have a greater voice in union
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and New England, it is less important because
technicians, who are generally paid more than customer service
representatives, are likely to favor more overtime. In that region,
they are gathered into union locals without much mixture with the
customer service representatives.
</P>
<P>
   At least officially, the communications workers' union for
employees in New York and New England said it supported its
counterpart in the mid-Atlantic region. It and the electrical
workers' union together represent nearly two-thirds of the striking
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bargaining team is prepared to work whatever hours it
takes to get a contract, but we are not willing to be ignored or
disrespected,'' negotiators from the communications workers' union
said in an e-mail message circulated before midnight among union
leaders in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, for its part, appeared ready to make some concessions
Thursday to speed a resolution to the strike, which has disrupted
the company's efforts to make repairs and start new service.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on the issue of movement of work, the company
reduced the percentage of employees who could have their jobs
formally redefined by the Bell Atlantic-GTE merger to between 1
percent and 2 percent, down from 4 percent. Still, the unions and
the company were in disagreement over how the movement of work
would be measured, a person close to the talks said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
