<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5364 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-LA-2TAKES-LADN     08-18 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-LA-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF TOWNERS FOR DNC TAKE HOME VARIED VIEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Daily News Staff Writers Alexa Haussler, Chris Sieroty, Donna
Huffaker and Greg Wilcox contributed to this story.) 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles evokes a lot of impressions: The great
growing metropolis that doesn't have mass transportation. The
art-starved community that's home to some of the world's most
creative people.
</P>
<P>
   Tinseltown. Smogville. The City of Angels. The city of broken
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of visitors to L.A. through the Democratic
National Convention had time to form their own impressions. Some
opinions will flatter Angelenos. Some will infuriate us. Some even
sound like they come from locals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mayra Uribe, 26, a Florida delegate, fell in love with Los
Angeles during her four-day stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles has been phenomenal. It has lived up to everything
I've ever heard in movies and fantasies,'' she said. ``It's a shame
that Los Angeles has gotten such a bad rap in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Uribe said, were the celebrity sightings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Ben Affleck,'' she said. ``And I just took a picture
with Billy Baldwin!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Armstrong Williams, host of the Washington, D.C.-based
``Armstrong Williams Show'' on the Talk America Network, found Los
Angeles warm, and not just because of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that a liberal city like Los Angeles gave me a
lot of love. They are very nice,'' he said. ``I expected to be
treated like a pariah while hosting my talk show from the
convention, but we have been getting everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Expensive. That is the greatest impression that Los Angeles
left on Puerto Rico delegate Eudaldo Baez-Galib, a senator from San
Juan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cabs alone cost almost $40 from here to there,'' said the
delegate who was staying in Bel-Air during the four-day convention.
``And the food. I liked it, but it was expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed, however, the friendly reception from Angelenos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one thing that I like very much,'' he said. ``That is
the hospitality. The people here are very hospitable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Rookie delegate Beth Mills of Gainsville, Fla., said that Los
Angeles lived up to its billing as one of the world's great fun
capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a great time,'' she said at the party California
threw for out-of-state delegates Monday night on Paramount Studios'
back lot.
</P>
<P>
   She was also a gracious visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for the people of this city because we're
disturbing their traffic,'' Mills said while enjoying a glass of
California chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   She credited Los Angeles with a fun-time grand slam, giving the
city high marks for its Hollywood atmosphere, wine, great food and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _ National Jewish Democratic Leadership Council's summer interns
from the nation's capital were working inside Staples Center and
had no idea of the disturbances outside until one of them called
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my mom on a cell phone from Washington, D.C. We
didn't know if we were going to walk out and find rioting. Nobody
inside had any idea anything was going on (outside),'' said Stephen
Krupin, 18, of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Risa Berkower, 20, said: ``We were a little surprised that
something so organized inside could be so chaotic outside.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A family from Mendocino, north of San Francisco, was among the
marchers in one rally against corporate greed.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Watson and her husband, Bruce Erickson, brought their
7-year-old son, Julian Erickson-Watson, who was dressed in a
sea-turtle costume in a show of support for the environment and
wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who said she was in Seattle for the World Trade
Organization demonstrations, said the couple decided to come to Los
Angeles with Julian to change ``the world that he grows up in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my son to know that he can be in the streets to voice
his concerns about the issues that affect him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was wide-eyed at a Los Angeles police officer who was
laden with teargas canisters hanging on his chest straps. The cans
jingled and clanged noisily as the officer moved in formation with
a squad of officers assigned to crowd control. ``What is that?''
the boy asked.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I never realized how diverse the population in Los Angeles
really was,'' said Wisconsin delegate Dave Stetter. ``The people
we've run into have been very friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Stetter's wife, Kathleen, was one of dozens of people who
complained about transportation for the convention and in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transportation is terrible. The bus schedule is a
well-kept secret, and I kept trying to find out what it was,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !boxes!
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hasevawa, a delegate from Hawaii, described the city as
``very large.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so spread out, it's so huge,'' he said. ``But I love the
cosmopolitanness.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been to the city once before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the smog has cleared up quite a bit since I was here a
couple of years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   _ Guam's Lt. Gov. Madeleine Bordallo has been to 10 conventions
in 10 cities since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale from one to 10, I'd say Los Angeles gets a good
eight or nine from me,'' she said. ``The people have been very
nice, and we've met everyone from the top organizers to the
volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Pennsylvania delegate Joseph Elias couldn't say enough good
stuff about Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fabulous, absolutely fabulous. The governor has done a
great job of presenting the state. This is my first time in Los
Angeles, and I love it,'' he said. ``And I'd like to compliment the
LAPD and Highway Patrol. They're doing an outstanding job.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Some delegates actually gave the convention high marks. That's
the case of Colorado delegates Bettina Bassanou and her daughter,
Nora Nye.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the free-flowing libations, mother and daughter were on a
Clinton High on Monday night after the president and first lady
addressed the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary and Bill, well that was fantastic,'' Bassanou said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we came for. It really got your adrenaline
shooting,'' Nye said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alan Lubin, a delegate from Albany, N.Y., also had glowing
reviews of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``It's a great city. The cabs are pretty
expensive, but the restaurants are wonderful, the people have been
superb, and you should be proud of your police force,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had one criticism about the city's layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit spread out. I remember one of your mayors once
saying it's 50 suburbs in search of a city,'' he said. ``I agree
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he enjoyed his stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's just the mountains, the fresh air, the ocean. You
can't do better than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0019 </DOCNO>
