<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-T     08-18 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BLOW LATE LEAD TO DRAW OATES' WRATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Johnny Oates has lost 432 games as the Rangers manager,
but rarely, if ever, has he been so blunt and so hard on his team
as he was last night.
</P>
<P>
   After watching his team blow a five-run lead and lose 8-7 to the
Boston Red Sox, Oates offered a simple summation of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game mirrored our season a whole lot,'' Oates said. ``It
stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Rangers' play last night, Oates said, ``We stunk. We
scored a few runs, but we stunk in a lot of areas.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little disagreement from within the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to make up ground or consider yourself one of the
better teams, you've got to find a way to win that game,'' starter
Rick Helling said. ``We're finding ways to lose. That's the story
of our season; we're finding ways to lose games we should win.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling left the game with a 6-2 lead in the seventh, but the
Red Sox scored six runs in the final two innings off the Rangers'
bullpen to win it. They got three off Jeff Zimmerman and Mike
Venafro in the eighth and three more off John Wetteland in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Mike Lansing, with the Rangers leading 7-6 with two out
in the ninth, delivered the killer blow, a two-run double off the
top of the wall to bring home the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel bad for Rick,'' Venafro said. ``It's his job to keep
it close, and he did just that. It's our job to shut it down from
there, and we failed to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the Rangers lost for the 12th time this season
despite leading after six innings, and for the sixth time when
leading after eight innings. Wetteland suffered his eighth blown
save, one more than last season, although one brief, momentary
bobble by shortstop Royce Clayton cost him as much as Lansing's
two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't make the plays tonight,'' Oates said. ``We did
a lot of things wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling had one of the most unusual games he has pitched. He
allowed a career-high 12 hits and walked two in 62/3 innings, but
he gave up only two runs because the Red Sox were only 2-for-16 off
him with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   But his bullpen didn't have the same astounding success rate.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman got out of the seventh with a 6-2 lead by getting
Nomar Garciaparra to pop out with the bases loaded. But he walked
Jose Offerman to start the eighth. After Venafro took over, Bernard
Gilkey's single and Lansing's two-run double made it 6-4, and
another run scored on first baseman Rafael Palmeiro's throwing
error.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers came back with another run in the ninth when Frank
Catalanotto doubled and scored on Rusty Greer's double, his third
of the game. But the Rangers couldn't make it stand up.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland got in trouble by walking Scott Hatteberg with one out
and giving up a two-out single to Offerman. Gilkey then reached
with a high chopper that Clayton bobbled in his glove while trying
to deal with a tricky hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got caught in between,'' Clayton said. ``I knew I didn't
have much time and I bobbled it just a little. But he busted his
tail and just beat it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland forced in a run when he hit Carl Everett on the wrist,
and Lansing then smashed his double to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get much better than this,'' Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Oates can only wonder if it will get any worse.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
