r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JONES-TEX     08-18 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE THE COWBOYS BREAK CAMP, OWNER JERRY JONES WEIGHS IN ON
SEVERAL TOPICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones didn't exactly
turn off the lights and shut the door on Camp Campo, which is
scheduled to break this morning, very likely for the last time ever
at Midwestern State University.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones did stop to discuss the state of the team before
pulling out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Jones discussed the dynamics of NFL training camps, the perils
of the NFL salary cap and the accomplishments of Camp Campo.
</P>
<P>
   He raised the issue of the Cowboys' front seven serving as a
safety net for an unproven secondary, and said he hopes to have
Houston's expansion team on the Cowboys' schedule as a
nondivisional, geographic rival every season, beginning in 2002,
when the NFL is expected to realign into eight four-team divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ST: Why have training camp and why does it have to be so long?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``For young players, it's really a way to evaluate how bad
they want it. It's a way to evaluate how they will perform under
extreme conditions, and these are extreme conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Is it a good idea to reduce the preseason, or at least
shorten training camp for veteran players?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``Yes, it is. I think it's just common sense. We don't want
to wear the players out so bad in preseason that when we get into
November and December, that they've left \Rtheir game\S on the
practice field in August and late July. But I don't quite know how
you solve the problem of getting in hard work for the young guys
and letting up on the veteran players.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Did you accomplish everything you had hoped to accomplish in
this camp?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``I really couldn't have asked for anything more. We were
able to evaluate our young players. We were able to do the
fundamental things ...\R such as\S getting down the timing between
Troy Aikman and the receivers. I think we also were able to see how
we might tailor this offense to Randall Cunningham when he's in
there. I really like the way Jackie Harris has established himself;
I see us moving him around. I couldn't have asked for Chris Warren
to have had a better camp than he had. Erik Williams is in \Rafter
a four-week holdout\S, and with enough time to get in enough work
to be what we want him to be. \RGuard\S Kelvin Garmon has shown us
that he's going to be the future. Yes, we've gotten a lot
accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Arkansas rookie Clint Stoerner looks as though he will be
the No. 3 quarterback. How do you like what you see?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``I'm particularly pleased with his presence on the field,
and the respect that players have for him. He fits just right. He's
Texas-born and went to Arkansas. That fits my plan real well.
Seriously, he's shown good poise, arm strength and quickness of
delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Top draft pick Dwayne Goodrich struggled early, now he's
injured. How concerned are you about his progress?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``Concerned that he has been limited, but that's the nature
of this game. We're going to see him when he's well. He'll be here,
and we'll get a good look at him. I like the idea of these young
players who are the future for the Dallas Cowboys. Our front seven
has a chance to be one of the best. That's going to help these
young guys in the secondary. So, I'm OK there.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Are you where you thought you would be with the salary cap,
say, five years ago?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``We are. This is a constant challenge, but there are no
surprises here. A couple of things could've happened differently,
and we might have had a little more \Rcap\S room. A couple of
things could've happened negatively, and we'd be in a lot worse
shape than we are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Your longtime NFC nemesis San Francisco mortgaged the
future. Some say the Redskins are going to be next. What's your
philosophy on going for broke _ literally _ to try to win another
Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``Over-extending yourself now so that you can't compete
later, that's madness. I've never done that in any business. I'm a
gambler ... but, at the same time, I've always been able to live
with the down side. I may pout. I may cry. But I live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ST: Houston returns to the NFL as the Texans in 2002. Should a
geographical rivalry be established with the Cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``Yes, I think that would be good for the league. I think it
would make great television. If, in any way, I can extend the
positiveness and tradition of the Dallas Cowboys in such a way to
give credibility to the new Houston franchise, I want to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ST: Bush or Gore? Who do you endorse?
</P>
<P>
   JJ: ``That's not appropriate. With as many Democrat and
Republican Cowboys fans as we have, we don't get involved in
politics.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
