<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-DIARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR MAN'S POLITICAL POLL: FINAL NUMBERS: CLINTON 25, LIEBERMAN 15,
GORE 5 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to insert new second item, Doing the Hokey Hokey.)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB AND ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Can political star power be measured by parking
lot rates? If so, Al Gore may have reason to worry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the outdoor parking lots closest to the convention has
altered its rates on a daily basis. On the day President Clinton
spoke, the lot charged $25. The Joseph Lieberman night resulted in
a discounted parking rate of $15. Thursday, the biggest and final
day of the convention, when the presidential candidate, Al Gore,
spoke to the delegates, parking lot rates tumbled. All-day parking
cost only $5.
</P>
<P>
   Doing the Hokey Hokey
</P>
<P>
   It was an hour before the biggest speech of Al Gore's life. The
packed Democratic National Convention was pulsing with energy. The
crowd waited. But then the convention's planners began an
Oprah-style tribute to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And no one listened.
</P>
<P>
   The stage presentation featured among others David Halberstam,
the Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist who talked about Gore's
family and The Tennessean, the Nashville newspaper where he and
Gore once worked. There were also tributes to Gore as a
mountaineer, a man of religion, a soldier, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute was designed to depict Gore as warm, gutsy and
accessible. But it went on and on.
</P>
<P>
   And on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear it,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear it,'' said Sheldon Silver, the speaker of the
New York state Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really listen to it,'' said Christine Quinn, a New
York City councilwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's hokey,'' said Jaynne Keyes, a former New York City
film commissioner. ``But three-fourths of America is hokey, and
proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Guy in Gore's Shadow
</P>
<P>
   Now that Al Gore is the Democratic Party's new leading man, what
happens to the big guy still on stage in the White House? At a
raucous reunion party late Wednesday in West Hollywood for past and
present Clinton staffers, Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman,
said that the president would be out fund-raising for Gore ``a
couple of times a week'' between now and the election.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Clinton's role in the Gore campaign is undecided _
and a big source of debate here. Will Clinton's presence on the
campaign trail strengthen Gore, or dwarf him? ``The president can
raise money and raise issues, but otherwise he ought not to be out
there campaigning,'' said Paul Begala, the former Clinton adviser,
who turned up at the party at Manhattan Wonton Co., a restaurant on
Melrose Place. `He would tend to distract and overshadow.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton would do whatever the Gore campaign
wanted, which, a Gore adviser said, will be trips to the South, to
black communities and to California _ places where he is popular.
Clinton is also speaking nearly every day to his old friend,
William Daley, the Gore-Lieberman campaign manager. Offering
political advice, yes? Lockhart wouldn't say, but Begala, a veteran
of the 1992 Clinton campaign offered this: `In 1992 there was
always a creative tension between the people who were hired to run
the campaign and the person who wanted to run the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghost of Elvis?
</P>
<P>
   He was Elvis in feathers one night, the serious guy on the
podium the next. Although Sen. John Breaux of Louisiana's biggest
role here was nominating Lieberman in a speech at the convention
Wednesday night, it was hard to forget his far more mesmerizing
appearance here: As an Elvis look-alike in white tights, big white
collar and purple, green and gold feathers at an over-the-top faux
Fat Tuesday party at Paramount Studios. The party, estimated to
cost $500,000, was paid for by the Democratic Leadership Council
and many of the companies Breaux helps to regulate on the finance
and commerce committees.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said Thursday that his costume was not, in fact, Elvis,
but a traditional Mardi Gras outfit that was `just Breaux being
Breaux.'' He also said that `there are some people in New York who
might think that's a little bit of an unusual costume for a U.S.
senator, but it's perfectly acceptable back home.''
</P>
<P>
   New Kosher Kid on the Block
</P>
<P>
   Kosher food for the Liebermans? No issue, said Wolfgang Puck,
the premier chef of Los Angeles, who has catered dozens of
convention parties in the last few days. Puck said he had not yet
specifically made dinner for Lieberman and his wife, Hadassah, who
keep kosher. ``But,'' he said, ``there's no difficulty at all _ I
cook for a lot of customers who have kosher homes and they eat some
white fish, some vegetables, some fruit. They don't eat butter and
cream with meat. You avoid these.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Orthodox Jews, like the Liebermans, either avoid
restaurants at any cost, or even bring their own plates out of
concern that restaurant dishes, however clean, had been used in the
past for nonkosher food. But the Connecticut Democrat has eaten at
numerous receptions here and dines at at trendy places in
Washington, like I Ricci. One of his friends said, ``He eats salad
and fish _ no big deal. He has bread. And he's a stickler for
kosher wine _ that's what he drinks when he has wine. Of course, he
wouldn't be caught dead at a steak place like The Palm or Smith &AMP;
Wollensky.''
</P>
<P>
   Puck, owner of Spago and other restaurants, said jokingly that
while providing food for the Liebermans would pose no difficulties,
the hungry delegates were another matter. ``They like to eat, they
really like to eat, much more than people do in L.A.,'' he said.
``In L.A., with the movie people, they take a little food, a little
mineral water, sometimes a glass of champagne. But these delegates
are something else. They enjoy their food! I like that. We had a
dinner the other night at Spago. Eight hundred were supposed to
show. Well, 1,800 showed. I was shocked. They kept coming and they
kept eating. That's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP Spin Squad
</P>
<P>
   Republicans? At the Democratic convention?
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like the people who were entering `Checkpoint
Charlie,' it's kind of like going into East Germany,'' said Rick
Wilson, a consultant to the Republican National Committee who has
been in town for the last week with a half-dozen members of the GOP
shmoozing the press at the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Republicans spinning the news? ``I prefer to call it
`rapid response,' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican spinners included Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey, Rep. Henry Bonilla of Texas, Jim Nicholson, chairman of the
Republican National Committee, and Pat Harrison, co-chairman. The
group operated from a small suite opposite the Staples Center, and
fanned out each day, sometimes wearing press passes, walking the
corridors and talking to journalists and radio correspondents about
the inadequacies of the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican convention in Philadelphia, the Democrats had
a similar squad, but their members were sometimes harder to spot.
The Republican group here wore pins reading: ``Bush/Cheney.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said the week passed perfectly pleasantly for the
interlopers. ``Actually we were treated kind of well by the
Democrats,'' Harrison said, sounding a bit puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   Pity the Poor Millionaire
</P>
<P>
   One-two-three. Everyone. Let's all feel sorry for the
millionaires at the Democratic Party. While billionaires like Eli
Broad, one of the Democrats' most generous patrons, seem to have no
complaints about how the party is falling all over itself with VIP
treatment, the lesser contributors are another matter. Lesser means
those who have given only, say, $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   As rich as these donors are, the red carpet is looking a bit
frayed to them. The computers were down when they checked into the
five-star Regent Beverly Wilshire Hotel, their parking passes and
convention center credentials were not ready, their skyboxes at the
convention had been commandeered by Democratic officials and their
parties, which they initially assumed would be exclusive affairs,
turned out to be grossly oversubscribed and seemed, at times, like
the subway at rush hour in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   One party fund-raiser heard a torrent of complaints from one big
donor and suggested that the unhappy millionaire speak to the party
leadership. ``He said to me, `who am I going to complain to? This
whole thing is being run by a bunch of 23-year-old kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   One-two-three. Everyone. Let's all feel sorry ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
