<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-UNIFORMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS HOPE NEW UNIFORMS WILL SHOW ENERGY, ENTHUSIASM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN WOOD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks are developing a new team logo that
features a horse instead of a cowboy hat and swaps the team's
green, blue and white color combination with a black, blue and
silver scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, team officials will meet with representatives from
the NBA and Nike, which makes the team's uniforms, to review the
first round of creative work on the new look.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the look to have a lot of energy, a lot of
attitude,'' said Matt Fitzgerald, senior vice president of
marketing and communications for the Mavericks. ``You want an
exciting color scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said the Mavericks will change their 20-year-old
image for the 2001-02 season, which will be their first in the new
American Airlines Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That logo is not a maverick,'' he said of the team's current
symbol. ``Our colors will be blue, black and silver.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has submitted proposed changes to the league and will
continue to work with league designers to refine them throughout
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes at least a year and a half to two years,'' said Chris
Heyn, senior vice president of the NBA's global merchandising
group. ``It's a long, thought-out process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have had basically the same look since the team
entered the league in 1980. They switched from green road uniforms
to blue road uniforms in the early 1990s. Otherwise, there have
been few changes beyond the look of the lettering.
</P>
<P>
   But the team has been making numerous changes since the
franchise was purchased earlier this year by Internet entrepreneur
Mark Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really kind of symbolized who the owner was at the time,''
Fitzgerald said. ``Mr. \RDonald\S Carter wears a white hat. Reunion
Arena was kind of a green, blue combination. It hasn't changed in
20 years. It's just become a tired mark in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The league has been working with teams in the past decade to
update their looks. Teams such as the Denver Nuggets, Detroit
Pistons, Golden State Warriors, Houston Rockets and Seattle
SuperSonics have all gone through logo changes that reflect a
certain amount of brand consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely what we're looking for right now is consistency
with a classic edge,'' Heyn said. ``We're not changing but evolving
that brand for that team. It's important for us to keep up to
date.''
</P>
<P>
   League rules dictate that if a team changes its logo, it can't
change again for eight years. It can change uniforms every four
years. ``The last thing we want to do is send so many mixed
messages from a team that the fans are turned off or confused,''
Heyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Mavericks merchandise have been disappointing, given
the team's dismal play in the 1990s. Fitzgerald said he did not
have the figures on where the team ranked in the league for
merchandise sales. But based on what they sell during games,
Fitzgerald said the team has to be ``near the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The logo makes it look like this is a laid-back cowboy town,''
he said. ``This town is not like that. It's a bold town. You try to
incorporate the attitude of the team, and that's what we're trying
to do in our new mark. You need a winning team and you need some
cool stuff.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5375 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-T     08-18 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONUS ON RANGERS' OWNER TO MAKE CRUCIAL WINTER DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers are a bad baseball team right now, and it has little
to do with catcher Ivan Rodriguez's being lost for the season. The
Rangers miss him terribly, but it's doubtful that the best catcher
in baseball could do anything to stop this free fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler is on a rampage, and Rick Helling has turned into
one of the best pitchers in the American League. But hitting coach
Rudy Jaramillo still has a lot of work ahead of him with Mike Lamb
and Ricky Ledee; the great experiment with young pitching has not
been an instant success; and many of the veteran players are in a
funk while wondering where this franchise is headed.
</P>
<P>
   The usual ``good nucleus'' will still be there next year, but
the Rangers' dismal showing since the All-Star break strongly
suggests this team is not as close to a pennant contender as people
think. The Rangers have a difficult decision facing them in the
off-season, and it's one that can't be made by general manager Doug
Melvin or manager Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   The man on the spot will be the owner himself, Tom Hicks. Only
Hicks can decide if he's willing to spend huge amounts of dollars
to try to compete with the New York Yankees, or if he would rather
sit through another trying season waiting for his young players to
develop.
</P>
<P>
   When the accountants finish their work this year, the Rangers
likely will spend $40 million to $44 million less on salaries this
year than the Yankees. That's a staggering amount considering Hicks
isn't one to be frugal. But $40 million also could be exactly what
Hicks will have to fork over this winter for the starting pitcher,
power hitter and front-line closer the Rangers need to close the
gap.
</P>
<P>
   However, even if the Rangers were able to sway Mike Hampton,
Manny Ramirez and Robb Nen to come to Texas, it still would be no
guarantee a pennant will be flying in Arlington at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. The Rangers could spend $100 million next year
on player salaries and still not be good enough to win the AL West,
much less the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Seattle and Chicago have proved, as the Rangers have
in the past, that you can win in the regular season without
spending in the Yankees' class. But the playoffs have proved to be
a totally different story.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks also could decide to take pretty much the same team into
next year with only a few cosmetic changes. They still would have
the same three young pitchers in Matt Perisho, Doug Davis and Ryan
Glynn, but they would have them for a full year, along with a
healthy Justin Thompson and a healthy Darren Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy also would give Kapler a chance to develop into a
true star, give Lamb an opportunity to make less errors and drive
in more runs, and provide Ruben Mateo a chance to finally stay
healthy for a season. That might be the best way to go as far as
the long-term success of the organization, but the Rangers would
have to do so knowing it will be difficult competing against the
best in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Melvin's philosophy of trying to be as competitive
as possible each year without sacrificing the future too much.
Melvin has proved adept at doing that, as shown by three division
titles in four years. One shrewd trade with the Arizona
Diamondbacks could get Curt Schilling here at the bargain price of
$6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is a firm believer that if you keep winning division
titles and keep making the playoffs, eventually you're going to win
a pennant and maybe even the World Series. He refers to it as his
Denver Broncos theory, in honor of the long-suffering John Elway,
who finally was rewarded for his perseverance with back-to-back
Super Bowl victories.
</P>
<P>
   But NFL teams don't have to deal with a $40 million gap in
payrolls. Hicks does, and this winter only he can decide what he's
going to do about it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
