<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-ASSESS-2NDLD-WRI     08-18 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ASSESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A MAN OF MANY TASKS TRIES TO RALLY HIS DECIDEDLY JITTERY
PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (Subs for rewriting thruout, new headline)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Al Gore tried to accomplish a political feat so
daunting Thursday night that even the maestro himself, President
Clinton, might have had trouble pulling it off.
</P>
<P>
   Gore presented himself as his own man and virtually skated over
his service as vice president as he sought to convince the nation
that he is more than the dutiful lieutenant. But he also tried to
take credit for helping to bring about ``the biggest surpluses
ever'' _ the grandest achievement of the Clinton era.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to shake the impressions of Americans who, in the words
of his campaign chairman, think he is ``boring, stiff'' and
``unable to speak.'' But he also asserted that he would build a
campaign based on the dry timber of issues rather than on the flash
and dazzle of personality.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to embolden and excite liberals whose turnout are
essential to his victory. But he also tried, though less
aggressively, to embolden and excite moderate voters who are
crucial to a victory in November _ and have shown an interest in
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas that has alarmed Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's elaborate _ and often conflicting _ objectives Thursday
night, and throughout this convention week, reflect the trying
challenges he and the Democrats confront as they emerge from this
convention. Forget the confetti and mirthful talk of harmony from
the rostrum. For the Democrats, happy days are certainly not here
again. They may not be panicked, but they are jittery about their
standard-bearer. And they are jittery about November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a difficult campaign,'' said James Patrick Leahy, a
delegate from Ohio, even after four days of enforced partisan
cheerleading. ``Gore has one of those personalities you have to
develop a relationship with.''
</P>
<P>
   The polls showing Gore behind, Leahy said, have dampened his
enthusiasm. ``The polling has a psychological effect,'' he said.
``It's like when you go to the racetrack and look at the racing
form and see your horse isn't supposed to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no such worries when the Republicans concluded their
political production in Philadelphia two weeks ago. At that
convention, Dick Cheney, the vice presidential nominee, did not
have to scurry from constituent group to constituent group with
words of appeasement _ as Sen. Joseph Lieberman did Thursday, and
the two days before.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years on the outside, even Republican delegates who
were not pleased with the inclusive tone of their program were so
desperate to return to power that it took little, if any, prodding
to corral them behind Bush. Eight years ago, Democrats were also
willing to put aside their differences in the name of the greater
goal of helping Bill Clinton bring them back to power. Now, they
are less accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   So the party tried to fire up the rank and file by jamming the
stage this week with liberal icons like Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and
the Rev. Jesse Jackson, and leaders of labor, abortion rights and
gay rights groups. Even Lieberman, in his speech, retreated from
his usual condemnation of the collapsed culture of Hollywood and
instead played the partisan. And Thursday night, Gore aimed his
message squarely at the party base _ and away from the broader
messages of Clinton's two acceptance speeches _ by sounding
traditional Democratic themes of abortion, affirmative action and
government spending.
</P>
<P>
   More than one Democratic official complained that the campaign
this week seemed more focused on winning over the liberals who
might back Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate, than the bigger
threat, Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans played to the country _ the Democrats played
to the hall,'' said Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster. ``Voters
saw through the big tent Republican convention. They know it was
staged. But they were thankful that somebody cared.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's address was carefully calibrated to offer a nod to the
man with whom he has such a complicated relationship _ and to move
on swiftly. In the 5,100-word text, the vice president mentioned
Clinton only once, declaring, ``Millions of Americans will live
better lives for a long time to come because of the job that's been
done by President Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   He also, subtly, sought to put some distance between himself and
a leader who had disappointed, if not embarrassed, the nation. ``I
will never let you down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The unknowing listener would not have a clue of what arguably
makes Gore best prepared to be president: That he has served the
past eight years as vice president. The thinking of Gore's campaign
is that no matter how active a political partner he was, voters
will never give a vice president credit.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is Gore. Whether it is his link to the
scandals of Clinton, the unfavorable comparisons to the more
politically adroit president _ or simply his personality _
Democrats here are just not as enamored of their new nominee. On
this day four years ago, even the bombshell that Clinton's top
strategist was having an affair with a call girl did nothing to
disrupt _ and maybe added a little spice _ to the week of lock-step
partisan harmony behind the president.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before his boss was to deliver the most consequential
speech of his political career, one of Gore's top aides confessed
that he was worried because the campaign was still roiled by
squabbling factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Daley has not gotten the warlords under control yet,''
this campaign official said, referring to William M. Daley, Gore's
campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident, certainly, that Gore spewed out lots of
policy Thursday night. He was trying to make the case that ``people
deserve to know specifically what a candidate proposes to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of polls showing that the public gives Democrats higher
marks than Republicans on a range of issues, Gore's aides said they
hope the campaign can be fought on that terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Before he can do that, Gore wants to neutralize Bush's biggest
advantage _ his appealing personality. That explains that footage
in a film Friday night lauding Gore for his Frankenstein disguise
during a Halloween party. That is why all week Democrats, and the
candidate himself, offered testaments to the fuzzy and decidedly
un-vice presidential side of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made only glancing blows at the Republicans and he did not
directly cite his opponent by name even once. But clearly
acknowledging that Bush had the edge on charm, Gore said, ``The
presidency is not a popularity contest. It's a day-by-day fight for
people. Sometimes, you have to chose to do what's difficult or
unpopular. Sometimes you have to be willing to spend your
popularity in order to pick the hard right over the easy wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then-Vice President George Bush, in his acceptance speech
in New Orleans in 1988, did not face the difficulties of Gore. He,
too, had the unfortunate fate of having to stand on his own after
eight years in the shadow of a far more dexterous political
performer. But Bush never had such trouble untangling himself from
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic transfer of political power was far smoother in
1988 when Reagan put forth a dignified and full-throated pitch for
his No. 2. This week, Clinton was criticized for not making more of
an energetic case for Gore in his speech here on Monday _ or in
their joint appearance in Michigan the next day. The rub is that
had he been more generous in his praise, Clinton might have been
accused of injecting himself too much into the role of star
performer giving an assist to his understudy.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday night, Gore seemed to borrow a bit from
the playbook of the man whose son is standing in his way to the
White House. He addressed the personality issue head on, saying,
``If you entrust me with the presidency, I know I won't always be
the most exciting politician.'' But in what could be interpreted as
a dig at Bush _ who is known as less engaged on the issues than
Gore _ he pledged, ``I will work for you every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Bush said in 1988: ``I may not be the most eloquent,
but I learned that eloquence won't draw oil from the ground. I may
sometimes be a little awkward, but there's nothing self-conscious
in my love of country.''And, as Bush did 12 years ago, Gore sought
to fasten himself to the economic successes of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that the appeal will work and, as happened with
Bush, that people will entrust Gore to continue bringing the nation
down the path of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But in a telling acknowledgment that the campaign ahead will not
be easy, Gore's aides were already playing down the import of
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important moment, a crescendo,'' said Tad Devine,
one of Gore's top strategists. `` But there will be other big
moments in this campaign, including the presidential debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, though, Gore will run out of big moments. And
Thursday night may have been his best opportunity to accomplish
what he has tried again and again in this race for president: to
reintroduce himself to the people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
