<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREDATOR-RELEASE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN BECOMES FIRST TO BE RELEASED FROM KANSAS' SEXUAL PREDATOR
PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ Former Olathe resident Jerry P. Inman on Thursday
became the first person to be released from Kansas' sexual predator
program since it began in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He will remain under the scrutiny of court officials for at
least five years and will be subject to annual polygraph tests and
continued psychological counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Inman, 51, who plans to leave Kansas, also signed an agreement
not to fight extradition to the state if he violates any of the
conditions of his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to get on with my life,'' he said Thursday after a
hearing in Johnson County District Court. ``I'm happy to be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   His release was nearly held up Thursday when the director of the
predator program said Inman had failed to achieve a ``clean
polygraph result.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin DesLauriers said that although Inman's answers appeared
to be deceitful on two points, there was no suspicion that he had
been involved in any ``sexual misbehavior.''
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Peter Ruddick said he was satisfied that Inman's
problems with the polygraph test should not block his release
because they were not related to issues of sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   Inman said he would be living and working on a farm outside
Kansas. He said he had arranged for therapy with a psychologist who
will provide annual reports to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three convicted sex offenders are being held in Kansas'
predator unit, based in the Larned Correctional Mental Health
Facility.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas lawmakers approved the predator legislation in 1994,
after a convicted rapist who had been released from prison killed
college student Stephanie Schmidt of Leawood, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows the state to hold some sex offenders indefinitely
for treatment after they have completed their prison terms. The
Kansas Supreme Court ruled that it was unconstitutional, but the
U.S. Supreme Court upheld the law in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the predator law, legislators approved the state's
Sex Offender Registration Act. It requires virtually all people
convicted of committing sex crimes after the law took effect in
1994 to register with the sheriff in the county where they reside.
</P>
<P>
   The information is available to the public in each sheriff's
office and is also maintained on the Kansas Bureau of
Investigation's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Inman would not have had to register as a sex offender because
he committed his crimes before the law took effect.
</P>
<P>
   He was committed to the predator unit in 1996 after a jury found
that he had a mental condition that made him likely to commit more
sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen women and girls testified at his predator trial
about his deviant sexual activities dating to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the girls testified that Inman molested them during
photographic modeling sessions in motel rooms. Others were
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County prosecutors filed the predator case in 1996 when
Inman was about to be paroled. He went to prison in 1994 after
pleading no contest to charges involving three victims.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, he became the first man in the predator unit to be
moved into the program's transitional release phase.
</P>
<P>
   He lived in a duplex on the state hospital grounds and worked on
the grounds. Inman and his attorney, Darrell Smith, argued for his
release from the program then, noting that he had received no
counseling during that time.
</P>
<P>
   In May, he was transferred to the Johnson County Community
Corrections residential center near Gardner, Kan., to complete the
transitional release phase.
</P>
<P>
   Inman on Thursday praised the staff at the residential center
but said no one from the predator program met with him while he was
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been dragging on longer than it had to be,'' Inman said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said part of the frustration was because Inman was the
first to get out and officials had to make release plans.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing Thursday, Smith said that Inman's release
shouldn't hinge on something as unreliable as a polygraph test.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason polygraphs are not admissible in court,''
Smith said. ``He'll take the test as many times as they want to
strap him into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Inman's release agreement will require an annual polygraph test
that he must pay for.
</P>
<P>
   He also agreed to keep a journal of his daily activities and a
record of people who can verify his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   He is not to have any involvement with pornography and have no
unsupervised contact with females under age 18. The judge said that
order should include online contacts such as chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Inman also will not be allowed to use photographic equipment
without court approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
