<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS GET LOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's a good thing the Anaheim Angels had a bus driver
who knew the way back to the team hotel Thursday night. Left on
their own, they might have ended up somewhere in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the Angels were lost on the basepaths in a 6-1
setback to the Yankees before 35,180 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees starter Denny Neagle (3-3) gave up nine hits in 6
innings, but no Angel crossed the plate against him because of
baserunning errors worthy of a blooper reel. The Angels avoided a
shutout when Scott Spiezio hit a two-out, pinch homer in the ninth
off Jason Grimsley.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Kent Mercker, making his second start since
recovering from a brain hemorrhage, pitched well in five innings,
yielding two runs and three hits. Still on a limited pitch count,
Mercker (0-2) was removed after making 88 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' weary bullpen, now laden with minor-leaguers, gave
up four runs in three innings and allowed the Yankees to win
easily.
</P>
<P>
   The baserunning gaffes, though, hurt the Angels when they still
had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   They loaded the bases with one out in the second inning when
Darin Erstad hit a fly ball to medium-deep right field. Slow-footed
Bengie Molina tagged at third and began lumbering toward the plate
as right fielder David Justice made the catch and threw home.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway home, though, Molina put on the brakes and returned to
third, as instructed by third-base coach Ron Roenicke. Meanwhile,
Adam Kennedy retreated to second, but Benji Gil tagged at first and
raced toward second.
</P>
<P>
   After joining Kennedy at second, Gil was tagged out in a rundown
between first and second for the final out of the inning while
Molina stood motionless just a few feet from third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my head down to run hard once the throw went over
(cutoff man) Tino Martinez's head,'' Gil explained. ``I should have
looked to see where Adam was. That's why I was out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, the Angels put runners on first and third with
one out. Troy Glaus hit a sharp grounder down the line and inside
third. Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius made a diving,
back-handed grab of the ball, preventing it from going into left
field.
</P>
<P>
   But Gil froze at third, and Erstad, running from first, rounded
second too far and was thrown out for the second out of the inning.
Tim Salmon then struck out to end the inning, as the Angels went 2
for 10 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I froze,'' Gil said. ``Once you freeze, it's hard to get going
again, even if you probably have time. Obviously I should have
scored on that play. I should have gone on contact. That's stuff
that shouldn't have happened. Unfortunately it happened more than
once today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot ourselves in the foot,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``We had a lot of opportunities. You look at the number of
hits in the game (Angels had 11, Yankees had six) and you'd think
we'd be the club up 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if we get out ahead, it's a different ballgame. You
allow Neagle to settle down, he's tough, as he proved to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The only positive in the game was Mercker's performance. He gave
up single runs in the second and third innings but nothing else
through five. It was a significant improvement from his 3-inning
outing five days ago against the same Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, yeah (it was encouraging), but we lost. I'd rather
pitch bad and win,'' Mercker said. ``I felt a lot better out there
tonight than five days ago. Tonight was a night that if I had the
endurance to throw 120 pitches, it was a good night to do it. I
could have pitched through the seventh and kept it right where it
was at.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Angels had to go to Juan Alvarez, Eric Weaver and
Derrick Turnbow. Alvarez gave up a two-run homer to Justice and
Weaver yielded a solo homer to slap-hitter Luis Sojo in the sixth
inning. Justice added a sacrifice fly in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the Yankees beat you,'' Scioscia said. ``They get
on base, put pressure on you and keep innings alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
