<SLUG> BC-FBN-TEXAS-TECH-COACH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH COACH, QUARTERBACK THINK ALIKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The offense conjured in the fertile mind of new Texas Tech head
coach Mike Leach is an ever-evolving work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as is possible,'' Leach said. ``We like to think it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture is easy to imagine of Leach, stick in hand, kneeling
over a spot of bare ground with his players huddled around him,
furiously drawing a new configuration as precious seconds tick off
the 25-second play clock. The offense does not always evolve on
such whim, though it's not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``A receiver comes to me and says, `Hey, I'm open on the curl
route,' we'll throw the curl route,'' Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   And regardless of the time frame, all suggestions are welcome,
quarterback Kliff Kingsbury confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Leach is real open-minded,'' Kingsbury said. ``\RThe
players\S came up with some new plays over the summer, and he was
open to trying them out. There are a couple of them in the offense
now. That makes it more fun for us because we really get to be a
part of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``And coach Leach is always coming up with new ways to beat the
defense. He's always thinking. It really is a new game every day
because there's no telling what he's going to put in. Meetings are
real interesting. We learn something new every day. As a coach, I
love him to death. I think we complement each other really well.''
</P>
<P>
   His new team, Leach said, has digested everything he can throw
at them as the Red Raiders slowly turn their focus toward game
preparation for the Hispanic College Fund Classic on Aug. 26
against New Mexico. Leach said Kingsbury, a 6-foot-4, 218-pound
sophomore who possesses a tireless arm, is one of the big reasons
why he believes the Raiders are, at this stage of development,
ahead of offenses he inherited as offensive coordinator at either
Kentucky (1997-98) or Oklahoma (1999).
</P>
<P>
   Kingsbury completed 24 of 26 passes for 321 yards and three
touchdowns in Tech's spring game and has hit the ground throwing
with the same precision in August workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as picking up the scheme, I think Kliff is ahead of a
lot of the quarterbacks I've had,'' said Leach, who coached Tim
Couch, the NFL No. 1 draft pick in 1999, at Kentucky and OU's Josh
Heupel. ``He doesn't have as much \Rgame\S experience as some of
them had, but he's made up for it by the way he studies the game.
He's really a self-starter kind of guy who learns something new
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingsbury played in six games last season as a redshirt
freshman, shining in his only start, ironically against the
Sooners. Kingsbury outdueled Heupel by throwing for 259 yards and
three touchdowns as the Raiders upset OU in their season finale,
38-28, to send retiring coach Spike Dykes out on a winning note.
</P>
<P>
   As Heupel, Kingsbury is a coach's son. So, making suggestions to
his head coach is nothing new to the New Braunfels High School
product who, as a senior, passed for 3,009 yards and 34 touchdowns
while leading the Unicorns to the 1997 Class 5A semifinals. He was
also a member of the National Honor Society and twice has qualified
for the Big 12 commissioner's academic honor roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kliff has always had a knack for understanding the game and
has studied it all his life,'' said his father, Tim Kingsbury, who
recently retired from coaching so he and his wife could watch his
son play on Saturdays. ``He would draw up plays and bring them to
me, and whenever he told me something, I always listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If what he brought me worked, we used it. I took his advice a
lot of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim believes the collaboration between Leach and his son will
prove to be a match made in football heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a good fit, I think, because Kliff and he are a lot
alike as far as their thinking in offensive football,'' the elder
Kingsbury said. ``Having been in the profession and been \Rto
Lubbock\S to watch some of spring training, I have been really
impressed with Mike's whole coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate Leach's attitude because he's willing to try
things that maybe traditionally other people wouldn't try. He's
willing to experiment, and that's great because it makes the game
enjoyable for the players. Kliff is really excited about having him
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The excitement has spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offense is going to put Kliff on a showcase,'' sophomore
H-back Shaud Williams predicted. ``It's perfect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach's system relies on a heady quarterback who can make snap
decisions at the line of scrimmage as the play clock dwindles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offense can be complex,'' Kingsbury conceded. ``You have
to buckle down and study the game a lot more because you control
the offense, you control how your team does. You have a lot more
leverage to make the calls on the field. If I see something good, I
get to check to \Ra new play\S. But I wouldn't say the scheme is
that complicated if you break it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingsbury said he would be confident if the Raiders were opening
the season tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd be ready to go,'' he said without hesitation.
``We've been going against our defense so long now that they have
learned our plays and checks, so it's getting tougher to do things.
But that's making us better, because we have to be a lot more
precise to get things done against them. I think it's going really
well.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this scenario, the quarterback's opinion is given more
than a passing thought. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
