r s BC-HKN-STARS-DONATO-TEX     08-18 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DONATO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DONATO IN FOLD, STARS FILLING IN THE GAPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars assistant general manager Doug Armstrong
won't guarantee that the team is done finagling their roster. But,
with yesterday's signing of free-agent forward Ted Donato and
winger Blake Sloan on board after a ruling in his arbitration case,
Armstrong said they are pretty darn close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're prepared to go with the players we have,''
Armstrong said of training camp, which begins Sept. 9 in Vail,
Colo. ``Getting \RDonato\S gives us another veteran. I think it's
important to have players that have been through the grind before,
to give support to Roman \RLyashenko\S, Brenden \RMorrow\S and
\RJon\S Sim and give them a chance to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato, who played last season for the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim,
signed a one-year deal. Terms were not disclosed. The 31-year-old
winger said the Stars were his No. 1 choice for ``obvious''
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they win,'' Donato said. ``And I want to be on a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   He had 11 goals and 19 assists in the 1999-2000 season and could
be used on the second line with Joe Nieuwendyk and Jamie
Langenbrunner or in a checking role on the third line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted is a guy not unlike Mike Keane. He'll play a very
versatile role for this team,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``We can also move him into a higher-profile position and he'll be
equally effective. He helps so we're not breaking in inexperienced
people in critical roles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have lost a lot of veteran leaders in the two
off-seasons since their 1998-99 Stanley Cup championship. They've
been replacing them with a mix of selected veterans, such as Donato
and younger players such as Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have known Sloan would be in Vail since he filed for
arbitration this summer. They just didn't know what kind of
contract he would have. They do now.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator ruled yesterday in favor of Sloan, awarding him a
one-year, one-way contract worth $550,000. The Stars asked for a
two-way deal that would have paid him considerably less for games
played with their minor-league affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very excited about the ruling,'' said Sloan, who made
$375,000 last season. ``I don't know if fair is the right word, but
I'm happy.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly Retired Stars center Brian Skrudland
has taken a developmental job in Calgary similar to the one Guy
Carbonneau took in Montreal. Calgary is where former Stars director
of player personal Craig Button was hired as general manager this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also signed forward David Ling, who was acquired last
week in a trade with Chicago, to a one-year deal with an option for
another year. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
