<HEADLINE>
ARLINGTON MAKES MILLIONS FOR CHAIRMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To commemorate the return of the Arlington Million from its
two-year absence, officials at Arlington International Racecourse
bumped the purse for the high-profile turf race from $1 million to
$2 million. And when the race is conducted tomorrow (ESPN, 3-4:30
p.m.), a field that includes Running Stag, Manndar, Bienamado,
Chester House and Slickly is expected to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Those are accomplished horses, but none strikes the imagination
as John Henry did when he competed in the race in the mid-'80s. In
fact, the best turf horse on display at Arlington on Saturday might
be competing earlier in the day when King Cugat goes for his fifth
consecutive victory against other 3-year-olds in the $400,000
Secretariat Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Million has attracted nice horses this year, but it's no
bonanza. The bonanza appears to belong to Dick Duchossois, the
strong-willed chairman at Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, an introduction is in order. Duchossois returned
racing to the Chicagoland track after the fire that torched the
grandstand in the late '80s. He did a good job.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 tracks in this country have either been constructed,
remodeled or rebuilt since Arlington burned. None _ Lone Star Park
at Grand Prairie included _ is as opulent as the rebuilt Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   To Duchossois, the racetrack is his bat, his ball, his game. So
if he ever went to Illinois' horse-racing regulators or to the
other two tracks in the Chicago area (Sportsman's Park or Hawthorne
Racecourse) and if he didn't get what he wanted, Duchossois
wouldn't hesitate to either reduce the number of race dates he
would offer or make threats to shut the place down.
</P>
<P>
   Since the arrival of riverboat casinos in the Chicago area,
Duchossois has wanted a piece of the action. Legislators told him
to take a hike, so that's what Duchossois did. He made good on his
threat to shut down the track in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   So after two years of keeping the track dormant, Duchossois won
legislative approval to get a cut on riverboat casino proceeds. But
that's nothing compared with the bonanza that's about to become
final in a Churchill Downs boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   Duchossois has agreed to allow Arlington to become the latest
racetrack to join the Churchill Downs corporate plan. But rather
than the complete buyout that Churchill used to acquire Calder
Racecourse and Hollywood Park, this is a merger.
</P>
<P>
   So Duchossois and his company gets 3.15 million shares of
Churchill stock. Based on Churchill's stock price, which closed at
22 13/16 Wednesday on the Nasdaq, it's a payday of $71 million. His
stake actually could grow to 4.4 million shares, and he would own
30 percent of Churchill Downs and its corporate-owned tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with a private investor named Brad Kelley, who is
based in Franklin, Ky., and has been identified as the most active
buyer of Churchill stock during the past 18 months. He owns 1
million shares, or 11 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   It's the season of political conventions, and there has been a
lot of talk about ``squandered opportunity.'' Duchossois certainly
hasn't squandered his.
\Nsubheds:LATE SCRATCHES... All American Derby A group of 48
entrants, including Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie stakes
performers Significant Speed and Gone Kool Man, are scheduled to
race in the time trials of the $300,000 All American Derby today at
Ruidoso Downs. Final for the event is Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Significant Speed, owned by Gus Barakis of Weatherford,
qualified for the Dash For Cash Futurity last year at Lone Star.
She also won the Rainbow Derby this year at Ruidoso. Gone Kool Man
is trained by defending Lone Star champion Steve Van Bebber and was
second in the Texas Classic Futurity last year. A Delightful
Dasher, winner of last year's All American Futurity, also is
entered in the Derby time trials. \Nsubheds:Racing at Arlington In
addition to the Arlington Million tomorrow, two other important
turf stakes races make their return to Arlington International
Racecourse near Chicago after a two-year absence. The Beverly D
Stakes is worth $500,000 for fillies and mares and the Secretariat
Stakes offers $400,000 for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag, fifth in his last start on a wet dirt track in the
Whitney Handicap, is the top money earner in the Million. Manndar
might be the most talented challenger; he has won two consecutive
Grade I stakes races at Churchill Downs and Belmont. Also in the
field are Godolphin Stable-owned Slickly, Bienamado, Chester House
(a jockey switch to Jerry Bailey), Mula Gula and Asidero.
</P>
<P>
   Happyanunoit, winner of the Grade I Beverly Hills Handicap at
Hollywood Park, faces nine others in the Beverly D, the most
talented appearing to be European stakes performers America and
Country Garden.
</P>
<P>
   King Cugat tries for his fifth victory in a row in the
Secretariat, and his toughest rival looks to be European invader
Ciro. He finished third in the Irish Derby. \Nsubheds:Alabama in NY
Saratoga Racecourse is in New York, but it calls its training track
the Oklahoma Training Facility. So it's no wonder that one of
Saratoga's biggest stakes races of the year is known as the Alabama
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Status, who won the Kentucky Oaks but faltered in her
latest start in the Coaching Club American Oaks, is the expected
favorite for the Alabama. The race is part of the Arlington Million
telecast tomorrow (ESPN, 3-4:30 p.m.).
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ... Pioneering Krone trying hand on new TV
venture Julie Krone's induction into the Horse Racing Hall of Fame
this month is easily the most controversial addition in years. One
prominent national columnist wrote prior to Krone's induction that
Krone, with her more than 3,000 victories as a jockey, was less
deserving for induction to the Hall of Fame than Earlie Fires. He
has ridden about twice as many winners as Krone.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing was written about measuring the idea of
trailblazing. Does a Hall of Fame honor stats or a contribution to
a sport?
</P>
<P>
   Krone has now moved into television work. She is an on-camera
host for the Television Games Network that is part of home
satellite dish systems. Her work there is hardly Hall of Fame
quality.
</P>
<P>
   While working as a studio co-host during a recent race day,
Krone used the medium to remind viewers on numerous occasions that
she was suffering from a sore throat. And when her co-host noted
that neither one of them predicted a winner from a race that just
finished at Calder Racecourse, Krone said, ``I did. I just didn't
tell anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   TVG is a new network that, like most ventures, needs some fine
tuning. Krone needs to be a part of that. She handled postrace
interviews of jockeys for ABC Radio at this year's Preakness Stakes
and did a respectable job. Krone ought to be doing that sort of
on-site work, rather than a studio host, for TVG.
\Nsubheds:By the numbers Time trials for the $2 million All
