<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MIGHT MOVE DOUG DAVIS TO BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was a lot of fallout from Brian Sikorski's
terrific pitching performance Tuesday night against the New York
Yankees. At the top of the list isthat left-hander Doug Davis is
being considered by manager Johnny Oates as a reliever next season
rather than a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly interested in Doug Davis as a starter, but I
think he would also be ideal as the second left-hander in the
bullpen,'' Oates said. ``With our depth of starting pitchers, that
might be his future as a reliever.''
</P>
<P>
   Sikorski is filling in while Ryan Glynn is on the disabled list.
But when Glynn returns, Sikorski could stay in the rotation and
Davis could go to the bullpen. It's not so much that Oates is
enamored with Sikorski, who has made only one start in the majors,
but he knows he must make room in next year's rotation for both
Darren Oliver and Justin Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes two left-handers in the bullpen and currently Mike
Venafro is the only one. \Nsubheds:Sikorski saves the day Other
repercussions from Brian Sikorski's outing against the Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   It kept Darren Oliver in the minors. While Sikorski was throwing
seven scoreless innings against the Yankees, Oliver was making his
second start for Triple-A Oklahoma. Oliver allowed one run in five
innings against the Las Vegas Stars, but gave up five hits and four
walks.
</P>
<P>
   If Sikorski had bombed, the Rangers probably would have brought
back Oliver to pitch Monday against the Yankees. Instead, Sikorski
will start against the Yankees, and Oliver will remain in the
minors on medical rehabilitation assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Glynn, on the disabled list because of Friday's fainting
spell, will join Oliver in Triple A on medical rehabilitation
assignment and will probably pitch next Thursday. Sikorski isn't
eligible to come off the disabled list until Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Sikorski will get at least two more starts, but he's also likely
to stay with the Rangers the remainder of the season. He can't be
sent to the minors unless he clears outright waivers, and his
performance against the Yankees makes it more likely he'll be
claimed. \Nsubheds:O'Brien snags Sikorski General manager Doug
Melvin gave assistant GM Dan O'Brien credit for recommending Brian
Sikorski when the Houston Astros put him on waivers in the
off-season. O'Brien knew Sikorski from his time with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``He drafted him in the fourth round in 1995 and recommended we
pick him up if he became available,'' Melvin said. ``I heard Kansas
City had interest in him. In fact, we were at the general managers
meetings \Rin November\S and two teams told me they were
considering claiming him, but they just missed it because those
waiver things can get overlooked when you're at those meetings.''
\Nsubheds:30 for Palmeiro Rafael Palmeiro's home run Wednesday
night was his 30th of the season, marking the sixth consecutive
season he has hit that many. Among active players, Barry Bonds has
done it nine consecutive seasons and Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
have done it six consecutive seasons. Albert Belle has hit at least
30 home runs the past eight years, but has 22 this season.
\Nsubheds:Briefly Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra got the day
off yesterday, his first since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said he expects to talk with
outfielder Tyrell Godwin's agent again today. Godwin, the Rangers'
second pick in the June draft, has agreed to a $1.2-million
contract, but it's pending the results of a physical. The Rangers
have concerns about Godwin's right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said one problem with the baseball draft is that teams
aren't allowed to conduct mass tryouts or physicals on prospective
draft picks. He said baseball should conduct an NFL-style combine
before the draft.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
