<HEADLINE>
STREISAND HEADLINES FUND-RAISER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spirits were high at the Shrine Auditorium late
Thursday, where Democrats gathered to celebrate Al Gore's
acceptance speech at a bash that included performances by Barbra
Streisand, Babyface and Boyz II Men.
</P>
<P>
   The average ticket price for Thursday's fund-raiser was $1,000.
Whoopi Goldberg hosted.
</P>
<P>
   Although entertainment was on the marquee, politics was on the
minds of most who attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's speech was passionate and very good,'' said Santa
Monica resident Jon Graff, a ``mid-30s'' entertainment industry
worker waiting to enter the Shrine. ``He made a statement about
what he wants to accomplish, but I think Tipper did a better job of
explaining who Al is.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Jefferson Boulevard, about 200 members of the Screen
Actors Guild stood for a candlelight vigil to bring attention to
its continuing strike over residuals on commercials airing on cable
TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see Ms. Streisand and Ms. Goldberg come out here
and joins us,'' said actress Mariette Hartley, as she stood holding
a sign reading ``Soar with Gore'' with other union members. ``We
need visible faces so people can see what's going on. We need big
names to fight for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Los Angeles actress, Tisza Major, also called upon
Streisand to back the guild's cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you are done in there, come join us,'' she said.
``We need your voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Streisand so far has not commented on the strike. But it was
announced Thursday that negotiations would continue on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   News that President Clinton was again under investigation by a
Washington, D.C., grand jury did little to dampen the enthusiasm of
those who attended the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leak was disgraceful,'' said Democratic National Committee
Chairman Ed Rendell, who was attending the Shrine event. ``This was
obviously timed to deflect the attention from Al Gore's big day. I
do hope they bring Clinton to trial because that jury is going to
raise its hand and say, `Let's acquit the president and convict the
prosecutor.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
