<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5401 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-KIDNAPPED-BOY-LADN     08-18 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAPPED-BOY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDNAPPING LINKED TO DRUG DEBT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ORITH GOLDBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 15-year-old West Hills boy whose
bullet-riddled body was found in a Santa Barbara park had been
kidnapped because his older half-brother owed $36,000 in drug
money, detectives with the Santa Barbara County Sheriff's
Department announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, three suspects were cruising Nicholas
``Nick'' Samuel Markowitz's neighborhood looking for 22-year-old
Benjamin Markowitz but found the teen-ager instead. They grabbed
the teen and took him to the house of one of the suspect's parents
in Santa Barbara, where they kept him for two days before finally
taking him to the park and killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Markowitz was fed a steady diet of marijuana and
Valium while at the house, and friends of the suspects took to
calling Markowitz the ``stolen kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Markowitz's family was stunned by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no preparing for something of this magnitude,'' said
Nick's mother, Susan Markowitz. ``Right now, I have a hard time
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hikers found Nick's body in a shallow grave in the Los Padres
National Forest near Santa Barbara on Saturday. Nick had been shot
nine times, mostly in the head and torso, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said in Thursday's press conference in Santa Barbara
that four of five suspects have been arrested. But a fifth suspect,
identified as 20-year-old Jesse James Hollywood from the West
Valley area, remained at large.
</P>
<P>
   Authorites believe Hollywood was looking for Benjamin because he
allegedly owed Hollywood $36,000 from a past drug deal.
</P>
<P>
   The other four suspects were arrested Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   William Skidmore, 20, was arrested Wednesday afternoon at his
home in Simi Valley. Jesse Taylor Rugge, 20, was arrested near his
home on Casiano Drive in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan James Hoyt was taken into custody Wednesday at 11 p.m. just
after leaving a friend's home. Hollywood, Skidmore, Hoyt and Rugge
apparently knew one another from growing up in the West Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A 17-year-old boy, who police said dug Nick's grave, was
arrested after his parents brought him into the Santa Barbara
sheriff's station Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four suspects has been booked on suspicion of
kidnapping, criminal conspiracy and murder.
</P>
<P>
   The last family members to see Nick on the day he was kidnapped
were a cousin and uncle who live a few houses away from the
Markowitz family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were coming home from the gym and pulled over near
Ingomar (Street) and Chaminade High School to ask (Nick) if he
wanted a ride home and he said, 'No , I'm fine,' '' his cousin
said.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Nick's mother knew something was wrong when she
paged her son and he didn't call home, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 8, Susan Markowitz and her husband, Jeffrey, reported
Nick missing with the LAPD's West Valley Division.
</P>
<P>
   Rugge, Hollywood and Hoyt, driving in a rented van, are
suspected of kidnapping Nick on Aug. 6 and taking him to Rugge's
house in the 700 block of Casiano Drive in Santa Barbara, where he
was held for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that during Nick's stay at the Rugge residence, he
was given marijuana and Valium. During the daytime, he was told not
to make phone calls or leave the house but apparently had some
degree of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Police were uncertain if he had been more confined at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he was given a large amount of drugs there ...
perhaps as a way to keep him quiet and passive,'' said Santa
Barbara Sheriff Jim Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Rugge's parents were apparently home during that time, but
police said it did not appear they knew what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   Four or five juveniles who visited the home in those two days
knew that Nick had been kidnapped and even referred to him as the
``stolen kid,'' officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they went to great lengths to hide it,'' he
said. ``Then plans were hashed to commit the murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said it did not appear that the suspects contacted
Benjamin or his family to seek ransom. After two days in the house,
they moved Nick to a State Street hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Hoyt and the unidentified 17-year-old left the hotel
and went to Lizard's Mouth, a popular hiking site, to dig a grave.
When they returned, Hoyt, Rugge and the 17-year-old took Nick to
the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Nick was bound and Hoyt and Rugge placed duct tape over his
mouth, taped his hands behind his back, placed him in the grave and
shot and then buried him. The weapon, a semiautomatic handgun, was
recovered in the grave.
</P>
<P>
   That Saturday, hikers found the body buried in the shallow grave
and reported the find to authorities. Part of Nick's clothing was
visible in the grave, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are seeking the public's help in the arrest of
Hollywood, who is believed to be staying at various friends' homes.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with information about Hollywood's whereabouts is asked
to contact the Santa Barbara County Sheriff's Department at (805)
681-4150, or the anonymous tip line at (805) 681-4171.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial for Nick will be held today at 2 p.m. at the Groman
Eden Mortuary at 11500 Sepulveda Blvd. in Mission Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Markowitz said Benjamin would not attend the service
because he didn't want to draw attention to himself on a day when
Nick's memory will be honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope (Benjamin) uses the love his brother had for him to get
him through this,'' Susan Markowitz said. ``I can't imagine how he
is feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
