<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5402 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BLACK-VOTERS-SFCHRON &LR;      08-18 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-VOTERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEMOCRATS NOT TAKING BLACK VOTES FOR GRANTED  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Listen up, Miss Bertha in the beauty shop. You're
about to become one popular lady.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Bertha is a fictional character that Donna Brazile, Al
Gore's Mississippi-born campaign manager, who is African American,
likes to talk about. Because Gore's election may depend upon it.
</P>
<P>
   Brazile's creation is just about one of the most important
voters in America to the Democratic Party. Miss Bertha is average
folks, good people. Miss Bertha is African American.
</P>
<P>
   And while Miss Bertha has always voted Democratic, this time, &LR; 
she may not be fully convinced that Al Gore's the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to talk to Miss Bertha in the beauty shop, and
Uncle Bob at the barber shop, that's really how the grapevine
begins in the African American community,'' Brazile said Thursday.
``People start talking it up.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Brazile _ along with the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Rep.
Maxine Waters of Los Angeles, San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, and
a whole host of Congressional black caucus members _ appeared
before African American delegates Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They preached their hearts out on behalf of Gore and his running
mate, Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   And surprisingly, their message is not such an easy sell in the
African American community this year.
</P>
<P>
   Not when a charming, folksy guy named George W. Bush has taken
his Republican message right into African American communities.
He's talking diversity and education. He's campaigning with J.C.
Watts. He had break dancers and rap artists and Chaka Khan _ could
you believe  &UR; that?  &LR; _ at his GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   It worked: Miss Bertha has started looking his way. So the
Democrats have to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Bertha knows Al Gore as Vice President Al Gore. She
doesn't know Al Gore, his story, what he's fought for, what he
intends to do, his presidency,'' Brazile said. ``And she's going to
hear the personal story _ who Al Gore is, and what his values are.
She's going to know that Al Gore is on her side.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miss Bertha and Uncle Bob have some other doubts, too. They
need to know that Lieberman is on their side, on issues like
affirmative action, even though he's been more conservative and
belongs to groups like the Democratic Leadership Council.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Waters was the first, and the most vocal, in raising some
of those issues this week.
</P>
<P>
   And another, unspoken question lingered in the background for
the Miss Berthas of the world: Did Lieberman's selection, as a
Jewish man, mean African Americans have been forgotten or bypassed,
or _ worse _ taken for granted by Democrats?
</P>
<P>
   It was Jesse Jackson Thursday who strode into the African
American delegation to hash the whole thing out, including what he
called the ``black-Jewish question.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson understands the issues, the doubts, the anger, and yes,
the conflicting emotions here; he once referred to New York as
``hymietown,'' and later apologized.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, he challenged African Americans ``to vote our
hopes and our dreams, not our fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are people who suggest there's ``an invisible quota''
of Jewish people in politics. But, Jackson said, blacks and Jews
have a common ground of ``shared suffering ... and shared
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are people of all kinds ``who have hang-ups about
Jews,'' he said. ``But that is not our religion. We are not raised
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks didn't keep Jews off the (presidential) ticket until
last Tuesday,'' he said. ``Blacks didn't lock Jews out of the
country clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger picture is this: Blacks and Jews marched together''
in the civil rights movement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he was not concerned with Lieberman's more
conservative bent. ``I'm not hung up by the Democratic Leadership
Council and the certain wing of the party. Because it takes two
wings to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was not concerned with the public doubts and perceptions
of the lead man on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say Al Gore is not charismatic,'` he said. ``We got a
surplus of charisma.  &UR; We need some resources. &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Bertha, get ready.
</P>
<P>
   Between the Republicans and the Democrats, your dance card is
gonna be full.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
