<HEADLINE>
COMETS BEAT SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Los Angeles Sparks played 34 games this year with
only four losses, but none were as bad as the one they played
Thursday night in the opener of the best-of-three Western
Conference Finals at the Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, there was nothing that they could do to change
their destructive course. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time defending WNBA champion Houston Comets, who lost
three regular-season games to Los Angeles, brought the Sparks down
to earth in a hurry and shackled them, 77-56, in front of a
deafening crowd of 14,597.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets had a playoff record 15 steals translating into 23
turnovers by the Sparks, who had nine miscues in the first nine
minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played 39 minutes of ugly basketball,'' Sparks coach
Michael Cooper said. ``It's just one of those games. Hopefully,
we'll get it out of our system, because we have two days to work us
out a situation, we'll look at game film ... and we'll come back
and play a better game on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The series moves to the Forum in Inglewood where the Sparks face
a must-win situation when the teams meet at 1 p.m. If they win,
they will play in the decisive game Monday at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' Sheryl Swoopes, who was honored as the league's most
valuable player, and Cynthia Cooper, a two-time MVP, set the tone
early. They combined for 25 points first-half points to give
Houston a comfortable 40-23 margin at the break. Swoopes finished
with 22 points, six rebounds, a playoff record five steals, and
Cooper had 21 points. Tina Thompson had 12 as the Houston's Big
Three outscored the Sparks starters, 55-52.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika tried to keep the Sparks in the game with a playoff
record 7 of 11 3-pointers for a team-high 21 points, but she wasn't
getting a lot of help.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were unable to get the defensive stops they needed to
slow the Comets' attack. DeLisha Milton, who fouled out with 10
points, scored two early baskets to start the second half and cut
the Sparks losses to 40-27. But Swoopes answered with a quick
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Houston took its first lead when Cooper came off back-to-back
screens to put the Comets ahead 8-4. The Comets built a 19-4
advantage and things just got worst for the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out ready to play,'' Milton said. ``They study us
well and did a good job with what we were trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was just anxious to play. The ball just didn't
bounce for us, it bounced against us. I don't think we were really
in sync. We were spastic.`'The Sparks' guards struggled. Tamecka
Dixon could not buy a basket. She was 1 for 9 and Ukari Figgs was 1
for 6. They had six assists between them and eight turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just didn't come out focused,'' Dixon said. ``We played the
worst basketball that we've ever played and we were still in the
game, We just couldn't get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other team that really took the Sparks out of their
comfort zone was the expansion Seattle Storm, which took the Sparks
to overtime games to earn a split. But Thursday's loss sent the
Sparks to their lowest point in the best season the franchise has
enjoyed in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just were not on the same page this time,'' said Leslie,
who had 14 points and eight rebounds. ``What we practiced to do I
guarantee you we didn't do it. I said all year, we've lost four
games not doing what the coaches have asked us to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5404 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION     08-18 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ACCEPTS NOMINATION, SEIZES CHANCE TO CHAMPION WORKING 
 FAMILIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Moving to separate himself from President Clinton
_ but not from the economic success of the past eight years _ Al
Gore accepted the Democratic Party's presidential nomination
Thursday by pledging to ``make sure that our prosperity enriches
not just the few, but all working families.''
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited address on the final night of the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles, the vice president vowed to
battle his Republican rivals on issues that matter to American
workers. ``My focus is on working families,'' Gore said. ``People
trying to make house payments and car payments, working overtime to
save for college and do right by their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   He also played off his reputation as a dull, policy wonk by
suggesting that a little boredom might not be bad for an America
exhausted by the national roller-coaster ride of the Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you entrust me with the presidency, I know I won't always
be the most exciting politician,'' Gore said. ``But I pledge to you
tonight: I will work for you every day and I will never let you
down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what presidents are supposed to do, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-minute speech also served as Gore's attempt to
reintroduce himself to the voters after eight years in Clinton's
long shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're entering a new time; we're electing a new president,''
he said. ``And I stand here tonight as my own man, and I want you
to know me for who I truly am.''
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president didn't distance himself from the economic
prosperity of the past eight years. Gore reminded the audience of
the country's fragile economic condition when he and Clinton took
over from the Republicans and President George Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not forget that a few years ago, you were also working
hard. But your hard work was undone by a government that didn't
work, didn't put people first and wasn't on your side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a rapid-fire delivery, Gore shifted between his vision of a
new and better life for America's working people and specific
references to the policies he believes will get them there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to talk seriously about the issues,'' the vice
president said. ``I believe people deserve to know specifically
what a candidate proposes to do. I intend to tell you tonight. You
ought to be able to know, and then judge for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore brought some people into the convention hall with him,
people with the type of problems he vowed to solve: a couple
fighting an HMO to get full-time nursing care for their disabled
young son, a working mother seeking to send a daughter to college,
an elderly woman struggling to pay prescription drug bills, a
family seeking a better school for their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this election is about Mildred Nystel, Jacqueline
Johnson, Caterina Gutierrez, Ian Malone,'' Gore said. ``It's about
millions of Americans whose names we may never know _ but whose
needs and dreams must always be our calling.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was interrupted more than 40 times by applause as
delegates waving flags and blue-and-white ``Gore'' pennants roared
their approval.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke with marked confidence, displaying only occasional
evidence of the wooden mannerisms or halting delivery that has
haunted him in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He softened up ... he took loose lessons,'' said William
Silver, a convention volunteer from Miami. ``A lot of the details
(of policy), we already knew. But he brought it to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Harris of Los Angeles, a security worker and Democratic
volunteer inside the Staples Center, was equally impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a good job,'' she said. ``There's only one Bill
Clinton. But Al Gore's his own man.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president made sure his theme _ and the likely focus of
the fall campaign _ wouldn't be missed. He repeated the phrase
``working families'' nine times and used the words ``fight'' or
``fighting'' 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are likely to hear those words over and over before the
November election, starting Friday on a riverboat trip along the
Mississippi River that will include stops in Wisconsin, Iowa,
Illinois and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing about the job of the president,'' Gore said.
``It is the only job in the Constitution that is charged with the
responsibility of fighting for all the people ... not just the
wealthy or powerful _ all the people. Especially those who need a
voice; those who need a champion; those who need to be lifted up,
so they are never left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Without ever mentioning Texas Gov. George W. Bush, his
Republican opponent, Gore tried to highlight some of the
differences between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my own imperfections,'' he said. ``I know that
sometimes people say I'm too serious, that I talk too much
substance and policy. Maybe I've done that tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the presidency is more than a popularity contest,'' he
continued. ``It's a day-by-day fight for people. Sometimes, you
have to choose to do what's difficult or unpopular. Sometimes, you
have to be willing to spend your popularity in order to pick the
hard right over the easy wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's press secretary, wasted little time in
responding to Gore's speech, saying he ``offered more of the same
old language of class warfare, partisanship and division.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of last night's program was devoted to giving people a look
behind the political persona of Al Gore. A parade of friends,
relatives, colleagues and others talked about Gore as a boy, a
college student, a soldier in Vietnam, a congressman and vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   After holding a job that, almost by definition, made Gore
invisible for eight years, Democratic leaders believe the vice
president is ``well-known, but not known well,'' in the words of
one commentator.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Republicans trying to paint Gore as a man who would
say and do anything to become president, the Democrats believe it
is critical to put a human face on their nominee.
</P>
<P>
   That job went, in part, to Gore's wife, Tipper, who narrated a
campaign video featuring, she said, ``a little bit more about Al
and the life of our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also tried to change his image as a man of privilege, a man
whose father was a senator and who grew up in a Washington hotel
and attended exclusive schools.
</P>
<P>
   His father grew up poor in Possum Hollow, Tenn., and was
teaching in a single-room schoolhouse when he was 18, Gore said
last night. His mother waited tables to earn enough money to go to
law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did give me a good life,'' he said. ``But like so many in
America, they started out with almost nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Democrats have been saying that Gore's acceptance
speech represented a do-or-die chance to make his case to the
American people. But in recent days, some party leaders have been
trying to lower expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware told California delegates earlier
this week not to lose heart if Gore's speech doesn't deliver a
knockout punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ... he doesn't hit it out of the ballpark, don't worry
about it,'' he said. ``He still deserves your overwhelming
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls this week have reinforced Democrats' concerns about the
fall campaign against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had an 11-point lead over Gore, 48 percent to 37 percent _
the same as Wednesday _ in a Voter.com-Battleground tracking poll
released Thursday. The poll has an error margin of 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has yet to see any convention ``bounce'' in
his tracking poll numbers. But in the week between the conventions
_ when he announced his selection of Connecticut Sen. Joseph
Lieberman as his running mate _ he cut in half the 18-point lead
held by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the convention, and especially Thursday, the
Democrats tried to project a feeling of unity and confidence behind
their new ticket. That's why Los Angeles Rep. Maxine Waters'
complaints about Lieberman's positions on affirmative action and
school vouchers sent party officials into a frenzy this week.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting privately with Lieberman and then listening to him
speak to the Congressional Black Caucus on Tuesday, Waters' vow of
support sounded lukewarm at best. But the feisty congresswoman
appeared to make up for it Thursday when she spoke to the
California delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My new best friend is Joe Lieberman, and make no mistake about
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle news services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
