<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5405 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GORE-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON     08-18 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ACCEPTANCE SPEECH, GORE REDEFINES CAMPAIGN IN TERMS
OF  ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Republicans have portrayed the 2000 election as a
campaign about leadership. Thursday night, Al Gore sought to
redefine it as a contest over issues.
</P>
<P>
   Honor, Gore declared, is earned by fighting to raise the minimum
wage, expand child care, enforce civil rights laws, protect
affirmative action and preserve a woman's right to an abortion.
Leadership, he asserted, is tested by standing up to cigarette
makers, to drug manufacturers and to big oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned President Clinton just once during the 51-minute
address. And he never brought up the matter that led to Clinton's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying message was unmistakable. Every time
Republicans bring up character _ a persistent theme of the GOP's
convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago _ Gore will respond with
issues. Responsibility, he said, is to be measured by one's
commitment to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, honor is not just a word, but an obligation,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's effort to refocus the campaign on issues is
understandable considering his double-digit deficit in the polls.
Most surveys show that while Americans agree with Gore's positions
on paying down the national debt, spending the surplus on Social
Security and Medicare, and providing new prescription drug
benefits, they see Texas Gov. George W. Bush as more of a leader.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sought to look presidential by entering the Staples Center
from a side entrance and working his way up to the podium through
the crowd a la Rocky Balboa. He then stood alone on the oversized
stage, speaking in a tone that began as reflective and built its
way up to a more combative conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used the word ``fight'' no fewer than two dozen times,
trying to regain the spirit that propelled him past Democratic
rival Bill Bradley in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when his campaign was sputtering and Bradley was
surging past him in the polls, Gore suddenly seemed to find the
rationale for his candidacy in a series of fiery speeches in which
he presented himself as a fighter for Democratic ideals.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast at the time was with the more subdued Bradley, whom
he portrayed as merely going through an ``academic exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore would never accuse Bush of anything so cerebral. The
contrast with his GOP rival is different. When Gore first entered
the U.S. Congress, Bush was still struggling in the oil business.
When Gore was elected to the Senate, Bush was working for the Texas
Rangers baseball team. Gore was already vice president when his
opponent won his first election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not directly bring up experience, as Bush's father did
against Clinton eight years ago. But he made it clear that he has
been ``fighting'' for ``working families'' for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know this: I've taken on the powerful forces.
And as president, I'll stand up to them, and I'll stand up for
you,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Substance Over Style
</P>
<P>
   With much written about his stylistic shortcomings, Gore even
sought to turn his own reputation as an awkward speaker into an
advantage, saying: ``perhaps I talk too much substance and
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's address came two years to the day after President
Clinton's grand jury testimony in the Monica Lewinsky matter. Hours
before his speech, word spread through the convention center that a
new grand jury would investigate whether Clinton should be
prosecuted for alleged lies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made clear that he would not be hung by the rope that
Republicans have tried to use against Democrats since the scandal
first broke. He talked at length about his family, and was
introduced by his wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's best family moment came 24 hours before, when he made a
surprise trip to the podium following a speech by his daughter,
Karenna. Gore walked onto the stage and gave her a warm hug. Though
he did not say a word to the delegates roaring their approval, the
moment spoke volumes about his devotion to his family.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Gore rattled off a list of core Democratic
priorities, hewing less to the center than Bush did in Philadelphia
two weeks ago. Perhaps it was a reflection of Gore's need to shore
up the party's liberal base, which is less solidly behind him than
conservatives are behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the centrist tone of the Democratic ticket was obvious
throughout the four-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence that of all the Bay Area Democrats to
speak from the podium, Rep. Ellen Tauscher _ the most conservative
of the Northern California congressional delegation _ got a prime
spot on the final night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was given a hero's welcome by the Democratic faithful, and
his speech won rave reviews in the earliest analyses.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even the most spectacular speeches sometimes lead to
unpredictable results. Former President Bush's 1988 address was the
launching point for his come from behind victory over Democrat
Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   But it contained a line that came back to haunt him four years
later.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress pushes to raise Taxes, Bush said, ``I'll say to
them: `Read my lips. No new taxes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Bush agreed to tax cuts. And two years after
that, Clinton defeated him for the presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
