<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BEFORE CLASS, A LESSON IN SALVATION  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dignity pops up in the strangest places.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Street just off Sixth Street's sad pawn-shop row is a
urine-soaked alley and pavement hotel. At 8 o'clock Thursday
morning, a man was sipping a Colt 45 and sucking a stogie, a woman
was raging incoherently, a few street people were sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   But in front of the Salvation Army Service Center, the sidewalk
was hosed clean and a few moms and kids were lined up quietly.
</P>
<P>
   They were waiting for their appointment times to enter the
building and shop for back-to-school clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything better than wearing that cool new shirt and
carrying that brand-new notebook on the first day back to school?
Your stuff is tight and you are ready to take on whatever they
might throw at you.
</P>
<P>
   But lots of kids don't get back-to-school clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a lot of them will delay going to school for a week or
two, so they don't have to be the only ones with no new clothes,''
says Salvation Army Lt. Col. Bettie Love.
</P>
<P>
   So every year at this time, the Army turns its big building into
a brightly decorated store where financially challenged parents who
have signed up and qualified bring their kids and load up. About
3,600 kids will shop here this week. Most of the stuff is donated
by Sears.
</P>
<P>
   There are balloons and displays, racks of nice new clothes,
underwear, backpacks, pencils and crayons. There are volunteer
personal shoppers to help with sizes and styles.
</P>
<P>
   There is no counter where someone slings you a charity bag of
donated stuff. There are no cash registers. There is dignity.
</P>
<P>
   First into the store is a grandma named Leather. She's shopping
for her five grandchildren, ages 5 through 13, who live with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have to buy clothes, but this will help,'' she says.
``I'm on SSI, their mother is in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrell, third grade, holds up his new sweat pants, WWF T-shirt
and hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get new friends,'' he says. ``I'll fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll fit in because of your personality and attitude,'' his
mother says.
</P>
<P>
   But now maybe he'll fit in better with himself.
</P>
<P>
   A SENSE OF humor, whatever happened to that?
</P>
<P>
   The MasterCard people are suing the Ralph Nader campaign because
a Nader-for-prez TV commercial is a spoof of MasterCard's
``Priceless Moments'' TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``(W)e will always do whatever it takes to protect the
campaign,'' said a high-ranking MasterCard drone.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy Awards people are miffed at Gov. Gray Davis for
presenting President Clinton with a spoof Oscar statuette at a
party Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy folk are afraid people think it's a real Oscar and
an official presentation. Do those movie people think we're idiots?
Wait, I've seen a couple of movies lately. They do think we're
idiots.
</P>
<P>
   But you know, it's time the Academy people admitted their
horrible error in not awarding Clinton the real best-actor Oscar
for his performance in the ``That Woman, Miss Lewinsky'' speech. I
get emotional just thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   SAD DAYS at Mama's, the little breakfast-lunch cafe on
Washington Square. Frances Muriel Sanchez _ Mama to everyone _
passed away last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   She also had restaurants at Macy's and on Nob Hill, and they say
Mama gave out as many free meals, through various charitable causes
and simply over the sill, as she sold.
</P>
<P>
   She could sing, and socialize. And cook? Says one regular, ``I
remember seeing Julia Child standing in line for a breakfast
table.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR EVERY item there is an equal and opposite correction.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's easternmost province is  &UR; not  &LR; a tip of Alameda
that spills over the mid-Bay boundary line, maintains Steven
Appleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the Sierra, where the City is the proud owner of the
Hetch Hetchy dam and watershed system.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, Jeff. That can't be part of San Francisco. I've been to
Hetch Hetchy. There's parking.
</P>
<P>
   And re: an item about Palo Alto's golden retrievers who drive
Porsches, Jeff Denno says, ``I would have thought they would have
preferred to drive Rovers.''
</P>
<P>
   DASHIN' NASH Bridges has the cool car, and in a recently filmed
episode he was bustin' the bay in a 38-foot Donzi Daytona
speedboat.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Rinehart, a San Rafael boat broker often used as a maritime
tech adviser for movies and TV, says the boat sells for around
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could Nash buy one of those on a police captain's salary?''
Joe wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Joe hasn't heard about the city employees' generous overtime
scams.
</P>
<P>
   AT LEAST BART has a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   At the Colma BART station, Holly Rizzo has noticed a brand-new
electronic message sign in the window of one information booth. All
week the sign has said in bright red letters, ``Welcome to Coma.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a party. BYO life support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
