r e BC-TV-CHRISCRAFT-COMMENT     08-18 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHRISCRAFT-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER UPN, FOX FIGURES TO FILL A VOID WITH MORE VOID 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So News Corp., which is to say Fox, will buy the Chris-Craft
television stations, squeeze out UPN and launch another Fox
network.
</P>
<P>
   Those stations include KBHK in San Francisco, and Rupert Murdoch
says a Fox 2 broadcast network is under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Without the stations that formed its core group, Viacom's UPN
network faces extinction even before its name changes to the
Paramount Network.
</P>
<P>
   But let's bring it down to earth. What this means to you is that
in one giant leap, you could go from ``Shasta McNasty'' to
something not quite as good as ``World's Wildest Police Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   What a bargain for the public.
</P>
<P>
   That's why God put Murdoch on the planet, and gave him American
citizenship along with all the newspapers and TV networks he could
possibly eat. And then some more.
</P>
<P>
   When Murdoch burps, he exhales the gaseous fumes of yet another
TV network.
</P>
<P>
   I'd weep no tears for UPN, a network that found its raison
d'etre in inciting hormonal disturbances among 13-year-old boys.
</P>
<P>
   But the slumberous public officials who are supposed to regulate
the broadcasting industry ought to prop themselves up on their
elbows, clear the cobwebs and ask a question.
</P>
<P>
   Why should Fox program another broadcast network when it can't
even program the original Fox?
</P>
<P>
   I direct your attention to the Fox fall schedule. At 8 p.m.
Wednesdays, watch for that audience favorite, ``To Be Announced.''
At 8:30 Wednesdays, ``The Untitled John Goodman Project.'' Just
Thursday, it was named ``Normal, Ohio.'' It'll premiere ...
sometime abnormal.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m. Thursdays, ``To Be Announced.'' At 9 p.m. Thursdays,
``To Be Announced.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox is scampering toward the fall season in wild disarray,
without dirt to fill all the holes. The average job tenure of its
entertainment presidents is roughly six minutes. If that's the
state of Fox's A team, what'll make its way onto a Fox 2 schedule?
Reruns of ``To Be Announced''?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Fox is more than broadcast TV. It's also cable. Lots
of cable, including the extra-glossy FX cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, one of the signature shows on FX is the bonzo bikini
Howard Stern production, ``Son of the Beach,'' which to date has
consumed 15 hours of time _ 15 minutes of which were funny.
</P>
<P>
   The TV industry has never been more industrial. It's big, and
ever bigger, companies trying to seize every programming venue in
sight, but demonstrating zero programming acumen to fill the
acquired space.
</P>
<P>
   The object, at a time of splintered audiences, is to grab shelf
space and hope your Fox-Fox 2-Fox Family Channel-FX-Fox News
Channel-Fox Sports is in aggregate huger than the other guy's
CBS-UPN-Showtime-MTV-VH1-Nickelodeon-et al.
</P>
<P>
   But consolidation hasn't been a vitamin for valuable programming
ideas to benefit the public. The blind energy is devoted to
acquisitions and mergers. Then the dust settles on low-rent
programming.
</P>
<P>
   To fulfill its neglected promise, television needs fewer bean
counters and more artisans. The trend line runs the other
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate reach exceeds creative grasp. It's the story of
television at the moment. Conglomerates want plenty, only to
deliver plenty of nuttin'.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
