<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5409 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SATELLITE-SFCHRON &LR;      08-18 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OFFICE AWAY FROM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY YAMANOUCHI  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Somewhere between road warrior and telecommuter
in traffic-clogged Marin County, Calif., Sue Russell has found the
workplace that makes the best use of her time.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Russell had dreaded fighting traffic for nearly an
hour to get to work, but she didn't like the idea of working from
home.
</P>
<P>
   Now, each morning she drives five minutes to a small office park
near her Petaluma, Calif., home, sets up her laptop and works for a
couple of hours. By 10 a.m., when the rush hour has passed, she
gets into her car for a smooth sail on Highway 101 to her office at
Fair, Isaac &AMP; Co. in San Rafael, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping employees content in their jobs by easing their commute
is a big priority for companies trying to attract and retain
workers.
</P>
<P>
   For many companies, telecommuting has been a popular choice to
offer employees frustrated with traffic tie-ups and rising gas
prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, it isn't the answer for those whose office homes are
simply too noisy or distracting. It also doesn't work for those
whose homes aren't technologically equipped for their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In these circumstances, enterprising companies are setting up
telecommuting centers somewhere between the residential areas of
their workers and the company office.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is flexible enough to allow telecommuters to
work there a couple of hours or the entire day.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are beginning to take note on how it can be used,''
said David Fleming, telework consultant to the state Department of
Personnel Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The telecenter idea surfaced six years ago when the California
Department of Transportation sponsored the opening of 15 sites.
Short on money for marketing, the idea never caught on, and the
underused centers eventually closed.
</P>
<P>
   The centers have been a tough sell in the private sector.
Consultants in the telecommuting industry say they have been trying
to gain support for the idea, but some managers are reluctant to
make the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, transportation consultants hope technological advances
will make these centers more attractive. With high-speed Internet
access connections more accessible for small-business operations,
commute centers can now be run more effectively than five years
ago, said Jeffrey Weil, a commercial real estate broker.
</P>
<P>
   Fair, Isaac, a financial softwaremaker with a number of
employees living in the Petaluma area, is among a handful of
companies in the San Francisco Bay Area that has opened telecommute
centers in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 14 employees use Fair, Isaac's Petaluma telecommuting
center daily.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, which invested $150,000 to set up the office three
years ago, spends $6,500 a month in rent and operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to 22 workstations, the center has such amenities as
conference rooms, a fax machine, a copier, printers, filing
cabinets, a refrigerator and a coffeemaker.
</P>
<P>
   The tab for rent and upkeep can add up. Abe Kleinfeld, who
manages the center, has had to start seeking ways to cut costs.
Other businesses, including Birkenstock, Autodesk and PG&AMP;E, have
asked to share the resource and expenses with Fair, Isaac so they
can offer the benefit to their employees. But Kleinfeld said he
first has to work out the possible security and safety risks.
</P>
<P>
   For those workers who have used it, the center has been a plus.
On a day when he works from the commute center, ``I get more time
at home and more time at the office,'' said Len Mowat, a Fair,
Isaac manager.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said that if she doesn't have meetings to attend, she
works all day from the commute office.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is not feasible to work from home because her
husband runs a home-based business that uses her home's only phone
line. In addition, her 9-year-old son and 6-year-old twin daughters
can be distracting.
</P>
<P>
   As a mother, Russell finds the commute center convenient. If she
has to take her kids to the doctor or ballet lessons in Petaluma
during the day, she will bring her kids to the commute center,
where they play in a conference room when it isn't being used.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're loud, it may interrupt people, but at least not as
many are being interrupted'' compared with the larger San Rafael
office, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Fair, Isaac employees say the company generally trusts its
employees to regulate their own work, adding that the firm
considers it more important to get the job done than to worry about
how many hours a worker is seen in the office.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who has worked at Fair, Isaac for 11 years and is now a
senior employee, said there was no problem getting approval from
her manager to use the commute center.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommute center works best for employees with
information-based jobs that can be done anywhere with a network
connection and a telephone. In that regard, industry experts say
such centers suit the needs of the Bay Area's many high-tech and
financial-services workers.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Mountain View, Calif., chip designer Synopsys. It
opened a telecommuting center in Pleasanton, Calif., a year ago to
cater to the needs of about 200 employees living on the east side
of San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of public transportation between the East Bay and
Mountain View forced workers in the Livermore, Calif., area, for
instance, to make a nearly two hour-drive in sluggish traffic to
the company office.
</P>
<P>
   The Pleasanton telecommuting center enables Synopsys employees
to work out of that office until highway gridlock eases.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Donaldson, the facility director, said East Bay
employees are saving eight to nine hours a week under the
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the gain in productivity, supporters of such centers
say the facilities help recruit and retain employees. Synopsys
found it could broaden its search for workers to as far east as
Stockton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Trent West, a software engineer, said having the option to use
the commute center was a tie-breaking factor between Fair, Isaac
and another job offer.
</P>
<P>
   When he doesn't have meetings, he works all day at the commute
center. In Petaluma, there are far fewer interruptions than during
a typical day in San Rafael. There is the option of working at
home, but there, he has only one phone line and a slower network
connection.
</P>
<P>
   A satellite office can also help a company pare operational
costs. For companies with offices in downtown areas where office
rents are high, Weil said, a satellite office paired with other
cost-saving measures can be a better deal than a branch office.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommuting center idea isn't for everyone, especially
those concerned with having enough ``face time'' with their bosses.
And anyone who thrives on the company's social environment would
wither away in the rather silent Petaluma commute center.
</P>
<P>
   But coping with a nomadic work style may be worth it for those
who put a premium on their free time, outside of the driver's seat.
Spending a day working from an office closer to home might mean
that a working parent can make it to a soccer game, rather than
getting home at a child's bedtime, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at kyamanouchi(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
