<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SATELLITE:  &LR; Keeping employees content in their jobs by easing their
commute is a big priority for companies trying to attract and
retain workers. For many companies, telecommuting has been a
popular choice to offer employees frustrated with traffic tie-ups
and rising gas prices. However, it isn't the answer for those whose
office homes are simply too noisy or distracting. It also doesn't
work for those whose homes aren't technologically equipped for
their jobs. In these circumstances, enterprising companies are
setting up telecommuting centers somewhere between the residential
areas of their workers and the company office.  &UR; By &LR; 
 &UR; Kelly Yamanouchi &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
NETWORTH: Giving stock options to most employees, not just top
executives, has a negligible impact on shareholder returns,
according to the biggest study yet on broad-based stock option
plans. That's actually good news for shareholders.  &UR; Column
by &LR;  &UR; Kathleen Pender &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
