<P>
   NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL (Undated) _ When Gov. George Pataki visited
the newly opened New Covenant charter school in Albany last fall,
he proclaimed it a model of the kind of educational change he was
trying to create. In the months following the visit, however, New
Covenant descended into apparent chaos, with fourth-graders scoring
among the lowest in the state on standardized tests, the for-profit
company overseeing the school resigning and two principals
quitting. How things went so wrong so quickly at New Covenant is a
cautionary tale for entrepreneurs, education reformers and
politicians who are tempted by the vaunted promise of charter
schools. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SKIN-CELLS (Undated) _ The source of the new skin cells that
replace those shed in every day's wear and tear turn out to be
hiding in the roots of the hair. The finding, if confirmed, could
lead to better understanding of how the skin heals as well as to
insights into basal cell carcinoma, a common skin cancer. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SF-QUAKE (Undated) _ A notorious fault that runs through
Berkeley, Calif., may not be capable of generating a large
earthquake on its own, scientists report Thursday. Using a new
technique based on measurements taken from space and from deep
within the earth, the researchers conclude that the Hayward fault
is creeping steadily along its entire width and depth, relieving
the tectonic stresses. However, people who live near the fault are
still in danger of heavy damage from quakes along faults nearby. By
Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
