 PERSONALS: A Baby by Any Other Name 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Following a path blazed when Candlestick became 3Com, a Hutchinson,
Kan., couple have won $5,000 by naming their just-born baby boy
 &UR; Iuma Dylan-Lucas Thornhill &LR; , his first name in paid homage to
Internet Underground Music Archive of Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its offer of the prize, to the first 10 babies
named Iuma born between August 1 and November 1, is ``the final
frontier in online marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Iuma's father,  &UR; Travis Thornhill &LR; , 22, said he had learned about
the contest the night before the baby was born and discussed it
with his wife,  &UR; Jessica &LR; , 21. They decided to go ahead with the
name because his mother, who he said is a metaphysical type,
predicted that the child would bring prosperity and good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WATERS' WORST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Waters &LR; , always a fount of opinions, told the New York
Post that ``Patch Adams'' and ``Forrest Gump'' are ``the twin
towers of bad cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both movies are shockingly bad,'' he said, ``but I think
`Patch Adams' is the `Pink Flamingos' for my generation. It's an
amazingly scary movie. Making me watch `Patch Adams' is like making
my grandmother watch `Pink Flamingos.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BRIGHT IDEAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In order to take advantage of the youthful passion for rainbow
hair colors, Clairol has a new XtremeFX hair color line aimed at
13- to 24-year-olds. Product manager  &UR; Karen Murabito &LR;  told the Wall
Street Journal that the company had rewritten its standard
instructions, using new ones with graffiti-style drawings and
phrases such as ``get it on'' instead of ``apply the product.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Writing in the Vallejo, Calif., journal Venus,  &UR; April Fresh &LR; 
describes the difficulties of finding brassieres appropriate for
women rock 'n' rollers. ``After coming home from show after show
with strap burns and soar (sic) breasts, I knew it was time to take
matters into my own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The RockBra, as described by Fresh but not yet manufactured,
would protect shoulders from guitar strap rub with one extra-wide
padded crossover strap. The other strap would be thin to allow the
free arm to swing around. Extra-firm padding in the cups would give
the breasts ``a safe landing area if jumping up and down is your
thing.'' The front would be cut extra high ``to prevent them from
coming out of the top of the bra.''
</P>
<P>
   The inventor says she's not ``trying to reach out to the
 &UR; Mariah Carey &LR; s or  &UR; Britney Spears &LR;  of the world. . . . It's all
about feeling good. Really good.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Stosh Wychulus &LR; , Personals' correspondent from the Market
Street Safeway in San Francisco, reports that an in-store Starbucks
Express kiosk is under construction, and coffee cup holders have
been installed on shopping carts. He's excited by the prospect of
``yuppies talking on their cell phones and mainlining caffeine as
they shop. Can aisle rage be far behind?''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Prince William &LR;  is to attend St. Andrews University in
Scotland, where he will major in art history, says the British
Press Association.
</P>
<P>
   _ W reports that  &UR; Giorgio Armani &LR; , who is opening a new store in
Rome, has been lobbying the government to remove a monument he says
is an eyesore. The work, an homage to former President and Prime
Minister  &UR; Sandro Pertini &LR; , stands in the piazza outside his store.
</P>
<P>
   Rival  &UR; Gianfranco Ferre &LR;  weighs in: ``Whether Giorgio likes it
or not, that monument is part of the city's cultural face. He only
noticed it now, because of the opening of the store.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The TV series ``West Wing'' won a Family Television Award but
has subsequently returned it, reports the Chicago Tribune.
Co-Executive Producer  &UR; John Wells &LR;  gave it back after an acceptance
speech made by  &UR; Allison Janney &LR;  _ who plays press secretary C.J.
Gregg _ was edited for the telecast of the ceremony. Janney's
expressed support of an actors strike was removed from her remarks.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Only difference between Hollywood and Washington is, in &LR; 
 &UR; Washington the people are uglier.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; James Carville &LR;  quoted in the New York Post.
</P>
