<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5422 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BO     08-18 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANSING, SOX RALLY IN NINTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dreams are made of this.
</P>
<P>
   A ball club bearing generations of unrequited hope spirals into
a morass of run-scoring misery. Each inning yields another lesson
in futility, as the days of the season dwindle and the situation
grows more dire.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the Improbable, if not _ dare anyone say it _ the
Impossible Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Defying every law of winning baseball except the most important
_ it ain't over 'til it's over _ the Red Sox Thursday night ended
their minidrama in Fenway with a cathartic, 8-7 victory over the
Texas Rangers. The crucial, come-from-far-behind triumph was capped
by Mike Lansing's two-out double off the Wall with the bases loaded
in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing crushed the winning hit on a night when the Sox had
seemed to invent ways to stymie themselves, leaving a staggering 15
runners on base and going 4 for 22 with runners in scoring
position. They had stranded 30 runners in the previous three games,
and their playoff chances appeared more in jeopardy with each
botched opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, they were in danger of falling five games behind
the East-leading Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, as 33,510 paying customers departed in glee and
tens of thousands of others in Red Sox country went to bed happy,
the Sox sensed something magical unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody can kind of feel the momentum changing,'' said
designated hitter Scott Hatteberg, who started the winning rally by
drawing a one-out walk off one of the game's top closers, John
Wetteland. ``We're going to be excited tonight, but we're
definitely going to carry it through (today.)''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Texas made the improbable occur. With two out
and Texas leading, 7-5, and Darren Lewis on first running for
Hatteberg, Jose Offerman whacked a single to right.
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer, Rico Brogna, who hit a two-out grand slam in the
ninth Monday night to lift the Sox to a dramatic victory over Tampa
Bay, ran for Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey reached first, loading the bases, when shortstop
Royce Clayton bobbled his routine grounder. Wetteland then hit Carl
Everett, scoring Lewis and cutting the Sox deficit to 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Up came Lansing, picked up last month from Colorado with pitcher
Rolando Arrojo. Lansing took a strike from Wetteland, then pounded
his next pitch off the Wall to score Brogna and Gilkey and win the
game. His teammates promptly mobbed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like waiting until the last at-bat,'' Lansing said,
``but they're a lot of fun when you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, who used every available position player,
vouched for that. The Sox were trailing, 6-2, after seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great victory for us to come back like that,'' Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the win, Rich Garces became the first reliever in Sox
history to start a season 8-0. Garces, who has now won his last 13
decisions, had seen that the Yankees won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important for us to win today because of the
Yankees,'' he said. ``Now we don't have to worry about them for a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, one of this season's biggest disappointments
after winning the AL West last year, the loss seemed like a
microcosm of a season gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game mirrored our whole season a lot,'' manager Johnny
Oates said. ``It stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing was, it was the Sox whose situation seemed so
desperate earlier in the night that the Fenway organist played a
rhapsodic version of ``Say A Little Prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even that didn't help, at least until the last three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox wasted promising scoring opportunities in each of the
first six innings. In the second, for example. Back-to-back singles
by Troy O'Leary and Lou Merloni, and a walk to Jason Varitek loaded
the bases with no outs. But Hatteberg flied to left, too shallow
for O'Leary to challenge Rusty Greer's arm. Then Manny Alexander,
playing shortstop as Nomar Garciaparra rested, went down on strikes
and Offerman flied out to left to scuttle the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Similar scenarios played out every inning until the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we had a lot of opportunities early in the game,''
Lansing said. ``But I don't think anybody was hanging their heads
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   With Texas leading, 6-1, in the seventh, O'Leary cut the deficit
to 6-2 by driving a home run around the Pesky Pole. It was
O'Leary's first home run in 86 at-bats, dating to July 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox rallied again in the eighth after Offerman walked and
Gilkey, pinch hitting for Trot Nixon, singled with no outs. After
Everett struck out, Lansing, pinch hitting for Brian Daubach,
doubled to make it 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary singled to first and Lansing scored when first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro threw the ball past the pitcher Mike Venafro, who
was running to cover first. Suddenly it was a 6-5 game.
</P>
<P>
   Texas added what seemed to be and insurance run in the ninth,
but it proved not to be enough. Garciaparra, who pinch hit for
Alexander in the seventh and finished, watched most of it from the
bench. But he liked what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never let up,'' he said. ``That says a lot about our
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-BOS &LR;      08-18 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM TUMBLES AROUND WILSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Olympus in sight and gold on their minds, the US men's
gymnastics team developed a slight stutter Thursday night at the
FleetCenter, with some of their best and brightest athletes
chopping up routines in the preliminary round of the Olympic
trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually everyone has one bad night,'' said head coach Peter
Kormann. ``I think a lot of our guys maybe had that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   First-night jitters or a frightening harbinger of what could be
ahead in Sydney?
</P>
<P>
   The answer could come Saturday afternoon in the finals, when
Kormann and his fellow decision-makers in USA Gymnastics must
decide who will be the half-dozen Yankees to go to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Already on board, without question, will be Blaine Wilson, who
again dominated the floor. Fresh from capturing his fifth
consecutive national title in St. Louis last month, Wilson opened
with an impressive 9.95 on rings and stormed his way to a
first-place finish for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt on,'' said Wilson. ``Things felt all in my grasp. What
did I have, one, two, three, maybe four sticks? But I'm probably my
worst critic. I didn't score a (perfect) 60. But, nobody can be
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   When Saturday night arrives, the men ranked 1-4 automatically
will be ticketed for Sydney. Now with 70 percent of their scores
totaled, with the July nationals counting for 40 percent, Wilson
holds the No. 1 spot, followed by Paul Hamm, Sean Townsend, and
Stephen McCain. The other two spots will be picked by Kormann and
the governing body. And Kormann was adamant upon leaving the
building that all athletes ranked 5-17 will receive equal
consideration for the trip Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy call,'' stressed Kormann, the former Olympic
bronze medalist from Braintree. ``It wouldn't be fair to preguess
what might happen. Even the 17th-placed guy will get a fair look.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Chris Young, just back after shredding an
Achilles' tendon in January, now ranks 17th overall. He badly
botched rings (7.8) and floor exercise (7.5).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really my first meet back,'' said the amiable Young, who
is Wilson's roommate at the Olympic training center. ``I did OK.
Not great, but OK. I've got to get some of those not-so-goods to be
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 10,250 clearly saw America's best hope for a medal in
Wilson, the former Ohio State star who was a member of the '96 team
in Atlanta. His lowest mark was a 9.475 on floor, improving from
there on pommel horse (9.525), vault (9.9), and high bar (9.825).
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical Blaine, I'd say,'' said an admiring Young. ``It's his
determination, combined with how hard he works _ he just works his
rear end off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kormann was duly impressed with Wilson's first-place finish in
St. Louis. But he wasn't convinced his prized student, whom he
coached at Ohio State, was yet ready to challenge legitimately for
a medal in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Following Thursday night, Kormann wasn't ready to annoint Wilson
the next American medalist, but he saw him inching closer to the
medal stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see he is much closer,'' said Kormann. ``He could win it. He
can. No question. But he needs to refine some things, too. I've
never seen him better than he was here, and I've been watching him
since he was 10 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   The night's biggest concern for the Yanks had to be the
lackluster work of two-time Olympian John Roethlisberger. He fell
off the high bar (9.35) and then botched his first approach on
floor exercise (8.3). He is now seated No. 7 and will be reaching
in his pocket for a miracle Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson figures he'll hear from the judges Friday. He knows they
want him to improve his pointing. Touch-ups. He'll begin the day
with a round of golf, come back for a little tutoring, and hit the
floor running Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at this now for 22 years,'' he said. ``For the first
two years after '96, I trained six and seven hours a day, every
day. Like I say, it's my job. It's what I do. If you don't go out
there confident, you are in deep trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   If some of that could rub off on his red, white, and blue
brethren, and nights like Thursday night could be eliminated, then
the Yanks could be an impressive bunch in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, there's work to do and some stuttering to stop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
