<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-REUNITING-KOREAS-ECON     08-18 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNITING-KOREAS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGS FOR KOREANS, BUT NOT YET FOR NORTH KOREAN LEADER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 800-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   This week's reunion of divided Korean families was an
emotionally charged affair, but also an important step in
dismantling one of the last frontiers of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   It involved 100 people from the North and another 100 from the
South travelling to each others' capitals to greet relatives they
had not seen for 50 or more years.
</P>
<P>
   All the hugs and tears were a welcome sign that the two Koreas
are continuing to make progress towards unifying their divided
peninsula. Yet the small number who made the journey shows just how
wide the gulf is.
</P>
<P>
   Those from prosperous, democratic South Korea were ordinary
people, mostly very elderly, who were selected in a computer
lottery; those from impoverished North Korea were mostly
luminaries, handpicked for their loyalty to the Stalinist regime
and carefully watched over by minders.
</P>
<P>
   And, however they were chosen, these were the lucky ones.
Millions of other Koreans have relatives whom they have not seen
for half a century, and can but hope that next time it will be
their turn. The signs are that there may be a next time.
</P>
<P>
   This week's reunion was a direct result of the summit held in
June in the North's capital, Pyongyang, between that country's
leader, Kim Jong Il, and the South's president, Kim Dae Jung.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the hermit kingdom began to emerge from his shell
earlier this year in a diplomatic charm offensive. But what is he
up to?
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics observe that whether Kim Jong Il is genuinely
interested in reforming his regime or simply trying to shore it up,
he expects substantial rewards for his country. So far, things have
gone well for him.
</P>
<P>
   This week the two Koreas also opened liaison offices in
Panmunjom, a village in the demilitarized zone where the armistice
was negotiated that ended the Korean War in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Next month work should begin on reconnecting the cross-border
railway. Power lines could be next, with the South helping the
North to overcome its electricity shortages. Southern companies are
being offered investment opportunities in the North.
</P>
<P>
   The two Kims plan further cabinet-level talks, which could lead
to a visit by Kim Jong Il to the South's capital, Seoul. Or could
not: he has indicated that his journey will depend on continued
``progress.'' Translation: concessions, perhaps from non-Korean
parts of the world as well.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders, though, do not see the issues quite as the Koreans
do. A collapse of the North's economy would worry the outside
world, but not, directly, much damage it; in contrast, the results
could devastate the economy of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Americans are deeply alarmed at the possibility
that North Korea may develop long-range missiles that could reach
the western United States; but that would add little to the
military threat faced by South Korea from the North.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jong Il has said what he would like the Americans to do:
drop his country from their list of states that sponsor terrorism.
This would allow it access to more international aid. It was
originally included in the list for harboring members of the
Japanese Red Army who had hijacked a Japanese airliner in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The North's subsequent nasty behavior has given the Americans no
reason to change their minds: North Korean agents are accused of
planting the bomb in Yangon, the capital of Myanmar, which in 1983
killed 17 visiting South Koreans, including several cabinet
ministers. They are blamed for the blowing up of a South Korean
airliner in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea also has been belligerent over international efforts
that would, in effect, pay it for freezing its nuclear program.
Then, two years ago it test-fired a missile over Japan.
</P>
<P>
   It is the rest of the world that needs to see more progress from
North Korea. Kim Jong Il clearly likes to appear to foreigners
arriving in Pyongyang as a modern, if Mao-suited, man who is a
movie buff and connoisseur of French wine. Yet he remains
worryingly unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   When Vladimir Putin visited Pyongyang last month, the North's
leader told the Russian president that it was prepared to stop
selling missiles to other nations if the Americans would launch its
satellites for it. Yet this week the North Korean leader told a
group of visitors from the South that he had only been joking.
</P>
<P>
   The two Koreas face a huge task in restoring _ rather,
reinventing _ relations. They have made remarkable progress. It is
to be hoped that they continue to do so. But Kim Jong Il has still
to convince the world that he is sincere about opening up, if he
wants his country to stop being considered as a dangerous rogue
nation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
