<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 04:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CLINTINSELTOWN-ECONOM     08-18 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTINSELTOWN-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S HOLLYWOOD: WIZARD OF AAHS AND THE YELLOW BRICK ROAD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 100-word trim; 1,050 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 1,050-word (uncut) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: 100-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 850; STORY UNCUT IS
1,050.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It is fitting that Bill Clinton should have given
his valedictory performance at a Democratic National Convention in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   No group has stood more solidly behind the boy from Arkansas
than the Hollywood crowd. And no group better symbolizes both the
attraction and the ultimate hollowness of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in office eight years ago surrounded by a
praetorian guard of Rhodes scholars and policy wonks. But over time
his center of gravity shifted relentlessly from Ivy League
universities to Hollywood swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment community was probably the only group of
sensate Americans that never harbored any doubts about his behavior
in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   And the grateful president became such a familiar figure in L.A.
that the locals will tell you he has both a mansion and a job
waiting for him when he retires, courtesy of Tom Hanks and Steven
Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   The film industry's adulation for Clinton was palpable this
week. On Saturday evening Stan Lee, the creator of Spider-Man,
hosted a $25,000-a-couple bash for Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate
campaign, with guests gorging themselves on lobster and beef and
listening to such deep political thinkers as Whoopi Goldberg and
Ted Danson.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning the Clintons headed off to another Malibu
estate, Barbra Streisand's, this time to raise money for the
president's library in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   A few Democrats worried that the first couple were soaking up
attention and money that should have gone to Al Gore. But by the
time they left town on Tuesday she had a reported $4 million and he
had $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the heir to a long tradition of mutual attraction
between the capitals of glamour and power.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Roosevelt and Dwight Eisenhower both cozied up to the
Hollywood moguls (FDR even wrote a screenplay). John Kennedy
partied with Frank Sinatra and dallied with Marilyn Monroe. Ronald
Reagan traded in a career as a B-list actor for one as an A-list
president.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has carried the relationship to new heights.
Previous presidents have always been careful to keep Hollywood at
arm's length. Clinton grew ever more dependent on Tinseltown with
every scandal that broke over his head, culminating in his use of
Harry Thomason to produce his finger-wagging denial that he ever
had sex with ``that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood crowd took to using the Lincoln Bedroom as their
favorite hotel in the capital: no sooner had Barbra moved out than
``Hanoi'' Jane Fonda moved in.
</P>
<P>
   They increasingly dominated the guest lists to glitzy state
dinners. And they encouraged everything that was least impressive
about Clinton, from his moral evasiveness to his over-reliance on
personal charm.
</P>
<P>
   If Kennedy is forever associated with the intellectuals who
designed the New Frontier, Clinton will forever be associated with
the stars who made him one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton years brought two other depressing changes in the
Hollywood-Washington connection. The first was the explosion in the
quantity of cash changing hands. The Democratic Party's various
national committees now receive an estimated 20 percent of their
money from the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the entertainment industry had already given the
Democrats some $50 million during the Clinton years, more than any
other interest group except the trade unions and the trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The second change is that Hollywood has become almost a
one-party town. Hollywood Republicans were already a beleaguered
minority when Reagan came to power. (A Reagan aide once sent out
2,000 letters seeking support from the president's old stamping
ground. He got 100 replies, 90 of them hate letters.) But now they
can probably be numbered on the fingers of one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Young actors who harbor secret doubts about liberal orthodoxies
have little choice but to hide their true feelings in Tinseltown.
</P>
<P>
   So what? Isn't money the lubricant of American politics? And
aren't most artists unrepentant lefties? Perhaps. But it is worth
noting that people do not give huge amounts of money without
expecting something in return.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's massive financial muscle has succeeded in
marginalizing important discussions, not least about the malevolent
impact of the industry's love affair with violence, just as it has
succeeded in opening foreign markets to Hollywood's products.
</P>
<P>
   It is also worth noting that filmmakers who present relentlessly
partisan views of the world risk provoking a reaction.
</P>
<P>
   America is never going to recover from the culture war that has
disfigured its politics for a generation if prime-time programs
such as ``The West Wing,'' a political soap opera about an
idealized version of the Clinton White House, routinely portray
religious fundamentalists as bigots and supporters of school
vouchers as closet members of the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's departure from office, things will be different.
The film industry's political bias prevents it from embracing
George W. Bush. But it cannot conceal its disappointment with
Clinton's chosen successor, as if it were being asked to replace a
favorite star with a reject from the afternoon soaps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (100-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 850) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Gore has added to the tension by choosing one of Hollywood's
leading critics, Joseph Lieberman, as his running mate. Lieberman
makes no secret of the fact that he thinks some of Hollywood's
products are polluting the country's culture: to dramatize his
point, he presents a silver-sewer award to the worst offenders.
</P>
<P>
   He has backed legislation that Hollywood hates, from the 1996
law requiring that television sets include the v-chip technology
which lets parents filter what their children watch to his more
recent bid to promote official inquiries into whether entertainment
companies are marketing violent material to children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that the imaginary metro line between Capitol
Hill and Bel Air will close down any time soon. Politicians will
always need money (and will always prefer to ask for it in
Hollywood rather than at conventions of chartered accountants in
Peoria). And the more thoughtful film types will always crave the
validation that comes from associating with the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   But it does mean that the relationship between the capital of
power and the capital of glamour is about to get a lot less intense
_ and less stomach-turning _ than it has been under Clinton. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
