<HEADER>
A5466 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-FADING-RIO-GRANDE-ECO     08-18 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FADING-RIO-GRANDE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIO GRANDE ISN'T GRANDE ENOUGH FOR THIRSTY SOUTHWEST  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New Mexico, Texas and Colorado)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 800-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE AND SANTA FE, N.M. _ The Rio Grande starts life
majestically, cutting deep through the volcanic canyons of the
Colorado plateau. But by the time it reaches the desert plains of
southern New Mexico it is a shade of its former self, depleted by
irrigation channels that feed the state's thirsty crops.
</P>
<P>
   Now the river faces a new challenge: fast-growing cities
increasingly desperate for water.
</P>
<P>
   Fights over water have dominated the history of the American
Southwest. In an area where land is abundant and cheap, the only
thing standing in the path of unbridled population growth is the
supply of water in the region's rivers and aquifers.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, New Mexico has avoided the water battles that
have torn apart Arizonans and Californians. Yet, with the state's
population expected to grow hugely over the next 25 years, and with
most of that growth projected in the largest cities of Albuquerque,
Santa Fe and Las Cruces, the state has become a new battleground in
the familiar tussles between developers, environmentalists, city
officials and the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for water in New Mexico's cities used to be met by
underground aquifers. But those reserves are expected to be largely
depleted over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Albuquerque and Santa Fe are planning a shift to surface water
by 2004, which means tapping (reluctantly, they insist) the flows
of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   By the terms of an agreement known as the San Juan-Chama
project, the cities have rights each year to over 50,000 acre-feet
of water that has been diverted from the Colorado River to the Rio
Grande (an acre-foot is enough water to cover an acre to the depth
of a foot).
</P>
<P>
   The cities insist that the plan will be phased in gradually, to
minimize its effect on water levels in the river. Environmentalists
do not believe them. The scheme, they say, will simply place
further demands on an already over-exploited stretch of water.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 50 years, farmers have been sucking an
ever-increasing amount out of the Rio Grande. According to John
Horning of the Forest Guardians, based in Santa Fe, New Mexico's
farmers have for years had carte blanche to divert the river as
they see fit, creating an inefficient system of irrigation canals
that wastes more water than it actually delivers to crops.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, environmentalists claim that water diversions
upstream have acted as a tourniquet, jeopardizing wildlife habitats
farther down the river.
</P>
<P>
   The matter is currently tied up in court, with a bundle of
lawsuits brought by environmentalists to protect endangered
species, such as the silvery minnow, that live in the southern
stretches of the river in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits contend that, under the terms of the federal
Endangered Species Act, an adequate water flow must be maintained
to ensure a proper habitat for the minnow.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory for environmentalists, federal courts recently
ruled that 170,000 acre-feet of Rio Grande water be allocated this
year to allow silvery minnows to swim in the style to which they
are accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   Such federal mandates do not sit well with New Mexico's water
officials, who fear they will hinder the state as it attempts to
deliver water to Texas under the Rio Grande Compact.
</P>
<P>
   The compact, made in 1938, divides the Rio Grande between
Colorado, New Mexico and Texas, and requires New Mexico to deliver
over 700,000 acre-feet of water each year to the Elephant Butte
reservoir in the southern part of the state. It is then sent along
to El Paso, in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But as upstream burdens on the Rio Grande multiply, New Mexico
is finding it increasingly difficult to fulfil the terms of the
compact.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trouble is that, when the deal was signed, New
Mexico had fewer demands for agricultural and municipal water than
its neighbors to the north and south. So it was given less. Now its
cities are growing fast, and it needs more.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, concerns about the Rio Grande's endangered
wildlife have also led to the closure of a big channel in the south
that once delivered water to Elephant Butte more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   For Norman Gaume of New Mexico's Interstate Stream Commission,
it is simple. There is just not enough water to meet the demands of
everyone who wants it. Hence the need for hard decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the battle begins, one thing seems certain: New Mexico
will have to keep the Texans happy. Like the neighborhood bully who
can out-muscle anyone, Texas will settle for nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   Gaume recalls the ominous words of a Texas commissioner of the
Rio Grande Compact: ``Deliver, or we'll see you in court.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
