<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 04:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5474 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-DEEP-SIXED-RUSSIA-NAV     08-18 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEP-SIXED-RUSSIA-NAVY-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURSK DEBACLE EXPOSES RUSSIA'S BROADER MILITARY WEAKNESS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 125-word trim; 900 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 900-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ If there is one component of Russia's conventional
armed forces that still keeps western defense planners awake at
night, it is the submarine fleet.
</P>
<P>
   With most of Russia's surface ships rusting away, and the number
of battle-ready army divisions languishing at less than a tenth of
the old Soviet total, it is all the more striking that Moscow's
subs have retained their ability to play underwater games of
hide-and-seek with their American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Submarines, moreover, are the only sort of big weapons platform
that post-Soviet Russia has continued to build for itself, rather
than for shady overseas customers.
</P>
<P>
   It is less than a year since the Severodvinsk shipyard in the
Arctic turned out its latest version of the Akula (Shark), a sneaky
sub that has managed to pop up unexpectedly near naval bases in
America. Lower-tech, but still stealthy and formidable, are the
diesel-powered submarines that Russia has supplied to China, India
and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   As for the giant submarines that carry Russia's ballistic
missiles, their strategic importance is huge, and growing. By 2003,
some 60 percent of Russia's long-range arsenal will be deployed on
these boats, up from 43 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, when the newly elected President Vladimir Putin
wanted to prove his macho credentials, a sleepover on a nuclear
submarine seemed a natural way of doing it.
</P>
<P>
   All this helps to explain the profound embarrassment that the
Russian leadership, civilian and military, must be feeling over the
disaster which befell the Kursk, a nuclear-powered (though
apparently not nuclear-armed) submarine in the Barents Sea, near
Norway, on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100 sailors, over half of them officers, confined
to a dark, bitter-cold, unventilated metal box on the ocean floor,
the navy found itself struggling, and failing, to cope not just
with a human disaster but a public-relations fiasco as well.
</P>
<P>
   It looked bad enough that no submarine rescue vessel was on
hand, as would normally be expected during a big maritime exercise.
Then the top brass maintained its prickly refusal to accept western
help as it undertook three unsuccessful attempts to dock a rescue
capsule with the ill-fated sub.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that failed, said the navy, it could still use
inflatable pontoons to raise the vessel. When, on Aug. 16, the
Russians finally overcame their reluctance and accepted foreign
help, it looked to be too late.
</P>
<P>
   With a British mini-submarine and Norwegian divers on their way
to the site, but not expected to get there until Saturday, the
Russians confirmed that they were no longer picking up signs of
life from the sub.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as though, in effect, some of the Arctic fleet's most
senior officers, along with their men, were sacrificed to a cold
Soviet-style concept of secrecy and pride.
</P>
<P>
   The sub was taking a leading part in Russia's biggest show of
naval force for five years: a war game in the Arctic, to be
followed by the deployment of an aircraft carrier, the Kuznetsov,
in the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   All these moves were supposed to give substance to Putin's
recent pledge that Russia would soon return to the high seas as an
oceangoing naval power, capable of defending trade routes _ or
busting embargoes.
</P>
<P>
   While military muscle-flexing goes down well, many Russians were
puzzled, exasperated and dismayed by the behavior of both the top
brass and their president during the Kursk debacle. At one point,
naval commanders suggested that a collision had occurred; then they
spoke of an explosion or a brush with an old mine.
</P>
<P>
   There was particularly harsh media criticism of the belated call
for help, and this while the hitherto popular President Putin
remained on his vacation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 625) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The accident that forced the Kursk to the ocean floor, about 150
metres (490 feet) below the surface, was mysterious and
devastating. With its double-layered hull, this class of submarine,
known as the Oskar-2, was designed to withstand torpedo attacks,
while packing enough punch to sink aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Even, for example, extensive flooding of its torpedo bays would
not, by itself, have crippled the Kursk; western specialists were
baffled over what could have incapacitated the boat and forced the
crew to resort to battery power, lasting for only a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vivid illustration of the appalling state of the
Russian submarine fleet,'' says Joanna Kidd of Britain's
International Institute for Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Kursk was an antique: it was built in 1995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 900) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The incident shows the serious problems afflicting all parts of
Russia's defense establishment, even those that command high
prestige and can generate export earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The future looks as problematic for Russia's submarine fleet as
the other services. While 20 new attack submarines have entered
service since the Soviet collapse, the pace is slowing: only five
have been commissioned since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a massive question mark over Russia's ability to
construct enough new strategic submarines to carry a bigger part of
its nuclear deterrent; all 21 of the large boats now in service
will reach the end of their service life within ten to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Russia can hardly afford to maintain its submarines, let alone
build new ones. It has designed a new missile-carrying boat, the
Borey, but construction of the first model is slow; it will be
finished by 2008 at best. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 05:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
