<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5479 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GRAPES-DE-WRATH-ECONO     08-18 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPES-DE-WRATH-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUR GRAPES: THE FRENCH WINE RESISTANCE VS. ROBERT MONDAVI  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Northern California)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 525-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ANIANE _ ``Jose Bov(acute)e is my friend,'' declares Aim(acute)e
Guibert, the 75-year-old maker of Daumas Gassac wines, the finest
of the Languedoc region.
</P>
<P>
   And his role model? While Bov(acute)e, the pipe-smoking and
media-savvy leader of France's small farmers, targets McDonald's as
the symbol of the evils of globalization, the silver-haired Guibert
_ a speaker at a protest rally when Bov(acute)e went on trial in
June for trashing a McDonald's building site _ has in his sights a
Californian wine giant, Robert Mondavi.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Guibert wants to block Mondavi's plan for a
winery in the beautiful garrigue, or wooded scrub, right next to
his own vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   It is an uneven contest. Guibert's family-owned domaine,
nestling in the hills above the town of Aniane, produces a mere
120,000 bottles a year of its superb red wine _ Robert Parker,
America's taste pundit, positively drools over it _ and 70,000 of
white _ ``also a knockout,'' as Parker puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi, though still family-controlled, is a quoted company
that produces over 90 million bottles a year, with an annual net
income of over $370 million.
</P>
<P>
   To hedge its bets geographically, the firm already produces wine
in Italy, Chile and southern France.
</P>
<P>
   Guibert, whose vines are tended by hand and allowed to mature
with no artificial irrigation, mixes respect with derision: ``Have
you seen how Americans make wine? It's an industrial product.
Everything is controlled _ and the end is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Guibert's chances do not look promising. Mondavi has a polished
public-relations operation in place. Its local representative,
David Pearson, whom Guibert dismisses as ``an American violinist''
playing on public opinion, spent two years searching for this
oenologically perfect spot.
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi, he says, does not plan mass production but just 240,000
bottles a year of a high-quality Syrah-based red wine made with
much the same care as Daumas Gassac.
</P>
<P>
   As to the charge of environmental damage, he notes that Guibert
himself also cleared the garrigue to make his wine.
</P>
<P>
   One ecologists' group even suggests that the Mondavi plan, which
covers ten plots, separated by garrigue, may promote biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
   The project, which depends on Mondavi obtaining a 99-year lease
on communal land, also has local political support. The Socialist
mayor of nearby Montpellier, George Fr(circumflex)eche, and his
friends in Aniane back it. Last month the Aniane town council
approved the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Mondavi is offering to help the 232 members of the
local wine cooperative to upgrade and market their wines.
</P>
<P>
   Given that 40 percent of last year's harvest is still unsold,
and the region's wine growers have taken to the streets to protest
at foreign imports, the offer is hard to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, though the final decision rests with the
national agricultural minister, and Guibert vows to keep up a legal
challenge, the Americans may well start clearing their land by next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, locals are resigned. ``The wine-growers of
Aniane,'' comments one, ``will end up as the workers of Mondavi.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
