<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 05:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-ASBESTOS-US-BIZ-ECONO     08-18 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-US-BIZ-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASBESTOS CLAIMS: STILL KILLING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 775-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Johns Manville Corporation agreed to be
acquired by a buyout firm and thus return to private ownership in
early July, a painful chapter in corporate history came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1920s until the 1970s, Manville had been the largest
American producer of asbestos, a product belatedly discovered to be
extraordinarily dangerous. Ensuing claims led to a bankruptcy in
1982 that penalized existing shareholders in favor of a trust fund
for victims.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Manville's time in purgatory is drawing to a close, it
looks likely that others will be forced down the same path by
increasingly virulent asbestos-related litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, the shares of four large industrial firms _ Owens
Corning, Armstrong Industries, USG and W.R. Grace _ have been
hammered. The two with most financial strength, Owens Corning
(insulation) and Armstrong (flooring), have seen their credit
ratings downgraded as well.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the companies had previously said they had
reserves sufficient to cover fully any asbestos claims, but they
have recently been forced to bump up their estimates of potential
liabilities, thus raising the suspicion that further increases are
to come.
</P>
<P>
   More devastatingly, another two firms _ Pittsburgh Corning
(glass insulation) and Babcock and Wilcox (boilers) _ have this
year gone bankrupt, citing asbestos claims as the reason.
</P>
<P>
   The filing by Babcock came after it had already settled 340,000
claims at a cost of $1.6 billion and had become unable to see any
resolution. ``The claims,'' the company groaned, ``have become
intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the alternative? Elihu Inselbuch, a lawyer for
plaintiffs in both of these cases and another asbestos-related
bankruptcy, Raytech Corp., is blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The liabilities exceed the value of assets of all these
companies,'' he says. ``Even a liability half the size puts them
under water. There's nothing you can get but the company.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, expect the Manville model to be repeated.
Expect, too, the number of litigious victims to rise.
</P>
<P>
   When Manville first filed for bankruptcy in 1982, it reckoned on
17,000 claims. It had upped that fivefold by 1988 and has so far
settled 320,000 claims, with another 70,000 pending. It expects at
least 500,000 more, with the final claim to be submitted in 2049.
</P>
<P>
   In total, it has paid out almost $2.4 billion, another $1
billion awaits disbursement, and yet another $1.5 billion should
come from Manville's sale. In time, these numbers may appear small.
</P>
<P>
   Owens Corning's involvement with asbestos stemmed from a single
product, an insulated pipe manufactured between 1958 and 1972, with
total sales of $135 million (less than $800 million in today's
money). Yet it has already paid out $4 billion in claims.
</P>
<P>
   A number of factors push up these claims. Asbestos-related
problems have a long latency period, while treatment has become
more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for cashing in has also become more widely known
(provoking several fraud investigations). And plaintiffs' lawyers
have become more imaginative, going after not only producers of
asbestos products, but also firms that merely used asbestos, says
Kenneth Bradley, editor of Asbestos Litigation Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   He cites as an example a $34 million decision that went against
a division of Royal Dutch/Shell, an oil company, in April. Shell
never made anything from asbestos but, like many oil firms, used it
in its refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms that must be surprised to find themselves caught up
in lawsuits include Campbell's Soup and Gerber, a baby-food maker.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor may be timing. According to a lawyer involved in
the cases, earlier this year efforts failed to pass federal
legislation that would control payments.
</P>
<P>
   While these drew wide support, they faced strong opposition from
trial lawyers as well as a likely veto from President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, so the idea goes, the Congress and government may
change and be less sympathetic to endless lawsuits. Thus there is a
rush to file suits fast.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that the asbestos-related companies, sick of
taking body blows, are starting to lash out themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In an intriguing reversal of roles, the Manville Trust, along
with several other defendants in asbestos cases, will go before a
Federal Appeals Court next month to get clearance for
multibillion-dollar claims against tobacco manufacturers (Owens
Corning has filed a similar suit in California).
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that the effects of asbestos poisoning are far
worse when combined with smoking cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most battered old bruisers, it seems, can still swing
the odd punch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 0510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 05:11 </DATE_TIME>
