 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MOSCOW _ ``I can't sit around waiting here any longer. I must go
up there,'' cried Valentina Staroseltseva, whose 20-year-old son,
Dmitry, is among the 118 submariners trapped on the Kursk at the
bottom of the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the city of Kursk, which regularly sends its young
men to serve in the Northern Fleet and after which the submarine
was named, collected money to help relatives like Mrs.
Staroseltseva to travel to the Arctic coast Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Their 45-hour train ride will bring them to Severomorsk, where
they will be able to see no more of the frantic rescue operation
than they have seen for the past five days on their television sets
at home. But at least they will feel nearer to their loved ones in
their underwater nightmare _ if, that is, the sailors are still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   As it dawned on Russians that their image-obsessed leaders had
wasted days before allowing a British team to join the rescue
effort, there was mounting public anger and more sympathy for the
conscripts than the top brass on the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven of the conscripts came from the city of Kursk,
500 km (325 miles) south of Moscow, which until the tragedy at sea
was known chiefly as the site of a major tank battle during the
Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Kursk relatives, Mrs. Staroseltseva, a nurse, was most
open to being filmed by Russian television. The independent NTV
station showed her, looking businesslike in a red suit, preparing
to channel her desperate, maternal energy into the practicalities
of the long journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am angry that we did not let the British come sooner,'' she
said, referring to Moscow's three-day delay in accepting the
British offer of help.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a mother, I want everything to be done faster and better. I
think maybe he (Dmitry) is lying silently. As a mother, I hope he
is calm. The main thing is not to panic,'' said Mrs. Staroseltseva,
who had passed her own Orthodox Christian beliefs on to her son.
</P>
<P>
   The irony was that Mrs. Staroseltseva had been pleased to see
Dmitry sent to the prestigious Northern Fleet instead of the
notorious ``stroibat'' (construction brigade), where bullying is
rife, or, worse, to what Russians call the ``meat grinder'' _
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the submarine was so safe,'' she said. ``We called
it our submarine. We were 100 percent confident in it. We really
believed in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dmitry, who graduated with high marks from a railway college
before joining the navy, had to compete with other conscripts for a
posting on the Kursk. ``He has always loved swimming in the
river,'' said his mother. ``It was impossible to pull him out of
there. He loves machinery too.''
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent letter home, he enthused about life on the
modern, 14,000-ton, nuclear submarine, which had been the pride of
the fleet. ``It is just like home here. I'm really happy. We have
four meals a day, just like home. We will resurface in the middle
of August. See you soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Staroseltseva had a premonition of disaster. She said
she felt ``ill and out of sorts'' on Sunday before the news of the
sinking broke. ``Then I heard the submarine was lying on the
seabed. I understood that something had gone wrong. The only thing
that helps me now is to pray.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
