<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DE-NAZIFY-YOUTHS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY SEEKS THE DE-NAZIFICATION OF YOUNG PEOPLE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 725-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By IMRE KARACS  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BERLIN _ Reacting to the relentless drumbeat of daily
atrocities, the German government Wednesday announced the first of
its sweeping measures to combat the far right.
</P>
<P>
   Some DM75 million has been earmarked for a program that seeks
the de-Nazification of German youth.
</P>
<P>
   Further steps will be unveiled by Gerhard Schroder personally
when he returns from his vacation at the weekend. What seemed like
a gentle comeback for the chancellor now promises to be a gruelling
chore: Schroder will be touring the East for the next two weeks,
visiting some of the worst hot spots of the resurgent far right.
</P>
<P>
   The program unveiled Wednesday is intended to be just the
beginning of what promises to be the most concerted attack on
right-wing extremism since the immediate aftermath of the Second
World War.
</P>
<P>
   The money is to be spent on extra lessons for children on German
history and on the threatening concept _ often denounced by
mainstream conservatives _ of ``multiculturalism.''
</P>
<P>
   A hot line for reporting racist violence will be set up. Private
groups and charities combating ignorance and xenophobia on
shoestring budgets can look forward to a windfall of public funds.
</P>
<P>
   The government will train staff who work on public transport not
to look away when foreigners are being harassed, and hire young
computer experts to track down neo-Nazi Web sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, social workers have been arguing that
poor education, especially in the East, was one of the main causes
of the simmering hatred towards foreigners. Their pleas have until
now fallen on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Racism is most acute in parts of the East where the local youth
have no experience of immigrants. Two years ago, nearly 13 percent
of voters in the eastern Land of Saxony-Anhalt voted for a far
right party, even though only 2 percent of the region's population
was of foreign origin.
</P>
<P>
   Extra lessons, though, will not be enough. Renate Kunast, one of
the Greens' two co-leaders, Wednesday called for retraining of
teachers in the East, because they are seen as part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The communist authorities planted the myth that Nazism had been
the work of an isolated bunch of people, successfully purged from
the Workers' Paradise, but still lurking in the decadent West.
</P>
<P>
   Many East German teachers therefore have an ambivalent attitude
to the Third Reich, and fail to see similarities between today's
xenophobic banter in the classroom and the chain of events that had
led to the rise of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a lot more than DM75 million to wipe away the
ingrained misconceptions of two generations. The opposition Free
Democrats are urging as much as DM300 million to be splashed out on
a national brainwashing program at schools.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond further training, the government is expected to set up a
panel of eminent personalities to coordinate the intellectual drive
against far-right tendencies. The real problem, as many politicians
are increasingly prepared to admit, is that the dislike of
foreigners is anything but a marginal phenomenon in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Xenophobia is socially respectable. Crime, for instance, is
routinely portrayed by the media and leading politicians as a
foreign pursuit. Such an initiative was launched earlier this week
in Germany's most populous Land, North Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
   The regional capital Dusseldorf was the scene last month of a
bomb attack injuring 10 immigrants from the former Soviet Union,
including six Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Clement, the Land prime minister and one of Schroder`s
closest political allies, is putting pressure on the local police
and judiciary to act tough on hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   This line of attack, coupled with moves to ban the far right
National Democratic Party (NPD), is expected to be at the center of
Schroder's plan to rid the country of neo-Nazi violence.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uproar over Dusseldorf and a string of outrages,
every day brings news of fresh attacks. Wednesday, for instance,
came reports from Hamburg of a neo-Nazi youth stabbing a Turkish
man.
</P>
<P>
   On the northeastern coast, about 250 posters have gone up
attacking the ``murder'' of Rudolf Hess. Today (Thursday) marks the
anniversary of the death of Hitler's deputy at Spandau prison, and
the lads in black leather jackets and combat boots will be marching
again. &QL; 
