<P>
   &UR; GERMANY SEEKS THE DE-NAZIFICATION OF YOUNG PEOPLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DE-NAZIFY-YOUTHS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Reacting to the rentless drumbeat of daily atrocities,
the German government Wednesday announced the first of its sweeping
measures to combat the far right. The program _ the de-Nazification
of German youth _ is intended to be just the beginning of what
promises to be the most concerted attack on right-wing extremism
since the immediate aftermath of the Second World War....By Imre
Karacs, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED MONDAY, 14 AUGUST: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OVERWORKED? OVERWHELMED?: SLOW DOWN, EASE UP, LOG OFF AND
LIVE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLOW-DOWN-LIFE-1075&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Just an hour's (slow) drive from San Gimignano are half
a dozen Italian towns that are trying to slow down the pace of
life. They are members of the ``Slow City'' movement, where towns
sign up to a series of measures designed to make life calmer and
hence more enjoyable for citizens and visitors alike. The Slow
Cities project touches a nerve everywhere because one of the
growing divisions in our society is not about money but about time.
For most of us there is a genuine problem of balance: how do we get
our work done, fulfill our social and family obligations, and still
find time for fun? The Slow Cities movement can teach us some
principles of how we might do so....By Hamish McRae, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Pithy Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story stands in 1,075; 1,200 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `WALTER': FOND TALES OF A JOURNALISTIC CAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WALTER-THE-CAT-FISK-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Walter was a street cat, a ``pusseini baladi'' as they
say in Beirut, brown and black with sharp ears and sharper teeth _
and the only creature of its kind to consume part of an Israeli
wire-guided air-to-ground missile. She could not escape journalism.
And journalism couldn't escape Walter....By Robert Fisk, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Poignant Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN EMERALD CITY, WIZARD OF OZ ENDORSES THE TIN MAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON-CURSE-GORE-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There could be no more irresistible political
farewell. Like the flawed hero in his own Hollywood movie,
President Bill Clinton prepared to address the Democratic Party
faithful Monday night on a wave of high emotion and extravagant
praise for the man who would succeed him, Vice President Al Gore.
But the Gore camp has had to worry about being upstaged. Just by
opening his mouth and smiling his infectiously boyish smile,
Clinton risks putting his putative successor into the shade. In the
Emerald City, it will inescapably seem that the Wizard of Oz is
handing over to the Tin Man....By Andrew Gumbel, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
