<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 05:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-TOO-HOT-GREENSPAN?-WO     08-18 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOO-HOT-GREENSPAN?-WORTH-900&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL HOT STOCK MARKET BURN INVESTORS IN FOURTH-QUARTER?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Financial Editors...Note 150-word trim)   (This 1,050-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: NOTE 150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 900; TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,050
WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JIM JUBAK  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Be careful what you wish for, because your wish just might come
true.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the stock market's recent rally as the calendar flipped
from May to June. The driving force behind the upswing: the
disclosure that the U.S. economy was no longer expanding as rapidly
as it had been earlier in the year. What was bad news for business,
in other words, had become good news for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This was exactly what the market had been hoping would happen.
For months, Wall Street had been focused on the Federal Reserve
Board. The Fed had become the nemesis of the stock market because
of its ongoing campaign to combat even the remotest prospect of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Four times in six months the central bank had seen fit to raise
interest rates. Each time it had done so, the Dow Jones Industrial
Average, Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, and the Nasdaq had all taken a hit.
</P>
<P>
   What Wall Street wanted to know more than anything else was when
the Fed was going to end its campaign. The predominant view was
that Fed chairman Alan Greenspan would call a halt as soon as he
got some sign that his nasty medicine was actually working. Any
hint of a slowdown in economic activity might serve this purpose _
which explains why investors began to hope and pray for some lousy
economic news.
</P>
<P>
   Such twisted thinking is, of course, vulnerable to reality.
Notice what's missing in the above line of reasoning: the impact
that a slowing economy in and of itself might have on stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it customary for a drop in business activity to hurt
corporate earnings _ and therefore depress stock values? Indeed,
what looks like a boost for stocks right now may not seem so
favorable by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Worries that Greenspan's Fed may have done its job too well _
that the economy might be slowing too much _ could derail the
fourth-quarter rally that many investors are banking on to rescue
their portfolios in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Once the market gets the proof it needs that the Fed has decided
to cease its anti-inflation campaign it, too, will probably begin
asking these questions.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly the collective attention of investors shifts from
the good news about the Fed to the bad news about a slowing economy
may be the single most important unknown facing equity investors in
the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, let's go back and review the underlying
economic news that first prompted the market rally.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, the Department of Commerce reported that spending on
construction projects had fallen by 0.6 percent in April. It was
the first decline in this important economic indicator since
September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The latest figure also represented a sharp change from the 0.8
percent gain Commerce had reported for the month of March.
Additionally, the April figure was well below the consensus
projection of Wall Street economists, who had anticipated a number
closer to zero.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, the National Association of Purchasing Management
in Tempe, Ariz., reported that its index of economic activity had
hit 53.2 in May. That suggested that while the economy was still
growing _ any reading above 50 foretells an expansion in GNP _ it
was doing so at a much slower rate than the 55.5 reading projected
by Wall Street economists (as well as the 54.9 reading recorded in
April).
</P>
<P>
   Other business-news headlines also appeared to confirm a picture
of a slowing economy. Sales at most U.S. retailers were tepid at
best in May. Kmart reported a mere 0.9 percent rise in same-store
sales for the month. The increase at May Department Stores was
slightly better, at 1.2 percent, but Saks reported only a 0.7
percent improvement in sales.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. automakers also had a sluggish month. Ford Motor said total
domestic vehicle sales rose just 1.4 percent in May compared to the
year-earlier month. That was a very different result from the 12
percent year-to-year gain Ford had reported as recently as April.
</P>
<P>
   At General Motors, total vehicle sales in May actually fell
almost 6 percent from the year-earlier total.
</P>
<P>
   More news of the Kmart and GM variety would begin to raise
questions about whether the Fed had actually given its patient an
overdose.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Smith, Prudential Securities' chief investment strategist,
first brought this up on May 3 when he wrote, ``It always seems to
happen that rates are raised so much that, rather than simply
slowing GDP growth to a more moderate rate of growth (say, 3
percent annually), the economy actually weakens.''
</P>
<P>
   Investor anticipation of an economic slowdown will likely unfold
in two stages. At first, the focus will be on specific stocks to
avoid _ such as those of middle-market retailers and the producers
of automobiles and houses. Money will flow out of these sectors and
into areas that seem likely to sidestep the worst of the downturn
or perhaps even to profit from it.
</P>
<P>
   Stage two will occur if and when the market as a whole begins to
seem vulnerable. At current price levels, stocks are attractive
buys only if current earnings expectations for the third and fourth
quarters are actually met (or even exceeded). There's no room for
disappointment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 900) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Different sectors of the stock market are likely to thrive
during each stage. Expect to see a relief bounce in the tech sector
on June 28 if the Fed indicates that its rate hikes are over. That
bounce could turn into a red-hot tech rally if investors quickly
start to worry about slower economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   These stocks' high revenues and earnings growth rates make them
seem immune to any slowdown in the economy. If investor attention
turns to panic about growth this quickly, the rally in technology
stocks that many investors are now pegging for September could
occur much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a few high-profile warnings about reduced
revenue or earnings prospects could also put high price-to-earnings
technology stocks under pressure again as analysts start to hedge
their forecasts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Sectors with dependable growth _ drug stocks, for example _
would become safe havens for money flowing out of the riskier
technology stocks. That kind of sector rotation could make the
fourth quarter very choppy.
</P>
<P>
   All this raises immense timing problems for investors who have
been trying to figure out when it's safe to put cash back to work
in the market and for those who, having switched sectors to avoid
the worst of the year's technology meltdown, are now trying to
decide which sectors to own for the remainder of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Investors could find themselves again facing the choice of
moving early _ and possibly in the wrong direction _ or staying put
and toughing it out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Jim Jubak is senior markets
editor at Microsoft's MoneyCentral (www.moneycentral.msn.com); his
column ``Jubak's Journal'' appears there every Tuesday and
Friday.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 1,050-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
