   FILM-LONG-NIGHT (San Francisco) ``Long Night's Journey Into
Day'' is an excellent documentary about the multitude of voices
articulately requesting amnesty for human-rights crimes committed
in South Africa between 1960 and 1994. Each case's violators and
their victims' relatives, the supporting players and the key
government figures are interviewed. Helen Mirren supplies the
transitional narration. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THE-CELL (undated) _ ``The Cell,'' is a tremendous change
of pace for the Jennifer Lopez, the
dancer-turned-actress-turnedsinger-turned-moll-turnedactress-again
insofar as she's not asked to lip sync her performance. Lopez plays
a shrink who must save a girl a from certain death by suiting up in
her highly advanced, highly suggestive cyber suit to enter the
brain of an unconscious serial killer (Vincent D'Onofrio), using
the latest in psycho-blather and deplorable screenwriting. By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-KINGS-COMEDY (undated) _ Every Saturday night, you can see
Steve Harvey presiding over Amateur Night on ``Showtime at the
Apollo.'' The dreamers who emerge from backstage to perform in a
scandalous outfit or shameless weave win his disapproval. If
``Apollo'' was an entire race's ``Star Search,`` Harvey was its Ed
McMahon. And the documentary ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' is a
shrewdly executed, often hysterical Spike Lee-directed stand-up
concert film with Harvey as its anchor. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
