<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-ESTIMATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SUGGESTS QUAKE LESS LIKELY IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scientists reported Friday that the northern
Hayward Fault in California is less likely to experience a major
quake in the next three decades than previously thought,
reaffirming a similar conclusion issued last year.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and 2030, there is only a 16 percent chance of
another major quake on the northern segment of the Hayward Fault,
on the east side of the San Francisco Bay, according to an article
published in Science magazine.
</P>
<P>
   By major quake, they mean one that is at least as bad as the
1994 Northridge quake in Southern California. That earthquake
killed 57 people and caused $20 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Geological Survey and geoscientists in California
issued a report in 1999 estimating a 16 percent chance of a
6.7-magnitude quake in the Bay Area by 2030. The northern segment
of the Hayward Fault runs from Berkeley to the San Pablo Bay.
</P>
<P>
   A decade earlier, the prospects looked somewhat worse for the
northern Hayward Fault. A 28 percent estimate was issued in a 1990
USGS report.
</P>
<P>
   The Science article does not unveil fundamentally new
information, said seismologist Bill Ellsworth of the USGS office in
Menlo Park. He said the article mainly reports the same research
data used in the 1999 forecast, although in a more refined fashion
following a review by outside experts.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, lay people shouldn't take too literally the
12-point difference between the 1990 and 1999 estimates. The two
forecasts were based on significantly different data and
assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the 1990 report estimated the probability of
another quake like Loma Prieta, which hit the San Francisco area in
1989 and measured about 7.0 magnitude. By contrast, the 1999 report
used as its model a weaker quake, the 6.7-magnitude Northridge
event of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``both of those are very damaging earthquakes,'' said
Bob Nadeau, one of the co-authors of the Science article. The lead
author was geophysicist Roland Burgmann of the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
