<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HOFFMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A NOT-SO-COMPELLING RETROSPECTIVE ON ABBIE HOFFMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Cast box at end)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sad truth about Abbie Hoffman is that time has relegated him
to little more than an exuberant footnote to his own revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Seventies counterculturalism used to have several first names
among the often-imitated, never-duplicated Abbie. Or make that
``Abbie!'' as director Robert Greenwald and writer Bruce Grahams'
account of Hoffman's ascent and subsequent retreat into obscurity
was originally called. A title like ``Abbie!'' has you looking into
the klieg lights _ or, if it's to be done properly, the flashlights
of your local guerilla theater troop, or Tim Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing early that they would never reach those euphoric (and,
maybe musical heights) needed for something called ``Abbie!'',
Greenwald and Graham have gone for the more Hoffmanesque ``Steal
This Movie,'' a title that denotes mischief and arouses excitement
in the way only an independent flick about an independent flake
could. But in ``Steal This Movie'' the mischief and Hoffman's wit
seems to have been left on the cutting-room floor along with the
stamped-out buds. The film implies that it's up to something
appetizing, but the prevailing vibe is flimsy speechifying.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from a book of letters exchanged between Hoffman and his
wife, Anita, and a Marty Jezer biography, ``Steal This Movie''
feels inexplicably scant. His stint as a member of the Chicago
Seven receives such short shrift that baby boomers should feel as
cheated as persnickety X-Men fans. We see Bobby Seale jailed, more
or less in another movie. Greenwald uses a blowsy performance by
Vincent D'Onofrio to transport us from his early days as a yippie
performance artist in late-'60s Boston to his twilight spent
pinging between two women, and finally and most effectively, his
return to overheated protest.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Abbie 101.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's audience would have to be anyone who doesn't mind
their fiction filmmaking more doped up on '60s archive footage than
a Woodstock swap meet, with a story better told by the period
soundtrack than by its makers. It's often a lapsed, under-informed
documentary with restagings. Nearly the entire first half of
``Steal This Movie'' is unwatchable, with its Bruce Conner-load of
found shots and an instantly tiresome reportage device that aspires
to ascribe a Charles Foster Kane-level of enigmatic panache to
Hoffman's travails.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Hoffman is afforded neither aggrandized
classic-rock star status nor the mournful glow of a tarnished
American martyr.
</P>
<P>
   This Hoffman is a one-man way-back machine. It's unclear how
deep the film's love of Hoffman runs. Here, he's a loony blowhard
whose rhetoric agenda is 'round-the-clock. ``I'm an existential
loner,'' D'Onofrio's Abbie tell us, if he doesn't say so himself.
In reality, he was also a charismatic, if alienating, organizer,
who every now and again was known to get high, then stop and smell
the tear gas, so to speak. Here Abbie and Anita make politics, not
love. The people in ``Steal This Movie'' speak in bumper-sticker
phrases and Peter Max posters.
</P>
<P>
   After Hoffman's drug addiction gets him trapped by the police
then forces him underground, the film unfurls into something like a
beautiful, bizarre love triangle between Abbie, Anita and Joanna
Lawrenson (Jeanne Tripplehorn), the waitress he meets on the run
who devotes herself to nursing his delusions. D'Onofrio's
fire-breathing acquires a sullen depth as the film reveals a
reconciliation between Abbie and his son, who spends years thinking
his dad is just a friend of his mother's.
</P>
<P>
   Those passages are so eloquently done, it is hard to believe you
are watching the same film. It's not long before the original
bluster is restored, but there is a heretofore unfelt emotional
weight behind anchoring it that reduces the boring blur of the
first hour. Though it all might seem better focused if you returned
the favor by watching it from a soapbox.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Steal This Movie''
</P>
<P>
   CAST Vincent D'Onofrio, Janeane Garofalo, Donal Logue, Kevin
Pollak
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR Robert Greenwald
</P>
<P>
   WRITER Bruce Graham, adapted from Anita and Abbie Hoffman's ``To
America With Love: Letters From the Underground`` and Marty Jezer's
``Abbie Hoffman: American Rebel``
</P>
<P>
   RATED R
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
