<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0819-CO     08-18 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    I will go to great lengths to find a fine piece of lumber
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I am on the lookout for lumber. Black
walnut is my favorite wood to work, but it's easier to find someone
who's going to vote for Ralph Nader than it is to find black
walnut. I'll buy red oak when I find a decent deal, trade for ash
or cypress on occasion, pick up cedar if the price is right and am
considering a trip to Central Texas to pick up some mesquite and
pecan.
</P>
<P>
   I scour the classifieds constantly in hopes of catching someone
ready to unload a pile of lumber air-dried in a barn for the past
20 years, which led me about a month ago to a nice cache of red oak
1-by-6s and a scattering of 2-bys, all stored in a loft. This was
number-one grade, rough cut and straight as Dick Cheney.
Singlehandledy I climbed up in the loft and took down one board at
a time and loaded them into the trailer. The temperature in the
barn hovered at about 120 degrees, and I thought for a while that
this is how I will die, collapsing of heat exhaustion while loading
lumber. I survived.
</P>
<P>
   You can't find much quality hardwood lumber in East Texas, and
you sure can't afford to buy it at the lumberyard. What little
furniture-quality timber is cut here is sent to sawmills in
Louisiana that specialize in selling to furniture makers. Most of
the hardwood cut here goes for crossties and such. So you have few
choices if you're an aspiring furniture maker: Go to Louisiana and
buy it from a sawmill there, which can be worthwhile but requires a
trip to a foreign country, or buy every stick of decent wood you
find, even if it means climbing up in lofts in 120-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   Rough-cut lumber is nasty looking at first sight. The nastier it
looks, the more likely it's high quality, at least from my
experience. Old lumber is usually covered with dirt dobber nests,
cobwebs and plenty of red-clay dust. I've been chased by wasps,
uncovered an alarmingly long snake skin when loading one pile, and
been chewed up by fireants. My first big haul of walnut came about
a year ago. My wife thought I had lost my mind when I pulled in a
trailer loaded with filthy wood, babbling about what a wonderful
find I had made. Until you know better, old rough-cut lumber looks
like it belongs on a burn pile.
</P>
<P>
   Woodworkers who do any amount of volume always buy rough-cut
lumber because it's a fraction of the price of an already-planed
board at the store _ when you can find it. An eight-foot 1x6 of red
oak sells for $25 retail. I built a small entertainment center over
the winter that used about 30 such pieces, which would have cost
$750 just for the lumber. The rough-cut lumber I planed cost about
$200.
</P>
<P>
   Planing lumber is done with a machine that costs about $400,
which means it takes no time at all to pay for the planer if you do
much woodworking. The drawback is that planing lumber is loud,
dirty and slow work. The machine sounds like a screaming banshee
and creates enough sawdust and chips that the only practical
solution is to do it outside where you can pile up the waste.
Planing a dozen boards will fill up a 55-gallon drum with waste in
no time. But the waste makes great garden mulch, so at least I'm
not paying $5 a bag for mulch at the Big Discount Store. And I like
the idea of making my own mulch.
</P>
<P>
   There is the neighbor problem, though. The only sensible way to
plane lumber is to do a huge batch at a time, enough for whatever
project is on tap. That means often two-to-three hours of running a
machine that can out-decibel a chainsaw, which is not conducive for
peace and tranquility in a subdivision. Oh, well. At least I don't
have barking dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Planing lumber is a pain, but the end result is worth it. A
piece of wood comes alive in your hands, the grains and sworls
popping up as the rough surface is sliced away. The natural color
of the wood slowly appears as the board goes through the planer _
the purple hue of walnut, the reddish tint of oak, the blond
delicacy of ash. From there it's to the woodshop almost every night
as a baseball game plays on the television while I laboriously
build a piece of furniture that will outlast me, with any luck.
</P>
<P>
   I am a notoriously slow furniture maker. I recently built a
Morris chair, which has three reclining positions, lathe-turned
legs and uses mortise-and-tenon joinery. It's pretty. The entire
chair was built out of an eight-foot 4x4 piece of black walnut that
cost me about $30. Roughly, I estimated my time at 80 hours,
meaning I would have to sell the chair for about $600 at minimum
wage to break even _ and that doesn't count the cushion. I doubt
anybody would pay $600 for this chair, but I wouldn't sell it for
twice that anyway. This is not a living. It's a passion, an escape,
and an avocation. One of my descendants will own this chair one day
and maybe think of me.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why I spend weekends climbing around barns and
dodging critters to find that perfect piece of lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
