<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women pay for success
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ We're just sure Rep. James Traficant will unearth
those affidavits any day now, the ones proving that Janet Reno has
been consorting with a lesbian mobster call girl. No doubt he has
misplaced them in a drawer somewhere, right next to the finished
manuscript of Truman Capote's final novel.
</P>
<P>
   It must be true, every last word of it, and not the Youngstown
Democrat's caged-animal response to his legal troubles. Where else
could he have dreamed up such wild allegations?
</P>
<P>
   Where else, that is, but on late-night talk shows, ``Saturday
Night Live'' skits or a popular culture that relentlessly spoofs
Reno's appearance?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a male attorney general getting the same treatment. But
put a woman in the top law-and-order job, and she is SNL's Will
Ferrell in a lace nightie, mooning over the commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Traficant is known for his loose tongue. During an Aug.
7 appearance on the Fox News Network's ``Hannity and Colmes''
program, he accused Reno of everything from ``treason'' to driving
under the influence. Believed to be under federal investigation for
accepting cars and other gifts illegally, his motives are, shall we
say, suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In a supreme triumph of stiff-upper-lipdom, Reno said, ``I just
consider the source.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the source, indeed. But the source, alas, goes far
deeper than Traficant.
</P>
<P>
   What woman in power, or anywhere close to it (witness Chelsea
Clinton and Amy Carter) hasn't undergone intense public scrutiny
for her looks? I once watched, open-mouthed, as a balding, paunchy
congressman rated Hillary Clinton's appearance. Sounding like a
fraternity boy checking out the women on their way to freshman
convocation, he conceded that Mrs. Clinton wasn't bad: ``She isn't
a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Reno has been the butt of talk show hosts,'' said Anne Runyan,
director of the women's studies program at Wright State University.
``It's a cultural grounding which essentially says that a woman in
power is a freak of nature. To be powerful is to be a man;
therefore to be a woman in power is to be manlike.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a political Catch-22: Women are mocked if they appear too
feminine (Pat Schroeder has never been forgiven for her brief
crying jag as she pulled out of the '92 presidential race); they're
mocked if perceived as too masculine. ``A woman can either be like
a man and therefore suffer jokes about her femininityhave I been
subsisting on blackened buffalo steak in the high mountains of
Colorado when back home tomatoes are at high tide, a second crop of
butter beans is coming on, pole beans are plentiful and, because of
the drought, figs are sweeter than they've been in years.
</P>
<P>
   I'm where I am because we had supper with our friends, Judy and
Alex Moye. There's an upside and a downside to dining with the
Moyes. The upside is Alex's charcoaled lamb chops. The downside is
they are always wanting to go somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Two summers ago, they invited us join them in their motor home
for a tour of the Northwestern United States and the Canadian
Rockies. At that time I pointed out some of the dimensions of the
Moye house on wheels, rather large as rolling stock goes.
</P>
<P>
   Last month when we arrived at the Moyes' for the lamb chops, I
noticed something different in their back yard. Alex had upscaled.
A former Eastern Airlines captain, he is working up to a land yacht
comparable to the Boeing 757 he flew between Hartsfield and
Seattle, roughly along the same route we are taking through Lost
Dog.
</P>
<P>
   After surviving an arduous trip into Egypt and up the Nile last
fall, followed by an unexpected visit to my wife's business
convention in Hawaii, I had hoped to spend the rest of the summer
at home, mowing pastures and tending my garden. I had even planned
to clean up my shop, a project I have been contemplating since the
spring of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   When the Moyes invited us along on their new land yacht's maiden
voyage I wasn't overly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to accept,'' said my wife, a direct
descendant of Marco Polo, who never passes up an opportunity to
travel on land, sea or air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Moyes are just being nice,'' I said. ``Don't you think
we'd be imposing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said. ``They really want us to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking about Colorado, Wyoming, Utah, Idaho and
Oregon,'' I pointed out. ``That part of the country is in a drought
worse than ours. We'd probably get burned up in one of those forest
fires.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nonsense,'' she countered. ``Alex is a pilot and knows
all about navigation. He can dodge the fires.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you're right,'' I admitted. The way he drives, Alex
would be the point leader if NASCAR had a motor coach division.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't realize how hot it gets out there,'' I said.
``According to the Weather Channel, 100-plus isn't unusual for this
time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said, ``but it's a dry heat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the mountains we'd be driving through are at
elevations of nearly 15,000 feet and even the new deluxe motor home
doesn't carry oxygen masks like jet airplanes,'' I explained. ``At
my age, I could have a heart attack and drop dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of my dropping dead didn't seem to bother her. So
here we are, in Lost Dog, on the lip of Wyoming's Flaming Canyon,
following a circuitous route to Oregon, passing the Salt Lake and
through Promontory in Idaho, where the famous gold spike hooked the
Atlantic and Pacific together via rail, and a few other interesting
stops.
</P>
<P>
   With a little luck, I think I will survive the latest of our
late-in-life explorations. Compared to China and the Australian
Outback, the sparsely populated American deserts with their
occasional truck stops seem more like New York City in the crowded
Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   However, in Lost Dog I do wonder how the dog got here to get
lost. Our tour of Wyoming has diminished my awe of Ted Turner,
whose ranches reportedly make him the world's largest landholder.
From what I've seen, you could own all of Wyoming and parts of Utah
and Idaho and not be all that well off.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday the thermometer was showing 110.5 when Captain Moye
taxied the motor home into a KOA slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see what I warned you about,'' I said to my wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't complain,'' she answered. ``It's a dry heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. We have upsides. On a three-night stop in
Colorado high country we gave our hosts a break. We put up in a
condo with a sweeping view of the mountains. When I called home to
report that we were alive, well and reasonably safe, our
semi-farmer's wife answered the phone.
</P>
<P>
   When I told her we had a fire that morning she was alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was anyone hurt?'' she asked. ``Are you safe?''
</P>
<P>
   I had to explain that the fire was in a fireplace. It was nice,
right in the middle of dog days, to open a bedroom window, sleep
under a blanket, and wake up to coffee before an open fire with the
bacon and eggs. Besides, Alex has promised to charcoal lamb chops
one evening before we get to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
