A5629 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0819-C     08-18 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting schools to test
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Since Texas Gov. George W. Bush has made education
a high priority in his presidential campaign, many non-Texans have
belittled the state's educational progress.
</P>
<P>
   Texans like to brag, but there's no question that the Lone Star
state has hit upon a winning formula to boost learning among all
categories of students _ rich, poor, minorities, urban, suburban or
rural.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that Vice President Al Gore gave his acceptance
speech at the Democratic convention, the Texas Education Agency
released its annual accountability report for the state's schools.
</P>
<P>
   Performance rating results of every Texas public school are made
public each year. Parents, teachers, administrators, school board
members and taxpayers can quickly see which schools are exemplary,
recognized, acceptable or low performing.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas experience shows that this information makes a
difference. Schools take pride in a high performance rating.
Likewise, they work hard to remove a low performance rating. It's
human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring each Texas school would have little meaning unless
schools had common standards. The Texas Assessment of Academic
Skills test is that statewide standard. It is targeted for specific
grades and is curriculum-based.
</P>
<P>
   NO LEARNING, NO DIPLOMA
</P>
<P>
   Texas public school students cannot graduate from high school
until they demonstrate they have learned the skills implied by
their diploma. They have ample opportunity to retake the test.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Texas has launched a new program to end social
promotions in other grades.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, students in grades 3 through 11 will have to
demonstrate sufficient learning in math, reading, writing, social
studies, science and language arts before they are promoted to a
higher grade.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' education reforms, along with reforms in North Carolina,
have been recognized as the best in the nation, according to a
school performance study by the prestigious nonprofit Rand
institution. Texas' progressive education reforms also have been
praised by other objective education researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's statewide school performance results show that the
state's public schools again bested previous performance records.
</P>
<P>
   Performance results are based on passing TAAS tests as well as
keeping attendance high and dropouts low.
</P>
<P>
   School districts and campuses that earned the highest
performance ratings had 90 percent or more of their total students
in student groups including Hispanic, African American, whites and
economically disadvantaged who passed all sections of the TAAS
test.
</P>
<P>
   While all public schools in Texas must abide by minimum state
standards, individual school districts are free to impose higher
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Waco Independent School District launched a bold
top-to-bottom accountability program three years ago that ended
social promotions in every grade. Teachers in Waco public schools
know their students have the skills required to succeed at a higher
grade.
</P>
<P>
   To be promoted, Waco students must have high attendance, pass
their classroom work and pass a curriculum-based standardized test.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, academic performance in Waco continues to improve,
especially among minorities and economically disadvantaged groups.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Waco's accountability program who warned that
minority students and those from high-poverty families could not
meet the new standards have been proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Higher standards and strict accountability requirements have
benefited minorities and economically disadvantaged students the
most. Dropouts and truancy are down. Grades are up. Academic
standards keep increasing.
</P>
<P>
   This Texas brag is no exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
