<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, August 19 and Sunday, August
20, 2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ WACO, Texas _ Since Texas Gov.
George W. Bush has made education a high priority in his
presidential campaign, many non-Texans have belittled the state's
educational progress. Texans like to brag, but there's no question
that the Lone Star state has hit upon a winning formula to boost
learning among all categories of students _ rich, poor, minorities,
urban, suburban or rural. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ LOST DOG, Wyo. _ Why am I here? Why have I been
subsisting on blackened buffalo steak in the high mountains of
Colorado when back home in Georgia tomatoes are at high tide, a
second crop of butter beans is coming on, pole beans are plentiful
and, because of the drought, figs are sweeter than they've been in
years. I'm where I am because we had supper with our friends, Judy
and Alex Moye. There's an upside and a downside to dining with the
Moyes. The upside is Alex's charcoaled lamb chops. The downside is
they are always wanting to go somewhere. (Jim Minter is a former
editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ We're just sure Rep. James
Traficant will unearth those affidavits any day now, the ones
