   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET HEALTHY LIVING PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
This layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet HEALTHY LIVING 0815 -- Most people need to drink more
than eight glasses of water a day. The reasons we need water are
many. After oxygen, water is the human body's most important need.
Our bodies consist largely of water, and water plays a role in
nearly every major bodily function. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 5-column color photo
illustration of a person pouring eight glasses of water and a
2-column color photo of a woman pouring water into a glass from a
large jug.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT-A-GLANCE BOXES -- Boxes showing foods thathelp
hydrate, ways to test for the purity of tap water and facts about
water filters. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STROKES DANGER -- Relatively few Americans understand what
strokes are, or know enough about them to recognize their symptoms,
even though strokes affect more than 600,000 Americans every year.
(McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PREGNANT TEENS -- Nationwide, the rate of teenage
pregnancies is dropping, even as more youths are becoming sexually
active and at younger ages. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FLAVORED MEDICINE -- Sour apple, cinnamon, root beer or
mint chocolate _ choose a flavor. Parents can take a vacation from
tantrums and screeching cries since pharmacist-technician Kenneth
Kramm invented Flavorx _ 42 flavors to cover the bitter taste of
some prescribed and over-the-counter liquid medicine. (Villalobos,
Dayton Daily News) Art includes a 2-column color photo of a
pharmacist mixing medication and a 6-pica color illustration of a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ Finishing wood is a chore rather than a
pleasure for most woodworkers, but it will make or break your
project. No matter how finely designed and constructed a piece may
be, a bad finish ruins it. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-KOSHER _ Politics, when all's not fare. No
cheeseburgers in paradise for Joseph Lieberman. Campaign staples
are seldom kosher. (Norris, Palm Beach Post). 14.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN. COX EDs: Budget Tool rundate is 0818, category is
LIfestyle
</P>
<P>
   TWINS _ WHITE PLAINS, N.C. _ To the world and to this day, they
are mostly objects of curiosity _ Chang and Eng, the conjoined
brothers whose May 1811 birth in Siam also spawned the phrase
``Siamese twins.'' But in the northwestern corner of North Carolina
where they settled some 30 years later, they have always been the
Bunker brothers _ hard-working tobacco farmers who married sisters,
fathered 21 children between them and lived utterly ordinary,
small-town lives. Officials recently renamed a bridge after the
twins on the White Plains farm where they lived and are buried.
Still, locals don't quite understand the outside world's
fascination with the twins, which has only grown with the
publication this summer of New Yorker Darin Strauss' acclaimed
novel ``Chang and Eng.'' To the folks who showed up at Strauss'
booksignings last week in nearby Mount Airy and Wilkesboro, and to
the1,000-plus descendants who gathered for one of their
semi-regular reunions in White Plains Saturday, it's actually a
pretty familiar story around these parts: The one about strong
family bonds. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-ADVICE _ With the school year approaching, it's time for
teachers and parents to reopen the lines of communication. To save
everyone time and stress, we asked working teachers and frenzied
moms and dads exactly what advice they would give the other side in
order to make this school year the most productive ever. (Dayton
Daily News) WITH ILLUSTRATION. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-COMPASS _ You may remember a time when you were a kid
and you got a toy compass maybe from the neighborhood candy store
or maybe even from a box of Cracker Jacks. Those cheesy little
devices featured a jiggling needle balanced on a pin, and the
painted end of the needle always pointed north. Unless there was a
magnet nearby or the needle fell off the pin. Today you can carry
around a digital device that does the same thing more reliably. The
Co-Pilot from Precision Navigation Inc. gives you a digital readout
that tells you exactly which way you're headed with an accuracy of
plus or minus 5 degrees. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 12. WITH
PHOTO. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is James Cummings' Gadgets Column.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   REL-LOTZ _ Anne Graham Lotz, 51, the daughter of evangelist
Billy Graham, has taken to the road in recent months, spreading the
word of God as part of a conference called, ``Just Give Me Jesus.''
The conference _ it comes to Atlanta next week _ is hugely
successful, drawing tens of thousands of women at each stop. Lotz
says she is driven by a personal need to be closer to God and to
reach others even as some Baptist evangelicals turn their backs on
her. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   GODZILLA-TIMELINE _ The latest chapter in Godzilla comes out
this Friday so we're doing a funny, very visual timeline of
Godzilla _ We're hitting some of the highpoints and lowpoints (the
Matthew Broderick movie) of the Godzilla franchise. (BLongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   NANCY-DREW _ The case of the Nancy Drew Fans. Readers of all
ages share memories and adventures inspired by the titian-haired
sheuth. With open color page. (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). 71 WITH
OPEN COLOR PAGE.
