Island and a 2-column color photo of a woman looking at the
military monument at Midway Island.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO BOX-- A list of tips for travelers going to
Midway Island.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Car rental rates jumped last month, with
Hertz taking the first step and the other national companies
following immediately. Others. (N.Y. Times News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ABINGTON _ ABINGTON, Va. _ It is an unseasonably cool,
moonless night in this historic Blue Ridge Mountain town, a good
evening for a ghost tour ems to have more than a healthy share.
Named Abingdon in honor of Martha Washington's ancestral home in
England, this mountain town is home to the Barter Theater, the
Martha Washington Inn and other intriguing historic places.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BLOWROCK _ BLOWING ROCK, N.C. The legend goes that a
Cherokee brave dived off the Blowing Rock to appease his gods and
was caught in an updraft so powerful that he was lifted back to his
sweetheart's arms. I wasn't feeling quite that lucky on my visit to
this popular Blue Ridge Mountains attraction. In fact I hung on to
the flat, upturned rock _ the parapet, it seemed, of a mighty
castle _ for dear life. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BLUERIDGE _ BLUE RIDGE, Ga. _ There it is, tucked into
the trees just off the road: Our pine-log-sided North Georgia cabin
with a red tin roof. Up the Creek, it's called. Clambering out of
the car and racing to the porch, we hear the soothing sounds of Hot
House Creek. Wooden stairs from the lower deck lead directly to the
chilly waters. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CASHIERS _ CASHIERS, N.C. _ Visiting the High Hampton Inn
&AMP; Country Club, a 1,400-acre antebellum estate that will fill your
belly three times a day and house you in a rustic cottage free of
certain conveniences. ``Son,'' I told our 12-year-old before we
left, ``this resort where we're staying is going to cost about $350
a night and it won't have a telephone or a television.'' It was
enough to turn his face away from the computer screen. ``You're
kidding, right?'' (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-HENDERSONVILLE _ HENDERSONVILLE, N.C. _ The social
``hour'' at the Waverly Inn was already two hours old when those of
us rocking and sipping wine on the porch decided to move the party
a few blocks down Main Street to the Monday-night street dance.
That's right, a street dance. On a Monday night. That's the kind of
place this is: a small mountain town in the heart of North Carolina
apple country, where hundreds of folks cut a rug (or just watch
from lawn chairs) during the street dances (continuing through
Labor Day). (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MAGGIEVALLEY _ MAGGIE VALLEY, N.C. _ The Smoky Mountains
look different from the back of a horse. Lovelier. Less familiar.
Maybe it's because this place, the 1,000-acre Cataloochee Ranch, is
so close to paradise you half-expect to enter it through pearly
gates. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ROOFTOP _ ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ If you're heading here to
look at the fall leaves, one of your best viewing sites might be
from the roof of the Biltmore House. That's right. The roof. The
guided 75-minute Rooftop Tour will take you up amid the turrets and
gargoyles, where you can get a panoramic view of the gardens, the
French Broad River and Mount Pisgah. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LITTLE-SWISS _ LITTLE SWITZERLAND, N.C. _ Other places in
the North Carolina mountains are better-known, but none are like
this faux-alpine hideaway nestled at 3,500 feet in the southern
Appalachians. It brims daily with color and tranquillity. In the
fall, especially, Little Switzerland, just off the Blue Ridge
Parkway, is a place many folks come for a long weekend. Many come
to like it so much they plan ahead, booking a week at the
Switzerland Inn or another nearby mountain lodge. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TOWNSEND _ TOWNSEND, Tenn. _ The campfire is a portable
propane model that looks like something out of the Flintstones. The
moonlit mesa is in truth a screen-printed mural. But the guy in the
black chaps, vest and tall cowboy hat, the fellow spinning cowpoke
tales as tall as a saguaro cactus, stories that roll on like
tumbleweeds,he's got this western thing down. Ladies and gentlemen,
put your hands together for tonight's headliner, cowboy poet
extraordinaire David ``Buffalo Bill'' Nelson. Oh, by the way,
Buffalo, er, David is also your innkeeper. He and wife Jean operate
the western-decorated B&AMP;B Abode and Beyond, here near the entrance
to the Great Smoky Mountains National Park. (Pousner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MNT-FESTS _ A listing of Southeast mountain festivals
this fall. (Brooks, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ABORIGINE-ART _ Thirty years ago, an art professor encouraged a
group of Aborigines in the central desert of Australia to paint on
canvas the symbolic patterns their people had been making in the
red dirt for eons. The dirt patterns evolved into dot paintings, a
popular form of folk art that has become synonymous with Australia
and will figure prominently in the Sydney Olympic Arts Festival. We
look at the field, which has interesting parallels with the artwork
that won praise at the last Olympics: Southern folk art.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. EMBARGOED
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   DEBBIE-ALLEN _ A conversation with Debbie Allen, the Broadway
dancer who here plays writer-composer of a new dance drama, ``Soul
Possessed,'' about a girl who runs off with a mysterious drifter,
set against the mysticism of the Louisiana bayous. (Auchmutey,
Atlanta Journal-Con commentary.
</P>
