<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS RIDING WOODS'S WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rob Correa quickly runs out of superlatives to describe Tiger
Woods and the impact he has had on televised golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to be original when you are talking about Tiger,''
the CBS Sports senior vice president said. ``But he has been
unbelievably great. He is the biggest sports story in recent
memory. He has changed the sport of golf much like Muhammad Ali
changed the sport of boxing. He has already surpassed Michael
Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Surpassed Michael Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   Correa is not exaggerating. At 24, Woods is the youngest player
to win all four majors, breaking the mark set by Jack Nicklaus at
26. Tiger has been equally impressive as a television attraction.
According to CBS Sports research, in 1999, when Tiger was even in
contention in a golf event, the broadcast averaged a 4.1 rating and
11 share, 41 percent higher than when he was not in contention or
did not play.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Woods has increased network ratings by 104
percent when he is in contention. He also has expanded the golf
audience among young viewers, including a 150 percent increase in
men 18-34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is good for everybody,'' Correa said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, according to several agents representing other PGA
players.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Giles, a player agent with Pros Inc., which represents
Davis Love and Justin Leonard, told the Bloomberg News that Woods
has caused a drop in endorsement money for other Tour members.
``Other players are going to get less and less off-tour income;
it's that simple,'' Giles said. ``It's not going to be any
better.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Correa strongly believes that Woods is great for golf
and particularly for networks that air major events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy the argument that Tiger is hurting other player's
endorsements,'' said Correa. ``Tiger is the reason that more people
are tuning into the sport in the first place. He has raised the
awareness of the sport to include minorities, women and younger
viewers. More people are wathcing the sport now that have never
watched it before. Tiger can't be bad for the sport. He has no
negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his gushing, Correa said that CBS will not have a camera
dedicated to Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to cover the PGA Championship,'' Correa said.
``We still have to show the leaderboard. We can't go into the
weekend with any preconceived notions. Nor do we want someone to
sneak up on the leaderboard without people at home seeing how they
got there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Self-evaluation
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Miller thinks he's doing all right on ``Monday Night
Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm getting wood on the ball; I'm keeping the at-bat
alive,'' Miller told Jim Litke of ``One on One Sports'' (AM 1510)
on Tuesday. ``I'm having a blast. I can't believe I walk into the
booth and have this seat on the 50-yard line. I'll be honest with
you: Before the Canton Hall of Fame game, I had been to only one
football game in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that he is unsure whether the NFL or football fans
are ready for his sarcasm. ``I'm perfectly willing to be fired if
they're not,'' Miller said. ``I don't have any qualms about that. I
have a great job at HBO. I'm not trying to be a martyr, I just do
what I do. I'm not going to be bullheaded about it. Believe me,
I'll handle it with a nice degree of aplomb if they come up and
say, `Hey listen, we think you're OK but you're not for us, you're
whacked. It's like G. Gordon Liddy said, `Just tell me what corner
to be standing on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's third game (Green Bay-Miami) airs 8 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Like It Is' . . . again
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO's Emmy Award-winning sports documentary ``Howard Cosell:
Telling It Like It Is'' re-airs 7 p.m. Monday . . . ESPN's
``Outside the Lines'' takes a look at the pressure on the
Washington Redskins to win the Super Bowl. ESPN reports that owner
Daniel Synder is spending $77 million on player salaries this year,
the highest ever for any professional sports team. Snyder
apparently has a lot. He sold his communications compoany for $2.1
billion in 1999, and purchased the team for $800 million. The
30-minute show airs at 7 p.m. ESPN has the Vikings-Cardinals game
at 8 with Mike Patrick, Joe Theismann, Paul Maguire and Solomon
Wilcots making the calls . . . Jon Miller and Joe Morgan call the
Red Sox-Rangers game at 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Issue taken
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Olbermann blasted the Red Sox for coming down on Boston
Magazine for running a photograph of Pedro Martinez on its cover
apparently without permission. ``The Boston Red Sox are furious at
Boston Magazine because it has put a picture of Pedro Martinez on
the cover of its most recent issue,'' Olbermann said on his Monday
show. ``What's he doing on it? Making an obscene gesture? Shouting
at a little kid? Crossing a picket line? Nope. He's smiling. He
should be. The current issue is devoted to Boston's Best, and
according to the magazine, Pedro is . . . it. Then why are the Red
Sox angry? The magazine didn't get the team's s permission first.
You know . . . sometimes in this life, you just have to draw a line
in the sand. Gotta stamp out that unauthorized good publicity
before it gets out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
