<SLUG> BC-OLY-USGYM-MALONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGERIES KEEP KRISTEN MALONEY A CUT ABOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Playing with pain is part of the game for an Olympic
athlete. What can you expect, after all, after years of
somersaulting on a 4-inch-wide balance beam, flying off the vault
with a double-twist handspring, or swinging from one bar to the
other, then releasing and landing on the mat with a loud thud.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend athlete gasps; the Olympic hopeful just shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   A little soreness is to be expected and a little pain is often
ignored. Well, until it becomes a big pain.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Kristen Maloney, who blithely cruised
through the Worlds and Nationals in 1998 and 1999 with a stress
fracture in her right shin and persistent soreness in her left
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last fall, doctors said, ``Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, they made an incision and hammered a titanium rod
inside the length of her right tibia, and then they tightened the
tendons in her left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   By January, she resumed training. By March, she was the top
American finisher in the International Games. In July, Maloney
almost defended her title of national champion, falling short to
Elise Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a miracle,'' declared Bela Karolyi, coordinator of the
national women's team, earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney concedes that her comeback was pretty amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was surprised at how quickly I got my skills back
from my injuries, especially after how much time I had to take
off,'' she said. ``I think I was even surprised myself.''
</P>
<P>
   So by now, nothing seems to faze Maloney, who will compete at
the FleetCenter this weekend against 13 other women for a spot on
the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   She just laughs _ not nervously, but confidently _ and says,
``I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's one person who's not surprised at Maloney's comeback,
it's Donna Strauss, who with her husband, Bill, runs the Parkettes
Gym in Allentown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss said that when Maloney, 19, was 6 years old and living
in Pen Argyl, Pa., her mother enrolled her in the gym so she'd have
something to do while her other brother and sister went to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``She started out just doing tumbling then each year got a
little bit better, a little bit better,'' Strauss said. ``Then when
she was about 12, we saw how she had a lot on perserverance and
drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss taps her chest with her fist when she describes how her
star pupil blossomed into an Olympic hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``With some kids, success comes very quickly and naturally,''
she said. ``But Kristen chisled at it little by little, and I think
that's what made her such a strong competitor and has kept her
driven for this long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   And neither challenges not adversity seemed to matter.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 12, her parents took her to a regional meet, but
told Strauss that their daughter had a fever and they didn't think
she could compete. But she did, and ended up winning the meet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Maloney's litany of injuries did concern the coach. In
June 1998, her shin started hurting but she was insistent on
competing.
</P>
<P>
   First, she won the Pacific Alliance Championship in Canada, then
won a gold medal on the balance beam at the Goodwill Games, and
finally, won the US Championships in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   All of that was with a stress fracture in her shin.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss decided to rest Maloney that fall, demanding she only
work the upper body and exercise on the stationary bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, she deemed Maloney ready to train vigorously.
In March, she gave her the OK to compete in the International Team
Meet in Richmond, Va. Maloney finished second in the all-around
competition and was the top American finisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked because she really wasn't ready to go full
force,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   The season brought more success as Maloney defended her national
title.
</P>
<P>
   But by the fall, the pain in Maloney's shin was getting worse,
exacerbated by a fall off the uneven bars in the Worlds in which
she sprained her knee.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors decided to insert the rod, a procedure that's been
used with accident victims who have had their bones crushed and to
relieve stress fractures. Maloney didn't mind at all; in fact, she
wanted to watch as the doctor hammered in the 8-millimeter wide
titanium rod along the length of her tibia.
</P>
<P>
   But her medical woes weren't over, as doctors decided to check
out her left shoulder that had been bothering her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wast just hurting on and off for a couple years and I had
therapy, but nothing seemed to help,'' Maloney said. ``So they went
in and tightened up the socket.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though soreness does go along with her sport, Maloney said
she's learned to heed the warning light that goes off when
something's beyond sore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell right away, like when I'm warming up, what's
hurting and what's sore,'' she said. ``I know my body and I know
what it can take.''
</P>
<P>
   And after all the X-rays, physical therapy, and breaks from
training, maybe the rod in her leg is a good luck charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In certain ways, I feel better than I was before,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1204EDT &QL; 
