<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     08-18 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGENDS SHARE AN UNCOMMON GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tiger Woods respectfully walked into Jack
Nicklaus's house and gave (itals)him(unitals) the tour. That's not
supposed to happen, is it? What is the polite thing to say when a
visitor knows your home's layout just as well as you do?
</P>
<P>
   Woods figured the grounds out so quickly that the host didn't
have time to be hospitable. Nicklaus designed this place, Valhalla
Golf Club, when Woods was 10 years old. As he watched Woods
artfully walk over the course during the opening round of the PGA
Championship, Nicklaus looked like a homeowner who realized that he
had built too soon. Fourteen years too soon. If you had observed
and talked with the 60-year-old Nicklaus Thursday, it would have
been obvious that the Golden Bear didn't have a player like Woods
in mind when he came up with the concept of Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time Nicklaus and Woods played together in a
tournament. Masters champion Vijay Singh was also in their group.
The three men began their work day at 9:17 a.m. By noon, Nicklaus
and Singh could have easily answered the question: How good is
Tiger Woods?
</P>
<P>
   Officially, he was good enough to shoot a 66, even though
Nicklaus said Woods could have had a 12-under 60 and that he ``was
unlucky to shoot 66. You are out there struggling for 75. (Woods)
makes you look like you are shooting 95.''
</P>
<P>
   Since we're talking about official numbers, the leaderboard
reports that Woods is now tied with Scott Dunlap for first place,
two shots ahead of Davis Love and Darren Clarke. Now that we have
that settled, can we speak honestly? Tiger Woods is going to win
this tournament. You know it, I know it, and Scott Dunlap probably
knows it, too. When Woods wins Sunday, he will capture his third
major championship of the year. No player has done that since Ben
Hogan in 1953. Hogan once said that a player can dominate his
competition with a combination of talent, intimidation, and hard
work. Woods took the late Texan's list and added another entry:
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has fused those elements so well that Nicklaus, designer
of 209 courses, was stumped when asked what kind of layouts can
neutralize the defending PGA champion. What would happen if courses
were longer?
</P>
<P>
   ``The more yardage you put on a golf course, the more dominant
he is going to be,'' Nicklaus said.
</P>
<P>
   What about shorter? ``Well, he knocks it past everything,'' he
said. ``What I am really trying to say is I don't believe you can .
. . ''
</P>
<P>
   So, what do you do? ``You are not going to harness the best
player in the world,'' he said. ``The only thing you are going to
do is make the other guys play better. I don't know. That's the
only way I can answer.''
</P>
<P>
   It may sound strange, but a lot of pros were pleased to hear
Nicklaus say that. Some of them felt slighted when Nicklaus seemed
to imply previously that Woods had psyched them out of their games.
Maybe some of them were caught in a complex Woods mind game, but
can anyone say that Ernie Els hasn't had a great year? He finished
11 under at the British Open and still lost. So it's more accurate
to say that Woods is better than everyone else _ and improving.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, some fans believed Sergio Garcia, who
shot 74, would be Woods's longtime rival. If not Garcia, then David
Duval, who withdrew Tuesday, Els . . . somebody. With any prodigy,
athlete, or actor, the temptation is to wonder if they will
eventually fade into oblivion (see ``Bridges, Todd'' in ``Diff'rent
Strokes''). But there will be no rivals nor fading any time soon.
Nicklaus realized that as he was roughing his way to a 77.
</P>
<P>
   The two legends, born nearly 36 years apart, studied each other
and soon understood why there is so much lore surrounding each of
them. Woods said he knew Nicklaus's mind was elsewhere, due to the
death of Nicklaus's mother Wednesday. He said he could also see
that Nicklaus was and is a thinker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell he is used to being specific on his shots,''
Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   On the 163-yard eighth hole, Nicklaus was surprised when Woods
went to work with a 9-iron (Nicklaus was using a 6-iron).
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept turning mine upside down,'' the older man said, ``I
said, `Turn yours upside down so it looks like we're playing the
same club.' He hit some long irons. Gosh, he hits the ball a long
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The men chatted and laughed a couple times as they played in the
90-degree heat. Nicklaus told Woods about a new driver; Woods
explained to Nicklaus what his strategy had been on an approach to
a hole. Nicklaus, the builder of the place, acknowledged that Woods
did some things on the course that he didn't think were possible.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, they both talked about what it's like to
work when someone close to you dies or comes close to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no desire to be here, I promise you,'' Nicklaus said.
``But I felt like it is what (his mother) would have wanted me to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 _ during Woods's first year on the tour _ his father,
Earl, was in the hospital with chest pains. ``I spent all night at
the hospital with him and didn't sleep,'' Woods said. ``I slept
sitting in a chair for a couple hours and had to go play. But I
asked my dad, you know, `(Can I) be here with you?' He said, `No,
get your butt out there so I can watch you on TV. At least I have
something to look forward to, because I have got tubes and stuff
stuck in me.'''
</P>
<P>
   As Woods and Nicklaus walked and talked, the easy thing to say
was that they had a lot in common. They do. But when it comes to
the game, Woods has few obstacles, Nicklaus-designed courses
included.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
