u s BC-BOX-NASEEM-BOS &LR;      08-18 1882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NASEEM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCE HAS THE POWER TO CONQUER THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIANTIC, Conn. _ Pulsating beats and loud rhythms blast their
way out of a boombox, one decible after another, until no eardrum
in the cramped, stuffy boxing gym is spared.
</P>
<P>
   And, these eardrums belong to folks of various ages and ethnic
groups, many of whom wouldn't be tuned in to Mary J. Blige,
Notorious B.I.G., and Shalamar if it weren't for the 26-year-old,
5-foot-3-inch boxer in the middle of the ring _ who is getting his
groove on while his handlers slip his gloves on.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Naseem Hamed sashays around the ring, hurls his
diminutive frame into the ropes, bounces off, and delivers a
dazzling shadow-boxing display. Then the canvas becomes a dance
floor again and the popular, effervescent WBO featherweight
champion moves to the beat. Then it's back to canvas. Dance floor.
Canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The music stops and the beats give way to the
leather-upon-leather sounds of Hamed's gloves against the pads of
trainer Oscar Suarez. The sound of the punches fill the room the
way the music once did and it's hard to believe a guy that small
could hit that hard. On one combination, Hamed nearly knocks Suarez
off balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt, didn't it?'' asks Hamed, who once dislocated
Suarez's shoulder while hitting the pads.
</P>
<P>
   The punches keep coming, heads shake at the display of enormous
power and speed, and the British-born, Yemeni fighter can't help
but thinking aloud about his HBO fight Saturday night at Foxwoods
Casino, where he will put his flashy style, eye-popping talents,
and perfect record on the line against Augie Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's gonna be out,' Hamed says while finishing a flurry.
``Somebody's gonna be out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 7-year old son of a Sheffield, England, corner grocer had to
wait four years before he was old enough for his first amateur
bout. In the meantime, Naseem Hamed trained six days a week and
once encouraged a boxing publication editor to write a story on him
because he was going to be world champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were telling me, `Naz, heavyweights get paid
unbelievable amounts of money, man. Middleweights.
Super-middleweights. Featherweights don't get nothing like that,'
'' he said. ``I said, `You watch. I'm gonna change boxing.' I was
predicted champion and a multimillionaire at age 21 when I was 10
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hamed finally became eligible for amateur bouts, he
discovered he was so light that he didn't fit any weight class for
11-year-olds. He spent a year trying to gain weight, but, a year
later, was still too light.
</P>
<P>
   But his trainers signed him up anyway, and subsequently stitched
lead weights into his trunks for the weigh-in. That did it. Folks
would soon discover Hamed's fists packed a lead wallop, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed shot through the amateur ranks, claiming five National
Schoolboy championships, an England Schoolboy International
championship, and two junior Amateur Boxing Association
championships, growing with confidence (some would say cockiness)
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   It was around then Naseem Hamed began carving the image of a
fighter who would do as his boyhood boxing idol, Muhammad Ali, had
done decades earlier: infuse life into the sport by ushering in a
color and personality that would be loved or hated but rarely
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people out there who want to see me get beat.
Now I ain't got a problem with that, not at all,'' said Hamed.
``Want to see me get beat? Want to see me win? No problem. As long
as you interested in watching me fighting or boxing. I don't care.
Switch on or pay for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already brought in a sparkle into boxing. Thank Allah, I
brought something into boxing that wasn't really in, because when
Ali went out, he brought a hell of a lot out with him. I want to
bring just a little bit of that back.''
</P>
<P>
   George Azar, who handles Hamed's public relations in the United
States, said Hamed was discovered by Irish boxing trainer Brendan
Ingle, who used to make fighters watch films starring Gene Kelly
and Fred Astaire to learn footwork. Hamed also studied Ali, Jersey
Joe Wolcott, and Sugar Ray Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name, `Prince,' was given to me by myself at 17, before
turning pro,'' said Hamed. ``I didn't want to be just Naseem Hamed,
because Naseem means gentle breeze in Arabic, and I'm not a gentle
breeze in the ring. So it needs to be a ringing tone people will
remember as a prince because a prince must always become a king.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a professional, Hamed dominated the Eastern Hemisphere and
moved up the super bantamweight ranks. He captured the WBC super
bantamweight title in 1994 then won the WBO featherweight crown a
year later.
</P>
<P>
   In his US debut, he scored a fourth-round knockout of New Yorker
Kevin Kelly in Manhattan to retain the WBO crown, in a grueling
match in which each fighter was knocked down three times.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed's winning ways rolled on, and he successfully defendended
his title in a 12-round unanimous decision over Wayne McCullough in
Atlantic City a year later. But it was evident that Hamed's
unorthodox boxing style was being exploited by more skilled
American fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Suarez and legendary trainer Emanuel Steward, who added
fundamentals to Hamed's arsenal, while helping him tune his skills.
</P>
<P>
   Steward said early on he was surprised how far Hamed had come
despite the fact that he never had been in a training camp, had
never done roadwork, and despite suffering a broken hand as an
amateur, never taped his hands before a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no one ever in the history of the boxing to do
what he's done and accomplished what he accomplished,'' said
Steward. ``And, I think just at the time when Oscar Suarez got
involved with him was about the time he was about to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition was stepping up. Guys like Kevin Kelly. He
really won the fight, but you could see, to me, the beginning of
the end. The mistakes he made with his unorthodox style and the
fighters were beginning to take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did was not change his basic style, believe it or not,
because it's a good, effective style for him. We've tried to take
advantage of it by making improvements, keeping his chin down more.
He's a high-energy kid and that's OK. But mainly watching his
balance, particularly when he finishes up his punches.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hamed ascended the professional ranks, he noticed the
love-me-or-hate-me reaction he wanted came in flood-like
proportions worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the fact he was one of few fighters of Arab descent
making a major impact on the sport, but he had the gall to do it
his way, to defy a sport deeply rooted in tradition and ring
etiquette (particularly in Europe) with outlandish tactics and
turbo-charged ego.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed is widely known for his ring entrances, which include
flipping over the top rope and kissing his biceps. He often drops
his gloves at his waist during bouts. He turns his back on his
opponent. He plays to the crowd. He has been able to get away with
this in part because of his enormous punching power and speed.
</P>
<P>
   He has often been villified by the traditional fans and media,
particularly those in England: Azar said British officials have
been bothered so much by Hamed's dropping his guard they they once
ruled he wasn't defending himself in a fight and awarded the fight
to his battered opponent. Hamed said, as an amateur everyone told
him they enjoyed his boxing style, but he said he does regret being
left off England's Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to tell me as an amateur, `Just make sure you
bring everything you have to the professional ranks, because you
are an exception,' '' he said. ``I see how heavyweights get so
much, and I said, `I'm going to be the first featherweight to make
history.' Because if you're an exception, television wants you,
you're gonna get paid. You're gonna get paid.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And how. In fact, for every Hamed detractor, there are throngs
of folks who can't get enough of his show. There are many who
consider him an icon, one who has helped fuel interest in the sport
among those who otherwise wouldn't watch boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Azar said he has particularly become a symbol of pride in the
Arab community and is a national sports hero in Yemen, where six
postage stamps have been issued in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Naz fights, 150 million people tune in worldwide,'' said
Azar, who pointed out his place in Fortune's list as one of the 40
highest-paid athletes in the world. ``Naseem makes as much money in
product endorsements as Lennox Lewis, Evander Holyfield, and Oscar
De La Hoya combined.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamed comes from a close-knit family and now has his siblings
involved in his boxing venture, Prince Promotions. Handling his own
promotions ensures big paydays.
</P>
<P>
   His oldest brother, Riath, is the CEO and has brokered deals
with Sony, addidas, Pepsi, and Audi. His brother Nabeel, a former
boxer himself, manages his training camp. Brother Ali is his
spiritual adviser. Brother Murad is in charge of the music at his
events and camp and said several hip-hop artists, including LL Cool
J and producer Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, have made tapes for him to
play at fights.
</P>
<P>
   A former salesman, Nabeel said if he wasn't managing his
brother's training camp, he would probably own his own business.
Then he added with a laugh, ``But that's boring compared to what
we're doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Naseem said, much of this has been a bonanza for
television. Hamed's second US fight, against McCullough, reportedly
posted a 12.8 rating and was the most-watched boxing broadcast of
1998. Those who put on his fights have gotten into the act, too,
punctuating Hamed's entrance into the ring with elaborate stage
props.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically a few days before the fight he will tell (the
network) a few things, and they'll put the five different entrances
together and ask him which one he would like to pick,'' said Murad.
``Then he'll see what it's like and rehearse and he adds a few
changes in rehearsal.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamed also has right of refusal, which he has exercised. Azar
said one network televising a Hamed bout on Halloween suggested he
come from a graveyard with tombstones of all his opponents behind
him. He said Hamed balked, reminding the producers of the fatal
nature of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Hamed (34-0, 30 KOs) will be recognized as the best
in his division until he beats those now widely considered the
best, Erik Morales and Marco Antonio Barerra. Lee Samuels of Top
Rank, Inc., who handles Morales, said that fight will likely come
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamed said he is not looking past the likes of Sanchez
(26-1, 23 KOs), who has won 10 straight bouts, nine by knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Steward said that an opponent like Sanchez has him
concerned. Hamed, seated about 5 feet away, yelled out, ``I'm
not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big weakness for Augie Sanchez, that's Prince Naseem,''
Steward said. ``He's never seen this certain style. He's never been
hit as hard or as fast or as accurate. I don't underestimate or
overestimate him. I feel like I'm going to dismantle him and take
him out and expose him to the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
