<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-BOS &LR;      08-18 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' KEEPS VIEWERS WATCHING . . . AND TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``Survivor'' premiered in late May, it was viewed as a new
strain of the Springer-esque ``reality TV'' virus, and many an
eyebrow was seen heading toward the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   In the twelve weeks since that first day on Pulau Tiga, though,
``Survivor'' has grown into America's favorite new pop-cultural
obsession. It has become a mystery craze on the level of ``Who Shot
J.R.?,'' it has topped the Nielsen ratings and delivered a
much-needed young demographic to CBS, and it has served as a
launching pad for 16 mini-celebrities who are best known by first
name only. And, most importantly, despite its nonfictional
trappings, ``Survivor'' has proven itself to be an entirely
different beast from the reality likes of ``Big Brother,'' the
psuedo-voyeuristic cesspool with which it was said to form a trend.
``Survivor,'' which finishes its first season Wednesday night, has
proven itself to be drama of the first order.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, drama. There may be real bug-infested sores on
``Survivor,'' but the brilliantly edited series has played out like
the most absorbing, carefully paced fiction on TV. It's got the
scheming villainy of ``Dynasty,'' it's got the paranoia of ``The
X-Files,'' it's got the calm-faced duplicity of a ``Masterpiece
Theatre'' adaptation, and, if you view the tribal councils as
metaphorical, it's got the murder and self-preservation of ``The
Sopranos.'' With apologies to Richard, the show's resident
naturist, ``Survivor'' is a stark naked glimpse of the human drama
in a competitive setting. There's no costuming, no Denver
Carrington or ColbyCo; just a bunch of ambitious losers on an empty
island, simultaneously trying to coexist and stab one another in
the back for a million bucks. It's group mind games laid completely
bare.
</P>
<P>
   The editing, of course, is what makes ``Survivor'' more drama
than reality. Each hour has been culled from miles of footage, then
arranged into a roller-coaster of a narrative equipt with dizzying
reversals. Producer Mark Burnett and his crew manipulate viewers
shamelessly from commercial to commercial, giving us the Tagi
alliance conspiring against Sean and then _ surprise! _ giving us
the alliance booting Jenna to capitalize on Sean's alphabet
approach. In a neat series of scenes, we saw tough-talking Susan
turn one face to Richard, another to Kelly, and yet another to us.
Even the tribal councils are rigged for titillation as camp
counselor Jeff Probst reads off the votes (holding them in the now
signature gesture) in the most suspense-building order possible.
``Survivor'' isn't too far from an improvised Robert Altman movie,
where the ``script'' is constructed in the editing room.
</P>
<P>
   After all, viewers do like to be toyed with by storytellers, an
entertainment rule that the ``Big Brother'' people ignore. The idea
of real-time TV like ``Big Brother'' may be cool, in a
performance-art-meets-Internet sort of way; but the actuality has
become a prime-time yawner of epic proportions. Get out the knives,
``Big Brother'' editors, and chop chop chop!
</P>
<P>
   Also, the ``Survivor'' editors work hard to sculpt their
characters into an ensemble worthy of Aaron Spelling. Richard, of
course, is portrayed as the clever conniver, and his slimeball
alliance goons aren't made to look much better _ worse, in fact, if
you think hidden evil is more insidious than the visible kind. On
one level, Rudy is a curmudgeon passively riding Richard's
coattails; on another level, he's a judgmental homophobe who isn't
above threatening violence if Richard betrays him in their
sub-alliance. Meanwhile, the editors have given us a few good guys
_ sensible Colleen, cautious Gretchen, naive Sean _ all of whom
have been gobbled up by the hungrier reservoir dogs.
</P>
<P>
   These people are characters, creations of Mark Burnett and
``Survivor,'' and not exactly the people themselves. In an
interview with EW.com, Colleen pointed out how the show's creative
team devised their own version of her, a phenomenon often mentioned
by graduates of MTV's ``The Real World.'' ``The editing really made
it seem like I started speaking out only after Greg left,'' she
said. ``That was the storyline, I think. You know, Greg's left,
Colleen now comes into her own. But I'd been talking the whole
time.'' Kelly, who has been portrayed as a player uncomfortable
with her own opportunistic nature, summed it up nicely in this
week's episode: ``We're not evil; we just play bad people on TV.''
Does that mean Richard may not be such a creep?
</P>
<P>
   The other secret to the success of ``Survivor'': Secrecy. In
today's massive hype factory, a good secret is very hard to find.
Movie trailers, magazine profiles, newspaper reviews,
``Entertainment Tonight'' pieces _ each trumpets movie and TV plot
information like a cell-phone addict on a crowded bus. Except for a
live awards show like the Oscars _ and even the Wall Street Journal
tried to scoop that event last year by polling Oscar voters _ we
aren't allowed to enjoy much mystery these days. That ``Survivor''
has been able to keep the identity of the winner from our
spoiler-hungry press is nothing short of a millennial miracle.
What's more, Burnett may have been clever enough to plant
disinformation when conjecture began to heat up, most famously with
a hacked-up ``Survivor'' website image indicating Gervase was the
last man standing.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, I won't argue that ``Survivor'' is great art, or
that Richard Hatch now stands beside Richard III and Richard
Burton. But I do believe that the series qualifies as great TV,
that it has fully realized the potential of its medium to capture
the country's imagination and get us talking, and thinking.
Alliances, sub-alliances, strategies like booting your best
competitor first (bye, Gretchen) _ these concepts have become the
stuff of passionate mainstream chitchat, along with some pretty
rigorous character analysis of the castaways. Indeed, what has made
this the summer of ``Survivor'' is the intensity of the show's
water cooler buzz, much of which takes place on the Internet,
particularly at a coyly written site called Survivorsucks.com.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, the buzz about ``Survivor'' will segue to the
buzz about a much weighier contest. And like the castaways, we too
will find ourselves caught in a changing society, preparing to cast
votes, and very, very tired of rats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Sean out of the picture, the competition has come down to
the Tagi alliance, comprised of the four most ruthless castaways:
Kelly, Richard, Rudy, and Susan. Will they eat each other for
dinner?
</P>
<P>
   The first season of ``Survivor'' wraps next Wednesday with a
two-hour episode at 8 p.m. and then a live, hourlong Town Hall
meeting with the castmembers at 10 p.m. The episode will include
two immunity contests and three tribal councils. At the last
council, the winner will be determined after the two finalists
stand trial by the jury of seven. The Town Hall meeting,
``Survivor: The Reunion,'' will be hosted by Bryant Gumbel and
include all 16 contestants.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Jeff Probst? The much-mocked ``Survivor'' host will
be back early next year, leading a new pack of backstabbing
adventurers through the Australian outback for ``Survivor II.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
