<HEADLINE>
GALWAY'S SAW DOCTORS BRING PUNK POP TO THE STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Saw Doctors have been a rabidly well-liked Irish-rock club
act, but this summer they're stepping up to headline bigger stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to make it work. You have to be ambitious, don't
you?'' says Saw Doctors singer/guitarist Leo Goran, who formed the
band with fellow singer/guitarist Davy Carton over a pint of beer
in their small Galway hometown of Tuam 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Saw Doctors received a boost by performing on several
Guinness Fleadhs in recent years, but Guinness pulled its
sponsorship this year, thus eliminating any Fleadhs this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the irreverent punk-influenced Saw Doctors were not fazed
and are instead going full-tilt into their own headlining tour. And
this time they've added two horn players, including saxophonist
Anthony Thistlewaite, formerly of the Waterboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to bring people something new,'' says Moran.
``It's good, because it makes us rearrange some of the old songs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saw Doctors are still looking for breakthrough status in the
States, but they've been big in Ireland for years, ever since their
album, ``If This Is Rock 'n' Roll, I Want My Old Job Back,'' went
to No. 1 in 1991. By that time the band had also scored a No. 1
Irish single, ``I Useta Lover,'' a controversial song about going
to Catholic services and checking out members of the opposite sex
there.
</P>
<P>
   They even rhymed ``Mass'' with a part of the anatomy _ and got
away with it. ``People liked the honesty of it,'' Goran recalls.
</P>
<P>
   As might be obvious, the Saw Doctors are not trying to be
trendy. ``We're not like U2,'' says Moran. ``We don't have four
costume people and four makeup people. We've never been into that.
We've never tried to be cool. . . . And U2 goes out and tries to
play into what 18-year-olds are doing. We've never done that. There
are pros and cons to both approaches _ probably more pros to theirs
_ but that's not us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in the same room a couple of times with U2, but we
wouldn't know what to say to them,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to define the Saw Doctors' sound, Moran says, ``For me,
the essence is that it's pop music that takes in rock 'n' roll and
punk, with an Irish accent and Irish idioms. . . . But we're not
virtuoso musicians. We have to rely on having songs.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has been influenced by the Sex Pistols as well as by
the Kinks (notably the band's 12-string guitar sound) and by Bruce
Springsteen's working-class anthems. ``We like the way he writes
about the connectedness of ordinary people. That has influenced
us,'' says Moran.
</P>
<P>
   The Saw Doctors have had some record label difficulties in the
States _ their last label, Paradigm, folded _ but they're now
negotiating with four other companies (including Rounder Records)
for stateside distribution. They hope to have another album out
shortly, but for now, they're ready to slam Boston again with a
show lasting up to 2 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston area has always meant a lot to us,'' says Moran.
``Our first-ever show in the States was just outside Boston _ in
Easton _ in 1991. That's something that you don't forget.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staying Righteous: The Righteous Brothers are among the all-time
stars of pop radio. Their hit ``You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin' ''
was recently named the No. 1 most-played radio song ever, totaling
more than 8 million plays and besting anything by the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   The 1965 hit was written by Barry Mann and Cynthia Weill _ and
produced by the legendary Phil Spector. ``It was a two-day
situation to record it,'' Medley, now 59, says in a phone
interview. ``Phil was very, very particular, which was cool,
because the song kept getting better. Phil was an amazing producer.
He knew what he was going after and he didn't stop until the final
result. In later years, he might have gotten more `out there,' but
he was fine with us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovin' Feelin' '' became a hit again in 1986 in the ``Top
Gun'' soundtrack. Another Righteous Brothers hit, ``Unchained
Melody,'' had a similar revival in the film ``Ghost'' in 1990. And
in 1987 Medley and Jennifer Warnes had a hit, ``(I've Had) the Time
of My Life'' in the film ``Dirty Dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Medley has had to face tragedy as well, namely the shocking
murder 24 years ago of his ex-wife, Karen, who was raped and killed
by an intruder who has never been found, though detectives may
finally have a break in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had lost the DNA or misplaced it for 20 years, but they
found it and are now testing three or four guys,'' says Medley,
adding that it takes a few months to get the results.
</P>
<P>
   Medley, who lived in Newport Beach, Calif., then and now,
dropped out of the Righteous Brothers at the time to take care of
their son (``It didn't feel like a sacrifice _ it needed to be
done''). The group eventually reunited in 1982 and has been touring
ever since, playing up to 60 shows a year nationally, in addition
to two months annually in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're 80 years old and people still want to see us, we'll
keep singing,'' he says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phish on film: The new Phish documentary, ``Bittersweet Motel''
(and there's also a Web site by that name), is said to resemble the
Bob Dylan documentary, ``Don't Look Back,'' the new film concert
footage and backstage interviews and hijinks with band members. It
was directed by Todd Phillips, who also did ``Road Trip,'' ``Frat
House,'' and ``Hated'' (a documentary on New Hampshire punk rocker
G. G. Allin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
