<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GODZILLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST `GODZILLA' IS HOT ON FIRE-BREATHING FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GODZILLA 2000 
Directed by: Takao Okawara 
Screenplay by: Wataru Mimura, Hiroshi Kashiwabara 
Starring: Takehiro Murata, Shrio Sano, Hiroshi Abe, Naomi Nishida,
Mayu Suzuki, Tsutomu Kitagawa 
Running time: 97 minutes 
Rated: PG (monster violence and mild language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can take the boy out of Tokyo, but you can't take Tokyo out
of the boy. Which is why ``Godzilla 2000'' is miles better than
Hollywood's overblown, computerized 1998 ``Godzilla.'' You can all
but feel the new film sink back with relief into the old familiar
cheesiness, or at least a slick replica of it, complete with badly
dubbed dialogue, the all-important guy-in-the-rubber-suit look and
stomp-out-a-scale-model-of-Tokyo finale. It's got all the
pseudo-destructiveness you could hope for, and it still makes
contact with the impulses that drove the original, namely its
ability to provide a power fantasy to people feeling pretty
powerless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla,'' especially if you know the darker original without
the Raymond Burr footage spliced in, gave form and shape to the
powerlessness Japanese felt not only before US nuclear power, but
before nature itself. Godzilla, the mutant monster, became an
allegorical force of nature, beating back invading monsters, even
if it meant he caused a lot of damage in the process, before
walking back into the bay until next time. ``Godzilla'' was ``King
Kong'' with bad karma. ``Godzilla 2000'' is ``King Kong'' with bad
breath. Incendiary breath, too. It not only appeals to our inner
Godzilla. It appeals to our inner cheeseball.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a lot of tongue-in-cheek humor tied to the fact that
Godzilla now is viewed as a protector, even if he breaks the place
up protecting it. In a film at least as geared to young audiences
as to adults, his tail gives new meaning to the word backlash, his
voice (created by running a resin-saturated leather glove over a
stringed bass) tells all of Japan that he feels its pain. His fiery
dragon breath sometimes causes the pain, but who can knock it? It's
his secret weapon against his new adversary, Orga, from outer
space, dormant for many years in a flying saucer at the bottom of
Tokyo Bay until science, stirring up trouble as usual, raises it.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the film has a nice shot of a fishing boat coming into
view at a lighthouse keeper's eye level. Then the camera pulls back
and we see that the ship is being held between the teeth of
Godzilla, who promptly chomps down on it, splintering it. The
pro-Godzilla humans are a three-person Godzilla Prediction Network,
headed by Takehiro Murata, who's aided by his adolescent daughter
(Mayu Suzuki) and an intrepid reporter (Naomi Nishida). Predicting
Godzilla's return is not an arcane science. Things just start
shaking, a la ``Jurassic Park.'' The GPN philosophy is simple _
stay out of the big lizard's way.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's more reassuring than scary. Just as Dracula has been
transformed from frightening bloodsucker into breakfast-cereal-box
icon, Godzilla has been transformed in the collective psyche into a
sort of scaly Mary Poppins. The old Godzilla movies were recycled
on sci-fi channels. This new one seems headed for Nickelodeon, even
though Hiroshi Abe's security chief wants to kill Godzilla. This is
not a winning position, but his insane square-off with Godzilla
adds to the fun. Praise is in order, too, for Tsutomu Kitagawa, the
man in the latex suit, who must have spent more time battling
claustrophobia than evil old Orga.
</P>
<P>
   When the Godzilla films began, their primitive execution meant
that much of the humor was unintentionally campy. Although they've
become more sophisticated, they're careful to simulate the
rudimentary skill levels of the early days. The badly lip-synched
lines all but have little comic-strip balloons wrapped around them,
and it was shrewd to have Godzilla's foe look bigger and meaner.
When Orga puts his foot down, everybody within a 20-mile radius
knows it. So Godzilla's the underdog. But he never was a quitter.
One droll sequence involves Godzilla disappearing under a pile of
rubble after Orga drops an office tower on him, only to appear
moments later, still full of fight, having been no more than
briefly stunned. ``Godzilla 2000'' is a ton of fun, and then some.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
