<HEADER>
A5664 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKSSHOOKKANSAS-KAN &LR;      08-18 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT STORIES CAN SHAKE THE WORLD: SYLVIA BROWNRIGG'S NOVEL IDEAS
REACH AMERICAN SHORES 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- BOOKS SHOOK KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   Ten Women Who Shook the World, by
Sylvia Brownrigg (126 pages; Farrar, Straus and Giroux; $18)
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is shaping up to be the summer of the strange short story.
</P>
<P>
   George Saunders weighed in with his second collection of
touching but sharply satirical tales, Pastoralia. Amy Bloom offered
characters and love stories that were both disturbing and endearing
in A Blind Man Can See How Much I Love You. Now Sylvia Brownrigg
joins in with Ten Women Who Shook the World.
</P>
<P>
   Actually this collection was first published in 1997 in England,
two years before Brownrigg's novel The Metaphysical Touch. The
mostly positive reviews of that novel's mix of the philosophical
and erotic led Farrar, Straus and Giroux to bring Brownrigg's short
stories to an American audience.
</P>
<P>
   American readers should be thankful we finally have the chance.
Brownrigg's stories provide a surreal but poignant view of the
nature of femaleness and the roles women play _ or are not allowed
to play _ in our society.
</P>
<P>
   Men who still think that only men should construct, for example,
would do well to read the opening story, ``Amazon,'' in which a
mythical and apparently immortal builder and her assistant create
and erect the Pyramids, the Great Wall of China, the Taj Mahal and
the Golden Gate Bridge. Finally the assistant decides to strike out
on her own _ not to build things but to rebuild the beauty of the
rain forest:
</P>
<P>
   ``She speaks of the rubber plants that will no longer be bled to
make superballs, she chats about the wood that will never again
become A-frames. She talks of tearing down factories. She revels in
getting rid of the office sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a marvelously entertaining tale but also a lesson on the
human need to make _ and to unmake what has been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hussy From the West'' challenges patriarchal definitions of
promiscuity but also explores the very essence of what it means to
be sensual, suggesting that sexuality is only one component of a
state of mind that also includes one's relationship with everything
on earth, with all entities animate and inanimate. ``If I am
promiscuous,'' the narrator says, ``then so is that bed I slept in
where nothing happened but the hope of love; and so is that train
compartment where our eyes met; and so is my favorite novel that
has dozed beside me over the years in times of trouble or confusion
when I've needed its solace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistress of the Moons'' counterbalances the preoccupations of
``man's'' machine-driven explorations of the moon with a feminine
spirit's eros-inflected love of the universe itself. Call it mood
music of the spheres; it's an eccentric tune, but it's beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Brownrigg was born in California, majored in philosophy at Yale
and now lives in London. The Metaphysical Touch was criticized by
some for being overburdened with philosophical musings, but these
stories certainly don't suffer that fault. They are thoughtful,
yes, but never bog down into mere intellectual noodling, thanks to
Brownrigg's light touch and bright writing.
</P>
<P>
   What Brownrigg has created here, in fact, is a compact
collection of fables, oddly appealing little sketches that are not
really about characters but rather about how women think of
themselves and are thought of.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
