<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GEORGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SWITCH, GEORGE LOSES HIS SAFETY NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ By the end of last season, fans wanted to
see more of rookie safety Tony George. Now it appears they will be
seeing less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived my life by trying to make the best of a bad
situation and continue to move forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's overcome diabetes in becoming a professional athlete. That
meant defying the odds at every level of organized sports,
overcoming times when his blood sugar isn't regular, and overcoming
having to take insulin injections at certain times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last season, George was finally starting when
Chris Carter was injured. But Bill Belichick and his staff came in
and moved him to strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   There are many parts of the switch that bother George. First, he
has always been a free safety and now he's backing up Lawyer
Milloy, who may be the NFL's best. Third, George's not involved in
any of the sub packages on third down. He'll have to make it as a
special teams player, hardly what the third-round pick out of the
University of Florida had envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you think you're going to play one position it's
frustrating, but the mark of a true player is to bounce back and
play that position well,'' George said. ``I'm still trying to find
my role and do the best I can every time I get a chance. I want
everybody to see I can play ball and make plays wherever I go.''
</P>
<P>
   George has been watched throughout camp. He captured much
attention when he failed his running test on a hot, sultry day in
Smithfield, R.I., when he could not complete the remaining lap.
George became disoriented, his vision blurred, and he nearly lapsed
into a diabetic coma, an incredibly scary state for people of any
age.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, there didn't appear to be an understanding of his
illness by the new staff. It wasn't until a day later that he was
able to explain what being a diabetic trying to play sports was all
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a bit of a problem at first,'' said George.
``With a new coaching staff, you don't have time to sit down and
explain what's going on with you as a person. Diabetes is a part of
me. After the speeches Bill gave and everything, he was basically
going with a no-excuse-for-anything policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never used diabetes as an excuse and I know that first
impressions are everything. When you're not making your times on a
running test, it looks like you're out of shape. It's hard at
first. After you explain the situation, it gives you a line on what
you're up against. I'm not using it as an excuse, but at least you
can say that's the situation and now let's go on from here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of understanding. There's no excuse not to
understand what's wrong with a player. It's part of any program and
organization. The first thing I would want them to know is my
situation with my diabetes, and even if they don't know, I don't
mind sitting down and explaining it to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With things being in such a fragmented situation with training
camp, I've finally had time to sit with the coaches and explain it.
I think they were understanding afterward. To be out there running
and you can't take another step, the coaches are thinking you're
completely out of shape. If you understand diabetes, you can say
he's giving it his all _ and he's still coming out on the short
end.''
</P>
<P>
   George thinks it's important for each coach and organization to
understand each player and ``see what their personal issues are,
whether they're mental issues, emotional issues, or family
problems. Not knowing just makes the situation worst,'' said
George.
</P>
<P>
   Though he believes deep in his heart that free safety is where
he performs best, he knows he must adapt to strong safety. Even
though he's one injury away from taking over for Milloy, it is
George who will miss Sunday's game against Tampa Bay with a toe
injury. The injury forced the team to re-sign Reggie Rideau, who
was released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always try to be out there every down and play every
down,'' said George. ``It's a little disappointing (to switch
positions), but you know what you're working for. To make this team
a success, you have to find your niche in this defense. If I have
to be the best special teams player I can be, that's what I'll do.
But if I get a role on the defense, I want to go out there and make
some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Backing up Milloy is daunting, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm not going to beat out Lawyer,'' said George.
``There's nothing I can do except when I get my opportunity to make
plays. I feel I'm doing a pretty good job. There's always something
you have to do a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   And Belichick often lets him know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's a guy who's always going to find something wrong in
whatever you do,'' he said. ``He wants to make you better and a
complete player. I'm not trying to go out and do this and that, I'm
just doing what they ask me to do and do it to their satisfaction
and to my own satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   George said there was no room for discussion when Belichick
decoded to switch him in veteran minicamp in June. George said he
just did it and didn't ask why.
</P>
<P>
   Thew switch could be seen as a step back, for he could have been
competing with Tebucky Jones and Chris Carter at free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know (if it's a step back),'' said George. ``You can
always comment on that, but it's one of those situations you just
have to go with and see where it leads. You have to do what the
coach expects you do to make it better. I made my mark on special
teams in college and hopefully I can make my mark in the pros as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there are no signs George will even get on the field
in nickel and dime situations. Veteran Larry Whigham is also a
strong safety and, with his latest injury, George might not make
the 53-man roster, which would be quite a letdown for a kid who
impressed everyone with his ability to hit in the open field a year
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
