<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5681 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN19     08-18 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Los Angeles conventioneers try to keep the eternal flame lit
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Democratic convention now behind us, the campaign
shifts its focus from the the feel-good rhetoric _ that marked both
this and the Republican convention _ to the more serious job of
defining the differences between Al Gore and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   May God help us all.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats in Los Angeles weren't as choreographed as the
Republicans in Philadelphia, but they did their best to put on a
good show for the TV cameras:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the last surviving member of
John F. Kennedy's immediate family, exhibited the quiet dignity and
grace that was so much like her mother. Looking as though she
wanted to be somewhere else during her speech, she nevertheless
showed she was still the brave little girl a nation watched grow
up.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  While Caroline's speech was sentimental, Uncle Teddy Kennedy's
speech was a disappointment. Sen. Kennedy, looking as if he, too,
wanted to be somewhere else, stumbled through his remarks and did
little to rally the crowd. His bad back has obviously taken its
toll. The best thing about Kennedy's appearance: His mane of silver
hair.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Speaking of hair, Ann Richards, sporting a
less-than-big-hair-do, didn't get near the podium but instead held
court on CNN with Larry King. At 68, Richards looked as if she had
regained some of that zeal she lost during the 1994 Texas
governor's race when Bush trounced her. Appearing with Richards was
GOP stalwart Jack Kemp. It was entertaining to watch these old
political lions trade swipes. They should take their show on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No doubt one of Gore's primary considerations in choosing a
running mate was that he had to make himself look dynamic in
comparison. He succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joe Lieberman's drowsy monotone acceptance speech made us
want to sit up and yawn. According to political pundits, though,
Lieberman's address to the convention was his best effort yet. It
should really be a barn burner when Dick Cheney and Lieberman
square off in a debate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Touted as Gore's ``most important speech ever,'' the
Democratic presidential nominee has set his course and attempted to
steer away from Bill Clinton. Possibly the most asked question of
anyone associated with Gore is can he distance himself from the man
he's been in the shadow of for eight years? Gore's biggest obstacle
is still sitting in the White House and how Clinton behaves himself
over the next 11 weeks will play a big part in who will be at the
inaugural ball in January, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin (Texas) Daily
News. E-mail: emurray(AT)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
