<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ISLAND-DESALINATE-ART     08-18 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAND-DESALINATE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A FRESH (WATER) START IN MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACMAHAN ISLAND, Maine _ News of the alchemy started to spread
among Maine's islanders a month ago when it began: The residents of
MacMahan Island opened a valve, flipped a switch and began drinking
the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Curious visitors have come over in boats and tromped up to the
island's highest point, where 800 pounds of hissing pressure forces
the water through membrane after membrane into a tower of trembling
clear water. Almost every one of them asks for a cup, and peers
down into it, and then takes a careful drink. Superintendant Peter
Schuerch has explained a dozen times that the islanders have
replaced their precious, hoarded fresh water with desalted seawater
_ the first community in New England to do so, experts say. He
knows he will explain it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame them, when you see where it comes from,''
Schuerch said, with a nod toward the briny-smelling harbor. ``I
mean, we just drove across it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of water-rich New England, bounded by an ocean
landscape, Maine's islanders have spent 300 years worrying about
having enough drinking water. Many of Maine's islands have no
groundwater at all, only rain and melted snow that gets caught in
the fissures between rocks, and between the plants and the people,
that goes quickly. Come the end of August, Schuerch has found
himself climbing the ladder to peer down into the cistern three or
four times a day, the way a parent might check that a sleeping
child is still breathing.
</P>
<P>
   But the perfect, obvious solution to the classic
island-dweller's problem _ to transform sea water into fresh water
_ has been shrugged off as a mirage for 3,000 years. Since the time
of Aristotle, who proposed condensing the vapor of sea water around
300 B.C., engineers and inventors have seized upon the elusive goal
of efficient desalination.
</P>
<P>
   Progress in the quest has come hand-in-hand with mounting
desperation. In the United States, new dams meet with resistance on
environmental and safety grounds. More serious pressure has come
from the Persian Gulf and the Middle East, where the prospect of
running out of water completely has made control of aquifers
politically explosive. Great fortunes have been enlisted in the
development of cheaper technology, bringing the cost down by a
factor of 10 in the last 20 years, according to Ionics, a
Watertown-based desalination giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of desalination has been slowly dropping and the cost
of fresh water has been rising. In some parts of the world, these
two lines crossed years ago, and in others they haven't crossed
yet,'' said Jim Birkett, an international desalination expert who
lives in the coastal community of Nobleboro, Maine. ``They seem to
have crossed on MacMahan Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the end of water anxiety will change life on this
mile-long island, where the candy store still operates on the honor
system and any change at all is viewed with some suspicion. Every
year, as August turned into September, Schuerch's already estimable
powers over the island's 150 summer residents _ ``I have to be the
arbitrator, I have to be the harbormaster, I have to be
omnipotent,'' he said _ became tyrannical with regard to water, to
the point, once, of cutting off the supply in the middle of a
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time when the burden on island wells is highest. If
the level of fresh water falls too low, the well can ``salt out,''
drawing up salt water from below the fresh water and contaminating
the well's supply, perhaps permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to take a chance, because once you've lost it,
you don't get it back,'' Schuerch said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The islanders' ritual husbanding worked until last year, when
the Maine Department of Environmental Protection ruled that they
could no longer flush their toilets with salt water and release the
sewage in the ocean. That sent island authorities scrambling for
additional fresh water: Collecting rainwater through roof
catchments was out, because MacMahan is too thickly wooded. Adding
to the island's two existing wells _ cut 300 and 400 feet straight
into bedrock _ would have been prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   So Schuerch returned to the idea of desalination, which had been
dismissed again and again, over the years, not only on MacMahan
Island but all through this archipelago. On Vinalhaven, Lessard
said, the running joke was that ``only Kuwait can afford
desalination.'' But his research turned up costs far lower than
expected. Islanders split the cost of installing a $50,000
``reverse osmosis'' unit, a model popular on Caribbean islands and
cruise ships manufactured by the Florida-based Matrix Desalination,
Inc. The yearly electrical cost is $200, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but surely, authorities on coastal and island communities
are beginning to take notice, and some predict that desalination
could ease one of the chronic scarcities of life along the Maine
coast. A small number of communities in the Northeast have shown a
similar interest _ Cape May, N.J., installed a reverse osmosis unit
like MacMahan's last year, after local wells were contaminated by
seawater; engineers for the city of Brockton have spent years
lobbying to desalt water along the Taunton River.
</P>
<P>
   MacMahan is the first community in Maine to depend on seawater
for its water supply _ but, say observers, it is not likely to be
the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these things run, and run well, it's just going to change
the whole picture for development on islands, where most people
thought the limiting factor was the water supply,'' said Barry
Timson, a Hallowell geologist who has studied water supply on
Monhegan Island. ``Here's this theoretical supply, and it's less
than the present demand, so theroetically, there's room for more
development.''
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the problem. For the people who choose to live
on these rocky islands, the new fear of population growth could be
more threatening than the old fear of running out of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful what you wish for, because you just
might get it,'' said Susan Lessard, of Vinalhaven. ``In terms of
our island, it can't be a Nantucket, because it's not a sand
aquifer. It wouldn't have enough water to support that many
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerch worries about change himself, as he carries out the
duties of utilities commissioner, town planner and sole officer of
the law. Put many more than 150 people on this island, and you'd be
adding a new social phenomenon: the stranger. He'd rather that not
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot about that,'' Schuerch said. ``I think we're
good for this generation and one more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
