<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THIS RATE, GOMEZ IPO IS UP IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How does this rate?
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors Inc. made a name for itself on the Internet by
rating all kinds of services on the Web, first analyzing basic
financial offerings from banks and brokerages and later expanding
to a total of 37 consumer categories (perhaps you're interested in
the relative merits of cholesterol information on 11 competing
medical sites).
</P>
<P>
   Gomez doesn't hand out any ``incomplete'' ratings, but it might
have to do just that with its own initial public stock offering.
The IPO plan, first filed in late April, never made it to the
market but hasn't been scratched either.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of the Gomez deal getting off the ground in the spring
were stiff to begin with, faced from the start with a stock market
that had suddenly sobered up on Internet stocks. New deals were
dying left and right.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Gomez, the former Forrester Research Inc. analyst who runs
the Lincoln, Mass. company, declines to say much about what happens
next. He cites the company's still active, though now aged, IPO
registration statement, which legally limits his public comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to execute on our business plan to my
satisfaction,'' Gomez said. ``It's my responsibility as CEO to
access the market when it's right for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no stroke of genius to guess Gomez is hoping the right time
turns out to be this fall.
</P>
<P>
   He would be standing in a long line of chief executives at
Internet-oriented companies who pulled IPO plans earlier this year
and are now looking for a second chance in the typically active
fall underwriting season. Some companies, like Zefer Corp. of
Boston, scrubbed their original plan and have recently refiled
registration documents for a second try.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side: Many of those companies may be running out of
chances to go public if they don't make it in the fall. Losses
burning through cash, venture investors anxious for an IPO or some
other ``liquidity event,'' and just plain lack of momentum threaten
to sap their organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully for Gomez, money would not seem to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Months before the company filed IPO plans, it raised $30 million
from a group of venture investors that include Softbank, BancBoston
Ventures, HarbourVest Partners, and the John Hancock Global
Technology Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly available financial information on Gomez is ancient
by now. But what exists suggests $30 million would go a long way.
</P>
<P>
   The company lost $13.5 million in the last nine months of 1999,
but about half were paper losses connected to stock transactions.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, Gomez could stay afloat quite comfortably for a
long time. Following through on the big plans of springtime is
another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez was hoping to raise a lot of money with its original IPO
plan, perhaps as much as $60 million. But, despite all of the
visibility Gomez created for itself, the company generated only
$3.2 million in revenues over the last three quarters of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The days of raising $60 million for a company with $3 million of
revenues are over, unless it's working the telecommunications
business. Gomez is probably doing more business today, but IPO
expectations may be revised too.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, like other companies with postponed IPOs, also has to
face the opportunity cost of not raising tens of millions of
dollars when it had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gomez was first and remains the best-known Internet
rating service, it's hardly alone. Competition that could have been
faced more aggressively with IPO millions is broader and stronger
today, ranging from magazines ranking online stockbrokers to
full-service Internet consulting companies like Forrester and Giga
Information Group Inc. that offer their own products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are clearly the pioneer in this area and the leader in
terms of providing rankings,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Some competitors, like Steve Telleen at Giga, suspect Gomez has
focused less on ranking services for consumers in recent months and
has put more energy into targeting corporate consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the year, Gomez was earning about half of its
money from its consumer site and the other half from gomezpro.com,
aimed at e-commerce corporate clients. Gomez insists both legs of
his business remain important in similar proportion today.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez is firm about one other point, no matter what happens in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
