<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-STOCKS-ART-BO     08-18 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-STOCKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BIOTECH SHARES PROFITING FROM A HOT MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genome Therapeutics Corp., a Waltham, Mass. biotechnology
company seeking capital, recently decided to take advantage of a
sweet spot in the market by offering extra shares to investors.
</P>
<P>
   It hoped to shake loose $46 million, seemingly ambitious for a
company that had reported losses for three years running. But by
the time investors were done snatching up the extra shares last
month, the company had exceeded its target and more than doubled
its cash reserves.
</P>
<P>
   And Genome Therapeutics is not alone. After a brutal spring
sell-off in the high-tech sector, biotech shares have staged a
dramatic recovery, outpacing both the Nasdaq index and most
e-commerce companies. The boom has sent biotech companies rushing
to the market with intial public offerings. Others like Genome
Therapeutics have made secondary stock offerings, raising millions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say investors are finally seeing the potential in a
sector long viewed warily, as a rising number of biotech products
reach the public and hundreds more enter the late stages of human
testing.
</P>
<P>
   The shift to profitability in some biotech companies, combined
with excitement generated by the June announcement that the human
genome had been decoded, has also fueled the new wave of investor
interest.
</P>
<P>
   People disillusioned by the lackluster performance of e-commerce
stocks in recent months have turned to biotech companies in search
of the next high-growth area. Institutional investors have pumped
money into the sector. Even day traders have jumped aboard.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, 48 biotech companies have gone public
nationally and another 32 have made secondary stock offerings,
raising a record $12.2 billion, according to research by Richard
Peterson, an IPO expert at Thomson Financial Securities Data in
Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 48 IPOs, 16 have taken place already in August. Another
17 biotech companies are currently registered to make initial
public offerings at some time in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a different kind of market, these companies would have had
to raise money privately and wait for a window,'' said Gus Lawlor,
a partner at Health Care Ventures, a Cambridge, Mass. venture
capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   The biotech industry was the focus of speculative buying and
wild runups in stock valuations in the early 1990s. But a string of
disappointing drug trials and dwindling prospects for short-term
profits brought the boom to an end. Burned investors avoided the
sector for years.
</P>
<P>
   But by last year, many new biotech products had reached the
market, including treatments for rheumatoid arthritis,
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, and breast cancer. They'd also diversified
their business lines, reducing risk. Investors slowly started
moving back into the sector.
</P>
<P>
   And what began as a steady growth in investor interest has now
turned into a full-scale rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, the outlook is extremely good right now,'' said David
Carlson, comanager of the Putnam Health Sciences Trust. ``But
biotech companies have seen years when they couldn't raise capital.
They are taking the opportunity while it's there, because there's
always the potential that they'll go into a period like that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Genome Therapeutics, which markets genetic data to drug makers,
registered to sell 3 million additional shares in mid-March. A week
earlier, its share price had reached a peak of $75, after trading
at only $3 a year ago. The company shelved its offering in April
when the Nasdaq index plunged and its share price dropped below
$14.
</P>
<P>
   When the biotech sector recovered in late June, Genome sold 1.5
million shares at an average price of $31.01 and raised $46.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The cash infusion will allow the company to advance its
genome-based drug research and pursue new avenues to profitability,
said Richard D. Gill, its president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (capital) gives us a level of security and a level of
confidence to really build the company,'' Gill said.
</P>
<P>
   Variagenics Inc., a Cambridge company that studies how genetic
variations control drug responses, made its decision to go public
in part because the market was strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at a stage where it made sense to go public,'' said
Rick Shea, the company's chief financial officer. ``But if you look
at the biotech cycle over the last 20 years, there have been long
periods of time when financing wasn't available. Certainly, we
wanted to seize the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The company sold 5 million shares in early July, raising $70
million. The money will help cover the company's current ``burn
rate'' of $1 million a month and give it the flexibility to invest
in new technologies, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Variagenics' shares jumped nearly 100 percent within days of the
offering. It has given back some of that value in the past month
but is still up 80 percent from its offering price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is everything,'' said Dennis Shaughnessy, senior vice
president of Charles River Laboratories Holdings Inc., a
Wilmington, Mass. firm that has supplied mice, rats and research
tools to labs for more than 50 years and went public in June.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, when the company spun itself out from Bausch &AMP;
Lomb Inc., it expected to wait two or three years before going
public. But it raised $224 million with its public offering to pay
down debt from the buyout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business was doing very well, and the market was
receptive,'' Shaughnessy said. ``Drug discovery is accelerating
rapidly, and people are beginning to recognize the value of a tools
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bruker Daltonics Inc., a Billerica, Mass.
life sciences company, raised nearly $104 million in a public
offering. Gennaissance Pharmaceuticals Inc., a genome-based drug
company in New Haven, Conn., raised $78 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The Medicines Company, a Cambridge, Mass.
biopharmaceutical company, raised $96 million. And this week,
another Cambridge biopharmaceutical company, Dyax Corp., raised $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   Although investors in biotech companies expect the sector to
continue its strong performance for the balance of the year and
beyond, they warned that it is still a risky area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong not to expect any ups and downs,'' said
Lawlor of Health Care Ventures. ``There's a lot of uncertainty
associated with drug discovery, and there are always going to be
some disappointments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
