<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5717 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DR.DREW-LADN &LR;      08-18 1888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DR.DREW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD DOCTOR
</HEADLINE>
  Drew Pinsky does his (hectic) part to make things right 
(For use after Mon., Aug, 21, 2000 by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most frequently paraphrased portion of the Hippocratic oath
is a three-word phrase that runs like a broken record through the
multifaceted career of Dr. Drew Pinsky: ``Do no harm.'' Pinsky
follows it; so do the people who work for him.
</P>
<P>
   Counseling drug addicts at a chemical dependency unit _ do no
harm. Talking to lonely teens on the radio during the wee hours _
do no harm. Starting a Web site, distributing condoms to promote
responsible sexual behavior, interviewing celebrities, serving as a
medical commentator for the voyeuristic CBS TV show ``Big Brother''
_ do no harm.
</P>
<P>
   Pinsky, in fact, describes his approach to ``Big Brother'' in
much the same way as he would characterize any new venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It's) another opportunity to make something useful,'' says
Pinsky. ``It's kind of like walking onto a battlefield: `Well, OK,
I'll just dig in and try to help wherever I can.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound maudlin. When the day is done, I hope
what I do really is useful. I hope it's not misinterpreted. I hope
it does no harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't it follow that the physician who does no harm is also
expected to do some good?
</P>
<P>
   The people who have followed Dr. Pinsky's career say the answer
is an overwhelming ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When people meet him, they immediately comment on how genuine
and real the guy is,'' says Curtis Giesen, who is CEO of Pinsky's
interactive Web site, www.drDrew.com, and who has been a close
friend of Pinsky since junior high school. ``The mantra here is `do
good.' Drew has us all saying that. We don't do anything that veers
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   ---With that philosophy in mind, ``Big Brother'' could have been
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   A show that puts 10 people in close quarters to be watched
constantly by cameras, he says, could potentially cause damage to
the participants. Pinsky, who was initially approached to host the
program, said he struggled with the ethics for a long time before
signing on as a weekly behavior commentator.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't met the housemates, all of whom are monitored by a
team of psychologists. Pinsky's role is simply to comment on what
he _ and the rest of the world _ observes six nights a week on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Does Pinsky, who advises ``Loveline'' listeners based on
information gleaned in a 30-second radio call, feel like he knows
Cassandra, Jamie, George and the gang?
</P>
<P>
   It's a loaded question, says Pinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job of looking at what they're doing is based on inaccurate
information,'' he says. ``They are not asking me to be their
doctor. They are not expressing in any detail what their feelings
are or what their internal dynamics are based on. All we have is
the behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of little theories. But there are so many sources
of artifice _ the money, the constant cameras, the way they are
thrown together _ that it's treacherous to make assumptions about
the behavior you're seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   He credits the producers of ``Big Brother'' with their direction
to keep his insights focused on behavior. Better TV, he
acknowledges, would be for Pinsky to unleash potentially
embarrassing personal insights about the contestants.
</P>
<P>
   But to do so would not be Pinsky. And, thankfully he says, it's
not his directive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The producers and I agree: don't hurt them,'' Pinsky says. ``I
don't think anybody has been harmed by the experience so far. Maybe
some of the people have grown a little bit and learned
something.'' &QL; 
---Just in case anybody is keeping count, his ``Big Brother''
engagement is probably Extracurricular Activity No. 75 for Pinsky.
If it often seems like the man is everywhere, that's because he is:
from home, where he cooks his children breakfast and takes them to
school, to a private practice office in Pasadena, to the chemical
dependency unit he runs at Las Encinas Hospital, to the offices of
his Web site, which was launched in October. Afternoons are often
left open for media-related meetings or interviews. Then it's back
to the hospital. Most days he tries to be home by 5 p.m. for time
with his family. The nights are for ``Loveline.''
</P>
<P>
   Sleep, says Pinsky _ only half jokingly _ is an inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   So is illness. And on a recent Thursday morning, it's the doctor
who is not well.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular Thursday morning, Pinsky's day is typically
packed. His schedule includes seeing patients at his office, rounds
at Las Encinas and a round with Conway and Steckler on KLSX-FM
(97.1). The previous evening he and ``Big Brother'' host Julie Chen
rehashed the banishment of former stripper Jordan from the ``Big
Brother'' house. Pinsky's take: Jordan created the type of tension
that the house's inhabitants _ and the voting television audience _
seemed anxious to get rid of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are watching are making it a healthier
environment,'' says Pinsky. ``They're kicking the negative
influences out of the house which, I gather, didn't happen in
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Big Brother'' lab rats may be getting healthier. But
today, Pinsky says, he feels awful.
</P>
<P>
   Battling a lingering case of bronchitis, Pinsky tells everyone
he encounters how lousy he's feeling _ more by way of apologizing
for not being at the top of his game than by complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Pinsky was sick or well, the casual observer wouldn't
notice anything amiss. Neither would a listener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him walk in, and he's exhausted,'' says Ann Ingold,
producer of ``Loveline.'' ``His pager is going off; the hospital is
calling. But the minute he's on the air, he's 100 percent focused.
To be able to pull that off night after night _ he's an amazing
man.''
</P>
<P>
   On Conway and Steckler, Pinsky counsels, banters, reassures and
holds forth. People are calling in to ask questions of the
celebrated guest: ``When should you worry about a friend's
addiction?'' ``Does this morning-after pill really work?'' ``What
about my boyfriend?''
</P>
<P>
   Pinsky checks his pager during station breaks. Meetings are
scheduled, canceled and rescheduled, forcing him to cut out early
and have the drDrew.com agenda shuffled.
</P>
<P>
   The Ping-Ponging doesn't phase Pinsky, although he could
certainly do without the illness. There was a once a time when
Pinsky had fewer commitments yet worked !ital!more hours than he
does now. Weekend work and 16-hour days were common.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've structured my life in terms of back-ups,'' says Pinsky.
``When I was practicing full time, I used to insist on being `the
guy.' Now I have structure along with staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The one event that can't be rescheduled is the one Pinsky badly
wants to attend: the final little league game of the season for his
7-year-old triplets.
</P>
<P>
   And attend he does, although he practically falls asleep in the
bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife knows I love my work. Her concern is just that I don't
get so caught up that I'm not paying attention, to create more
structure in my day, so I have adequate time with her and the
kids,'' Pinsky says. ``As much time as I can possibly give them,
I'll give them. That's got to be Priority No. 1. If I screw that
up, there is no excuse.'' &QL; 
---Seventeen years ago, Drew Pinsky, a medical student at USC _
after getting his undergraduate degree at Amherst _ simply thought
he was performing community service. At the urging of friends, he
got on the radio at a fledgling Pasadena radio station, KROQ, and
started fielding questions from primarily teen-age callers. The
subject: usually sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it was, the middle of the night on a Sunday, and I had an
epiphany,'' recalls Pinsky. ``I was 24 years old, the kids were 17
and I put it in a historical context. In the early '80s,
adolescents weren't having sex as far as the world was concerned. I
thought, `Boy, somebody should just sit down and answer their
questions. This body of information is not that complicated.
Somebody should just tell them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, working unpaid, radio's Dr. Drew did just that.
Eventually, Pinsky started getting $25 per show. When Pinsky and
his wife, Susan, were starting their family, he negotiated a
contract. If he was going to be spending these kinds of hours away
from home, it could no longer be on a volunteer basis. Already an
internist _ with an M.D. from USC School of Medicine _ he became a
specialist in addiction as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still resisted the idea that I was on radio,'' says Pinsky,
who used the Dr. Drew title as a way of partially shielding his
identity. ``I wasn't one to step out of line. There was all this
sort of unpleasant pressure from my peers and superiors over the
years not to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then suddenly it went from `Don't do it' to `Oh, my God, this
is a great thing. How about if I do it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Agreed Dr. Joseph Haraszti, medical director of Las Encinas:
``There was a lot of controversy when he was first going on TV, and
people didn't want him to do it. I gave him a strong endorsement.
It's a tremendous community service, a responsible and sober
approach to sex education and relationship education to teens. Kids
listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, whether Pinsky is taking questions at university campuses
or in cyberspace at drDrew.com, he is still the wise straight man _
the guy with all the answers who takes a few shots simply because
he is sometimes less hip or funny than whoever happens to be
sharing the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, that's ``Loveline's'' sardonic co-host, Adam
Carolla, who admits, ``His lack of a sense of humor mixed with his
low self-esteem makes him easy prey. If everyone was like Drew, we
would all be living in a very boring utopia.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Carolla means that as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew is Drew is Drew, through and through. What you see is
what you get with him.'' &QL; 
---Pinsky would like to turn the microphone around. Politically
neutral though he claims to be, he wants to interview presidential
candidates George W. Bush and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have particularly strong feelings for either of those
guys,'' he says. ``I just want to see them address what's really
going on with the people who need help in this country. I'd like to
ask them the tough questions and see how they respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities, he says, have been very open during interviews for
drDrew.com and for the live show Pinsky conducts for the Web site
from a Pasadena studio. Part of it, he says, stems from a
willingness to talk about themselves openly and honestly. Part of
it is the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my training, because of the interviewing I do in
clinical practice, I can do the kind of interview that nobody else
in the media can do,'' Pinsky says. ``I can get to more
substantial, real material in two to three questions than anyone
else in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   He has answered more than an hour's worth of questions. Another
appointment beckons. Pinsky isn't asked to sum up his philosophy or
his career, but he does so anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And the self-reflection makes him sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there's no blueprint for what I do, it's risky all the
time, and acknowledging that, taking the risk, you get used to it,
but it's not me. It's a painful place to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really just want to do something worthwhile and interesting
along the way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
