<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5719 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-KARN-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      08-18 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARN-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ACCIDENTAL HANDYMAN
</HEADLINE>
  Richard Karn no professional, but he played one on TV 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: With sidebar, `Tools of the Trade') 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Karn is sitting in a Studio City coffee shop talking
about the house he recently bought in Big Bear _ and the summer
legacy he hopes the house will start for his 7-year-old son,
Cooper. And he's telling me the place is a 3/4-acre lot with a big
back yard.
</P>
<P>
   The place is ``perfectly fine,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And I do not, for one second, believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, this is not an easy person to doubt. Karn is, after
all, the man who spent eight years playing steady Al Borland on
``Home Improvement,'' the nice guy handyman's handyman, the guy who
would pull back and urge caution whenever Tim ``The Tool Man''
Taylor (a k a series star Tim Allen) would concoct some
hair-brained scheme to rip out another wall or amp up an already
lethal electric chainsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Karn is the guy whose friendly, bearded face has launched a
thousand real-life endorsements, from wares at Orchard Supply
Hardware to beard trimmers, rechargeable battery recycling and the
Internet Tool Box. The man once scored the second highest Q rating
_ which measures a performer's recognizability and likability
quotient _ of any actor on primetime TV (Allen was No. 1). My God,
if you can't trust Richard ``Al Borland'' Karn, whom can you trust?
</P>
<P>
   ``That character is him, in many ways,'' says Ralph Millard,
executive vice president of the Rechargeable Battery Recycling
Corporation, for which Karn is a spokesperson. ``He comes across as
very genuine in his speech and his actions, and he's got a certain
believability of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, when Richard Karn tells you his newly purchased house
is ``pretty much fine,'' you sense the man is itching _ if not to
pull out his own tool box _ then certainly to find the home's blue
prints, make a few well-placed calls and get busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My inner idea of a summer cabin is more like a log cabin,''
says Karn, 44. ``So now, I'm thinking like I did in my book when my
dad said, `Why replace the windows? They're perfectly fine.' I'm
figuring, `Why replace the house? It's perfectly fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's an Al Borland way of thinking. Richard Karn, on the
other hand, might have a different approach when it comes to
improving a homestead.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``House Broken: How I Remodeled My Home for Just
Under Three Times the Original Bid'' (Harper Collins; $23), trusty,
affable Richard Karn puts a seriocomic ``Money Pit''-like spin on
the full-scale overhaul he and his wife did to their Studio City
home in 1996. It's as close as one will get to a blurring of the
lines between Karn and his ``Al-ter'' ego: the actor who plays a
handyman remodeling his house _ with the help of professionals _
and then writing a book about the experience.
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle native, Karn's an actor first, lastut the experience.
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle native, Karn's an actor first, last and always. He
worked in professional theater before a couple of breaks landed him
the ``Home Improvement'' gig. But his tool-savvy signature role
isn't entirely fabricated. If Karn comes across as being more than
a little bit handy, you might say there's spackle in his DNA.
Karn's father, grandfather and great-grandfather were all
carpenters. He never gave family trade serious consideration.
(``That was something my dad did. I didn't seem to excel at it,''
he says.) And while tool proficiency wasn't a prerequisite for
landing the role of Al Borland, Karn admits that ``I know how to
play these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers apparently thought so as well. Focus group studies
would always reveal Al Borland as being the kind of guy you could
trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be getting these calls from all sorts of people. I
think there was a sense that Al knew what he was doing, and that he
was good at it,'' Karn says. ``The home improvement industry is
huge. If you've ever been to the hardware show in Chicago, it's
like there are so many millions of dollars going into that
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   When tackling his own house, Karn was anything but hands-off. He
didn't exactly hammer in nails or pour cement, but he and his wife,
Tudi Roche, knew exactly what they wanted. When the project grew
from simply redoing two rooms to performing nearly $300,000 worth
of remodeling, it was Karn _ still playing cautious Al as a day job
_ who OK'd the change orders and wrote the checks. Each experience,
he later discovered, became a chapter in his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd come back with stories,'' Karn says. ``Tim was going
through the same thing. (``Home Improvement'' co-star Patricia
Richardson) was going through the same thing as well. They were all
building their own homes or remodeling, especially after the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Tim is who he is, his stories are a lot funnier. Maybe
it's just the way he tells it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that could be Karn or Al Borland talking. Both are
unfailingly modest.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the author isn't giving himself enough credit.
``House Broken,'' co-written with George Mair, is both funny and
wise. In addition to the anecdotes _ a few of which make Karn look
a little bit foolish _ there's good advice to homeowners both on
home buying and remodeling: what the language means, the mistakes
you'll make and the ones you might avoid. The book is also laced
with anecdotes about historic building goofs (plumbing problems in
the Pentagon, why that tower in Pisa leans).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Karn's beautiful house came with a price. In the
course of their odyssey, the Karns did everything from stripping
their roof and replacing gas lines to rebuilding a wine rack and
replacing kitchen cabinet knob handles. After a year and a half of
work and 101 change orders, they ended up with a home that, one
suspects is better than ``perfectly fine.''
</P>
<P>
   And it all began with windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first domino, just going `dink,''' Karn says. ``You've
got 78 styles of windows, and you're going, `Well, I should just
change those out.' So once that fatal decision is made, while the
windows are out the contractor says, `Well, you're going to see the
patchwork.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So the stucco comes off and instead of putting the fake tile,
we can shoal up the walls, make it stronger, and use real tile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it just kept going. One thing leads to the next.
There would be a dark wall. Now all of a sudden the curtains don't
match the throw rug.''
</P>
<P>
   In person, Karn is slightly shorter than he appears on TV. His
beard, which he shaved for an upcoming episode of the American
Movie Classics' ``The Lot,'' is back and, no, he's not wearing the
Al Borland signature flannel shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Lot,'' the shorn Karn takes on a Fargo-esque accent to
play a representative from the Legion of Decency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really interesting thing hiring him,'' says show
executive producer Rick Mitz. ``I only know him one way _ he's the
straight man on 'Home Improvement' and the guy who sells tools on
commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   But that changed, Mitz says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him _ and I'm sure it drives him crazy _ `Hey,
you're really funny,''' Mitz says. ``I think he gets pigeon-holed
into the best friend roles. But he really is funny.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been two years since ``Home Improvement'' called it quits
and four years since he completed his real-life ``misadventures in
home improvement.'' In addition to appearing in a TV movie ``The
Pooch &AMP; the Pauper,'' Karn has traveled, worked on his golf game
and appeared at a couple of charity events. A spokesman for the
Rechargeable Battery Recycling Corporation, Karn helped
rehabilitate a house for Habitat for Humanity last April in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after ``Home Improvement'' ended, Karn had the
opportunity to appear in a Broadway play, but the process of
uprooting his family for a temporary move back east wasn't in the
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Television seems to present a more friendly work schedule to a
man who claims to be fully in the family mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I don't have this overall plan of how to move my
career. It just kind of happens.'' Karn says. ``On stage, it's
going to take you every night of the week. And you know, we're just
starting (reading) `Harry Potter.' That's my evening theater right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the Karn family handyman legacy seem to be in any
danger of dying out. After a visit to the Wild Wild West stunt show
at Universal Studios, young Cooper Karn has decided that, like his
father, he too wants to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's putting on a stunt show in the back yard, and he's cast
all the kids in his class,'' Karn says. ``So we're needing to build
breakaway walls and all sorts of things that he's outlined and
blue-printed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
