<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5721 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-18 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COACH DAVE COWENS IS ON A ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY RATTO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Danny Fortson and Adam Keefe showed up 45
minutes late to their first press conference as Golden State
Warriors, leaving a body to wonder if, with true Warrior luck, they
had both signed their contracts and then flunked their physicals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they signed, they passed, and then they spoke
cheerfully of being Warriors, which is news in and of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, when was the last free agent who chose to come here?''
general manager Garry St. Jean asked. ``Mark Price?''
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, when was the last impact free agent to come to
Oakland willingly? ``I don't know that one off the top of my
head,'' said St. Jean, whose top of the head is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fortson and Keefe came as part of a four-team deal with
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, Utah and Boston, but Fortson was a sign-and-trade. Which
is about as close to an actual big-deal free agent as the Warriors
have come in quite a good while.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the talk of Fortson and how he averaged 17 points
and 15 rebounds every time he played 35 minutes in a game, the most
enthusiasm in the room could be found coming out of the slightly
upturned mouth of head coach Dave Cowens, who might actually be the
answer to that free agent question of a paragraph ago.
</P>
<P>
   He was energized while discussing how Fortson would fit into the
</P>
<P>
   Warriors' first discernible master plan in six years. Fortson
would play power forward, he would get rebounds, and he would help
the Warriors run.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's an interesting notion. The Warriors running. They
</P>
<P>
   haven't bothered with that for years now, staying in touch with
the current NBA trend of reducing games to the minimum number of
possessions and the most exhaustive use of the 24-second clock.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors haven't even averaged 90 points a game since 1997,
</P>
<P>
   which you would think would be the absolute minimum standard for
an NBA team. It would also explain in part why the Warriors haven't
met the minimum standard for wins in a while, either.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Cowens is trying to construct a team that is not
only
</P>
<P>
   physically but emotionally committed to pushing the ball forward
and seeking the first best shot, as opposed to the first best
three-point shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Dennis Rodman,'' he said, deftly avoiding the
Youngman-esque punch line, ``Please.'' ``He got the rebound, he got
the ball to the point guard, he ran down the floor, he got
underneath the basket, and then he got another rebound. You can't
run a play better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, unless you make that first shot so you don't need
Rodman
</P>
<P>
   to get that offensive rebound. The message, though, was clear.
Cowens sees too much waste in the typical NBA game, and way too
much in the typical Warrior game.
</P>
<P>
   He wants 12 more possessions out of the Warriors every game. He
</P>
<P>
   wants to get a lot closer to 100 points a game. He wants, in
short, for the Warriors to be relevant again, to have a discernible
and watchable style. One that reminds him of his own glory days
with the Boston Celtics, when the best team in the league scored
nearly 120 points a game and the worst averaged 102.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Fortson to be the power forward Antawn Jamison seems
reluctant to be. Hence, Keefe, who knows the running game so well
from his years in Utah that Cowens describes his knowledge as
``cellular.'' Hence, Jamison and guard Larry Hughes to help force
the tempo Fortson could spark.
</P>
<P>
   This, on top of the other changes in Golden State's dramatis
</P>
<P>
   personae, to the point where the Warrior with the longest tenure
on the team is Adonal Foyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, when you win 19 games, you're going to make a lot of
changes,'' Cowens said. ``Now, I don't know if there's ever been a
five-way trade, but we've done a lot to try and get the kind of
team we want to build here. And we're not done. We're just done for
now.''
</P>
<P>
   How good a team they have built remains to be seen, but the safe
</P>
<P>
   betting is that they may have taken themselves from 19 to, say,
27 wins. Fortson is not Tim Duncan, after all, just an earnest and
talented power forward who can make an impact on a team that hasn't
made one since the Republicans took Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It is at least a decent guess to say that these new, presumably
</P>
<P>
   faster Warriors won't win only 19 again. When asked, Cowens
says, ``Damn right!'' but the history says ``pretty damn right.''
Only six teams since the season expanded to 82 games in 1967 have
failed to win 20 games in successive seasons, and only the '87
Clippers and 93 Mavericks managed it without the excuse of
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors have gone 19-63 in each of the last two regulation
</P>
<P>
   seasons (they went 21-29 in the strike-ravaged 1999 schedule),
so Cowens better say, ``Damn right!'' More to the immediate point,
though, he'd better say that these Warriors will at least exceed
the boredom threshold. That alone would be a significant
improvement, enough perhaps to inspire other crypto-free agents to
consider Golden State as something more than a port of last resort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
