<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-CAL-HNS &LR;      08-18 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A STRONGER CAL FOOTBALL TEAM TAKES SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;    c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turlock, Calif. - When Cal football training camp opened last
year, wide receivers dropped the ball left and right from day No.
1.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after day No. 1, quarterback Kyle Boller's passes
appear to be in surer hands.
</P>
<P>
   While it's much too early to say Air Cal is flying again, the
signs were encouraging Thursday, especially since last year's
ominous opening-day drops continued throughout the season as the
Bears finished dead last in the Pac-10 in passing.
</P>
<P>
   The difference has been apparent in spring practice, in workouts
over the summer and on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That's mostly because coach Tom Holmoe brought in three junior
college transfers last spring as the Bears receiving corps thinned.
Holmoe is cautious in assessing the impact of the newcomers.
``They're in the mix,'' he said. ``We have no starters. We're going
to go through this camp and determine who our starters are,
probably in the next six to seven days.''
</P>
<P>
   He can't be blamed for appearing reluctant to overly laud the
three transfers. Two years ago at Turlock, Holmoe greeted an
incoming class of coveted wide receivers _ a group called the Fab
Five.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ainsworth, last year's leading receiver and the only
player consistently able to handle Boller's bullets, flunked out of
school last spring. So did the team's No. 2 receiver, Ronnie
Davenport. Omar Bennett was academically ineligible last year and
attended a junior college to make up credits. Eddie Macha left
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Brian White is the only member of the Fab Five still with the
team, and he's off the depth chart as camp opens. Sean Currin, a
former walk-on, will contend for a starting spot this year. Still,
most eyes are on the transfers _ Charon Arnold, Chad Heydorff and
Derek Swafford.
</P>
<P>
   New wide receivers coach Ken Margerum is as cautious as Holmoe.
``I don't think we have any guys who are going to be All
Americans,'' he said. ``We have guys who can be consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Margerum is optimistic. ``I'm confident they'll line up
properly, move the chains and surprise people with their
craftiness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Center Reed Diehl says the new additions will give the Bears a
more potent air attack. ``I'm confident they can win in one-on-one
coverage,'' he said. ``We saw one-on-one coverage 60 percent of the
time last year because defenses didn't respect our wide
receivers,'' he added. ``But these guys can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Holmoe nor Margerum are ready to single out any player.
But players aren't so reluctant, and Heydorff has been attracting
the most attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some summer games he made some catches that were
phenomenal,'' Boller said.
</P>
<P>
   Heydorff, a transfer from Glendale Community College, said he
had an agenda in coming to Cal. ``The opportunity was great as far
as getting on the field and making a difference,'' he said.
Heydorff and the other receivers spent much of the summer in
Berkeley
</P>
<P>
   working with Boller, who last year often lacked touch on the
ball and wasn't helped by receivers who ran the wrong routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worked on his skills, he's perfected them,'' Heydorff
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I can keep up my end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
