<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CLASSIC CLINTON TO BOFFO BRADLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on speakers at the Democrats' convention:
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: You don't have to be a Slick Willie fan to be
awestruck by the president's ability to beguile his listeners when
he delivers a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton isn't a great orator in the classic sense. He rarely
indulges in soaring rhetoric driven by elegant language or
sophisticated symbolism. As often as not, his speeches are mostly
laundry lists of accomplishments and/or policy proposals. Usually,
they're way too long.
</P>
<P>
   But he never fails to cast a spell, to leave his audience
begging for more. It's hard to explain, but maybe the old saying
about the art of acting provides a clue to Clinton's appeal: Acting
is 90 percent sincerity; if you can fake that, you've got it made.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: The first lady/New York Senate
candidate, on the other hand, can't even do a good imitation of
sincerity. Everything she says seems contrived, forced, calculated.
If her convention speech exemplified her campaign style, I'm
guessing that Republican Rick Lazio, not Hillary Clinton, will be
the next U.S. senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   TEDDY KENNEDY: The senator from Massachusetts has never suffered
from a lack of sincerity, but he has suffered plenty from the
passage of time. I remember standing on the convention floor at New
York's Madison Square Garden in 1980 when Kennedy delivered what
was perhaps the greatest political speech I'd ever heard. Maybe you
saw the excerpt that kept popping up on television the other night:
``The work goes on ... the cause endures ... the dream will never
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's 2000 convention speech, sad to say, fell considerably
short of his long-ago New York performance. He stumbled and fumbled
his way through some partisan propaganda about health care and
reminisced about his brothers, but it was painfully obvious that he
no longer has anything to say _ or the skill to say it. Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINE KENNEDY SCHLOSSBERG: If it was an elegant Kennedy you
wanted to see _ if your heart craved a reminder of Camelot _ you
could find it in a rare public appearance by JFK's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline is not a polished speechifier, which made her remarks
all the more compelling. And if other speakers' sincerity was in
doubt, hers most definitely was not. She admires Democratic
presidential nominee Al Gore and clearly dragged herself into the
spotlight in hopes of boosting his campaign. Schlossberg exuded
enough class to make the convention's ``liberal night'' program
seem like a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Bill Bradley? Is he the guy who ran against Gore
in the Democratic primaries?
</P>
<P>
   Yep. Same guy. If his Tuesday night speech wasn't the best he's
ever given, it surely had to be in the top two or three. It brought
to mind a delegate's comment that night in 1980 when Ted Kennedy
ended his unsuccessful campaign against Jimmy Carter. ``If he'd
talked like that six months ago,'' the delegate said after
Kennedy's spectacular speech, ``he'd have won the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bradley had talked six months ago like he did this week, he
still wouldn't have won the nomination _ but he might have given
Gore a run for his money.
</P>
<P>
   JESSE JACKSON: When you've heard one carnival barker, you've
heard 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   HAROLD FORD JR.: Keep an eye on this 30-year-old congressman
from Tennessee. Ford could very well turn out to be the next big
deal in the Democratic Party. He has charisma. He has ideas. He
even has a sense of restraint: His convention keynote speech was
less than 13 minutes long.
</P>
<P>
   JOE LIEBERMAN: The vice presidential candidate's speech was
excellent, especially if you like cheap-shot partisanship delivered
in a style so low-key and amiable that the targets of his criticism
probably didn't know they were being attacked. Gore struck gold
when he put this guy on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   KARENNA GORE SCHIFF: Al Gore loves his daughter. His daughter
loves him. What the heck. There's always room at the podium for
someone as adorable as Karenna.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Check back with me later.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
