<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING ATTACHED TO AN E-MAIL VIEWER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have downloaded an .Snp file on my PC.MDNM/
but cannot open it. It's an attachment to an e.MDNM/-mail. I have
tried to get the sender to help, but no one answers me.
</P>
<P>
   _ Voice in the Wilderness
</P>
<P>
   DEAR VOICE: I get that same treatment, too, although it's
usually after I start talking about the substantial raise I
deserve. I'm not greedy. I'm really not. I just want parity with
all the other columnists. I mean, let's face it, you don't see
Heloise rolling pennies at the end of the month just so she can buy
a few cans of Beanee Weenees.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry. I didn't answer your question, did I? I'm not trying
to avoid you, but this salary thing has me really torqued. It's not
like they could hire somebody off the street to do this, although
certain people will tell you that's exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, I'll try to keep focused. Just because somebody sends you
a file attachment doesn't mean you can open it. No matter what kind
of computer you have, you need the appropriate file viewer or
application to take a look at it, a fact that seems to escape most
people when they're glibly e.MDNM/-mailing their stuff back and
forth.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if some overpaid public relations person sends me a
news release in Word 2000 format attached to an e.MDNM/-mail, I
can't open it unless I sell a couple of pints of blood so I can
afford the upgrade from Word 95.
</P>
<P>
   It should be common courtesy on any e.MDNM/-mailer's part to
assume that a recipient may not have the ability to open an
attachment. Almost any word-processing document can be saved as
plain text and inserted into the body of a letter, but spreadsheets
and databases are different animals.
</P>
<P>
   You're dealing with an .Snp, which is a Microsoft Access
snapshot file, sort of a picture of the report the sender has
generated from his database. Luckily, Microsoft provides a free
viewer for these files, as well as for Word and Excel documents.
Just do a Yahoo! search for ``Microsoft snapshot viewer'' or
``Microsoft Word viewer'' or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   When you get to the download link, click on it. You should be
prompted to save it in a location of your choosing. I generally
save stuff to an empty folder, but that's up to you as long as you
can find the file later. When you do, double-click on it, and it
will install itself. It should also associate itself as the default
viewer for those files. That means you can just click on the
attachment from now on, and it will open automatically.
</P>
<P>
   .MDRV/.MDUL/.MDNM/DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Reguarding your recent
column: i am uphauled at the blatent ignorance for terminology. The
word hacker has been LONG established. i was born on a computer,
and started programming excercises when i was 6 years old and i
have been hacking ever since. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Zero 7
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ZERO: Too bad you didn't pick up a copy of Reader Rabbit
back then. You might be able to communicate coherently or at least
express a cogent thought without embarrassing yourself. They really
don't pay me enough to deal with letters like these. I'm uphauled.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay is one of the wealthiest, most eligible
bachelors in North America, and certainly not the total loser that
his ex-girlfriend claims he is. Write him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
