<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Los Angeles) _ President Clinton has raised $100
million so far this year to help fellow Democrats and he is still
going strong. During one weekend in the Los Angeles area, Clinton
raised some $10 million for his presidential library, plus
California donors kicked in a bundle to bolster Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Senate campaign in New York. That's the way the system
works, and until campaign finance reform becomes a reality (don't
count on it soon), political aspirants will have to have their
hands out. By HELEN THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CAMPAIGN-BEGINS (Los Angeles) _ And they're off! The
Republican and Democratic candidates begin their head-to-head
competition for the approval of the American electorate. While the
candidates all say the only poll that counts is the Nov. 7 vote
tally, they are very aware of the historic fact that the ticket
leading in the polls on Labor Day is usually the ticket that wins
in November. By DAN FREEDMAN and MARK HELM. (Filed Thursday in the
``p'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The bombastic Pat Buchanan, who
was nominated for president last week by one wing of the warring
Reform Party, may hope to lead the nation into a future of
continued prosperity and enlightened policies. But the ideas he
espouses are not those of the future. If put into law, they would
not perpetuate prosperity or illuminate the way ahead. They would
have exactly the opposite affect. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed
Wednesday in the ``k'' category.)
</P>
