<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      08-18 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON HAS RAISED $100 MILLION THIS YEAR FOR DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton has raised $100 million so far
this year to help fellow Democrats, according to White House press
secretary Joe Lockhart, and he is still going strong. Clinton has
been averaging about two fundraisers a week _ and there are no
signs of donor fatigue so far.
</P>
<P>
   During a weekend of party-going in the Los Angeles area, Clinton
also raised some $10 million for his presidential library that will
be built in Little Rock, Ark. In addition, California donors kicked
in a bundle to bolster Hillary Rodham Clinton's coffers in her bid
for a Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the system works, and until campaign finance
reform becomes a reality (don't count on it soon), political
aspirants will have to have their hands out. Some candidates detest
that part of seeking public office.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Strauss, the venerable former chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, remembers when President Jimmy Carter was
running for re-election in 1980. The party was close to bankruptcy
and Strauss was asked to host a fundraiser at $10,000 a head. He
appealed to Democratic friends and others with deep pockets to
attend a reception for Carter and to kick in to keep the party
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   When Carter showed up for the fundraiser, Strauss asked him to
pose separately for photographs with each donor. Carter balked and
refused to do so, despite Strauss' pleas that he had promised the
generous contributors that they would get a picture with the
president. When Carter remained adamant, Strauss told him: ``All
right, Mr. President, but I'm going to have to give them their
money back.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the president saw the light. Without further
hesitation, Carter instructed Strauss: ``Line them up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush is projecting a new confidence in his
debating skills. His decision to go to the mat with Vice President
Al Gore three times this fall and to propose two debates between
vice presidential candidates Richard Cheney and Sen. Joe Lieberman
came as a surprise after the Bush team had dragged its feet in
agreeing to a debate schedule.
</P>
<P>
   All the debaters would do well to see an upcoming PBS televised
documentary featuring anchorman Jim Lehrer interviewing some past
presidents about their debates. The TV show will be broadcast in
September. Some of the presidential recollections are painful to
this day but are nonetheless instructive on te pitfalls of
political debates.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush complained to Lehrer that the
debates ``are all about someone making a mistake.'' He ought to
know. In 1992, a bored Bush looked at his watch a couple of times
during a three-way debate with Bill Clinton _ the Democratic
presidential nominee _ and Reform Party candidate Ross Perot.
Bush's distracted gesture led the late Pamela Harriman, a strong
Clinton backer, to pat a Republican leader's hand and, with a big
smile, announce to him that Bush had just lost the election.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer said President Gerald Ford ``can't bring himself'' to
this day to admit that he made a mistake in 1976 when he declared
in his debate with challenger Jimmy Carter that Poland was not
under Soviet domination.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's goof didn't help him in the public perception of his
knowledge of world affairs.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the sad story of Adm. James Stockdale, chosen
by Perot to be his running mate in 1992. Stockdale was at a loss
when he was suddenly thrust into the limelight in a debate with
Clinton running mate Al Gore and Vice President Dan Quayle. Few
will forget that poignant moment when Stockdale said, ``What am I
doing here?''
</P>
<P>
   He told Lehrer that he had been offered the No. 2 spot by Perot
only three days before the vice presidential debate and that he
wasn't privy to Perot's positions on the issues being debated. He
said his debate humiliation that night was worse than his years as
a prisoner of war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore and Hadassah Lieberman may be their husbands'
not-so-secret weapons on the campaign trail. They are graced with
warm personalities, especially compared with their spouses. Some
Democrats even wish Tipper was at the top of the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Strauss, former chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, thinks Tipper should follow in Lady Bird Johnson's
footsteps and undertake a whistle-stop tour through the South, to
drum up support among Southerners and women, areas where Vice
President Al Gore needs help in his election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss credited Lady Bird Johnson's four-day whistle stop tour
with 47 stops and even more speeches, with helping her husband,
Lyndon B. Johnson, win a landslide election in 1964. She embarked
on a crusade to sell her husband's ``Great Society'' programs and
it was not an easy ride in the South of that era where Johnson's
push for civil rights and voting rights were passionately opposed
by some.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady Bird, BLACK BIRD, GO HOME'' read some of the signs in
Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper always says she wants voters to see her husband as she
sees him as a human being and a man.
</P>
<P>
   LBJ needed no humanizing. If anything, he was all too human. The
whistle-stop with Alabama-born Lady Bird putting on her thickest
drawl didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   If Tipper invited Hadassah along for the ride, the two women
could be a dynamic duo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (Helen Thomas can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via email:
helent(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
