<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DEM-VOICES (Various datelines to come) _ Reactions from around
the country to the Democratic Convention and to Al Gore. (Bylines
to come)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (On the Mississippi River) _ Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman
hit the campaign trail. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Memphis, Tenn.) _ George W. Bush hits back in heart of
Gore territory with the theme ``The People Who Know Them Best.'' By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-DELEGATES (Los Angeles) _ What the party faithful are
feeling as they head home from the convention. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES-CAMPAIGNS (Undated) _ Across the country, elected judges
are being fined, censured, even threatened with removal from office
for practicing that venerable political tradition: exaggerating or
outright lying about an opponent's record. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Dateline to kum, Mont.) _ With Bruce Babbitt, the
Interior secretary, at the fire scene. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ A ruling is expected in the Wen
Ho Lee bail hearing. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CANCER (Scottsdale, Ariz.) _ Developments as Sen. John
McCain met with his doctors on Friday to discuss the seriousness of
his skin cancer and to chart the best action against the
malignancy. (Summary from wires) By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ Developing: The Russian effort to
save the 118 crew members trapped aboard a sunken submarine was
dealt a serious setback Friday when rescuers reached the deck but
were unable to open the escape hatch, Russian navy officials told
state television. President Vladimir Putin returns to Moscow. By
Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-U.S. (Jerusalem) _ Dennis Ross, the U.S. Middle East
envoy, was scheduled Friday to meet with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to discuss the Mideast peace effort. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-REUNIONS (Seoul) _ Weeping and embracing each other at the
end of their reunion meetings, North and South Korean family
members who met this week after 50 years of separation parted ways
again on Friday. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MEDIA (Beijing) _ The Chinese authorities have detained
the younger brother of a Boston-based poet who was arrested in
Beijing last week, apparently for his involvement in a left-leaning
literary journal that sometimes published work by dissidents. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ An influential expert on global
warming who for nearly 20 years has pressed countries to cut
emissions of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases now says the
emphasis on carbon dioxide may be misplaced. Instead, he and a team
of scientists have concluded that the best way to get quick results
in slowing warming is to cut other heat-trapping gasses first. By
Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LASER-NUKES (Washington) _ Developing the world's most
powerful laser to monitor the nation's nuclear arsenal without
testing could cost nearly three times the original $1 billion price
tag, congressional auditors say. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ Developments in the strike against
Verizon Communications. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-INTERNET (Tokyo) _ Mobile phone-based Internet services
have exploded in Japan. The wireless Web has not only increased the
time people can spend on the Internet, it has also given service
providers an easy way to collect subscription fees through
customers' mobile phone bills. That ease of payment has fed an
entrepreneurial boom. Dozens of services, from restaurant guides to
surf forecasts, have already captured a large user base and new
ones are announced almost daily, offering games, weather, traffic
information, stock quotes, even cartoons. While Internet companies
in the United States struggle to generate profits, many Japanese
mobile phone contents providers are in the black within months of
starting business. ``It's a new business model'' for
information-providers on the Internet, says a Tokyo analyst. By
Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
<P>
   GM-ICHAN (Detroit) _ General Motors says that Carl Icahn plans
to buy more than $15 million, but less than 15 percent, of its
common shares. GM shares rise 3 percent. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-SUITS (Undated) _ Heartened by a court victory in the
managed care wars, lawyers for health insurance companies are
seeking to consolidate a large number off suits attacking managed
care and transfer them to Philadelphia from Miami. By Milt
Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAMS-ACQUIRE (London) _ Diageo of Britain, the world's
biggest liquor company, and Pernod Ricard of France said Friday
that they plan to make a joint bid for Seagram's wine and spirits
business, valued at at least $7 billion. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-TELECOM (Frankfurt) _ On the fallout following Germany's
auction of mobile phone licenses, in which six companies bid nearly
$50 billion. Shares of most bidding companies fall sharply. KPN of
the Netherlands says it can still finance its bid after a partner,
Hutchison Whampoa of Hong Kong, pulls out. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
