   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OED-IN-AMERICA (Undated) _ A profile of Jesse Sheidlower, a
young American lexicographer with impeccable credentials _ who also
happens to be the author of a 288-page book on a certain inelegant
word that rhymes with duck _ who the Oxford English Dictionary
engaged earlier this year when it decided to open a North American
office to document the evolution of American English. By Janny
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,4.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIOLOGISTS (Undated) _ Walter Goodman gives us the flavor of
the 95th annual meeting of the American Sociological Association.
</P>
<P>
   FAILED-UTOPIA (Undated) _ In her new and eccentric book, one of
Susan Buck-Morss' worries is that with the fall of the Soviet
Union, the great dream of a ``mass utopia'' that marked the 20th
century in both East and West is near extinction. There was, she
argues, nothing wrong with the dream; only its execution went awry.
By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
