<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-560&AMP;     08-18 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUERS REACH SUBMARINE DECK BUT ARE UNABLE TO OPEN ESCAPE HATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER with JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian effort to save the 118 crew members trapped
aboard a crippled submarine was dealt a major setback Friday when
workers hooked a rescue capsule to the deck but were unable to open
the escape hatch, Russian navy officials told state television.
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Vyachevslav Popov, the commander of the Russian Northern
Fleet, told Russian television Friday that the rescue effort began
last Saturday, four hours after the accident occurred, as soon as
the navy found the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concentrated all our efforts on saving the crew,'' Popov
said. ``The rescuers are tired but they continue their work.''
Russian officials said they would continue to try to rescue the
crew.
</P>
<P>
   After days of trying, Russian navy officers finally reached the
escape hatch at the rear of the submarine with a rescue capsule.
But the deck was so badly damaged the capsule was unable to
establish an airtight lock. Without such an airtight seal, rescuers
cannot open the hatch and enter the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to the deck around the hatch makes any successful
rescue extremely unlikely. Russian President Vladimir Putin
acknowledged on Friday what some Russian officials have been saying
since the accident happened: that there was never much hope of
rescuing the crew. Putin said that when he was informed of the
accident he asked Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev about chances to
save the crew of the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer was, `There is an extremely small chance for
rescue, but it exists,''' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers on Friday tried several times to make a seal between the
submarine and the rescue capsule, but as soon as they pumped out
water, more rushed in. The rescuers in the capsule kept working
until its batteries ran out and the team was forced to return to
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The failure Friday was a big disappointment for the navy.
Officials had already ruled out trying to enter through the two
front escape hatches, saying they were too badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if the deck around the rear hatch was deformed in
the initial accident that crippled the Kursk or immediately
afterward, when the submarine crashed to the floor of the Barents
Sea during a military exercise.
</P>
<P>
   With the newly acknowledged extent of the damage, the next best
hope is likely a British rescue sub that is being transported to
the scene of the accident. It is due to reach the Kursk Saturday,
but it is not clear if the British submarine will be able to make
an airtight connection.
</P>
<P>
   Putin will return Friday to Moscow, cutting short a summit
meeting with leaders of the former Soviet states. The Russian
president has been criticized for making only a few public comments
since the accident. Putin said Friday that he initially wanted to
fly to the accident scene, but decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did the right thing, because the arrival of
non-specialists from any field at the disaster area would not help
high-placed officials and more often would hamper work,'' Putin
said. ``Everyone should keep to his place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for rescuing any crew members have been steadily falling.
There have been no signs of life since a tapping noise from the
hull stopped a few days ago. And as more is learned about the
extent of the damage, many officials believe crew members could
have perished immediately after the accident.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Popov said Friday that much of the damage was caused by an
explosion, but he did not know what caused the explosion. Some
Russian officials have speculated that a collision with another
vessel set off one of the torpedoes in the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said Thursday that catastrophic damage and
``irrefutable data'' pointed to a collision. They said the object
or ship that had collided with the Kursk has not yet been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Any vessel that could cause the sort of damage described by the
Russian officials would itself have suffered enormous damage, and
no such vessel has been reported.
</P>
<P>
   George Tenet, the director of the U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency, visited Moscow Friday, Russian officials said. But it was
not clear if Tenet had traveled to Russia to discuss the accident
or another security matter.
</P>
<P>
   Russian navy commanders met for eight hours Thursday with Deputy
Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov at Severomorsk, headquarters of the
Northern Fleet, and decided to continue the rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would continue studying a plan to raise the
vessel with pontoons and begin salvaging operations to recover the
two nuclear reactors on board that could pose a long-term threat to
the fisheries of the Arctic seas.
</P>
</TEXT>
