<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUB _ LONDON _ After days of anguished efforts, a rescue
capsule finally reaches an escape hatch on the shattered hull of
the sunken Russian submarine Kursk, but finds the hatch so mangled
that it can't link up. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-TRAVEL _ DAMASCUS, Syria _ From the ornate tomb of the
great conqueror Salaheddin, to the ramshackle exhibit of the only
Syrian Cosmonaut, Syria's capital offers a captivating sampling of
the best of classic Arab and Moslem culture. Visitors can step back
in time, dining in courtyards enclosed by the black and red blocks
of classic Arab architecture and touring dozens of castles in the
countryside. There's no McDonald's and little Coca-Cola, but you
can shop for dehydrated Newts in the medicinal herb stalls of the
old market. All possible for those willing to join a small but
growing number of American tourists to a country that may be slowly
opening up to the west. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-PALMYRA _ PALMYRA, Syria _ These expansive ruins show the
legacy of a working city built on taxation of goods on the old Silk
Road. Connecting it's grand temples is a system of roads, a senate
and treasury. On the outskirts of town are the tower tombs, where
family members were encased behind eerie carvings of their
likenesses. Considered one of the greatest ruins in the world,
Palmyra, about 4,000 years old, is still only lightly visited.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). WIT PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   With information for locator map; if-you-go box attached at end
of main story.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in advance Wed., Aug. 16, on the NYT wire in (i)
International and (t) Travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE _ Ford is getting plaudits for its handling of the
Firestone tire recall involving its popular Explorer SUV,
particularly since the automaker's release of Firestone data
showing that Firestone's ATX series is exceptionally prone to tread
failure and the company suspected a problem at least by 1997. But
legal and scientific experts say Ford is just trying deflect blame
and save its brand name; the Explorer's suspension design means
that tire failures are far more likely to trigger a rollover,
compared with other SUVs, and that Ford's decision to use cheaper
glass in side windows means passengers are more likely to be
ejected and killed. Ford's redesigned 2002 Explorer, with a
different suspension, is set to be unveiled in January. (Carmody,
Austin American-Statesman). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   TOOTER _ Tillie Tooter, an 83-year-old grandmother, speaks to
the media about being stuck in the trees above an alligator- and
snake-infested swamp in Broward County. (Lambert, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   UNC-QA _ Q&AMP;A with James Moeser, the new chancellor at the
University of North Carolina, who arrived on campus this week from
the University of Nebraska. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POWER-GLIDERS _ At the quirky airport in Smithville, Texas, the
dominant aircraft on weekend mornings is the motorized parachute.
They waft around like a bunch of giant butterflies carrying their
own individual rainbows. Fairly safe, as long as the wind's not
high. When you're up in one of these contraptions _ kind of a
go-kart with a fan in back _ it's like being in a plane with all
the windows wide open and nothing underfoot. (Banks, Austin
American-Statesman). 32. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-WEDDING _ ALEXANDRIA, Va _ Former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich gets married _ again _ this time at an Alexandria hotel.
Developing. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, Washington; Subcategory,
National.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Wedding is at 7:30 p.m. EDT. Story expected to move by 10
p.m. EDT on the NYT wire.
