<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-BORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE: BORING BUT HIGH ON CONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Sn Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ By failing to deliver in his presidential
acceptance speech, Al Gore didn't let anybody down. He lived up to
the expectations. And in the process he found his identity.
</P>
<P>
   We know this much: Al Gore's picture is not in the Toastmasters
Hall of Fame. Few people outside of Henry Hyde and the cast of
``Big Brother'' can make television as utterly lifeless as Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But we knew that coming in. We knew Gore was going to be a bore.
We knew he'd barrel through his punch lines like a freight train
painted flat gray. We knew he'd give us substance and issues to
chew on - humor be damned. We knew, ultimately, that Al would be
Al.
</P>
<P>
   And right now that's looking pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, this is not a thrilling election. The economy is
still on fire. And the Republicans can make Bill Clinton the
lightning rod all they want, but this election isn't about Clinton
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And so Americans have been reduced to thinking about two not
very exciting guys wanting very badly to get a job that doesn't
seem half as exciting or important as Martin Sheen makes it out to
be on TV.
</P>
<P>
   While George W. Bush put some charisma and attitude on the table
two weeks ago in his acceptance speech, he did little to disprove
the notion that he is ``The Candidate,'' a hollow man with almost
no substance, questionable mental ability and a lineage that
doesn't inspire in the same way as the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Bush's rousing speech was empty of content. But it was
fun to watch and made for good television.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore doesn't care about good television. He knew that short
of an improvisational back-flip or saying something like, ``I know
who wins `Survivor,''' he wasn't going to thrill us.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he gave us the beef.
</P>
<P>
   That was pretty wily. And it was refreshing. You've got to like
a guy who comes out and eschews rousing rhetoric and carefully
crafted applause breaks and instead lays down what sounded
suspiciously like a State of the Union Address.
</P>
<P>
   Good old Al. That political wonk. No dressing up in the phony
clothes of entertainment and inspiration. Nah, how about some
content from an actual political platform instead?
</P>
<P>
   The kids won't like it. But it's good for them. Really, that was
50 minutes of spinach compared with W's box of Cheesy Poofs.
</P>
<P>
   As Dan Rather said afterward: ``Tonight, Al Gore bet on
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   He did indeed. Substance is dangerous. Television especially
hates substance. It gums up the works. By not igniting the verbal
fireworks we've come to expect at these affairs, Gore sent the
pundits straight to the knee-jerk reaction anyone could have seen
coming down the road like a neon Kenworth: The speech was flat, it
didn't ``play'' on television, it didn't Clintonize the audience
like an illicit orgasm.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   If Al Gore tried to channel Jerry Seinfeld or suddenly become
the white Jesse Jackson, nobody would have bought it. They would
accuse him of selling out, of pandering to what's expected of
politicians in these big speeches. Instead, Gore seemed intent on
being just what we know him to be: Boring but earnest, a guy who
knows his numbers and has a gigantic heart and who will do good
things for people _ but not someone who gets rewarded for those
virtues by being let into the cool crowd.
</P>
<P>
   He's Anthony Edwards in a George Clooney world. That's an ``ER''
reference for you PBS fans. Good for Gore. He wanted to let the
world know who he is. ``I stand here tonight as my own man,'' he
said, not only distancing himself from Clinton but also revealing
his true self. He told family stories of his mother and father. He
passionately kissed his wife, several times.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, he blew through his applause breaks, obliviously. He
went on long, windbag sentences that changed pitch and tone
ineffectively. He laughed a weird, non-flattering laugh. His neck
and head worked as one piece, while his upper torso seemed to knot
up and stiffen as we watched.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, he didn't dance.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated core Democratic beliefs like inclusion for all
people, higher wages, affirmative action, pro-abortion rights, laws
against hate crimes and more. He made 50 minutes seem like a long,
long time.
</P>
<P>
   But savvy Democrats probably breathed a sigh of relief. Two
weeks agoit looked like there was a new Reagan on the horizon and,
for them, maybe another Michael Dukakis. But Al Gore came through
in a different way on Thursday. He said, ``This is me, this is what
I know, this is what we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So let the pundits say Gore was a bore. Because the next stage
of this election will shift from staged infomercials to the
debates. And W doesn't get in a steel-cage death match with a man
so confident of his platform that he took the bells and whistles
off it and gave it to the country in prime time, like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Goodman is a columnist with the San Francisco Examiner. He can
be reached by e-mail (goodman(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
