<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-18 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE KISS THAT ROARED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Al Gore held Tipper and kissed her full on
the lips the way they must have as young lovers, I knew he had
found his real self.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't a geek anymore. He was the young hunk in the old
photographs. Any politician can kiss babies, but not many can plant
a perfect Rodin kiss on his wife of three decades in front of
millions of people. They didn't unlock for a full seven seconds,
and for a while I thought Gore's acceptance speech might need one
of Tipper's warning labels.
</P>
<P>
   Strong political women around me shivered. Men laughed in
appreciation. We remembered that the most basic family value of
all, love, starts with a kiss. If George W. Bush knows what's good
for him, he'll get his lip consultant working on kissing and not
just smirk removal. With a kiss, the Tennessee prince awoke from an
eight-year slumber. Poof, Bill Clinton was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know who I truly am,'' said Gore, and spoke of
his wife as ``someone I've loved with all my heart since the night
of my senior prom.''
</P>
<P>
   You knew he wasn't lying, and you also knew he isn't exactly the
stiff he's supposed to be. He looked as if someone had taken the
coat hanger out of his suit.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote his speech from the heart, and it worked. Well, it was
a good speech for Al Gore, and one of his better moments was
admitting he's not the most exciting man in the world, while
finally exciting us.
</P>
<P>
   Gore came to talk issues, just as Bush had talked generalities
about values, and Gore trounced him on values, too. Where anyone
got the idea that issues are different from values, I don't know.
But Al Gore explicitly made the connection.
</P>
<P>
   Giving all children health care and a good education is a family
value. Giving the elderly affordable medicine, and not gutting
their Medicare and Social Security, is a family value.
</P>
<P>
   Gore inherits his family values from his strong New Deal family,
and basically the fight between Gore and Bush comes down to
advancing the New Deal, or repealing it so the rich can be
richer.It's a very clear choice this election.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be honest here. I like Al Gore because of the woman he
kissed. Seven years ago, Tipper Gore visited San Francisco and I
interviewed her. I asked if she'd noticed all the homeless lying on
San Francisco sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have seen them, and it's outrageous,'' she said with a
passion reporters usually don't hear from prominent individuals.
``This country badly needs mental health programs to take care of
these people.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an issue (and value) I care strongly about, too. So we
talked for quite a while about the scandalous state of mental
health care and the stigma that prevents some people from seeking
care, and others from providing help.
</P>
<P>
   Some people would rather not see. Tipper has been opening their
eyes. As a first lady, she really would be something. At the end of
the interview, I mentioned the famous Harvard-Yale game of 1968, in
which Harvard scored 16 points in the last 46 seconds to tie Yale.
Al Gore's roommate, Tommy Lee Jones, was a guard on the Harvard
team.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Tipper became a 20-year-old again, and whooped,
``Harvard beats Yale, 28-28!'' _ which was the headline in the
college paper. This woman's enthusiasm is amazing. Anyone married
to Tipper must be OK, and it's easy to see why Al keeps kissing her
like that.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore always seemed stiff at the podium, making hand gestures
that didn't fit his words, and emphasizing the wrong words, often
lowly little prepositions.
</P>
<P>
   There was a little of that in his speech. Just enough to let you
know who he was. He's not some guy who changed his whole mouth to
give a speech, like Bush, who scowled for 52 minutes to keep the
smirk at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Gore stayed focused and serious, yet loose, with no goofy smiles
and only one forced joke. Finally, the Al Gore on the podium was
beginning to morph with the Al Gore you see in a small room.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago I went with Gore to a classroom in nearby
Cupertino where he was going to demonstrate the educational
usefulness of the Internet to reporters and high school students,
who already knew more about it than any of us.
</P>
<P>
   Gore really knew how to use the Internet, which was unusual for
a middle-aged man at the time, but then he did invent it. When he
tried to get into the Library of Congress, though, nothing
happened. Gore started making jokes with the kids about government
inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The kids loved this big guy sitting at a little desk hitting
keys to no avail, and wisecracking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Watch a politician in a room filled with high school kids, and
you learn a lot about him. Gore does well in such a room. Look at
this guy, and the infectiously happy Gore and Lieberman families.
Maybe Al Gore is not all that exciting, but he likes kids and vows
to protect a woman's right to choose. He may get that women's vote
after all.
</P>
<P>
   And he can kiss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
