<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TENANTS FRET LATE OPENING OF NEW AIRPORT TERMINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Officials of the San Francisco International
Airport announced last week that the $850 million International
Terminal would open at least six weeks later than planned because
of construction delays, prompting concern for tenants who are
finishing stores and restaurants and hiring workers.
</P>
<P>
   Nidal Nazzal, who owns Burger Joint, one of the 16 restaurants
slated for the new terminal, plans to open in mid-September as
originally scheduled. But that is well before the Nov. 1 to Dec. 15
time frame that airport officials now believe is more realistic for
the opening of the new wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will give us a little time to get the kinks out so when
the airport finally does open, we'll be really ready,'' said
Nazzal, who has already hired eight employees and plans to serve
airport workers until the terminal opens. ``But it's hard not
knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   For tenants, every day past the original opening _ Sept. 26 _
translates into losses.
</P>
<P>
   Many have already hired employees and must pay their salaries if
they want to keep them. They have advertised September opening
dates. Most have loan payments. On top of that, construction costs
are two to three times higher than most of the tenants expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay is just one more thing,'' said Michael Levine, a
partner in Il Fornaio/Cafe Del Mondo at the International Terminal
and chairman of the newly formed San Francisco International
Airport Restaurant Association. ``The reality is, you don't have a
Host Marriott. You have individual entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine was referring to the airport's decision to abandon the
practice of hiring a master concessionaire, like Host Marriott
International, in favor of selecting local businesses to fill most
of the 140,000 square feet of retail space in the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Airport spokesman Peter Nardoza said the airport had agreed to
defray some costs by covering the salaries of already-hired
employees from Sept. 26 to the new opening date _ whenever that is.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the airport will pay the interest on loans
that come due after the original start date and before the
businesses start making money. And some other unexpected costs may
be covered by rent credits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to see them lose,'' Nardoza said. ``If they have
legitimate costs that are unexpected, we'll work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nardoza said the airport, which does not rely on tax dollars for
operations, hoped to recoup those extra costs by filing claims
against contractors responsible for the delays. He declined to
identify any of the contractors who might be sued. He said delays
from labor strikes were not subject to such claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
