<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ATTN: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, August 20, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; August 20 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MALE-BODIES (Undated) _ The new book, ``The Adonis Complex''
(Free Press), tries to show exhaustively how concerns about body
image have come to dominate, and tyrannize, many American men.
``There's no question that there's a much greater emphasis on male
body image than there was a generation ago,'' said Dr. Harrison G.
Pope Jr., one of the book's three authors and a professor of
psychiatry at Harvard Medical School. By Guy Trebay.
</P>
<P>
   CHLOE-SEVIGNY-CULT (Undated) _ What is it about Chloe Sevigny
that has turned the fashion world into a pack of dogs howling about
her as if she were a full moon, or a lamb chop? Is it the fact that
she's vacant? Waspy? Not quite pretty? Alternative? For whatever
reason, the banquettes are alive with the sound of Chloe, recently
dubbed by Vogue as ``the New Postmodern Grunge Audrey Hepburn.'' By
Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   RAZOR-SCOOTERS (New York) _ Since arriving from Hong Kong at
Christmas, the chrome Razor scooters, which go for about $100 a
pop, have been selling out at both Toys ``R'' Us and the Sharper
Image, appealing equally to superannuated kids and to the regular
kind. By John Leland.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL-BUTLERY-SCHOOL (Undated) - Butler training school at the
St. Regis Hotel in Manhattan. Alex Witchel writes: ``When I stayed
at the St. Regis a few years ago, I opened the door to a young
woman dressed in white tie and tails who identified herself as the
butler. Since I had no idea what to do with her, I sent her on her
way. A female butler. What a funny idea. During my fifth hour of
butler training last week, I was no longer amused. Maybe it was
having to wear the white tie and tails in 80-degree heat. Or maybe
it was the new Manhattan phone books that needed to be carried into
the rooms and the old ones carried out. Or maybe it was that the
butlers training me had a quality _ a stillness, a patience, an
obedience of sorts _ that I will never have in this lifetime. If I
could have gotten my hands on the guest who left her underwear
piled in the bathtub and her shirt draped over a bedroom lamp, she
would not be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Geography can play a big role in the
August psyche of a gardener. By Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-POWER-DRESSING (Undated) _ Based on the women at the
Democratic National Convention, blue is the new power color, the
color that suggests true love and fidelity. By Ruth LaFerla.
</P>
