<HEADLINE>
KEEPING RACCOON OUT OF CHIMNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August   20, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. A raccoon set up shop in my chimney with her babies. I wasn't
sure what I was going to do, but they left after about two weeks,
on their own. Now I wonder what to do about the chimney where I am
sure they left their calling cards. I opened the fireplace damper
and out dropped a few small pieces of concrete and a bit of dust.
Should I have the chimney swept? We don't use the fireplace much.
</P>
<P>
   B.E., Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is not much you have to do except put a stainless steel
cap on the chimney to keep out raccoons and other vermin. You could
have the chimney swept, but I think this will stir up more debris
and scat than if you let it alone. I think it is best left as is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have received some very different opinions about staining
my house, which is sided with cedar clapboards that are stained a
dark brown (I think it is an oil-based stain) that is not peeling
but dry; the last stain job was in 1981. One painter does power
washing, another does not. One says oil is good, another said it is
not. One said my clapboards have a solid stain, another said it was
oil. There are sections of the house that are plywood, and one
painter said it is stained with a solid stain. I thought it was
paint. Now I am confused and don't know what to do. What should I
do?
</P>
<P>
   BERNICE KREIGSMAN, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. With all those conflicting opinions, the handyman is confused
too, but he still has his opinions: The clapboards are stained with
a semitransparent stain (no other finish could last 19 years
without peeling), and anything new you put on should be an
oil-based semitransparent stain of the same color. Trying to change
colors or using a solid-color stain is asking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The plywood was stained, with a solid color stain, which looks
like paint. Continue with a solid-color stain. Avoid changing
colors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I hear weird sounds in my attic and crawl space behind
built-in drawers in my bedroom. They sound like mice, only at night
and not downstairs. How do mice get up there? I have a trap door
but little room in the attic. I can get at the crawl space by
pulling out the drawers. What can I do? I don't want to leave them
to die.
</P>
<P>
   ALERTED AT NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   A. Chances are they are mice. Squirrels would make a lot more
noise. You hear the sounds at night because all is quiet. In the
daytime the mice are quiet because you are making so much noise.
They have found a home in your attic and got there because they are
excellent jumpers and climbers. They will stay there as long as
there is food.
</P>
<P>
   You can put traps behind those built-in drawers, and in the
attic, as far as you can reach around that trap door. Snap traps
are effective but sticky traps are easier to use. Some people say
the sticky traps are cruel, but mice are vermin and have no right
living in your house; besides, they can carry a deadly disease. You
can even get live traps for mice, but then you have to dispose of
them; transporting them away from the house is illegal. Killing
them is not.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid using traps and disposing of the mice, you can use
D-Con instead. It is very effective, and contrary to some opinions,
it does not leave dead corpses in the house to rot and smell up the
place. Keep the D-Con away from pets, people, and other animals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a lot of latticework on my porches, part of it is
painted and part is stained. For some reason, I am getting mildew
on the lattice. It is the first time it has happened in some years.
Why?
</P>
<P>
   I know I have to treat the lattice to get rid of the mildew. Can
I pressure wash with bleach? Can I use JoMax solution? What would
be most effective, and how can I keep the mildew from returning?
</P>
<P>
   CLAIRE MELVILLE, Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Who knows why the mildew appeared this year after many years
of none at all? No one can tell for sure, but I can suggest that
conditions were just right for mildew to grow: The paint and stain,
which is mildew-resistant, has gotten old and less effective, and
just enough moisture appeared on the lattice to attract the
wandering mold spores that are all around us, just waiting to land
on the right surface and start growing.
</P>
<P>
   Do not power wash with bleach; you'd scatter too much bleach
around and wouldn't hit the lattice enough. Use a regular hose
spray with the right bleach solution. You can use the JoMax, which
must be mixed with bleach; it simply makes the bleach more
effective longer.
</P>
<P>
   After bleaching and rinsing, you could repaint or restain the
lattice; as I said, exterior paints and stains are mildew
resistant, but are effective for only about two years.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is to replace the wood lattice with vinyl lattice,
which will resist the mold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
