<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5829 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-LONG-NIGHT-HNS &LR;      08-18 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LONG-NIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DOCUMENTARY LOOKS INSIDE SOUTH AFRICAN TRUTH PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note cast box at end)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The exorcism comes late in Deborah Hoffman and Frances Reid's
shattering ``Long Night's Journey Into Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliably unobtrusive documentarians, Hoffman and Reid turn their
video cameras on South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission
and the individuals who come before it seeking amnesty or
enlightenment, without chipping away at the mysterious ethos
glowing around.
</P>
<P>
   The foreignness of the system intercut with the shocking
capacity for forgiveness is unmistakably powerful. But apartheid
and the commission are decidedly otherworldly _ in its sincerity
and ornate scope, it's unlike any justice system in the world. If
the commission is post-apartheid, it's also extra-legal justice, an
odd characteristic not lost on the film, which took home Sundance's
top-documentary prize in January.
</P>
<P>
   Complex legal explanations are jettisoned and a dizzying array
of footage is employed to bring the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission to some spiritual level, one that transcends legality.
The film implies that the law is hardly equipped to deal with the
human stain on a political incident _ as self-evident as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and Reid assume that this disjunction between South
Africa's system and, say, the United States' would become evident
to the film's audience. It doesn't take long. Half way through you
start thinking of mourned victims of American police violence like
Abner Louima and the Amadou Diallo, both in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But if Southern trees bear strange fruit, South African ones
have something downright rotten dangling from their branches.
Broken into four movements, each involving a grisly case taken all
the way to the commission, ``Long Night's Journey Into Day'' is
about the multitude of voices articulately requesting amnesty for
human-rights crimes committed between 1960 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Each case's violators and their victims' relatives, the
supporting players and the key commission figures are interviewed.
(The actress Helen Mirren supplies the transitional narration.)
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and Reid stitch a plaintive sampler of what the
commission sees for itself and what it can only imagine. The tiers
of honesty, disgust and bottomless humanity are uncommonly moving.
Their pain is heartbreaking; their humanity the ultimate mother's
milk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Night's Journey Into Day''
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR Deborah Hoffman and Frances Reid
</P>
<P>
   RATED PG-13
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-KINGS-COMEDY-HNS     08-18 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KINGS-COMEDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `KINGS': SPIKE LEE'S EXCELLENT STAND-UP COMEDY CONCERT FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;    
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every Saturday night, you can see Steve Harvey presiding over
AmateurNight on ``Showtime at the Apollo.''
</P>
<P>
   The dreamers who emerge from backstage to perform in a
scandalous outfit or shameless weave win his disapproval. The
hyperkinetic dance troupes and near-weekly, truly soulful
renditions of ``I'm Telling You,'' ``The Rapture'' or ``I Feel Good
All Over'' leave him in awe, particularly when belted in full
gutturalness and with a soaring dismount by some white or Korean
cutie from Astoria. And should the audience have to summon the
show's dreamy muse Kiki Shepard to escort off some poor brother
trying to have a Bobby McFerrin moment, Harvey feels our pain by
mocking theirs.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Apollo'' was an entire race's ``Star Search,'' Harvey was
its Ed McMahon. As the emcee of ``The Original Kings of Comedy,''
the shrewdly executed, often hysterical Spike Lee-directed stand-up
concert film, Harvey has another set of dreamers poised to get a
piece of what Chris Rock, Chris Tucker and Dave Chapelle have.
</P>
<P>
   Between routines by D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer and
Bernie Mac, Harvey gives a few minutes of warm-up shtick, ripping
into Rae Carruth (the former member of the NFL's Carolina Panthers
who is on trial for murder), stealing a jacket from someone in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The people who've been bum-rushing sold-out stadium box offices
for the past three years know all too well who Harvey and the
comics behind the curtain are. Lee's documentary is for the
uninitiated _ for folks who didn't know there was a ``Steve Harvey
Show'' or that Mac plays Moesha's Uncle Bernie or that Hughley has
an eponymous ABC sitcom about a black family in suburban America.
Yes, it's meant as a bawdy, XXL coming-out event for anyone who
doesn't think UPN and WB spell appointment television.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has captured on digital-video, shot gymnastically by Malik
Hassan Sayeed, a thundering pair of tour dates at the Charlotte
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon used to say his show would ``reach for the stars and
catch 'em.'' Meanwhile, the self-described Kings of Comedy are
already stars in black America, but when Mac pleads for a sitcom of
his own in one of the film's addictive entr'actes, a candid envy
overwhelms his mockery. Mac performs last, as though he were the
film's secret weapon, like the other three guys he's upstaged by
Sayeed's cameras and the rhythms in Barry Alexander Brown's
cutting. Laughing at his act, though, it's evident, both to him and
to us, why he's still languishing in development hell: There is no
place on television for his blatancy.
</P>
<P>
   Looking every bit like vintage Nipsey Russell, Mac comes on as
the wry, sadistic, deprecating American id, his pop-eyes roiling,
his shtick delivered in the self-conscious cadences of the ghetto's
Mae West. He's a fascinating, vivid storyteller when you can surf
the undulations in his speech. His best bits are pointed familial
dissections, the evolution of his 20-year marriage since he became
uninterested in sex and his inheritance of a relative's children,
who seem to be the same demonic kids the late Robin Harris
inherited from his girlfriend Bebe in his stand-up act.
</P>
<P>
   They're crassly funny passages, informed, miraculously, by Mac's
tough, stubborn affection, the stuff of sitcoms not ready for prime
time. It's our loss. But not everyone's: The occasional
exasperated-looking white person seems miffed that she's not
watching the Martin Scorsese's ``King of Comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is designed to follow a path from Hughley's innocuously
charming shibboleths about cheap black people and the joys of
caller ID to Cedric's more shapeless jabs at makeover-ready people
in the audience to Mac's own blunt self-analysis. Structurally,
``Kings'' is the avuncular summer-cookout version of ``Richard
Pryor Live on the Sunset Strip,'' with Sayeed's photography finding
twice as many iconic angles as Haskell Wexler's and Harvey spitting
Pryor's image like a Halloween sight gag.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, Harvey is what Pryor would have looked like if he'd
had an interest in primping and lucidity. ``Sunset Strip'' was more
or less remade as Eddie Murphy's ``Raw.'' And Lee's film resides in
Pryor's deep, inimitable shadow. It's a thrill ride as opposed to a
seminal journey and psychological profile.
</P>
<P>
   As funny as ``Kings of Comedy'' is as a concert film, it's
wanting as documentary. Who are these guys? There's one revealing
sequence involving the potential fallout from Harvey's decision to
borrow that jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise the interludes consist of their four-way banter but
seem to have mistaken being backstage with seeing
behind-the-scenes. Lee is using the documentary format to be
hands-off, as though he'd spent all his persuasion points in the
creepy, bravura scene between George Wallace and his black
right-hand man in ``Four Little Girls.'' (The ton of cutaways,
however, to audience members convulsing with laughter is Lee having
a carnivalesque moment with our own unrestricted glee: Is that what
I look when I'm laughing at these guys?)
</P>
<P>
   But the tour's name, for instance, is a question left begging.
</P>
<P>
   The ``original'' kings of comedy? What kind of comedy? When the
tour began in '97, I thought Pryor had licked his fight with
multiple sclerosis and had hit the road with Bill Cosby and Dick
Gregory. But ``The Kings of Comedy'' is new-school product in
old-school packaging. Back in the day, Pryor was as much a king as
he was a rock star, living from a jazz musician's text. Did he fall
or was he pushed? In either scenario, the king's horses and the
king's men failed to reassemble him. Now we have a multitude of
supplicants calling themselves kings. But what kind? Which country?
</P>
<P>
   The title is merely that, but perhaps in the fiercely aggressive
way Run DMC called themselves the kings of rock in 1984. The
difference, of course, being that that group had a kingdom over
which their rule was indisputable. And the word ``new'' _ not
``black'' _ rested tacitly between the ``king'' and the ``rock.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
