A5832 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-BIGBUCKS-NNS     08-18 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BIGBUCKS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE CONVENTIONS ENDED, THE ATTACKS BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, Aug. 18, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: EMBARGOED AGAINST USE BEFORE SUNDAY 
 By J. SCOTT ORR  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Now that the last piece of confetti has fallen at
the political conventions in Philadelphia and Los Angeles, the next
downpour to hit this campaign for the White House will be a
blizzard of green.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 presidential campaign has already been the most
expensive in American history. Now, as the general election battle
is joined, special interest groups are embarking on a spending
spree of historic proportions, with much of the money expected to
fund attack advertising.
</P>
<P>
   For Republican nominee George W. Bush and his Democratic
counterpart Al Gore, the spending by national party committees and
outside groups on attack ads will be a blessing if it allows them
to avoid getting their hands dirty as the mud flies.
</P>
<P>
   Observers of campaign spending expect record outlays by groups
like the Republican National Committee, the Democratic National
Committee, the religious right, organized labor, corporate-backed
political action committees and many, many others. Much of the
money will go for so-called ``issue advocacy'' spots, the most
negative form of campaign advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from previous studies that issue ads are distinctly
more attack-oriented than any other form of political discourse,''
said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, director of the Annenberg Public
Policy Center at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing is more issue ads that attack and more of
them earlier in the campaign. Attack is emerging as the dominant
form of issue advertising,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   How much will be spent on the campaign? The public may never
know since independent expenditures are unlimited, unregulated and,
in many cases, unreported. It is clear from anecdotal evidence,
however, that the total for the 2000 election cycle will make
spending on all previous races look like chump change.
</P>
<P>
   We know that Bush and Gore can spend only the $67.6 million they
each received in public financing. That is in addition to the $81
million already spent by Bush and the $42 million spent by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures will be dwarfed, however, by the investments of
others. The DNC and the RNC are sitting on campaign war chests
totaling more than $250 million. Add to that hundreds of millions
in unregulated spending by special interest groups and the total
could easily top $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by the Annenberg Center, at least $114
million had been spent on ``issue advocacy advertising'' by last
March. But since special interest groups were not required to
divulge spending on issue advertising, that figure ``represents a
fraction of the total expenditures expected for the cycle,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the current system argue that the Supreme Court
was clear in its 1996 decision that such spending by individuals
and groups is constitutionally protected political speech. Banning
issue advocacy, they say, will limit free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few nonprofit groups will want to risk their tax-exempt status
or incur legal expenses to engage in speech that could be
interpreted by the Federal Election Commission to have an influence
on the outcome of an election,'' said Laura W. Murphy, director of
the Washington office of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   She told Congress recently that attempts to limit issue advocacy
will ``create burdensome laws that will abridge the very speech
that the First Amendment was designed to protect -- political
speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Issue advocacy advertising cannot expressly advocate the
election or defeat of particular candidates, but it can praise or,
as is usually the case, attack candidates by name.
</P>
<P>
   The ads typically are narrow in focus -- they may support
prescription drug benefits or oppose gun control for example -- and
they are exempt from Federal Election Commission reporting
requirements under the 1996 Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this month, however, spending on issue ads by
tax-exempt groups will have to be reported to the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Called 527 groups after the section of the Internal Revenue Code
that gives them tax exemptions, these former ``stealth groups''
will be required to file monthly or quarterly reports outlining
their contributors and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Thousand of groups -- including state and local political
organizations, political action committees, unions and others --
met the Aug. 1 deadline to identify themselves to the IRS and state
the purpose of their planned spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there are thousands of groups that have been
identified to the IRS and therefore to the public is encouraging,''
said Marianne Holt, senior associate with the campaign finance
watch dog group the Center for Public Integrity.
</P>
<P>
   She cautioned, however, that this disclosure may not necessarily
make it clear to the public exactly what goals the groups are
pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of this law is to help people recognize the true
identity of groups that are using pseudonyms to shield themselves,
but groups can easily be misleading on their forms in the statement
of their purpose,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   One 527 group, called Republicans for Clean Air, drew fire from
Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) when it spent $2.5 million attacking
McCain's environmental record in advance of the March 7 Super
Tuesday primaries. Bush denied any connection to the group even
though it was organized and funded by two of his long-time
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing with the IRS, the group identified its purpose as
``raising public awareness about the threat of air pollution,
especially from the nation's coal-burning electric power plants.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Citizens for Better Medicare, identified as a 527 group, has
been running issue advertisements against drug price controls for
the elderly for months, according to the Center for Public
Integrity. The group, which is funded largely by drug
manufacturers, plans to spend $50 million on ads this year.
</P>
<P>
   The group's statement to the IRS is vague about its purpose,
however, saying that it is ``engaging in an issue advocacy and
grass-roots lobbying program that will raise public consciousness
about the importance of the social, economic and political values
it favors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for consumers of these messages to know who is
sponsoring them,'' said Lorie Slass, of the Annenberg Center. ``If
a group is called Citizens for Better Medicare, people should know
that it is funded by the pharmaceutical industry and what their
agenda is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore or George W. Bush, or the Democratic or Republican
party is identified with a message, people process it differently
than if it comes from a group with a name like, say, Citizens for a
Better World or Americans for a Sound Economy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By law, issue advertisements cannot be run in coordination with
political campaigns, but they do offer a convenient shelter for
candidates who don't want to be seen as slinging the mud
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's kind of a good cop, bad cop relationship here,'' said
Holt. ``The interest group does the dirty work, while the candidate
can continue to be the good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore are calling for a clean campaign and neither
has been particularly harsh in attacking the other so far. Still,
they are no doubt mindful that the attack money is out there.
</P>
<P>
   For the record: Gore supports campaign finance reform
legislation that would rid elections of soft money including issue
advertising while Bush supports banning only soft money from unions
and corporations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
