<SLUG> BC-THESTREETCOM-EUROPE-CONVERGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS SEEK CONVERGENCE PLAYS IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Financial Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from TheStreet.com, the
premier business/finance Web site, is available from the New York
Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DAVID KURAPKA  
 c.2000 TheStreet.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Convergence is a word that may evoke New Age images of modern
shamans reading crystals during planetary alignments. But for
international investors, convergence more prosaically refers to a
shrewd investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, it most commonly refers to nations joining the
European Union or the European Monetary Union. Countries making
that move have to meet a number of policy requirements that
``converge'' with the norms of the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For example, countries wanting to adopt Europe's single
currency, the euro, are expected to have inflation rates below 2.5
percent, public debt of less than 60 percent of gross domestic
product, and budget deficits below 3 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
   Those are pretty strict targets, stricter than the measures the
countries must first adopt to join the European Union before
entering the monetary union. Part of the controversy surrounding
the euro has been the lack of flexibility it gives individual
countries to pursue their own economic goals.
</P>
<P>
   But for investors, such policies translate into sound economic
conditions, lower interest rates, more investable companies
(particularly as nations privatize state-owned enterprises) and
considerable market rallies. Italy, Spain, Portugal and Greece all
experienced strong stock-market performance leading up their
respective entries into the EU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countries [entering the EU] have a very solid set of
guardrails guiding their economic policies,'' says Steven
Schoenfeld, head of international equity strategies at Barclays
Global Investors.
</P>
<P>
   A kind of ``virtuous cycle'' is formed, says Schoenfeld.
Countries are invited to join because they look like they are
already pursuing sound policies. Those policies are cemented by the
process involved in joining either the EU or the currency. They
become more attractive places to invest because many investors pay
closer attention to a country once it moves from being an emerging
economy to being part of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The key, then, as seen in the Italy-Spain-Portugal-Greece
experience, is to get in early.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just interesting history. The potential for another
convergence rally exists now, as a total of 13 nations have been
invited by the EU to apply for membership. Cyprus, the Czech
Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Poland and Slovenia were invited in
1997, while the EU made the same offer to Bulgaria, Lithuania,
Latvia, Malta, Romania, Slovakia and Turkey last December.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to hear a lot more about ``convergence plays'' in these
countries. However, potential rallies are not clear-cut. Some of
these nations won't make it into the EU for years, and some don't
offer investors much anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The countries that are now up for membership, even if they meet
the economic requirements, may run into political problems. Most in
this batch are from Eastern or Central Europe, and the rest of the
EU, which must ultimately approve the entry, may balk at some to
avoid angering the Russians. Cultural differences may delay Muslim
Turkey's entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``To buy to expect a rally like you saw in Italy, Portugal,
Spain and Greece when they joined is a mistake,'' says David
Aserkoff, an Eastern and Central European strategist for Credit
Suisse First Boston based in London.
</P>
<P>
   Aserkoff believes the prospects for convergence rallies are out
there, but are still several years off. ``Four years ago, I said [a
convergence play] would be within five years and I'm still saying
that,'' he says. ``It's always five years away.''
</P>
<P>
   Barclays' Schoenfeld thinks that Poland and Hungary are the most
attractive countries now. Aserkoff thinks Turkey will make for an
interesting opportunity over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investors have numerous choices to invest in Central and
Eastern Europe. There are several closed-end funds. The Central
European Equity Fund (CEE on the new York Stock Exchange) has 23
percent of its portfolio in Hungary, 22 percent in Poland and 7
percent in the Czech Republic. The Central European Value Fund (CRF
on the New York exchange) has 20 percent in Poland and 16 percent
in the Czech Republic. The Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Eastern
Europe Fund (RNE on the New York exchange) has 39 percent in Russia
(not likely to join the EU soon), 21 percent in Poland and 14
percent in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Turkish Investment Fund (TKF on the New York
exchange) invests solely in Turkey. Meanwhile, Barclays is planning
to offer a Greek exchange-traded fund later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the convergence play happens or not, ``there are plenty
of other good reasons to buy these stock markets,'' Aserkoff says,
pointing to good companies at good prices. In addition, the
policies the countries pursue to enter the EU improve market
conditions even if actual entry is far away.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they may converge, without converging. Sounds
downright New Age-y.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (David Kurapka is a senior writer for TheStreet.com. In keeping
with TSC's editorial policy, he does not own shares in any
companies or mutual funds mentioned in this column. He also doesn't
invest in hedge funds or other private investment partnerships. He
welcomes your feedback at dkurapka(at)thestreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Distributed by New York Times Special Features
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
