<HEADER>
A5847 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-GARDENCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-18 2058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-GARDENCOLUMN
 &HT;      SUMMER IS TOUGH ON AREA LAWNS 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    BY KATHY HUBER
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We returned from vacation to find dead areas in our lawn.
Chinch bugs? How should we treat these areas? _ T.K., Houston,
Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: We, too, returned after three vacation weeks to find the
lawns in our neighborhood drought-damaged and stricken with various
pests _ a summer form of brown patch; take-all patch; chinch bugs;
and sod webworms. And it is often difficult to distinguish one
problem from the next, so if you're not sure, seek the help of a
certified nursery professional or lawn expert.
</P>
<P>
   According to these professionals, chinch bugs have wreaked havoc
on lawns. The first signs of these pests are irregular patches of
dead or stunted grass that are surrounded by a ``halo'' of
yellowing and dying grass. These patches of dying grass, often
found in the hottest, driest areas of the lawn, such as those near
the drive or sidewalk, expand and merge as the pest population
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Before you treat, make a positive identification that chinch
bugs are your problem. The damage these insects cause looks like
drought damage _ irregular brown, dead areas _ so look for the
pests in the yellowing areas (not the dead areas) before treatment.
Chinch bugs are only about [-inch to 1/5-inch long and have black
bodies and white wings with black triangular markings. The
beneficial big-eyed bug resembles the enemy, but, of course, has
big eyes. If you don't see the chinch bugs near the soil surface,
push a bottomless can several inches into the ground in an area
where the grass is turning yellow. Fill the can with water, wait
several minutes and any bugs will float to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Chinch-bug damage also can resemble brown patch symptoms. The
difference: Brown patch, a fungal disease, usually creates circular
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Proper lawn care can go a long way in discouraging chinch bugs.
Irrigate sunny areas that quickly become hot and dry. Sufficient
moisture can suppress chinch bugs. Mow at proper heights. Avoid
thatch buildup _ a haven for chinch bugs. If chinch bug populations
become a real threat to the lawn, apply an appropriate insecticide.
But don't overdo it because such treatments often wipe out
beneficial insects and those organisms that decompose thatch.
`Floratam' is one St. Augustine variety that is touted as resistant
to chinch bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Sod webworms create patches of chewed blades. If they are
present, you may notice webbing in affected areas in the early
morning. The worms are the night-feeding larvae of a white to gray
moth that deposits her eggs on the lawn in late afternoon or early
evening. During the day, the worms burrow into the turf and the
layer of thatch. To discourage, rake up dead grass and thatch.
After the next mowing, rake again. New, green blades may reappear,
especially in well-maintained lawns.
</P>
<P>
   To test for sod webworms, soak an area of the lawn with a highly
diluted soap solution. The webworms should rise to the surface. If
you're still not sure, ask your nurseryman for pest identification.
Beneficial nematodes and Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt) are weapons
against this pest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you make some suggestions for low-maintenance plants _
medium-size shrubs, vines and small trees _ to be planted around a
small patio that is nestled between two three-story townhouse
buildings? The bed will get about 3{-4 hours of daily sunlight. _
S.B., Houston, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Ornamental trees to consider for your patio include the
Chinese fringe tree (Chionanthus retusas), a beautiful spring
bloomer that produces showy, 4-inch flower clusters and matures to
15 to 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican plum (Prunus mexicana) is a 15- to 35-foot,
drought-tolerant native that also tolerates clay soil and will give
you fragrant white blooms in early spring that will fade to pale
pink and small purple plums for the birds or for jelly. Its trunk
bark ages to a blue-gray.
</P>
<P>
   The gumbo-tolerant parsley hawthorn (Crataegus Marshallii) has
white spring flowers, parsley-shaped bright green foliage and fall
color. The Texas redbud (Cercis canadensis var. texensis) is a
drought-tolerant native that provides masses of tiny rose-pink
blooms in early spring. The foliage is glossy and rounder than that
of other redbuds.
</P>
<P>
   Medium-sized shrubs you might consider include Gardenia
jasminoides `Veitchii,' a 3- to 4-foot compact shrub with 1- to
2-inch fragrant white blooms. Give these good drainage and an
organically enriched soil. Abelia grandiflor `Francis Mason' (or
other lower-growing abelias) matures to a height of about 4 feet.
This evergreen shrub has graceful, arching branches with dense,
glossy foliage that is bronze when new. Leaves become dark green,
then bronze again in the fall. The delicate, bell-shaped,
pinkish-white blooms appear late spring to fall. Abelia tolerates
partial sun and is drought-resistant but likes water when the soil
is dry.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese mahonia (Mahonia fortunei) is an attractive evergreen
good for shade or filtered sunlight. The yellow flowers are
followed by blue berries that are food for the birds. The
pest-resistant Chinese mahonia likes an organically enriched soil
that drains well. Mature height is about 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A grouping of dwarf nandinas is a possibility, as is dwarf
yaupon (Ilex vomitora `Nana'), a dense 1- to 2-foot mound of small,
dark foliage. Plumbago produces a 4-foot cloud of phloxlike blue
(or white) flowers for months each year.
</P>
<P>
   I like to use Dietes bicolor and Dietes vegata for their
evergreen clumps of swordlike foliage and beautiful flowers. D.
bicolor, sometimes called African iris, produces 2-inch pale yellow
blooms with maroon-chocolate patches. D. vegata, or butterfly iris,
produces slightly larger white flowers with blue markings. These
plants are easy and rewarding. I'd try to work some gingers, rain
lilies and leopard plants (Ligularia) into the small garden as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Vines for the patio garden include butterfly vine (Mascagnia
macroptera), which produces yellow blooms followed by chartreuse
seed pods that turn a golden brown and resemble butterflies, and
black-eyed Susan vine (Thunbergia alata), which produces yellow,
orange or cream blooms, often with a contrasting eye.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the spring, I purchased a candlestick tree and planted it
in a large pot. It was about 5 feet tall and now is 10-12 feet
tall. It has not bushed out at all. Is it supposed to bush out? _
M.A.P., Montgomery, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Usually, candlestick trees bush out, and width can equal
height. Gardeners prune plants hard in early spring to encourage
branching, and they tip-prune during the growing season to
encourage a bushy habit. Gardeners tip-prune young plants, too. If
you're willing to wait a little on the flowering, you could cut
your stalky plant back about a third, and perhaps it would branch
some and then flower.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently moved to Friendswood, and the lawn is going to
need a lot of work. Could you tell me if zoysia would be good for
this area? _ G.P., Friendswood, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, zoysia should do fine, but I would research this
turfgrass before planting. Zoysia is a warm-season grass that is a
slow grower, but once established it provides a beautiful, dense
lawn. It is touted as drought-tolerant, browning with a lack of
moisture but responding well when irrigated. This grass will also
brown with a hard frost, but it greens early in spring. Zoysia is
said to be tolerant of various soils, but it needs good drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Zoysia does best with frequent, close mowing and moderate
nitrogen fertilization. Watch thatch buildup. Late spring and early
summer are ideal times to sprig, plug or sod with zoysia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My morning glories won't bloom. Any suggestions? _ F.S.,
Houston, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: It is possible your morning glories have received an
abundance of nitrogen (perhaps picked up when you fertilized the
lawn) and have put on a lot of growth at the expense of flowers.
Morning glories bloom best in full sun and in a soil that's not
overly rich in nitrogen and that is on the dry side. Perhaps yours
will come around. Sometimes they flower best in late summer, so
there's a good chance yours will still bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I moved to a new home, and I am finding so many unknown
treasures in my yard. I am enclosing a few pictures to see if you
can identify two plants. The first grows on bamboolike stalks, has
leaves with velvety undersides and red with yellow blooms. The
second plant is invasive and grows rapidly. The flower is like an
unopened hollyhock or single hibiscus. _ J.J.M, Houston, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The first plant is a spiral ginger, so called because the
foliage of so many in the genus Costus spiral around their reedlike
stems. The red cones are beautiful in the garden and in indoor
arrangements. The second plant is a member of the mallow family, as
is the hibiscus. It is a turk's cap, Malvaviscus drummondii. This
perennial is native to our state as well as other Gulf Coast
states. It may reach 3 feet in height or tower above 8 feet,
usually dying back in winter but regrowing come spring. It will
colonize by self-layering. Turk's-cap produces bright red blooms
summer and fall and is a favorite with hummingbirds and
butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   To K.B.: Thanks for the dahlia update.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw tomato plants in a nursery this week. Can we plant them
now? _ D.W., Houston, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, some gardeners do grow a fall crop. To do so, plant in
the second half of July and into August. Hurry. Plant sturdy, dark
green transplants in a sunny spot and in an organically enriched,
well-draining soil. Plant deeper than originally grown to encourage
development of a strong root system that will in turn encourage
good production.
</P>
<P>
   As the plants become established, water deeply. Mulch with
organic material such as compost or leaves. This helps retain soil
moisture and keep weeds down. Tomatoes are heavy feeders. In
addition to enriching the soil with organic matter prior to
planting, periodic applications of fertilizer are needed for
maximum yields.
</P>
<P>
   Cage your tomato plants just after transplanting to keep them
off the ground and away from damage and disease as they grow.
Should an early fall freeze threaten, wrap the cages with row cover
or a sheet to create a greenhouse for each plant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the back corner of my son's garden, we found a small tree
loaded with green fruit that looked like apples, but we were not
aware that apples grow in Houston. However, that's what they are,
and they are very tasty. My son has decided they are `Golden
Delicious,' but we read that those trees require something like 140
days of temperatures below 45 degrees, not likely in Houston. I am
enclosing a small branch of the tree in hopes that you can help us
identify it and give us some information on apples. _ B.C.,
Houston, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm afraid I can't identify your apple by the foliage, so I
would suggest you call the Harris County Extension Service,
281-855-5600, and ask for help. Perhaps an agent can identify the
variety, especially if you're able to take him or her a fruit. The
extension service also can give you publications on growing apples
in our area.
</P>
<P>
   `Golden Delicious' needs 700 to 800 chilling hours for good
flower development, so while it may do fine in the upper regions of
Texas, it is not the best choice along the Gulf Coast. Houston
receives 600 or fewer chilling hours, those times when the
temperature is in the 32- to 45-degree range. Apple varieties
suitable for our area include `Anna,' which requires 100 to 300
chilling hours, and `Dorsett Golden,' which needs only 100 to 200.
Both of these will produce a little fruit without
cross-pollination, but it is recommended that gardeners plant both
varieties since they flower at the same time and will increase
production through cross-pollination.
</P>
<P>
   Well-maintained apple trees can set more fruit than the trees
can support. Such excess can result in broken branches, stunting
and alternate bearing, that is, bearing every other year. To
prevent the problem, thin young apples when they are about the size
of marbles. Remove all but one apple per cluster.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Huber is the Houston Chronicle Garden Editor.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
