<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN PARENT COMPANY LAIDLAW WOULD CONSIDER SELLING GREYHOUND
LINES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dallas-based Greyhound Lines, the nation's
largest bus company, is again facing a financial crunch, but not
because its venerable business is declining.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the trouble stems from Greyhound's parent company,
Laidlaw, a Canadian firm that has stumbled under a big debt load
and some failed investments.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Laidlaw's chief executive, John
Grainger, said he hopes to restructure Laidlaw around its core
transportation business, with Greyhound playing a key part in that
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not rule out the sale of the bus company.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into the straits we're in, any reasonable offer I
guess would have to be considered, wouldn't it?'' Grainger said.
``But that is not our plan at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Grainger elaborated on his position in a second conversation,
emphasizing that Laidlaw is not actively seeking a buyer for
Greyhound.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company is not for sale,'' he said. ``If someone made an
unsolicited offer, yes, I would have to consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw has been under pressure this year as its stock price
plunged and its losses soared. Last month, as it worked on a plan
to deal with creditors, the company hired a turnaround specialist
and gave him the title of ``chief restructuring officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw's stock, which traded at more than $14 a share two years
ago, closed Thursday at 51 cents, down a penny. The company lost
nearly $2 billion for the nine months ended in May.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, Laidlaw has not made interest payments on more than
$3 billion in debt, and this month it cut off financial support of
its Greyhound subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Greyhound disclosed this week that it is seeking outside
financing to cover capital expenses, such as new buses, and the
cash shortfalls that strike during seasonal slowdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Laidlaw had provided the funds for those purposes,
Grainger said. But now Greyhound is on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can stand alone if they have to,'' Grainger said, noting
that Greyhound was self-financed before Laidlaw acquired the firm
for about $800 million in March 1999. ``It's actually a positive
story. It presents an opportunity for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to owning Greyhound, Laidlaw is the largest provider
of school bus service in North America. It operates an ambulance
service, which it is trying to unload; and it holds 44 percent of
Safety-Kleen Corp., an industrial waste recycler that filed for
bankruptcy protection in June.
</P>
<P>
   In a securities filing this week, Greyhound said there was no
assurance that it would secure financing. The company said it ``may
not be able to continue to operate as a going concern'' if
alternate funding sources could not be found.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman said the warning was made several weeks ago,
when the process was in its early stages.
</P>
<P>
   She said company executives are now in ``substantial talks''
with prospective lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will find the funding,'' said Kristin Parsley, a Greyhound
spokeswoman. ``We just need it before the down periods in winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the financial squeeze is surfacing at a time when
the bus company is enjoying its best prospects in years.
</P>
<P>
   Greyhound, which serves 3,700 destinations in the United States
and Canada, struggled for most of the '90s. It reorganized under
bankruptcy protection at the beginning of the decade and faced
insolvency a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   But a new management team began to turn around the operation in
the mid-'90s. In '98, Greyhound reported a net profit of $35
million.
</P>
<P>
   It slipped back into the red last year, primarily because it
paid $21 million in stock options as part of the Laidlaw sale.
</P>
<P>
   But Greyhound's financial position has grown stronger under
Laidlaw, an analyst said. It spent nearly $80 million last year on
new buses, real estate and facility improvements. And having
Laidlaw as its parent let it cut its insurance and security
deposits by nearly $46 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended in June, Greyhound's operating income
nearly doubled to $16.7 million and its revenue increased 13
percent to $258.8 million. Summer traffic remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually had our most successful July 4 period in company
history,'' Parsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Velgot, an analyst at Tejas Securities Group in Austin,
said he believes that Greyhound will raise the funds it needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had financing before Laidlaw and now they're even
stronger,'' Velgot said. ``I don't think they're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those situations where the trouble is really at
the holding company level, not at the core operations.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
