<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5852 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      08-18 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DECISION TIME COMING FOR THE COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENT ZWERNEMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ While the entrenched veteran Cowboys are
winding down after a month of training camp, most of the rookies
and ``bubble'' players are wound tighter than ever, as if their
professional lives depend on the next week.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, they do.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas will trim its roster from 88 to 65 Tuesday, and narrow
the squad to a final 53 five days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine how the younger players (feel), knowing
they're going to cut this group down,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones
said. ``But they wouldn't be going through this if they didn't want
to be on the Dallas Cowboys or in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, here's a glance at the team by position, and
who needs a big showing starting 8 p.m. Saturday at Denver:
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback: Rookie long shot Clint Stoerner completed 8-of-12
passes last Sunday against Oakland, strengthening his chance to
step in first after starter Troy Aikman against the Broncos.
Meanwhile, Paul Justin's best chances of being the No. 3 appear to
be behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Running back: Michael Wylie (3.7 yards per carry), Troy Hambrick
(3.4) and Michael Black all have played decently in camp and in the
preseason, but the Cowboys can't keep all three. Hambrick should
stick because he can play fullback or tailback. Wylie is versatile
enough to play in the slot at receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver: San Antonio's Wane McGarity has finished strong at
camp, if not in preseason games. Should Dallas keep six receivers,
an unlikely scenario, look for Alice's Chris Brazzell to stick
after a hot-and-cold camp.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end: The Cowboys continue searching for a blocker _ the
candidates are recent addition Lawrence Hart, Rickey Brady and Tyji
Armstrong _ who also can play in three-tight end sets with David
LaFleur and Jackie Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line: Things are much clearer with Erik Williams
finally in house after his vacation from camp. While Solomon Page
is the right tackle of the future, the line is much stronger for
now with him at right guard. That means Jorge Diaz, who started the
past four seasons at Tampa Bay, is now a capable backup. Many of
the reserve offensive linemen are banged up, making it hard for
coaches to evaluate them.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line: Brandon Noble has seemed a little more polished
than Michael Myers in the preseason, and has had a hand in more big
plays _ literally. Noble blocked a Sebastian Janikowski field-goal
attempt Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker: Darren Hambrick took it personally when the Cowboys
signed Joe Bowden to compete on the strong side, and has responded
with a good camp. How deep is this position when Bowden and Barron
Wortham, starters for the AFC-champion Tennessee Titans last
season, may be backups? Corey Atkins, Orantes Grant (despite a
great camp) and Brandon Tolbert are on the outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback: Kareem Larrimore, a rookie from West Texas A&AMP;M,
played decently Sunday in his first start in Kevin Smith's absence.
Coach Dave Campo is quick to remind that veterans Charlie Williams
and Duane Hawthorne, both hampered by injury during camp, will be
available. Second-round pick Dwayne Goodrich is a bust until he
proves otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Safety: In every preseason Cowboys game, free-wheeling free
safety Jason Kaiser seems to be in on multiple plays. But he may be
a victim of numbers, as coaches are counting on a healthy Izell
Reese to plug in for hard-hitting George Teague.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams: Rookie Tim Seder is now the lone kicker. No
pressure, right? Wrong. Now all he's got to do is make all his
kicks, so the Cowboys don't rush in a veteran. Micah Knorr, who's
handling kickoffs and punting, about has that job wrapped up over
Barry Cantrell, who's been hurt. Darran Hall has at times looked
exceptional returning kicks, but so did Jason Tucker last year. And
Tucker, who's been injured, is a much better receiver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
