<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURING THE BLAHS OF AUGUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 20)  
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geography can play a big role in the August psyche of a
gardener. In my travels at this time of year _ through northern New
England, around Minneapolis and in the San Francisco Bay area _ I
have consistently met gardeners who are proud to display their
colorful borders.
</P>
<P>
   This is in marked contrast to where I live. In the humid,
insect-prone mid-Atlantic region, August gardens tend to be
worn-out disasters. I've yet to encounter anyone here saying, ``You
must see my August garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, I've been voicing a modified version of that
sentiment, thanks to a wonderful, carefree group of plants. Holding
back their flower power until this listless month, their freshness,
in whites, pinks, yellows and blues, creates a joyful sight in
drooping, mildewed borders.
</P>
<P>
   Several sweet pepperbushes (Clethra alnifolia) start the month
with an intoxicating oomph. Their panicles _ 2 to 4 inches, in
light to white pink _ emit a lush fragrance that permeates muggy
humidity. Those in sun start their bloom period of two to three
weeks in early August, and those in shade a week later. A dwarf
form, Hummingbird, is only 3 feet high, and the species plant tops
out at 6 to 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The cheerful golden yellow flowers of brown-eyed Susans
(Rudbeckia triloba) usually open the first week of August. This
little known, 3- to 3 1/2-foot biennial cousin of the popular
black-eyed Susan resists mildew and thrives in full sun to part
shade. Its numerous branches, jutting out from the sturdy main
stem, are dotted with 1-to2-inch flowers for more than six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the quiet of deep shade, the soft yellow, 2-inch dangling
flowers of wax-bells (Kirengeshoma palmata) usually open in
mid-August and hold for almost a month. The maplelike leaves on
this 3- to 4-foot perennial contrast handsomely with hosta foliage.
</P>
<P>
   Three tried and true hostas are flowering stalwarts in my August
borders: H. lancifolia, H. plantaginea and H. Royal Standard.
</P>
<P>
   Lancifolia has slim, dark green leaves that are only 5 by 2
inches. The abundant flowers are a rich bluish purple, last three
to five weeks, and float 12 inches above neat mounds that are about
36 inches wide and 18 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   Plantaginea is an old-fashioned hosta treasured for its
fragrant, gleaming white flowers. These bloom for more than three
weeks and are lovely in arrangements. The warm green heart-shaped
leaves measure about five by seven inches and form mounds similar
in size to those of lance lily.
</P>
<P>
   Closely related, Royal Standard differs significantly in that it
thrives in full sun as well as shade. It's a much bolder plant,
too, with densely packed upright leaves that form large clumps two
feet tall. While the flowers are not as fragrant as plantaginea's,
their bloom period is one or two weeks longer.
</P>
<P>
   The elegant pink buds, flowers and seed capsules of hardy
begonia (B. grandis subsp. evansiana) start their eight-week color
presence in early August. Technically a tuber but generally sold as
a perennial because it is hardy to Zone 6, hardy begonia looks like
an angel wing begonia. Two to 3 feet tall, it has large leaves with
soft red undercoats.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic chives (Allium tuberosum) are usually found in vegetable
beds. I've sprinkled them about my sunny flower borders, where they
bloom for three weeks in August. They are 2 to 3 feet tall and
feature white umbrella-shaped flowers heads that crown slim stems.
And yes, you can use the ribbonlike foliage as a mild food
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   The September Charm anemone hybrid, despite its name, blooms
throughout most of August in my garden. Its lovely lavender pink
flowers bob about in sunny areas on slim 3-foot stems.
</P>
<P>
   Two other perennials' bloom period of six weeks or longer starts
in mid-August, adding elegant coolness to sunny and partly shaded
areas.
</P>
<P>
   One _ hardy ageratum (Eupatorium coelestinum) _ is covered with
blue flowers that to a nonscientific eye look the same as those on
the annual ageratum. The fuzzy swaths of blue, crowning stems of
one to three feet, are smashing. Be warned that this is an
aggressive spreader. But I resist yanking it all out in early
spring because of its beautiful August presence.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is what many view as the piece de resistance in
August gardens: Lobelia Ruby Slippers. This magnificent hybrid was
created by the North Carolina breeder Thurman Maness 15 years ago
and has gone on to win fame and fans across the country. Its
luscious wine red petals cluster on imposing spikes 4 to 5 feet
tall and thrive on side shoots after the spikes are cut.
</P>
<P>
   All these newly opening flowers soothe my psyche in this hot,
humid month. They may do the same for yours.
</P>
<P>
   Bluestone Perennials, 7211 Middle Ridge Rd., Madison, OH 44057;
(800) 852-5243; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Forestfarm, 990 Tetherow Rd., Williams, OR 97544; (541)
846-7269; catalog, $4.
</P>
<P>
   We-Du Nurseries, Route 5, Box 724, Marion, NC 28752-9338; (828)
738-8300; catalog, $2.
</P>
<P>
   Willow Pond Nursery, P.O. Box 192, Hewlett, NY 11557; (516)
374-2522; catalog, $2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
