<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-RAZOR-SCOOTERS-ART-$A     08-18 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAZOR-SCOOTERS-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDING A FAD, AND HITTING A BUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 20) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN LELAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The maitre d'hotel at Coup, a swanky New American
restaurant in the East Village, smiled as he fingered the coat
check. Coup is a place of daring high-modern style, and one can
only imagine what finery has passed through its coat room. Yet even
so, this article cut a figure: sleek of line, cutting edge in
design, of the moment and yet blue-collar practical. ``I'm so glad
you had this ticket,'' he said with a smile, ``to distinguish it
from all the others back there.'' He handed over my scooter, and I
rode off into the night.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to travel everywhere for one week on these two
resin wheels, testing whether the stylish new scooters are a viable
alternative to cabs and hoofing. Since arriving from Hong Kong at
Christmas, the chrome Razor scooters, which go for about $100 a
pop, have been selling out at both Toys ``R'' Us and the Sharper
Image, appealing equally to superannuated kids and to the regular
kind. With a handful of other manufacturers and distributors
jumping on the Razorwagon, the devices have become a new form of
transit for the masses. When historians recount New York's summer
of 2000, they will tell of plaster cows and of grown professionals
on little chrome scooters, a confluence of cutesy infantilism that
made even the political conventions seem grown up.
</P>
<P>
   But on to the road test. As a mode of transportation, sadly, the
scooter proved the stiletto heel of the two-wheeled set: great to
look at, lousy for carrying laundry to the dry cleaner. Do not be
seduced, as I was, by images of dapper men and women in graceful
glide, cool breezes slicing through the hot city. Scootering is
work, especially at rush hour. The small wheels bog down on the
city's rough surfaces, and the base rides so low that a bump of any
size becomes a potential obstacle. By the time I reached the office
my first morning, a 40-block ride, I was drenched in perspiration,
my knee was bruised from a near tumble and my hands ached as if I'd
been working a jackhammer.
</P>
<P>
   These things I learned: cracks and seams in the sidewalk are not
the scooterist's friend, a polite ``excuse me'' cuts you only so
much slack and the scooterist's code is a subtle one. One
afternoon, as I passed a fellow rider somewhat my junior _ by, say,
about 30 years _ I threw him a fraternal salute. The boy stared
back blankly and whizzed by. This, I figured, is the code of the
road, at least when some crazy adult lets go of his handgrip,
posing a threat to self and all around.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as I glided down Murray Hill, on Manhattan's East Side,
weaving perilously among the scaffolds, I felt part of a new urban
tribe, joined by our insouciant disregard for the slow pace of
pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune magazine reported last month that the Amish have taken
to these new nonmotorized scooters for small errands, but while
they may be an appealing alternative to buggies on the Pennsylvania
Dutch back roads, the city scooter is a thing of freedom and menace
all its own. Ours is a hardened attitude that says, ``I know it's
raining, but I can't hold an umbrella and manage my scooter at the
same time.'' Or perhaps just, ``Yes, I am insured.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the pavement-bound, they mostly didn't get it.
Construction guys asked for a lift; others shot dirty looks,
rightly fearing for their ankles.
</P>
<P>
   When I did impress a couple of gym bunnies on Eighth Avenue with
my lapidary roll, they simply parked themselves in my path,
astounded that they had just read ``a whole article'' about these
gizmos in a men's fashion magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Now get out of my way. Sic transit Razor.
</P>
<P>
   I also learned that, contrary to what you might think, it is
actually the stationary leg, not the pushing one, that gets the
more rigorous workout. Or rather, the gluteal muscles attached to
that leg. If you aren't careful to switch legs from time to time,
you might find that your seated position begins to lean to the left
or right, poor form in most any occupation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, once you get the hang of it, there is real
fetishistic satisfaction in unfolding the finely machined frame _
every bar and bolt sliding silently into place _ and in breaking it
down again before entering the Metropolitan Museum or your local
noodle house. For those of us who have never had call to assemble a
high-powered weapon in a James Bond movie, this seems the next best
thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, steady rains and the scooter-related return of an
old repetitive-strain injury cut my experiment short. It was a
relief to rejoin the slow-moving ranks of the asphalt-bound. As a
trend, scootermania properly belongs in the category of irrational
mob behavior, like soccer rioting or Capri pants: one person starts
shouting something, an alpha male does this or that and before you
know it, everybody is on scooters. I was ready to get off the
razor's edge.
</P>
<P>
   But before I pass my scooter along to my 12-year-old son, there
are still a few New York environs I'd like to try on wheels. Right
now I'm weighing the ``1900'' exhibition at the Guggenheim. See you
there, and stay out of my path.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
