<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5860 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-BLUE-POWER-DRESSING-$     08-18 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-POWER-DRESSING-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS, MEET THE BLUE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 20)  
 By RUTH LA FERLA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looked like an instance of fashion by fiat. When she strolled
out in front of the cameras at the Democratic National Convention
on Thursday night, Tipper Gore was sheathed in blue, her lustrous
coat by Ellen Tracy lending her an aura of beatitude. Gore was just
the last of the candidates' wives who arrived for their respective
spotlight moments decked out in tints of blue like so many blossoms
in a Victorian nosegay.
</P>
<P>
   There was Hillary Rodham Clinton, wearing not her customary
neutral trouser suit, but a matching skirt and jacket of the purest
cornflower blue. Onstage, before taking the podium, she received a
group hug from a flock of women, most of them suited in blue. Next
was Hadassah Lieberman, who played to the crowd in a suit whose
hyacinth hue looked freshly plucked from a suburban garden.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Gore took center stage, embracing her blue-clad
daughter Karenna, one could not help but wonder. In politics, where
no gesture can be counted as spontaneous, this ubiquitous blue suit
looked contrived, a result of canny image coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Those acquainted with the closets of the candidates' wives deny
anyone acted in concert, but concede that blue, often considered
safe and dull, was indeed the most popular choice for women on the
convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue, I can't imagine a better choice,'' mused Bonnie McNies,
an image consultant, who used to advise Gore as a senator's wife.
McNies trilled a hymn to the Democratic ladies' color of choice.
``Blue is soothing but powerful,'' she said. ``It's smart, but not
trendy like black. It suggests harmony among team players. It
suggests unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is certainly savvy about the associative powers of
color, especially the power of certain colors to flatter or disarm.
Robin Givhan, a former style reporter for The Washington Post, who
is now at Vogue, suggested the first lady might lately have adopted
blue along with skirts both to soften her image and to define it
more sharply. ``Everyone assigns a color to recent first ladies,''
Givhan noted. ``Nancy Reagan had red. Barbara had cadet blue. But
Hillary never had a color.''
</P>
<P>
   In the collective consciousness, blue is often the color of
clarity, piety and goodness (think of a Swiss mountain lake or a
Raphael Madonna). To some minds, blue also conveys true love and
fidelity. And sure enough, Gore treated audiences on Thursday night
to a vintage snapshot of herself hanging laundry in front of her
trailer home, garbed in _ what else? _ a housedress of faded blue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore underscored the meaning of true blue by introducing her
husband simply as ``the man I love and have loved for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that week, Lieberman, wore blue as she introduced her
husband as ``the love of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Did any or all of them choose blue to make a political
statement?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said Camille Johnston, Gore's press secretary.
``There is no consensus-building around wardrobe here.'' So, as
fashion people are so fond of saying, maybe it's just something in
the air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
