<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPGROUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS IN THE CARDS FOR TEEN MUSIC GROUP 3 OF HEARTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURST, Texas _ While most girls their age spent their summer
vacations dancing at teen clubs, Blaire Stroud, Katie McNeill and
Deserea Wasdin were taking dance lessons from Toni Basil _ you
know, the girl who did that ``Mickey'' song in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   While their friends were hanging at the mall, these three were
inking a concert-tour deal with Seventeen magazine.
</P>
<P>
   And while their peers were out buying the latest records by
Britney and 'N Sync, they were making their own record _ and
meeting 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   It's been quite a summer for the three girls in 3 of Hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of country sensation LeAnn Rimes,
R&AMP;B/pop singer Jessica Simpson and, most recently, 13-year-old
North Richland Hills pop gal Mikaila, 3 of Hearts, based in
northeast Tarrant County, is the latest local teen act to get
signed to a major label.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, they're not being marketed as a trio of Britney
knockoffs. Rather, the girls' music will be serviced to country
radio first, with a possibility of crossing over to pop _ a la
Faith Hill and Shania Twain _ on down the road. On their debut, due
in March, there's an emphasis on Dixie Chicks-style country, with
pedal steel and fiddles. Pop touches are there as well, along with
an occasional nod to Latin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're totally different than anything that's out there,'' says
Blaire Stroud, 17. ``First off, we're country, and we're the only
young, non-sister (female) country act right now. There's no one
else doing what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   A CD is not the only thing in store for the girls, all seniors
at L.D. Bell High School.
</P>
<P>
   A TV series is a major possibility, says their manager, Ken
Kragen, who also manages Kenny Rogers, among others. On a recent
trip to Los Angeles, the girls met with ``Beverly Hills, 90210''
producer Aaron Spelling, and Kragen says negotiations with various
producers and networks are under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sing like angels and look like `Charlie's Angels,''' says
Kragen. ``We've just sort of scratched the surface of
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes a 50-city mall-tour sponsored by Seventeen.
</P>
<P>
   Kragen says he wants the girls to strike while the iron is hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get as many things going at once, because
those opportunities may not be there when they get older,'' he
says. ``Teens are so hot right now, in sports, in music, in
entertainment. Everyone wants to climb aboard a hot bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   During an interview this week at Stroud's home, the three girls
seemed both genuinely unaffected and totally stoked by the
limelight they're about to step into. One second, they seem like
your typical teen girls, giggling about boys, dancing around the
house (they're all cheerleaders), bouncing on a trampoline.
</P>
<P>
   Next second, they're pulling out photos of themselves taken with
various celebrities, from Aaron Spelling to the members of 'N Sync.
``I'd never been so nervous in all my life,'' Wasdin, 16, says of
meeting the teen-pop sensations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're just people, just like us,'' Stroud says.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one reason the girls are so well-grounded is because
they've already had several tastes of success, having appeared on
the Grand Ole Opry, ``Positively Texas'' and at this year's Fan
Fare concert in Nashville, where the trio performed to more than
25,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was awesome,'' says McNeill, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Stroud, Blaire's mother and the group's co-manager, chalks
up the girls' earnestness to, simply enough, the fact that they
knew what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly tell you that this is what they've always
wanted to do,'' she says. ``And they've been preparing for it for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a tragic event to form the trio, though. They met at
Bedford Junior High, but did not start singing together until they
were enlisted to sing ``He Leadeth Me'' a cappella at the funeral
of a friend's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a weird story, but that's how it happened,'' says
Jan Stroud. ``After that, we just knew there was something special
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Naming themselves Girlfriendz, which they later changed when
they caught wind of another outfit with the same name, the trio
started performing at places such as Johnnie High Country Music
Revue (where Rimes got her start) and the Grapevine Opry. A friend
sent a demo tape to local record producer Peter Svendsen, who
helped Rimes, among others, jump-start her career.
</P>
<P>
   Svendsen took the girls under his wing, accompanying them to
Nashville, where they showcased for nine labels in two days. They
went with RCA.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to record their debut CD this summer, RCA
spared no expense, hiring a powerhouse recording team that included
in-demand producer Byron Gallimore, whose credits include Faith
Hill, Tim McGraw and Jo Dee Messina.
</P>
<P>
   The girls also had to make time this summer for dancing and
acting lessons. ``We have a different choreographed dance for every
song,'' says Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   The disc and tour, Kragen is quick to remind, are just the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're stars. They can sing, dance and act. They're the whole
package.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
