<SLUG> BC-TAMMYFAYE-FILM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FILM SHOWS TAMMY FAYE IS LOVING, FORGIVING AND NONJUDGMENTAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word that keeps coming up in descriptions of ``The Eyes of
Tammy Faye,'' the new documentary about former televangelist Tammy
Faye Bakker Messner, is ``kitsch.'' And Fenton Bailey, the movie's
co-director, doesn't quite get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it comes from the fact that people find Tammy
herself very kitschy or in some sort of poor taste. This is, of
course, what's she's been so ridiculed for,'' Bailey says in his
plummy British accent. ``I just find it very surprising, really. I
suppose it reveals just how much we judge books by their covers and
just how prejudicial we are about visual things.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie seeks to get beneath the surface of Messner's famed
makeup. Bailey and his filmmaking partner, Randy Barbato _ who is
atypically absent during a brief phone interview _ were curious
about Messner when she was still Tammy Faye Bakker, long before the
PTL scandals broke in the mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't approach her until the late '90s, when she was a
semi-recluse who had weathered a scandal-riddled divorce, a battle
with drug addiction, and the conviction of her second husband, Roe
Messner, on bankruptcy-fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really know the story that we were going to tell
when we started out,'' Bailey says. ``What we did know is that here
was a very entertaining person, and here was someone very different
from the public image. Contrary to the two-dimensional cartoon
image, (she) was a real complicated person.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie traces Messner's life, beginning with her teen-age
church-going days, her youthful marriage to Jim Bakker and their
founding of the PTL empire. Part of the kitsch accusation comes
from the movie's use of sock puppets _ Messner's own _ to introduce
the various ``chapters'' of her life. But the movie's intentions,
and execution, are more earnest than the sock puppets might lead
you to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers paint a sympathetic portrait of Messner, who is
seen as loving, forgiving and nonjudgmental. They're also kind to
Jim Bakker, who is portrayed as humble and penitent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is nothing mean-spirited about her,'' Bailey
says. ``I think the reason PTL was such a success is, OK, so they
talked about God and they talked about Jesus, a lot, but the real
core message was a humanist message _ and a message about love. I
think that was real atypical to a lot of other religious
broadcasters or evangelists.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real appeal of Messner, Bailey believes, is in her
open-hearted emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always criticize her for crying,'' he says. ``And yet
she's not particularly self-pitying. And she doesn't have a sort of
victim mentality. She laughs a lot and she cries a lot, and maybe
it would be good for all of us if we just bawled a bit, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
