r e BC-DIGITALACTORS-840(2Ta     08-18 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITALACTORS-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL ACTORS VYING FOR HOLLYWOOD'S A-LIST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Angelina Jolie was cast as Lara Croft in the movie version
of ``Tomb Raider,'' most gamers applauded the choice; Jolie, they
say, has the look and the attitude to convincingly play the star of
the popular video game. A handful of fans, however, were nonplused
_ Lara Croft is a sex symbol in her own right and one of the most
downloaded faces on the Internet. Why couldn't she play herself?
</P>
<P>
   The answer ``Because she's not real'' won't cut it anymore. The
busty, butt-kicking Lara Croft is a digital creation, and not even
a state-of-the-art one. But with recent advances in
computer-generated imagery, filmmakers could develop
photo-realistic human characters for the movie. In fact, the
upcoming ``Final Fantasy,'' set for release in 2001, features a
``human cast'' created entirely in the computer. A peek at a teaser
trailer on the film's Web site (www.finalfantasy.com) shows just
how realistic they are; although no one is likely to mistake them
for living, breathing human beings, they are the most convincing
facsimiles anyone has come up with yet _ and even greater advances
are promised before the film's release.
</P>
<P>
   Topping that, a Hollywood Reporter article this week stated that
Andrew Niccol (who wrote ``The Truman Show'') plans to use a
computer-generated actress opposite Al Pacino in his next movie,
``Simone.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors should be worried, right? After all, Lara Croft is
already an international star, the dream girl of millions of
hormone-juiced teen boys. And photo-realistic human characters
aren't going to show up late to the set, pout in their trailers,
throw tantrums or demand salary increases. Even so, it seems it's
the very people who are likely to do that _ the stars _ who are
least threatened by the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that the human spirit is ever something that
can be crushed,'' says Orlando Jones, who currently appears in
``The Replacements'' but is probably best-recognized as the guy in
the ``Make 7-Up Yours'' commercials. ``I think there's something
just electric between an audience and a performer that I'm not sure
animation will ever (equal). You're going to have to do it through
voice, and you're going to have to do it through the programmer
putting in those nuances that seem particularly human, but all
those things come back to the human spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agree. ``I don't think there's a lot of concern among
principal actors,'' says Allen Weingartner of the Screen Actors
Guild. ``There's sort of a human spark that they have that a
digital character can't provide.''
</P>
<P>
   There must be some concern, though: Weingartner's full title is
``senior administrator of industrial and interactive contracts.''
And digital characters, most notably Jar Jar Binks from ``Star
Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' have already been used. But
Weingartner points out that even Jar Jar wasn't completely digital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think you will eventually see a movie with one completely
digital character,'' he says. ``It hasn't happened yet. With Jar
Jar, there was an actor who did the voice.''
</P>
<P>
   And even ``Final Fantasy'' _ whose makers declined to comment
for this article _ is providing work for familiar names: Alec
Baldwin, James Woods and Ming-Na, to name a few. And SAG is
watching ``Simone'' carefully, to make sure that a guild member is
used in developing the computer-generated character. ``They better
have lists of hundreds of girls he looked at,'' SAG spokesman Greg
Krizman told The New York Daily News. ``We have plenty of actors
and actresses out there who wonder about computer-generated
directors.'' (Krizman's comments were reprinted on the Internet
Movie Database).
</P>
<P>
   Further down the acting food chain, though, there may be cause
for worry. Digital technology has already been used to increase the
number of extras in scenes (recent examples include ``The Patriot''
and ``Gladiator'') and to substitute for stunt people in especially
risky situations.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   ```Titanic' is a case in point,'' says Bob Hoffman, an effects
supervisor at Digital Domain, which did the effects for the movie.
``You have a character fall 350 feet, hit a propeller, then drop
300 more feet into the water. There is no stunt man alive who could
do that or who would even be nuts enough to try.'' So a stunt man
fell 50 feet, and then the fall was digitally ``extended.''
</P>
<P>
   Effects supervisors stress that movies are a collaborative
process, and the effects are just part of the process. They're not
in the business to make Frankenstein creations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'd ever want to put an actor out of work,''
says Chris Mitchell of Industrial Light and Magic, George Lucas'
effects house. ``People may want to create substitutes just because
they can, but I don't see it.'' Mitchell, in fact, recently worked
in tandem with an actor-director: He was lead animator on Clint
Eastwood's ``Space Cowboys,'' which used digital duplicates of
Eastwood, Donald Sutherland, Tommy Lee Jones and Loren Dean for
spacewalk scenes (a duplicate James Garner wasn't needed, since he
remains on the ship).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff that we're doing in space, in this
weightless environment, we had to do digitally,'' Mitchell says.
``If we have someone just hanging from wires, they look like
they're hanging from wires. Some of that stuff you can get away
with, but most audiences are too sophisticated for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology is so sophisticated now that most moviegoers
didn't realize that ``Space Cowboys''' spacewalkers occasionally
were not the actors themselves but digital mock-ups. It would
therefore stand to reason that if digital effects are that
convincing, it could be a way to steer around skyrocketing actor
salaries. But as it turns out, the technology is often still more
expensive and labor-intensive than using an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a meeting about this once,'' Weingartner says. ``And
(director) James Cameron came by and said something interesting. He
said, `If I go onto a sound stage and tell an actor what I want, I
can tell him to do it and he'll do it and I leave. If I want the
computer guys to do something, I tell 10 people what I want and I
leave.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, substitutions occur _ sometimes in desperate situations.
When Brandon Lee died during filming of ``The Crow,'' and Oliver
Reed died before production was complete on ``Gladiator,'' digital
technology was used to help ``complete'' their roles. And if it
could be done so seamlessly when someone dies, who's to say that it
can't be done in other emergency situations _ say, when actors go
on strike, as they're currently doing against the advertising
industry?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, commercials have used digital spokespeople already.
Digital Domain created Mya, a computer-generated personality, for a
Motorola campaign. ``It premiered during the Academy Awards during
March,'' Hoffman says. ``That was long before the actors strike, I
might add. And even in the case of that commercial, we worked with
an actress to provide the movements and the voice.'' And
apparently, you can be too realistic: ``It was so real,'' Hoffman
says, ``that the client actually asked us to make it more cyber.''
</P>
<P>
   Effects technicians see the co-existence of actors and digital
characters as nothing new; after all, Bugs Bunny and Mickey Mouse
became stars, and didn't usurp real actors. The time may indeed
come when digitally created actors who look and act like real
humans will be widely accepted by audiences. But neither actors nor
computer effects pros see the real, live movie star going away soon
_ especially since today's passion for celebrities is fueled as
much by what stars do offscreen as on.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, says Jones, there's one very good reason why Hollywood
isn't likely to reach ``Matrix''-like levels of digital dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think that the machine technology is gonna take
over,'' he says. ``But somehow, they forget that we're running
those machines.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5868 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV20-NY     08-18 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOMAKERS PAYING THE PRICE OF HIGHER RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 20)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ When automakers brought out their 2000 models last
fall, executives were jubilant. Their companies were enjoying
record sales, and the Federal Reserve's two interest rate increases
seemed to be having little effect; the manufacturers simply offset
them by subsidizing their discounted auto loans more heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Auto sales remain strong, but the optimism has faded. Alan
Greenspan, the Fed chairman, has pushed up short-term interest
rates four more times since last autumn. Trying to avoid raising
interest rates for their discounted loans, automakers stepped up
the subsidies even further, but the mounting costs crimped profit
margins. They wound up having to raise rates anyway on their
lowest-rate loans this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenspan was trying to slow it down and we didn't believe it
_ we thought it was just a bump; we'll eat it,'' said Tom McAlear,
the chief operating officer of DaimlerChrysler Financial Services,
the North American lending unit of the German automaker. ``Finally,
we said, `Alan, you're serious, we believe you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Economists are fond of repeating the adage that monetary policy
affects the real economy with long and variable lags. The lag has
seemed longer than usual for the current round of rate increases.
The continued strength of the stock market has played a role, but
so has the remarkable stamina of auto sales even as rates have
risen.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fed raised interest rates in 1994 in leaps of half a
point and even three-quarters of a point at a time, the automakers'
finance subsidiaries reacted with alarm, swiftly passing on
matching rate increases to their loan customers. The automakers,
particularly General Motors, were still reeling from the 1991
recession and in no mood then for a war of discounts.
</P>
<P>
   But the current round of Fed increases crept up on an industry
that has been very profitable since the mid-1990s. Each increase
came in just a quarter-point increment, and most have been hailed
on Wall Street as the last. One result has been a gradual
ratcheting up of incentive costs, escalating into a discounting war
that no automaker is willing to lose, even as everyone in the
industry hopes that the Fed will not act again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little heat on _ we're hoping for no more
increases,'' said G. Richard Wagoner Jr., GM's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet and computer companies now rule Wall Street, the
auto industry remains a cornerstone of the real economy. Autos
still account for about 4 percent of the nation's economy, a
percentage that has barely budged in decades. General Motors, Ford
Motor and DaimlerChrysler are each eight times the size of
Microsoft in sales, and economic output is measured by final sales
of goods and services, not by stock prices. Yet GM's market value
is now just a tenth of Microsoft's, one reason that Carl Icahn
bought a big stake in GM last week.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer interest rates are the crucial economic factor in auto
sales. Four-fifths of all vehicle buyers finance their cars,
minivans, pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles through loans or
leases. They closely study monthly payments, which depend on
interest rates. By contrast, the price of filling up the tank, high
this summer, has rarely had much impact on auto sales over the
years, except when the overall economy was weak.
</P>
<P>
   Banks raised their auto loan rates repeatedly over the last year
in response to Fed actions. The average bank rate for four-year
auto loans is now just over 10 percent, compared with 8.3 percent
in the spring of last year, said David L. Littmann, the senior
economist at Comerica Bank in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   After the recent increases, automakers' finance subsidiaries are
now charging an average of about 7 percent. Their average for the
second quarter, 6.48 percent, was actually a few hundredths of a
point lower than a year earlier. Automakers tried to raise their
finance subsidiaries' rates last winter, but they retreated rather
than lose market share to rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the manufacturers have been financing a
growing number of their customers' purchases, and the subsidies to
keep rates so low have pushed automakers' marketing costs to as
much as $2,300 a vehicle. Sales continue to roll along at a very
strong pace of 17.5 million cars and light trucks a year, a little
slower than last winter on a seasonally adjusted basis but still
ahead of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how much longer it will be before the auto
industry gives in and raises or restricts its subsidized rates, at
the risk of losing sales. James Holden, the chief executive of the
Chrysler unit of DaimlerChrysler, says this has begun to happen,
but slowly. ``We have stopped matching every Fed increase and
holding flat payments,'' he said. ``Payments have gone up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
