<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0819-COX     08-18 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITISH RESCUE TEAM SET TO ARRIVE, AS RUSSIAN ATTEMPTS TO SAVE
SUB CREW FAIL
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British team that represents the last best hope for
the crew aboard a downed Russian submarine is expected to arrive at
the rescue site Saturday afternoon and make its first dive before
nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-member team is optimistic despite diminishing prospects
that they will find any of 118-member crew of the nuclear submarine
Kursk alive when they reach them.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin on Friday told his countrymen
that there had been little chance to save the crew from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who has been attacked in the Russian press for the
belated requests for international assistance, said he had been
told by Russian Naval officers from the start of the crisis a week
ago that the chances of finding any survivors was slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer was 'there is an extremely small chance for rescue,
but it exists,''' Putin said in televised remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Putin defended his decision to stay on holiday when the crisis
struck, saying his first wish had been to fly to the scene, but he
had feared he would hamper rescue work. ``Everyone should keep to
his place,'' he said slowly, and looking grave.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare show of emotion, Putin said he knew personally the
commander of the Kursk and this made the disaster even harder to
stomach, knowing that the chances of success were few.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no signs of life since tapping on the hull
reported by Russian officials in the early days of the crisis
ceased on Wednesday. While Russian Naval officers have put the best
face on this chilling fact, their words have been betrayed by daily
revelations that damage to the Kursk was so devastating that many
officials believe the crew may have died soon after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   While it is still unclear what happened to the Kursk, it is
widely accepted that two explosions _ the second with the power of
two tons of dynamite _ were reported from Kursk at about the time
the Oscar-class submarine sank. A hole was torn in the 14,000-ton
submarine, once thought to be virtually unsinkable, from the nose
to the conning tower.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the crew worked in the portion of the submarine that was
most heavily damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk plummeted to the seabed in less than two minutes,
providing too little time for the crew to release a buoy or send an
emergency signal.
</P>
<P>
   Currents around the submarine, which is sinking in the mud at
350 feet below the surface of the Barents Sea, have been so strong
that Russian rescue teams have failed repeatedly to dock with the
Kursk using tethered diving bells.
</P>
<P>
   One capsule made it to the deck Friday, but was unable to enter
the vessel because the escape hatch reached by the capsule was
badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, British rescuers remain hopeful of saving
crewmembers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the British Defense Ministry said the rescue
team's LR5 mini-submarine is fitted with different equipment to the
Russian rescue capsules. ``We do not know what to expect until we
get there,'' she said. ``But the LR5 submersible has different
technology to the Russian capsules and we have not given up hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-foot LR5, described as an ``underwater helicopter'' is
the most advanced machine of its type in the world, the spokeswoman
said. It is fitted with a ``mating wedge'' which makes airtight
connections possible in difficult positions.
</P>
<P>
   While one escape hatch is very badly damaged, the team is hoping
that another hatch can be made to work. The British team should be
able to open the hatch from the outside without assistance from
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfectly straightforward escape hatch system which can
be opened from the inside and the outside,'' said Richard Sharpe, a
retired Royal Navy nuclear submarine captain and editor of Jane's
Fighting Ships, a respected publication on military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ee to four hours. The LR5 will stop after every three trips to
recharge its batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have provided necessary data on the Kursk for the
rescue attempt, but questions remain over the currents around it.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the British team aboard the Normand Pioneer was on
schedule to reach the rescue site by the afternoon, the defense
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of Russia's Northern Fleet said Friday that an
explosion had crippled the Kursk, but he said it wasn't clear what
caused the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an explosion inside a compartment of the submarine,
but the reason for the blast could be because of something from the
outside, I mean a collision, or ... (an explosion) inside,''
Vyacheslav Popov said on RTR television.
</P>
<P>
   Other Russian officials have said there had been a collision
with an unknown object, while U.S. surveillance equipment and a
Norwegian seismic institute recorded two explosions.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public statement since the crisis, Popov said from
the deck of a rescue ship that he and his fleet had done everything
they could to save the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a clear conscience that we have not lost one minute,
one hour, it is very difficult,'' he said. ``I will stay until I
fulfill my duty whatever the end is.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian and Western newspapers, expressing a public mood of
helplessness and outrage, have openly accused the authorities of
neglecting their duties while men were in peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``The behavior of our president is immoral,'' said Boris
Nemtsov, head of the reformist parliamentary group that backed
Putin in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those dying in the Barents Sea did not merit our statesmen
interrupting their summer holidays,'' said the daily Izvestia.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.janes.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.government.gov.ru/english/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mod.uk/
</P>
