<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5885 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-CHLOE-SEVIGNY-$ADV20-     08-18 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHLOE-SEVIGNY-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FASHION, THEY ALL SCREAM FOR CHLOE SEVIGNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 20) 
 By BOB MORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is it about the young indie actress Chloe
Sevigny that has turned the fashion world into a pack of dogs
howling about her as if she were a full moon, or a lamb chop? Is it
that she's alternative? Not quite pretty? Is it that she wears
vintage prairie dresses one day and Yves Saint Laurent the next and
that at the same time she seems to care and not care about it?
Could it be the odd dress by Alber Elbaz she wore to a New York
City Ballet benefit last spring, or the fact that she pretended not
to know who designed it when approached by a supplicating Andre
Leon Talley, editor at large of Vogue?
</P>
<P>
   Are people clamoring for Chloe because she eschews being on
magazine covers (why bother when The New Yorker already had Jay
McInerney profile her as ``super-cool girl'' six years ago)? Is it
because Gwyneth's too pretty and Courtney's too mean? Is it that
the name Chloe Sevigny is exotic, or that until recently, as was
well known, she lived with her mother in Darien, Conn., even as she
took downtown by storm?
</P>
<P>
   Is it because, after giving off nothing in ``Kids,'' her first
movie, and in later ones like ``The Last Days of Disco,'' she
surprisingly turned out to be a talented actress in ``Boys Don't
Cry,'' as the backwoods girlfriend of a cross-dressing woman? Or is
it because she has the nerve to say that she detests seeing her
face on H&AMP;M department store ads around town, but would rather make
money that way than in bad movies?
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, the banquettes are alive with the sound of
Chloe, recently labeled by Vogue as ``the New Postmodern Grunge
Audrey Hepburn.'' Of course, fashion people are always fussing over
this one or that one. It justifies using exclamation points for
something other than shades of mascara. In 1964, it was Baby Jane
Holzer, a mod young Park Avenue wife who acted in Andy Warhol
movies and who did the swim and was called ``the most contemporary
girl I know'' by Diana Vreeland. Ten years later, according to
Vanity Fair's new `` `It' Parade'' issue, it was Ali McGraw, among
others. Now, and despite the fact that Vanity Fair did not include
Sevigny on its `` `It' Parade'' list, she's It, the anti-actress,
unfashionably fashionable, fresh, raw, unreachable. Being so
adamantly anti-It only makes her It-ier, it seems. ``Born Free!''
sings the cover line next to her face from the latest issue of
Interview. ``She refuses to be a puppet for the media,'' proclaims
Ingrid Sischy, the editor in chief, in her introduction, adding
that Sevigny and Harmony Korine, the writer of ``Kids'' (about
teen-age punks and a seducer with HIV) and ``Gummo'' (about cat
killers, among other things)are the Elizabeth Taylor and Richard
Burton of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has something to say about her, it seems. ``She's like
this skater kid who just fell into the right shoes and an Yves
Saint Laurent dress,'' said Stefan Campbell, a stylist, who found
Sevigny cute when she had the gumption to show up uninvited for a
Vibe magazine skateboarding fashion shoot years ago. ``Designers
and photographers love her because plain girls can make clothes
come alive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Fahey, a publicist at Chanel, who's a fan, said: ``She was
in the store a while ago to look at clothes for the Oscars, and she
had on this Hello Kitty-like underwear and I just thought that was
so cool.'' Jorge Ramon, senior fashion editor of Teen People,
added, ``She's an anticheerleader, which I love, and she makes
wearing a beret look fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York novelist I know calls her ``ugly-beautiful'' and
extols her for escaping the unifying hands of stylists. An online
editor, who said she can't decide if Sevigny is bright or not, but
thinks she's a really nice person even though she has never met
her, declared that we have a moral imperative to support her
because of ``Boys Don't Cry,'' which earned her an Oscar nomination
as best supporting actress. Another person admires her for sticking
by the collections of Elbaz, the low-key designer who was deposed
last spring by the hot shot Tom Ford at Yves Saint Laurent. Yet
another lauded her virtue for understanding vintage fashion and for
pushing Imitation of Christ, a friend's new clothing line. Michael
Kors, meanwhile, has declared her a major muse and Nicolas
Ghesquiere, another designer, who is revitalizing Balenciaga, calls
her ``sophisticated and negligent and emblematic of the new
generation of actresses.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just a short list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it was power that created high style,'' Tom Wolfe wrote
about Baby Jane Holzer, who has moved on to become a bona fide
has-been. ``But now high styles come from low places, from people
who have no power, who slink away from it, in fact, who are
marginal, who carve out worlds for themselves in nether depths, in
tainted undergrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   From skate-rat girl who worked in a vintage clothing store to an
icon who allows the fashion world to congratulate itself for lining
up behind someone who treats it with indifference, things haven't
changed much in 35 years, it seems. At a moment when everything, no
matter how contrived, is supposed to seem effortless, Chloe
Sevigny's ``accidental'' rise to just-under-the-radar prominence is
a lesson in how naive some ambitious people can be about actresses
who seem to be without ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have witnessed her climb more closely have a more
nuanced view. ``There's something very natural about her,'' said
Clifford Streit, a producer who worked with her in ``American
Psycho,'' her latest film. ``But it's not an accident. She knows
how to project an image on the public and make it appear
effortless.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Zalaznick, the producer who cast Sevigny in ``Kids'' in
1994, observed: ``It's basically a full-time job making it into the
world she's in. And no matter what she wants you to think, she's
definitely working it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sevigny, who got her start in the business by working on the
costumes for ``Kids,'' declined to be interviewed. Her publicist
said she would like to disassociate from fashion right now.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vogue and VH1 are planning their joint fashion awards
show for October. Who do we think is on the top of every Vogue
editor's list for the best personal style? ``Her aura has been
hanging over every single meeting,'' said Zalaznick, who is the
show's executive producer. ``It's this fascination with unfabulous
fabulousness, and it's a little ridiculous. I mean, if it's about
fashion why not just obsess over a model? Does it make these Vogue
people feel more beautiful themselves for thinking she's so
beautiful?''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say. All I know is that these days the Chloe watch
never stops.
</P>
<P>
   The week before last, for instance, the possibility of her
appearance either enhanced or sucked the air out of two parties,
depending on your point of view. One, at the Rainbow Room for the
director Wit Stillman's novel ``The Last Days of Disco, With
Cocktails at Petrossian Afterwards'' was Chloe-free because she had
Polish lessons for a new part. The other, a singles bash in
Chelsea, featured Paul Sevigny, Chloe's
commodities-trader-turned-celebrity-D.J. brother spinning CDs.
Despite his rapid rise, not everybody loves his taste. ``Just for
the hope of seeing his sister,'' said one disgruntled celebrity
guest, ``we had to put up with his music.''
</P>
<P>
   This, too, will end one day. In the meantime, all hail our new
dis-ingenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
