<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5888 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD19-COX     08-18 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the end, secret's often in the finish
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finishing wood is a chore rather than a pleasure for most
woodworkers, but it will make or break your project. No matter how
finely designed and constructed a piece may be, a bad finish ruins
it.
</P>
<P>
   A reader named Dennis McLeroy sent me an e-mail a few days ago
on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently completed a solid cherry cradle for good friends
of ours. I'd like a suggestion on finishing. I want the wood to
retain its ability to darken to its natural patina, but at the same
time would like a nice, not glossy, finish. I know I'm probably
opening Pandora's box here, but what would you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A: The entire subject of wood finishing is indeed a Pandora's
box, but if you break it down into the possible, the improbable and
the impossible, it gets easier.
</P>
<P>
   You can select a finish by establishing parameters. First,
consider your skill level and your equipment. Do you have spray
equipment and a spray booth? Are you an expert with a brush?
</P>
<P>
   Do you want a hard, glass-like finish or a soft sheen?
</P>
<P>
   If you want a glassy finish the prime choice is lacquer. In that
case, you'd better have spray equipment and skill using it, or be
an absolute wizard with a brush. The second choice would be
varnish, and again you need an excellent brush technique.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these finishes have a major drawback: they are difficult
to repair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you leave out such romantic things as French polish, we
are left with an oil finish. The village idiot can apply a good oil
finish; I am living proof of that. The drawback with pure oil
finishes is that they don't provide much protection.
</P>
<P>
   Thus some enterprising woodworker invented the oil-varnish
finish, using various portions of tung or linseed oil, polyurethane
and a thinner such as turpentine. The result looks like a pure oil
finish, but it will provide a good deal more protection, and it is
easily repaired.
</P>
<P>
   I used to make it up myself, but over the intervening years it
has become commonly available in various commercial forms.
</P>
<P>
   Highland Hardware in Atlanta (www.highland-hardware.com)
features the Sam Maloof finishes. The main finish is an oil-poly
mix. The secondary finish is oil-wax. I don't know that you need
the latter; Sam applies it outdoors, because he heats it up before
application.
</P>
<P>
   Woodcraft (check the Web site at www.woodcraft.com) has several
oil-varnish finishes. Some even come in a range of glosses.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, however, you achieve the degree of sheen or gloss you
want by applying more coats. The process is simple: flood the stuff
on, adding more if the wood sucks it up, and then wiping off the
excess before it begins to stiffen. With use, you'll learn about
how long you can wait before rubbing it off.
</P>
<P>
   Some instructions will tell you to apply a new coat every 24
hours. That may be fine in dry areas, but in a humid climate I'd
wait at least 48 before reapplying.
</P>
<P>
   The wood will age nicely, and repair simply involves applying
more finish.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
