A5890 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-NICHOLS-BOS &LR;      08-18 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-NICHOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH NICHOLS, 47; CHRONICLED BATTLE WITH CANCER IN VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elizabeth (Tucker) Nichols of Harvard, Mass., whose battle
against breast cancer was chronicled in the video ``When Breast
Cancer Comes Back: Skills for Living,'' died of the disease Sunday
in Harwich Port. She was 47.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nichols, known as ``Liz,'' was born in Fitchburg. She
designed jewelry and was an adminstrative assistant at Paine Webber
in Boston and BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   She was first diagnosed with cancer seven years ago. She
underwent a lumpectomy and received radiation treatment,
chemotherapy, and hormonal therapy. Eighteen months later, when
cancer was discovered in her other breast, she underwent a
mastectomy and reconstructive surgery. A year later, cancer was
found in her bones. She received a stem cell transplant and
continued to receive chemotherapy and radiation treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nichols was the narrator of ``When Breast Cancer Comes
Back,'' which chronicled several women dealing with a recurrence of
the disease. She appeared on TV's ``Today Show'' last fall to
discuss the film.
</P>
<P>
   In promotional material for the video posted on the Web site
AboutHealth.com, she spoke of her reaction when her oncologist told
her she probably had six months to live. She said she tried not to
dwell on the bleak prognosis because, ``It will spiral you down, it
will bring you down, and it will carry you further and deeper and
deeper into the abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she avoided despair by living in the day. ``I did get
that coat for Christmas,'' she said. ``I wore that coat every day
and loved it and whether I'm not even here next year, I don't even
care, because I enjoyed it for now. I enjoy going outside for now.
I enjoy every single thing that I do, for now. None of us know how
long we are going to be here. None of us know.''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her husband, Carlton ``Tuck'' Nichols; a son, Carlton
`Tripp'' of Harvard; a daughter, Elizabeth of Harvard; a
stepdaughter, Alexi Nichols of New York City; her father, Norman D.
Tucker Jr. of Shirley; and four brothers, Norman ``Kit'' Tucker III
of Fitchburg, David Tucker of Martha's Vineyard, Gregory Tucker of
Burlington, Vt., and Douglas Tucker of Granby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
