   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   LIES _ As you consider that new job, here's a question to
ponder: Will you have to lie at work? In much of the American
workplace there is a corporate culture of lying. If you value
honesty (tell the truth!) we'll look at clues to judge how
forthcoming your new employer really is. (Mallory, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH LLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The first report on a law passed by Congress in
1988 to curb abuses by the IRS is in and it turns out that of the
830 formal complaints of IRS abuse, not one _ zero, zilch, nada _
panned out. Worse, it seems the fix has had consequences more
perverse than purposeful. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for
Cox Newspapers.) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg's column is not available
this week.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TWINS _ WHITE PLAINS, N.C. _ To the world and to this day, they
are mostly objects of curiosity _ Chang and Eng, the conjoined
brothers whose May 1811 birth in Siam also spawned the phrase
``Siamese twins.'' But in the northwestern corner of North Carolina
where they settled some 30 years later, they have always been the
Bunker brothers _ hard-working tobacco farmers who married sisters,
fathered 21 children between them and lived utterly ordinary,
small-town lives. Officials recently renamed a bridge after the
twins on the White Plains farm where they lived and are buried.
Still, locals don't quite understand the outside world's
fascination with the twins, which has only grown with the
publication this summer of New Yorker Darin Strauss' acclaimed
novel ``Chang and Eng.'' To the folks who showed up at Strauss'
booksignings last week in nearby Mount Airy and Wilkesboro, and to
the1,000-plus descendants who gathered for one of their
semi-regular reunions in White Plains Saturday, it's actually a
pretty familiar story around these parts: The one about strong
family bonds. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-ADVICE _ With the school year approaching, it's time for
teachers and parents to reopen the lines of communication. To save
everyone time and stress, we asked working teachers and frenzied
moms and dads exactly what advice they would give the other side in
order to make this school year the most productive ever. (Dayton
Daily News) WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-COMPASS _ You may remember a time when you were a kid
and you got a toy compass maybe from the neighborhood candy store
or maybe even from a box of Cracker Jacks. Those cheesy little
devices featured a jiggling needle balanced on a pin, and the
painted end of the needle always pointed north. Unless there was a
magnet nearby or the needle fell off the pin. Today you can carry
around a digital device that does the same thing more reliably. The
Co-Pilot from Precision Navigation Inc. gives you a digital readout
that tells you exactly which way you're headed with an accuracy of
plus or minus 5 degrees. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 12. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is James Cummings' Gadgets Column.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The following stories from the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
are part of a Fall Getaways package of the Southeast Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ABINGTON _ ABINGTON, Va. _ It is an unseasonably cool,
moonless night in this historic Blue Ridge Mountain town, a good
evening for a ghost tour in this old place that seems to have more
than a healthy share. Named Abingdon in honor of Martha
Washington's ancestral home in England, this mountain town is home
to the Barter Theater, the Martha Washington Inn and other
intriguing historic places. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BLOWROCK _ BLOWING ROCK, N.C. The legend goes that a
Cherokee brave dived off the Blowing Rock to appease his gods and
was caught in an updraft so powerful that he was lifted back to his
sweetheart's arms. I wasn't feeling quite that lucky on my visit to
this popular Blue Ridge Mountains attraction. In fact I hung on to
the flat, upturned rock _ the parapet, it seemed, of a mighty
castle _ for dear life. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BLUERIDGE _ BLUE RIDGE, Ga. _ There it is, tucked into
the trees just off the road: Our pine-log-sided North Georgia cabin
with a red tin roof. Up the Creek, ie back of a horse. Lovelier.
Less familiar. Maybe it's because this place, the 1,000-acre
Cataloochee Ranch, is so close to paradise you half-expect to enter
it through pearly gates. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ROOFTOP _ ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ If you're heading here to
look at the fall leaves, one of your best viewing sites might be
from the roof of the Biltmore House. That's right. The roof. The
guided 75-minute Rooftop Tour will take you up amid the turrets and
gargoyles, where you can get a panoramic view of the gardens, the
French Broad River and Mount Pisgah. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LITTLE-SWISS _ LITTLE SWITZERLAND, N.C. _ Other places in
the North Carolina mountains are better-known, but none are like
this faux-alpine hideaway nestled at 3,500 feet in the southern
Appalachians. It brims daily with color and tranquillity. In the
fall, especially, Little Switzerland, just off the Blue Ridge
Parkway, is a place many folks come for a long weekend. Many come
to like it so much they plan ahead, booking a week at the
Switzerland Inn or another nearby mountain lodge. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TOWNSEND _ TOWNSEND, Tenn. _ The campfire is a portable
propane model that looks like something out of the Flintstones. The
moonlit mesa is in truth a screen-printed mural. But the guy in the
black chaps, vest and tall cowboy hat, the fellow spinning cowpoke
tales as tall as a saguaro cactus, stories that roll on like
tumbleweeds,he's got this western thing down. Ladies and gentlemen,
put your hands together for tonight's headliner, cowboy poet
extraordinaire David ``Buffalo Bill'' Nelson. Oh, by the way,
Buffalo, er, David is also your innkeeper. He and wife Jean operate
the western-decorated B&AMP;B Abode and Beyond, here near the entrance
to the Great Smoky Mountains National Park. (Pousner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MNT-FESTS _ A listing of Southeast mountain festivals
this fall. (Brooks, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ABORIGINE-ART _ Thirty years ago, an art professor encouraged a
group of Aborigines in the central desert of Australia to paint on
canvas the symbolic patterns their people had been making in the
red dirt for eons. The dirt patterns evolved into dot paintings, a
popular form of folk art that has become synonymous with Australia
and will figure prominently in the Sydney Olympic Arts Festival. We
look at the field, which has interesting parallels with the artwork
that won praise at the last Olympics: Southern folk art.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   DEBBIE-ALLEN _ A conversation with Debbie Allen, the Broadway
dancer who here plays writer-composer of a new dance drama, ``Soul
Possessed,'' about a girl who runs off with a mysterious drifter,
set against the mysticism of the Louisiana bayous. (Auchmutey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MURALS _ The new murals at the Bird House at Riverbanks Zoo in
Columbia, S.C.; filming on ``Hannibal'' at the Biltmore House in
Asheville, N.C.; and ``Remembering Charles Kuralt,'' a new book.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Who was Deep Throat, the unnamed source who met
Washington Post reporter Bob Woodward in an underground parking
garage at 2 in the morning? Did he even exist? Was he one person or
a composite of two or more? Was he a only a fiction created as a
linchpin for Woodward and Carl Bernstein's book ``All the King's
Men''? Now Leonard Garment, an old Nixon hand who has made Deep
Throat his personal quarry, thinks he knows. ``In Search of Deep
Throat'' (Basic Books, $25) is a lawyerly deduction from plausible
hypotheses but in the end an intuitive guess. ``It is my
conviction,'' Garment writes on page 2, ``that Deep Throat ... was
John Sears.'' (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 26
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBO-FURCAL _ ATLANTA _ Braves rookie Rafael Furcal is defining
what speed can bring to a solid lineup. (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-GYM-TRIALS _ Coverage of Olympic Gymnastics trials, second
half. (Rosen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWM-JOSHDAVIS _ Four years ago, Josh Davis had to be the
happiest and luckiest man in Atlanta. Although he didn't win a
single individual medal at the Olympics, he struck gold three times
as a relay swimmer for the United States and left the Games with
more of that precious metal draped around his neck than any male
athlete from any country. Times change, and so has Davis' role. He
still is not the individual star of the U.S. team, but the
27-year-old former Texas Longhorn is its leader, the emotional rock
for a squad that certainly will need one in Sydney, Australia.
These Olympics will be no house party for the U.S. swimmers the way
the Atlanta Games were. The rest of the world has been improving,
and the talented Aussies will be defending their home surf in a
country that's fanatical about the sport. ``Everyone's talking
about swimming there. It's kind of like the NBA and NFL over
here,'' said Olympic swim coach Richard Quick. (Maher, Austin
American-Statesman). 35.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWM-TEXAS _ At the recent U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials there
were times when there were so many Longhorns in the final it was a
wonder they didn't turn the pool orange. The Three Amigos, seniors
Jamie Rauch, Scott Goldblatt and Nate Dusing, all finished in the
top six in the 200 meter freestyle and are eligible to swim on the
U.S.'s 800 meter relay team in Sydney. The 100 meter butterfly was
another Texas affair with Longhorn recruit Ian Crocker beating
Tommy Hannan. If you count Gary Hall, who had a cup of coffee at
Texas, eight of the 24 men selected to the team were either former,
current or incoming Longhorns. And there were a rash of Texas
swimmers who didn't make the team but still turned in impressive
performances, including incoming freshman Brendan Hansen, who
finished third in both the 100 and 200 meter breaststroke. (Maher,
Austin American-Statesman). 24.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-FORTNER _ Former Longhorn basketball standout Nell
Fortner has a big task at hand. She is head coach of the U.S.
women's Olympic basketball team. Like the men's national team, they
are expected to return home from the 2000 Summer Olympics in
Sydney, Australia next month with a gold medal ? and nothing else
but souvenirs. But the U.S.'s trip to the Olympics every four years
in basketball is not as easy as it used to be, as other countires
have colsed the talent gap. There's as much pressure on Fortner to
carry on a tradition of dominance as on her 12-player superstar
roster. She's looking forward to it. (Estwick, Austin
American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PGA _ LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Coverage of the third round of the
PGA Championship from Valhalla at Louisville, Ky. (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BISHER _ LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Columnist Furman Bisher from the
PGA Championship. (Bisher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
