<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUB _ LONDON _ After days of anguished efforts, a rescue
capsule finally reaches an escape hatch on the shattered hull of
the sunken Russian submarine Kursk, but finds the hatch so mangled
that it can't link up. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-TRAVEL _ DAMASCUS, Syria _ From the ornate tomb of the
great conqueror Salaheddin, to the ramshackle exhibit of the only
Syrian Cosmonaut, Syria's capital offers a captivating sampling of
the best of classic Arab and Moslem culture. Visitors can step back
in time, dining in courtyards enclosed by the black and red blocks
of classic Arab architecture and touring dozens of castles in the
countryside. There's no McDonald's and little Coca-Cola, but you
can shop for dehydrated Newts in the medicinal herb stalls of the
old market. All possible for those willing to join a small but
growing number of American tourists to a country that may be slowly
opening up to the west. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-PALMYRA _ PALMYRA, Syria _ These expansive ruins show the
legacy of a working city built on taxation of goods on the old Silk
Road. Connecting it's grand temples is a system of roads, a senate
and treasury. On the outskirts of town are the tower tombs, where
family members were encased behind eerie carvings of their
likenesses. Considered one of the greatest ruins in the world,
Palmyra, about 4,000 years old, is still only lightly visited.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   With information for locator map; if-you-go box attached at end
of main story.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in advance Wed., Aug. 16, on the NYT wire in (i)
International and (t) Travel categories.
</P>
