<HEADER>
A5893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0819-COX     08-18 1780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Looking for pictures and votes . . . looking
for pictures and votes . . .
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having raced east to catch the sunrise, Democrats Al Gore and
Joe Lieberman shoved off from the banks of the Mississippi River
today for a paddlewheel cruise on the Mark Twain riverboat meant to
stir heartland excitement for their freshly launched campaign. The
two, along with their families, set off on their ``Charting
America's Course'' cruise in La Crosse, Wis., barely 12 hours after
closing their convention half a continent away. The folksy,
made-for-pictures tour goes through battleground states that could
well decide the November election: Wisconsin, Illinois, Iowa and
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   . . . BUT NOT THAT KIND OF PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   An unwieldy entourage of campaign aides and journalists also
piled onto the 120-foot, triple-decked Mark Twain, complete with
calliope. Boats of Secret Service agents sputtered along on either
side of the Mark Twain, whose maximum speed is a mere 8 mph. Posing
near the bow, Al Gore turned down photographers' suggestions he
balance himself hands-free _ as Leonardo DiCaprio's character did
in ``Titanic.'' ``No. Wrong metaphor,'' Gore chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   INVASION OF TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, who laid low on his Texas ranch for the four-day
Democratic convention, burst back on the campaign trail today with
a joint visit to Al Gore's backyard with running mate Dick Cheney.
``We like playing on the other guy's turf,'' said Bush's chief
strategist, Karl Rove. Bush suggested in Memphis that Gore's
acceptance speech reflected ``the rhetoric of the past'' and
underscored seven years of inaction. But Bush also gave his
Democratic rival a nod for attempting to emerge from the shadow of
President Clinton. ``I mean he's standing on his own two feet,'' he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A BOUNCE, BUT NOT A BIG ONE
</P>
<P>
   Fresh surveys suggested Al Gore gained a post-convention bounce
as candidates usually do after their nomination when voters show an
initial emotional reaction. An overnight NBC News poll gave Gore 46
percent and George W. Bush 43 percent. With an an error margin of 4
percentage points, that makes for a dead heat. A
Voter.com-Battleground tracking poll released today showed Bush
holding a 45 to 40 percent lead in a four-way matchup with the
Green Party's Ralph Nader at 3 percent and the Reform Party's Pat
Buchanan at 1 percent. A day earlier, that same poll (3 percentage
point error margin) had Bush up 48-37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD WORD FOR MCCAIN FROM DOCTORS
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's skin cancer likely has not spread, his doctors
said today. The 63-year-old senator planned surgery Saturday to
remove more skin and lymph nodes around the spots of melanoma,
which is the most serious form of skin cancer. The lymph nodes will
be tested to make certain the cancer has not spread. McCain and his
wife, Cindy, met with doctors for about 3 1/2 hours at the Mayo
Clinic in Scottsdale, Ariz., today. They said tests didn't find any
evidence the cancer has spread to other areas of McCain's body,
such as the lungs or liver.
</P>
<P>
   SURGERY FOR BUCHANAN, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan had his gall bladder removed. The Reform Party
candidate was admitted to Washington Hospital Center after
experiencing repeated episodes of stomach pain during the last few
months, according to his sister, Bay Buchanan. Buchanan had known
he had gallstones, and was waiting until after the November
election to have them removed. But after an episode of discomfort
last week he decided to do it sooner. During the surgery doctors
decided to remove the entire gall bladder.
</P>
<P>
   BUT IT'S A HAPPY HOLLYWOOD ENDING
</P>
<P>
   William Bennett, one of Joe Lieberman's Washington allies in
attacking Hollywood's exploitation of sex and violence, said he was
disappointed that the passionate rhetoric and stinging critiques of
``the old Joe'' were missing from his convention address. ``Joe is
getting incredible pressure from the campaign. The Gore people are
saying `fall in line' on the issues,'' said Bennett, a Republican
and former secretary of education. ``He should acknowledge Al Gore,
the head of the ticket, speaks for the party. But what he can't do
is compromise his core convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   TWO WAYS TO SAY `NO'
</P>
<P>
   Denied a chance to address the Republican convention, NAACP
president Kweisi Mfume stood on the Democrats' podium and praised
Al Gore and Joe Lieberman for having ``listened and responded and
stood with us'' on issues such as hate crimes, health care and
racial equality. ``We offered to give both major political parties
our best thinking on matters of concern to the millions of
Americans who believe as we airness and equality and fair
play,'' Mfume said. ``The Democratic Party said `No problem.' The
Republican Party said `No thanks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   MAKING BIG OIL A BIG ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   While Dick Cheney and his lawyers are scrambling to find a
solution to a knotty problem that could cost him a fortune _risk
political criticism by keeping millions of dollars worth of stock
options in Halliburton Co., the Texas oil services giant from which
he just retired, or forfeit the money _ the Democrats stepped up
their criticism. The Gore campaign highlighted Cheney's connection
to the oil industry. ``It seems big oil is making a big investment
in the Bush-Cheney ticket,'' said Gore campaign spokesman Doug
Hattaway. ``People would rightfully wonder whose side Dick Cheney
is on in taking on oil companies on the subject of gas prices and
pollution controls.''
</P>
<P>
   NOW, TO PUT THAT FIRE INTO THE SPEECHES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's passionate kiss left more than just Tipper breathless.
The delegates in the convention hall were impressed as well. Gore
gave his wife a long, full-on-the-lips smooch after she introduced
him Thursday night for his acceptance speech. ``Wow. He's got
fire,'' said Wisconsin delegate Barbara Hintz. ``Did you see his
kiss?'' marveled Alison Cameron of Houston. ``I was like, Oooooh!''
Then, in the speech, Gore described Tipper as ``someone I've loved
with my whole heart since the night of my high school senior
prom.''
</P>
<P>
   EVERY MOTHER'S HAPPIEST DREAM
</P>
<P>
   Two dignified old ladies sat in the convention audience, busting
with pride. Both Al Gore and Joe Lieberman have lost their fathers,
but their octogenarian moms _ two once-formidable women rendered
fragile by age _ wouldn't have missed the convention for anything.
``Mom is 85 years old, but I'll tell you, she never felt younger
than she feels today,'' Lieberman said from the stage as his
mother, Marcia, beamed. ``Mom, thank you, I love you. And you and I
know how proud Pop would be tonight.'' And Pauline LaFon Gore, 87,
the family matriarch known throughout Tennessee as Miz Pauline, saw
a life's ambition fulfilled when she watched her son accept the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   UNDER THE PINK, IT'S STILL GREEN
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 campaign, the gay community has written more and
bigger checks than ever before, making ``pink money,'' as it is
known, one of the most important financial sources for the
Democratic Party. In all, gays have contributed about $5 million
this election to the Democratic National Committee alone _ a total
that puts them among the top tier of Democratic givers, along with
unions, trial lawyers and the Jewish community. Al Gore tapped into
the gay community to bring another several million dollars into his
presidential campaign, making it a significant source of funds
among the $48 million raised for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   POINT, CLICK, PAY UP
</P>
<P>
   Americans clicked their way onto the Internet during the
conventions to donate enough money at a pace brisk enough to
surprise the infant Web fund-raising industry. One of the
Internet's leading political fund-raising companies _
eContributor.com _ said its clients raised about a quarter-million
dollars through Web sites between July 24 and Monday's start of the
Democratic convention _ an increase of 242 percent from late July.
The average Internet donation was $123, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   SEEING SOME STARS FOR THEIR MONEY
</P>
<P>
   After taking center stage on the final day of the convention, Al
Gore shared the spotlight with Barbra Streisand and Whoopi Goldberg
at a fund-raiser that fattened party coffers by more than $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg served as master of ceremonies at the Shrine
Auditorium, where the Academy Awards are handed out each year,
while Streisand provided the finale for a concert that included
singers Enrique Iglesias, Baby Face and Boyz II Men. Tickets sold
for as little as $150, but the best seats went to co-chairs, who
raised or donated $50,000, and vice chairs, at the $20,000 level.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY'S OVER _ LET'S GO HOME
</P>
<P>
   For the thousands of demonstrators who went to the convention to
press their causes, the last day on the streets ended simply: no
shoving, no rubber bullets and no arrests. After a final festive
march from the convention site to the jail where nearly 200 of
their number had been booked over the previous week, they simply
turned around and went home early today. Outside the jail, a masked
anarchist tried to urge protesters to continue blocking the street.
``Are we just going to go home and watch our TVs?'' he implored.
But the crowd melted away down side streets under the watchful eye
of riot-gear-clad police officers.
</P>
<P>
   TAMALES ARE , it was Mummers and cheesesteaks. In L.A., it was
traffic snarls and helicopter noise. Indeed, there was little
evidence of a convention at all once out of sight of the Staples
Center. Center City Philadelphia, by contrast, was festooned with
bunting and swamped with signs. And the legions of smiling
volunteers in Philly were nowhere to be found in glitzy Southern
Cal.
</P>
<P>
   MONDALE _ ISN'T THAT A SUBURB OF L.A.?
</P>
<P>
   Walter Mondale, vice president under Jimmy Carter and the
party's nominee against Ronald Reagan in 1984, made a surprise
visit to the Michigan delegation. He spoke briefly about the
importance of campaign finance reform and Rep. Debbie Stabenow's
race for the Senate, then posed for pictures. Mondale said he was
invited by former Michigan Gov. Jim Blanchard. ``He said the
Michigan delegation is running short of free speakers,'' Mondale
joked. ``I'm here, I'm free and I'm worth what you're paying.''
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
