<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEAGRAMS-ACQUIRE-400&AMP;     08-18 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAMS-ACQUIRE-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAGEO AND PERNOD TO MAKE JOINT BID FOR SEAGRAM'S WINE AND SPIRITS
BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Diageo PLC of Britain, the world's leading liquor
company, and Pernod Ricard SA of France announced Friday that they
would team up to compete for the wine and spirits business of the
Seagram Co., a move likely to start a bidding war with Allied
Domecq PLC, the No. 2 liquor concern, that could push the price
towards $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's spirits businesses, which include Chivas Regal premium
Scotch whiskey, are to be sold as part of the company's acquisition
by Vivendi SA, the French utility-to-media conglomerate, which
wants to use the proceeds from selling the liquor assets to reduce
its $6.6 billion in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's wine and spirits business, the third biggest after
Diageo and Allied Domecq, represents one of the last major jewels
up for grabs in a scramble for profitable, high-profile brands. The
major challenger to the Diageo-Pernod Ricard bid, Allied Domecq,
owner of Ballantine's Scotch whiskey and Kahlua liqueur, needs an
acquisition on this scale to draw level with Diageo. Allied Domecq
had initially been viewed as the front-runner for the Seagram
liquor business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already confirmed our interest in bidding for
Seagram's drinks business,'' said Anthony Cardew, a spokesman for
Allied Domecq, which, in addition to its liquor businesses,
operates the Baskin-Robbins ice cream and Dunkin' Donuts chains.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo sold 91 million 12-bottle cases of liquor in 1999, while
Allied Domecq sold 48 million and Seagram's sold 41 million,
according to industry figures.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo, owner of brands that include Johnnie Walker Scotch
whiskey, Smirnoff vodka and Gordon's gin, gave no details of its
bidding agreement with Pernod Ricard, which has brands including
Pernod and Ricard aniseed spirits, Wild Turkey bourbon, Jameson
Irish whiskey and Havana Club rum.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's portfolio ranges from Chivas Regal to Martell cognac,
Crown Royal Canadian whiskey and Captain Morgan rum. It also holds
distribution rights to Sweden's top-selling premium vodka, Absolut,
until 2004, but it remained unclear whether those rights would be
included in the auction. If they are not included, the price is
likely to be lower, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo and Pernod Richard The two companies said in a statement
only that they had ``agreed to work together to make an offer for
Seagram's wine and spirits business in the forthcoming disposal
process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Up until a few days ago, Diageo had been widely expected to
strike a joint bidding deal with privately owned Bacardi to bid for
the Seagram's businesses, but those talks apparently collapsed over
how to divide Seagram's brands.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo was likely to be interested in Seagram's Canadian whiskey
and rum brands, while Pernod Ricard, the world's fifth largest
liquor company, would primarily want Chivas Regal, the analysts
said. Pernod said its ``major interest is in the Scotch whiskey
category.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale is critical to Diageo's long-range goal of securing its
leadership of the liquor business as it sheds other interests to
focus on spirits and Guinness beer holdings. It has just sold its
Pillsbury food division and plans to spin off its Burger King
fast-food chain. Diageo called Seagram's business ``a logical
extension to our focus on beverage alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the likely bidding war sent Allied Domecq stock down by
as much as 3.6 percent to 314.5 pence, or about $4.72, a share, and
Diageo was down 2.5 percent at 596 pence or $8.94 a share. In
Paris, Pernod Ricard rose 2.56 percent to 60 euros or $54.60 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Pernod Ricard has been looking to expand in the liquor business
despite a major setback last year when regulators blocked its
planned sale of Orangina soft drinks to Coca Cola Co., ending
speculation that it planned to use the proceeds to bid for Allied
Domecq.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential bidder in the Seagram auction, which is likely
to get under way in the next few weeks, is the Bronfman family,
which founded Seagram and owns 24 percent of the company. But there
was no immediate word Friday on whether that bid would proceed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
