<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LUNA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT     08-18 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA LUNA: BEING INVENTIVE WITH PERIOD INSTRUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the early days of the period-instrument movement,
when accomplished players were comparatively few, listeners grew
used to seeing the same musicians performing under the flags of
several ensembles, each of which either explored a different corner
of the repertory or helped bring to life a different leader's
interpretive ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pool of musicians able to turn out polished, technically
first-rate performances on period instruments in the United States
is large enough to support active early-music scenes on both
coasts. Yet the urge to regroup apparently remains as strong among
early-music players as among jazz musicians.
</P>
<P>
   La Luna, a quartet that specializes in baroque chamber music, is
a group drawn from other groups, and rather far-flung ones. Ingrid
Mathews, one of the two violinists, is the music director of the
Seattle Baroque Orchestra, and the quartet's harpsichordist, Byron
Schenckman, is the Seattle group's artistic director. The other
violinist, Scott Metcalfe, and the cellist, Emily Walhout, are
members of the King's Noyse, a Renaissance ensemble based in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   La Luna made its public debut at the Boston Early Music Festival
in 1995, and since then has toured and made recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The Frick Collection, which has an unimpeachable record of
spotting fine period-instrument bands early in their careers,
presented La Luna in its New York debut on Wednesday afternoon. The
program was devoted to 17th-century Italian composers, both famous
(Frescobaldi, Rossi, Marini and Cavalli) and obscure (Falconieri,
Selma y Salaverde, Fontana and Castello), and it offered a thorough
examination of this ensemble's considerable strengths as well as
the charms of the repertory.
</P>
<P>
   The works at hand _ canzonas, sonatas, fantasias and assorted
dance movements _ were composed to entertain by way of a form of
virtuosity that was subtle compared with that of romantic times.
Where romantic virtuosity seeks to evoke a sense of the heroic, or
at least, the larger than life, the baroque variety is about
inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   It would be incorrect to say that technical polish is beside the
point. Falconieri's and Marini's violin lines and Frescobaldi's
keyboard writing made great demands. But what dazzles in these
works is not so much the grand gesture as the tiny one _ the
fleetness of a passing embellishment, for example, or the deftness
with which two strands of counterpoint are wound together.
</P>
<P>
   La Luna played its program with an involving zestiness. Matthews
and Metcalf each produced a distinctive violin sound _ hers was
brighter, his had a viola's depth _ that worked particularly well
in trio sonatas where the two lines had a conversational give and
take. Matthews often seemed to have the edge when the music
demanded agility, although in the florid passage work of the
Fontana Sonata No. 17, Metcalf easily matched the clarity and
shapeliness of her ornamentation.
</P>
<P>
   Baroque works often require a cellist to provide only a steady
bass line, mirrored and expanded upon by the harpsichord, but La
Luna chose works _ a gallarda by Falconieri and a sonata by Marini,
for example _ that gave Walhout a bit more to do. She executed her
soloistic moments deftly and with an appealingly rounded tone. And
Schenkman brought a dramatic interpretive touch to a handful of
Frescobaldi solo works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
