<HEADER>
A5907 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-AWOL-OFFICER-HNS &LR;      08-18 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AWOL-OFFICER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILITARY INTELLIGENCE OFFICIAL ACCUSED OF DESERTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ U.S. officials are seeking the return of a former
Army Reserve intelligence unit commander accused of deserting his
post.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Jeremiah J. Mattysse, who is now in Israel, has been
investigated here for activities that included allegations of a
liaison with a mistress. Until February, he led the U.S. Army
Intelligence Support Center at Camp Bullis, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse has been charged with desertion, absence without leave
and conduct unbecoming an officer after failing to return to duty
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Hanley, a spokesman for the U.S. Army Reserve Command,
would not elaborate on Mattysse, whose unit had access to
classified information produced by the CIA and other intelligence
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is basically a case of an individual who has not reported
to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the Pentagon, State Department, Army Reserve
Command headquarters in Little Rock, Ark., and Israel have been in
contact over the disappearance of Mattysse.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry into Mattysse's conduct began as a result of a
relationship he had with a married woman, Hanley said. He declined
to discuss details about her.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Mattysse's military intelligence background, ``We've
taken reasonable and prudent steps to ensure that the security of
the military intelligence mission remains as high as it ever is,''
Hanley said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse, 49, commanded the unit, a facility in which Army
Reserve intelligence specialists are trained, until his
reassignment as a special projects officer with the 90th Regional
Support Group in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hanley stressed that Mattysse was charged with just three
violations of the Uniform Code of Military Justice after failing to
return to the unit, he said: ``As in any case, the possibility of
additional charges always exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse has been AWOL since Aug. 8, when he failed to report
back from leave, and now is in Israel, Army spokesman Russ Oaks
said.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said the U.S. government is working
with the Israeli government to secure Mattysse's return.
</P>
<P>
   A number of officials said they did not know if Mattysse is
Jewish or could claim Israeli citizenship. But Israel has
extradition arrangements with the United States and has returned
Americans in the past, said Mark Regev, a spokesman for the Israeli
Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, he said, will ``cooperate fully. We always do with the
Americans on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse was accused by his estranged wife, Vanda, of having an
illicit affair with a San Antonio woman. A divorce complaint Vanda
Mattysse filed March 7 in Albemarle County, Va., claimed he not
only had the affair, but also spent ``thousands of dollars on his
paramour.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse's San Antonio lawyer, William A. Wilson, cited
attorney-client privilege in declining to discuss the case. Vanda
Mattysse's Charlottesville, Va., attorney, Patricia M. Brady, did
not return a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse's father, Curtis James Banker Sr., said late Wednesday
he had not talked with his son and did not know his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Banker, of Plattsburgh, N.Y., said he gave Army investigators
the same information when he recently talked with them.
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse was born Curtis James Banker Jr. on Sept. 29, 1950, but
later changed his name.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Sig Christenson by e-mail at sigc(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
