<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-KURZON-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCE, BY AN EX-PUNK ROCKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 20) 
 By ABBY ELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing you learn quickly about Ken Kurson, who as founder and
editor of Green magazine has become the financial mentor for the
Limp Bizkit set: he does not have an ounce of pretension. He is
slightly rumpled, chronically bemused. A mischievous glint leaps
out of his eye during a conversation. He always looks ready to hop
on his Vespa motorcycle to take a friend on his ``Sopranos'' tour
of New Jersey. And that's precisely the point.
</P>
<P>
   Kurson, who is 31, has made personal finance palatable for
people who might otherwise believe that it belongs on the shelf
with Geritol and Dentu-Creme. He derives enormous pleasure from
explaining in everyday language the murky world of stock indexes,
P/E ratios and betas.
</P>
<P>
   His common-sense views _ already heard in his guest appearances
on CNN, CNNfn, ABC, MSNBC and National Public Radio's
``Marketplace'' _ are getting a wider audience. Early last month,
Green began providing two articles a week to the business section
of Salon, the online magazine. Also in July, he began twice-a-week
appearances on ZDTV, the Ziff-Davis cable channel, directly from
Green's offices. Next month, United Feature Syndicate (Peanuts,
Manners, Dilbert, etc.) will begin selling a weekly package of
Green content to newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, all this is not Money for Morons. For all his
glibness, Kurson is very serious _ passionate, really _ about
showing young people the money. ``Five years ago, I paid a couple
hundred bucks for the trademark to the phrase `Personal Finance for
the Unashamed,' and that's who Green is for _ those who don't care
how cool it is to admit they care about their lives and their
futures,'' he said at a restaurant near his Midtown Manhattan
offices. His advice is wide-ranging. He adheres to the idea that an
investor should subtract his age from 100 and invest the remainder,
as a percentage, in stocks. But he says a sector fund can be a good
compromise between the passivity of investing in a general mutual
fund and the ``take-chargedness of individual stock-picking.''
</P>
<P>
   In the preface to his book, ``The Green Magazine Guide to
Personal Finance,'' (Doubleday, 1998), he wrote: ``It's not about
the ability to quit your job at any moment or to jet off to suave
locales. It's about knowing that you have some control over the
things that matter to you. It's about working at a job because you
love it, because it elevates you, instead of because you're deeply
in debt, stuck with rent you can't afford or so afraid of investing
you bury your savings in jars, scattered around the backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurson does have the backyard, if not the jars. He lives in
Montclair, N.J., with his wife, Rebecca, a literary agent. He keeps
the Vespa and a Harley Davidson in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   David Granger, editor in chief of Esquire, saw Kurson's
noncomformist streak in full color as soon as he chose him to write
a monthly money column, ``Green,'' in 1997. ``The day I told him he
got the job, he went out and dyed his hair orange,'' Granger
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But then Kurson has always believed that money matters should be
fun. ``I've never met anybody who thought they could bring joy to
people by telling them how to spend and save it,'' Granger said.
``He might be the only financial writer in the world who makes that
part of his mission. He has a real feeling that understanding
personal finance can improve people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurson says his financial skills date from the late 1980s, when
he played the bass in a Chicago punk rock band called _ you guessed
it _ Green. He ended up in charge of the band's books and
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he headed to New York, figuring to get into journalism,
and landed internships and jobs at Rolling Stone, Harper's and
Worth. (He had attended the University of Chicago for two years,
but he calls college ``soul-deadening.'')
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he began publishing an irreverent eight-page
publication, calling it The Kenny Quarterly, which he furtively
photocopied at his day job as an editor at United Media and
distributed to friends in need of financial advice. Its one and
only issue was a hit _ especially among investment professionals
who in turn gave it to friends and family who hadn't previously
found discourse about Simplified Employee Pensions particularly
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, he and his best friend, John Packel, turned The
Kenny Quarterly into Green. It now has a paid circulation of
25,000, with enhanced prospects for growth since Eastern
Distributors, a major magazine handler, recently agreed to handle
it. The Web site has 335,000 unique users, according to PCData
Reports last month.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the magazine and the Web site,
www.greenmagazine.com, were bought by Ilife..com (formerly
Intelligent Life), based in North Palm Beach, Fla., and the owner
of financial sites including Bankrate.com, for about $830,000 in
cash and stock, plus options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I doing well? Absolutely,'' he said. ``My dad was a
traveling salesman of motorcycle parts. Some years were good;
others we had to sell our piano and all our furniture. I probably
make more than he ever did. But I'm poorer than 90 percent of the
people I've interviewed in my career as a business journalist. I'm
on the phone all day with people, many of whom are brilliant and
hard-working but plenty of whom are lazy dunces _ who spend more
than my annual income on wine.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees few limits to young people's appetite for what he is
serving up. ``The Internet has changed just about everything,'' he
said. ``Not the fundamentals of corporate economics, but the way we
live. Green is for a person who essentially didn't exist as
recently as 10 years ago: the guy who likely won't stay in a job
long enough to learn where the bathroom is, let alone retire with a
gold watch; the gal who never wanted to learn the word mutual fund
and suddenly finds herself controlling a substantial sum of money
that can be invested in any of 7,923 funds, or thousands of stocks.
These are people whose parents told them even less about money
management than they did about religion and sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, despite his anti-establishment roots, will he apologize for
being a die-hard capitalist. ``I write about money for two
reasons,'' he said. ``It fascinates me, and it is the most powerful
way for people I care about to enact the kinds of lives they want
and deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
