<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-RONISIZE     08-18 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-RONISIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: MESMERIZING SOUNDS FROM EAST TO WEST ON A SUMMER
NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anoushka Shankar's father, Ravi Shankar, learned what it was
like to play Indian classical music for uncomprehending audiences
at 1960s rock festivals like Monterey Pop and Woodstock. Ms.
Shankar, who is 19, had her version of the experience on Thursday
night at Central Park Summerstage, where she shared a bill with
Roni Size's band, Reprazent, a dance-music dynamo.
</P>
<P>
   The audience that packed every square foot of Rumsey Playfield
was there for Size's feverish drum-and-bass propulsion, and it
eventually got exactly what it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Reprazent merges human and machine, with Size and three fellow
disc jockeys (Krust, Die and Suv) working computer consoles behind
Rob Merrill on drums, Si John on bass, a singer, Onallee, and a
rapper, MC Dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   They take the relentless computerized beat of drum-and-bass,
which has threatened to become a dance-music cliche, and partly
humanize it with a flesh-and-blood rhythm section. At the same
time, they pile on so many samples and effects that the music turns
dizzying and enveloping. Each sound has been shaped to create
maximum disorientation. Notes began with one timbre, only to mutate
and distort a fraction of a second later; sounds echoed all around
the beat, toying with time perception.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing nonstop music, like a dance disc jockey,
Reprazent performed discrete songs drawn from its 1997 album, ``New
Forms'' (Mercury) and its coming one, ``In the Mode'' (Def Jam), to
be released on Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new material moved toward hip-hop and
rhythm-and-blues. ``Who Told You'' picked up the blunt beat and
plinking synthesizer of Detroit ghetto-tech, with MC Dynamite
rapping in sync with the bass drum; ``Lucky Pressure'' had Onallee
singing rhythm-and-blues verses and refrains over a backdrop of
melancholy string-orchestra chords and the fast beat. But the core
of the music was its hurtling momentum and aural density, an
ominous thrill ride through a barrage of perfectly placed zingers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shankar gracefully handled a crowd that treated her ragas as
a backdrop to conversation. Before one piece, she gently asked
people to be a little quieter during the slow, exploratory
introductions to the ragas because she couldn't hear herself. She
kept those preludes fairly short, floating their wisps of melody.
Then she was joined by two tabla drummers, Bikram Ghosh and Tanmoy
Bose, for the faster, flashier sections of the ragas; they engaged
Ms. Shankar and each other in quick volleys.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shankar started her career performing alongside her father,
who is also her teacher, and her impressive technique drew
immediate praise. But she was playing music she had memorized,
while Indian classical music revolves around improvisation.
Performing on her own, she has begun to improvise, and her
inexperience shows.
</P>
<P>
   Like her father, she plays long lines of what would be
eighth-notes in Western notation. But where her father makes those
phrases jab and strike, Ms. Shankar does not yet match his
flexibility of rhythm and pitch or his aggressive sense of
direction. But she's fast-fingered and sure, and when she and the
drummers chased each other through her speedy finales, conversation
gave way to applause. To connect the disparate styles, the concert
included Asian underground dance music, which blends electronic
dance beats with traditional voices and drumming from India and
Pakistan. A short set presented a trans-Atlantic alliance: the disc
jockey Siraiki, from the New York Asian underground parties called
Mutiny, and Chandrasonic, the Asian Dub Foundation in England,
traded drones, hovering voices and breakneck drum-and-bass beats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
