<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-0819-COX     08-18 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, LIEBERMAN EMBARK ON CAMPAIGN DOWN MISSISSIPPI TARGETING
MIDWEST
 &HT;    (775&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER _ Democratic presidential nominee Al
Gore, and running mate Joseph Lieberman embarked on a four-day trip
down the majestic Mississippi River on Friday, trying to catch a
wave of political momentum in the wake of the Democratic Party's
national convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Their voyage, on a 120-foot boat named after legendary author
and humorist Mark Twain, coincided with the first sign that Gore's
issue-filled acceptance speech may have given the vice president an
important boost in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   NBC-TV's overnight poll of 500 likely voters showed Gore with 46
percent, Republican presidential nominee George Bush with 43
percent and Green Party nominee Ralph Nader with 7 percent. The
margin of error was +/- 4.4 percent. NBC's overnight poll after
Bush's acceptance speech at the GOP convention two weeks ago had
Bush at 44 percent and Gore at 41 percent, with the same margin of
error.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane was elated by the latest
poll, but cautioned against reading too much into it. ``The polls
are going to bounce around a lot over the next two weeks,'' he
said, underscoring the importance of the presidential nominee's
decision to quickly begin campaigning in these Midwest swing
states. Although President Clinton carried the crucial Midwest in
both 1992 and 1996, Gore has consistently trailed Bush in polls
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ticket boarded the triple-decker Mark Twain in La
Crosse, Wis., Friday morning, having raced from Los Angeles on Air
Force Two to arrive on the banks of the Mississippi River around
dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Just 12 hours earlier, Gore had accepted his party's
presidential nomination with a 50-minute speech in which he not
only contrasted himself with Bush on a variety of issues but vowed
to usher in a ``new time'' of opportunity for American families.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of La Cross residents gave Gore, Lieberman and their
wives a spirited send-off at sun-drenched Riverside Park with a
rally of music, balloons, confetti, barbershop-style acapella
singers and a white-suited Mark Twain impersonator.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, his voice showing slight signs of wear after an intense
two weeks of campaigning, said special interests have erected a
``mighty wall of resistance'' to the changes he has promised if
elected president.
</P>
<P>
   But with Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin sharing the stage
with him, Gore reiterated the importance of one change _ campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here knows that our democracy must be reclaimed from
special interests,'' he said. ``We want to give it back to the
people. And we have to get all of the special interest money out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Feingold is the Democratic co-sponsor of the campaign finance
reform measure introduced by Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who gave
Bush a tougher-than-expected contest for the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, fresh from a four-day convention that tried to rekindle
the ``New Frontier'' spirit of John F. Kennedy, also struck a
Kennedyesque tone in his riverside remarks, summoning younger
voters to ``allow yourself to believe'' in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of where you stand, get involved and allow yourself
to participate fully with your heart,'' he said. ``We have always,
in every generation, had enough men and women and young people who
have been willing to come forward and say: 'This is our country, it
is the best in the world: the hope of human kind.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before boarding the riverboat, Gore shook hands with hundreds of
supporters, often reaching four-people deep into the crowd to grab
hands as a U.S. Secret Service agent held him by the belt to
prevent him from toppling forward.
</P>
<P>
   He hugged Denise Hedrick Mulvaney, a 31-year-old nurse from
nearby Sparta. ``I'm pregnant, and my baby book is going to say: Al
Gore was president wnapped photos while Gore, Lieberman and
Hadassah Lieberman clapped and pumped their arms in the air to the
beat of a rock classic, ``Proud Mary,'' with its well-known refrain
of ``rollin' on the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore declined an invitation from photographers to pose at the
bow of the ship with arms spread, like Leonardo DeCaprio's
character in the Academy Award winning movie, ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong metaphor,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The trip down the Mississippi, which ends Monday night with an
arrival in Twain's boyhood home of Hannibal, Mo., will take the two
politicians through media markets in five Midwestern states that
could swing either for the Gore or Bush tickets this fall:
Minnesota, Wisconsin, Iowa, Illinois and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But the churning waters of the Mississippi, its lush green banks
and the gleaming white Mark Twain, outfitted with a red faux paddle
wheel and patriotic red, white and blue bunting, provided the Gore
campaign _ and news organizations _ with spectacular images of the
vice president and his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't all imagery.
</P>
<P>
   On board the boat's sunny deck, Gore and Lieberman led a
floating town hall meeting with local citizens, discussing the vice
president's proposal to use $250 billion of projected budget
surpluses over the next 10 years to provide prescription drug
benefits under the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the discussion, Gore noted that he got less
than three hours sleep en route from Los Angeles. To stay awake, he
said, he had used up ``two or three of those daily Diet Coke
rations'' _ his preference to coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said of Gore: ``I'd put this guy with two and a half
hours sleep against anybody with a full night's sleep, and I think
he'd make more sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's hitting his stride,'' Karenna Gore Schiff, the
candidate's daughter, told reporters as the Mark Twain made its way
southward for a dockside rally planned Friday night in Prairie du
Chien, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
