<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE UNEMPLOYMENT RISES DESPITE ECONOMIC SLOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' jobless rate inched up to 2.9 percent in
July, staying below 3 percent for the fifth straight month, despite
creeping evidence that the nation's economy is slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment, recorded at 2.6 percent in June, remained well
below the US rate of 4.0 percent in July, the state reported
Friday. During these boom times for job growth, the Commonwealth
has fared better than the nation as a whole for more than five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy remains strong and our companies are creating a
record number of jobs,'' Governor Paul Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts added 7,400 new jobs last month, led by the
service sector, which saw its biggest gain since December 1994.
Resident employment stood at nearly 3.2 million _ as it did in
January _ while total jobs rose to a record high of nearly 3.3
million, up 1.7 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the July gains were attributed to the Sail Boston 2000
festivities, which boosted jobs in recreation services.
</P>
<P>
   Job gains also were logged in the finance, insurance, and real
estate sector, as 1,500 new positions followed a two-month
contraction. Manufacturing counted 2,600 fewer jobs in July,
largely due to traditional summer vacation shutdowns in the
southeastern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Construction added 500 jobs in July, despite a slowdown in the
white-hot housing market regionally and across the country. The
sector had lost 1,500 jobs in June.
</P>
<P>
   Home building has slowed down as a result of higher interest
rates, said Larry Horowitz, senior US economist at Primark Decision
Economics. But mortgage rates are back below 8 percent, he said,
concluding, ``The floor is not going to drop out of the housing
market any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists are still trying to assess the impact more modest
growth will have on the economy. Purchases of appliances and other
large items have slowed somewhat with the decrease in home buying,
but recent government data show that consumers have hardly zipped
up their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Department data showed the June trade grap widening to
a record $30.6 billion, as Americans lapped up imports, from South
African diamonds and Japanese cars to Asian TVs and VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending growth did slow down in the second quarter, to
3 percent from 7.5 percent, Horowitz said. But he expects that to
rise to 3.5 percent this quarter. Retail sales picked up 0.7
percent last month, for the fastest pace in five months.
</P>
<P>
   Factors affecting spending _ and ultimately jobs _ include high
gas prices, Horowitz said, as well as a less euphoric stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much less of the so-called wealth effect,'' he
observed, ``because markets have been volatile, and people have
wondered a lot more about what they're really worth.''
</P>
<P>
   The mounting signs of a slower economic pace, plus recent
evidence that productivity is still on the rise, are expected to
prevent the Federal Reserve from raising interest rates at next
week's policy meeting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
