<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-SHOUTMAIL-BOS &LR;      08-18 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SHOUTMAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM HASTENS TO COMPETE IN VOICE-ACCESSED E-MAIL MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With a new deal in hand to provide voice-powered access
to the popular Lycos Web portal, the Chestnut Hill company formerly
known as Shoutmail is moving to branch out from its roots providing
a telephone-based electronic mail service that has quickly amassed
more than 1 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Now called Mobilee Inc., the 40-person company is gearing up to
take on emerging ``voice portal'' players such as TellMe and
Quack.com.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next several weeks Lycos will use Mobilee to roll out
a new nationwide service offering access to Lycos content, such as
stock quotes, weather reports, and movie listings over telephones
through speech-synthesis technology.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication that voice-enabled access to Internet content
has gone from a novelty to an intensely competitive field,
privately held Mobilee, working with California-based speech
technology provider Nuance, is replacing Quack as the voice-access
partner for Lycos, the fourth most-visited Web portal.
</P>
<P>
   Mobilee, which was founded in 1998, last autumn launched a way
to get voice mail without necessarily owning a computer, by
offering accounts where subscribers dial in to hear their e-mails
read to them by a speech robot and can respond by dictating ``wave
files'' sent back to the e-mail sender.
</P>
<P>
   Mobilee president Jacob Guedalia said the company now reports
over 1 million subcribers for the free e-mail service. It has begun
branching into what it calls ``phonecasting,'' or development of
news and information people hear by calling in from a wireless or
landline phone, and both services are supported by advertising
revenues from short ad spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've developed an infrastructure for our own applications,
but now we've built it to a scale where we can directly offer it to
partners,'' Guedalia said.
</P>
<P>
   A Quack spokesman characterized the divorce from Lycos as a
situation where ``both companies have mutually decided to work
separately'' and said Quack ``remains the early leader in
voice-to-Web solutions for businesses'' and will have new
partnerships to announce soon.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos spokesman Brian Payea said the company would make no
comment on why it was dumping Quack. ``All we're saying is that the
contract was terminated, but we can say Mobilee had some very
compelling technological advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   Those include a wide-ranging nationwide network of over 500
local phone numbers initially set up for Shoutmail where people can
call to hear Lycos content read aloud, which is far less expensive
than the toll-free 800 numbers used by some voice portals. Guedalia
said using local numbers can cost 1/10th as much as 800 numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Payea also cited the existing base of 1 million Shoutmail
customers as a crucial springboard for attracting an audience for
Lycos content delivered by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers will be able to use the Lycos portal to create a
personalized list of information sources they want to be able to
hear by calling over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sege, Lycos executive vice president, said that ``Mobilee's
technology platform is the best available anywhere, and we're
excited to be working together with them to make the Web more
accessible than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, of Waltham, Mass., had planned to roll out the voice
portal in the autumn quarter through its Quack contract. ``We have
not lost any time'' by replacing Quack with Mobilee, Payea said.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos shares closed at $60.0625, down 25 cents, in trading on
the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
