<SLUG> BC-BOX-SANCHEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICAL MOMENT FOR CHALLENGER SANCHEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ For years, Augie Sanchez has been known as
the guy who suffered a narrow defeat to Floyd Mayweather in the
finals of the 1996 US Olympic boxing trials.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, of Las Vegas, could vault into the mainstream Saturday
night should he defeat unbeaten WBO featherweight champion Prince
Naseem Hamed (34-0, 30 knockouts) at Foxwoods Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, what kind of entrance will Sanchez make.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up 20 minutes late for a press conference Thursday,
angering Hamed, who is known for his lavish prefight entrances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who am I waiting for? Why am I waiting?'' yelled Hamed.
``Where's Augie Sanchez?''
</P>
<P>
   Word has it the 21-year-old Sanchez (26-1, 24 KOs) was late in
part because he and his wife were carded at the casino entrance
because they looked so young and were forced to take a back
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed, whose ring entrances often take up to 10 minutes, vowed
Friday to cut back on some of the routine in an effort to get into
the ring faster. Friday, he expected the same punctuality from his
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey man, how you doing, you OK?'' Hamed asked Sanchez after he
finally arrived. Then, while shaking his hand, Hamed asked, ``How
come you're so late?''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez spent the remainder of the press conference absorbing
barbs from the extroverted champ. But at one point, he turned to
Hamed and said, ``Shut your mouth. Know your role.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamed's handlers are already talking about upcoming bouts,
particuarly eagerly awaited fights against Marco Antonio Barrera
and Eric Morales, two of the top super bantamweights.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez might play a big role in altering Hamed's plans. His
most-noted victory came May 8, 1999, when he scored a seventh-round
knockout of former featherweight champion Jorge Paez.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a name change on Saturday,'' said Fred
Sterburg, Sanchez's manager. ``Prince will be formerly known as the
champ.''
</P>
<P>
   The telecast begins at 9:30 p.m. with the main event expected to
begin by 10:45. The undercard includes Lowell's Micky Ward (35-9,
26 KOs) against Antonio Diaz (32-2, 22 KOs).
</P>
</TEXT>
