<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Aug. 19 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service night
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Undated) _ After four days of silence and a ceding of the
spotlight to the Democrats and Al Gore, George W. Bush finally
responds _ and on Al Gore's home turf, no less. The event was in
Memphis, Tenn. And the tit-for-tat of Gore's speech and Bush's
response will show how the battle lines are drawn right now,
heading into the fall. In his speech, Bush took pointed jabs at
Gore. He accused him of fomenting ``class warfare'' in aligning
himself with the people vs. the powerful. He ridiculed Gore's list
of promises as a list of all the things that he and Clinton never
got done. He said Gore was not a credible person on the issue of
campaign finance reform, and said that his first priority in office
would be education, not campaign finance. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-VOICES (Various datelines to come) _ Reactions from around
the country to the Democratic Convention and to Al Gore. (Bylines
to come)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ASSESS (Washington) _ When he accepted the Republican
presidential nomination in Philadelphia two weeks ago, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas skipped lightly over a few issues _ taxes, Social
Security, education, nuclear weapons _ and then got to his topic
sentence: ``We must usher in an era of responsibility.'' In Los
Angeles on Thursday night, Vice President Al Gore took the opposite
approach. Declaring that ``the presidency is more than a popularity
contest,'' he said, ``I am here to talk seriously about the
issues.'' And that he did, one issue after another, as if he were
delivering a State of the Union Message and not speaking to a
political convention, so that by the time he finished, there could
be no doubt where he stood on virtually every important matter
before the federal government. A news analysis by David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-IMMIG (Zagreb, Croatia) _ The Yugoslav government of
Slobodan Milosevic has opened the floodgates to thousands of
Chinese immigrants intent on reaching Western Europe, immigrations
officials here say. By granting tourist visas to all comers in
China, Belgrade has become the latest gateway to Europe for human
trafficking. The accounts of detainees here appear to confirm the
growing alarm among Western diplomats and migration officials that
a sophisticated and far-reaching network of human traffickers from
Asia has switched its attention from the United States and is now
targeting Europe. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   VODKA-SMUGGLE (Undated) _ A number of distilleries in the United
States are under criminal investigation in a scheme to illegally
ship pure grain alcohol to Russia disguised as hair tonic. Its
cheaper and easier to export goods like windshield-wiper fluid into
Russia, and the Russians don't seem to mind drinking pure grain
alcohol labeled as vodka. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   OED-IN-AMERICA (Undated) _ When the Oxford English Dictionary
decided to open a North American office this year to document the
evolution of American English from the thick of it, it engaged a
young American lexicographer with impeccable credentials who also
happened to be the author of a 288-page book on a certain
unmentionable word. Jesse Sheidlower, known far beyond the
anonymous world of dictionary-making as an energetic and accessible
expert on neologisms and slang, now sits ensconced in a building in
Old Saybrook, Conn., which the OED shares with a hearing-aid
company and a dentist, and toils over how best to define terms like
``McMansion,'' ``chowhound'' and ``jiggy.'' By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,4.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NORTH-POLE (Undated) _ Developments on global warming. By
John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT19.
</P>
