<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5942 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-NANCY-DREW0819-COX     08-18 2242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANCY-DREW0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Case of The Nancy Drew Fans
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ She is pluck. She is guts. She is
cleverness personified.
</P>
<P>
   She is a speedy but safe driver, an immaculate dresser, an
All-American beauty and a Jill of all trades.
</P>
<P>
   She is Nancy Drew, the ``girl detective'' who represents so much
to so many, and this year she turns 70.
</P>
<P>
   A triple threat, Nancy Drew possesses the deductive reasoning of
Jessica Fletcher, the track record of Miss Marple and the physical
daring of V.I. Warshawski. Along with loyal chums Bess and George,
Nancy formed an early prototype of Charlie's Angels _ without the
jiggle, but with just as much fashion sense.
</P>
<P>
   We recently invited readers to dish about Nancy Drew, and almost
75 fans, ages 8 to 78, responded. What made Nancy everyone's
favorite strawberry-blond sleuth? No mystery here.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like Barbie with brains,'' writes Sabra Ingeman of
Tequesta.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy lived the dream-house life, all right, says Allyson
Samiljan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't drive a regular car, she `motored' in a `roadster';
she never just had lunch, but ate `luncheon' . . . and instead of
wearing ordinary dresses or shorts, like we did in South Florida,
Nancy sported beautiful `frocks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What some truly envied, however, was Nancy's independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had the freedom of roving around, which most of us in the
1940s and late 1930s did not have,'' recalls Fran Leppowitz.
``Nancy Drew was the person I wanted to be like when I grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   COPYCAT DETECTIVES
</P>
<P>
   Some little girls did grow up to be like Nancy Drew.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Betty Preble.
</P>
<P>
   After reading, say, ``The Mystery at Lilac Inn'' or ``The Secret
of Red Gate Farm,'' any pedestrian or vehicle was fair game for
Preble's active imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask myself, `Is that a burglar casing out the
neighborhood _ or a pervert lurking for children?' I would write
down the license numbers and the descriptions of the `suspect' and
watch them in case anything unusual ever happened. Much to my
disappointment, it never did.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward. Preble becomes a sheriff's deputy in Texas while
earning degrees in law enforcement and criminal justice. Returns to
home state of Florida, opens a private detective agency in Port St.
Lucie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still write down license-plate numbers of suspicious
vehicles in my neighborhood,'' she says. ``But now, I can run them
to find out who the vehicle is registered to, their address, if
they have any criminal history record and/or are a sexual predator
_ and I'm absolutely thrilled if no crime ever takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   INFLUENCED CAREERS
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hetzel also earned a bachelor's degree in criminal
justice, but one night when she was 16, she pretended she was on
the wrong side of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving around with my girlfriends and a police car
started following us,'' remembers Hetzel. ``I did what Nancy Drew
did. I made a couple of quick turns, pulled into a driveway, cut
the lights, and we all ducked down. It worked! The police car drove
right past.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy inspired career choices, too, among girls who did not
enter law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Blake has been a Nancy fan since the mid-'60s. ``When we
visited friends with older homes, I used to tap on walls and
inspect the woodwork, looking for secret compartments and sliding
doors,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Now Blake is a critical care nurse. ``Trying to figure out why a
patient has certain symptoms or what those lab results mean
definitely requires detective work.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Claire Alfano Hill had been fascinated by ``the
plucky, clever, brave Nancy, who seemed to have unlimited
independence in an age when Italian-American teenaged girls like me
were barely allowed out of the sight of our parents.''
</P>
<P>
   As a graduate student in Boston, Hill was drawn to a summer job
at a detective agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the summer typing the reports of the `operatives' and
begging to be sent out on a case. It was the `Summer of Love' in
Boston, runaways and hippie types on every corner, and as it turned
out, totally by accident, I did finally end up solving a mystery,
`The Case of My Runaway Cousin.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I became my idol.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SOME OF NANCY'S YOUNG FANS SAY ABOUT HER TODAY
</P>
<P>
   _ Autumn Perdue, 9: ``Nancy teaches you to stop and think things
through. She tests your mind and lets you help her in the cases,
and right when you think you know who it is . . . it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Katie Johnson, 9: ``Nancy Drew Notebooks are better for kids 7
years old through 10 because in the books Nancy's 8 years old. I
like Nancy Drew Notebooks because . . . I picture myself in Nancy's
place.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Faith Peak, 14: ``Nancy is creative, smart, funny and can get
herself and her friends out of a jam because she is so clever. I
think many girls like her because the story can take them places,
in their minds, they can't go otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   INSPIRED LOVE OF READING
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1934, little Irene Parent was confined to a
sanatorium after she was diagnosed with bone tuberculosis. She
seldom saw her family during her 8-year stay.
</P>
<P>
   The antidote to her loneliness? A towering metal cabinet filled
with donated books, including Nancy Drew mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``How amazed and delighted I was over the gift of a roadster to
her by her father! What richness! How cleverly Nancy discovered
``The Secret of the Old Clock'' and continued her sleuthing by
unsealing ``The Hidden Staircase,'' remembers Parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was she who first inspired my love of reading, a love which
helped me through my years away from home; a love which endures
still, into my 74th year.''
</P>
<P>
   When bed rest was ordered, many young girls reached for Nancy
Drew.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, 9-year-old Carol Robertson was confined to bed for six
months with rheumatic fever. An older cousin introduced her to
Nancy Drew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first book was a hand-me-down, and she had no others, so I
begged my mother for another Nancy Drew book. Soon everyone was
buying them for me, and I was reading them faster and faster,''
says Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could read one a day _ I had nothing else to do _ and at
last my mother begged me to read slower or reread some as it was
costing too much.''
</P>
<P>
   A TREASURED PRIZE
</P>
<P>
   During the Great Depression, books were a decided luxury for
some families.
</P>
<P>
   Ethel Cohen was entering the sixth grade at P.S. 67 in New York
City, and on thar's end. Doc Savage for the boy, Nancy Drew for the
girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, how I wanted to win!'' Cohen remembers. ``As the term
progressed, the competition became keener and keener and finally
narrowed down to Zella and I.'' With each test, they compared
marks. ``We both tried our hardest to be the best, most helpful
citizen in the class.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the last day of school. ``When my name was called as
the best girl, I was ecstatic. The applause resounded in my ears. I
stood up, knees shaking, made my way to the front of the class on
Cloud Nine and accepted the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book had a blue cover with orange letters spelling out the
title, ``The Secret of the Old Clock.'' I read that book over and
over, treasured it for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zella probably went on to earn a Ph.D. somewhere, winning many
more honors,'' Cohen figures. ``But I had my Nancy Drew.''
</P>
<P>
   SELF-AFFIRMING RESPITE
</P>
<P>
   Bayla Singer did go on to earn a Ph.D. in History of Technology,
and as a young girl, she found Nancy Drew to be an invaluable
literary companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy Drew was a normal girl who happened to be clever,
analytical, independent and responsible, and who was treated with
respect by the adults who knew her,'' says Singer. ``That such a
character could actually appear in a book meant that my parents and
their circle weren't the only adults ready to admit that those
qualities in a girl were both conceivable and admirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Nancy Drew actually had friends her own age, too! What a
comfort to a girl in her pre-teens whose schoolmates teased her
unmercifully for being `smart' and `teacher's pet.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy Drew's existence reassured me that I wasn't a freak, and
that it wasn't `unfeminine' to have brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lavins learned a similar lesson from Miss Drew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only girl in a family with four boys. This was an
atmosphere of noise, confusion and raging testosterone that at
times seemed overwhelming. Naturally, this made me feel somewhat
isolated since I had no interest in the physical games they played
nor did I understand the `no girls allowed' camaraderie that they
and their friends enjoyed and promoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curling up with the latest adventure was my own private
retreat away from the chaos that surrounded me. I savored the
luxury of being in my own room and living vicariously with the
adventures of my heroine. These stories were my first indication
that I could do anything that I wanted and that I was not some
inferior type of human being.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that I did not have the brawn of my brothers, but over
time I came to accept that I had the brains of my fictional
counterpart,'' Lavins says.
</P>
<P>
   HOW NANCY ENCOURAGED RISKY BEHAVIOR AMONG SOME READERS . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I am a 78-year-old woman who read and loved all the Nancy
Drew books beginning on her 8th birthday. My favorite ploy was when
invited to a friend's birthday party, I would purchase a couple of
said books for 50 cents each and before wrapping them I would
avidly read them from cover to cover.'' _ Beth Reifman
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I am both ashamed and pleased that Nancy Drew was the reason
I, as a pre-teen in the mid-'50s, cut school. I did this when I
managed to get my hands on a new book because I wanted to prop up
in bed, chomp on a delicious apple and absorb every word of this
compelling detective that was about my same age. I would read the
book start to finish in one sitting, then quickly recover to attend
school the next day.'' _ Joella Cain
</P>
<P>
   _ ``In bed at night, I would hide under the blanket with a
flashlight and read the night away. When inevitably caught, my
mother's lecture included telling me that I would ruin my eyes.
Sure enough, I needed glasses at an early age _ could Mother have
been right? If so, it's all Nancy's fault.'' _ Caroline Parrish
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I lived in the country so I had to be imaginative. I would
sneak around my home and my grandparents'. I would quietly come in
the back door and eventually surprise whoever was around. They
would ask what I was doing. `Oh, just doing a little
investigating,' I would say. `Oh, you have been reading Nancy Drew
again!' `Yes, I have!' Oh, those were the years!'' _ Debi Brenner
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My best friend and I have been avid Nancy Drew fans ever
since the third grade in 1950. We would follow anyone we didn't
know or who looked suspicious. We would call the phone number we
found written on phone booth walls to find out who they were. When
we found any paper with anything written on it we would try to
`track it down.' We would accost and interrogate and even try to
bribe 'witnesses' to save the world. I'm really very surprised we
didn't get into real trouble with our sleuthing.'' _ Nancy Zane
</P>
<P>
   AMATEUR SLEUTHS
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Straas Pollak and her friends also played amateur sleuth,
in a tiny Mississippi town.
</P>
<P>
   They were fascinated by a condemned, turn-of-the-century jail,
behind the courthouse on Main Street. ``I decided that someone was
being held hostage in the old jail, so I recruited my friends to
shadow Percy Shaw, the caretaker of the courthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Percy wore a khaki uniform, Pollak dubbed him ``The
Khaki Pants Man'' and even dreamed up a special whistle and tune,
``Here comes the Khaki Pants Man,'' so that the young detectives
could signal one another when Percy made a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several times we gained entry into the old jail, and we would
go up the winding stairs, hearts beating so fast we could barely
breathe, as we knew we were going to find the hostages.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Pollak's uncle was mayor of the town, and when an
informant tipped him off that Pollak and company were spending most
of their days hidden behind a bush, he put an end to the shadowing
of Percy Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mystery of the old jail,'' Pollak says, ``would remain
unsolved.''
</P>
<P>
   A PRIZED GIFT
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than inspiring me to `detect,' Nancy inspired me to
read _ a cherished gift,'' writes Maureen Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the gift of a Nancy Drew book was undeniably the best
present of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my 10th birthday, and I had just unwrapped a beautiful
gold charm bracelet from my grandparents. I glanced at it,'' writes
Ann Romer. ``The next gift was the latest Nancy Drew mystery from
Aunt Arlene and Uncle Eddie. I dove immediately into the book, and
wandered off to my room reading as I climbed the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I traipsed off with my new book, I never even heard my
mother call out, `Ann, thank Papa and Betty for that beautiful
bracelet! Ann? Ann!' ''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of excitement still exists today for 40-year-old
Alicia Ortiz, whose sister gives her five or six Nancy Drews each
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new covers are all slick and new, but I would still love
to find an old complete collection,'' Ortiz says. ``There is just
something about an old worn book that makes you want to curl up and
get lost in it!
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is nothing better than Nancy Drew!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
