<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5946 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-EBAY-POWERSELLERS-$AD     08-18 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-POWERSELLERS-$ADV20-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BUSINESSES REMAKE THE GARAGE-SALE IMAGE OF EBAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Fla., Miss.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 20)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When people think of online auctions, they probably envision
retirees selling bean bags from their basements and collectors
trading baseball cards or limited-edition lunch boxes. After all,
the founder of eBay, Pierre M. Omidyar, and its chief executive,
Meg Whitman, are considered ingenious precisely because they
created the first efficient global marketplace where consumers
could sell directly to one another.
</P>
<P>
   But occasional sellers are hardly what have made eBay, with more
than $87.9 million in online revenue in the second quarter, one of
the most successful Internet businesses to date. Log on to eBay and
you can easily find brand-new air-conditioners, boxes of unused
printer cartridges and cases of 7-inch zippers, all nylon, all
black. Rather than just items destined for garage sales, plenty of
new merchandise is available. ``This is not just mom and pop
cleaning out their attics,'' said Evie Black Dykema, a senior
analyst at Forrester Research. ``There is this whole subeconomy of
small businesses who use eBay.''
</P>
<P>
   The real powers behind eBay's success are those small operators
_ the liquidators, wholesalers, small retail shops and stay-at-home
entrepreneurs _ that offer the bulk of goods for sale on eBay,
underpinning its entire business.
</P>
<P>
   Call them power sellers _ eBay does. By putting dozens of new
items up for sale every day, these sellers keep buyers coming back
to bid and bid again. Of the 4 million items listed on the site on
any given day, the top 20 sellers are responsible for 72,000
listings, and the top 38,000 sellers account for 2.7 million items,
according to AuctionWatch.com, an online auction services company.
At last count, eBay had 15.8 million registered users, or Internet
names for people who use the site to buy or sell or both.
</P>
<P>
   And because power sellers, like all other sellers, pay eBay
listing fees and commissions ranging from 1.25 to 5 percent of the
value of each item sold, they contribute a huge proportion of the
company's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Some sellers list goods on other auction sites, either as an
alternative or supplement to eBay. Yahoo Auctions, the biggest of
those rivals, has 2.5 million listings. But as the first company to
exploit the online auction model, eBay dominates, holding nearly 90
percent of the online auction market, measured by sales. That sheer
volume, said Steven Johnson, director of the e-commerce program at
Andersen Consulting, drives more buyers to eBay, which in turn
attracts even more high-volume sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these overachievers? A power seller, by eBay's
definition, has met at least one of three levels of standards in
volume and customer service _ designated as bronze, silver and
gold. To earn the bronze label, a seller must have minimum monthly
sales of $2,000; for silver, $10,000 a month; for gold, at least
$25,000 a month _ more than many small businesses ever achieve,
online or off. Would-be power sellers must also have received at
least 100 comments from buyers in the feedback forum, where buyers
and sellers rate each others' performance, and 98 percent of their
ratings must be positive.
</P>
<P>
   EBay says it has 20,000 to 25,000 power sellers, though it will
not disclose how many have hit any particular level. But those
numbers do not include people who may be meeting the power-seller
standards but have not had the time or the inclination to join
eBay's program, which offers them perks like full-time customer
service support and permission to display an official power-seller
logo.
</P>
<P>
   EBay declined to disclose financial details about the sellers
who make its business hum. But Andale Inc., an auction management
company in Mountain View, Calif., that provides e-mail tools and
database services to online sellers, has pored over eBay's listings
and determined that 10 percent of eBay's sellers are responsible
for 80 percent of its sales. That 10 percent thus sold about $1
billion of the $1.3 billion worth of toys, jewelry, computers,
sporting goods, real estate and other merchandise that changed
hands on eBay in the last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And they may be making hefty profits. Again, eBay would not give
details of its users' businesses, but a survey conducted by Andale
in March found that sellers made a 40 percent profit margin, on
average. By contrast, many online retailers are not yet in the
black, according to Forrester. According to a report that Forrester
released in April, and based in part on interviews with 50
companies, less than 40 percent of the e-tailers expected to make
money before 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online auctions are a seriously lucrative way to sell,'' said
Munjal Shah, chief executive of Andale. ``There are a whole troop
of merchants that have grown up around that realization.''
</P>
<P>
   For these sellers, there are obvious advantages, mainly that
they can attract buyers without spending money on marketing and
that commissions are low. By contrast, Amazon.com spent about 25
percent of its sales on marketing last year _ and that proportion
is ``significantly lower than everyone else's online,'' according
to Mike May, a senior analyst for Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   EBay's role as an inexpensive marketing channel, however, may
also make it a breeding ground for fraud. The company does not
attempt to police transactions, enabling it to keep its own costs
low. But that raises the possibility that sellers may be hawking
stolen, counterfeit, damaged or fake merchandise on its site. One
dissatisfied buyer is trying to organize a class action suit by
customers who believe they were defrauded by big sellers.
</P>
<P>
   And while some buyers, in comments left on feedback forums, rave
about individual power sellers, others complain that eBay coddles
its power sellers at the expense of buyers.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as eBay thrives, power sellers appear to be here to
stay, and their numbers will probably grow. In recent months, a new
category of businesses has emerged that is dedicated to helping
them. These companies, like Andale, AuctionWorks and
AuctionWatch.com, provide billing and shipping services and
software to track and respond to hundreds of auction listings
simultaneously. ``This has become a real business,'' said Dykema of
Forrester, ``and there are now real tools to manage it.''
</P>
<P>
   So exactly who are these small businesses that use eBay as a
staging ground for e-commerce? Here are four whose revenues meet
power-seller standards.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
