<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUNKEN-SUB-BOS     08-18 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUNKEN-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE CAPSULE CAN'T LOCK ONTO STRICKEN SUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Desperate efforts to save any survivors from a sunken
Russian nuclear submarine met with a new setback Friday when a
rescue capsule reached one of the escape hatches but found it too
damaged to open, rescuers said.
</P>
<P>
   The heartbreaking revelation brought a grim ending to what had
been the most successful attempt at reaching the stricken submarine
Kursk after days of frustration. It all but extinguished hopes that
any of the 118 men on board will be found alive if rescuers finally
manage to get inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to go down until there is no hope left,'' a
visibly weary rescuer told a Russian Television correspondent
aboard the vessel Mikhail Rudnitsky, which is leading the rescue
operation at the site where the Kursk sank in 354 feet of water
during major naval exercises last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two rescuers said that after numerous attempts, a small
submersible finally managed to reach one of the Kursk's two escape
hatches. But it was unable to establish an airtight connection
because the hatch was ``badly damaged,'' one of them told Russian
Television.
</P>
<P>
   The failure cast doubt on hopes that British and Norwegian
rescue teams, expected to arrive late Saturday after Russia at
first declined Western offers of assistance, would fare any better.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Russian officials had said any survivors on the
Kursk would run out of oxygen Friday. But both the commander of
Russia's navy, Admiral Vladimir Kuroyedov, and the senior cabinet
official in charge of the rescue, Deputy Prime Minister Ilya
Klebanov, have now extended by a week their assessments of how long
anyone alive on board could hold out.
</P>
<P>
   Klebanov further dampened hopes of a happy ending when he
described a ``terrifying hole'' on the starboard side of the
forward part of the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rather big part of the crew was in the part of the boat that
was hit by a catastrophe that developed at lightning speed,''
Klebanov told reporters in Murmansk, home of the Russian Northern
Fleet where the Kursk was based.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no sounds for quite a long time'' from within
the Kursk, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of docking with the Kursk is complicated by
currents of up to 1.8 knots, naval officials said, as well as the
vessel's 20-degree tilt. This angle is much less than the 60 degree
tilt the Russians had described until Friday, but still enough to
cause rescue capsules to slide off the hull.
</P>
<P>
   Just how difficult the docking procedure has been became clear
when Russian Television filmed a crew lowering one of the rescue
submersibles onto its berth on the Mikhail Rudnitsky. The process
is similar to what the pilot has to do to latch onto the Kursk:
guide his submersible so that a specially designed hatch on its
bottom lands squarely onto the escape hatch of the sunken
submarine. On board the Mikhail Rudnitsky, the process required a
crane, a half dozen men, and several tries to guide the submersible
into place. Under water, the pilot of the submersible has to guide
his vessel by sight, taking account of the current and the
visibility of less than five feet.
</P>
<P>
   A demonstration for television of how a Russian minisub works
turned into another painful reminder of the decrepit state of
Russia's navy, and nearly turned into another disaster, when the
small orange and white vessel began to leak, forcing its crew to
sail it slowly back to the Mikhail Rudnitsky.
</P>
<P>
   The British LR5 rescue minisub on its way to the site has never
been involved in a real rescue operation. But its captain, Alan
Hopkins, said Thursday it can operate comfortably in currents of up
to 2 knots.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's late decision to accept the British offer of help has
led to growing criticism of President Vladimir Putin's handling of
the crisis. He also came under fire for not breaking off his
vacation on the Black Sea while his country was glued to television
screens, waiting from news from the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   In his first extensive comments to reporters, Putin Friday said
he decided not to go to the site, or to Murmansk, because ``the
arrival of non-specialists and high-ranking officials to the scene
of disaster does not help, but usually interferes.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin acknowledged that Russian officials knew about the
accident ``four hours'' after it occurred, which he said was at 11
p.m. last Saturday. He said the decision not to inform the rest of
the world until Monday was dictated by the need to get ``objective
information'' about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   However, the information released for the first day or so was
often contradictory and played down the scope of the tragedy,
describing what happened on the Kursk as a ``malfunction.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin denied reports that he had not been given objective
information about the disaster by subordinates, saying that at the
outset he was told ``the chances are extremely low _ but they
exist'' of finding survivors. He also brushed off criticism that in
refusing international assistance, Russia may have put geopolitics
above the lives of the crew, saying the navy had done everything it
could to save the crew from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Klebanov, who only arrived in Murmansk on Thursday, had said
Tuesday that Russia did not need outside help because its rescue
equipment was ``no worse'' than anything Western countries had.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the Northern Fleet also responded to the
criticism that the navy reacted slowly to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a clear conscience that we have not wasted one minute,
one hour,'' said Admiral Vyacheslav Popov from his flagship, the
Pyotr Veliky missile cruiser. ``We have been doing one thing,
saving the people, saving the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials have offered various explanations of what might have
happened to the Kursk, including a collision with another vessel,
an internal explosion, or a freak encounter with a World War II
mine. Klebanov suggested the submarine hit an unspecified ``huge,
heavy object'' about 65 feet below the surface and plunged to the
sea bottom in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Two US submarines in the area and a Norwegian seismic center
have reported two explosions, the second larger than the first. One
theory is that a torpedo exploded, leading to the second explosion
as other munitions detonated.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible explanation is that the 480-foot-long submarine
performed a maneuver known as a ``whale jump,'' surfacing so
rapidly it lunged partly out of the water _ an ill-advised stunt in
waters shallower than the vessel is long. As the submarine
reentered the water, this theory goes, its momentum caused it to
plow into the sea floor the way a diver in shallow water might hit
the bottom and break his neck.
</P>
<P>
   As in any unexplained disaster, theories about the cause of the
sinking have multiplied as time goes on. Friday, two Moscow dailies
reported that the Kursk collided with an American submarine, which
the US and Russian militaries have denied.
</P>
<P>
   But with little official information available, journalists have
been hard-pressed to come up with any information at all.
</P>
<P>
   In a searing condemnation of the official secrecy surrounding
the Kursk accident, the Moscow daily Komsomolskaya Pravda Friday
printed a list of what it said were the names of the 118 crew, and
where they were stationed on board. The paper said it had paid a
naval officer $650 for the list.
</P>
<P>
   The navy has refused to release the names of the crew, much to
the consternation of relatives who are not sure if their loved ones
were on board. The Kursk, like many large Russian submarines,
rotates three crews, and since many men were on vacation, it
borrowed from the crews of two other submarines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hearsay about what's going on,'' Irina
Lyachina, wife of the Kursk's commander, told reporters in
Murmansk. ``I hope they will tell me the truth when the time
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
