<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5948 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-EBAY-POWERSELLERS-$AD     08-18 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-POWERSELLERS-$ADV20-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: power-seller standards. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Retailer
</P>
<P>
   A Small Business Triples Its Volume
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday night a year and a half ago, Nang Nguyen was sitting
at his computer, looking at jewelry listings on eBay. He had
decided to bid on a diamond ring in a platinum setting; it would be
a present for his wife, Kim. The ring was listed by a store he had
never heard of _ Sun Jewelry, a tiny shop in a Los Angeles shopping
mall, thousands of miles from his home in Hershey, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   When he won the bidding, he and his wife were thrilled. ``The
price was incredible,'' remembered Nguyen (pronounced ``win''). He
immediately called Los Angeles to talk with the shop's owner, Abit
Uygan. They hit it off.
</P>
<P>
   Uygan said he was a new seller on eBay. Nguyen responded that he
was a rookie buyer. Uygan described the bad luck he had experienced
with other forms of online sales, including several failed attempts
to run a Web site. Nguyen, who was working in his father's shoe
store in Hershey, offered to help Uygan sell other pieces of
jewelry on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Their partnership, Nguyen said, has thrived. Since last year,
the two men have owned Sun Jewelry together. While Uygan continues
to oversee the production of the jewelry, which he and a few
employees make by hand in the back room of the Los Angeles shop,
Nguyen runs the administrative side, including the eBay listings,
from an office next door to his father's shoe store in Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's sales have tripled in the last year and a half, Nguyen
said. They sell up to 800 pieces of jewelry a month, about 90
percent online. The two men are now considering taking the company
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the online auction, I don't think it would be possible
to be where we are today, thinking about an IPO,'' Nguyen said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the beginning, he was not sure that eBay was the answer.
Sun Jewelry already had its own Web site (www.sunjewelry.com) and
Nguyen had decided to try several Internet marketing avenues at
once. Those included banner and classified advertising, links with
other Web sites and requests for listing on search engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listing your Web site _ trust me, it doesn't work,'' he said.
Selling items through eBay was the only thing that did. ``It has
put us in an area where everyone can see us,'' he added. ``Before,
we were just a small store, tucked away.'' Now Nguyen does not even
try to advertise the Sun Jewelry Web site, although it still
attracts customers who remember seeing it on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen has also started using eBay as a test bed for pricing. He
will list a ring on eBay and watch how many bids it gets, and how
many people click through to see the photograph and the closing
price. If the ring sells well, he may offer a few more of a similar
design on eBay or decide to showcase it on his Web site at a set
price.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the surge in business has brought trials. During the
holiday season last year, the company had a three-week backup in
orders. And maintaining friendly and accessible customer service
has been a challenge. Nguyen said he calls almost every one of his
customers himself. His phone bill, he said, runs from $800 to
$1,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, he has bought services from Andale, the
auction-management company that automates his listings, allows for
different forms of payment and reminds him to send feedback to each
buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the activity, in fact, he still has not yet visited the
Sun Jewelry store in Los Angeles, or even met his partner face to
face. ``I have no idea what he looks like,'' Nguyen said. ``But I'm
going out to his wedding next year, so I'll finally see him
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Home Business
</P>
<P>
   Clearing Out Closets and Making Money
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Kimberly Crockett was working for a regional
investment company, selling mutual funds from her home in Panama
City Beach, Fla. Still in her 20s, she had already built a fine
life, with a three-bedroom house within walking distance of the
beach on the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, Crockett does not have much time to get to the
beach, and her fund work is on the back burner. Since the spring of
1998, she has built a booming business from her home, selling
collectible toys on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Always enchanted by ``The Wizard of Oz,'' Crockett had secretly
hoped she might be able to make money by collecting television and
movie memorabilia. In 1989, she decided on a whim to buy two
shopping carts full of Pee Wee Herman toys that were on sale in a
store for a few dollars apiece. It was a smart gamble: Several
pieces now sell for more than $200 each.
</P>
<P>
   But until the Web came along, she never imagined being able to
make a good living from her hobby. Today, she sells 1,000 to 2,000
toys a month on eBay, and has just hired her first employee. She
declined to divulge details of her profits, but said she was having
no trouble making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always double my money,'' Crockett said in a phone interview
from her home, barely distracted by her light-brown cat, Panama,
which sat beside her crouched on a Three Stooges mouse pad.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett, who goes by the name SillyOzibul on eBay, started
collecting toys with a fervor about three years ago, after helping
a ``Star Wars'' fan find a rare Princess Leia figurine. After a few
months of scouring toy shows, garage sales and collectors'
conventions, she realized that she had developed a sizable
collection without any plan for what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I opened one of the bedroom doors, and there were just
bags and bags of stuff,'' she said. ``I couldn't even walk in. And
I said: `What are you doing, Kim? You just can't horde this
stuff.'''
</P>
<P>
   Crockett decided to try eBay. The first item, one of those Pee
Wee Herman dolls, sold for $18, and within a few months she had
built a company called Oz Wars Toys, a title that blends ``Wizard
of Oz'' and ``Star Wars.'' Two of the three bedrooms in her house
are now storage areas, and the living room is a packaging site,
strewn with boxes and bubble wrap. The kitchen is the only area
that is devoid of collectibles _ except for the Oz plates that hang
above the cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
