<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5949 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-EBAY-POWERSELLERS-$AD     08-18 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-POWERSELLERS-$ADV20-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the cabinets. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her house is so full of toys, Crockett said, that she is looking
to rent about 1,000 square feet of space in a nearby building,
where she can operate the online business and sell a few items to
local residents who stop by.
</P>
<P>
   As the business grows, it is becoming more professional. She has
bought services from AuctionWorks to help manage the business; the
move saved her the 30 hours a week she had spent writing e-mail
messages to customers and filling out feedback forms rating her
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of how much her business grows, Crockett said,
she is not ready to part with all of her collectibles, especially
those related to Dorothy and the Yellow Brick Road. ``I've just
sold a bunch of `Wizard of Oz' flags for $50 apiece,'' she said.
``They are really nice ruby-slippers flags, with slippers that
sparkle and a sign that says, `No Place Like Home.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Several bidders fought over them on eBay,'' she said, ``but
I've got to keep one for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liquidator
</P>
<P>
   A Hot Market for Unsold Clothes
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Waites, a tall, tan, well-dressed man with a thick
Southern accent, jumped into e-commerce last year. But he has no
intention of moving his liquidating business to Silicon Valley from
West Front Street in Hattiesburg, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, he would not fit in, he declared in a recent
interview. ``In south Mississippi,'' he said with a playful smile,
``we're not smart enough to figure out how to make money by selling
merchandise and losing money on each item.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has turned to eBay, which he will use as the
infrastructure for a new site, eValueville.com. His company,
Inventory Procurement Services, specializes in selling the shirts,
coats, jeans and dresses that retail shops want to get rid of,
usually because they want to make room for new styles and more
seasonable clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, he distributed those goods to small retail shops
that have closeouts. Then, last summer, he received a box of
Kenneth Cole leather coats of different shapes and sizes. ``We
said, `How are we going to sell these in the summer in Hattiesburg,
Mississippi?''' he recalled. ``We put them on eBay, and we were
amazed at the final sales price.'' As a result, something that
would have been almost impossible to sell at $69 in his hometown
became a hot $200 item.
</P>
<P>
   But one real advantage of the online auction sites, he said, is
the ability to reduce expenses, especially for marketing.
Sometimes, he said, he does not bother paying eBay's $2 fee for
putting a listing in bold type, yet he has sold 100 percent of the
clothing that he has tried to sell and has made a profit on each
item.
</P>
<P>
   Waites also uses eBay as a hook. He sometimes starts items at $1
each, regardless of what they must sell for to recover costs, to
draw just-lookers _ in hopes that they will go to the Evalueville
site. By mid-September, he added, he will be listing 5,000 items a
week on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been visiting department stores and manufacturers,
trying to sell them on his new business plan. He is betting that he
will be able to get them better prices than they might through
conventional liquidation channels. ``I think we can improve their
recovery by 2 to 3 percentage points,'' he said. ``We think eBay
will be for us the biggest outlet mall in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wholesaler
</P>
<P>
   Giving the Consumer Economies of Scale
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, Larry Bence has been supplying retail
stores with collectible cards and coins. And he has been using
computers for 15 years _ he was part of a proprietary network of
dealers who were sending messages back and forth in the very early
days of the Internet. So in the mid-1990s, when everyone started
talking about expanding commerce on the Web, he was all for it.
</P>
<P>
   But after setting up a Web site, he found that the effort was
not worth it. He and his staff, including his daughter, Julie,
would spend hours listing the prices of sports cards, posters, toy
cars and dinnerware with football logos. Then something in the news
would bump the prices up or down, and the site would have to be
updated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just impossible to maintain that many different pricing
ranges,'' said Bence, whose company is called Abon Cards and Coins
Ltd. After trying six times with different Web site designs, he
gave up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people that I've seen who make money on Web sites,''
he said, ``are the people who design them.'' Bence still has a Web
site, but it is just a few pages.
</P>
<P>
   As a wholesaler with more than 100,000 square feet of warehouse
space in Ohio, Bence did not have to worry about finding a place
for inventory to feed his online business. And he could have
settled for a continuation of his conventional business, selling
pallets of cards and memorabilia to retailers. But he wanted to tap
into the consumer market, too, without doing any advertising.
</P>
<P>
   That is why he turned to eBay, he said. He now assigns about a
dozen of his 22 staff members to manage his eBay listings of cards,
coins and related items. His eBay business is now large enough that
he has chosen to become an eBay gold power seller. He has developed
software to help his company manage all of the accounts; one of his
homemade software packages runs checks on credit card numbers and
addresses to make sure that a buyer is not using a stolen card.
``It's hairy,'' he said. ``We are gritting our teeth. That's the
one area that is very vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The venture has turned his business into a blend of wholesale
and retail, a mix that he said is becoming increasingly common on
the Internet. Ultimately, he is able to sell small quantities of
goods to consumers at wholesale prices, while still selling pallets
of merchandise to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Bence said his presence on eBay had also built his contact base,
enabling him find more items to sell: ``There are people who see us
on eBay who contact us and say, `I wonder if he'll want to buy
stuff,''' he added. ``I just bought a bunch of collegiate
dinnerware _ Michigan State dinnerware. In Ohio, not many people
may want Michigan State dinnerware. But on the Internet, there are
probably plenty of Michigan State fans who will have no problem
paying up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
