<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-KOSHER0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eating kosher can be a challenge for busy politicians
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Along with the never-ending chicken
dinners and dawn-o'clock fund-raising breakfasts, pig roasts and
barbecues are part of campaign trail dining.
</P>
<P>
   For most candidates, they're not a problem: a vote's a vote,
whether it's country music and ribs at $15 a plate or chamber music
and lobster at $500.
</P>
<P>
   If you keep kosher, however, as Sen. Joseph Lieberman does, a
candidate could go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Kashrut, the dietary laws of Orthodox Jews, say no pork, no
shellfish and no mixing dairy and meat in the same meal. So the
poor guy can't even run out for a cheeseburger.
</P>
<P>
   The strictest of the Orthodox also will not eat vegetables in a
non-kosher restaurant because meat and dairy may have been served
on the plate at some time.
</P>
<P>
   Two local politicos who keep kosher know just what the
Democratic vice presidential candidate is up against.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Krischer, Palm Beach County's state attorney, was the
first observant Orthodox Jew elected countywide. His 1992 campaign
produced some interesting moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ate a lot of salad and bread, of course,'' he said. ``And
there were many times I just didn't eat at all. There were many
chicken luncheons, and pig roasts in Belle Glade, where there was
nothing I could eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not a problem usually. I just avoided eating when
there were meats served, which is just about every time.''
</P>
<P>
   He eats vegetarian meals where possible, but says the chances of
finding kosher foods locally is greater today than in his campaign
days. ``In Palm Beach County, it's gotten much better now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rob Wexler, D-Boca Raton, agrees. Wexler, who also
keeps kosher at home, isn't as strict as some of his political
friends from New York. ``They won't eat in non-kosher restaurants,
for instance. I won't eat hamburgers or cheeseburgers or chicken,
and certainly no shellfish, but I eat dairy off plates that I've
got to assume meat was served on. It's just where you want to draw
the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosher foods are much more available in South Florida than even
in Washington, D.C., he said, so campaigning in his home district
isn't a problem. ``They've got a great kosher pizza place and meat
place down there (in Boca Raton) now, and even Disney World can do
kosher. We just went to an Orthodox wedding there.''
</P>
<P>
   All his fund-raisers feature kosher dining. ``The Boca Hotel has
a contract with a kosher caterer and is able to do a completely
kosher function. It's no problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Krischer says different regions present different problems. He
has a particularly hard time in Tallahassee, a frequent
destination. ``It's a lot of Southern food, collard greens and
what's that stuff called _ pork back or fat back?'' Definitely not
kosher.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, even people who mean well get it wrong. ``There
were the black beans at Jimbo's, in Tallahassee. Delicious. I had
asked if they were vegetarian, and was assured they were indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   But after he scarfed them down, the truth stared back at him
from the bottom of the dish. It was a large chunk of. . . what's
that stuff called? Fatback!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
