<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MEDIA-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE POLICE DETAIN EDITOR'S BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The police have detained the younger brother of a
Boston-based poet who was arrested in Beijing last week, apparently
for his involvement in a literary journal that has sometimes
published work by Chinese dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   The poet, Bei Ling, a Chinese citizen with a U.S. green card,
was taken into custody last Saturday during a visit to Beijing. His
younger brother, Huang Feng, 32, also a writer, who lives in
Beijing, was detained Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what charges are being brought against the two
men, although Bei, 40, is being held in criminal detention, which
suggests that the charges may be serious.
</P>
<P>
   It is at least the second time in little over a year that a
Chinese intellectual with permanent residence status in the United
States has been arrested in Beijing. Last summer, Song Yongyi, a
researcher and librarian at Dickinson College in Pennsylvania was
arrested in connection with his studies of the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution, a disastrous and embarrassing period in modern Chinese
history.
</P>
<P>
   An aggressive campaign by U.S. politicians and academics helped
secure his release after six months in detention. Similar forces
seem to be gathering in Bei's defense.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Thursday to promote a major cultural
exchange between China and the United States, the U.S. ambassador,
Joseph Prueher, said of Bei: ``We have officially expressed our
concern to the Chinese government about him. Obviously the issue of
freedom of expression is a core point for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Others noted that if Bei's case is not resolved quickly, it
could prove to be a public relations nightmare for China. Within
the next three weeks both President Jiang Zemin and Li Peng, the
head of China's parliament, will be in New York for a U.N. summit
conference. At the same time, as part of the announced exchange
with the United States, a Chinese cultural exhibit aimed at
enhancing China's image will be touring U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will cause a great deal of embarrassment to a useful
cultural effort if they continue to hold him this way,'' said
Jerome Cohen, a New York lawyer specializing in China law, who
helped secure Song's release. ``They will not want to have
demonstrators protesting outside the Javits Center,'' he said,
referring to the convention center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Bei's arrest, Beijing police confiscated hundreds
of copies of Tendency, the quarterly journal that he edits, which
had apparently been shipped into the country. Tendency, which is
published in the United States, is not legally available in China.
</P>
<P>
   All magazines in China must have a government sponsor that
formally takes responsibility for their content. Foreign magazines
must have permits for import, although many circulate in
intellectual circles, and essays published overseas are often
easily available on the Chinese Internet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bei's journal combines work by both Western and Chinese authors.
The latest issue contains a poem by a Chinese political dissident,
a photograph of the exiled student leader Wang Dan and an essay by
the Irish Nobel laureate Seamus Heaney.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what level of the Chinese bureaucracy was
responsible for Bei's _ or his brother's _ arrest and whether it
was intended to send a larger signal. In high-profile cases,
arrests may be ordered by top officials. But local public security
forces can also act on their own, sometimes to the chagrin of other
government departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when we look into cases, it's not a government plan
but the action of a small entity,'' Prueher said at Thursday's news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at the same press event, Zhao Qizheng _ the information
minister for China's State Council, or Cabinet _ said he was not
aware of the Bei Ling case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
