<SLUG> BC-HIGH-NOON-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN IS BIG ENOUGH FOR TWO VERSIONS
</HEADLINE>
  TNT tries its hand at a beloved Western with an all-star lineup 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients. Program airs originally
on Sun., Aug. 20, 2000.) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hadleyville is an isolated Western town. Its most respected
citizen is worn down by the demands of his job and the imminent
arrival of his nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes the squinty-eyed bad guy in the black hat. He's on a
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Calgary location of TBS's version of ``High
Noon.''
</P>
<P>
   The remake of the 1952 classic Western premieres Sunday with Tom
Skerritt in the Gary Cooper role of Sheriff Will Kane, who retires
on his wedding day and then returns to the job to protect his town
and himself from Frank Miller (Michael Madsen), a vengeful criminal
who has just been released from prison and is expected on the noon
train.
</P>
<P>
   Skerritt and the rest of the company _ including Susanna
Thompson of ``Once and Again'' in Grace Kelly's role of Amy and
Maria Conchita Alonso as Will's former flame Helen Ramirez _ had
been putting in long hours in the very tight 19-day shoot when
Madsen arrived toward the end of the production schedule for his
brief part.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran Tom pretty hard and it was pretty evident when I got
there that he was pretty beat up, pretty tired and he wanted to go
home,'' Madsen said. ``I kind of thought that was good that he was
tired because I thought maybe Will Kane would have been tired by
the time Frank showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the mood that Tom was in and the fact that I just got to
Canada and I was feeling pretty good _ I think sometimes
subconsciously actors find themselves in psychological situations
that are similar to their characters, and that was a perfect
example.''
</P>
<P>
   While the cameras rolled there was tension between Kane, the
hero all but foresaken by his bride and the rest of the town, and
Miller, whose reputation and vow to kill Kane have everyone but the
sheriff cowering.
</P>
<P>
   But between scenes there was another kind of tension between
Skerritt, one of Hollywood's most respected actors and a notorious
prankster, and Madsen, who lives and breathes by the Stanislavsky
Method.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom tried real hard to lighten everybody up when the bad guys
showed up,'' Madsen said. ``He wanted to do a little dance sequence
off camera. He thought that was going to be really funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I just said, `Tom, you know what? I'm really not here to
dance. I'm here to kill you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kind of walked away real slow,'' said Madsen, adding
that he apologized to Skerritt for it at the wrap party. ``He's a
sweet man, he's a nice man. I certainly didn't want to upset the
guy. I just had a job to do and I was there to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie purists are sure to cry foul over the very nerve of
Skerritt, Thompson, Madsen, director Ron Hardy and executive
producer David Rosemont remaking such a beloved film. Each of them
considered his and her own concerns with that issue and decided to
go ahead with it.
</P>
<P>
   Skerritt says he was undaunted by the idea of stepping into
Cooper's boots in probably his most memorable character, a
performance that earned him an Oscar. ``All I could do is pay
respects,'' he said. ``That's all any of us could do, pay respects
to the original and to Gary Cooper and Grace Kelly and look at a
script that was very beautiful in terms of economy, very
minimalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we remaking this movie? No, I think we're remaking the
script,'' Skerritt said. ``There's a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never our intention, certainly not mine, to try and
make a better version because the best version of 'High Noon' has
been made by other people,'' said Hardy, effusively grateful for
the endorsements his project received from 1952 ``High Noon''
producer Stanley Kramer and the son of Carl Foreman, whose original
script was used with a few alterations by T.S. Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starved of good material and when there's a good script
like 'High Noon,' it seems like such a shame not to give it another
chance,'' Hardy said. He said stage plays are given many different
treatments in assorted theaters by diverse directors, and great
movie scripts are entitled to the same _ as long as they are
treated with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not against being criticized for bad filmmaking. I'll be
open to that until the cows come home,'' the director said. ``And I
have sensed the criticism of 'how can you dare go and make this
again.' I just say to those people, 'Please sit down, watch and
make your own judgments. Don't be coerced into not seeing the film
because somebody has said that it's wrong to do so.'''
</P>
<P>
   Among the differences between the Skerritt/Thompson movie and
the Cooper/Kelly version directed by Fred Zinnemann: The old one
was in black and white, a bold choice when Technicolor was the
norm, while the new one is in subdued color; the old one used
bright, nearly shadowless lighting typical of the '50s, while the
new version has more of a natural-light look; the relationship
between Amy and Helen has been expanded somewhat, and Miller,
speechless in the original, has been given a few terse lines; and
the theme music of the original (``Do not foresake me, oh my
darlin', on this our wedding day ... '') was burned into the
American pop culture consciousness but is not used in the remake.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who enjoyed Coop's version but believe it's worthy of
another treatment can watch the new ``High Noon'' on Sunday and
again on Aug. 26 and Sept. 2. For those who hold the 1952 version
sacred, it's being shown _ not coincidentally _ on TBS' sister
network, Turner Classic Movies, where ``Noon'' strikes at 11 a.m.
(PDT) Sunday and again on Aug. 26.---The show: ``High Noon.'' &QL; 
What: Remake of the 1952 Western in which a sheriff faces a
vengeful outlaw without any help from his bride or the townfolk. &QL; 
The stars: Tom Skerritt, Susanna Thompson, Maria Conchita Alonso,
Michael Madsen. &QL; 
Where: TBS. &QL; 
When: Check local listings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
