<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WINFEMME-FILMFEST-LAD     08-18 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINFEMME-FILMFEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMME FILMS, NOT CHICK FLICKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second annual Winfemme Film Festival, under way in Beverly
Hills, focuses attention on features, documentaries and shorts with
women in leading roles, but it's not a women's film festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its films simply feature female protagonists,'' said Phyllis
Stuart, president of Women's Image Network. ``These are not chick
flicks. They are great flicks that will appeal to people who love
movies _ or those who love women.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's lineup includes a block of three humorous shorts playing
at 4:45 p.m. _ `'A Friend Comes to Visit,'' ``Anal'' and ``Ladies
Room L.A.'' _ all bathroom-themed movies.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's highlights include ``Kathryn &AMP; Her Daughters,'' a
documentary about a 75-year-old widow whose outlook is shaped by
her farm life in the '50s and '60s; a short, ``A Feeling Called
Glory,'' about a summer friendship between two odd characters; and
``The Georgia Peach Boy,'' a short about a Georgia woman who dreams
of having a baby and finds an infant in the pit of a giant peach.
</P>
<P>
   The closing celebration, 7 p.m. Sunday at the Beverly Hills
Civic Plaza, will honor actress Lauren Bacall and director Jane
Campion. Bacall will be on hand to accept her WIN Award and see a
screening of ``The Mirror Has Two Faces,'' for which she received
an Oscar nomination. Campion is filming on location and will be
represented by actor Sam Neill, one of the stars of Campion's ``The
Piano.'' Tickets for that event cost $50.
</P>
<P>
   Film screenings at the Laemmle Music Hall, 9036 Wilshire Blvd.,
are sold in blocks of titles for $7 per block. For more
information, call WIN at (310) 996-0267 or go to
www.ticketmaster.com on the Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
