<HEADLINE>
BABBITT INDICATES WEST'S RAGING FIRES MAY BE OUT OF CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said
Friday that the wildfires raging across the West are likely to get
worse and warned that, with resources already stretched to the
limit, little can be done to slow their progress.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million acres were burning Friday in 11 Western
states, the most land on fire at any one time in the United States
since 1910. Federal officials said Friday that they were growing
increasingly concerned that the situation in Montana, the
hardest-hit state, might turn more catastrophic, with separate
fires beginning to merge.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, who spent the day traversing the smoky skies and
walking the soot-covered soil, said the scope of the fires and the
limited availability of trained firefighting supervisors meant that
the intensity of the fires in the weeks ahead would depend more on
weather than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional bodies will not help in this fire season,'' Babbitt
said on a stop here, where he met with some of the 25,000 people
battling the fires from Montana to California to New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt seemed to be trying in part to head off public calls for
the deployment of more firefighters, a step that he warned might be
counterproductive. But his comments Friday seemed also to
underscore a sense of powerlessness in a fire season that some
federal officials say appears on track to be the most devastating
in 90 years.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Clinton administration say it has been slow to
respond to the fires, and even contributed to the problem through
its conservation policies. Representatives of the timber industry
have said that the priority given to environmental concerns within
the administration had prevented officials from confronting the
fire threat as might have been most appropriate, through emergency
logging measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be an alarmist, and I'm not saying it will
become catastrophic,'' Babbitt said. ``But the probability that it
will become worse is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Of most immediate concern, said a top federal fire official with
Babbitt, is what could happen over the next few days, when high
winds are predicted across Montana and Idaho, the locations of the
worst fires. The official, Larry E. Hamilton, director of the
National Office of Fire and Aviation in Boise, Idaho, said the fear
is that scattered fires could consolidate, posing new dangers to
communities like those in Montana's Bitterroot Valley, south of
Missoula in western Montana, whose residents have already been
evacuated twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you could have in some places is a 20- to 40-mile wall of
flame, and that would be just unstoppable,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far this year, wildfires in the West have consumed 4.7
million acres, including the more than 1 million acres still
burning. Hamilton said there is a significant chance that the total
by the end of the fire season could top the more than 8 million
acres that burned in 1910, regarded as the worst year on record.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 85 major fires burning across the region, 27 are in
Montana, with more than 470,000 acres listed as burned or burning.
</P>
<P>
   To reinforce the hundreds of fire crews battling the blazes, the
federal government has turned to the military, which has deployed
four battalions, and to other countries, including Canada,
Australia and New Zealand, which have sent some 600 firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   But Babbitt said Friday that a shortage of firefighting
supervisors meant that to deploy any additional firefighters now
risks overloading the system and could put untrained volunteers in
harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a point of diminishing returns, and actually,
diminishing loss of effectiveness when you start piling people in
without trained leadership to manage them,'' Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the fires, Gov. Marc Racicot of Montana imposed a
state of emergency on Wednesday and called up the National Guard to
assist in firefighting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said he believed that such reinforcements would be best
used to assist in evacuations, if necessary, rather than on the
fire lines.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 percent of those people battling this summer's fires
are college students, and with a new semester about to begin,
Babbitt said he was concerned that large numbers of firefighters
might feel obliged to head back to school before the worst of the
danger passes.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of preventing such a drain, Babbitt said he had spent
much of the last few days pressing Western governors to defer
registration deadlines in public universities until at least Sept.
15, so firefighters could stay on the job. Montana and Idaho have
already announced such plans, and Babbitt said he hoped that
universities would offer remedial teaching to students who decided
to begin their studies late because of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who are already trained up and on the ground,
and we don't want to lose them,'' Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   On a day that began with a briefing at the interagency fire
center, Babbitt flew on to Montana and then Wyoming on a route that
passed through some of the worst of the fire zone. For much of the
journey, the view of the ground was obscured by thick smoke, but
some fires could be readily identified, including one that broke
out late Thursday in the small town of Atlanta, Idaho, northeast of
Boise, and forced the evacuation of about 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   A trained firefighter himself, with many summers' experience on
the lines, Babbitt pointed out the line of the fire's advance,
driven by winds that had tossed burning embers long distances on
the rugged hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   In West Yellowstone, Babbitt met with crews who are battling the
Beaver Creek fire, a 4,500-acre blaze that began a week ago and has
made for considerable uneasiness in the nearby town of Big Sky,
where 300 residents turned out for a meeting on Thursday night to
discuss possible evacuation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Duke of the U.S. Forest Service, the local incident
commander, told Babbitt that he had been unable to secure the
manpower and helicopter support necessary to fight the fire in
earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said he could promise only to do what we can with what
we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   By federal policy, top priority in all firefighting operations
is given to protecting lives and property. This summer, that
obligation alone has been so considerable that, in more isolated
areas, fire commanders have had no choice but to allow blazes to
burn.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, the federal fire official, said the agency's concerns
about the spread of the fires intensified in the last week, in part
because of analysis from experts at a Forest Service research
station in Missoula.
</P>
<P>
   A computer model that assesses such factors as drought,
lightning strikes and fuel loads has concluded that there was at
least a 10 percent chance that the fires could turn catastrophic in
a way that could force large-scale evacuation.
</P>
</TEXT>
