<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS (These stories will move in `f' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-LINUX (Undated) _ Remember Linus Torvalds? Last year, the
Linux operating system he created was going to revolutionize the
software industry, do more damage to Microsoft than the Justice
Department and make investors rich. This year, Torvalds has been
replaced on magazine covers by Napster's Shawn Fanning as the
technologist most likely to wreak havoc on traditional ways of
doing business. By Danny Hakim. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-STRATEGIES-COLUMN (Undated) _ A new study finds the
market overall was less volatile in the '90s than in the '70s or
'80s, but individual stocks were more volatile, so portfolios need
greater diversification. By Mark Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-ULTRA-TRAVEL (Undated) _ A look at the proliferation of
ultra-expensive, ultra-exotic package tours, like the Lost City
Tour that visits places like Angkor Wat, Lhasa, Petra and
Samarkand. By Suzanne Macneille.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-LOS-ANGELES (Los Angeles) _ The thriving Los Angeles fashion
district has more in common with 12th-century Baghdad than the
California of the new millennium. The 80-block jumble of prewar
commercial buildings, hastily constructed low-rise arcades
commingled with a few modern towers, is home to 5,000 companies
employing 50,000 people and taking in $8 billion a year in
wholesale and retail sales. And it epitomizes raw capitalism in
both its glory and its shame. By Joel Kotkin.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   PRELUDES-COLUMN-FAILURES (Undated) _ Failure used to connote
welfare and leaving town in the dead of night to escape the
disapproving stares of neighbors. Today it's a rite of passage.
``Failure is the price of being on the bleeding edge, on the
forefront of something you take pride in,'' said Gretchen Craft
Rubin, author of ``Money, Fame, Power, Sex.'' By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW (These stories will move in `a' or `i' categories,
as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-LOYALTY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Two-thirds of Americans
still consider themselves Democrats or Republicans. Party still
matters, and party attachment is still considered a good predictor
of how people will vote _ if they vote. But appealing to those
loyalties, while still wooing the independents who decide
elections, is a complex challenge these days. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUBMARINE-STORIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The world has been
transfixed by the sinking of the Russian submarine Kursk and the
desperate attempts to reach the 118 men inside. What is it about
the sea _ and especially submarines _ that makes being trapped
below the waves often resonate even more than similar disasters on
land, like mine cave-ins? Part of the answer is that for all the
advances in science, the sea remains a mysterious _ and mystical _
force. By Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONAIRE-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' has turned into an empire, with 27 versions being
produced and broadcast in countries around the world. The questions
are now almost educational. Some examples are presented.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-MEDIA-REVIEW (Undated) _ Iran's crackdown on
reform-oriented writers, editors and media has spread to
cartoonists. A magazine called Tavana was banned after publishing a
caricature of President Mohammad Khatami, who is himself a
reformer. But it showed him without his clerical turban and robe.
That, the court said, amounted to defamation. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CARTOONISTS-REVIEW (United Nations) _ At the United
Nations, where one person's joke can strike other people from other
cultures as incomprehensible or offensive, diplomats favor the
universal language of the political cartoon. Over the next few
weeks, a panel of diplomats and American celebrities will choose
the winner of a $10,000 prize for the best political cartoon on a
U.N. theme. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
