<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, IN TENNESSEE, ATTACKS GORE'S SINCERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It was planned as a terrific irony: George W. Bush
campaigning in Tennessee, challenging the vice president for votes
in his own home state.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a slogan for Friday's campaign stop in a Memphis
suburb: ``Listen to people who know them best.'' But in a short
visit _ which was cut even shorter when Bush decided to return to
Texas early to go jogging _ the Republican candidate mostly told
voters what to think of his opponent, using some of his strongest
language thus far in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a midday rally that drew thousands, Bush tore into the speech
Gore gave at the Democratic Convention the previous night,
attacking the vice president's style of politics and questioning
his sincerity. Accusing Gore of being divisive, Bush said his
speech was essentially empty, designed purely to cover up past
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we heard a laundry list of new promises which I
thought was an attempt to cover up old failures _ a list of of
promises without purpose or vision,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventions are over and the battle lines are clearly
drawn,'' he continued. ``On the one hand, they have four more years
of finger-pointing, politicizing and blaming, a candidate who wants
to pit one group of people against another, a candidate who wants
to wage class warfare to get ahead. I've got a different vision of
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks came as the campaign entered a new phase, following
the end of both parties' nominating conventions. Both candidates
had predicted a sea change starting Friday, as the election cycle
drew closer to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who a day earlier announced he would participate in three
presidential debates, reiterated his commitment to facing Gore in
the final months of the election, saying he would meet the vice
president ``in a format that people will listen to and pay
attention to.'' He left open questions about whether he would
participate in a series of debates planned by the official
Commission on Presidential Debates.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore kept up a hectic pace Friday, making a red-eye flight
aboard Air Force Two to the Midwest to embark on an 11-hour day of
campaigning along the Mississippi River, Bush kept a more limited
schedule. After holding the Tennessee rally, he and running mate
Dick Cheney flew to Dallas, where they spoke to reporters at the
airport before disappearing from public view.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, the Bush communications director, said the Texas
governor cut short the visit because he prefers going running in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters on board his campaign plane, Bush gave his
take on the race, and on Gore's speech in particular. He even
offered Gore some praise for his Democratic convention performance,
saying he thought the vice president had achieved his goal of
presenting himself as independent from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well he convinced me. . . . What he convinced me of is that,
sure. Yes. I mean, he's standing on his own two feet,'' Bush said,
stammering a bit when asked whether Gore's claim that he is his
``own man'' was convincing. ``Having done that myself, I know what
it's like to stand up in front of the convention and say, `Here's
my view, here's my plan, here's how I intend to lead.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush took issue with Gore's attempts to cast the Democratic
ticket as a populist force that contrasts with an elitist
Republican ticket. Accusing Gore of being divisive, Bush said that
he did not believe the tactic would work, suggesting the voters
would be turned off by Gore's rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to lead a nation by dividing, by pitting people
against each other,'' he said. ``That's the rhetoric of the past,
where you kind of group warfare or class warfare, and I don't think
Americans are going to buy that style of leadership. But what the
heck do I know?''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush said Gore's speech was intrinsically
flawed, raising more questions about the accomplishments of the
Clinton-Gore adminisration than it answered. ``His speech last
night, obviously, I thought, was a tacit admission that they
haven't done a lot in terms of Medicare and Social Security,'' he
said. Asked to elaborate, he continued: ``Because why would you
need to be saying that we need to do something on Social Security
after seven years unless nothing had been done?''
</P>
</TEXT>
