<P>
   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-INTERNET (Tokyo) _ In early 1999, Japanese
wireless-communications companies introduced mobile-phone-based
Internet services. The wireless Web not only increased the time
people could spend on the Internet, it gave service providers an
easy way to collect subscription fees _ through customers'
mobile-phone bills. ``It's a new business model'' for
information-providers on the Internet, said Toby Rodes, an analyst
at Nikko Salomon Smith Barney in Tokyo. But it remains to be seen
if the Japanese model can be transplanted to North America and
Europe, where markets are more fragmented and consumer tastes vary.
By Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center right)
</P>
<P>
   DATEK-BUYOUT (Undated) _ Trying to distance itself from a
troubled past, Datek Online, one of the nation's fastest-growing
online brokerage firms, has agreed to raise about $500 million to
buy out the company's two majority shareholders, according to
people who have been briefed on the deal. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom right)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-TELECOM (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Hours after they clinked
champagne glasses on Thursday evening, winners in Germany's $46
billion auction for wireless licenses began feeling the hangover
Friday. In the most vivid case of winner's remorse, Hutchison
Whampoa of Hong Kong immediately announced that it was pulling out
of one of the six groups that won a license because the prices were
simply too high. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
