<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-NYT     08-18 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT REUNION'S END, 50 YEARS OF SEPARATION RESUMES FOR KOREAN
FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
  By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Four days after they had begun to mend the
shattered fragments of their pasts, 200 North and South Koreans
were separated from their families again on Friday, as the reunions
authorized by the leaders of both countries came to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother, try not to think about me, and take good care
yourself,'' said Rim Jae Hyok, 69, bowing to his mother as she sat
in her wheelchair. Buses waited to take him and the other North
Korean visitors to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Gyu Sol, 66, spoke to his brother over a cellular phone
handed to him by his family members in South Korea. ``Take good
care of our parents, and you must fill in for the role that I
cannot play,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes took place outside the Sheraton Walker Hill Hotel in
Seoul, where the 100 visitors from the North stayed during their
four-day reunions. An equal number of South Koreans made a
simultaneous trip north. Both groups returned to their homes on
Friday after celebratory, but bittersweet, visits.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, as eight buses of relatives headed out of the parking
lot and toward the airport, several North Koreans _ their hands on
the windows _ could be seen trying to catch a last glimpse of
family members.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 South Koreans, who were chosen through a lottery from
among 76,000 applicants, returned to Seoul at about 2 p.m. on a
chartered Korean Air jet. Earlier in the day, the same plane
carried the 100 North Koreans back home.
</P>
<P>
   The South Koreans described Pyongyang, the North Korean capital,
as a drab yet orderly city, with tall buildings and crowded
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Pyongyang appeared to be a lot freer than I had
thought, but their expressions seemed rigid,'' said Han Jae-il, 82,
who went north to meet his wife, who is 75. ``But all of the bad
feelings I had toward North Korea are all gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Television footage of Pyongyang showed a spacious and manicured
city, with long rows of 30-story buildings, mostly in drab grays or
tans. Accentuating the somber buildings were red signs bearing
revolutionary slogans like ``Self-Reliance, Powerful Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot more high-rise buildings and apartments than
I had expected,'' said Kang Ki-joo, 90, who met with his son in
Pyongyang. It is a city with ``no fat people,'' another visitor
said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, politics intruded on the family reunions. Lee
Jong-sung, 84, while visiting two sons in the north, said he heard
more praise of the North's leader, Kim Jong Il, than he could
stand. ``I finally told them to get some common sense,'' Lee said,
according to an Associated Press report. ``When they gave me that
political nonsense, they didn't feel like my own sons.''
</P>
<P>
   While more exchanges between the two countries are planned, the
visits will involve few of the families separated since the Korean
War solidified the division of the nation into a communist north
and a capitalist south. Some 10 million people have been separated
from their family members since 1950, according to South Korean
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The reunions are part of an accord reached the by North Korean
leader, Kim Jong Il, and the South Korean president, Kim Dae-jung,
during their historic meeting in June, when they agreed to start a
process toward reunifying the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has already agreed to re-establish rail links, and
last week it signed an agreement with one of South Korea's
conglomerates to develop a permanent meeting place for separated
families at Kaesong, just north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the North Korean visitors were given a heavily
guarded tour of a royal Korean palace built hundreds of years ago.
But unlike the upbeat atmosphere during an earlier tour of a giant
shopping mall, the North Koreans appeared somber and reluctant to
speak, even to each other.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the hourlong tour, a reporter asked a North
Korean visitor if he had been to the palace before.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long time ago,'' the North Korean man said. After a few more
steps, he added, ``I think it was 60 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But the short conversation came to a halt when a North Korean
cameraman swerved by, pointed to the old man and said: ``Look how
red his face is. He's tired. Leave him alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, rapprochement efforts continued between the two
Koreas. Soon after the plane carrying the visitors left for
Pyongyang, North Korea's State Symphony Orchestra arrived in Seoul
to hold the first joint concert with the Korean Broadcasting System
Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   The two Koreas have held joint performances of traditional arts
and pop concerts but never before combined their symphony
orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Byoung Hwa, lead conductor of the North Korean orchestra,
described the opportunity for a cultural union. ``We will show you
the soul of Korean music,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
