<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     08-18 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET INSIGHT: PUZZLEMENT IN A LAND WHERE RATES SELDOM RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 20.)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pushing on a string must get tiring. Or maybe just tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, these are probably not the best attempts to explain
why the Bank of Japan decided on Aug. 11 to lift short-term
interest rates for the first time in a decade. But they may not be
the worst explanations either, since the central bank's loose money
approach _ a zero-interest policy had been in effect since February
1999 _ seems to have done little to lift the Japanese economy out
of recession.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank, however, asserts that the economy is showing
``clearer signs of recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese stock market, which should be a leading economic
indicator, does not reflect those signs. The Topix index, which hit
a 52-week low Aug. 4, is down more than 14 percent this year in
local currency terms.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Elizabeth Allan, a senior vice president at Scudder
Kemper Investments and an analyst for the Japan Fund, talked about
the Bank of Japan and the outlook for Japanese equities. Following
are excerpts from the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. The decision by the Bank of Japan has perplexed a lot of
smart folks. Why do you think it raised rates? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing in Japan is ever made explicit, and people are
scratching their heads to understand this. But there are a number
of interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   One is that the bank wanted to assert its independence. Masaru
Hayami, the governor, had been saying it was abnormal to have
zero-interest rates. The subagenda there was the fact the
government has been piling up too much debt. In that context, I
suspect his thinking was that some cost for that borrowing is
different from essentially no cost.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor to bear in mind is that Japan is an aging country
with a lot of people on fixed incomes. They want there to be some
kind of return on savings.
</P>
<P>
   A third explanation is that Hayami is on a personal mission to
force a restructuring of the Japanese corporate and financial
structure. The thinking here is that if companies have free cash,
they will postpone making hard decisions. By putting a price tag on
the cost of money, you are pushing companies to restructure. If you
are a company on the edge of bankruptcy, an increase in interest
rates of 25 basis points could make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. The bank seems to think the economy is gaining strength. Do
you agree? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not clear if the economy is actually recovering. And I
don't think anybody expects the rate increase we saw will lead to a
series of tightenings. Politically, it would be very difficult for
the Bank of Japan to raise interest rates a second time without
much more concrete signs of recovery than we have had. That said,
the export sector has been extremely strong, as has investment
spending in technology by Japanese companies. But private demand
remains weak.
</P>
<P>
   However, as equity investors we are not completely wedded to how
the economy does on a macro basis. We see a lot of good things
going on at the micro level. A lot of companies are restructuring
and are doing things like providing employees with incentive-based
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   And this economy has been in a slump for over 10 years. That
means the potential for improvement is large.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. If demand is still slack, how can companies improve the
bottom line?  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Companies that have a lot of fat are getting rid of it. That
means if the economy stays in the doldrums and revenue growth
remains stagnant, the bottom line is expanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Shinko Research Institute did a survey of companies listed
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange for the fiscal year ended March 31 that
illustrates this point. The companies surveyed showed a 1 percent
decline in sales, but a 28.6 percent increase in profits.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if the survey is representative or not. But the
magnitude of the numbers is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Japan was hit hard by the energy crisis in the 1970s. Has
the run &LR; - &UR; up in oil prices this year done much damage? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. The rise in oil prices has not had much of an impact. The
Japanese used to be very dependent on imported oil, and the 1970s
were a very scary experience for them. But they have cut their
dependence on imported oil a great deal, in part by becoming
heavily dependent on nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. So far this year, the Japan Fund is down about 10 percent,
compared with an average decline of around 19 percent for mutual
funds that concentrate on Japan. What are you investing in? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Electrical machinery companies make up about 25 percent of
our portfolio, a group that includes stocks like Sony and Kyocera.
</P>
<P>
   We also have a reasonable position in the banks on the
expectation that a lot of bad news is already in the price. Bank of
Yokohama is our biggest bank holding.
</P>
<P>
   And our biggest holding is in Nippon Telegraph and Telephone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
