<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HCA-CREDIT-MARKETS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEST FOR HEALTHCARE CREDIT ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 20) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although still under the shadows of a government investigation
into its billing practices, HCA-The Healthcare Corp., the nation's
largest hospital chain, made a successful foray into the debt
markets on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Strong investor demand allowed HCA, formerly called the
Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp., to increase the size of its issue by
50 percent to $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   The debt offering was a key test of whether HCA had regained the
trust of investors, and apparently it had: they placed more than $2
billion in orders for the 10-year notes. It was also a test of
whether the for-profit health care industry was recovering after
years in critical care.
</P>
<P>
   The reception investors gave the HCA issue added to evidence
from the stock market that it is. Shares of publicly traded
hospital companies have soared this year, even as the overall stock
market has stumbled on concerns about rising interest rates and
slowing corporate growth.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen F. Lamb, a high-yield health care analyst at Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, called the market hot for hospital credit
issues. ``Issuers not taking advantage of this are asleep at the
wheel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Through underwriters led by Chase Securities and Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co., Nashville-based HCA priced 10-year senior unsecured notes at
99.53 to yield 8.821 percent, or about 305 basis points _ a basis
point is one-hundredth of a percentage point _ more than a 10-year
Treasury note with a comparable maturity. Price talk ahead of the
sale was of a spread over Treasuries of 312.5 to 325 basis points.
The notes, which were given an 8.75 percent coupon, have a maturity
date of Sept. 1, 2010.
</P>
<P>
   HCA is considered a bellwether in the hospital industry. It
initially planned to issue two maturities but settled on one.
Moody's Investors Services rated the 10-year note Ba-2, its
second-highest junk grade. The Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. gave it a
low investment grade, BB+.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Carter, senior market analyst at MCM CorporateWatch, a
research firm, said the deal included a make-whole call provision.
``In effect what this means is that the issue is essentially
noncallable because the price is so high and will only be called if
Treasury yields move significantly lower and it makes economic
sense to do so,'' he said. ``This is a regular feature on many
investment grade and upper-level-rated high-yield bond issues.''
</P>
<P>
   HCA said the proceeds from the financing would be used for
general corporate purposes including repayment of bank debt. In May
the company agreed to pay $745 million in civil penalties to settle
part of a broad government inquiry into whether its success was
achieved in part by cheating federal health programs. If approved,
it would be largest health care fraud settlement ever obtained by
the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, criminal and other civil investigations that have long
been at the heart of the case remain unresolved. They concern
whether the company's hospitals fraudulently overstated expenses to
increase reimbursement from Medicare and other federal health
programs and engaged in illegal financial relationships with
doctors. Under the terms of the partial settlement, both Columbia
and the government are under pressure to resolve the entire case
before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's debt sale represented the company's first trip to
the bond market since 1997, when government agents raided the
company's offices and hospitals in seven states, seizing documents.
Last year under the old corporate name HCA tried to sell $250
million of shorter maturity securities, but withdrew before they
could sell, citing market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the government's investigation, the hospital chain has
changed its name and installed a strong new management team to the
delight of some portfolio managers. It has also improved its
balance sheet by shedding 140 hospitals from a peak of 340 in 1997
and reduced its debt by about $2.4 billion, to just a little less
than $7 billion, trimmed costs and bargained for better terms with
private insurers who pay patient bills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to HCA, a large number of other companies issued
debt last week, selling over $12 billion in investment grade
securities, according to MCM CorporateWatch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
