<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIG-RED-WIRE-BOS &LR;      08-18 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-RED-WIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDE BILLBOARD COPY IS SATIRICAL, DOT.COM FIRM SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As ads go, they may be memorable for all the wrong reasons, and
they may be spotted soon nationwide, despite complaints about
irreverent content and possible legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   On billboards around Los Angeles for the last six weeks,
motorists have seen an image of George W. Bush on the phone. The ad
isn't touting Bush's presidential candidacy but the services of a
long-distance phone company called Bigredwire.com.
</P>
<P>
   The ad copy reads: ``Pay for long distance? Fuhgdat!''
</P>
<P>
   A vulgar wordplay on popular ``Whassup?'' ads from Budweiser?
Maybe, maybe not. A second Bigredwire.com ad features Queen
Elizabeth II, and plans call for a version of the ad to run soon in
Boston with an image of US Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a problem with people seeing us as a little bit
rude,'' said Bigredwire.com general manager Frank Jiang, explaining
the advertising strategy of the California-based company. ``People
who are rebellious are our market.''
</P>
<P>
   The company did not seek permission from Bush, Queen Elizabeth,
or Kennedy to use their images in ads, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling home from the Democratic Convention in Los Angeles
Friday, Kennedy had no comment, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In other cities, Bigredwire.com plans to use different local
figures such as Hillary Rodham Clinton in New York, Elian Gonzalez
in Miami, and Al Gore in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satirizing public figures'' is ``fair game,'' Jiang said of a
campaign that could run through Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   But these ads might not meet a court's definition of parody and
satire, said M. Robert Dushman, an attorney with Brown Rudnick
Freed &AMP; Gesmer of Boston who specializes in First Amendment rights
and free speech issues.
</P>
<P>
   While satires and parodies may qualify as protected speech, the
unauthorized appropriation of the likeness of a public figure in a
commercial ad campaign may not. Otherwise, a fast-food chain could
use images of Michael Jordan to promote their hamburgers and not
bother to pay him an endoresement fee.
</P>
<P>
   Courts can distinguish between ``pure speech'' and ``commercial
speech,'' and some courts might be willing to award monetary
damages to the public figure or order the advertiser to ``cease and
desist'' from running ads that use the public figure's likeness,
said Natasha C. Lisman, a partner at Sugarman Rogers Barshak &AMP;
Cohen, a Boston law firm.
</P>
<P>
   But just because public figures have the right to sue a
commmercial venture that attempts to profit from their image
doesn't mean they will; public figures might conclude that a legal
battle would bring them even more unwanted publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood of Queen Elizabeth being a plaintiff in an
American lawsuit is pretty small,'' Dushman said.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the queen or Bush were to sue, the suit might raise
Bigredwire.com's public awareness _ just what the company wants,
said Judy Warner, a former editor of Adweek New England.
</P>
<P>
   Bigredwire.com could simply take down the billboards and say,
```OK, sorry, we quit,''' and that could end the lawsuit, said
Warner, who just launched ComAve, a Melrose, Mass. firm that
advises clients on how to manage content on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it might possible for Bigredwire.com to reap a
lot of publicity without suffering major consequences, and just
because the queen won a battle against the company, it wouldn't
necessarily mean it would have to stop running ads of other public
figures. Each might have to bring a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang said Bigredwire.com hasn't heard anything from the Bush
campaign or the British consul's office, though he's heard plenty
from local politicians complaining about the proximity of the
billboards to churches and residential neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In running the ads, Bigredwire.com wants to get out the message
that it offers free long-distance calling to consumers who agree to
view ads on the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how its business plan is supposed to work. Consumers
register at Bigredwire.com. Then they make long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   A record of calls appears at the company's Web site. Next the
consumer visits the Web site. If a call is checked off within a
specified time, charges can be forgiven. If consumers fails to
visit the Web site, they're billed for the call.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the appeal of free calls could make Bigredwire.com
one of the busiest sites on the Web, and the company hopes to make
money by selling advertising on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the billboards in LA and the media attention it's gotten
for the ads have attracted many new customers to the company, Jiang
said. Closely held Bigredwire.com does not disclose financial
information. It hopes to go public next year.
</P>
<P>
   One cheap way a for tiny unknown to stand out in a space
occupied by giants such as AT&AMP;T is to stir up ``controversy for
controversy's sake,'' said former Adweek editor Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telecommunications is very competitive,'' she said. ``An
upstart needs to make noise. Otherwise, it's dot-com who?''
</P>
<P>
   Combining celebrity with an ``in-your-face message'' is a
surefire way to get attention, said Stephen A. Greyser, a professor
of consumer marketing at Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   And Bigredwire.com is probably delighted when reporters call.
</P>
<P>
   Said Greyser, ``From the company's perspective, media coverage
is free public relations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
