u f BC-GERMANY-TELCOM-NYT &LR;      08-18 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-TELCOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY-AFTER SYNDROME HAUNTS WINNERS IN GERMANY'S MOBILE PHONE LICENSE
AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Hours after they clinked Champagne glasses
on Thursday evening, winners in Germany's $46 billion auction for
wireless licenses began feeling the hangover on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the most vivid case of winner's remorse, Hutchison Whampoa of
Hong Kong immediately announced that it was pulling out of one of
the six groups that won a license because the prices were simply
too high. Hutchison, which is loaded with cash as a result of
selling its stake in the British mobile phone company Orange PLC,
had been partners with the Dutch telephone company KPN and NTT
DoCoMo of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison was supposed to contribute 22.5 percent of the group's
license fee, and that money will probably be made up by KPN and
BellSouth Corp., which owns 50 percent of KPN's mobile telephone
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's, meanwhile, confirmed that it would reduce the
credit ratings for most of the big telephone companies involved in
the bidding: Deutsche Telekom of Germany; France Telecom, which is
investing through the German company Mobilcom AG; British
Telecommunications PLC, which is investing through Viag Interkom;
and KPN.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also continued to sell stocks in the winning
companies. Mobilcom's stock plunged 7 percent Friday in Frankfurt,
from 117 to 110 euros. Telefonica SA of Spain and Sonera Oy of
Finland, which lead a group called Group 3G, saw their shares
decline by similar amounts on their exchanges. Shares of Deutsche
Telekom, the German telephone giant that is determined to build a
pan-European network, had already lost half their value since the
company paid $6 billion for a similar wireless license in Britain
in April; on Friday, Telekom nudged down another 3.89 percent
Friday after pledging to pay $7.6 billion for its German license.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the frenzied bidding, analysts and company
executives generally agreed that the auction's outcome was about
the worst one possible. Beyond the dizzying level of the prices
offered, the real surprise was that the auction produced six rivals
rather than five. Deutsche Telekom and Vodafone Airtouch PLC, the
two biggest wireless players in Europe, had been determined to
outbid seemingly weaker bidders like Group 3G and acquire enough
licenses to reduce the field.
</P>
<P>
   But even though only seven groups joined the bidding originally,
one of which dropped out last Friday, neither Telekom nor Vodafone
was able to force out any of the other six. What they did manage to
do was push up the total price of licenses by nearly $15 billion
between Monday morning and Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sommer, chief executive of Deutsche Telekom, complained on
Thursday night that the auction had been distorted because some of
the rival telephone companies came from countries that awarded
licenses to them for little or no money. Telekom officials were
particularly incensed by Telefonica of Spain, part of the
victorious Group 3G, because the Spanish government had awarded it
a Spanish wireless license at very low cost while rejecting
Telekom's application.
</P>
<P>
   The deeper question is when _ or even whether _ the huge bets on
third-generation wireless licenses will pay off. Using a
technological standard called United Mobile Telecommunications
Service, or UMTS, the telephone companies hope to offer high-speed
data transmission that will give people wireless access to the
Internet and a host of new mobile commercial and information
services.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies must first build the new networks and then
market an entire generation of new services, most of which are
still unknown to consumers. Industry executives say the networks
will not be ready until at least 2002 or 2003, though all operators
will be under heavy pressure to have their networks running as soon
as possible. Gerhard Schmid, the chief executive of Mobilcom,
predicted that his company could break even on its investment by
2005. Most other companies have been reluctant to divulge their
time-frames for turning a profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
