<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIAPAS ELECTIONS TO TEST STRENGTH OF MEXICO'S LONG-POWERFUL
PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Although he calls himself a religious man, there
is something mildly unholy about the way Pablo Salazar delights in
the prospect of killing the Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigns to be governor of Chiapas, the 45-year-old
senator and father of three projects himself as a kind of political
dragon-slayer, struggling against a government that has wreaked
havoc on the lives of poor and defenseless Mexicans for more than
seven decades. The long-governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, known to all as the PRI but which he calls a fire-breather,
was severely wounded on July 2, when it lost the presidency for the
first time since 1929. But, Salazar warns, the party still gasps
with life.
</P>
<P>
   So with the help of his supporters at the polls, the candidate
promises to deliver the coup de grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI has entered intensive care,'' he called out to some
400 supporters in a rally outside the city of San Cristobal de las
Casas. ``It is gasping for breath. And on August 20, we are going
to disconnect its oxygen tank and give a Christian burial to a
party that no longer has a place in Chiapas.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dawning months of what may be a new era of democracy in
Mexico, the people of Chiapas will be the first to test the depths
of this country's political reforms when they go to the polls on
Sunday to elect a new governor.
</P>
<P>
   The election _ in a state racked by generations of poverty,
layers of social divisions and sporadic violence between the
government and the Zapatista rebels _ will be the first major state
contest since the fall of the PRI on July 2. It offers a look at
how local politics have begun to evolve in Mexico. And for the PRI,
this election is widely seen as a test of the party's ability to
survive among the scrappy forces of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar, a former member of the PRI who served as a mediator
between the government and the Zapatistas, says a fair, transparent
election will mean the difference between war and peace.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, he says, he would urge the president to drastically
reduce the military presence in Chiapas, estimated at up to 50,000
troops. And he says he would create political openings that would
allow leaders of the rebel Zapatista army to stop their fight and
join the government in resolving the social crises in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   He offers his campaign as a testament to his ability to forge
agreements. Eight opposition parties with otherwise divergent
agendas _ including the conservative National Action Party of the
president-elect and the leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party _
have united behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past governors have been obsessed with defeating the
Zapatistas,'' Salazar said in an interview. ``That is not in my
agenda. I am not a Zapatista, but I have learned to understand
them, and I believe that we must try to get them involved in
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the PRI carried about 45 percent of the vote in Chiapas
during last month's presidential elections, opinion polls and most
political analysts predict that Salazar will win by a comfortable
margin.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, Sami David, 50, the PRI's candidate, has found
more than the polls to be ominous. At the start of a campaign visit
to his opponent's hometown, Soyalo, David was greeted by a
belligerent mob that pelted his entourage with rocks and sticks,
and he was forced to scramble for safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that I have not come at the best time to the
party,'' said an exasperated David, referring to his run for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, among people in a village called Corazon de Maria,
the people seem likely to cast their votes more as an act of
protest against the PRI than as a show of support for the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Radishes in this village grow as big as apples, while the people
languish from illiteracy and poverty. Although the village sits in
the shadow of a brand new airport and less than 10 miles from one
of Chiapas' largest cities, the people of Corazon de Maria still do
not have paved roads and clean drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   On good days, farmers said, they sell their radishes at a local
market for about $5 per crate. But most days are bad, and the
farmers are stuck giving away their produce for pennies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided that we will not vote for the PRI,'' said
Javier Gomez Diaz, 19, taking a break from bundling his radishes
for market. ``Even if they come here and make promises, they will
not deceive us anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this discontent echoes across most of the state, some
communities continue to support the PRI. But that support hardly
sounds enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   In Amentenango del Valle, a community supported mostly by the
work of women artisans who mold clay pots, Petrona Gomez Hernandez,
34, described voting for the PRI more as a habit than an act of
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our custom to vote for the PRI,'' she said. ``We have
always given them our vote.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the PRI had improved the lives of people in her
community, she shook her head no. ``Our lives never change,'' she
said. ``We are poor and that is how we will continue; poor until we
die.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At a rally there, David presented his candidacy as a force for
reform across Chiapas and within his own party. He told voters he
would increase government spending on social programs; that he
would make the government more accessible to their pleas for
assistance in selling their clay pots across the country; that he
would work to build peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must work so that there are more doves of peace than there
are guns in Chiapas,'' he said, holding up the clay doves made by
the young girls in training to become pot makers. ``There must be
more doves of peace than expressions of impugnity; more doves of
peace than injustice and insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Election monitors said that they have received hundreds of
reports about PRI campaign officials trying to coerce voters by
telling them that their social benefits would be cut if the
opposition wins. But recent incidents among Zapatista supporters
and right-wing paramilitary groups have raised concerns about the
possibility of violence on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, 90 people accused of supporting the Zapatista
rebels were burned out of their homes by a masked group of men
carrying rifles and semiautomatic weapons. The group, which called
itself ``Peace and Justice,'' refused to let the rightful residents
return to their land for several days until they were chased away
by military troops.
</P>
<P>
   Such attacks, observers worry, might frighten voters from going
to the polls on Sunday. In last month's election, more than 50
percent of voters in Chiapas did not cast ballots, the highest
abstention rate in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   A high turnout is crucial to Pablo Salazar. But when he winds up
his speeches _ often full of plans to increase higher education,
reform the state justice system and improve health care _ he asks
more of his supporters than just their votes. He enlists them for
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is preparing more of the dirty election tricks that
have kept it in power for 71 years,'' he says. ``And the only way
to stop them is by doing whatever it takes to defend people's
votes.'' He asks them to stay at the polls all day to monitor the
voting, and then to form caravans of cars to escort the ballot
boxes to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Then with a sly smile spreading across his face, Salazar warns
there will be trouble for anyone who stands in their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think the PRI would try to steal the ballots if they
see a group as big as this one watching over the polls?'' he said
to a crowd that filled the plaza. ``And if they do, we will beat
them. If anyone dares, we will tie them up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
