<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      08-18 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNOLOGY EASES EFFECTS OF VERIZON STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mabel Graham learned last week that the repair of her
sister's telephone line had been delayed by a strike at Verizon
Communications, she loaned her sister and brother-in-law a cellular
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't affected by the strike, not at all,'' said the
71-year-old Boston woman. ``I let my sister and brother-in-law use
my cell phone so they could reach their children and their doctor.
Sometimes, it's better to have one of these cellular phones than
having a regular telephone in the house,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two weeks after 85,000 telephone workers walked off jobs
at Verizon Communications, the company created by the merger of
Bell Atlantic Corp. and GTE, cellular telephones and a host of
other alternatives offering everything from directory assistance to
nationwide call completion have reduced one portion of the strike's
roar to a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the company's 25 million clients on the East Coast have
had Internet access and basic telephone service since telephone
operators, customer-service representatives, and technicians struck
shortly after 12 a.m. Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of choices available for some services that were
once the sole province of the phone company are staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS offers a nationwide directory, and it will connect
your call. Internet service providers such as 555.1212.com,
switchboard.com, and AT&AMP;T's online directory anywho.com are also
filling the directory-assistance void.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the strike has not impacted the company,
however. A backlog of repair orders increased this week to 100,000
from 80,000 last week. And, residential and business customers
seeking installation of new wireline data or telephone services are
being told that services will not resume until the strike is
settled. This may be particularly difficult for Verizon since the
summer is its busiest period for new residential and business
installations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unions know that the company cannot tolerate for very long
a large backup of installations and repairs,'' said Robert Ross, a
labor expert at Clark University in Worcester, Mass. ``One hundred
thousand backlogged repair orders is, when you look at it closely,
gigantic, especially if many of them are business orders. So the
real weapon, the incentive to bargain, is the impact a strike will
have on installations and repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the tactic has worked. Days after union negotiators
for 72,000 members of the Communications Workers of America
demanded the right to use a card check neutrality agreement to
organize an estimated 32,500 Verizon Wireless employees, the
company agreed to a significant portion of the union's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have resolved a dispute over the CWA's push for
access to work involving the installation of high-speed digital
subscriber lines _ jobs that are critical to the growth of the CWA
and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which
represents 13,000 striking telephone technicians.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the creation of so many alternatives to
directory assistance and customer service underscores the impact
automation and deregulation have had on the telecommunications
industry and, ultimately, on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of choices increase, from major suppliers such as
Verizon to new nimble start-ups, some analysts maintain that
consumers will be less tolerant of inconveniences and more likely
to switch to providers that can guarantee optimal service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are no longer a captive audience,'' noted Keffrey
Kagan, an independent telecommunications analyst in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in history, telephone customers are
starting to have choice,'' he added. ``In three or four years, they
will be much more comfortable with making a switch. Soon, they will
be looking for other avenues and they will switch quickly. Churn
will have a big impact on local phone service, especially when
unions roar. . . . Five years ago, there was no competition and no
place to go. Now, that's changing. People are not necessarily
stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago the loss of a telephone operator would have been
enough to shut the old Bell Telephone Co. down. ``Today, directory
assistance is more of a convenience and eventually it will probably
be consolidated,'' said David Mahan, executive vice president of
CTC Communications in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He envisions a future dominated by broadband, high speed lines
that offer efficient and instantaneous connections 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``To install and deliver this system to customers will be less
labor-intensive, and consumers will be offered a market basket
approach to products,'' noted Mahan. ``These will be web-based
services. That is the infrastructure for the way people will
communicate in the next 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahon should know. His company, CTC, offers voice and data
services to 13,000 customers. CTC, which has deployed a Cisco
Systems-powered high-speed broadband network across more than 30
states, is also one of Verizon's largest wholesale customers.
</P>
<P>
   When new customers sign up with Verizon, CTC offers billing
audits, calling plans, and technology evaluations. The firm then
bids directly for Verizon customers, offering to move them from
Verizon's network to its own.
</P>
<P>
   Because CTC customers place their orders through computers, it
has not been hampered by the loss of directory assistance or other
customer services.
</P>
<P>
   However, company requests for new installations have backed up
because of the strike. The company has a backlog of about 50
orders; its customers are typically big businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
