<SLUG> BC-DEM-VOICES-I-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FLORIDA, DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION HAS IMPACT ON SOME, BUT NOT
OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ The speech, confident and powerful, rang
through the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles and, far
across the country in South Florida, made Darren Gentry reconsider
his vote for George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But it was President Clinton's address Monday night, three days
before Vice President Al Gore took the microphone, that swayed
Gentry, a registered independent and fitness manager from Coral
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   He was leaning toward Bush when Clinton took that podium. As
Clinton spoke of the prosperity the nation enjoyed during his
presidency, Gentry, watching on television, began to doubt the
wisdom of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it turned me around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore's vote to lose, as he took his turn on stage
Thursday. He did not lose it. He did not win it, either. His speech
lacked real passion, Gentry said, repeating the criticism that has
long dogged Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of words,'' he said, as he watched. ``It doesn't seem
like he's conveying his emotions.'' And, he said, Gore had made
promises without saying how he would deliver, in a speech lacking
style and substance.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gentry, he is back where he started, in the middle. At
least for Gore's sake, he no longer is leaning the other way.
</P>
<P>
   In vote-rich Florida, which has elected Bush's brother, Jeb
Bush, as its governor, the vast majority of Republicans have
refused to even think about jumping across the party line and
joining Gore. This convention seemed his best opportunity to cement
his base with unexcited Democrats and, maybe, to sway independent
voters here.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry, 25, liked what he saw in Bush's campaign coming out of
the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what he's doing with Social Security,'' allowing people
to invest a percentage of it, Gentry said. ``I believe he's
building a strong nucleus of people who support him, people like
John McCain and Colin Powell.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, going into his own convention, just seemed bland, Gentry
said. But Gentry began to waver as he listened to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton made a great speech,'' he said. ``He nailed it. I
think it was the best speech of his entire presidency. Why change
things? When was the economy this good? And the Republican Party
keeps saying that we need this massive change? Obviously that's not
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Gentry said he would have listened to more campaigning
before he firmly made up his mind, Gore had a chance at the
convention to at least continue his advantage going into the
speech. But Gentry said he did not do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is saying, `I will, I will,' but he is not saying how,''
Gentry said of Gore's speech. ``I'd like him to tell me how he
plans to implement his ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   He did find some reasons for preferring the Democratic platform,
after watching both conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Several voters interviewed this week have said that the two
conventions seemed programmed, almost too smooth, but Gentry was
pricked by one thing about the Republican convention. The
Republicans spoke a lot about their diversity but did not back up
their claims with real proof, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Clinton kept saying about diversity is true,'' he said.
``Look at the people in his administration. That's diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's speech inspired traditional Democrats, Gore's
speech seemed to comfort them. Adele Yuckman, 82, of Key Biscayne,
missed Clinton's speech. ``I fell asleep,'' said Yuckman, a
lifelong Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   She watched Gore from bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course he's dull,'' she said, watching his speech, propped
up on pillows, a book close by. ``But he isn't as dull as he
usually is.''
</P>
<P>
   She will vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personality isn't everything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Torres, a psychologist in Miami, only listened to the
convention. He is blind.
</P>
<P>
   What he heard in Clinton's voice, early in the convention, was
the great orator, more style than substance. What he heard from
Gore, he said, was ``pragmatic, sincere, specific.''
</P>
<P>
   He also heard a candidate ever edging toward the political
center, toward survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they need to win,'' he said, adding that he had
heard the same thing in Bush's voice. He will listen harder, to
decide who gets his vote.
</P>
<P>
   Among Miami's Cuban-Americans, there seemed little Gore could
say to win over a voting bloc that lands solidly, election after
election, on the Republican side.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian Gonzalez case turned many here even more solidly
against the Clinton administration. Gore's split with his party _
he said that family court should decide the custody _ has been
dismissed by many voters here as a weak gesture, politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   But in the slivers of that community where people have voted
Democrat _ or at least considered it _ it was Clinton's speech,
again, that made voters consider Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Serrano, 58, a mortgage broker, watched the convention with
his brother, Ruben Serrano, 56. They are both registered
Republicans. ``The speech,'' Raul Serrano said of Clinton,
``reminded me of the good things the Democrats have done. I don't
think it will be that bad with Gore, after all.''
</P>
<P>
   His brother, a real estate agent, said he would have a hard time
voting for Gore, but was also undecided. ``These conventions are
just all-night parties that are not helping me at all,'' he
grumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech, to Ruben Serrano, was more of the same. ``A big
show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Raul Serrano warmed to Gore during his speech. ``I think the
guy needs to be given a chance,'' he said. ``I think he
strengthened his position.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``he seems to be loosening up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's selection of Senator Joseph I. Lieberman as his running
mate did not seem to resonate here with Gentry, who is Jewish, or
others. It was not a big issue, before or after Lieberman's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice presidents play a minor role for me,'' said Michael
Shapiro, a vice president for Smith Barney Investments in Boca
Raton, as he watched the convention earlier this week. ``I believe
Gore needed to do something to untarnish his party's image.
Lieberman was it.'' He, too, said he would make up his mind later,
after the presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   The convention was far from a fixation for many people here in
South Florida. But, because the Florida Marlins were off Thursday
night, the patrons at Nippers Bar in Boca Raton tuned a television
to Gore's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' said Geoff Klein, a
25-year-old stockbroker from Boca Raton who has made up his mind to
vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A few tables away, a group of men stared at another television
with excitement. They seemed impressed by what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   But they were watching wrestling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
