<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHEALTHY ATTITUDES FOR MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men's Health magazine is doing its readers no favor with its
survey listing the nation's most ``anti-male'' college campuses.
Listen up, freshmen: If you buy half the chauvinistic claptrap in
this magazine, you'll never get a date.
</P>
<P>
   The September issue of Men's Health (``Sex Olympics!'' ``Fat to
Flat!'') features a report on the best and worst colleges for men,
based on a series of criteria including how many fraternities are
on campus (more is better), the quality of the athletic facilities,
and _ the real determinant _ whether men feel ``welcome.'' A school
betraying an interest in women being protected from rape gets a bad
mark. Ditto a school with an abundance of women's studies programs.
And check out how well the college complies with Title IX, the
federal law requiring equal access to school sports. More for gals
can mean less for guys.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, four of the 10 worst colleges in this backlash
bonanza are in New England: Brown, Dartmouth, UMass at Amherst, and
Bates College in Maine. All are tarred with having ``frigid sex
policies'' or promoting the attitude that ``Every guy's a rapist
here'' because women are told they have a right to refuse sex, even
from a BMOC.
</P>
<P>
   Oberlin College in Ohio is listed in the top 10 worst schools
for men because the students ``protest everything from human rights
violations in Latin America to the use of rats in the neuroscience
lab.'' Human rights: how very antimale!
</P>
<P>
   One matter of higher math seems to confuse the men, however. The
influx of women into college over the last decade, especially in
the Ivy League, has tipped the balance against men's dominance on
campus, a bad thing. But a ratio of two babes for every guy, hey,
that's a good thing, isn't it? Back to the calculator.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another math lesson for the folks at Men's Health: Gender
equity is not a zero-sum game. Giving women _ or blacks or gays or
the disabled _ more rights doesn't take anything away from the
straight, white, privileged, or pumped-up men cruising America's
campuses. Assuming otherwise is a definite turn-off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
