<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SOCIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY'S DURABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(For release Monday, August 21, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senator Joseph Lieberman changed his mind about privatizating
Social Security, and Governor George W. Bush should do the same. As
the governor acknowledged in a campaign position paper, ``Social
Security is a defining American promise that must be kept.'' With
modest changes, the program can be made fiscally sound for the
retirement of the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . Privatization would likely make our most important
social safety net less safe, while doing little if anything to
actually benefit beneficiaries,'' Lieberman wrote in an unpublished
article. Lieberman prepared the article in June when he knew he was
under consideration to be Al Gore's running mate, but there is no
reason to doubt his sincerity. He flirted with the notion of
privatization a few years ago, but as he looked closer at the
proposal he saw, correctly, that it comes with hidden costs.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest is the amount of money required to pay for a
transition from the present system. Social Security is a
pay-as-you-go program, with current tax revenues paying the
pensions of current retirees. If some of its revenue is diverted to
private investment accounts, the government must eventually either
cut benefits or find the money elsewhere. Bush has promised not to
lower benefits for current recipients and those near retirement. He
would have to dip into general revenues to keep his word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal accounts will allow everyone to build assets and
independence,'' Bush says. His statement assumes a stock market in
which there are no losers. He pledges that there will be safeguards
on investments, but the only iron-clad investments are government
bonds, and Social Security already invests in these. Bush is
disingenuous if he does not acknowledge the possibility that some
people will invest unwisely. Either he insures the investment,
which encourages investors to speculate, or he is willing to allow
people to accept losses in what ought to be their bedrock
retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security trustees are bound by law to keep the program
solvent, and they have made projections 75 years into the future.
According to the middle of three scenarios, the system will begin
to run a deficit in 2015 and run out of money by 2037.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong economy has pushed the insolvency back from 2030
in the 1995 projection. And the most optimistic scenario, which
assumes a very strong economy, would have the system survive the
onslaught of the baby boomers with little difficulty. The most
pessimistic projection has the system going bankrupt by 2026, but
based on recent economic performance, this is extremely unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Bush employs the middle-range projection as if it were pure
fact. However, when it comes to his own plan, he avoids the
specificity of the Social Security scenarios. He does not reveal
estimates of future stock market growth, the range of investments
he contemplates for the private accounts, or the fees that
investment managers would charge for administering them. His is a
showy program tailored for campaign consumption, not a fully
realized plan.
</P>
<P>
   Using the middle-range projection, it is possible to keep the
system solvent by several limited changes, including moving
government workers into the system and raising the cap on the
amount of salary subject to the Social Security tax. The government
could also invest some portion of the tax revenue in the stock
market, where, as Bush says, the rate of return historically is
better than that of government bonds. However, the government would
still be responsible for paying benefits if the market had a bad
stretch sometime over the next 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, it would have been impossible to predict the advent of
antibiotics, let alone the treatments for heart disease and other
ailments that have lengthened life so considerably. And few could
have been so prescient as to foresee the great boom of the 1950s
and 1960s, then the slough of the 1970s and early '80s. Most people
could not even look four years ahead to the onset of the Great
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   That economic catastrophe reminded Americans in the 1930s of the
need to buffer old age against the vicissitudes of life. Back then,
Americans lived to an average age of 61; now their average lifespan
exceeds 76 years. They still need a guaranteed pension for their
final years. It would be unfair to future retirees to tamper with
what Lieberman rightly describes as ``the greatest social insurance
program ever created.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1952EDT &QL; 
