<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUFFRAGE FOR SUMMER FOLK? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 20, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tax revolt of second-home owners is bubbling up in vacation
resorts from the Hamptons to Cape Cod. ``Taxation without
representation!'' the summer residents cry, as their property taxes
rise to fund the schools or land banks or other issues where they
have no vote. Although it may seem logical at first to give a
franchise to people paying large property tax bills, offering
voting rights to summer residents who want to be able to vote in
their year-round communities too is not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Voting rights should not accrue to anyone based on the number of
pickets in their fences. The 24th Amendment to the Constitution,
which permanently banned poll taxes in 1964, crystalized the
country's evolving policy on suffrage. Beginning at the state level
and eventually at the US Supreme Court (in Harper v. the Virginia
Board of Elections) America has been steadily separating property
ownership from voting rights. In the Harper decision, the court
established that ``voter qualifications have no relation to
wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, thanks to the large number of transient
students, establishing residence for the purpose of voting is a
simple matter. A court case in 1972 brought by three Clark
University students resulted in the state dropping a six-month
residency requirement and opened voter registration to anyone who
establishes ``actual domicile and intention'' to stay, but not for
any fixed period. Summer residents who want to register and vote on
a proposed tax assessment in Truro can do so, but they can't also
vote for mayor or Congress back home.
</P>
<P>
   Summer folk obviously contribute to the economies of resort
communities, ideally in a rough balance with the costs they exact
on land, water, and other resources. But people who rent also
contribute through meals and sales taxes, and no one is claiming
they should be able to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is not the only arrow in democracy's quiver. Summer
residents still have ample means to participate in local affairs:
attending town meetings, writing letters to the editor,
volunteering, forming residents' associations. Direct community
involvement is still the best way to increase their stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
