<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CANCER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN TO UNDERGO SURGERY SATURDAY TO REMOVE MALIGNANT MELANOMAS  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sen. John McCain of Arizona said Friday he would have
surgery on Saturday morning to remove two malignant melanomas that
were discovered after a routine skin examination earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The operations will require him to receive general anesthesia
and stay overnight at the Mayo Clinic Hospital in north Phoenix
where doctors Friday told McCain that treating the melanoma at his
left temple will also require a biopsy of his lymph nodes to
determine whether the cancer has spread to any internal organs. If
that becomes the case, McCain's condition would be regarded as far
more serious.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said the other melanoma, on his left arm, had been
detected early enough to remove it easily with no anticipated
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   But in both cases, doctors told him, the malignant spots were
unrelated and separate from any he had treated in the past _ which
medical experts consider a positive sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident; the doctors are very confident that we
will have this thing done very quickly,'' McCain said, smiling and
sounding upbeat as he and his wife, Cindy, met with reporters
outside the couple's adobe-style house in the north-central section
of Phoenix, a short distance from the hospital. ``I've been in a
number of fights in my life. This is just another one. I'm sure we
will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCain, 63, who abandoned his recent run for president in March,
conceded that there was a chance doctors might find something more
serious to treat after tests were conducted on the biopsy. But he
played down any concerns, joking with reporters and predicting that
he would return to the campaign trail on behalf of his party's
presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, and other
Republican candidates by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a short time, I'll be back on the Straight Talk Express,''
he said, referring to the bus rides he commandeered during his
campaigning for president, and after he withdrew, for other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, he cautioned, ``The doctors are confident, but you never
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Melanomas, can be the deadliest and most aggressive forms of
skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts say people with light skin are much more
susceptible to skin cancer than others, and McCain has been dealing
with the condition for years. In 1993, he had a malignant melanoma
removed from his shoulder, and ever since he has undergone periodic
medical examinations to monitor any additional or recurring
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks the curse of the Irish is alcohol,'' McCain
said. ``It's their fair-skin.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during a routine examination on Aug. 3 that doctors at
the Bethesda Naval Medical Center just outside Washington found the
two melanomas. They recommended further testing, and on Thursday at
the Mayo Clinic in Scottsdale, a suburb of Phoenix, McCain was
administered a battery of tests, including blood work, chest X-rays
and an electrocardiogram.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, McCain and his wife returned to the clinic to meet
with doctors, who discussed the results of his tests and their
recommended course of action. McCain said his doctors would meet
with reporters on Saturday after the operation to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking to reporters Friday, McCain apologized for news
leaks on Wednesday of his latest round of tests. He said he had not
intended to say anything until the tests were complete and that he
did not know who was responsible for the leaks. He said he was
especially sorry for the timing because the leaks came on the same
day Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut was accepting the
nomination to be the Democratic choice for vice president, making
him the first Jewish candidate for so high an office.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Lieberman as ``a dear friend,'' McCain said, ``I
don't think anything should have detracted from his moment.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also dispelled one erroneous theory, that his disposition
to skin cancer might have been caused by the five years he spent in
a Vietnamese prison camp. He said he was mostly indoors at the
time, adding, ``The one thing I wanted to do as a prisoner of war
was to see the sun. I went years without seeing the sun.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite potential problems that further medical tests might
suggest, both McCains tried to keep the situation light. As they
approached reporters who had been waiting more than an hour in a
broiling midday sun, McCain carried a basket of sunscreen bottles,
and an aide pushed along a wheelbarrow filled with ice and bottles
of water.
</P>
<P>
   McCain used the basket to make a case for constant use of sun
screen and that early detection of skin problems alleviates many
more serious problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before he and his wife returned to the house, a reporter asked
him to clarify a report that the couple had gone to the movies this
week. Yes, he said, they saw ``What Lies Beneath.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly realizing the allusion to his medical condition, he
laughed and said, ``I should have gone to see `The Gladiator.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
