<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-VOICES-III-NYT &LR;      08-18 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-VOICES-III-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEATTLE, YOUNG LIBERALS WEIGH GORE VS. NADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DEM-VOICES I, II, IV, V) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In one obvious sense, it would be hard to consider
Martine Dedek or John Roderick ``swing voters'' in the coming
presidential election. Young, unabashedly liberal, both proud
participants in last fall's demonstrations here against the World
Trade Organization, they both roll their eyes and offer a vigorous
``no way'' when asked if they would consider voting for the
Republican candidate, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, they will definitely go to the polls in November, they
are still undecided, and they could be part of a hugely influential
group in this election, especially in West Coast states where some
polls suggest that as many as 10 percent of voters express a
preference for Ralph Nader, the consumer advocate and Green Party
nominee. They are among the voters who are still making up their
mind between Al Gore and Nader.
</P>
<P>
   So as they followed the Democratic convention this week,
gathering at a friend's house Thursday night to watch Gore accept
the party nomination, they were willing to listen intently to the
vice president's speech. They came away ambivalent _ suggesting
that while Gore failed to dazzle or even much impress them with his
speech in Los Angeles, he may have drawn enough of a distinction
between himself and Bush to get their vote if the election seems
close in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore speech left all the friends grumbling that only Nader
was still bringing up the issues they considered central in this
election: corporate power, the forces of globalization, the
widening divide between the rich and the poor, here in this country
and around the world. They scoffed at many parts, and Dedek, 28,
who has worked as an advocate for battered women and for welfare
recipients, at one point pronounced the whole speech ``so
orchestrated, so predictable, so scripted.''
</P>
<P>
   She nearly rose out of her chair at one point when Gore pledged
to bring down the rising cost of prescription drugs. ``I mean, he's
still not getting at any of the larger issues here,'' Dedek said.
``Why are prescription drugs so expensive?''
</P>
<P>
   Roderick, a singer-songwriter and the piano player in a Seattle
rock band by the name of Harvey Danger, nodded in agreement, and
worried aloud that a Gore victory might bring four more years of
complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not horrified about the idea of Bush winning this
election,'' said Roderick, 31, who is about to graduate from the
University of Washington with a degree in the comparative history
of ideas. ``It could be the thing that reunites liberals around a
common enemy, I guess, for lack of a better word. It could force
liberals to see what their principles are.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, Phil Campbell, a reporter for The Stranger, an
alternative weekly newspaper in Seattle, said Gore still left him
feeling uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this obsession he has with his imperfections,'' said
Campbell, 27, who covers criminal-justice issues, breaking into an
imitation of Gore's voice as he watched the speech. ``I'm not
popular; I'm not at ease with myself,''' he intoned, as his friends
laughed. ``It's weird. A little self-deprecation's fine, but this
is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   If the election looks like a rout for either candidate of the
two main parties, there was general agreement that a vote for Nader
would be in order. But if the election looks like a close one, the
friends said, it could be a very different matter _ and here, their
words may offer some salve to the Gore campaign, which has always
insisted that in the end, many people will not want to ``throw
away'' their vote on Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it looks like Gore is clearly winning on Election Day, then
you can send a vote for Nader, especially with the time
difference'' on the West Coast, Campbell explained. ``If you know
Gore's going to win, you can vote for Nader and contribute to that
message being sent.'' But if it looks like a tight contest, he
said, he will probably vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Dedek, who currently has a job in public relations, reluctantly
agreed, explaining that on one core issue raised by Gore, she
thought there was a critical difference between him and Bush _
abortion rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
