<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-VOICES-IV-720&AMP;ADD     08-18 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-VOICES-IV-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S SPEECH HELPED TO OPEN MINDS, DELEGATES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Calif., Mass., Ill.)  (See also DEM-VOICES I, II, III, V) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As they packed their placards and headed home to
where the hard work waits, Democratic delegates and elected
officials said Friday they were confident that Vice President Al
Gore had opened the minds of undecided voters with his convention
speech on Thursday night, even if he might not have closed the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's address had two purposes: to mollify and energize party
loyalists who had expressed concern about the centrist cast of the
Democratic ticket, while also grabbing the attention of independent
voters at home. In dozens of interviews, those who watched Gore
from the floor said that he had clearly accomplished the first and
had put himself in a position to compete with Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas for swing votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited,'' said David Giese, a 58-year-old delegate
and small-business owner from Vermilion, Ohio. ``I can't wait to
get home and spread the word. He energized the Democrats and
brought in the independents. We know we can win this thing now.''
</P>
<P>
   While the speech may have been short on memorable lines, many
said that Gore had succeeded in establishing his own persona, in
subtly reassuring voters that he would not repeat President
Clinton's mistakes, and in turning his focus on policy into an
asset. Frustrated for months by the perception that Bush was simply
more likable than Gore, they responded particularly well to Gore's
assertion that ``the presidency is more than a popularity
contest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been this nervousness among delegates,'' said Richard
L. Brodsky, an assemblyman from suburban New York, ``because we've
got the Republicans on the dead run on every single issue. Ask the
American people who they agree with and they agree with us. Yet the
campaign had the trappings of a race for president of the senior
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky maintained that Gore's speech would help reposition the
race as less about personality and more about policy. ``It was up
to Al to insist on his agenda, and not let them back him off of
health care, the environment and the economy,'' he said. ``And I
think he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of those interviewed also said that Gore seemed
authentic and completely in control of his message. They said his
image was softened by the lingering kiss he shared with his wife,
Tipper, and they applauded his simple declaration of independence
from Clinton: ``I stand here tonight as my own man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world now knows he is not Bill Clinton,'' said Peter
Zachos, 60, an airline mechanic from San Mateo, Calif. ``It was an
emancipation proclamation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gus P. Bickford, a 37-year-old delegate from Westford, Mass.,
said that Gore had established himself by laying out his agenda in
such detail. ``I was into it,'' he said, ``because he was saying,
`These are my priorities, this is my candidacy.' And in a subtle
way he was saying: `I'm going to take you on, George Bush. You can
run against the previous administration, but we're talking about
the future here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the convention hall said that Gore seemed looser than
usual, and that he had disarmed the critics of his sometimes
robotic style by acknowledging, ``Sometimes people say I'm too
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning he was way too fast,'' said Bob Woodworth, a
Democratic ward leader from Cleveland, Ohio. ``But he didn't have
his usual quirks, the jerkiness of his body. He was very
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Several delegates commended Gore for speaking calmly and evenly,
without the volume he sometimes uses to inject passion into his
speeches. That device, said Cynthia Contreras-Rodriguez, a
29-year-old aide to an assemblyman from Santa Ana, Calif., has made
Gore seem insincere. ``He seemed really relaxed,'' she said. ``It
made me finally connect with him. When he wasn't calm, it made me
tune him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there were those who, accustomed to Clinton's gift for
connecting with his audience, felt Gore still needed to show more
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people can work a crowd,'' said Michael A. Schafer, the
husband of a delegate from Mansfield, Ohio. ``He's not really that
kind of guy. I just think he needed to space his wording and take
in the applause and show a little fire with the subjects he touched
on. He sounded like a good wholesome man, though, and I think the
country needs a good wholesome man.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Members of the party's liberal base _ minorities, trade
unionists, women, teachers _ were pleased that Gore took strong
stands for affirmative action, abortion rights, and hate-crimes
legislation, and against school vouchers and Bush's proposed
income-tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a concerted appeal to his base, and he did it in very,
very specific terms,'' said Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Chicago, who
had expressed concern this week about the ticket's centrist
leanings.
</P>
<P>
   As for the undecided voters, the delegates here were convinced
that Gore had started the process of reeling them in. His vows to
protect Social Security, add a Medicare prescription-drug benefit,
take medical decisions away from health-maintenance organizations,
provide tax credits for college tuition, and reduce crime rates
should all score with that part of the electorate, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the speech was to open minds,'' Brodsky said.
``What he had to do here was begin the campaign, not clinch it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
