<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-POWER-GLIDERS0819-COX     08-18 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-GLIDERS0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powered parachutes dot the skies
 &HT;    By Carolyn Banks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHVILLE, Texas _ From a powered parachute, wafting along 600
feet up at sunrise, ``top of the morning'' takes on a new
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The endless horizon, breathtaking. Look down, though, and it's
heart-stopping: like flying in an airplane with the windows wide
open and nothing underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   At Smithville Municipal Airport, which operator Les Hentschel
calls ``a little old country airport,'' pilots of conventional
private planes increasingly find themselves surrounded by new-age
interlopers: powered parachutes, three-wheeled vehicles with a
large propeller behind the pilot's seat. They look like go-carts
until the chutes behind them fill and they go up, up and away.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Williams offers introductory flights and instruction in
his specially outfitted rig with two seats and two throttles.
</P>
<P>
   The craft have been around since the 1980s and can be registered
as experimental aircraft with the Federal Aviation Administration.
The Smithville airport, far away from regular air traffic but close
to plenty of open land, has become something of a haven for powered
parachuting. Cars along Texas 71 sometimes swerve when drivers spot
one of the colorful aircraft flying over a field alongside the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, powered parachute enthusiasts fly at sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you have the stillest air,'' Williams said, adding
that an aircraft can fly until 11 a.m. if the wind is light.
</P>
<P>
   ``After than it gets very bumpy,'' he said, ``very thermally,
and it isn't as much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusk is also a good time to fly.
</P>
<P>
   A powered parachute can go as high as 16,000 feet, an unofficial
record held by a pilot in Missouri. Williams has been up to 3,000
feet. ``Between 500 and 1,000 feet is pretty standard around
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The machines can also fly very low, especially near an airport
with as much open land around it as Smithville's.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're not flying over people or scaring livestock,
we can fly as low as we want,'' Williams said. ``There are these
huge hayfields out here where we'll get down to maybe 10 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something like levitating.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said a powered parachute can fly 25 to 30 mph, but the
speed depends on the wind. One of the machines heading into a stiff
wind can stand still.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, Williams and some buddies went to a fly-in
at nearby Giddings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind is usually out of the south this time of year,''
Williams explained, ``so we can get there in no time.'' ``No time''
amounted to about 35 minutes to cover 20 miles.
</P>
<P>
   On such trips the powered parachutes rely on ground support.
Friends or family members drive pickups to the landing site so that
the flying machines can be brought home if need be.
</P>
<P>
   Portability and cost help make the sport more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a hangar for a powered parachute,'' Williams
said. ``You can keep them in your garage.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some people don't bother with an airport, he said. They
just unfurl their chutes on the ground in their front yard and take
off.
</P>
<P>
   Powered parachutes are relatively inexpensive compared with
other types of small aircraft: $8,000 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been flying powered parachutes since 1992. He had
received his private pilot's license a year before and tried
skydiving. He discovered that he liked flying with the parachute
more than the free fall.
</P>
<P>
   Tex West is Williams' oldest student. He's 67 and has 11 flights
and eight hours of training under his belt. He had seen the craft
before, ``but I always thought that was stuff they do in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long about November of last year I saw one flying around here
and found out they were flying out of a field about a quarter of a
mile from my house.'' He located Williams and signed on for
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Last month West bought his own powered parachute. ``It's the one
I'm going to solo in when my instructor says I'm ready to solo.''
He keeps it on his porch.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Tucker is another Williams student. Tucker used to
sky-dive, ``but my legs got so beat up, I couldn't take landing
anymore.'' Before he found Williams, Tucker had tried flying a
powered parachute on his own and flipped during takeoff. ``I got up
and was fine, but I was very embarrassed,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board said
the agency does not keep statistics on deaths or injuries resulting
from powered parachute crashes.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a pilot's license to fly a powered parachute.
Williams, who is certified to teach by Aero Sports Connection, one
of three national organizations committed to ultra-light aircraft
safety, said that has its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   On any powered parachute Web site you'll find people talking
about how easy it is. ``And in good weather, if everything's going
right, it is,'' Williams said. ``They don't cover all of the
situations that someone can encounter, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Those might include a sudden gust of wind, a tangled line or an
uninflated end cell on the chute.
</P>
<P>
   Takeoff is the most critical moment. ``You have to make sure
your chute inflates all the way, and you have to make sure that
it's right overhead and it isn't oscillating,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Oscillation can overturn the machine, though the frame that
surrounds the propeller serves as a roll bar. Pilots wear safety
helmets and are strapped in, so they are rarely hurt in a takeoff
rollover, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Most pilots keep a practised eye on the chute as they taxi, and
then whoosh _ the chute is full and the craft makes its ascent,
which is surprisingly steep. Once aloft, the pilot steers with his
feet on a long bar, his hand on the throttle stick.
</P>
<P>
   Landing is said to be easy. ``Just head into the wind and power
down,'' Williams said. There's a slight tip forward when the front
wheel hits the ground, but the jarring is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason they're so safe,'' Williams said, ``is that there
isn't much to do, and they're moving so slowly that you have a lot
of time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans offer plenty of stories about powered parachutes that have
come down safely even when the engine has quit. Williams practices
landing with no engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a parachute,'' he pointed out. ``It's always up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the brightly colored rectangular chutes arc overhead
like the pilots' private rainbows.
</P>
<P>
   The powered parachutes at Smithville Municipal Airport have
attracted the attention of conventional pilots. Peggy Walicek, a
former judge and a member of airport's advisory board, says she's
dying to go up in one. ``I'm fascinated by them,'' said Walicek, a
former Cessna pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Even airport operator Les Hentschel, who owns a retired
crop-duster biplane, said he's considered trying a flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time I've been around these things,'' he
hedged. ``One of these days I'm going to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
