<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOMALIA-ARMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMALIA'S WARLORDS: COURTEOUS, WELL-ARMED FOES OF PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time
rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOGADISHU, Somalia _ The warlords of Mogadishu are a courteous
bunch. They smile. They reason in soft tones. They even serve
visitors cardamom tea and something sweet and orange resembling
Tang. But it is not their good manners that you notice first.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is,'' Osman Atto, one warlord, said with some
understatement, ``an assortment of armaments in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside his house here, Atto's militia was decked out with
countless automatic weapons, including a spiffy submachine-gun that
would fit nicely under a jacket. Many militiamen drive around town
in pickups mounted with antiaircraft guns. That might seem
excessive, but it was apparently useful when gunmen allied with
Atto recently blasted down a steel gate and kidnapped two foreign
aid workers for ransom money.
</P>
<P>
   The warlords _ who prefer to be called faction leaders _ look as
scary as ever. But there is a question in the hopeful air of
Somalia these days: How much power do the warlords really wield
nowadays? Not as much as they once did, many Somalis say, but
enough to make trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The question will be put to the test if, as expected, the first
Somali government since 1991 is formed and actually tries to govern
the chaos here. For the last several months, thousands of Somalis
have gathered in the neighboring country of Djibouti for political
planning. They have already set up an assembly aimed at guiding
Somalia through to a permanent government.
</P>
<P>
   But four of the five major warlords in Mogadishu have refused to
attend the conference, which makes any government's success a major
uncertainty. No one has forgotten that the warlords were the major
obstacle to the U.N. operation here in the early 1990s. And in
interviews here, three of them hinted at violence if any government
comes into Somalia from Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the consent of the population and the leaders of the
factional organizations, this would lead to civil war,'' said
Hussein Aidid, 38, who took power of one major faction after his
father, Gen. Mohamed Farah Aidid, was killed in 1996. ``Nobody can
impose on us a government.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another warlord, Muse Sudi Yalahow, said, ``We are going to
defend our town from these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Atto, who speaks a rough, idiomatic American English, said: ``I
would ignore it. And if anybody tries to tell me, `I am your
government,' I would tell them: `You go to hell.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harsh words, there is a growing sense in Somalia
that the warlords _ who divided power into clan fiefdoms after the
dictatorship of Siad Barre fell in 1991 _ may not be the deciding
factor any more. Courts and police set up by local Islamic groups
have siphoned off some of their authority. So have businessmen, who
not only hire their own militias but provide jobs and money to
people who are not thugs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most of all, Somalis seem plain weary of the warlords _
responsible for much of the factional fighting and failing in 12
previous peace conferences over the last decade to settle their
differences. ``Nobody listens to them,'' said one man, Ali Mohamed
Osman, 38, working in the Bakara market, in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
   Another man in the market, Farhan Mohamed Hersi, 18, suggested
that the warlords were out of step with most Somalis, who seem to
support the work in Djibouti overwhelmingly. ``We are against
anyone who is against peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell whether the warlords would oppose any
government, on the theory that order might mean less power for
them. But there is little doubt why they hate what is happening now
in Djibouti: The conference was organized explicitly to exclude
them as leaders. They were invited to Djibouti, but only as
ordinary citizens or members of their clans.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Djibouti is a reconciliation conference,'' Yalahow said. ``But
with whom are we reconciling in Djibouti? All the faction leaders
are here.''
</P>
<P>
   All except one, Ali Madhi, who served briefly as president in
1991 after Barre fell and who is taking active part in the talks in
Djibouti. He seems to be betting his own political future on a new
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the faction leaders who will decide what will
happen,'' he said in a recent interview in Djibouti. ``It's the
people who have the right to decide for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are not here,'' he added, ``they don't care
about their country.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the warlords' objections to the Djibouti conference have
been echoed by other Somalis. First among those is the number of
high officials from the collapsed Barre regime, including his
former ministers for interior, finance and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Second is that two politicians with more respect and influence
than the warlords have also refused to take part in the conference.
One is Abdullahi Yussef Ahmed, a former faction leader who set up a
stable, regional government in northeast Somalia called Puntland.
The other is Mohamed Ibrahim Egal, a former prime minister of
Somalia who is the leader of another pocket of stability,
Somaliland, in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Aidid, who served in the U.S. Marines, said the conference in
Djibouti is rushing ahead without Ahmed or Egal _ and may turn them
further away from the rest of Somalia, perhaps violently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a fear,'' he said. ``There is no quick solution to the
problems of Somalia.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts say they believe that Somaliland and Puntland
present political problems for the longer term. But the warlords,
they say, present the real threat of violence as soon any
government tries to assert its authority. To lessen that worry, the
delegates in Djibouti decided to seat any new government in the
inland city of Baidoa, at least temporarily, rather than the still
fractious historical capital, Mogadishu. But that issue is still
not settled.
</P>
<P>
   As with so many problems in places of the world with very
little, the final issue may be one of money. Many Somalis say that
the best way for a new government to succeed is to have money
donated from rich governments that would make it popular among
ordinary people and provide jobs for the warlords' gunmen. It may
even have something for the warlords themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they are going to do: kill them, put them
behind bars or give them contracts,'' said one businessman in
Mogadishu, whose name is being omitted here just to be on the safe
side.
</P>
<P>
   That last option is not so far-fetched: The three warlords
interviewed here are in business, and Atto was once a successful
construction contractor. He made a point of showing off to a
visitor his huge outdoor garage, filled with millions of dollars of
bulldozers, backhoes and other heavy machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't he make more money, he was asked, reconstructing the
nation's roads and buildings in peace?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not a problem _ being rich,'' he insisted. ``The
problem is achieving what you would call stability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
