<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FAILED-UTOPIA-1STLD-W     08-18 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAILED-UTOPIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTOPIAN DREAM SAID TO HAVE FAILED IN EAST AND WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Ideas) 
 (Eds: Inserts title and publisher of Susan Buck-Morss' book in 2nd
graf.)  
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1988, Susan Buck-Morss, a professor of government at Cornell
University and an authority on Marxist thought, visited Moscow to
meet with a group of Soviet philosophers. She had written a knotty
but keen book about Theodor Adorno and the Frankfurt School of
philosophy (``The Origin of Negative Dialectics'') and admired the
philosopher Walter Benjamin, who himself went on a pilgrimage to
Moscow in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I had been schooled in Western Marxism had
everything to do with my desire to enter into a collaboration,''
she writes in ``Dreamworld and Catastrophe'' (M.I.T. Press). ``Yet
this Marxist orientation,'' she adds with some chagrin, ``was of
very little interest to my Moscow counterparts.'' In fact, when she
began a lecture by citing Marx, the audience laughed; they thought
she was mocking standard ritualistic invocations of Marx and Lenin.
</P>
<P>
   But Buck-Morss wasn't intending satire. In fact, one of her
worries in her new, and eccentric, book is that with the fall of
the Soviet Union, the great dream of a ``mass utopia'' that marked
the 20th century in both East and West _ a dream in which Marx
played an important role _ is near extinction. There was nothing
wrong with the dream, Buck-Morss argues, but its execution went
awry, and despite most assumptions it failed in the West as well as
in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Her argument, which sometimes glints with insights but is almost
always clouded by distortion, deserves some close attention, for it
is exactly the kind of argument that is bound to be heard more
often as problems facing the formerly communist countries mount, as
the memories of the Soviet past recede, and as the very notion that
totalitarianism even existed comes under increasing challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Buck-Morss suggests, there is a ``hegemonic
discourse'' _ a dominant interpretation _ that affirms the moral
superiority of the West after the collapse of the Soviet Union and
the fall of the Berlin Wall: Totalitarianism was evil and democracy
virtuous, and virtue emerged victorious.
</P>
<P>
   But, Buck-Morss argues, this is all wrong. The Cold War, far
from being a battle between radically different societies, was
actually a ``story of similarities.'' East and West saw each other
as evil and ``refused to face their own failures as democracies.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck-Morss' similarities are actually symmetries. When she talks
about the 1920s for example, she outlines the various failures in
American ``democracy'' (the ironic quotation marks are hers): the
``red scare'' that brought all protesters under suspicion, the
Espionage Act of 1918 making criticism of the military punishable
by 20 years' imprisonment, attacks on aliens, labor unrest. ``The
record in the Soviet Union,'' she continues, ``is hardly more
heartening.'' There was the violence of the civil war, the quashing
of protests and, in the late '20s, Stalin's ``ruthless
destruction'' of peasants.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges that the ``body count was incomparably higher''
than in similar repressive events in the West, but even this is an
understatement that tries to preserve a symmetry where there is
none. Flaws in a democratic nation that could be and generally were
corrected by legislative and constitutional process are being
compared with the murder and starvation of tens of millions of
people in a social engineering experiment that created one of the
century's worst horrors.
</P>
<P>
   This is the pattern of most of Buck-Morss' symmetries. There are
sins of misplaced blame on both sides: After World War II, the
Soviets interpreted fascism as a capitalist phenomenon, exonerating
East German communists, while in the West, socialists were slurred
by being ``lumped together'' with fascists as totalitarian.
</P>
<P>
   There are also sins of violent excess: In the East, the class
war led to ``the danger of suffocation'' of liberties; in the West,
aggressive territorial ambitions led to ``grotesque'' weapons and
``orgies of annihilation.'' But all these symmetries are weighted
to give what Buck-Morss elsewhere calls ``the benefit of the
doubt'' to the East.
</P>
<P>
   When Buck-Morss turns her attention to cultural symmetries, it
comes as a bit of relief _ even though she tends to view art in the
Marxist manner, asserting that the aesthetic experience should
teach a political lesson.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible not to be intrigued by the similarities she
points out between the 1933 image of King Kong on the Empire State
Building and the 1933 plans for a gargantuan Palace of the Soviets
topped by a colossal statue of Lenin, or to be reminded of the
strange cultural interplay that moved the designers of Radio City
Music Hall to visit the Soviet Union for ideas, or Soviet planners
to seek out the factory designs of Henry Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Such detail (and some fascinating illustrations) are far more
concrete than Buck-Morss' political arguments. Still, in her world,
abstractions rule. And historical judgments have less to do with
life as it is lived than with the wish for what it could have been
or should still be.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no wonder that Buck-Morss caused some dismay among her
Soviet colleagues when she kept focusing on the commonalities
between East and West. They kept insisting, instead, that there
were ``modern horrors'' that were unique to them and that were not
being comprehended.
</P>
<P>
   The critic Frederic Jameson, who joined Buck-Morss in a Soviet
conference in 1990, even pointed out that the Cold War roles now
seemed reversed, with Western Marxists criticizing ``capitalist
commodity culture,'' while the Soviet philosophers used the
vocabulary of ``Cold War anti-communism.''
</P>
<P>
   This was, of course, because these Western intellectuals knew
all the flaws that scar the democratic state, all the weaknesses of
democratic culture, all the unkept promises and unmet ideals. They
dreamed of a more perfect world. But the Eastern intellectuals may
have known something more profound: that in the midst of a world of
imperfections and injustices, some distinctions are still worth
making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
