   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-LINUX (Undated) _ Remember Linus Torvalds? Last year, the
Linux operating system he created was going to revolutionize the
software industry, do more damage to Microsoft than the Justice
Department and make investors rich. This year, Linux stocks have
been in a prolonged downward spiral and Torvalds has been replaced
on magazine covers by Napster's Shawn Fanning as the technologist
most likely to wreak havoc on traditional ways of doing business.
By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-STRATEGIES-COLUMN (Undated) _ A new study finds the
market overall was less volatile in the '90s than in the '70s or
'80s, but individual stocks were more volatile, so portfolios need
greater diversification. By Mark Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Elizabeth Allan, a senior vice
president at Scudder Kemper Investments and an analyst for the
Japan Fund, talks about the Bank of Japan and the outlook for
Japanese equities. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-MCQUIDDY-AMSOUTH (Undated) _ Investing With: Dean
McQuiddy, manager of AmSouth Small Cap growth fund. By Jane Tanner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-SARALEE-COACH (Undated) _ Sara Lee Corp. is hoping that
nobody doesn't like Coach Inc. The upscale leather goods maker is
one of a handful of businesses, each being sold off in 20 percent
chunks, by Sara Lee, the $20 billion conglomerate that is stripping
down to its essentials _ underwear, food and household goods. With
a hand dipped in so many different businesses, from bras to hot
dogs to hosiery, Sara Lee is trying to whittle down to a smaller
size to attract Wall Street's attention. By Kate Berry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-PROFILE-KURZON (Undated) _ Kenneth Kurzon, publisher of
Greenmagazine and Greenmagazine.com, the Martha Stewart of personal
finance for the younger set. By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-ULTRA-TRAVEL (Undated) _ A look at the proliferation of
ultra-expensive, ultra-exotic package tours, like the Lost City
Tour that visits places like Angkor Wat, Lhasa, Petra and
Samarkand. By Suzanne Macneille.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-LOS-ANGELES (Los Angeles) _ The thriving Los Angeles fashion
district has more in common with 12th-century Baghdad than the
California of the new millennium. The 80-block jumble of prewar
commercial buildings, hastily constructed low-rise arcades
commingled with a few modern towers, is home to 5,000 companies
employing 50,000 people and taking in $8 billion a year in
wholesale and retail sales. And it epitomizes raw capitalism in
both its glory and its shame. By Joel Kotkin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RETIRE-401-PLANS (Undated) _ Of American workers eligible for a
401(k) plan, about three-quarters are enrolled, according to Hewitt
Associates, a Lincolnshire, Ill., benefits research firm. But that
still leaves about 75 million Americans who are not participating
in any retirement savings program. By Eve Tahmincioglu.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Detroit) _ When automakers brought out their 2000
models last autumn, executives were jubilant. Their companies were
enjoying record sales and the Federal Reserve's two interest-rate
increases seemed to be having little effect, as manufacturers
offset them by subsidizing more heavily their discounted auto
loans. Sales are still strong now, but the optimism has faded. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   PRELUDES-COLUMN-FAILURES (Undated) _ Failure used to connote
repo men and food stamps, leaving town in the dead of night to
escape the disapproving stares of neighbors. Today it's a rite of
passage. ``Failure is the price of being on the bleeding edge, on
the forefront of something you take pride in,'' said Gretchen Craft
Rubin, author of ``Money, Fame, Power, Sex.'' By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   ETHICS-COLUMN (Undated) _ What should an ethical person think
when asked to operate behind a colleague's back? By Jeffrey L.
Seglin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-ACURA (Undated) _ Acura has challenged the Mount
Everest of the auto world. Honda's luxury division gets straight to
the point: its new Acura 3.2 CL luxury performance coupe, on sale
since March, is aimed squarely at BMW's 3 Series coupe, introduced
last summer. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   CARSMART-LEXUS (Undated) _ It is difficult to reproduce the
exact mechanical alchemy that gives certain cars their living,
breathing spirit. Lexus has given it the old college try with its
IS 300, a 2001 model that is nearly identical to the BMW 328i sport
sedan in all the critical dimensions. By Dan Neil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Coded `l') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MALE-BODIES (Undated) _ The new book, ``The Adonis Complex''
(Free Press), tries to show exhaustively how concerns about body
image have come to dominate, and tyrannize, many American men.
``There's no question that there's a much greater emphasis on male
body image than there was a generation ago,'' said Dr. Harrison G.
Pope Jr., one of the book's three authors and a professor of
psychiatry at Harvard Medical School. By Guy Trebay.
</P>
<P>
   CHLOE-SEVIGNY-CULT (Undated) _ What is it about Chloe Sevigny
that has turned the fashion world into a pack of dogs howling about
her as if she were a full moon, or a lamb chop? Is it the fact that
she's vacant? Waspy? Not quite pretty? Alternative? For whatever
reason, the banquettes are alive with the sound of Chloe, recently
dubbed by Vogue as ``the New Postmodern Grunge Audrey Hepburn.'' By
Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   RAZOR-SCOOTERS (New York) _ Since arriving from Hong Kong at
Christmas, the chrome Razor scooters, which go for about $100 a
pop, have been selling out at both Toys ``R'' Us and the Sharper
Image, appealing equally to superannuated kids and to the regular
kind. By John Leland.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL-BUTLERY-SCHOOL (Undated) - Butler training school at the
St. Regis Hotel in Manhattan. Alex Witchel writes: ``When I stayed
at the St. Regis a few years ago, I opened the door to a young
woman dressed in white tie and tails who identified herself as the
butler. Since I had no idea what to do with her, I sent her on her
way. A female butler. What a funny idea. During my fifth hour of
butler training last week, I was no longer amused. Maybe it was
having to wear the white tie and tails in 80-degree heat. Or maybe
it was the new Manhattan phone books that needed to be carried into
the rooms and the old ones carried out. Or maybe it was that the
butlers training me had a quality _ a stillness, a patience, an
obedience of sorts _ that I will never have in this lifetime. If I
could have gotten my hands on the guest who left her underwear
piled in the bathtub and her shirt draped over a bedroom lamp, she
would not be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Geography can play a big role in the
August psyche of a gardener. By Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-POWER-DRESSING (Undated) _ Based on the women at the
Democratic National Convention, blue is the new power color, the
color that suggests true love and fidelity. By Ruth LaFerla.
</P>
