<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LASER-NUKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASER PROJECT FACES COSTS OVERRUNS AND DELAYS, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A giant laser being built at Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory will cost nearly $2 billion more than the laboratory
originally announced that it would, and will be delayed by at least
six years, according to a report released on Thursday by the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Called the National Ignition Facility, or NIF, the project was
originally expected to cost $2.1 billion and be finished by 2003 or
2004. By heating and compressing pellets of nuclear fuel with 192
converging lasers, NIF would aim to study the physics of nuclear
weapons without exploding them.
</P>
<P>
   So many technical questions surround the ambitious project, the
report found, that ``the cost of NIF could grow even higher and
completion of the project could take even longer'' than the revised
estimates suggest. The report also found that the former director
of the project withheld information about the problems from the
laboratory and from the Energy Department, which runs it.
</P>
<P>
   The project forms part of the nation's program to ensure the
safety and reliability of its nuclear stockpile. Because other
parts of this ``stockpile stewardship'' program may have to absorb
cost overruns at NIF, its political support has eroded.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., chairman of the energy
subcommittee of the Senate Appropriations Committee, which
recommends funding levels for the troubled project, said that the
GAO numbers were ``not out of the estimating ballpark from what we
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   But Domenici said that despite its importance as an element of
stockpile stewardship, ``NIF is a very controversial one now
because of these very excessive, these huge overruns.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has pledged to cover the
overruns largely using money from Livermore's part of the stockpile
stewardship budget. On June 1, he sent a letter to Domenici asking
that the project's construction allocation for fiscal year 2001 be
increased by $95 million, more than doubling the Clinton
administration's original request. The funds ``will come from other
Stockpile Stewardship Program activities,'' Richardson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is likely to meet with resistance, partly because
some of the money would probably come from other laboratories'
stewardship budgets. Domenici said he did not favor the change and
predicted the effort would fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own assessment would be that that GAO report will haunt
it,'' Domenici said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he would press the Energy Department to study
alternative versions of the project that would use a smaller number
of laser beams and cost less to build.
</P>
<P>
   Madelyn Creedon, deputy administrator for defense programs at
the Energy Department, said in an interview that money for the
overruns could be found within the stewardship program without
damaging it.
</P>
<P>
   The department ``is in the business of maintaining the
stockpile,'' she said. ``It's not in our best interests to skew the
balance of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report also found that the NIF's director until last
year, E. Michael Campbell, failed to report the problems to senior
management at Livermore and at the Energy Department. That decision
led to a major embarrassment for Richardson, who in June of last
year, shortly before learning of the problems, gave a speech
hailing the project as on time and within its budget.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell left the laboratory in August of last year when it was
disclosed that he had never completed a Ph.D. from Princeton
University, as he had allowed the laboratory to believe he had. The
overruns and delays became public at about the same time. Campbell,
now a vice president at General Atomics, a government contractor,
was traveling and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever things were going through his mind, he convinced
himself and his senior people that everything was okay,'' said Gary
Boss, the GAO assistant director who oversaw the report.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusions on Campbell's responsibility jibed with findings
released earlier this year by a panel appointed by Richardson. But
in a sharp difference with those findings, the GAO report largely
exonerated Dr. Victor H. Reis, a former assistant secretary of
energy who was the principal architect of the stockpile stewardship
program.
</P>
<P>
   Reis had been insulated from the problems by lower-level Energy
Department officials who ``should have been more aggressive in
acting on their suspicions,'' Boss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
