<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, IN TENNESSEE, SAYS GORE'S POLICIES WOULD DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS &UR; ,  &LR; Tenn. _ Roaring into Vice President Al Gore's home
state on the morning after the Democratic National Convention, Gov.
George W. Bush, accused Gore on Friday of using his convention
speech to sow divisions and foment class warfare among Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, at the start of a campaign trip through the Midwest,
pressed his claim to being a crusader against the influence of
corporations and their privileged chieftains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters have a clear choice,'' Bush said at a lavishly
choreographed rally in Bartlett, a suburb of this city. ``They've
got one candidate who wants four more years of finger-pointing,
politicizing and blaming, a candidate who pits one group of people
against another, a candidate who wants to wage class warfare to get
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a different vision of leadership,'' the Texas
governor added, ``a leaders is somebody who brings people
together.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, speaking in La Crosse, Wisc., Friday morning before he
shoved off on a carefully orchestrated boat trip through the
Midwest, said that some people were striving harder and less
successfully than others, and that he wanted to be their champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole struggle is about the future of this country and
what happens for working families,'' the vice president said,
referring to his bid for the presidency. ``Don't ever lose sight of
the fact that this (ital) is (ital) a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   With their competing statements and viewpoints, Bush and Gore
were delineating what will undoubtedly be some of the sharpest
battle lines between them this fall. There were distinct echoes of
presidential elections past, in which Democrats tried, sometimes
successfully and sometimes not, to tag Republicans as the
protectors of privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and Gore were also vying dramatically for the precious,
fickle attention of voters as the conventions faded into memory and
the candidates headed into the final 11 weeks of a presidential
race that many political analysts say will be extraordinarily
close.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate sought to make a bold statement with his
itinerary Friday. Bush pointedly traveled to Gore's political
doorstep, and the banner behind him on the stage at his rally said,
``Listen to the People Who Know Them Best.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a reference to the fact, mentioned repeatedly throughout
the day by Bush's advisers, that several polls show Bush in a tight
race against Gore in Tennessee, while Gore trails Bush by what is
likely to be an insurmountable double-digit margin in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers pulled out all the stops for his rally here in
an enormous warehouse that was packed with somewhere between 5,000
and 10,000 wildly enthusiastic supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The singer Travis Tritt performed several songs before Bush took
the stage, and Bush was flanked by his running mate, Dick Cheney,
and by Tennessee's two Republican senators, Bill Frist and Fred
Thompson. The end of Bush's remarks, which lasted only about 15
minutes, was punctuated with a dense, dizzy blizzard of confetti.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, for his part, hopped aboard an old-fashioned boat to head
down the Mississippi, indulging in a bit of political theater that
wrapped his journey in a populist aura and evoked the sturdy,
timeless values of the American heartland.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was determined to sustain whatever momentum
he had wrung from his party's four-day jubilee in Los Angeles and
from his political coronation on Thursday night. Bush was equally
determined to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was singling out a cluster of swing states
that could prove decisive in the fall election. Bush was asserting,
as he had with his campaign schedule over the previous four weeks,
that his potent appeal to voters would enable him to compete in,
and possibly win, states where the odds should be against him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments at the rally in Bartlett and aboard his campaign
plane as he flew to Memphis from Austin, Texas, represented his
first public response to the Democrats' convention and his opening
salvo against Gore in the wake of the event. It was aggressive and
relatively unhampered by one of his campaign's central slogans, to
``change the tone'' in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed skepticism, for example, about Gore's vow on
Thursday night to make an overhaul of campaign finance laws the
first of legislation he would tackle if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's got any credibility on the issue,'' Bush
told reporters on his plane, explicitly reminding them of ``the
Buddhist temple event'' that symbolized the ethical questions
raised in the aftermath of Gore's aggressive fund raising for the
Democratic Party in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that the array of resolutions in Gore's
convention speech, including pledges to shore up Social Security
and expand Medicare to include a prescription-drug benefit for
elderly Americans, was really a litany of unaccomplished goals
during the seven and a half years that Gore has been vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we heard a laundry list of new promises, which I
thought was an attempt to cover up old failures,'' Bush told the
audience at his rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as he tried to separate himself from the squandered
opportunities of his own administration, the vice president's
speech reminded us of the fundamental choice in this election: Will
we prolong four more years of Clinton-Gore, or will we give America
a fresh start?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush plans to spend most of the next two weeks on the campaign
trail talking about education, the issue on which he has long
depended most heavily to reach out to independent and swing voters
in the political center.
</P>
<P>
   It is also one of the issues with which he will seek to
inoculate himself from charges by Gore that Bush cares too little
about those Americans struggling to build a better life for
themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
