<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-TV-RATINGS-NYT &LR;      08-18 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-TV-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS' AUDIENCE SLIGHTLY HIGHER THAN GOP'S 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democrats appeared to be a slightly bigger draw on
television in prime time during their convention this week than
were the Republicans during their convention two weeks earlier. But
the audiences for both events were down overall compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And the Democrats' ratings may have been helped along by the
simple fact that their convention received more minutes of network
coverage in prime time than the Republican event did.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night through Thursday night, the coverage of the
Democratic convention provided by both the cable and broadcast news
outlets in prime time was watched in a combined average of 15.4
million homes, according to data compiled by Nielsen Media
Research. That represented 28 percent of the homes watching
television in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The television coverage of the four nights of the Republican
convention two weeks earlier was watched in an approximate average
of 14 million homes, or 26 percent of the homes watching television
in prime time that week, according to Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   According to a tally by the research department of NBC News, the
Republican convention received 756 minutes of coverage on the
broadcast networks during prime time. The Democratic convention
received 902 minutes of coverage in prime time, the network said.
Both political parties saw fewer minutes of network attention in
prime time than they did in 1996, when the Democrats were covered
for 991 minutes and the Republicans were covered for 904.
</P>
<P>
   Before the conventions began this year, there was an overall
perception that the television audience would be less interested
than it was in 1996. That, combined with a general sense that the
conventions were staged to the point of becoming less interesting
and newsworthy than in the past, had led news executives to debate
heavily how much coverage they deserved.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Nielsen figures, the difference in convention
viewership between the two years was not at all stark. The
Democratic convention was watched by about 5 percent fewer people
in 2000 than it was 1996. The Republican convention was watched by
about 2 percent fewer people in 2000 than it was in 1996, according
to the Nielsen data.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Friedman, the executive vice president of ABC News, said he
believed that the conventions probably got about the amount of
coverage, and the level of audience, that they deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the way to look at it is that millions of Americans made
the entirely logical conclusion that there is nothing to be decided
and they have several months to make up their minds,'' he said.
``They didn't feel it was necessary to invest time in watching
well-packaged events when they have other ways of making up their
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's coverage of the 2000 Democratic convention was watched by
four percent more people than was its coverage of the 1996
convention, a clear indication of the strength of its hit game
show, ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' which has raised the
network's overall ratings this year.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the major broadcast and cable outlets covering this
year's Democratic convention, the biggest draw was Al Gore on
Thursday night. The prime-time coverage of his speech accepting the
Democratic nomination for president was watched by about 21.8
million people. According to preliminary statistics, another 3.1
million people watched the prime-time coverage of Gore's speech on
PBS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
