A6059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-AGENDA-NYT &LR;      08-18 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-AGENDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING ASIDE FRIENDLY FACE, DEMOCRATS PLOT ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After four days of showing a national television
audience a generally positive look at itself and its candidates,
the Democratic Party turned Friday to how to attack the Republicans
and Gov. George W. Bush on a variety of issues, with a heavy
emphasis on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   At a raucously enthusiastic meeting of the Democratic National
Committee, the party's general chairman, Edward G. Rendell, said,
``This was a nice, upbeat convention, and it was the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Rendell denounced Republicans for the ``fraud'' of saying
they were ``inclusive'' and ``compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, he said Bush would replace retiring Supreme Court
justices who supported abortion rights with jurists hostile to
abortion and, ``Very soon, Roe vs. Wade will be voted out.'' Then,
he said, ``Dozens of state legislatures will pass laws prohibiting
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   That warning was seconded by Carol Browner, administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency, who got an ovation for telling the
committee, ``As a woman, I don't want anyone telling me what I can
do with my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Dennis Archer of Detroit said a victory by Vice President
Al Gore was necessary to ``preserve a woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other lines of attack suggested, too.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Brazile, Gore's campaign manager, said Bush had nothing to
offer to the ``poor in America without health insurance.'' The Rev.
Jesse Jackson ridiculed Republican efforts to make it appear that
African-Americans were a significant part of their party by using
``workers from concession stands sitting in delegates' seats at the
GOP convention in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell said Democrats had to remind voters that while Gore
wanted a prescription drug entitlement under Medicare and available
to all elderly Americans, Bush had a plan that would only cover a
third of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should carry Pennsylvania and Florida on this issue
alone,'' Rendell said.
</P>
<P>
   Browner also hit the prescription drug issue and then attacked
Bush over the environment. She said Houston had become ``the most
polluted city in the country'' because Bush had chosen not to spend
money on the environment, with Texas ranking 49th in environmental
spending per capital.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, calling for efforts to elect Democrats to the House and
Senate, accused Republicans of blocking confirmation of black
judges and for general opposition to affirmative action. He
recalled what he said was the hostility to civil rights of the
Reagan administration's assistant attorney general for civil
rights, William Bradford Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those memories, he said, ``it scares me when people
like George W. Bush and Dick Cheney have every opportunity to
become president and vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   The messages on how to attack the Republicans were interspersed
with instructions to work hard and unite. Jackson said the time was
past for Democrats to fight each other. He said two congressmen who
held a press conference to complain they had not been seen on
television when their state cast its votes on a roll call were
forgetting it was ``Super Bowl time,'' when only Republicans should
be blocked and tackled. He also said Republicans and reporters were
seeking to drive a wedge between Jews and blacks in the party.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that a few blacks may have criticized Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, the vice presidential nominee, and that they had to be
answered, but that they amounted to ``a tree leaf, not a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, Jackson said, had not kept Jews off national tickets or
out of country clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument about the black-Jewish thing is a diversion,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And every speaker called for all-out efforts. Joe Andrew, the
party's national chairman, urged the committee members to always
``lick an extra envelope, make an extra phone call, pick an extra
pocket.'' Browner urged efforts to get women to vote.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rev. William Smart, a former committee staff member who
now serves as an African Methodist Episcopal minister, offered an
invocation that concluded, ``Lord God, let the Democrats be
elected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
