<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-BIAS0819-COX     08-18 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BIAS0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    200 lost individual suit rights, Coke says
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nearly 10 percent of the 2,100 current and former
employees covered by the tentative settlement in the Coca-Cola
racial discrimination case may not be able to file individual
lawsuits if they don't like the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Both Coca-Cola and attorneys for the class of 2,100 said Friday
that 200 former employees essentially forfeited their right to sue
the company in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But an attorney representing four of the eight plaintiffs in the
case said Coke's legal opinion, as well as the opinion of the
attorneys for the class, ``could be suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   And Larry Jones, one of the 200 former employees, said he is
holding a meeting next Thursday with class members to discuss this
``major issue,'' as well as others surrounding the agreement in
principle settling the case.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the settlement in principle, reached two months ago,
are not expected to be announced until late October or early
November, after a final agreement has been reached. The suit
alleges that the company has discriminated against
African-Americans in pay, promotions and performance evaluations.
The company has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Once the agreement is consummated, about 90 percent of the class
will have one of three options:
</P>
<P>
   _ They can accept the settlement;
</P>
<P>
   _ They can ``opt out'' of it and file individual suits for
monetary damages;
</P>
<P>
   _ Or they can challenge the settlement as being unfair.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly 10 percent of the class may not have the right to opt
out, and attorneys say here's why.
</P>
<P>
   The 200 former workers were among the 5,200 employees whose jobs
were eliminated earlier this year when Coke went through a major
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, those 200 had to choose between participating in the
lawsuit or receiving enhanced severance benefits when they left the
company. But Jones and others protested to the company, saying that
was unfair. Also, the legal team representing the class was trying
to overturn the company's policy in court, although the company
prevailed at the lower court level.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola eventually relented and made an exception for this
specific case. The company allowed the 200 workers to get what
amounts to double the normal severance benefits and still
participate in the suit. To accomplish that, the company revised
its waiver form, which the laid-off workers then signed.
</P>
<P>
   The waiver form allows these 200 former employees to receive the
same monetary benefits the other 1,900 class members will.
</P>
<P>
   But both Coke and attorneys for the class said Friday the waiver
essentially prevents the 200 former workers from filing a new
individual suit if they don't like the monetary terms of the
class-action settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We modified the waiver in March to specifically address the
confusion that occurred as a result of the unique circumstances
surrounding the concurrent events of the company's realignment and
the discrimination lawsuit,'' said Coca-Cola spokesman Ben Deutsch.
``As a result, these individuals have already been given the double
benefit of receiving an enhanced severance payment, as well as
participating in the monetary settlement of the lawsuit. They
agreed to the modified waiver, knowingly and with a clear
understanding that they could not sue the company through a
separate lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Class attorney Cyrus Mehri said these individuals face a
``monumental'' uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who took the enhanced severance package last spring is
going to have a very difficult time claiming they still can bring
an individual action,'' Mehri said. ``As we pointed out at the
time, under the terms of the waiver, an individual who accepted
enhanced benefits may be barred entirely from bringing an
individual discrimination claim. On the other hand, as a result of
the modification of the waiver achieved in early March, we
preserved the right of those individuals to reap the monetary
benefits from this class action.''
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Tricia C. K. Hoffler had a different view. She is a
partner in the Florida law firm of Willie Gary, who represents four
plaintiffs in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither Cyrus Mehri or any of the other attorneys for the
class, nor Coca-Cola, should be advising any potential class
members as to whether or not they can opt in or opt out of the
class, according to the judge's order in this case,'' Hoffler said.
``Therefore, they are all in strict violation of the court's orders
and any opinion that they would give could be suspect, as they do
not have authority to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffler's firm does not represent the class, although she said
it has been contacted by numerous individuals ``who hope that the
Gary firm will represent them in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
