<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-ACURA-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAST COUPE THAT GIVES RIVALS A RUN FOR THE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Release for Sunday, August 20) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sporty coupes come and go, but BMW's 3-Series reigns supreme,
deftly deflecting all challengers to its throne. Now Acura has
stepped up, drawn a bull's-eye on the Bimmer and taken aim.
</P>
<P>
   Acura's 3.2 CL, once a slightly fancier, more eccentrically
styled version of the Honda Accord coupe, has been redone for 2001
with more style, size and substance. More important, it now has
enough of a sporty edge, especially the Type S version, to make a
direct challenge to two-door models in BMW's 3-Series.
</P>
<P>
   My Type S test car had a 3.2-liter V-6 specially tuned to
deliver 260 horsepower _ 67 more than the 2000-model BMW 328Ci and
35 more than its 2001-model replacement, the 330Ci. Peak torque of
the front-drive Acura is 232 foot-pounds, compared with 214
foot-pounds for the 2001 BMW. (The regular 3.2 CL, with a milder
version of the same engine, has 225 horsepower.)
</P>
<P>
   The second-generation CL is longer, wider, taller and heavier
than the 328Ci. Compared with the BMW, it has 5 more cubic feet in
the cabin, plus 4 more cubic feet in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   At the racetrack, the two cars run about even, at just under 7
seconds in 0-to-60 acceleration tests by enthusiast magazine's. But
the 328Ci _ with rear-wheel drive and a perfect front-to-rear
balance of weight _ performed better in handling tests.
</P>
<P>
   But in the battle of the window stickers, Acura has the edge.
The '02 330Ci starts at $35,560, including the delivery charge and
standard features like antilock brakes, traction and stability
control, four air bags and an inflatable head-protection pillow.
But that is just the beginning. A premium package includes leather
upholstery, power sunroof and other items, for $2,900. Add $1,275
for an automatic transmission; $475 for metallic paint, $500 for
heated front seats; $500 for Xenon headlamps; and $675 for an
upgraded Harman-Kardon stereo. Cars at dealerships often wear
prices of $40,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with the simplified pricing of the 3.2 CL: $28,455
for the regular model and $32,785 for the Type S. There is only one
option, a $2,000 navigation system. Everything else is standard:
the traction and stability systems, a five-speed automatic that can
be manually shifted; heated power seats with leather trim; xenon
headlamps; power sunroof; high-performance tires, even an an air
bag system on the passenger side that detects the size and position
of the occupant.
</P>
<P>
   Acura's navigation system, already one of the best, now comes
with a six-inch color touch-screen and a DVD data base that maps
the entire country on one disk, including more than 3.7 million
suggestions for restaurants, service stations and points of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell only part of the story, of course. No matter
how quickly the Acura accelerates or how sporty it feels, purists
will object to its front-drive design and lack of a stick shift.
</P>
<P>
   While the CL does not outshine the BMW on a racetrack, it
handles curves on real roads swiftly and confidently. It moves
quickly but smoothly away from stoplights and excels at high-speed
cruising. Gear changes are nearly imperceptible. The steering is
quick _ so quick that it reminded me of the lightning-fast reflexes
of Honda's S2000 sports car.
</P>
<P>
   While the CL's rigid chassis keeps interior noise low, the growl
of the engine can still be heard. With its firm suspension
settings, the Type S may ride too harshly for Americans accustomed
to luxury cars; my companion wanted to feel more isolated from the
road. But I found the ride comfortable, and I liked the messages I
got through the wheel from the pavement. The CL strikes a nice
balance between luxury ride and high-performance handling.
</P>
<P>
   The CL's styling evolved from a sharply creased design study,
though the look has been toned down for the production car. The
test model, in a shade of orange that Acura calls Sundance gold,
certainly stood out.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Type S was dressed in tasteful black and gray with
elegant gathered leather upholstery on the seats and doors. The
interior had its quirks, too; instead of wood, the test car had
black and gray plastic trim that looked like slate. I'm still not
sure if I liked it.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of nice touches. The front seats automatically
move forward for easy entry to the rear, which is roomier than most
coupes'. The controls are logically laid out, as they always are in
cars from the Honda family. The gauges have black letters on
off-white faces that have a metallic sheen.
</P>
<P>
   I found the seats to be extremely comfortable, by far the best
ever from Honda. Thick side bolsters hold you in place on hard
turns.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio-built 3.2 CL is not a Bimmer, and it won't win over
BMW's hard-core loyalists. But it is a far better car, in every
respect, than the first-generation CL. And judged on its own
merits, it is an impressive package at a fair price, a Japanese
David with a powerful slingshot and a pretty good bead on Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BERNSTEIN-ALLIANCE-AR     08-18 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNSTEIN-ALLIANCE-ART-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET'S FUNDAMENTALISTS FACE A NEW WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, August 20) 
 By ALEX BERENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faye Landes had some bad news for investors in Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, Landes, a research analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP;
Co., told shareholders in Amazon, the online retailer, that a
Bernstein-run focus group had found that most Amazon customers
believed that the company sold only books and music. The findings
called into question Amazon's plans to sell big-profit items like
consumer electronics, Landes argued.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she issued Bernstein's first report on Amazon,
saying it would ``underperform'' the market; its stock fell 6
percent. (Amazon disputes Landes' conclusions, saying that sales in
its new product lines will reach $500 million this year.)
</P>
<P>
   But for experienced investors, the way Landes reached her
judgment about Amazon was at least as interesting as the call
itself.
</P>
<P>
   A focus group? Convened by Bernstein? An analyst conducting
original research on a company she covers?
</P>
<P>
   Glory be, glory be.
</P>
<P>
   It is a truth universally acknowledged on Wall Street that
original research is on life support. Serious research can be bad
for business, as well as expensive. The biggest profit center for
investment banks is the hefty fees they charge for underwriting
stock offerings and giving financial advice, and analysts put those
profits at risk if they publish negative conclusions about the
companies that pay the fees.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many analysts choose to work hand-in-glove with the
companies they cover, designing projections that closely track
internal corporate forecasts. At the same time, they rely on
executives for tidbits of information about sales and new products,
a practice that the Securities and Exchange Commission tried to
limit earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Bernstein. Founded in 1967, the firm, with 1,400
employees, is not a true investment bank. It does not advise on
mergers or serve as a lead underwriter on offerings. Instead,
Bernstein, based in Midtown Manhattan, focuses on managing money _
and offering research to institutional investors, the fund managers
who pay for the reports by sending stock trades and commissions to
Bernstein's trading desk.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bernstein and its fans say, the company does not
face the potential conflicts of interest confronted by analysts at
investment banks like Merrill Lynch and PaineWebber. Its analysts
can spend their time on research, not pitching potential investment
banking clients. And they can report what they find to portfolio
managers without fear of angering those potential banking clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is do research all day long, and that's all
they do here,'' said Landes, who has previously worked for Salomon
Smith Barney and Thomas Weisel Partners. ``Things change when
you're answering to more than one master. Here we only do one
thing. That's the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Berghoef, co-manager of the $1.7 billion Oakmark Select
mutual fund, said that Bernstein's research is usually ``much more
detailed than the typical sell-side research'' and that ``their
work has somewhat more credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Landes' bold call left one question unanswered: What did
Bernstein think of Amazon earlier this year, as the stock lost more
than half its value? Or last year, as Amazon became one of the most
heavily traded and closely watched stocks in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   What did Bernstein think about Amazon? Absolutely nothing,
because Bernstein did not cover the company, or any other Internet
retailer, until Landes started working for the firm in May. And
Internet retailing is not the only market sector where Bernstein
has been absent. With biotechnology companies routinely reporting
scientific breakthroughs, Bernstein has no biotechnology analyst.
Perhaps most surprising, a combination of turnover and slow hiring
has left Bernstein with only three analysts publishing reports on
the high-technology sector, which accounts for one-third of the
market value of all stocks in the United States. Other firms have
dozens of analysts following high technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bernstein is at a crossroads as it prepares for life under
Alliance Capital Management, a fund manager based in New York that
agreed in June to buy it for $3.5 billion. Institutional investors
are crying out for good fundamental research on the technology
stocks that drive American stock markets. Bernstein must either
find a way to give it to them _ or watch its prestige and
importance, which has waned as the technology sector has grown,
continue to dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein's research has won acclaim over the years, both for
its willingness to buck convention on the outlook for individual
stocks and for its broad, deep analysis of industry trends.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known stock picks include Gary Black's 1993 prediction
that cigarette pricing would come under pressure. It came months
before Philip Morris slashed prices on Marlboro, its flagship
brand, in a move that caught nearly everyone else by surprise and
caused the company's stock to fall by 22 percent in a day. More
recently, Bernstein analysts have offered contrarian and correct
views on energy stocks and on Qualcomm, which makes software that
runs cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, Bernstein research focuses on important trends
rather than on the day-to-day minutiae of new product announcements
or weekly sales figures. In addition to using secondhand data from
companies, the firm regularly conducts its own focus groups and
surveys to gain exclusive insights on where industries are heading.
Information seekers find the firm's distinctive black-covered
reports pure joy, filled with enough charts to turn anyone who
bothers to read them into experts.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Evans, Bernstein's drug company analyst, surveyed more
than 100 physicians for a March report that predicted that a
crucial new drug from Bristol Myers-Squibb would initially be
prescribed less than expected. In May, Bernstein released its
annual consumer personal computer survey, a 76-page report complete
with 104 charts and graphs, including data on ``PC Extended Service
Plan Attachment Rates by Retailer'' and ``Frequency of Cartridge
Replacement'' for printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to do pure Wall Street research, Sanford Bernstein
is the only place on Wall Street to work,'' said Steve Galbraith, a
Bernstein veteran who left in June to join Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter as a strategist. ``It's sort of `Revenge of the Nerds' _
incredibly bright people who won through analytical excellence.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
