<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEBVAN0820-COX     08-18 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online grocers gaining customers, but aren't yet packing a
profit
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lynda Reis, who spends more than $180 a week on
groceries for her family, is convinced she saves money using
Webvan.com.
</P>
<P>
   That's because she avoids impulse purchases at the local grocery
store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend less money per week,'' Reis said while inspecting an
order delivered to her home by the online grocer. ``I would have
bought what I didn't need if I went to the store.''
</P>
<P>
   The economics of buying groceries online and having them
delivered to the home may make sense for Reis. The question is
whether they will work for Webvan. While the company has generated
a lot of positive buzz and impressed many customers, it is a long
way from making money.
</P>
<P>
   Like most dot-coms, Webvan has posted a string of losses in the
early going. It is burning through cash and its stock has been
hammered. Shares have fallen 88 percent since their November 1999
high of $34, closing Friday at $4.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Foster City, Calif.-based company is convinced its
model for profitability will work, and it notes that revenue and
customer volume is building fast.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan's profitability model assumes that 120,000 active
customers will order two times a month, with orders averaging $103,
said Bob Okunski, director of investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   The company won't say how close it is to achieving that, but
reported that its average order was $91 for the quarter ended June
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that (average order size) can go higher,'' said
analyst Shawn Milne, with E Offering, an online investment bank in
San Francisco. ``But they're getting closer to where they need to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Those figures include metro Atlanta, San Francisco and
Sacramento, the markets where Webvan operated in June. The Atlanta
service started May 1, and this month the company launched in
Chicago. Other markets will be added this year, including Baltimore
and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Each Webvan division is expected to reach profitability by the
end of its fifth quarter of operation, said Mark San Fratello, a
company spokesman in Suwanee, Ga., where the Atlanta operation is
based.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan's first operating market _ San Francisco _ is in its
fifth quarter. But the company doesn't break out results by
division.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan hopes to turn a profit in Atlanta in November, 2001. So
far, the area's performance is ``ahead'' of where San Francisco had
been during its first three months of operation, San Fratello said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orders per day are more than 1,000,'' he said, without
releasing exact figures.
</P>
<P>
   Milne attributes Webvan's progress in metro Atlanta to the
company ``stepping down the learning curve.'' The company learned
from mistakes made in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were certainly plenty of crushed tomatoes, and
too-little-too-late stories over the first few months of operation
last summer (in San Francisco), but the company claims to have
ironed them out,'' said Evie Black Dykema, an analyst with
Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   One way Milne thinks Webvan can boost its average order size is
by adding more non-grocery products and services. It already stocks
music CDs and recently started offering Harry Potter books.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan's Atlanta division, which employs about 700 people, is
built around a $35 million distribution center in Suwanee. It can
handle 8,000 orders per day, seven days a week at full capacity.
There are eight smaller delivery substations, most in the northern
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The company promises delivery within a half-hour window. To
build volume, it isn't charging for delivery but plans to add a
delivery fee of $4.95 for orders less than $50 starting Sept. 15.
Webvan's grocery prices are about the same as those at big chains.
</P>
<P>
   In the warehouse _ the size of about seven Krogers, or 350,000
square feet _ orders via Webvan.com come in and are picked and
packed into brightly colored totes. Totes make their way around 4
miles of conveyor belts and are packed along the way. Blue totes
hold frozen items, green holds chilled, and yellow holds dry goods.
When orders are completed, the totes are trucked to substations.
</P>
<P>
   The substations store the goods for delivery during two work
shifts: 7 a.m. to 2 p.m. and 3 p.m. to 10 p.m. Once loaded, Webvan
trucks make about two deliveries per hour.
</P>
<P>
   While the distribution chain is complex, the company argues it
is far leaner than that of a traditional grocery store. For
instance, one Webvan distribution center can handle product volumes
equivalent to about 18 supermarkets, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do that with almost one-third the labor,'' said
Webvan's Okunski. ``That's where the efficiencies come in.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, about 8.6 percent of metro Atlanta's population has gone
to the Webvan.com site, according to the latest figures by Media
Metrix, a New York-based research firm that tracks Web site
traffic. The company did not track figures for Webvan.com in San
Francisco or Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Performance is likely better in metro Atlanta because Webvan
agreed to buy HomeGrocer.com for $1.2 billion in stock. Kirkland,
Wash.-based HomeGrocer.com was days from launching in Atlanta when
Webvan gobbled up its would-be competitor. That transaction is
scheduled to close in September.
</P>
<P>
   HomeGrocer.com's sales were $22 million last year, compared with
Webvan's $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan's latest quarterly results beat analysts' expectations,
although the company reported a widened loss of $82 million, for
the three months ended June 30, compared with $23.4 million in the
same period a year earlier. Revenues were $28.3 million, compared
with $383,000 in 1999, not long after Webvan began operations.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Webvan is burning through cash at about $30
million a month as it opens new markets. The company has about $400
million in cash left from its estimated $805 million raised during
its initial public offering last November.
</P>
<P>
   George Shaheen, chief executive officer of Webvan, has told Wall
Street the online grocer has enough money to last through next
June, and plans to raise more money.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe the future for online grocers could lie in
partnerships with established supermarket chains. The big chains
could supply needed capital for the home delivery services, which
in turn would give them access to a burgeoning online grocery
market. Internet research firm Jupiter Communications estimates
online grocery sales will balloon from $200 million last year to
$7.5 billion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dutch grocer Royal Ahold NV, which operates the Bi-Lo
chain among others, has taken a $73 million controlling stake in
Skokie, Ill.-based Peapod Inc., which doesn't serve Atlanta.
Safeway Inc. agreed to invest $30 million for half of closely held
GroceryWorks.com, a Texas-based online grocery delivery service.
</P>
<P>
   And Kroger, Winn-Dixie, and Bi-Lo are linked with Priceline.com
for name-your-price groceries that shoppers pay for online but pick
out themselves at selected locations.
</P>
<P>
   Kroger used to be linked in several markets with Peapod, but
that relationship ended with the Ahold investment. Locally, Kroger
worked with OnCart for less than a year until the California-based
company folded in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a model making money,'' said Susie Brower, a
spokeswoman in the Kroger's Atlanta division. ``Being publicly
held, our shareholders want us to be making money. Kroger's
strategy is to stay abreast of developments and see what others are
doing before getting involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
