<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BERNSTEIN-ALLIANCE-AR     08-18 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNSTEIN-ALLIANCE-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: analytical excellence.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernstein has always prided itself on being different from
larger Wall Street companies. ``Get a copy of our reports and then
look at copies of others, and then see where you've learned
something,'' said Bernstein's president, Roger Hertog.
</P>
<P>
   The firm looks for ``people for whom the pursuit of truth is
important,'' said Marc Mayer, the senior vice president who
oversees Bernstein's research department, at an interview at
Bernstein's headquarters last week.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We want a certain type of personal integrity,
iconoclastic nature, comfort with controversy. Sometimes, he said,
the firm takes itself too seriously. ``At the end of day,'' he
said, ``we're trying to forecast earnings for companies,'' not cure
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sallie Krawcheck, Bernstein's research director, said, ``The
goal is to think deeply, to be creative, to be thought-provoking.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, those goals mean that Bernstein rarely hires from
other Wall Street firms, preferring to find its analysts in the
industries they will be covering. It is usually slow to hire,
requiring many rounds of interviews. After hiring, it gives new
analysts as long as a year to deepen their knowledge about the
industries before they publish ratings on specific companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bernstein's research department is relatively small
and tightknit. The firm has about 30 analysts covering both
domestic and international stocks, compared with hundreds of
analysts at firms like Goldman, Sachs. That reduces the risk of
turf battles, Krawcheck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to hire the very best and give them a lot of room,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaine Mehring, a former Bernstein analyst who now covers the
food industry for Salomon Smith Barney, half-jokingly calls
Bernstein a cult. ``It was a great place to learn to be an analyst,
because you're very protected from other constituencies,'' Mehring
said. ``But it was very enclosed, cloistered in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the firm's strengths, its franchise is under strain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Bernstein's 19 analysts occupied 24 of 529 places in
Institutional Investor magazine's All-America Research Team survey,
an important gauge of sentiment among the money managers who are
the audience for the company's research. While larger investment
banks had more ranked analysts than Bernstein, the firm's ratio of
rankings to analysts _ better than one to one _ was the best on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1999, Bernstein's 18 analysts won only 12 of 429 places
in the magazine's survey, half as many as five years earlier. Four
other firms had a higher percentage.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bernstein has suffered a notable loss of
talent, with several of the firm's best-known analysts leaving for
potentially bigger paydays at other financial firms. Weston Hicks,
a first-teamer for six consecutive years, headed to J.P. Morgan. So
did third-teamer Tod Jacobs, Bernstein's only ranked analyst in
telecommunications or technology. Other recent departure include an
auto analyst, Gary Lapidus; a bank analyst, Moshe Orenbuch, and
Galbraith, who covered consumer companies.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of that much talent would crimp even the largest
research departments on Wall Street. For Bernstein, the departures
have punched noticeable holes in its coverage. Many of the analysts
who remain at the firm focus on staid industries like metals or
savings institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Schutte, who parlayed a stint at Bernstein into a career as
a computer industry analyst at PaineWebber and Goldman, Sachs
before leaving Goldman earlier this year to become a money manager,
said he deeply respects the research that Bernstein produces. But
he does not read it, because it does not focus on the industries he
cares about. ``If they had some more tech analysts, I would
definitely read their stuff,'' Schutte said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein is hardly down for the count. The report by Landes
last week won widespread attention. But at best, Bernstein has
missed an opportunity to meet a growing demand for technology
research. At worst, the firm faces a slow death of its unique
culture, as its best remaining analysts leave for other Wall Street
firms more quickly than Bernstein can train replacements.
</P>
<P>
   To fill holes in its coverage of technology, communications and
health care, Bernstein recently hired four analysts _ one each for
software, computer services, medical-device makers and
international drug companies. It is actively seeking a
biotechnology analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``More tech and more telecom is on the way,'' Krawcheck said.
</P>
<P>
   But hiring analysts will not solve Bernstein's problem, unless
the firm can keep its employees _ old and new _ from jumping to
larger investment banks. Until a couple of years ago, that was not
a problem. Bernstein paid competitively, and its culture appealed
to many analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have half the responsibilities of my colleagues, but I get
paid the same amount,'' said Lisa Shallet, a Bernstein analyst who
covers capital goods companies like Caterpillar. ``I'm never here
at midnight working on the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But in technology and telecommunications, where the fees for
investment banking and underwriting are flooding firms like
Goldman, Sachs, Bernstein is having an increasingly difficult time
paying competitively.
</P>
<P>
   One person who recently left Bernstein for another firm said he
doubled his pay at the new job. In addition, Bernstein has been
stingy in distributing equity to employees. Before the sale to
Alliance Capital, employees said, most of the company was owned by
the chief executive, Lewis Sanders; Hertog; and the estate of the
founder, Zalman Chaim Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly was not and is not an egalitarian partnership a
la Goldman Sachs,'' Shallet said.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance deal might alleviate those complaints. Although
Alliance is controlled by AXA, a diversified French financial
services company, Alliance shares are publicly traded. So the new
Alliance Bernstein would be able to offer Bernstein employees stock
options comparable to those of other publicly traded companies _ if
it chose to do so. An AXA spokesman declined to comment on his
company's plans for Bernstein, noting that the takeover would not
be completed until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bernstein can pay its analysts competitively, it may
face a more subtle problem in analyzing biotechnology and other
fast-changing sectors. In those industries, investment bankers
often see companies before analysts do, because the young companies
come to them to raise money. That gives analysts at full-service
investment banks a source of information that Bernstein researchers
do not have, said Jacobs, the former Bernstein telecommunications
analyst who is now J.P. Morgan's telecommunications strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein analysts do not cover small new companies, which are
important in fast-growing industries. ``In an area like telecom,
you miss too much of what's going on if you just cover large-cap
companies,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   Vadim Zlotnikov, Bernstein's top technology analyst, said his
firm keeps smaller technology companies on its radar screen. But he
added that Bernstein's priority is covering large firms, both
because many small companies do not survive and because big
institutional investors are much more interested in coverage of
large companies where they can make big bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get paid to follow the smallest of the small guys,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein must also adapt to the fact that Wall Street's
attention span is shorter than ever. Each day, newspapers report
mutual fund prices, giving investors an instant score card on their
funds' performance. And a year or two of bad performance can
destroy even hedge-fund managers with decades of success, like
Julian H. Robertson Jr. of Tiger Management. The resulting
short-term attitude of managers plays to the strengths of analysts
who follow every tick of a company's sales, rather than to
Bernstein's traditional focus on the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent defections and Bernstein's slippage in
Institutional Investor, Krawcheck says the firm's future is
brighter than ever. Bernstein's new analysts will bring the firm's
intellectual rigor to technology, where analysis independent of
investment banking relationships is at a premium, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A new SEC rule that requires companies to disclose sensitive
information more freely would also help Bernstein, by preventing
companies from offering extra information to favored analysts,
Krawcheck said. In that environment, she added, Bernstein's
proprietary studies and research would stand out even more.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, Bernstein plans to increase its use of focus
groups, surveys and other proprietary research, and the firm is
well aware that it must offer investors insights into both
long-term trends and short-term trading opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of doing the stuff that we do has just increased,''
Krawcheck said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
