<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-900(2TAKES)-     08-18 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TAKES HIS MESSAGE FROM THE CONVENTION FLOOR TO THE
MISSISSIPPI 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Tenn., Iowa, Ill., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1, NYT5, NYT7 and NYT11 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA CROSSE, Wis. _ Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Joe Lieberman
took to the Mississippi Friday, weaving the river's epic symbolism
into a populist challenge against the political influence of oil
corporations, health maintenance organizations and drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   Before boarding the Mark Twain riverboat for a four-day,
390-mile journey down the Mississippi, Gore stood at the riverbank
here and promised, as he had done Thursday night in accepting the
Democratic presidential nomination in Los Angeles, to make campaign
finance reform his first legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reform measure is important because now the wealthy and
powerful special interests have too much of an ability to stop good
things,'' he told a crowd of roughly 5,000 people. Why, he asked,
hasn't Congress increased the minimum wage, or passed legislation
to provide free prescription drugs to the elderly? Why, he asked,
are ``bean counters'' at health insurance companies allowed to
``play God'' and overrule the judgments of doctors? In each case,
he argued, action was blocked by corporate influence bought with
huge campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just morally wrong,'' he said, speaking of elderly
people who cut back on groceries to pay for drugs ``when the drug
companies have the highest profits of any industry.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate that this is a ticket of mainstream values _ and
perhaps to erase images of this week's Hollywood hobnobbing _ the
campaign is traveling down the Mississippi on a quaint 120-foot
paddle boat draped with red, white and blue bunting. At Friday's
kickoff event in La Crosse, a Mark Twain look-alike actor took the
stage to impart some homespun Twainisms. The La Crosse Coulee
Chordsmen sang barbershop harmonies, and a high school marching
band, the Onalaska Hilltoppers, played ``God Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman, along with their wives and several family
members, boarded the Mark Twain to a blast from the boat's air horn
and a final spray of confetti. As the riverboat pushed off, Gore
and Lieberman stood at the stern, positioned just under an American
flag for the photographers, and waved to the crowds on the banks.
``We love you!'' Lieberman yelled, and many in the crowd hollered
their encouragement right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give 'em hell, Al!'' one man called out, and all along the
roads that connect the small river towns on this part of the
Mississippi, hundreds of people stopped their cars to wave and gawk
and snap pictures. At one point Friday afternoon, as Gore and
Lieberman led a somewhat stilted group discussion about Medicare on
the riverboat's top deck, faint voices could be heard calling out
from the distant riverbank. ``Hi!'' Lieberman called back. ``Are
there real people out there?''
</P>
<P>
   And Gore, mindful of the beating sun, said that he and Lieberman
had been admonished by their wives to wear sunscreen. ``If any of
you did not put sunscreen on, we have some available,'' he offered,
adding that Sen. John McCain, undergoing treatment for malignant
melanoma, was in his prayers.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Gore returned to his aggressive criticism of the drug
industry and health insurers, accusing them of reaping profits and
hurting ``working families'' by erecting ``a mighty wall of
resistance'' to prescription drug benefits and a patients' bill of
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was joined in La Crosse by Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis.,
who as a sponsor of the McCain-Feingold campaign finance reform
bill is one of the Senate's loudest advocates for eliminating
unlimited, unregulated donations from corporations and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the populist fire, neither Gore nor Lieberman
mentioned the millions of dollars the Democratic Party raised in
Los Angeles this week, much of that from major corporations. Nor
did Gore mention his own prodigious fund-raising in the 1996
campaign, when he made dozens of telephone calls to corporate
executives to solicit five-figure donations.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally Friday in Memphis, Tenn., the Republican nominee,
George W. Bush, charged that Gore is ``a little short on
credibility'' when it comes to campaign finance reform, and he
accused Gore of conducting ``class warfare'' for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore largely avoided direct criticism of Bush on Friday. He
called Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney, ``honorable men,''
but then went on to suggest that their campaign was more about show
than substance. ``I hope in the next 2 1/2 months we can shift the
focus away from sound bites and images,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Lieberman showed the effects of an exhausting week
in Los Angeles. When the riverboat came upon a high school marching
band waiting on the banks, Gore called over the public address
system for them to play ``On Wisconsin,'' not realizing he was
addressing Lansing, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates were having trouble with their voices, which
were noticeably hoarse from speechmaking and lack of sleep. Gore
sucked on lozenges, and Lieberman planned to get some extra rest
after disembarking from the riverboat Friday evening to observe the
Sabbath. He is expected to rejoin Gore on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore joked that he had taken extra rations of Diet Coke, and he
was clearly determined to build from the momentum generated this
week in Los Angeles. The candidates and their families flew out of
Los Angeles long after midnight and landed here shortly after
sunrise. They had time only to shower and change clothes before
setting out for the river.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gore is a fan of using metaphors to communicate big ideas, and
so naturally he and his aides missed no opportunity Friday to turn
his river excursion into a traveling parable of broad campaign
themes.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman evoked the river as an age-old symbol of journey. ``It
has been a great thrill to be here on the banks of the Mississippi
as we begin a journey across America, down this great American
river which has inspired the American imagination and American
dreams,'' Lieberman said. ``And that's what this ticket is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, of course, old-fashioned political calculation behind
the trip. The itinerary began in Wisconsin, a state long a hotbed
of populist politics, and will take Gore and Lieberman through
several important battleground states. Riverbank rallies are
planned in Dubuque, Iowa, and Moline, Ill., as well as Hannibal,
Mo., the birthplace of Mark Twain. Lieberman will not be at the
Dubuque rally.
</P>
<P>
   `We're going to touch a lot of important communities in key
states that often end up deciding presidential elections, and we're
going to have a good time in the process,'' Gore said. And as if to
prove the point, he and his wife, Tipper, took turns Friday
steering the riverboat.
</P>
<P>
   Told by reporters Friday that some postconvention polls now
showed him holding a slight edge over Bush, Gore played it cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put much stock in the polls, although they seem to be
gaining in relevancy,'' he said, tongue in cheek. He nonetheless
pronounced himself pleased with his speech Thursday night _ ``I had
a good time'' _ and Lieberman offered the opinion that Gore had
delivered the finest convention speech he had ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's daughter Karenna Gore Schiff spoke proudly of the long,
lingering kiss her father planted on her mother moments before his
address.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like that,'' Schiff told reporters on the riverboat.
``There it is. It's out there. Some people my think it's a bit
racy, but I'm used to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
