A6078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-SECT-470&AMP;ADD-NY     08-18 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SECT-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DELAYS ASYLUM HEARING FOR CHINESE SECT LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Immigration officials have delayed until next month
a decision on whether to grant asylum to the leader of a Chinese
spiritual movement after Chinese officials appealed for his return
and submitted detailed charges that he raped followers, people
involved in the case say.
</P>
<P>
   The movement's leader, Zhang Hongbao, has been held in detention
in Guam since January after arriving in the U.S. territory carrying
a false passport, the people said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Beijing outlawed Zhong Gong, the quasi-religious
group that Zhang founded in 1987, along with several other groups
that practice the Chinese meditation and exercise regimen known as
qigong.
</P>
<P>
   While human rights groups say that Zhang has a strong claim to
asylum, U.S. officials now have the delicate task of assessing the
credibility of the Chinese charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese authorities recently provided U.S. officials with a
list of alleged crimes, specifying dates and places and including
testimony from followers who say that Zhang sexually assaulted
them, people who were told of the charges said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States recently has tried to elevate cooperation with
the Chinese police to fight international drug trafficking, making
it difficult to dismiss Beijing's allegations without investigating
them. Zhang's group has attracted little international attention
and does not fit common definitions of a political or religious
movement.
</P>
<P>
   China in the past has brought charges of rape against people
whom it considers seditious, and U.S. officials and human rights
groups say the charges have in some cases proved unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials requested that an asylum hearing that had
been scheduled for Friday be postponed until U.S. officials weigh
the validity of the rape charges. A new hearing is set for early
September.
</P>
<P>
   The delay came shortly after Yan Qingxin, who says she is the
No. 2 leader of Zhong Gong, was granted asylum. Yan, who is now in
Washington seeking to generate support for Zhang, said she and
Zhang arrived in Guam early this year to escape a Chinese dragnet
and were thrown into detention with suspected smugglers. They
waited six months to have their case heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to America because we thought that this country
protects human rights,'' Yan said in an interview. ``But we are
deeply disappointed to find that American courts do not treat such
cases with urgency. I also fear that American officials are subject
to pressure from the Chinese government.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and State Department officials said they do not
comment on individual asylum cases. People involved in the case
said the State Department was preparing an advisory opinion
criticizing Beijing's suppression of Zhong Gong as politically
motivated and noting the risk to Zhang if he returns to China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   China began a crackdown on spiritual groups a year ago after
followers of Falun Gong, another qigong group, organized a
demonstration outside the Chinese leadership compound in Beijing.
The authorities then banned Falun Gong and Zhong Gong, which are
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Falun Gong, which operates through autonomous cells with
no clear hierarchy, Zhong Gong established an extensive
organization with schools, healing centers, factories and printing
houses.
</P>
<P>
   People who have studied the movement say it raised millions of
dollars from school fees and the sale of medical goods, books and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang tailored his teachings to the needs of China's poorest
people. He said those who practiced Zhong Gong could fight cancer
and heart disease more effectively than they could by taking drugs
or undergoing surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Zhong Gong also says its leading practitioners have paranormal
powers, including a ``thousand-mile eye'' that works like an X-ray
and a telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang first went into hiding in 1994 after criticism of his
group grew. Yan said Zhang decided to seek asylum in the United
States late last year after the Chinese authorities shut down Zhong
Gong's schools and healing centers and detained staff members. She
called the charges against Zhang ``sheer fabrication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
