<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     08-18 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANTIDOTE FOR KITTY'S BAD ENERGY
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Are you doing enough for your cat?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chances are you are not. At least according to your cat. To say
that cats are a little demanding is like saying Charlton Heston is
a little bit pro-gun.
</P>
<P>
   If your cat is acting aloof, indifferent or standoffish, it
could be because you have not maximized its energy streams. (More
likely it is acting that way because it is a cat, but for the sake
of argument, let's go with the energy streams.)
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there is a book to help you. Actually, three books.
(Some of you may wonder why it takes only one book to lay out the
framework of Judeo-Christian thought and three books to explain why
a cat is most content sitting on your head. I cannot answer this,
other than to suggest that there were not as many publishing
companies in Moses' day as there are now.)
</P>
<P>
   They are: ``Feng Shui for You and Your Cat'' by Alison Daniels;
``Feng Shui for Cats: By Cats, for Cats'' by Roni Jay and, simply,
``Feng Shui for Cats'' by Chris Riddell.
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui is defined as a way of manipulating your environment
in order to enhance the health, happiness and wealth of people who
write feng shui books. A cat is defined as something that doesn't
give a fig one way or the other. (The same could be said of voters
in this year's presidential election, which just goes to show how
powerful misaligned cat feng-shui can be. Instead of holding
conventions, the candidates might be better off giving each voter a
rubber mouse with a bell in it or a scratching post.)
</P>
<P>
   Daniels says her book shows ``how to maximize the strengths and
minimize the weaknesses of a house's space so that the cat and
owner never again need fight for that favorite patch of sofa.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many cat owners fight with their cat over
control of the sofa. My guess is that the first fight is the last
fight and that it is a brief but exceedingly bloody affair at the
end of which the cat curls up for a nap on its favorite patch of
sofa while the owner, with his one good eye, frantically searches
the medicine cabinet for gauze pads and iodine.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominously, Jay says her book shows ``how to manipulate
your human into maximizing the chi energy in your environment.''
</P>
<P>
   This conjures a chilling ``Village of the Damned''-type scenario
in which the cats, who were conceived by aliens, shoot hypnotic
beams of light from their eyes, compelling the humans, against
their will, to let the cats sit on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   If I were a cat owner, I would be afraid to alter my home
environment in the slightest, up to and including vacuuming and
dusting _ especially vacuuming and dusting _ lest my cat become so
charged with positive chi that I couldn't touch it without getting
shocked.
</P>
<P>
   (While it might be nice, for awhile, to own a cat that doubles
as a bug zapper, you've got to think the advantages of an
insect-free home would be outweighed by the constant, irritating
glare.)
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that cats acquire precisely as much positive chi as
they want, when they want, with or without the assistance or
consent of humans, especially human authors. Any attempt to funnel
more positive chi in the cat's direction is simply asking for
trouble of the sort one normally associates with sofa disputes,
with the added threat of electrocution.
</P>
<P>
   Cats barely tolerate humans as it is. Let's not push our luck.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
