<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-PREVIEW0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tigers' Leard has high hopes
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ ``That which doesn't kill us makes us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Leard has heard the expression. He doesn't know who wrote
it, but he figures it must have been a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' said Leard. ``But everything I've gone
through has made me a better football player. And I know it's made
me a better person.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, life could not be better for the Auburn quarterback.
Last week, he donned a cap and gown and marched down the aisle to
receive his degree in mass communications. This fall, he will be
the first Tigers quarterback to play as a graduate student. He will
also be able to take a light academic load, freeing most of his
time to concentrate on his final college football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to live in the film room,'' he laughed. ``Just move
me a cot in there.''
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER TRIUMPH IN ATHENS
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, Leard got engaged to Melanie King, his high school
sweetheart, who is a student at Georgia. It was his second big
triumph in Athens. In November, Leard played the game of his life
and torched the Bulldogs for 416 yards passing in a 38-21 win in
Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, and she agreed to marry me anyway,'' Leard said.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs because football is fun again. In his four years at
Auburn he has been beaten, battered, taunted, ridiculed, ignored
and, finally, given up for lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm still here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After serving a two-year apprenticeship under Dameyune Craig,
Leard became the starter as a sophomore in 1998. He struggled
early. By the fifth game, he had lost his starting job to freshman
Gabe Gross and did not play in the final five games. After the
season, he had surgery to correct a bulging disk in his back.
</P>
<P>
   In the the first game of the 1999 season against Appalachian
State, Leard came off the bench to throw a 33-yard touchdown pass
with 38 seconds left to win the game. Leard reclaimed the starting
job, and by the fourth game he was playing so well that Gross quit
to concentrate on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn was 3-0 when Ole Miss came to town on Sept. 25. Leard was
picking the Rebels' defense apart, completing 14 of his first 17
passes when he was hit and suffered a separated shoulder. Auburn
lost in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   He sat out the next three games, all Auburn losses, and tried to
come back in the eighth game against Arkansas. He completed five of
his first eight passes, but then was knocked unconscious. It was
the fourth concussion of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Leard missed the next game against Central Florida. Then, on
Nov. 13, before more than 40 friends and family members, he
completed 24 of 32 passes against a thoroughly confused Georgia
defense. Auburn won 38-21. ``Along with the Appalachian State game,
it was the best football moment of my life,'' said Leard.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Leard is the elder statesman of the Auburn football team.
He is comfortable in the offensive system of coordinator Noel
Mazzone and has more weapons to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that Ben's the leader of this offense,''
Mazzone said. ``He's proven he can get it done at this level. The
other guys listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   PIQUING NFL INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   Given his poise and clear-headedness under fire, the NFL is
starting to take a second look. One Internet site has him projected
as a pick in the first round of next year's NFL Draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben's a big guy (6-4, 225 pounds), and he makes the right
decisions because he is so well-prepared,'' Auburn head coach Tommy
Tuberville said. ``Because he's so smart, I see him as a guy who
could be in the league for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk about pro football is heady stuff for a guy who was
once ``all dried up,'' according to a letter he received from one
fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love that opportunity, but right now I just want to
concentrate on my last college season,'' he said. ``If this is
going to be it for me, I want to give it everything I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn might not win the SEC West, but Leard is convinced that
this collection of players is capable of going to a bowl, which
would be the Tigers' first since 1997. Auburn must find a running
game, which was nonexistent last season. Running back Rudi Johnson,
a junior-college transfer, will help. Leard has a great collection
of receivers, led by sophomore Ronney Daniels and freshman Deandre
Green. If a couple of junior-college transfers come through at
tackle, the defense should be stout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be a BCS team, but we want to lay the groundwork
for the future,'' Leard said. ``Someday, when Auburn is back in the
national spotlight, people will say that those guys in 2000 were
the ones who got it started.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
