<SLUG> BC-DEM-VOICES-V-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DENVER, FOUR INDEPENDENTS SIZE UP GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DEM-VOICES I, II, III, IV) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Roy Rosa watched television images of Democratic
conventioneers whirling like dervishes after Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., finished his speech on Tuesday night, and asked, ``Don't
these people realize they're going to lose?''
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, a college student, joined three other independent voters
in a hotel room here earlier this week to view the convention,
cracking jokes at the proceedings and matching notes on what did or
did not work about the carefully orchestrated series of speeches
presented by the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the convention's rhetoric, they agreed, seemed intended
to attract independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa is perhaps a typical independent voter. A member of both
the National Rifle Association and the board of the national Gay
and Lesbian Task Force, he supported Sen. John McCain's
presidential bid. Like the three others watching the convention in
the hotel room, he viewed it with an open, if skeptical, mind.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four had supported President Clinton when he first
ran for the White House in 1992; two had even done volunteer work
in his campaign. But none of them voted for Clinton in 1996, and
not one would support him if he were running today, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the lying and duplicity just bugged me with Clinton,''
said Sarah Edgell, a 42-year old graphic designer who voted for
Ross Perot in 1996 as a protest against the president. ``He is such
a complex man. He can seem so honest and then be such a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't trust him then and I don't trust him now,'' said
Jeanne Smith, 29, an administrator for the University of Colorado's
Health Science Center.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Keith, a senior officer with the American Indian
College Fund, said that after feeling initial enthusiasm for the
Clinton administration, he had become progressively disenchanted
with the Democrats over their handling of Indian issues.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not mean he was willing to leap to the Republicans.
``George Bush doesn't understand Indian affairs,'' said Smith, a
Navajo. ``You can't believe the ignorance of the man on Indian
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into the convention, he had been leaning toward Vice
President Al Gore, as was Edgell; Smith hadn't made up her mind yet
and Rosa, 22, planned to vote for Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   The dishing started almost immediately as Hillary Rodham Clinton
took the convention stage Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's petty, but look, she's wearing Barbara Bush's
pearls,'' Edgell told the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd forgotten just how nauseating she can be,'' said Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was more forgiving: ``She's put up with a lot,'' he noted.
``By the time this is over, Gore may be riding on her coat tails.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's lineup of party liberals and Kennedy family
members sparked a discussion between Rosa and Edgell about the role
of family values and the booming economy in the upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boom economy means the bosses make more money out of your
menial labor, but you're not getting paid any more,'' Rosa said.
</P>
<P>
   The election, Edgell said, should be about providing homes,
education, food and health care for everybody. ``There are so many
people out there working for the minimum wage, not getting
anywhere,'' she said. ``I don't want someone as president who's
just a mouthpiece for big business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, a former Reserve Officer Training Corps member, said:
```Don't ask don't tell' in the military was a big mistake. The
Democrats give gays a seat at the table, then bind us to the chair.
They don't want to hear us speak. In my main issue, gay rights,
both parties get an F.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman's speech on Wednesday night that
seemed to heighten the viewers' interest in the Democratic ticket
the most.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly important, said Smith, 31, was Lieberman's emphasis
on his religion. ``Respect for faith is part of the Navajo being,''
he said. ``A lot of our relationships with other people and other
tribes are grounded in our respect for others' beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely want to know more about Lieberman,'' said Smith.
``He was genuine in what he had to say. He was so natural and
honest, he didn't sound like a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Gore finally took the podium Thursday night, Smith
was even more inclined to vote for him, as were his wife and
Edgell; Rosa was still wavering between Gore and Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speech started off slowly, basically rehashing all the
stuff we'd heard before,'' said Smith. ``He picked up in the
middle, but overall, I was disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgell and Rosa thought Gore's speech was an unqualified
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved that he talked about traditional Democratic values and
working- family issues,'' Edgell said. She was so impressed, she
said, that she was going to volunteer to work in his campaign.
``This election is important and I need to get involved in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But of the four voters, the one most affected by Gore's speech
was Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it was banal and boring at the beginning, but when he
got warmed up it was awesome,'' said Rosa. ``He covered the whole
plight of the working class and he didn't do it in a patronizing
way.''
</P>
<P>
   And if one of the Democratic Party's goals for the convention
was to solidify its base, Rosa thought the speech accomplished
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really energized the activists by talking about Roe versus
Wade, and hate crimes, and racial profiling. Gore did it very well,
and I was really impressed. He sold himself to me at the same
time,'' Rosa said. ``Yeah, I'm going vote for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
