<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One Earnhardt short?
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Sunday's Earnhardt family reunion might be
canceled at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt and his sons Dale Earnhardt Jr. and Kerry
Earnhardt were all trying to qualify Friday for the Pepsi 400. The
last time a father competed against his two sons on NASCAR's top
circuit was in 1960, when Lee Petty raced against sons Maurice and
Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   The good news on Friday was that Dale Jr. won the pole position
for the second time this season. ``Little E'', who has also posted
two Winston Cup wins during his rookie season, set a new record for
qualifying at the two-mile oval with a speed of 191.149 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news was that Earnhardt Sr. had engine problems and
registered the 33rd-fastest speed in the time trials. But the
seven-time Winston Cup champion is assured of making Sunday's race,
whether by running in today's second round of qualifying or taking
an owner's provisional.
</P>
<P>
   The worst news is that Kerry needs a miracle to join his family
on the track Sunday. Kerry, 30, is trying to make his first Winston
Cup start. He is driving the No. 71 Chevrolet, which is normally
operated by veteran Dave Marcis and sponsored by Columbus-based
Realtree.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry had the 40th fastest time Friday. Marcis is out of owner's
provisionals until Darlington in two weeks, so Kerry needs to
heavily improve on his speed in today's second round of time trials
to make the 43-car field.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, the morning practice we were real good,'' Kerry
said. ``To come back and qualify like that, it kind of brings you
down a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun was out and the track is a little hotter . . . the car
just doesn't stick like it did in practice. I wanted to qualify in
the first round. We didn't get close. We'll just have to come back
(today) and try it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jr. was excited to win the pole, but it was tempered by the
results of his father and brother in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my father, when he does poorly, it's best not to get
anywhere near him,'' Dale Jr. said. ``As far as Kerry, he came up
in the trailer and we talked a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found some things today that improved my lap times . . . and
comfort level. I filled him in on some of those things. I am going
to do whatever I can with him in my power to improve his situation
(today).''
</P>
