<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS EARN OUR ENVY DURING LONG HOT SUMMERS
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   The teachers say they smell fall,
which means they have only a few weeks left. Soon they'll head back
after being off the entire summer, sitting around their pools,
drinking iced lattes and reading all the new novels.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In your dreams they would probably say, and they're right about
that. Who doesn't think ``I should have been a teacher'' at least
once each summer?
</P>
<P>
   They are our summer envy. Our brief vacation glow quickly fades
to office drab while theirs gets more golden. They get to stay up
for Ted Koppel. They could go shoeless for three months if they
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   I see one teacher friend mornings at the gym, and torture myself
by asking her, ``So, what are you going to do today?'' Her answers
have to do with cleaning out her closets or tying up her tomatoes,
which tells me that teachers really are smarter than the rest of
us.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I know, too, that many teachers keep working through
the summer, but they get a change of venue. They drive cabs, take
tickets at the fair, sell their flowers at the farmers market. Some
of them even land exotic jobs, teaching painting in France or
leading river rafters.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I'm related to two teachers, I see their summers up
close. A new teacher, whose peers may start off their ad agency
jobs making twice as much, has to spend some of her first summers
studying for more required certificates, putting in as many hours
as an MBA but never approaching the money.
</P>
<P>
   Other teachers spend their summers in school learning to be
librarians or counselors, and I imagine many work at
sometimes-unappealing jobs just to pay car insurance and the rent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet teachers are lucky to have this two- to three-month escape
period when they're being something else. I've had teachers explain
that they need this time to purge themselves of their school
selves, scrub the overhead projector ink off their hands, so they
can walk back into the classroom at summer's end refreshed and
ready to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Such a time-out would be good for just about any career type, I
think. Drop out for three months and do another job. You couldn't
help be a better editor or more interesting dentist upon returning.
</P>
<P>
   Back to teachers. I went camping with three of them and learned
it is not only newspaper people who are job-obsessed. Teachers tell
tales. They go on about administrators and personalities and all
the regular shop talk, but when they speak of the kids, usually
referring to them as ``my kids,'' they are in love. Even with the
tough ones and their needy parents.
</P>
<P>
   They really can't imagine being anything but teachers. And this
is pretty amazing considering the small money, early mornings and
late days, goosey school boards, voucher threats and demands to
produce the best test scores. Plus having to look out for guns and
mysterious bruises, as well as counter the crass, idiot-making
humor on TV, make sure no one gets picked on and inspire kids to
want to read.
</P>
<P>
   What gets me, too, about teachers is that they must always be
on. Even with cold sores or a headache, bad hair, coffee spilled on
their white shirt and cat hair on their black pants, they are
stared at all day by eyes that don't miss a flaw.
</P>
<P>
   I have been around a lot of people lately who are discouraged by
corporate takeovers, ``Survivor'' shows and $389,000 median-priced
homes, but teachers keep the faith. Maybe because they look at real
value every day.
</P>
<P>
   I now know a secret about teachers and their summers. They start
sneaking back into their classrooms early, sometimes even in July,
to rearrange furniture, make the walls inviting and cut out those
neat fall leaves that show up on school windows every end of
August.
</P>
<P>
   You thought it was elves?
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
