<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-MEN0819-COX     08-18 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-MEN0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamms on verge of Games history
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gymnasts Paul and Morgan Hamm are 17-year-old twins who
look so much alike that ``a lot of the guys can't tell us apart,''
Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   They are about the same size, 5 feet 6, and have the same
hairstyle, the same splatter of freckles and the same calm
demeanor. They say nearly the same things. And the Waukesha, Wis.,
high school seniors could wear the same uniform come September, as
the youngest members of the U.S. Olympic men's gymnastics team in
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our noses are a little bit different,'' Paul said,
helpfully.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Paul is right-handed, Morgan left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   And Paul Hamm _ pronounced ``Hom'' _ is ranked No. 2 entering
today's fourth and final round at the Olympic Trials, while Morgan
is sixth. The gymnasts with the four highest point totals _
currently Blaine Wilson, Paul Hamm, Sean Townsend and Stephen
McCain _ will make the team. The final two will be chosen by a
committee to shore up weak areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamms broke into gymnastics' old-boys club quickly. Last
year, Paul was 11th in the U.S. Championships to make his first
senior national team, while Morgan, who isn't quite as consistent,
was on the junior national team.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Paul placed third in last month's nationals and maneuvered
into second after two events Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of stress off me, getting higher,'' Paul said,
``because then I know my chances are so much better to make the
Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Hamm is a good bet for a wild-card spot. He has had the
fourth-best scores the last two rounds and is strongest in the
three events in which the U.S. needs help: Floor exercise, rings
and vault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end of the world if we don't make it,'' said
Paul, figuring that they will be only 21 in 2004. ``There's more
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   And if only one Hamm makes it? ``The only thing you can be is
happy for the other person,'' Morgan said. ``It's great for your
brother to go to the Olympics; how many people can actually say
that?''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic men's gymnastics team has had only one set of
brothers, and never twins. And if the Hamms make it, they could be
younger than most, if not all, of the women's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's amazing in my mind,'' Olympic coach Peter
Kormann said, ``is not just their gymnastics, but the way they
compete. They compete like they have all the experience, and they
don't have any _ I mean very little. They don't get their cages
rattled like some guys do.''
</P>
<P>
   And they have twice as much reason to be on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on the bubble of making it,'' Paul said, ``so I get
really nervous when he's up, just watching and saying, `Come on,
come on,' even though he can't hear me. You just do that kind of
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
