<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIDAMERICA-AIRPORT-NY     08-18 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDAMERICA-AIRPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND ST. LOUIS AIRPORT `NO-HASSLE' AS EXPECTED: IT JUST NEEDS
FLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JO THOMAS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASCOUTAH, Ill. _ When it was completed here two years ago to
relieve overcrowding at Lambert Field in St. Louis, MidAmerica
Airport was an airline passenger's dream: a brand new terminal with
free parking just 22 minutes from downtown. All it lacked was an
airline.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the $310 million airport, called ``the gateway to
nowhere'' by critics, got one. A reconstituted Pan Am started
service to Gary, Ind. Now, there are six flights a day.
</P>
<P>
   While major airports around the country are plagued with
increasing congestion, and passengers are facing a record number of
cancellations and delays, airport executives are frustrated that
such a new facility is sitting virtually unused. Mainly, they say,
this is because airlines are unwilling to leave the convenience and
efficiency of hubs, like TWA's at Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as a passenger is willing to get on an airplane,
airlines tend not to think of how long it takes you to get there,
the parking, the hassles, getting through the terminal,'' said Todd
Hauptli, senior vice president for policy and government affairs of
the American Association of Airport Executives. ``All they care
about is that you get in one of their seats. When it becomes such a
problem that people chose not to fly, or fly from a different
location, airlines sit up and take notice.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Southwest Airlines, Linda Rutherford, said the
discount-fare carrier had looked at MidAmerica, ``but we are
committed to Lambert, and we have a fairly substantial expansion
program going on right now. We are expanding our gates.''
</P>
<P>
   MidAmerica had not met several of Southwest's criteria,
Rutherford, said, though that is subject to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most travelers are on the west side of St. Louis, and that's
where Lambert is. MidAmerica would be more of a trek.''
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, which has flights from Lambert, also decided
against MidAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, we don't think there are the passenger loads
that would be necessary,'' a spokesman there said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Hargrove, MidAmerica's director, said he knows congestion
first hand. He was deputy director of Lambert Field from 1989 to
1994.
</P>
<P>
   All 3,000 acres of Lambert are ``for all practical purposes,
totally built up,'' he said. ``There is no more room for air cargo,
maintenance, repair or overhaul.''
</P>
<P>
   As the hub for Trans World Airlines, 17 million people per year
board airplanes there _ and sometimes, they don't. The delay time,
Hargrove said, is ``in excess of 20,000 hours a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Passengers learn _ to their dismay _ that the runways at
Lambert, built 1,300 feet apart, are too close for simultaneous
operation in bad weather. When the visibility is less than three
miles or the ceiling is less than 1,500 feet, one runway must
close. A third runway, to be completed in 2007, is expected to cost
more than $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Illinois cornfields east of St. Louis, where land
costs $4,000 an acre, MidAmerica sits on 8,000 acres, with room to
expand and two runways, set 7,000 feet apart. The military runway
was extended to 8,000 feet. And the new runway is 10,000 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Roxann Reum, of Collinsville, Ill., greeted her daughter at
MidAmerica on Thursday after she spent the summer with her
grandmother in Sanford, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no traffic and no parking hassles,'' Reum said
happily, adding that the airport in Sanford, like MidAmerica, is a
satellite to a busier airport airport serving Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom hates the Orlando airport,'' she said. ``It takes her
two hours to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   MidAmerica was built next to Scott Air Force Base. Even before
the airport found a civilian airline, state officials, who put up
$60 million, felt it was worth the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan to build MidAmerica was a critical factor in keeping
Scott Air Force Base open,'' said Martha Schiebel, a spokesman for
the Illinois Department of Transportation. ``It employs more than
10,000 people and is one of the biggest employers in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer runway also drew the 126th Refueling Wing of the Air
National Guard, which moved here from O'Hare Airport in Chicago,
another overcrowded airport where United Airlines needed additional
space. The guard brought 300 full-time and 1,000 part-time
employees.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the new 190-foot airport tower is being manned by
military air traffic controllers. When civilian traffic exceeds
military traffic, civilians will take over.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the Pan Am ticket agents were working without benefit
of a conveyor for luggage, but one is on the way, along with office
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a no-hassle airport,'' Hargrove said happily as he
walked through the terminal, pointing out how the baggage area
could quickly be converted to accommodate international flights,
and how the terminal, which has four gates, could be extended to
accommodate as many as 82.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds aren't here,'' he said. ``The traffic's not here.
We have quick and easy access to the runways for takeoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   David Fink, who bought the name and logo of Pan Am from
bankruptcy and is now president of the new airline, said both the
airport and the airline hope to fill a niche at a time when air
travel is expected to double in the next ten years.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes to use less congested airports in metropolitan
areas to provide low-cost flights, first to the leisure market and
then to business travelers. ``We're not looking to fill up every
plane,'' he said. ``We're hoping to bring a little civility and
make a dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Pan Am, based in Portmouth, N.H., now flies from airports in
Portmouth, Bangor, Maine, and Pittsburgh, as well as Mascoutah,
Ill., Gary, Ind., and Sanford, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   David Plavin, president of the Airports Council International, a
worldwide association of airports, said he considered MidAmerica
unusual only in the sense that ``most people don't have the
foresight and the courage to build before the demand
materializes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when it was routine to build in advance of
immediate demand: Newark, Dulles, Dallas, and even Denver were all
built before the demand actually materialized. No one considers
them white elephants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
