<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6108 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-SARALEE-COACH-     08-18 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SARALEE-COACH-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POCKETBOOK ISSUES ON THE FUTURE OF A COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 20) 
 By KATE BERRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors who are awaiting the initial public offering of Coach
Inc., the luxury leather goods maker, are likely to be
disappointed, analysts warn, because Coach's parent, the Sara Lee
Corp., might well do better if it sells the unit than if it takes
it public.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee reached a similar conclusion last week when it agreed
to sell its PYA/Monarch food service unit to Koninklijke Ahold
N.V., the Dutch supermarket giant, for $1.57 billion. In June,
PYA/Monarch filed with the Securities and Exchange Corp. to raise
$160 million in an initial offering to be managed by Goldman Sachs,
Bear Stearns and Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Sara Lee intended initially to keep 80 percent of
the company and offer 20 percent to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the direct sale of PYA/Monarch to Ahold, Sara Lee obtains
cash now, eliminates market uncertainty and secures a multiyear
supply contract, creating significant value for Sara Lee
shareholders,'' said C.Steven McMillan, chief executive of Sara
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan was the architect of the company's plan to sell some
assets and focus on its core businesses. Though it is best known
for its baked goods, Sara Lee also owns brands including Ball Park
franks, L'eggs hosiery, Hanes underwear, Wonderbra, Endust
furniture cleaner and Kiwi shoe polish.
</P>
<P>
   A Sara Lee spokeswoman, Julie Ketay, said after the PYA/Monarch
deal that the $140 million Coach offering, to be managed by Goldman
Sachs, was still on track to be completed by the end of the year,
but some fund managers and analysts are not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the French luxury goods group,
is among the many names being tossed up as potential buyers of
Coach. Last year LVMH teamed up with its archrival Prada S.p.A. to
win a bidding war with the Gucci Group for another high-class
brand, Fendi, the Italian apparel and accessories group. They paid
one trillion lire, or $483.6 million, for a 51 percent stake in
Fendi.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, the market will put a higher multiple on the
same business with the same earnings if Bernard Arnault owned this
company,'' said Greg Fontana, vice president and co-manager for the
John Hancock funds in Boston, referring to the LVMH chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Bernal, an analyst at Wachovia Securities in Charlotte,
N.C., said: ``The most likely choice is for it to be sold than to
do an IPO. Just about everybody has been mentioned, so it's not a
question of who, but what price.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some fashion stocks have performed poorly, like
Donna Karan International and Tommy Hilfiger. But those with
expanded product lines like jewelry, shoes and handbags, have
proved that pricey baubles have a place on Wall Street. Coach, with
sales of $507 million in the fiscal year ended July 3, 1999,
according to its prospectus, may be aiming for a valuation akin to
that of Kenneth Cole, the shoe designer that also makes handbags
and accessories, analysts say. Kenneth Cole, which has seen its
shares jump to $45.3125, from below $10 a share in 1998, has a
market capitalization of $925.05 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Kanter, an analyst at Prudential Securities, said Coach
had plenty of momentum behind it. ``It's bouncing back from a
difficult environment over the past few years where Asia reduced
their purchasing power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales grew at a compounded annual rate of 32 percent a year, to
$540.4 million in 1997, from $19 million in 1985 when Sara Lee
acquired the family-owned business, only to slide as a result of
Asia's financial crisis. Sales dipped 3.4 percent in 1998 and 2.8
percent in 1999 but are now starting to recover.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has 106 American retail stores, hopes to
rebound with an ambitious plan to open 50 new stores in the next
three years, remodel existing ones and expand its international
presence. Similar strategies helped fatten revenue for Tiffany,
Gucci, and LVMH, all of which have expanded their product lines to
attract upper middle-class shoppers _ those that have fared so well
in today's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Coach, which also sells through several catalogs and 63 factory
outlets, sees big growth opportunities in Japan, where consumers
spend substantially more for handbags than in the United States.
The company has a fashionably modern Web site and is branching into
products for the home, like leather director's chairs, and even
into pet supplies, from collars to beds. But analysts caution that
fashion trends change quickly in high-end luxury goods.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an initial offering, Coach could gain points
because, unlike many others going public, it is profitable. In the
first 39 weeks of fiscal 2000, Coach's net income jumped 67
percent, to $32.3 million, as sales rose 9.7 percent, to $427.2
million, according to its SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the initial offering would be used to repay a
portion of debt to Sara Lee. Coach also plans to enter into a
revolving credit facility with Sara Lee under which it may borrow
up to $75 million. (It expects to borrow about $50 million in the
first quarter of fiscal 2001.)
</P>
<P>
   Within 18 months of the initial offering, Sara Lee plans to sell
its 80.1 percent stake in Coach. Sara Lee also plans to shed
Champion sportswear, with $500 million in annual sales, and its
recently acquired International Fabrics division of the British
retailer Courtaulds Textiles, with $400 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the divestiture plans, McMillan said that the
sales would bring in at least $2.5 billion, giving the company
enough cash to buy other companies that fit better with the brands
it is keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve McMillan will spend the peak of his career disassembling
the conglomerate that he built,'' said Fontana, at John Hancock
funds. ``I don't believe conglomerates make sense unless you're
Jack Welch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
