<HEADER>
A6110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-BOS &LR;      08-18 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REUNION FAMILIES AGONIZE AS THEY SEPARATE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ With tear-drenched cheeks and trembling palms pressed to
bus windows, swollen lips mouthing goodbyes and kisses, shoulders
shaking with the agony of parting, 100 North Koreans began a sad
journey home Friday after a wrenching reunion with families they
had not seen since war separated them 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ending a three-day exchange that transfixed the two Koreas, they
sat mournfully as their buses headed to the airport, the joy of
rediscovery washed away by the anguish of having to leave.
</P>
<P>
   As the buses pulled away, one sobbing man traced the Korean
character for mother again and again on the glass. Another pried
open his window and reached out to grab the arm of his crying
sister. Others murmured into mobile phones that their relatives
thrust into their hands as they boarded so they could share the
last seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional outpouring of the reunions _ only the second time
in 50 years that a few families have been able to meet _ left both
halves of Korea galvanized by reunification fever. South Korea's
government called for a permanent reunion point at a border village
where families could meet regularly. Northern leader Kim Jong Il
said he would allow further restricted visits in the next two
months, and perhaps visits to hometowns next year.
</P>
<P>
   But amid memories of past broken promises and failed diplomacy,
the sorrowful farewells of 100 northerners departing Seoul and the
somber arrival of 100 southerners returning from Pyongyang
underlined the uncertainties faced by a Korea divided by the
world's last Cold War frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The reunion journeys were made possible by a landmark summit
between the two country's leaders in June.
</P>
<P>
   But the 200 who were reunited with relatives are a tiny fraction
of the 10 million living members of divided families, who amount to
10 percent of the population of the Korean penisula, according to
South Korean officials. They are not allowed telephone calls,
letters, or any contact across the sealed border. Most do not even
know if long-lost relatives are alive.
</P>
<P>
   There are 1.23 million elderly first-generation members of
separated families in the South alone, all of them longing to see
sons who were conscripted and never came home and daughters who
disappeared without a trace from their schools as war broke out. A
local newspaper calculated that, at the rate of 100 a month, it
would take more than 1,000 years for all of them to meet relatives
in the North.
</P>
<P>
   Well aware of the odds, desperate families who were not included
in this week's visits waved placards and tried to pass notes across
security lines to the departing northern visitors, begging for
information about their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors had just bid a final, agonizing farewell in 100
heartbreaking ways along a rope line guarded by hundreds of police
against any desperate outbursts in the last minutes of the 72-hour
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't go! Don't go!'' Kim Bong Ja, 86, cried from her
wheelchair, clinging to her son's neck and wetting him with flood
of tears as he tried to soothe her with a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we met, Mother, didn't we?'' 66-year-old son Ri Yong Su
choked out, bowing before her and clinging to her knees before he
was gently nudged onto the waiting bus by an escort. As Ri forced
open the bus window and reached out to wave, his sister surged
through the security cordon and leapt up to grasp his hand, trying
unsuccessfully to hug him one last time. Ri began to sing an old
anthem calling for reunification of the Koreas, and his relatives
joined in, crying as they sang.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, there is only hope freighted with sadness, after
families were forced to separate again after just starting to get
reacquainted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anything more, now that I've seen you,'' said the
mother of Ri Dong Sop, 65, who had to return to Pyongyang. ``I'd
just like reunification soon, so I can meet my daughter-in-law
before I die.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten feet away, Kim Ok-bae, 67, a professor of dance who
disappeared from her high school during the war, fell to her knees
before her 87-year-old mother, as her two sisters cried
inconsolably.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I let you go while I am still living here?'' wailed
one mother, Hong Kil Soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a heartbreaking moment,'' said Kim Yong Bae, 62, after
her sister boarded the bus. ``We wish she could have slept with us
for even one night.''
</P>
<P>
   During the reunions, the relatives were kept in separate hotels
on opposite side of the Han River and were allowed to meet only a
few times in hotel rooms and a convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   In the Seoul airport, the mood was restrained, as 100
southerners returned from the north. ``It feels like I met someone
who came back from the dead,'' said Lee Tae Hoon, 83, of seeing the
daughter who got left behind in the war. ``I'm so sad, but there's
nothing I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee and others said they were struck by the absence of cars,
pedestrians, and lights in the northern capital, but found the city
clean and its people warm and hospitable, if gaunt. Families were
allowed to meet without escorts, in contrast to the Seoul reunions,
but Southerners said they were afraid to pry about life in the
hermetically sealed North.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother said he has a house with its own yard and a
pension, and he said is happy,'' said Seonwoo Chun Shil, 72, who
had taken gifts to the little brother she lost when she fled south.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't believe it,'' she said. ``He looks so bad, not
only him, but all the people there are grey-faced, with teeth
falling out. . . . You can say 10 times over that I was lucky to
end up on this side. . . . But of course I want reunification as
soon as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6115 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-BISHER0819-CO     08-18 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-BISHER0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicklaus reflects on his No. 1 fan
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ He's beginning to walk a little older.
Wrinkles are developing where wrinkles usually develop for
60-year-olds. The crow's feet around his eyes go into a graceful
squint when he smiles. But don't for once doubt the heart or the
passion for the game of Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   If this is, in fact, Jack Nicklaus' last round of major
tournament golf, then America said its farewell, with feeling, to
one of its treasures at this 82nd PGA Championship in the Friday
gloaming.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he moved around these 18 holes of his own design at
Valhalla, he was met with compassionate applause. You could feel
the difference in the Nicklaus cheers and the cheers for his
celebrated match companion, Tiger Woods. Cheers for Woods had a
lustiness to them, Nicklaus' a depth and lingering sadness.
</P>
<P>
   The week was for more than another PGA Championship, another
major, presumably the last in a long line of majors than began 41
years ago. This was the week his mother passed away, Helen
Nicklaus, or Mrs. Charles Nicklaus, as she probably preferred to be
addressed. As he last visited with her on Monday, she had made
certain that no matter what the case, he should play the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her greatest concern the last two years was that she might
pass away while I was in a major tournament, and she wanted to make
sure that I played on,'' he said, earlier this week, when he was
honored with the PGA's highest award. ``So that is why I am playing
this week.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his multiple news conferences, he spoke of
mothers, his in particular. ``Mothers are always there to do for
you, what you need, always there when you've got problems. They are
in the background, but they are in the forefront, too. My mother
was no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a tough old girl, and she hung in there and I talked
to her a lot. She never missed watching golf on television and she
was a great supporter, but never in the forefront, always in the
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Nicklaus was 90 years old.
</P>
<P>
   So two majors in Jack Nicklaus' life went out with the sunset.
He goes home to bury his mother Monday in Columbus, Ohio, and he
walked off the 18th green at Valhalla, an aptly named location,
Friday as the sun lowered, presumably leaving behind once and for
all his life among the U.S. and British Opens, the Masters and the
PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably. I have no reason to doubt it, but I won't be
surprised if he shows up at the Masters next April.
</P>
<P>
   To estimate the meaning Jack Nicklaus has brought to golf isn't
within my realm. I do find it incongruous that for all the
championships he has won and the trophies he has collected, in this
one year alone Tiger Woods has made more money than Nicklaus in all
his years.
</P>
<P>
   The finish was as if fate had orchestrated it. The 18th hole is
a long par-5, downhill to a green divided by a bunker, designed,
you understand, by Nicklaus himself. (``I was told by Dwight Gahm,
who owned the land, to build a golf course where the PGA
Championship could be played.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus' drive was straight and true and his second shot left
him about 100 yards from the green. His approach flew toward the
pin in an arc, landed, spun backward and almost into the hole for
an eagle. He finished off, appropriately, with a birdie, and while
the world of Valhalla exploded, he walked off the green arm in arm
with son Steve, his caddie.
</P>
<P>
   The old warhorse had not been sent out for show, he had gone out
to play his game and he had responded with the grim determination
of Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
