<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ART-     08-18 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBMARINE LIKELY DAMAGED BY INTERNAL EXPLOSION, RUSSIA SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for complete rewrite to update and add details) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics
are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER with STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The commander of Russia's Northern Fleet acknowledged
Friday that a terrible internal explosion devastated the nuclear
submarine Kursk before it went down last Saturday, confirming
Western intelligence reports of huge underwater explosions.
</P>
<P>
   The report by Adm. Vyacheslav Popov on Russian television came
as the Russian navy finally docked a rescue vehicle to the spine of
the wrecked submarine after numerous unsuccessful attempts. But
rescuers said they found the deck area around a rear escape hatch
so deformed that they were unable to make a water-tight connection
and enter the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred eighteen men were on board the Kursk when it sank.
Navy officials said they would keep trying to reach them, and there
remained the possibility that a British submersible, to arrive
Saturday night, might manage to enter the Kursk with a more
flexible docking mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   Popov said the last signals from the crew were heard on Monday.
Other naval officials have said that survivors were tapping on the
hull of the vessel through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Popov also said that he was ``very worried that according to our
calculations the pressure in the submarine is higher than the
normal atmosphere,'' indicating a dangerous threat to normal
respiration. ``Our estimates of the time limit'' for the crew's
survival ``have been based on the fact that the air pressure is
normal,'' he said. He added, ``The situation is very grave.'' Most
Russian officials have said that the oxygen in the Kursk would be
depleted by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Though Popov confirmed internal explosions, he did not rule out
earlier Russian claims that the Kursk sank after a collision with
an unidentified object or vessel. He said the investigation into
what triggered the explosions centered on an outside impact, like a
collision, or something inside. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. officials in Washington said Friday that it was
conceivable that a collision preceded the large explosion detected
aboard the Kursk. Others felt that such a collision also would have
been heard by Western intelligence sensors monitoring the Russian
naval maneuvers in the Barents Sea last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   One theory circulating among U.S. defense officials Friday was
that the Kursk was in the process of firing an antisubmarine rocket
from one of its forward weapons tubes when the rocket jammed in the
tube. With its warhead outside the hull and still attached to the
rocket body and flaming engine, it triggered a fire and an
explosion, the first of the two detected by Western intelligence
sensors.
</P>
<P>
   After two minutes and 15 seconds, the officials theorized, the
missile's warhead of high-yield conventional explosive could have
detonated with the force of one to two tons of TNT, causing
extensive damage to deck structures in the forward section and near
the conning tower.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. analysts estimated that a high-yield exploding warhead
and a shock wave from the explosion could have destroyed an
estimated 40 percent of the submarine, splitting and deforming
parts of the hull. That may have given the appearance that the ship
had been pummeled by the glancing blow of another ship and opened a
gaping hole in the hull.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Polmar, an independent naval expert, said one torpedo
carried by this type of submarine is designed to be fired
underwater, shoot up through the air and then drop back into the
water to home in on another submarine.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said that the Russians had been practicing
missile and torpedo firings in a large naval exercise right before
the explosions were heard. Polmar said that in the two minutes and
15 seconds before the torpedo's warhead exploded, it is possible
that sailors in the back of the submarine could have shut a series
of watertight doors. He said those crew members could have survived
as the sub plummeted to the bottom, while most men in the front of
the submarine would have perished quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts said the submarine's batteries lay below the front
compartments and probably would have been knocked out. That would
make it unlikely that survivors would have had battery power and
would decrease the odds that any could have survived more than
three or four days.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A Norwegian seismic institute joined with Western governments
Friday in saying that it had detected two underwater explosions in
the area where the Kursk went down. The explosions were a little
more than two minutes apart, the first one much smaller than the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first explosion we recorded was probably the equivalent of
less than 100 kilograms of TNT,'' said Frode Ringdal, scientific
director of the institute. But the second explosion was the
equivalent of one to two tons of TNT, he added. The explosion sent
powerful shock waves through the water that could be detected by
seismic equipment on Norway's northern coast, near where U.S.
intelligence sensors aboard submarines operating in the Arctic
Ocean area also detected the powerful explosions.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin flew back to Moscow late Friday after
attending the opening in Yalta, Ukraine, of a summit meeting of
leaders of former Soviet republics. He faced biting criticism in
the Russian press and among some leading political figures for
vacationing at a Black Sea resort while any survivors on board the
Kursk slowly asphyxiated below the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   He defended his five-day delay. ``Of course, my first wish was
to fly to the region, to the fleet base in order to study the
situation on the spot,'' Putin told reporters before leaving Yalta.
``But I decided against that, and I think I made the correct
decision,'' he said, explaining that ``the arrival in the disaster
area of high-ranking officials who are not specialists'' does not
``help rescue either people or equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, criticism was intense. The leader of Russia's liberal
Union of Right Forces Party, Boris Nemtsov, said in a statement
Friday that Putin, as commander-in-chief has ``no right to vacation
while his subordinates, Northern Fleet sailors, face this drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin defended his actions saying that the first assessment he
received of the disaster from Marshal Igor Sergeyev, the defense
minister, indicated that ``the chances the crew will survive are
few, but they exist and specialists will do their utmost.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader said he also was assured that ``Russia has
all the means for rescue work.'' When this proved not to be the
case, Putin said discussions were carried out with Western
countries as soon as help was offered.
</P>
<P>
   Though there were rumors in Murmansk that Putin would fly
straight to the northern submarine base to console the families,
Russian officials remained silent about whether Putin had reached
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government announced Friday evening that each family
of Kursk crew members would be allocated the equivalent of about
$18,000 in immediate financial assistance to cover their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Adm. Vladimir Kuroyedov, the navy
commander, said that he would remain optimistic ``until Aug. 18.''
Other navy experts have suggested that any surviving crew members
have already run out of oxygen and that most of the 86 officers, 31
enlisted men and the one civilian likely perished in the first
minutes after a catastrophic blow or explosion ruptured the hull
and allowed water to enter the ship.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Murmansk edition of the newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda on
Friday published a full list of the names of 118 people aboard the
Kursk with an editorial note stating that after repeated attempts
to obtain the list through officials navy channels, the newspaper
finally resorted to bribery and paid 16,000 rubles for the list,
the equivalent of about $650.
</P>
<P>
   Inflaming the mystery about the accident were numerous
unconfirmed reports and theories spun out in the Russian press,
several of them asserting that the Russian navy suspected that one
of the two U.S. submarines alleged to have been operating in the
area might have been involved in a collision with the Kursk and had
then sought refuge at a Norwegian port.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports were only fanned by the arrival in Moscow of
George Tenet, the U.S. Director of Central Intelligence. Tenet's
agenda was not clear, but Russian officials said that his visit had
been planned before the Kursk tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has denied that any of its submarines were
involved in the disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
