u f BC-DATEK-BUYOUT-NYT &LR;      08-18 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATEK-BUYOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE BROKER MAY BUY OUT TWO BIG INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trying to distance itself from a troubled past, Datek
Online, one of the United States' fastest-growing online brokerage
firms, has agreed to raise about $500 million to buy out the
company's two majority shareholders, according to people who have
been briefed on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The company's board and top executives are trying to end Datek's
relationship with Jeffrey A. Citron, the company's former chief
executive, and Sheldon Maschler, a former trader with a history of
regulatory problems. Together they own about 52 percent of Datek.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who may retain a minority stake, were instrumental
in transforming what began as a small day-trading operation in
Brooklyn into what is now the nation's sixth-largest online broker,
with over $14 billion in customer assets.
</P>
<P>
   But continuing criminal and regulatory investigations into the
company's day-trading operations in the 1990s have prevented Datek
from offering shares to the public and have scared away many
potential investors in Datek and its subsidiary, Island ECN, a
popular electronic trading network.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the buyout agreement was prompted by any
of the investigations. But people close to Datek's operations say
that the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York and
the Securities and Exchange Commission are still investigating
Datek and its former day-trading unit, which was spun off in 1998
as Heartland Securities. Datek Online, the popular online trading
unit, is not the focus of the inquiry, people close to the
investigations say.
</P>
<P>
   Datek, which is based in Edison, N.J., hopes that by
substantially reducing the stakes of Maschler and Citron, who will
lose their voting power in the company, Datek can attract new
investors and prepare for an initial public offering, people close
to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Datek issued a terse statement confirming that a
buyout deal had been reached with Maschler and Citron. But a
spokesman for the company, Robert O. Bethge, declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have entered into an agreement with the principal
shareholders to seek to repurchase a substantial portion of their
shares,'' the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   People who have been briefed on the deal, however, said that for
over a month top executives at Datek and representatives of the
board had been in tense negotiations with Maschler and Citron about
buying out their stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Maschler, who was sued in 1998 by the SEC on accusations of
playing a role in a stock manipulation scheme, now lives in
Florida. Citron, who has also been fined by the SEC for trading
violations, lives in Brielle, N.J. Neither Citron nor Maschler
could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The two men agreed a few weeks ago to sell at least 75 percent
of their shares to new investors, according to people close to the
deal. The company is expected to find private investors willing to
pay about $500 million for that stake, according to people who were
briefed on the deal. The repurchase values Datek at about $1.1
billion. The company's investment banker is Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Datek, however, does not plan to pay for the deal with an
initial public offering, people close to the deal say. But Datek
officials have said publicly in recent months that they would like
to move toward a public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the company canceled plans for an initial
offering, after the Manhattan district attorney's office said it
was investigating whether Datek had participated in a
money-laundering operation, and former Datek traders said they had
been interviewed by the SEC about questionable off-shore
transactions and illegal trading practices at Datek's day-trading
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, Vulcan Ventures, a venture capital fund
controlled by Paul G. Allen, one of the co-founders of Microsoft,
pulled out of a planned $100 million investment in Datek and Island
ECN. People close to the deal said the withdrawal was partly
because of concerns about investigations into the company. (TA
Associates, a venture capital fund in Boston, and Groupe Arnault of
Paris, proceeded with a $195 million investment.)
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, TD Waterhouse, a big online broker and a unit of
Toronto Dominion Bank, decided not to follow through on plans to
spend about $25 million for a 12 percent stake in Island ECN, which
is seeking approval from the SEC to become a full-fledged stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   And last October, Citron, the 29-year-old chief executive at
Datek, stepped down under pressure from other executives and
investors in the company in a move that Datek officials hoped would
end some questions about the company's past.
</P>
<P>
   Though he kept a 30 percent stake in Datek, Citron agreed to
turn over all his management and voting rights to the board. He
also agreed to have no role at the company for two years, at which
time Datek hoped investigations into its former day-trading unit
would be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Maschler has not had a role in the company since 1996, when as
chief trader at Datek he was suspended for one year for trading
infractions. But it was Maschler who went to Datek in 1987 and
started building a day-trading powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he hired Citron, who was 17, to work as a clerk in the
office. Citron later became an enormously successful day trader _
using software the company created _ and then at the age of 26
became chief executive of Datek, which in 1996 transformed itself
into an online broker.
</P>
<P>
   But Citron resigned last October after over two years of
revelations that the day-trading unit he was running had been under
the scrutiny of authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials are still scrutinizing Maschler and
Citron's relationship to Robert E. Brennan, the penny-stock
promoter who was banned from the securities industry for life, and
who two weeks ago was arrested on charges of failing to report
cashing in $500,000 of gambling chips after declaring bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Citron and Maschler, who once worked for Brennan at First Jersey
Securities, have each made financial deals with Brennan. Brennan
borrowed about $3 million from a company owned by Maschler,
according to files in Brennan's bankruptcy case. And Citron bought
Brennan's mansion in New Jersey for $3.3 million in 1996 and his
private jet for $3.8 million. Brennan recently traveled on a plane
chartered through a company owned by Citron and his wife, according
to court records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0360 </DOCNO>
