<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AUDI-ROADSTER0819-COX     08-18 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDI-ROADSTER0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2001 Audi TT a bundle of fun
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like a finely made and rather expensive Swiss watch,
Audi's 2001 TT roadster is a bit of an engineering marvel. Just how
much of a gee-whiz car it is depends on the drivetrain, which comes
in several variations.
</P>
<P>
   There's the basic front-drive 180-horsepower model that checks
in at $32,850 and an all-wheel drive, 225-hp version listing for
$38,500. Note that versions now coming to market have revised
suspensions and aerodynamic work following several high-speed
accidents in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have affected the performance and driving
characteristics of the TT, but it retains enough sports-car
qualities to satisfy all but the most aggressive drivers and should
be very satisfying on American roads.
</P>
<P>
   Although a comfortable car for driver and passenger, the TT
(stands for Tourist Trophy, an old racing classification) is small.
Its wheelbase is 95.4 inches, and overall length is 159.1 inches,
or about 13 feet long. Get stuck in expressway traffic, and it's
downright intimidating to be beside trucks and SUVs with tires that
seem larger than your vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But put the TT in its proper habitat, a two-lane road, and push
back the folding top, which can be done from behind the steering
wheel, and it's a little bundle of fun for even placid drivers. So
what if the 180-hp TT needs about eight seconds to get to 60 mph?
This is a 3,000-pound car that feels tight and capable.
</P>
<P>
   It did finish behind the Porsche Boxster S, the Honda S2000 and
BMW M roadster in one of those car vs. car tests by the
performance-loving crowd at Road &AMP; Track. But they point out that
it's ``fun and predictable . . . If your bias is canted slightly
toward comfort, it's a small price to pay,'' the reference being to
the TT's less than razor-sharp handling.
</P>
<P>
   But one area in which the TT is sharp enough to dazzle is its
interior. Brightwork abounds, with colored leather given what Audi
calls ``baseball stitching'' and gleaming aluminum on the steering
wheel, the gauges and elsewhere. The brassy appearance may make
some uncomfortable, but the accommodations and equipment are way up
the comfort scale.
</P>
<P>
   As AutoWeek points out, the ``TT'' could easily stand for those
``Terrific Things,'' which is what Audi's roadster has in abundance
_ and not the least is its fun-in-the-sun (and wind) quotient.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
