u k BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT     08-18 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REVIVING THE MIDEAST SUMMIT TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   Israeli, Palestinian and U.S. diplomats are exploring the
possibility of a new summit meeting to complete the peace
negotiations broken off at Camp David last month. Despite political
opposition in Israel, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has resolved to
push for a final-status agreement with the Palestinians before his
Parliament returns in late October. The Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, hints encouragingly that he will postpone his threat to
proclaim an independent state if no agreement is reached by Sept.
13. But a new summit meeting only makes sense if there is a
realistic hope of breaking the impasse over Jerusalem that halted
the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Israel was prepared to consider a U.S. proposal
that would have given the Palestinians control over parts of the
Old City containing Muslim holy sites, along with some outlying
Arab neighborhoods in East Jerusalem. But Arafat showed little
interest, and was forcefully reminded by other Arab countries,
particularly Egypt and Saudi Arabia, that anything less than full
Arab sovereignty over East Jerusalem was unacceptable to them. Both
countries warn that Islamic militants throughout the Arab world
might react violently if sovereignty over any part of East
Jerusalem is conceded to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   For any progress to be made at a new summit meeting, these U.S.
allies must take a more flexible position. Jerusalem is a highly
emotive issue for Muslims, as it is among Jews. But this is a time
for President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Crown Prince Abdullah of
Saudi Arabia to demonstrate leadership in the interest of regional
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State Edward Walker has just returned
from two weeks of discussions with Arab leaders in which he sought
their help in finding an acceptable compromise on Jerusalem. During
the same period Arafat has been traveling to Arab and Islamic
capitals, where he encountered little support for proceeding with
his independence declaration in September. By deferring such a
move, he can reduce the risks of new violence in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip and allow more time for negotiations. High-level talks
between Israelis and Palestinians resumed this week, assisted by
the U.S. mediator Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
   If there is to be a return to the summit, it should come within
the next month or so. The Jewish High Holy Days begin at the end of
September, quickly followed by the return of Israel's Parliament
for its fall term. If no agreement is reached by then, Barak is
sure to face renewed pressure from parties opposed to any further
compromises with the Palestinians. Meanwhile, the Clinton
administration's ability to broker an accord will fade as America's
elections approach. Now is the time for the Palestinians and
Israelis to concentrate on reaching an acceptable compromise on
Jerusalem and sealing a final peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
