<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-ROUND20819-CO     08-18 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-ROUND20819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No surrender in Dunlop
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ It's the most unlikely of final pairings in
today's third round of the PGA Championship at Valhalla Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   It's Scott Dunlap, 37, who has never won a PGA Tour event,
paired with Tiger Woods, 24, who has 21 PGA Tour victories in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   And, heck, Woods hasn't won a major championship all month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won more majors than I've made cuts in,'' Dunlap said.
``It will be old hat for him and a new experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of no one, Woods rammed in an 18-foot putt for a
birdie at the 18th hole Friday to grab a one-shot lead over Dunlap
at 11-under-par 133 with a 5-under-par 67.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of practically everyone, Dunlap, the
globe-trotting veteran who plays out of the TPC at Sugarloaf, hung
tough, firing a 68 at a Valhalla course softened by a Thursday
night thunderstorm, to finish at 10-under 134.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap played with Woods once before, during the U.S. Open at
Congressional in 1997. He tied for 24th then, five spots below
Woods, who had not yet begun his sprint to world golf domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen so many people on a golf course in my entire
life,'' Dunlap said. ``It's not a social experience, but it will be
a nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's very little pressure on Dunlap, whose best
finish in a major was a tie for 10th at the 1999 British Open.
Woods is the one expected to rewrite history, seeking a third
straight major, to tie Ben Hogan's mark of 1953, after record routs
at the U.S. Open (15 shots) and British Open (eight).
</P>
<P>
   At least Woods, the defending PGA champion, is having to fight a
bit harder this time. He coasted by six shots through 36 holes at
Pebble Beach; by three shots at St. Andrews. Admittedly, Dunlap,
when he was a kid watching Jack Nicklaus in his prime, would have
given a newcomer to the situation little hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Done and dusted, for sure,'' Dunlap said. ``The majors are so
much more important and the better players relish those moments.
It's not that they're so much better; it's that they're so much
better in that situation. And that's why Tiger will be extremely
difficult to beat, because that's what he lives for. He actually
gets better at that time and at that moment, much like Jack did.''
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III, who's four shots back at 7-under
137 after a 69, bogeyed his final two holes to lose valuable
ground. Also at 7-under are J.P. Hayes (68) and Fred Funk (68).
Five shots off the pace is Bob May, who had the day's low round, a
66.
</P>
<P>
   The cut (to the low 70 and ties) will not come until Saturday
morning, when 11 players conclude the second round, which was
halted at 8:32 p.m. by darkness. It's start was delayed an hour
Friday morning for the course to be cleaned up from a thunderstorm
that dumped three inches of rain Thursday night. The course played
longer Friday, but somewhat easlier, with more receptive greens and
kinder pins.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the grouping of Woods and Jack Nicklaus (with
Masters champion Vijay Singh barely noticed), emerged as the
featured attraction. After playing poorly on Thursday (77)
following the death of his mother Helen, the 60-year-old Nicklaus
managed a sometimes stirring 1-under 71, but missed the cut in his
37th and possibly final PGA.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup had its highlights. Nicklaus birdied the first two
holes, revving up the gallery. Woods nearly slam-dunked his second
shot at the 5th hole, after Nicklaus hit to within eight feet. At
the par-5 18th, Nicklaus nearly spun his third shot into the cup
for eagle, then made a 3-footer for birdie,
</P>
<P>
   ``You just knew he was going to birdie the last hole,'' Woods
said. ``It was kind of neat to look at the sight and take it all
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, miffed at himself for 3-putting the 17th for bogey
(missing a three-footer), got out of a tough spot at 18. His second
shot was semi-plugged in the greenside bunker, but he artfully
escaped to 18 feet, then sank the putt.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
