<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GRANDJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE ADMITS TO CLINTON INVESTIGATION LEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court judge in Chicago said on
Friday that he was the source of a report on Thursday that a new
grand jury had been impaneled by the independent counsel
investigating President Clinton's relationship with a former White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The reports that a new grand jury was reviewing Clinton brought
an angry response on Thursday from Democrats and Republicans who
described the leak as an apparent effort to embarrass Vice
President Al Gore hours before he accepted the Democratic Party's
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Richard D. Cudahy of the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Chicago, who was appointed to the bench by President
Carter in 1979, said he had inadvertently mentioned the new grand
jury to a reporter from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Cudahy, one of three appellate judges who preside over
independent counsel matters, said the reaction to the report
prompted him to speak out on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, Robert W. Ray, convened the new grand
jury in July after saying publicly that he would consider whether
Clinton should be charged after he leaves office in connection with
testimony in which he denied having a relationship with a White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Cudahy said Friday that he wanted ``to set the record
straight.'' ``I don't think it ever entered my head it had anything
to do with what was going on in the convention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he did not want prosecutors in the independent
counsel's office to be blamed for the leak. ``I didn't think Robert
Ray ought to get blamed for the whole thing as far as timing was
concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Sewert said Friday night that
``Wherever the information came from, even after $50 million, an
800-page report, proceedings in both houses of Congress, the
independent counsel seems to want this investigation to go on and
on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have put this episode behind them and they
must be wondering why the independent counsel can't do the same,''
Sewert said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three appellate judges who preside over independent
counsel matters, Cudahy is the only Democratic appointee. The other
two judges, David B. Sentelle of the District of Columbia U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals and Peter T. Fay of the 11th U.S. Court of
Appeals in Atlanta, are Republican appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Cudahy said that he revealed the existence of the new grand jury
in response to the reporter's questions about a one-sentence order
issued late Wednesday by the three-judge panel. That order
authorized Ray to continue his investigation for another year, an
annual finding required by law.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he inadvertently mentioned the grand jury while
explaining why he had changed his position on the independent
counsel. Last year, Cudahy was the only one on the panel who voted
to terminate the independent counsel's operation.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in explaining his reason for changing his position
and voting this year to keep the inquiry open, he mentioned the new
grand jury to the reporter. The judge said Ray had told the
judicial panel earlier this year that the impanelling of the new
grand jury was one reason prosecutors should be allowed to continue
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the independent counsel's office said in a statement
that it condemned unauthorized disclosures of information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disclosure subjected this office to unsubstantiated
accusations that this investigation intended to improperly impact
the political process,'' the office said in the statement, and
added that the timing of the disclosure ``undermines our ability to
complete this matter in a prompt, responsible and cost-effective
manner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
