<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-FIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE'S ARMAS SIDELINED, TO MISS GALAXY GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A day after being named to the United States'
Olympic soccer team, midfielder Chris Armas of the Chicago Fire has
suffered a possible season-ending knee sprain.
</P>
<P>
   It came at the worst possible time for Armas, who sprained his
left medial collateral ligament in the first half of the U.S.
national team's 7-0 World Cup qualifying victory over Barbados on
Wednesday. After an MRI on Thursday, Chicago team officials said
Armas will be out three to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will Armas miss today's game with the Los Angeles
Galaxy at Soldier Field, but he will miss Wednesday's U.S. Open Cup
semifinal against the Galaxy at Cal State Fullerton, along with a
World Cup qualifier (Sept. 3 against Guatemala) and possibly the
Olympics and MLS playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Armas was one of three over-age players named to the team, which
is made up of players under 23 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to make it to the Olympics,'' said Armas, a former
Galaxy midfielder. ``It's going to be close.''
</P>
<P>
   If Armas is unavailable for the Olympics, Galaxy midfielder
Sasha Victorine, named an alternate, could be chosen to replace
Armas.
</P>
<P>
   Armas has established himself as the United States' best
defensive midfielder and man-marker. Galaxy defender Greg Vanney
said Armas is the one player Chicago can't afford to lose. The Fire
is already missing starters Lubos Kubik and Diego Gutierrez because
of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why Chris is so important,'' said Vanney, the
hero of Wednesday's 1-0 victory over Colorado, scoring with two
minutes left in sudden-death overtime. ``He really knows (Mauricio)
Cienfuegos.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos is the Galaxy playmaker, but he's usually a
non-factor when paired against Armas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is as quick as (Cienfuegos), he's similar size and he's
stronger than Cien, so he gives him fits,'' said Vanney. ``With
Armas not there, it means they have to use Jesse Marsch or someone
who is just not Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the Galaxy (12-7-8, 44 points) face Chicago
(12-9-5, 41 points) twice in the next five days, but the Fire could
also be the Galaxy's first-round opponent when the playoffs start
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago trails the Galaxy by three points in the race for the
fourth playoff seed and home-field advantage in the first round of
the playoffs. If the Galaxy can push that margin to six, the Fire
doesn't have much of a chance. But if the Fire can pull even today,
Chicago has an advantage with a game in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``At full strength, we're probably the best two teams in the
league,'' Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri said. ``Them missing Armas
is unfortunate because he's really the glue to that team,
offensively and defensively. He's the type of player you need on
your team to win championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, we still have a lot of respect for Chicago. This
is the one team we need to face and believe we can beat. I think
winning in dramatic fashion the other night gives us a little
momentum heading into this game.''
</P>
<P>
   In their only other meeting this season, the Galaxy tied the
Fire 1-1 at the Rose Bowl on June 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
