<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TOOTER0819-COX     08-18 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOOTER0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tillie Tooter talks about her 3-day ordeal
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Fourteen television cameras followed an
83-year-old woman Friday as a hospital attendant wheeled her toward
a mountain of microphones in a Broward General Medical Center
conference room.
</P>
<P>
   A nasty bruise stretched from the left side of the woman's
forehead to a point just below her eye. The bruising continued up
her left arm, fighting dozens of fresh bug bites for the attention
of their host.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman was in position, the attendant leaned into the
microphones and said:
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see, Tillie Tooter is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since a little Cuban boy came ashore in Miami has one
unassuming person assumed so much attention in South Florida.
Friday, the woman who survived three days dangling between
Interstate 595 and the swamp below, put on a show for the media.
When she finished a half-hour later, a room made hot by dozens of
jaded journalists burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter's life-and-death adventure began shortly before 3 a.m.
Saturday. She walked out of her apartment that morning, beginning
what should have been a 15-minute jaunt to Fort
Lauderdale/Hollywood International Airport to pick up her
granddaughter and the young woman's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   But Tooter never made it to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Heading east on I-595, one mile west of the airport, her Toyota
Tercel was hit from behind. The force of the crash sent Tooter's
car over a 3-foot concrete barrier and into a tangle of trees 40
feet below the roadway. The hit-and-run driver left the scene.
</P>
<P>
   At least two witnesses to the collision called 911 but
responding emergency crews failed to find evidence of the crash.
When those crews left, Tooter's ordeal began.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall, Tooter unbuckled her seat belt and flipped out
of the driver's seat into the passenger side of the car, she said.
When no one answered her screams for help, Tooter began to blare
the car horn with her foot. She switched the car's headlights on,
then off. Still, no one came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screamed, I ranted, I cursed, I pleaded and I begged,'' she
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Soon she began to take stock of the things that might keep her
alive. She found the Tercel's pantry nearly bare: A single cough
drop. A pack of gum. Some peppermints. And a button.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sucked on the button to produce moisture in my mouth,'' she
said. ``I had heard a long time ago that would help.''
</P>
<P>
   As she told her tale, Tooter surveyed the disbelieving, mostly
much younger faces of the reporters who had gathered around her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are all so young, but when you live to be 83 years old,
you learn a lot of things along the way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the crash, she caught rainwater in a steering
wheel cover. She also used socks to soak up the rain, then sucked
the moisture out of the socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little bit helped,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also sought ways to pass the time _ any distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sang songs,'' she said. ``Songs from the 40s and 50s, the
ones by the name bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reciting things that I had heard in my lifetime. I was
thinking of people who were here and people who are not still
here,'' Tooter said.
</P>
<P>
   But as the ordeal dragged on, Tooter said her resolve weakened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel there is nothing left for you in the world,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter worried that her granddaughter, Lori Simms, would feel
guilty because of the circumstances that led her grandmother to
that stretch of roadway. So Tooter scribbled a loving note on the
back of a Publix receipt. She said she figured if rescuers couldn't
find her in time, they might at least find the note someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my peace,'' she said. ``I thought I was dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty hours passed between the time Tooter's car tumbled over
the embankment and the Tuesday morning when a 15-year-old road
crewman peered over the highway's edge to see what had bent back
the trees. Justin Vannelli found a woman alive and a friend for
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seen her leg,'' Vannelli told reporters at the same press
conference on Friday. ``She was trying to stick her arm out and I
told her to stay still.''
</P>
<P>
   Tooter said she yelled up to Vannelli, but the teenager said he
couldn't hear anything against the roar of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told her to hang on, that help was coming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in the hospital, the hero met the rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I embarrassed him,'' Tooter said. ``I kissed him, not
once, but twice. I love him forever. He saved my life. I'm here
because of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vannelli said he is just the type of person who helps others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm real happy she is all right,'' Vannelli said.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked Tooter how she felt, she responded:
``About what?''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital lists her in fair condition. There was no date set
for Tooter's release, a hospital spokeswoman said. Tooter is
receiving fluids intravenously, but not other medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm itching all over, I'm black and blue, but I'm here,''
Tooter said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Florida Highway Patrol spokesman Lt. John Bagnardi
said the department has a ``decent lead'' on the hit-and-run
driver. Investigators impounded the car of a driver who claimed to
have been in a single-car wreck that night, just east of where
Tooter was found. That driver's name was not immediately released
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Simms, Tooter's daughter, is angry that no one returned to
recheck the bridge, particularly after her family reported that
Tooter disappeared driving to the airport. I-595 was her obvious
route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who to be upset with _ the (Florida) Highway
Patrol, the fire department, whoever,'' she said. ``I realize that
in the spot she was in she was difficult to see, but when you get
all of those cell phone calls coming in, you have to keep
looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Tooter, though, places the blame on the other driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hurt that anybody could do anything like that and
leave,'' she said. ``I hope he gets what he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her demolished car, Tooter won't have to walk home from
the hospital. On Friday, a Toyota distributorship gave her a new
Corolla and a Boca Raton company donated something she could have
used a week earlier: A voice-activated global positioning system
that would have allowed her to call for help without a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
