<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  PROGRESS IS SEEN IN TALKS AS PHONE STRIKE CONTINUES
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiators for more than 86,000 striking telephone workers and
Verizon Communications reached tentative agreement on several
critical issues, but an overall settlement of the 13-day walkout
remained bogged down in the details.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon agreed to move less than 1 percent of its employees each
year to other places, and it broadened an agreement to organize
employees of Verizon's wireless division, people close to the talks
said.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP STOCKS EXTEND THEIR RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor stocks extended their recent rally. The
Philadelphia Semiconductor Index rose 2.1 percent, bringing its
six-day gain to 20 percent. It is still down 10 percent since
mid-July. Still, losses elsewhere sent the Nasdaq composite index
down 10.53 points, or 0.3 percent, to 3,930.34. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index lost 4.35 points, to 1,491.72. The Dow Jones
industrial average declined 9.16 points, to 11,046.48.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY SOUGHT IN NASDAQ PLAN REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Two members of Congress who oversee the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Sen. Phil Gramm and Rep. Thomas Bliley, have asked the
commission to delay its review of a plan that is intended to give
investors more information about the way Nasdaq stocks are traded,
and fairer prices.
</P>
<P>
   HARCOURT PLANS AN ONLINE COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt General will formally apply on Monday for approval to
operate an online college. The educational publisher is trying to
join a handful of private companies offering college-level courses
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH CARE COMPANIES HEARTENED
</P>
<P>
   Heartened by a federal court victory in Philadelphia last week
in the managed-care wars, lawyers for several large
health-insurance companies are seeking to consolidate a slew of
lawsuits accusing managed-care companies of misleading their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. TRADE DEFICIT CLIMBS TO RECORD
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade deficit widened to a record $30.6 billion in June
as the appetite for foreign crude oil increased even as prices were
the highest in nearly 10 years. The deficit expanded from a revised
$30.3 billion in May, the Commerce Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   UNION PUTS FIRESTONE ON NOTICE
</P>
<P>
   The United Steelworkers of America said it had issued a strike
notice to Firestone, posing another potential burden for the tire
maker, which is already conducting a huge tire recall. The union
said contract extension agreements, covering more than 8,000
workers at nine plants, would expire in 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   BIDDING WAR SEEN FOR SEAGRAM UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Diageo of Britain, the world's leading liquor company, and
Pernod Ricard of France said they would team up to compete for the
wine and spirits business of Seagram. The move is likely to start a
bidding war with Allied Domecq, the No. 2 liquor concern, that
could push the price toward $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   INSURERS AGREE TO $1.2 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   American International Group, one of the world's largest
insurers, agreed to acquire HSB Group, parent of Hartford Steam
Boiler Inspection and Insurance Co., for about $1.2 billion in
stock. The deal will bolster AIG's range of products by adding
several specialty insurance lines.
</P>
<P>
   QXL TO BUY RIVAL FOR $256.5 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   The British Internet auctioneer QXL agreed to buy a German
rival, Ricardo.de, although it lowered its original offer by nearly
three-quarters, to 171 million pounds, or $256.5 million, after
learning that Ricardo's fourth-quarter revenue had declined
sharply.
</P>
</TEXT>
