<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS IN PHONE TALKS, BUT NO OVERALL ACCORD YET 
</HEADLINE>
  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiators for more than 86,000 striking telephone workers and
Verizon Communications reached tentative agreements on several
critical issues Friday, but an overall settlement to the 13-day
walkout remained bogged down in details.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of America,
and Lawrence T. Babbio Jr., Verizon's president and co-chairman,
worked through the early morning hours and into the day in a
bargaining session that left both men and their associates
weary-eyed yet satisfied, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Bahr and Babbio agreed on were limits to the
movement of work resulting from the merger of Bell Atlantic and the
GTE Corp., which created Verizon, and the broadening of an
agreement to organize employees of Verizon's wireless division, the
people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon agreed to move less than 1 percent of its employees each
year to other places using criteria based on the geographical
location of the workers and not the net total of its work force _
an important concession to one union demand, people close to the
talks said.
</P>
<P>
   And a tentative agreement reached last week that would make the
organizing of wireless workers easier in the 12-state region
affected by the strike would also potentially ease the organizing
of several hundred employees in Verizon Wireless retail stores,
according to people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Verizon and the unions reached broad agreement on some
important issues, it seemed late Friday that the minutiae of a deal
was slowing negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of progress has been made, but there is a consensus
process that needs to be carried out for a comprehensive agreement
to be reached,'' said Jeff Miller, a spokesman for the
communications workers' union, which represents about 72,000
striking employees.
</P>
<P>
   Before the strike is settled, about 35 people on the bargaining
committee of the communications workers' union need to sign off on
high-level negotiators' progress. And the International Brotherhood
of Electrical Workers, which represents more than 14,000 workers,
needs to ratify its own agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Both unions could reach an agreement with Verizon at different
times, possibly prolonging the strike for some workers, although
this is unlikely, representatives from both unions said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Verizon attempted to deal with with delays in
repairing and installing telephone service and with vandalism that
has interrupted phone service for thousands of Verizon customers
since the strike began. In addition, hundreds of thousands of
consumers were inconvenienced on Friday by a technical failure at
Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   About 11:35 p.m. Thursday, a complex piece of communications
equipment that helps connect Verizon's local network to the
long-distance systems of other companies failed at a Verizon site
in Rochelle Park, N.J. Until about 12:20 p.m. on Friday, several
hundred thousand of Verizon's local phone customers in New Jersey,
mostly in Bergen County, but also in Passaic County, were unable to
make long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of AT&AMP;T's wireless phone subscribers, in New
Jersey and in parts of New York City, suffered a more severe
problem: the inability to make any calls at all. In the Northeast,
AT&AMP;T uses Verizon's land-based communications network to link the
various antennas used for wireless calls. The Rochelle Park
failure, which began in a circuit card that controls complicated
timing sequences, disrupted AT&AMP;T's wireless system.
</P>
<P>
   A Verizon spokesman said that no unionized workers were in the
Rochelle Park site at the time of the failure and that the problems
were technical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
