<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NASDAQ-PRICE-DATA-NYT     08-18 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-PRICE-DATA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAY SOUGHT IN REVIEW OF PLAN TO GIVE INVESTORS MORE NASDAQ PRICE
DATA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and Rep. Thomas J. Bliley Jr., R-Va.,
have asked the Securities and Exchange Commission to delay its
review of a plan intended to give investors more information about
Nasdaq stocks and trades at the best available prices.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the SEC on Thursday, Gramm and Bliley, who are
chairmen of committees that oversee the SEC, asked the commission
to add 30 days to a comment period now set to expire Aug. 30. At
issue is a proposal to combine price quotes for stocks from
different trading systems into one ``supermontage'' on the Nasdaq.
Under SEC rules, the commission can approve the proposal any time
after the comment period expires.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers, which runs
Nasdaq, says the new system would enable investors to make sure
they are getting the best price when they buy and sell stocks. But
electronic communications networks, like Instinet, which directly
match buyers and sellers of Nasdaq stocks, argue that the proposal
will make Nasdaq both a regulator and a competitor of electronic
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues raised by this proposal are significant and must be
considered and addressed only with the greatest of care,'' Gramm
and Bliley wrote to Arthur Levitt, the SEC chairman. ``Market
participants, investors, regulatory agencies and Congress must all
have adequate time to review these proposals, consult and evaluate
their implications.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter does not take a position on the merits of the
supermontage proposal itself. A spokesman for Bliley said he had
not yet decided whether to support or oppose the changes. Bliley is
``concerned that we not move in to implement too quickly such a new
idea that will affect our markets,'' the spokesman said. ``There's
certainly not consensus on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the supermontage proposal, electronic networks and market
makers, which are brokerage firms that buy and sell shares from
investors, would be encouraged to send their orders to buy and sell
stocks to a central server maintained by Nasdaq. (Electronic
networks make money by charging a small per-share fee to match
investors directly; market makers profit on the difference between
the bid and offer price on a trade.) Investors would be able to see
the aggregate of all buy and sell orders at both the best bid and
offer prices and two ``price levels'' above and below the best bid
and offer.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if market makers and electronic networks have
collectively offered to buy 10,000 shares of Cisco at $65 and sell
12,000 shares at $65.05, investors would be able to see the entire
pool of orders on the supermontage. Investors would also be able to
see the orders at the next-lowest offer and next-highest bid, as
well as the third-highest bid and third-lowest offer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the supermontage proposal would essentially end the
difference between limit orders and quotes, which are treated
differently under the current Nasdaq system. That means if an
investor wanted to buy 15,000 shares of Cisco with a limit of
$65.05, and 12,000 shares were available at that price, the
investor would buy the available shares and have the new highest
bid price, for 3,000 shares at $65.05.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq argues that the supermontage proposal will simplify
and improve its current system, which is a hodgepodge of quotes,
limit orders and prices that are sometimes out of date. The
proposal will also give investors a better sense of the total buy
and sell interest, or liquidity, available from all market
participants, Nasdaq says.
</P>
<P>
   But electronic networks, which account for a rapidly growing
share of the Nasdaq's volume, say that the proposal essentially
turns Nasdaq into a competitor that is biased against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Nasdaq might be positioning this otherwise,'' said
Douglas Atkins, chief executive of Instinet, the largest electronic
network, ``this fundamentally changes Nasdaq's role in the
marketplace, creates a competitor to the institutions that they
regulate and creates concerns for investors.'' Instinet is a unit
of Reuters Group PLC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
