<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6168 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-EBAY-CONSUMERS-$ADV20     08-18 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-CONSUMERS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF A TRANSACTION GOES SOUR, WHERE DO YOU TURN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EBAY-POWERSELLERS) 
(For release Sunday, August 20) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The diamond advertised by ``mrwatch'' on eBay was precisely what
Robert and Teri La Plant wanted.
</P>
<P>
   A 1.41 carat marquise-cut diamond that was of good quality and
could be used to upgrade her old engagement ring for their 10th
wedding anniversary last September. They were told by mrwatch, a
seller of estate jewelry, that the diamond had not been
artificially enhanced and, though it had a small flaw, it was
described as not visible to the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   The La Plants checked mrwatch's feedback rating, which had more
than 600 positive responses, zero neutral comments and one negative
comment. So they felt that mrwatch, who is now an eBay ``power
seller'' _ one who has achieved certain levels of sales and service
_ would be a safe bet. For reassurance, they checked eBay's
insurance and fraud policies. EBay insures an item for up to $175
($200, less a $25 deductible), but La Plant was pleased to find
that the company pledged to remove sellers involved in cases in
which insurance was paid out.
</P>
<P>
   He was soon disappointed. When his $2,950 purchase disintegrated
into finger-pointing over who was responsible for a chip in the
diamond, La Plant said, he received no support from eBay. Even
today, he added, the seller, despite an insurance payment in the
case, has never been removed or suspended.
</P>
<P>
   La Plant, who lives in the Houston area, is trying to organize a
class action suit against eBay, contending that it failed to act
against fraud, particularly when it comes to big sellers. Ebay is
currently facing a class action lawsuit in California that contends
that it failed to act against sale of fake sports memorabilia
despite years of warnings. The suit contends that designations like
``power seller'' give buyers a false sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chesnut, associate general counsel for eBay, said the
company has several services to protect buyers. Three were in place
at the time of La Plant's purchase _ the feedback system providing
buyer comments about transactions, an escrow service to hold funds
until deals are successfully concluded and the insurance policy,
which is free.
</P>
<P>
   But, Chesnut said, eBay does not become directly involved in
trying to resolve such situations. Instead, when fraud is
suspected, he said, eBay tries to facilitate notification of law
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Chesnut disputed La Plant's accusation that the site goes easy
on power sellers, noting that he personally had suspended dozens of
such sellers in the last year. Mrwatch was not suspended _ although
La Plant said he was told in an e-mail message that action would be
taken if a claim were paid _ because mrwatch has a high approval
rating, more than 1,800 positive responses and only 8 negatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should eBay jump in and say, `We are not going to let you do
business on our Web site because your satisfaction rate is 99
percent'?'' Chesnut asked, adding, ``We're not in a good position
to evaluate in a singular instance who's right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   La Plant said he found a chip on the diamond immediately after
receiving it by UPS and, within an hour, took it to a jeweler for a
professional assessment.
</P>
<P>
   La Plant returned the diamond and asked for a refund. In
response, mrwatch replied that there was nothing wrong with the
diamond when it was shipped and accused him of damaging the
diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Al Bagon, who, along with his wife Judy, trades on eBay as
mrwatch, said, ``we've done nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bagons, the diamond went out with an appraisal
verifying its quality. They speculated that La Plant received the
diamond, thought he overpaid and then either tried to switch the
diamond or chipped it himself so he get a refund.
</P>
<P>
   In response, La Plant said the appraisal was a year and a half
old.
</P>
<P>
   The La Plant dispute is one of many about sales on eBay. But
most involve far less money, and the company has regularly said
that less than 1 percent of sales on its site involve fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Other disappointed customers are more philosophical. Shelley
Sangmaster, of Rodeo, Calif., said putting much faith in merchant
ratings might be misguided. She said she bought three autographed
business cards for about $430 from a highly rated site but never
received them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of consider it gambling,'' she said. ``Generally, I
stick to things that aren't more than $25. Then, if it doesn't show
up, oh well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
