<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GINGRICH-WEDDING-0819     08-18 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-WEDDING-0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GINGRICH, BISEK WED IN NIGHTTIME CEREMONY BEFORE FAMILY, FRIENDS
 &HT;    Moving in both (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich was married
Friday night to Calista Bisek, the congressional secretary with
whom he has been romantically involved for the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding, Gingrich's third and Bisek's first, took place in
front of 150 guests at the Morrison House, a small, expensive and
somewhat secluded hotel in Alexandria's historic Old Town district.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, in black-tie and tails, beamed broadly as soon as he
saw the blonde bride being escorted by her father to the altar
where the Rev. James Ford, the former chaplain of the U.S. House of
Representatives married them.
</P>
<P>
   Bisek admitted in a court deposition a year ago that she and
Gingrich had been having an affair since November 1993, more than a
year before he engineered the first Republican takeover of the
House since the 1950s and became speaker.
</P>
<P>
   She was deposed by lawyers for Gingrich's second wife, Marianne.
Gingrich filed for divorce from Marianne Gingrich on July 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But with the state flags of Georgia and Wisconsin, Bisek's home
state, flying over the hotel beside the U.S. flag and a string
quintet playing Pachebel's Canon in D, Gingrich and his new bride
seemed radiantly happy, making their separate ways down a curving
set of steps at the hotel's entrance and into a nearby tent.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel officials said the former speaker ``just beamed'' when
Bisek and her father, Alfonse Bisek, entered the tent.
</P>
<P>
   The bride wore a white strapless gown with a short train and
carried white roses. Her bride's maids wore black gowns and carried
bouquets of red roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those roses are red. I'm a biologist and I know,'' said Carla
Fehr, one of several Old Town residents who watched the wedding
from behind police lines, along with journalists.
</P>
<P>
   A soprano sang Ave Maria and The Lord's Prayer, and guests _
primarily family and friends _ sang Ode to Joy during the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda McKeon, general manager of the Morrison House, said
Gingrich had reserved the entire hotel, which has 43 rooms and
suites that range from $180 to $500 a night, as well as the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   After the wedding, guests dined on filet mignon and Alaskan
salmon, which was grilled according to a recipe provided by Sen.
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska. Then they returned to the tent for dancing.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Nesmith's E-mail address is: jeffn(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.morrisonhouse.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
