<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS AND VIEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's sultry news-and-views edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   News: The Baltimore Orioles may be shopping for a new general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Views: OK, people, let's all get on the same page. No more
public lynchings of Dodgers G.M. Kevin Malone. From now on,
everyone agrees that the signing of Carlos Perez to a three-year
contract was a brilliant move, and we'd make the Charles
Johnson-for-Todd Hundley trade all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Heretofore, Malone is a genius who is not being provided all the
resources necessary to bring his dream of a dynasty to Los Angeles,
because the Foxies got in the way of his hiring the man he really
wanted as manager, and has since saddled him with a movie producer
as the new CEO when, naturally, it should have been Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Foxies did get in his way on the manager issue,
but only after The Sheriff sent a much-publicized posse after
Felipe Alou and failed to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Angelos and Kevin Malone. It just rolls off your tongue.
Send letters of support to Camden Yards, c/o P. Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   News: Malone says Davey Johnson is safe for the balance of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Views: That's sort of like the executioner telling the death row
prisoner that the electric chair will be fixed tomorrow. It's still
going to happen. All it means is that Johnson gets to suffer
through September like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm Bob Daly, I check the September gate receipts against
past years, because that will be a true assessment whether the fan
base is tuning out.
</P>
<P>
   News: Media experts begin making lists of replacement candidates
for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Views: The first thing everyone needs to consider is that six
other Major League Baseball teams are currently managed by an
ex-Dodger, a fact of life that ranks high on the list of things
that bother fans.
</P>
<P>
   Alphabetically, that includes Dusty Baker (Giants), Phil Garner
(Tigers), Davey Lopes (Brewers), Johnny Oates (Rangers), Mike
Scioscia (Angels) and Bobby Valentine (Mets). Charlie Manuel
(Indians) also spent a little time in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Heres's one man's handicap as things stand at the moment, with
the standings as they are and Malone in charge:
</P>
<P>
   1. Felipe Alou, 5-2. Malone still considers him family and he
would love to finish what he started two years ago. Alou isn't
likely to miss a second chance to leave the Expos, and the team
probably could better use the money they're paying him.
</P>
<P>
   2, Baker, 3-1. The popular choice. Daly is enough of a fan to
offer him everything to take the job. But I just don't see the
Giants letting Baker get away if he wins the division.
</P>
<P>
   3. Kevin Kennedy, 7-2. Malone's second choice before the Foxies
told him to hire Johnson. He's available, assuming he wants to
leave his cushy job at Fox.
</P>
<P>
   4. Valentine, 6-1. He could become a candidate if Baker says no
and Daly takes the decision out of Malone's hand. Tommy Lasorda's
support of the Mets manager could swing either way depending on who
gets to make the decision, Daly or Malone. Short of a World Series
title, Valentine isn't likely to stay with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   5. Scioscia, no line: He'd be a great choice, but he isn't
likely to return with Malone in charge, and I have a hard time
imagining Disney letting Fox talk to him when he's under contract
and underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up another issue: Shouldn't Disney step up and
improve Scioscia's contract after what he's done in his first year
as a manager?
</P>
<P>
   News: Dog days of August begin to have their sweltering impact
on the pennant races.
</P>
<P>
   Views: It's evident everywhere. Seattle's fine but young
pitching staff has hit a wall, allowing Oakland to draw closer. The
Red Sox pitching staff is already suffering, and they haven't even
begun a series of doubleheaders causes by early season rainouts.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona may have traded for Curt Schilling, but its bullpen is a
mess, and the Cardinals have more questions than answers about
their starting pitching. A fast start and the lack of anyone else
in the N.L. Central with a winning record has kept them on top.
</P>
<P>
   Listmania continues. A.L. postseason handicap:
</P>
<P>
   1. New York, even money. Until someone better steps up, the
Yankees remain the team to beat. The fact they've separated from
Boston and Toronto despite the problems of David Cone and Orlando
Hernandez is more proof of their baseball-best depth.
</P>
<P>
   2. Seattle, 5-2. This is on the assumption that August will
eventually end and the Mariner pitchers will regroup. When in
doubt, go with pitching.
</P>
<P>
   3. Chicago, 3-1. Yes, that was former Dirtbag Rocky Biddle
winning his first major league game last week. Chicago needs to be
taken seriously, but their team defense is a negative and it's a
guess whether their young pitchers can deliver when it counts.
</P>
<P>
   4. Oakland, 9-2. One has to go with the A's in the wild card
race on the strength of better pitching and a deep lineup.
</P>
<P>
   5. Field. Boston (5-1) has Pedro Martinez and a prayer, which
could be enough. The Angels (6-1) need a healthy Troy Percival to
still be alive by September 1. The Indians and Blue Jays are off
the board and pretending.
</P>
<P>
   N.L. postseason handicap:
</P>
<P>
   1. Atlanta, 6-5. This Braves team isn't as good as past Braves
teams, but it might be good enough to deliver a world title if the
Yankees prove mortal.
</P>
<P>
   2. New York Mets, 8-5. Leading the wild card race by 4 games,
the Mets are the only team capable of challenging the Braves. Mike
Piazza is having a MVP year and there's no holes in the lineup. In
a close series, I have to believe Valentine will overmanage.
</P>
<P>
   3. San Francisco, 3-1. Quick, name a Giants starter other than
Shawn Estes. Baker's handling of a pitching staff that's neither
deep nor well-known has been terrific, and Barry Bonds is having a
MVP year. The X factor.
</P>
<P>
   4. St. Louis, 8-1. The Cards never know one day from the next
what kind of effort they'll get from their pitchers. Hitting has
taken them this far, but it's hard to imagine them beating a team
with better pitching, with or without Mark MGwire.
</P>
<P>
   5. Field. Arizona's (10-1) come unwrapped, with the vets tired
of Buck Showalter and the team already wondering what players get
gassed after the season because of a lack of money. Dodgers? They
have all the chance of Ralph Nader. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
