<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOOTER FEVER IN EUROPE
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM DIEM  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A Parisienne and her companion walked around a red BMW
C1 parked on a sidewalk near Trinity Church. He leaned in to view
the speedometer, with a top marking of 120 kilometers an hour, or
about 70 mph, then fiddled with the windshield wiper. She stood
back, regarded the curved roof and nodded approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the minivan of scooters,'' she declared, summing up the
safe appearance of the relatively large scooter, which has a
windshield, rollover bars and safety belts.
</P>
<P>
   The C1 represents a new niche in two-wheel vehicles at a time
when scooters are hot. Sales of two-wheel motorized vehicles jumped
44 percent in Europe from 1995 to 1999, and although scooters are
not tallied separately, several manufacturers said they were
gaining faster than motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Scooters have a flat floor and an upright riding position;
motorcycles force riders to straddle the engine. In a nutshell,
riders can touch their knees together on scooters, and motorcycles
are generally more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers have not ignored scooters' new popularity. BMW
started selling the C1 in May, and Renault will introduce a line in
spring. They join Peugeot Motocycle, which has made scooters for 50
years, and Honda, which builds them in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers don't regard scooters as competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a car and a C1, or a big motorcycle for the road
and a C1 for the city,'' says Arvid Des Horts, BMW's marketing
director for the C1 in France.
</P>
<P>
   Scooters are popular, in part, because they can squirt through
traffic. ``Urban congestion is creating a great opportunity,'' said
Jacques Compagne, secretary-general of the Association des
Constructeurs Europeens de Motocycle, an industry group in
Brussels. ``It has become a market of middle managers who want to
get around.''
</P>
<P>
   Car drivers tend to choose scooters over motorcycles because of
their automatic transmissions and lower center of gravity. ``There
will always be a market of passion for the motorcycle,'' Des Horts
said. ``But the scooter is loved for its efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Renault wanted to get into the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``An important market is developing for urban mobility with
light two-wheelers,'' said Francois Rouvier, chief of commercial
projects for Renault Sport, the division handling the scooter
project. ``Our dealer network has forcefully and repeatedly asked
for our help in developing two-wheel products.''
</P>
<P>
   Benelli Spa, an Italian scooter company with about 6 percent of
the European market, will manufacture Renault's scooters. Renault
will provide new designs, suspensions and clean-engine technology.
</P>
<P>
   For carmakers, two-wheelers carry their brand names to young
people. In much of Europe, teen-agers without driver's licenses can
ride scooters of up to 50 cubic centimeters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of special series for young people,'' said
Isabelle Puzenat, a spokeswoman for Peugeot. ``The X-Team is in
red, white and blue. The Urban Black was all matte black, for them
to personalize.''
</P>
<P>
   While the youth market is relatively stable, more adults are
getting on board scooters. In many European countries, adults with
a car driver's license can drive a 125 cc scooter.
</P>
<P>
   Compagne, of the industry group, said the average age of a
two-wheel buyer was 40 last year, compared with 30 in 1990.
European sales of 50 cc scooters were down 2.3 percent last year,
Peugeot said, while sales of larger scooters were up 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BMW is content with the 125 cc engine in the C1, which it
introduced in May after 10 years of development, because it has the
widest possible market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a marriage of the automobile and the two-wheeler,'' Des
Horts said. Riders strap themselves into the seat with a four-point
safety belt. The windshield and roof that protect them from rain
are attached to rings of extruded aluminum that protect them in
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Germany, France and several other countries have
agreed that the C1's safety features mean that its drivers don't
need helmets. ``For women, it's especially nice to drive without a
helmet,'' said Christine Bellanger, a BMW dealer in Tours, France.
</P>
<P>
   She sold six C1s in the first two months, and says the no-helmet
provision ``is the fundamental argument, the most powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   The red C1 parked near the Paris church belongs to Edouard
Martin, a consultant in Paris who lives 22 miles away, in
Elancourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The round trip in my car takes two and a half hours,'' Martin
said. ``With the C1, I save an hour. I park in front of my office,
which saves more time and 1,700 francs a month,'' or about $250.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my clients are in and around Paris, and I gain an
average of 45 minutes a day on trips to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the C1 was noisy and relatively expensive at 44,000
francs, about $6,500, but he said he well understands the
trade-offs between two and four wheels: His consulting firm helps
companies manage their fleets of cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
