<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-HNS &LR;      08-18 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER _ Democratic presidential contender Al
Gore basked in the glow of his convention speech and wooed voters
in the nation's midsection Friday, as he embarked on a four-day
boat ride down the nation's most famous river.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, along with running mate Joseph Lieberman and their wives,
flew overnight from Los Angeles to the Midwest, where they
addressed a morning rally in La Crosse, Wis., before boarding a
Mississippi riverboat named the Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Before a sign-waving crowd of about 5,000 people, Gore repeated
many of the themes of his Thursday-night address at the Democratic
National Convention, including his vow to work for prescription
drug benefits for the elderly, managed health care reform and more
education funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of the United States have had enough,'' said the
vice president, his voice hoarse with exhaustion. ``We want these
changes, and we're going to the ballot box to get these changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Introduced by a chief proponent of campaign finance reform, Sen.
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., Gore also pledged to make cleansing the
political system of special-interest dollars a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Democracy must be saved from special interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said that the first measure he would send to Congress
would be the campaign-finance reform legislation sponsored by
Feingold and former GOP presidential contender John McCain, a
senator from Arizona. Among other things, that bill would regulate
``soft-money'' contributions to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   However, the last stop Gore and Lieberman made before leaving
Los Angeles was a high-dollar Democratic National Committee
fund-raiser hosted by such Hollywood stars as Barbra Streisand and
Whoopi Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was buoyed by the candidate's Thursday speech,
which received generally positive reviews and appeared to give him
at least a temporary bounce in overnight polls.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC poll of 500 likely voters had Gore picking up 5
percentage points to overtake Republican George W. Bush, 46 percent
to 43 percent. The poll had a margin of error of 4.4 percent. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A Voter.com-Battleground tracking poll of likely voters had
Gore still behind, 45 percent to 40 percent, but narrowing the gap
with Bush by six points. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Most candidates tend to get short-lived lifts in polls after
their party conventions, however. The real question is whether
Gore, who has trailed Bush most of the year, can stay competitive
with his Republican rival by Labor Day, when the glow of the summer
conventions dies down and the fall campaign begins in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   The 400-mile boat trip down the Mississippi is intended to
generate support in four swing states and provide attractive
photographs and television images for the Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The morning rally offered a slice of Americana, with a Mark
Twain look-alike and a barbershop chorus entertaining the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As the boat made its leisurely way down the wide river, the
Gores and Liebermans stood on the deck and waved to scattered
clumps of onlookers along the shores.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's eldest daughter, Karenna, wandered among the large pack
of journalists situated on the boat's bottom level. She was asked
about the prolonged kiss between her father and mother before his
convention speech, which provided grist for the morning talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people might think it was a bit racy, but I'm used to
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore offered nothing new in terms of policy during the day, even
though he led a discussion of health care reform on the deck of the
Mark Twain as it cruised down the river.
</P>
<P>
   The Liebermans broke away from the boat tour in the afternoon to
observe the Jewish Sabbath, which lasts from sundown Friday to
sundown Saturday. They planned to rejoin the tour this evening. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The trip is expected to end Monday in Mark Twain's birthplace
of Hannibal, Mo. The boat also will make stops in towns in Illinois
and Iowa, two other crucial states for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people who came to see the candidates in La Crosse
suggested that Gore had helped himself with his performance at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked hearing his views and where he was going rather than
the rah-rah pep talk,'' said Charise Boch, an undecided voter.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hauser, a middle-school history teacher and loyal Democrat,
said that before the speech he had been concerned that Gore was
faltering.
</P>
<P>
   ``But last night he reassured me he could run a good campaign,''
Hauser said. ``I liked the specifics on the issues. He told you
exactly what he was going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   David Weinrich, a 29-year-old college math professor who had
been leaning toward Green Party candidate Ralph Nader, said he
worried that Gore had abandoned liberal causes when he picked
Lieberman, a moderate senator from Connecticut, to be his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the speech erased those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with the liberal themes he touched on, things
like support for the environment, emphasizing working people over
corporations, and campaign finance reform,'' Weinrich said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were plenty of people in the crowd who didn't hear the
speech, which began shortly before 9 p.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Donell Kerns, who works at the local university, said she and
her husband don't watch television. So they came to the rally to
check out the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to hear him and get a sense of who he is,'' she
said.'' My sense is, he is more sincere and honest than Bush.
Midwesterners are big on sincerity.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
