<HEADLINE>
SPARKS' FIGGS SURVIVES ROLLER-COASTER YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif.  &UR; _ &LR;  To say that last year was difficult for
Ukari Figgs is an understatement. It was an emotional roller
coaster.
</P>
<P>
   In February she had to deal with the death of her grandmother,
who lived next door to the family home in Georgetown, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   In April she helped Purdue to the NCAA championship and was
picked by the Los Angeles Sparks in the third round of the WNBA
draft.
</P>
<P>
   In June she started 10 games before suffering an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   And in August one of her college teammates was killed in a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs persevered through her faith and support from her family.
She dealt with the losses in her young life the only way she knew
how.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to know that God has a plan for everything,''
said Figgs, who said her grandmother took her to church every
Sunday and her teammate and friend Tiffany Young was like a sister
on the tight-knit Purdue team. ``You can't dwell on them or
question them. It's not going to change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She is only 23 years old but has the maturity and poise of
someone much older.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs recovered from her injury and humbly accepted her role as
backup. But it became clear after Gordana Grubin was left
unprotected in the expansion draft as the top pick that Figgs would
have a bigger role to play this season on the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an important part of our team this year and going back
to last year (of) the players that we decided to protect during the
expansion draft, she was number one on our list,'' said Michael
Cooper, who took over as head coach following last season. ``I was
looking at it coming from a defensive perspective. Ukari is an
excellent defender.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgs was chosen most valuable player of the NCAA championship
after leading the Boilermakers to their first title last year. She
had high hopes coming to the Sparks, looking to duplicate the
effort. But she sprained her ankle in a double-overtime game
against the Minnesota Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   She was elated that Cooper was planning on starting her this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boosted my confidence that he had that much faith in me,''
said Figgs, who averaged 6.7 points and 4.0 assists in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are in the Western Conference finals, thanks in part
to Figgs. She's had a difficult role, trying to distribute the ball
among four capable scorers in Lisa Leslie, Mwadi Mabika, DeLisha
Milton and Tamecka Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of advantages, but there's some disadvantages
because there are so many scorers,'' Figgs said. ``It's a point
guard's dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
