</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-CANCER-ISSUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO CHALLENGES HILLARY CLINTON'S COMMITMENT TO CANCER
PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANANDAIGUA, N.Y. _ After a visit to the birthplace of the
women's suffrage movement, Rep. Rick Lazio challenged Hillary
Rodham Clinton on one of her core issues, women's health care,
sparking contention over which Senate candidate had done more for
breast cancer prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican candidate, has said all along that he
would court constituencies and speak on issues not normally
identified with Republicans, but his attack Friday showed an
aggressive attempt to seize an issue about which Clinton has been
vocal. It also illustrated the opportunity Lazio strategists see to
attract women voters, some of whom, according to recent polls, were
not backing Clinton as strongly as had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they have a record on education or health care, it's a
horrendous record of undermining women's health, particularly on
life-threatening diseases like breast cancer,'' Lazio told
reporters shortly after a visit to the Women's Rights National
Historic Park in Seneca Falls, where in 1848 the suffragist
Elizabeth Cady Stanton and other activists met to formulate the
foundation of the women's rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, on a statewide bus tour that also brought him to this
village, said Clinton fell short on advocating mammograms for the
early detection of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton's health care reform plan of 1993-94 did not
include provisions to allow women under 50 with no health insurance
and at higher risk of contracting the disease to receive the exams.
But Clinton's staff immediately replied that Lazio had overlooked
an amendment to the plan that did include such a provision. At the
time, the recommended age was a matter of dispute among doctors,
but by 1997 the American Cancer Society suggested women begin
receiving tests at 40.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in an interview with The New York Times last week
that in 1998 she pushed for legislation that would allow Medicare
patients 40 and older to receive the exams, a response to the
American Cancer Society's recommendations. The legislation passed
and was signed into law in February of that year.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio, who said he had supported legislation for several
years advocating the exams beginning at 40 or sooner, seized on
what he considered the discrepancy between Clinton's health care
proposal and her remarks in the interview as evidence that she was
not a strong advocate for the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between these two camps,'' Lazio said.
``I say what I mean. I can back up my speech, my comments, with the
truth, with the facts, with a record. What they say is always
suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign called Lazio's claims a ``joke'' and noted
that the National Breast Cancer Coalition, an advocacy group on the
issue, had honored Clinton this week for her work promoting breast
cancer prevention and treatment, one of several awards it has given
the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has received two awards from the organization in the last
year, a spokeswoman for the coalition said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who will New Yorkers believe, the National Breast Cancer
Coalition or Rick Lazio?'' said Howard Wolfson, Clinton's chief
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble highlighted a recurring theme for Lazio. He seeks
to emphasize his legislative record as an advantage over Clinton,
who has never held elected office, but who contends she has
functioned as a virtual senior adviser to President Clinton on
various bills.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio's legislative record has also provided Clinton and
Democrats a tool to use against him.
</P>
<P>
   When Lazio released an advertisement this week promoting his
record, Democrats, in Los Angeles for the national party
convention, held a news conference to denounce him and claim he had
taken too much credit for some bills.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and Democrats have disputed credit for the Breast and
Cervical Cancer Treatment Act, which would provide financing for
women too poor to afford insurance but earning too much to qualify
for government health care. The bill, which passed the House, is
awaiting action in the Senate. It has bipartisan sponsors,
including Lazio, but Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., has said Lazio
speaks as if he were the sole sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lazio called the bill one of his achievements on
women's issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
