<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMPAIGNS IN GORE'S HOME STATE 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARTLETT, Tenn. _ Determined to thwart a post-convention surge
by the Democrats, Gov. George W. Bush campaigned Friday in Vice
President Al Gore's home state, where he claimed that Gore's plea
for more time in office indicated that the Clinton-Gore
administration had not accomplished enough.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by running mate Dick Cheney and greeted by a noisy
throng of 10,000 people, Bush said, ``The size of this crowd tells
me this November, Texas and Tennessee are going to be in the
Bush-Cheney column.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cheney: ``This year we're going to follow the Sam Houston
strategy. We're going to carry Texas and Tennessee.'' Houston was
governor of both states, Cheney noted. He then took some partisan
jabs at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big changes are coming to Washington,'' he predicted.
``Starting next January, we're going to end this era of division
and distrust. We're going to change the tone in our nation's
capital, and we are going to restore honor and dignity to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Gore ``wants four more years of fingerpointing and
politicizing and blaming.'' He painted his opponent as ``a
candidate who will pit one group of people against another, a
candidate who will wage class warfare to get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's nomination acceptance speech amounted to ``a laundry list
of new promises, which I thought was an attempt to cover up old
failures,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gore displayed a lack of priorities, purpose and vision,
and ``as much as he tried to separate himself from the squandered
opportunities of his own administration, the vice president
reminded us of the fundamental choice in this election: Will we
prolong four more years of Clinton-Gore, or will we give America a
fresh start?''
</P>
<P>
   En route to Tennessee, Bush told reporters that Gore's remarks
Thursday left ``a lot of unanswered business from the last seven
years, like Medicare reform, Social Security reform, strengthening
the military. His speech was a tacit admission that they haven't
done a lot in terms of Medicare or Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Gore declared campaign finance reform as his top
priority, Bush said, ``My No. 1 agenda item will be strengthening
public schools.'' He added that Gore lacks credibility on the
campaign reform issue because of the incident in which Gore
solicited contributions at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Gore was only partially successful in distancing
himself from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he convinced me of is, sure, he's standing on his own two
feet. Having done that myself, I know what it's like to stand up in
front of the convention and say here's my view, here's my plan,
here's how I intend to lead,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized the timing of news leaks indicating that there
is another investigation of Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky
under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the timing of the announcement was unfair for Al
Gore. I did. I didn't appreciate that. And I don't know who leaked
it, but it was as we say in Texas, that wasn't right,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He equated it with a pre-election leak of an independent
counsel's report in the Iran-Contra arms-for-hostages scandal days
before his father sought re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody did the same thing to my dad about three days before
the election in 1992,'' he said. ``I didn't appreciate it then; I
don't appreciate it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair to the vice president that somebody
leak an internal memo or whatever was leaked, that would affect his
night. He needed to have his night free and clear, I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. appeals court judge said Friday he was the accidental
source of word that a new federal grand jury was probing Clinton
over his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement ``with apologies to all concerned,'' Judge
Richard Cudahy said he accidentally disclosed empanelment of the
grand jury during an interview about the work of independent
counsel Richard Ray. Cudahy is one of three judges who oversee
independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a NBC-Wall Street Journal poll that showed Gore
leading Bush was a one-day snapshot that doesn't tell the whole
story. ``I think we better take a deep breath and let everything
settle out, and I think you're going to get a feel for what it's
like around Labor Day,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Bush said he expects to make an issue of Gore's
spending proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a lot of spending promises, and it'll be an
interesting part of the fall campaign as we total up the amount of
money he's promised and the amount of money available,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bush will rally Dallas Republicans at Southern Methodist
University before traveling to Las Cruces, N.M., where he plans to
tout education policies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was campaigning in Texas, where he holds
significant leads over Gore in several polls, Bush said, ``I take
nothing for granted.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
