<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ATLANTA-HEAT-SMOG0819     08-18 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-HEAT-SMOG0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exposure to Atlanta heat and smog causing health concerns
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ 101 degrees. Cope with that.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the hottest day in Atlanta in five years, according
to the National Weather Service. The extreme heat caused the death
of a construction worker Thursday from hyperthermia and officials
are again issuing this warning: Stay indoors.
</P>
<P>
   And if the heat didn't get you, the dirty air probably did.
</P>
<P>
   As the air quality index stayed in the unhealthy ``Red Zone,''
metro Atlanta doctors reported an increase of patients complaining
of troubled breathing, red eyes and a ``catch in the throat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are acting like they have allergy symptoms but they have
no history of allergies,'' said Dr. Linnette Sells of Physicians
Immediate Med in Norcross. ``The ragweed pollen is not that bad yet
so it's probably the smog.''
</P>
<P>
   Sells says she also noticed more patients with sinus infections
and conductivities.
</P>
<P>
   Some pediatric lung and respiratory specialists reported an
increase of calls from worried parents as the bad air triggered
flare-ups of their child's asthma. Depending on the individual, an
asthmatic child could feel the effects of smoggier days within one
day to one week of the exposure.
</P>
<P>
   At Hughes Spalding Children's Hospital, Susan Thomas held her
2-year-old nephew, Tyrone Johnson, as he got a dose of fresh air
through a nebulizer.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said she tries to limit the boy's exposure to the
outdoors but some days seem worse than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep him in the house and under the AC,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Fulton County schools, teachers were advised to ``use
caution'' during recess and physical education classes due to the
extreme heat, humidity and smog. A memorandum sent to all grades
also reminded staff to closely monitor asthmatic children, give
ample time for students to drink water and to look for signs of
heat exhaustion and heat stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Ground level ozone is the primary ingredient of Atlanta's smog
that's created when automobile exhaust and power plant pollutants
react in hot, sunny weather. Various studies are finding it affects
children more than adults because the children's lungs are still
developing.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the hotter the temperature, the worse the air
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Most summer days in Atlanta mean air that's ``unhealthy for
sensitive groups.'' But when it climbs into the ``very unhealthy''
range as it did Thursday and the ``unhealthy'' range of Friday,
doctors advise it's best for everyone to limit their time outdoors
if possible. Wednesday was the worst concentration of smog the city
has created and felt since 1995, said Michael Chang, coordinator of
Georgia Tech's Center for Urban and Regional Ecology.
</P>
<P>
   Today's level was predicted to fall into the ``orange level,''
or unhealthy for sensitive groups.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can the bad smog days burn lungs, it can stress those
with bad hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects people differently. Some people hardly notice it,''
said Ron Methier, chief of the state Environmental Protection
Agency's Air Protection Branch. ``We're not saying it's to the
point of being dangerous and wear a gas mask. But we do advise if
you don't actually have to go outside, don't. We shouldn't have to
say that but that's the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and city officials also stress that residents should do
their part during smog season, particularly on the worst days.
</P>
<P>
   That means cut down on driving, combine errands, gas up your car
in the morning, not during the peak ozone of the afternoon and
early evening, and forgo mowing the lawn for a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shouldn't hurt to be a child and go out and play,''
said Dr. Leroy Graham, a pediatric lung specialist with Georgia
Pediatric Pulmonology Association of Atlanta. ``This smog season is
worse than last year, which was worse than the year before. We're
now looking at air that's going into unchartered territory. The
cumulative affect over time is very frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
