<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6216 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-18 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stalking Tiger not for Everyman
</P>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tiger. Tiger. Tiger. Tiger. Tiger. Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Tig-ARRRRRGH!
</P>
<P>
   Enough already, OK? Today, we shall attempt to spread the
applause around. Before the weekend, when Valhalla's hills will be
alive with the sound of Woods' music, let's pay token homage to the
chorus, the faceless Everyman PGA tourists who, despite fully
recognizing the abject futility of their mission, have adamantly
insisted upon their 15 minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Hayes, for example. And obviously Scott Dunlap. Bob May,
too. And good ol' Fred Funk, once the pride of the Shell Houston
Open. Bravo, fellas, for daring to tease the beast.
</P>
<P>
   Come Sunday, when there's another major tournament to be won and
Tiger Woods figures to be doing the winning, each of the
aforementioned will be relegated to forgotten-footnote status in
the files of the 82nd PGA Championship. After 36 holes, everything
appears set for the regular, business-as-usual conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els shot himself back into contention for another
second-place finish, and Woods did nothing Friday to raise the most
minuscule of concerns regarding his capacity to complete the first
U.S. Open-British Open-PGA trifecta. Save for an occasional flash
of temper _ there's a human being behind that mask _ he remains a
picture of poise and precision, so much so that it's almost boring.
</P>
<P>
   Almost. While perfection, Tiger-style, can get a tad tedious,
it's never boring.
</P>
<P>
   But John Patrick Hayes, whose father, ``Jumbo,'' was once the
Wisconsin state amateur champion, can at least tell his
grandchildren he briefly led the PGA and, more significantly, Tiger
by a whopping two swings.
</P>
<P>
   For almost an hour Friday afternoon, Hayes was alone atop the
field, although Tiger hadn't yet teed off. Be assured, however,
that J.P. was laboring under no delusions of grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect (Woods) will be ahead of me when the day is
over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Tiger was, leading the tournament by one stroke
over Dunlap, with Hayes, Funk and Davis Love III four to the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' inevitably leaving J.P. in his wake should take nothing
away from what the El Paso golfer (by way of his Appleton, Wis.,
birthplace) has had to surmount to get 7 under par _ he was minus-8
until an admittedly careless bogey on 18 _ in one of golf's four
benchmark tests of skill and courage.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger was a known commodity from roughly the age of 2, when he
beat Bob Hope in a putting contest on The Mike Douglas Show. Hayes,
rising from the opposite end of the celebrity/superstar spectrum,
had to go through Q-school four times and spend four years on the
Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Before this year, in which he has finally established a toehold
with a pair of top-three finishes and more than $700,000 in
earnings, his PGA Tour rankings have been 166th, 118th, 109th and
104th. At 35, he's competing in just his sixth major and has
survived a cut in same for only the second time. Meanwhile, Woods,
at 24, is halfway to winning his fifth.
</P>
<P>
   J.P., in short, is the anti-Tiger. Ditto Dunlap, who also led
Woods by a stroke in the middle of the round, then caught him
briefly when Woods bogeyed No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   May, in contrast, was a former child prodigy himself, having
also played in the Los Angeles Open at 16, the same as Tiger. May
would best Woods on Friday, 66 to 67, but golf is a four-day war of
grinding attrition, not a five-hour, go-for-broke sprint. And
nobody has the tunnel-visioned staying power of you know who.
</P>
<P>
   What Woods has done this summer is render irrelevant everyone
else's efforts. Even when you see a player of Love's pedigree stay
in close pursuit, it's easy to give him short shrift, too.
</P>
<P>
   When Tiger is front-running, his overwhelming tendency of late,
it's worse than when he's merely lurking. The others see Woods'
name atop the leader board, and more often than not, their
shoulders sag visibly. The lesser players lose hope altogether,
while the better ones begin to press, trying to squeeze a little
extra out of their games.
</P>
<P>
   Which often leads to fatal errors. Note Love's consecutive
bogeys at 17 and 18 after he had charged to 9 under. It's a vicious
circle, stalking Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woods pays no one else much, if any, heed. Should an
Els or a Love be chasing him, or if it's a Dunlap, a Hayes or
another of their anonymous ilk, it hardly seems to matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Tiger is too concerned about anyone else,''
Hayes admitted. ``You know, when he sits up here (on the interview
dais), nobody is asking him about the other players. It's pretty
much just Tiger. It's always just Tiger and the course.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right, you know. A goodly number of guys played some fine
golf Friday, but it's assumed only one of them played fine golf
that will still matter come Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many bookies,'' Dunlap said, ``will be taking
bets on Scott Dunlap tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
