   (NYT30) MOGADISHU, Somalia -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- SOMALIA-ARMS --
Somalis seem plain weary of the warlords who have caused much of
the factional fighting and who have failed in 12 peace conferences
over a decade to settle their differences. Some think that perhaps
the warlords would oppose any government, no matter what, seeing it
as impinging on their power. Mogadishu residents, surrounded by
ruins, are eager for a government. As one put it, ``We are against
anyone who is against peace.'' (Tyler Hicks/The New York Times)
