chrome Razor scooters, which go for about $100 a pop, have been
selling out at both Toys ``R'' Us and the Sharper Image, appealing
equally to superannuated kids and to the regular kind. With a
handful of other manufacturers and distributors jumping on the
Razorwagon, the devices have become a new form of transit for the
masses. (David Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 18, 2000 --
DEM-CONVENTION-DAYAFTER-- Years in the planning, a day in the
scrapping. As Al Gore made his way down the Mississippi River,
crews were busy Friday tearing down bunting and returning the site
of the Democratic National Convention to a sports arena. Laura
Smissaert, of Los Angeles, waits for her boyfriend following
Thursday night's activities on the floor of the convention. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times) FLOATER PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ORLANDO, Fla. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20
-- RETIRE-401-PLANS -- Of American workers eligible for a 401(k)
plan, about three-quarters are enrolled. But that still leaves
about 75 million Americans who are not participating in any
retirement savings program. In fact, experts say, most people
cannot afford not to contribute to the plans. Employees of
7-eleven, like Tammy Albright in Orlando, Fla., are automatically
enrolled in its 401(k) plan. Only those who want to opt out of
participation needed to lift a finger. (Todd Anderson/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
BIZ-ULTRA-TRAVEL -- In an age gilded by 10 years of prosperity,
there seems to be no shortage of affluent travelers who want to
cover as much prime territory as they can in the most expedient --
and most comfortable -- way possible. Intrav promotes its private
jet tours as a mix of high-end comfort, such as a Boeing 737 that
seats just 44 people, top, and exotic experiences like viewing wild
game in Africa, below. (Toni Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NORTH POLE -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- SCI-NORTH-POLE -- The
thick ice that has covered the Artic Ocean at the pole for the last
57 million years or so has turned to water, recent visitors there
reported Friday. At least for the time being, an ice-free patch of
ocean about a mile wide has opened at the very top of the world.
This photo, of opened patch, was taken by Malcolm C. McKenna, a
paleontologist at the American Museum of Natural History while
aboard a Russian icebreaker which was taking tourists on a polar
cruise from Spitsbergen, Norway. (Malcolm C. McKenna/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
BIZ-LOS-ANGELES-3 -- In Los Angeles' fashion district, for many of
those who work here, including some who have made fortunes, the
district reflects the essence of the American dream. It is a place
where recent immigrants can build successful businesses and new
lives in an environment not dissimilar to those found in many
developing countries. John DeCindis photographs models for
Directives West, a fashion consulting firm, at the California Mart
in Los Angeles' fashion district. (Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
BIZ-LOS-ANGELES-2 -- An 80-block jumble of prewar commercial
buildings, hastily constructed in downtown Los Angeles, is now home
to the city's thriving fashion district. The district, just
southeast of the center of downtown Los Angeles, was widely
perceived as dirty and dangerous five years ago, but it has since
blossomed. In the showroom of Betsee Isenberg clothing, Melissa
Cronkite writes up orders. (Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
BIZ-LOS-ANGELES-1 -- Just a short walk from the Staples Center,
where the Democrats, the news media and assorted demonstrators
spent the week playing out the politics of the Information Age. But
the thriving Los Angeles fashion district has more in common with
12th-century Baghdad than the California of the new millennium.
Santee Alley is a retail corridor in the bustling Los Angeles
fashion district, home to 5,000 companies employing 50,000 people
and taking in $8 billion a year in wholesale and retail sales.
(Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
MALE-BODIES -- Many remember when it was just women who were
obsessing over every square inch of their bodies. Now, men are
going to that place where women always were. In 1996, American men
underwent 690,361 cosmetic surgical procedures, including 217,083
hair transplant operations and 54,106 liposuction procedures. Many
men, in other words, seem to be suffering a crisis of identity
whose remedy is apparently to become cartoons. Fitness fanatics on
Jones Beach in Long Island, N.Y. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LACROSSE, Wisc. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- DEM-GORE-5 -- Having
raced east to catch the sunrise, Democrats Al Gore and Joseph
Lieberman shoved off from the banks of the Mississippi River on
Friday for a paddlewheel cruise meant to stir heartland excitement
for their freshly launched campaign. The riverboat Mark Twain,
right, heads down the Mississipi on Friday carrying Lieberman and
Gore. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
HOTEL-BUTLERY-SCHOOL -- While most poeple are puzzled by the notion
of a butler, in the last two years the service has taken off,
increasing occupancy rates and customer loyalty at finer hotels in
New York City. Other luxury hotels have started imitating it,
especially as the economy booms and people have more money than
time. At the St. Regis Hotel, butler Keiley Rea checks for dust
with white gloves, part of her normal room inspection after daily
room cleaning by maids. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEWPORT, R.I. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ILLEGAL-WORKERS-BOS --
Raids by the INS in Newport, R.I. have caused dozens of
undocumented workers to flee the state. But the raids have had
another effect, one that few had imagined. Illegal immigrants have
come out of hiding and banded together to protest what they called
``selective enforcement'' by the INS. David Quiroa, a U.S. resident
who emigrated from Guatemala, together with his wife Iris, are
helping to lobby Congress for general amnesty for illegal immigrant
Latinos. Quioa and his wfie Iris, with their children David, 4, and
Andre, 16 months in Newport. (Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   RETRANSMISSION TO CHANGE PHOTO NUMBER
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LACROSSE, Wisc. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- SUB-DEM-GORE-3 --
Democratic presidential candidate Vice President Al Gore greets
supporters before a riverboat, Friday. Gore and Lieberman began a
four day riverboat trip down the Mississippi River Friday. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- GORE-SOUTH -- As if Al
Gore didn't have enough problems in his native region, several
prominent Southern politicians of his own party have decided to
keep their distance from him as the general election campaign
begins. Gov. Jim Hodges of South Carolina left the convention
before Gore's speech Thursday night, saying he had to campaign for
a state senate candidate. Hodges, left, greets U.S. Special Trade
Representative to Latin America Buddy Mackay, of Ocala, Fla.,
during a meeting of the Florida delegation to the Democratic
National Convention, Wednesday. (Tony Ranze/The (Lakeland, Fla.)
Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MACMAHAN ISLAND, Maine -- Aug. 18, 2000 --
ISLAND-DESALINATE-BOS -- In the middle of water-rich New England,
bounded by an ocean landscape, Maine's islanders have spent 300
years worrying about having enough drinking water. The perfect,
obvious solution to MacMahan Island's problem was to transform sea
water into fresh water -- a method that has been shrugged off as a
mirage for 3,000 years. Superintendent Peter Schuerch in front of
the desalinization plant on the island that uses a ``reverse
osmosis'' unit, a model popular on Caribbean islands and cruise
ships. (Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- BIOTECH-STOCKS-BOS --
Genome Therapeutics Corp., a Waltham, Mass. biotechnology company
seeking capital, recently decided to take advantage of a sweet spot
in the market by offering extra shares to investors. The company
hopes to shake loose $46 million, seemingly ambitious for a company
that had reported losses for three years running. Genome
Therapeutics Corporation Production Scientist Katrina Kopcewicz
checks a Genetix colony plate with DNA at the GTC Sequencing
Center. (Suzuki Chitose/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LACROSSE, Wisc. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- DEM-GORE-4 --
Democratic presidential candidate Vice President Al Gore, bottom
second from left, flanked by his wife Tipper, left, running mate
Sen. Joseph Lieberman and his wife Hadassah, aboard the Mark Twain
riverboat at the start of a four day campaign swing down the
Mississippi River, Friday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-- At
Russia's suggestion, the Pentagon is coordinating with NATO to
offer three options for technical assistance in reaching the crew
of the sunken Russian submarine, Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Friday during a news conference at the Pentagon. (Justin
Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LACROSSE, Wisc. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- DEM-GORE-2 --
Democratic presidential candidate Vice President Al Gore, with his
wife Tipper, right, is joined by his running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman and his wife Hadassah before boarding the Mark Twain
Riverboat as they walk to a campaign rally at Riverside Park on
Friday. The rally precedes a four day riverboat trip down the
Mississippi River. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) OLD SAYBROOK, Conn. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- OED-IN-AMERICA-2
-- When the Oxford English Dictionary decided to open a North
American office this year to document the evolution of American
English from the thick of it, it engaged a young American
lexicographer with impeccable credentials who also happened to be
the author of a 288-page book on a certain inelegant word that
rhymes with duck. Some of Jesse Sheidlower's collection of research
books. (Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) OLD SAYBROOK, Conn. -- Aug. 18, 2000 --OED-IN-AMERICA-1
-- When the Oxford English Dictionary decided to open a North
American office this year to document the evolution of American
English from the thick of it, it engaged a young American
lexicographer with impeccable credentials who also happened to be
the author of a 288-page book on a certain inelegant word that
rhymes with duck. Jesse Sheidlower, in his office earlier this
month. (Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- CLINTONS-ANIMALS-BOS --
Dozens of retired veterans are serving their country again -- this
time armed with black pens and envelopes to take on the thousands
of letters sent to the White House each day. The mailroom duties
for residents of the Soldiers' and Airmen's Home include meeting
requests for birthday greetings and get-well cards. But one job is
theirs alone: answering letters sent to President Clinton's cat,
Socks, and dog, Buddy. Retired U.S. Navy Chief Allan H. Gordon
tends to the first cat's mail earlier this month. (Jonathan
Wiggs/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LACROSSE, Wisc. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- DEM-GORE --
Democratic presidential candidate Vice President Al Gore, with his
wife Tipper, is followed by his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman
and his Hadassah pass in front of the Mark Twain Riverboat as they
walk to a campaign rally at Riverside Park on Friday. The rally
precedes a four day riverboat trip down the Mississippi River.
(Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
