<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The following photos have been sent as part of tonight's New
York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 08/18/00.
</P>
<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive our photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) MOGADISHU, Somalia -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- SOMALIA-ARMS --
Somalis seem plain weary of the warlords who have caused much of
the factional fighting and who have failed in 12 peace conferences
over a decade to settle their differences. Some think that perhaps
the warlords would oppose any government, no matter what, seeing it
as impinging on their power. Mogadishu residents, surrounded by
ruins, are eager for a government. As one put it, ``We are against
anyone who is against peace.'' (Tyler Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
EBAY-POWERSELLERS-2 -- Andrew J. Waites from West Front Street in
Hattiesburg, Miss., jumped into e-commerce last year. Waites buys
job lots of clothing in Manhattan and sells the garments on eBay.
His company, Inventory Procurement Services, specializes in selling
shirts, jeans and dresses that retail shops want to get rid of,
usually because they want to make room for new styles and more
seasonable clothing. ``One real advantage of the online auction
sites,'' he says, ``is the ability to reduce expenses, especially
for marketing.'' Waites with a load of goods in Manhattan's Garment
District. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
BERNSTEIN-ALLIANCE-2 -- Founded in 1967, Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP;
Co., with 1,400 employees, is not a true investment bank. It does
not advise on mergers or serve as a lead underwriter on offerings.
Instead, Bernstein, based in Midtown Manhattan, focuses on managing
money -- and offering research to institutional investors, the fund
managers who pay for the reports by sending stock trades and
commissions to Bernstein's trading desk. Sallie Krawcheck is
research director at Bernstein. Analysts, seated from left, are
Graham Copley, Bill Pecoriello and Faye I. Landes. Standing are
Richard T. Evans, Toni Sacconaghi and Vadim Zlotnikov. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
BERNSTEIN-ALLIANCE-1 -- Founded in 1967, Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP;
Co., with 1,400 employees, is not a true investment bank. It does
not advise on mergers or serve as a lead underwriter on offerings.
Instead, Bernstein, based in Midtown Manhattan, focuses on managing
money -- and offering research to institutional investors, the fund
managers who pay for the reports by sending stock trades and
commissions to Bernstein's trading desk. Roger Hertog, president of
Bernstein, says the firm prides itself on its reports. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING -- Dr.
James E. Hansen, an influential expert on global warming who for
nearly 20 years has pressed countries to cut emissions of carbon
dioxide and other heat-trapping greenhouse gases now says the
emphasis on carbon dioxide may be misplaced. Instead, he and a team
of scientists have concluded that the quickest way to slow warming
is to cut other heat-trapping greenhouse gases first. Hansen, the
director of NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies, in his
office in Manhattan. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- LEE-TRIAL-DAUGHTER
-- Alberta Lee, 26, the daughter of Wen Ho Lee, the scientist
formerly with Los Alamos National Laboratory who is charged with
mishandling some of the country's most sensitive nuclear weapons
secrets. Alberta, a technical writer in San Francisco, and her
father's supporters believe he has been singled out by the
government because he is Chinese-American and want to use his case
to fight against discrimination. Lee in front of the United States
Courthouse in Albuquerque, N.M. (Steve Northup/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 20, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
EBAY-POWERSELLERS -- The real powers behind eBay's success are
those small operators -- the liquidators, wholesalers, small retail
shops and stay-at-home entrepreneurs -- that offer the bulk of
goods for sale on eBay, underpinning its entire business. Abit
Uygan, owner of Sun jewelry in Los Angeles, looking at ring, formed
a partnership with Nang Nguyen in Hershey, Pa., who bought a ring
from his store on eBay. A partnership has resulted in sales of 800
pieces of jewelry a month and the two men are now considering
taking the company public. (Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 20 --
RAZOR-SCOOTERS -- Since arriving from Hong Kong at Christmas, the
chrome Razor scooters, which go for about $100 a pop, have been
selling out at both Toys ``R'' Us and the Sharper Image, appealing
equally to superannuated kids and to the regular kind. With a
handful of other manufacturers and distributors jumping on the
Razorwagon, the devices have become a new form of transit for the
masses. (David Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 18, 2000 --
DEM-CONVENTION-DAYAFTER-- Years in the planning, a day in the
scrapping. As Al Gore made his way down the Mississippi River,
crews were busy Friday tearing down bunting and returning the site
of the Democratic National Convention to a sports arena. Laura
Smissaert, of Los Angeles, waits for her boyfriend following
Thursday night's activities on the floor of the convention. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times) FLOATER PHOTO
</P>
