<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A FINAL BIRDIE FOR BEAR? 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GLF-PGA, GLF-PGA-INJURY) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Near the 18th green, the sign on the
scoreboard read, ``37 Golden Years at the PGA. Thank you, Bear.''
And now the applause was surrounding the Golden Bear, 60-year-old
Jack Nicklaus, as he walked down the fairway on what he described
later as ``maybe my last hole in a major'' tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Taking off his cap, he waved, then he put the cap back on, took
his sand wedge and surveyed the 72 uphill yards to the flagstick on
the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   In the long sundown shadows streaking across the Valhalla Golf
Club course that he designed, a voice in the gallery yelled: ``Do
it. Do it.'' And as Nicklaus' ball soared high toward the
flagstick, several people yelled, ``Go in the hole.'' It almost
did, landing above the hole, spinning back and sliding past the cup
by about three feet for what loomed as a birdie 4 on the 542-yard
par-5 hole.
</P>
<P>
   Even louder cheers erupted now and when Nicklaus, his cap off,
walked across the front of the green, Tiger Woods slapped him five.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, a PGA official had announced the arrival of the
golfers at the 18th green, but now that official turned to the
crowd and said, ``I think Mr. Nicklaus just introduced himself,''
before introducing Woods and Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, when Woods holed a 15-foot birdie putt, Nicklaus
smiled, pointed his right forefinger at the 24-year-old U.S. Open
and British Open champion, then raised his right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   After Singh putted out, Nicklaus stood over his putt in his
familiar hunch, then knocked it in for his birdie, prompting an
even louder roar. He took off his cap, embraced his son Steve, who
was caddying for him, then walked over and shook hands with Woods,
Singh and their caddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great birdie, Jack,'' several voices shouted as he moved up
the slope through the gallery to the scorer's tent. ``Great
birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was. But it wasn't great enough to help him make the
36-hole cut in this 82nd Professional Golfers' Association
Championship, a title he won five times in accumulating 18 major
titles. He had shot a 1-under 71, but his two-round total of 148
apparently will miss the cut by at least one stroke when the second
round is completed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked later where that final birdie will rank among
his memories, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ranks one short of making the cut,'' he said. ``I needed
for it to go in for an eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his accomplishments, at 60 he still disliked not having
made the cut; he still retained the embers of the competitive fire
that earned him the stature of being the best golfer in history,
the golfer who set the standard that Woods aspires to.
</P>
<P>
   But after having watched Woods shoot 66-67, Nicklaus was as
gracious in talking about his heir apparent to the ``best golfer in
history'' title as he always was when he finished second in 19
majors. Asked if he had passed the torch to Woods here, he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was handed over long before this,'' Nicklaus said.
``What Tiger is doing right now, he's a better player than I was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
