A6229 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-18 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNLAP IS ENJOYING THE MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Scott Dunlap is perfectly cast for the role
he's playing this weekend at the PGA Championship. His bushy
eyebrows and bulbous nose evoke a character actor.
</P>
<P>
   If the stage was Hollywood, Dunlap would get the roles that once
belonged to Karl Malden. Seeing as how the setting is Valhalla Golf
Club, he'll gladly settle for acting the part once perfected on a
stage out west by Jack Fleck.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955 the lightly regarded Fleck denied Ben Hogan his fifth
U.S. Open title at San Francisco's Olympic Club with a three-shot
victory in an 18-hole playoff. Today, Dunlap will go head-to-head
with Tiger Woods, the Hogan of this era, in the third round of
golf's fourth major.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 24, shot a 5-under-par 67 to Dunlap's 68 on Friday to put
a sliver of daylight between himself and the 37-year-old Floridian,
with whom he started the day tied for the lead. In the bigger
picture, there's a chasm separating Woods, the No. 1-ranked golfer
in the world rankings, and Dunlap, who is No. 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has won more majors than I have made cuts,'' said Dunlap of
Woods, the defending champion here who is bidding to become the
first golfer since Hogan in 1953 to win three consecutive majors.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, the delightful journeyman, is bidding to make his first
PGA Tour title a major win in the manner of Jeff Sluman at the 1988
PGA Championship. He realizes it's a formidable role he is
undertaking, but, hey, somebody has to play it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to put yourself in a position to win before you can
win,'' said Dunlap, who has never finished higher than third on the
Tour. ``If you can forget it's a major and just go out and play,
who knows? You never know when you're ready to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, who turned 37 on Wednesday, had to overcome not only the
specter of Woods on Friday but also the ghost of his second-round
showing at last month's British Open. As he did here, Dunlap broke
from the gate fast at the Old Course in St. Andrews, opening with a
68 that was surpassed by only three golfers.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round he stumbled to a 78 and missed the cut. ``To
play like that at the British Open on Friday was a real bummer,''
said Dunlap, who could have been forgiven for wondering if he was
back in Scotland when he found himself staring at 12-foot putts to
save par on each of the first two holes of his second round here.
</P>
<P>
   He made a par at the par-5 second, which felt like a bogey
considering that six of the other nine players on the first tier of
the leaderboard birdied the hole. Just when the wheels on Dunlap's
bandwagon appeared to be wobbling, Dunlap steered his game back
into the fast lane with a snaking 35-foot birdie putt on the par-3
third hole. He had the elephantine crowds riding shotgun for the
rest of his five-birdie, one-bogey jaunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are eager to jump on the bandwagon,'' Dunlap said.
``I'm eager to keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   The inclination is to portray Dunlap as Everyman. It's not until
you glance at his 2000 record and see he has earned $795,028 in 21
events that it hits you that he is actually less like you and more
like the CEO way down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap's face definitely shows the wear and tear of a man who
had to go to South Africa and South America to find his game. It's
as weathered as an old suitcase, every line on his face a veritable
sticker attesting to the out-of-the-way places he has been.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap turned professional in 1985, after graduating from
Florida with a degree in finance, but didn't qualify to play a PGA
Tour event until 1992. By the time he gained his PGA Tour playing
privileges, in 1998, Woods already had won seven times on the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Before this week, Dunlap's greatest distinction, as he took
delight in describing, was a dubious one. ``I was the oldest
American still living with his parents,'' Dunlap said. ``Until I
was 31 years old my official residence was my folks' (house).''
</P>
<P>
   Not to suggest his 20s was a debt-ridden decade or anything, but
``MasterCard was sponsoring me on a number of occasions,
unbeknownst to them,'' Dunlap said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   He can afford to chuckle as he has left those lean times behind.
Without winning Dunlap has managed to collect $1,677, 703 in 109
PGA Tour events. That's more than Jack Nicklaus, who designed
Valhalla and missed the projected cut here by one stroke, earned in
his first six years as a professional despite winning 20
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap remembers watching the telecasts of golf's Grand Slams in
the 1970s and thinking the tournaments were over as soon as
Nicklaus took the lead. ``As it usually was, wasn't it?'' mused
Dunlap, who obviously appreciates why there are some people who
don't think he has a prayer against Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with majors is they are so much more important and
the better players relish those moments,'' Dunlap said. ``It's not
that their games are that much better; it is that they are so much
better in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why Tiger will be so extremely difficult to beat,
because, you know, that is what he lives for. He actually gets that
much better at that time and at that moment, much like Jack did.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap is going to go out today, anyway, and try to give the
performance of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be many bookies taking bets on Scott
Dunlap,'' he said and laughed, playing his role for all it's worth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
