 INVESTORS STILL UNFAZED BY PEOPLEPC  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ PeoplePC signed its biggest deal yet, but the
announcement's failure to boost the company's sagging stock price
could spell trouble for the San Francisco supplier of low-priced
computers.
</P>
<P>
   PeoplePC agreed to offer its computer and Internet service
packages for $23 per month to more than 2.5 million customers and
employees of Highmark Blue Cross Blue Shield, an insurer based in
Pittsburgh, Pa. PeoplePC's stock moved up 10 percent in Friday
morning trading, but closed at $6.81, the same price as Thursday's
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a significant win in terms of potential, but
financially, they're just not sound,'' said Anne Bui, a senior
analyst with International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   PeoplePC made its initial public offering at $10 a share
Wednesday and the price fell immediately, ending the day down 11
percent. Bui suggested that investors are uncomfortable with
PeoplePC's business model, which she said smacks of free PC and
dot-com companies that have already gone out of business. PeoplePC
sells its bundled computer and service packages at a very low
margin, and hopes to make a profit from commissions it earns when
its customers shop at selected e-tailers. However, PeoplePC hasn't
generated significant revenue from this channel so far, according
to the company's financial filings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business model of e-tail referrals isn't paying off,''
said Bui. The fact that PeoplePC doesn't expect to break even until
2003 probably dampened Wall Street's response to the announcement,
Bui added. ``Three years is a long time to wait for signs of making
money.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the San Francisco startup won press attention
when it signed agreements with Ford Motor Co., Delta Air Lines and
Singapore's largest trade union to provide workers with computer
systems that their employers would subsidize. Those deals give
PeoplePC access to more than 700,000 potential customers, but the
1-year-old company hasn't realized any revenue from them. Highmark
predicts that as many as 100,000 of its customers and employees
will take advantage of PeoplePC's offer. They should be able to
start placing orders by the end of September, a Highmark
spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
   After PeoplePC's IPO flopped Wednesday, some analysts suggested
that the problem was a lack of new, big agreement announcements.
Now that a big deal has arrived with little effect, PC Data senior
analyst Steve Koenig says that PeoplePC's whole plan of wiring the
masses through their employers may be suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reliance on big corporate deals is a little bit risky because
you're putting all your eggs in one basket,'' said Koenig. ``If
they could do more to reach into the consumer space, and
demonstrate that they can be more successful there, that might help
attract investors.''
</P>
<P>
   PeoplePC may also be overwhelmed by orders if too many of its
new potential customers sign up right away, Bui said.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike other computer suppliers, PeoplePC outsources
its equipment, Internet service and tech support to
more-established companies, which it hopes will allow it to meet
large volumes of orders.
</P>
<P>
   PeoplePC said it could not comment on the agreement with
Highmark, announced Thursday night, because it is still in the
``quiet period'' surrounding its IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Delta subsidize their employees' computer purchases,
reducing workers' monthly payments to $5-to-$12 per month over
three years. Highmark isn't helping its customers or employees buy
the computers. Its agreement with PeoplePC simply offers them a
better deal than they could get otherwise _ $2 less than what
individual customers pay. The agreements require customers to pay
monthly fees for three years. After that time, they can keep the
computer and pay for their own Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, PeoplePC made two new higher-end packages
available to both individual and business customers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
