 SAN FRANCISCO AIRPORT PLANS RESTAURANT UPGRADE  &HT;     By MICHAEL TAYLOR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There you are, at San Francisco International
Airport and _ surprise! _ your fight to London has been delayed.
It's lunchtime and you now have got time to kill. How about a
withered ham sandwich, washed down with a cup of some dank brown
liquid possibly resembling coffee?
</P>
<P>
   Well, airport eaters, the revolution has arrived. As you wait
for your flight at San Francisco's new international terminal _
scheduled to open sometime before the end of the year _ you will be
able to sit down at the chic new Restaurant Qi and Water Bar or one
of 17 other restaurants of local origin and actually eat something
worth remembering.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you would like to tuck into a three-course (``30
minutes, Guaranteed!'') lunch. You could order up a ``soft tofu and
shrimp terrine in Green Kimono, summer yellow tomato Jus and
avocado puree'' followed by ``saffron risotto, sauteed sea
scallop,'' with a ``julienne of spinach, dust of Parmesan and twist
of chili.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, after all that, pour me on that 747 and let me know when
we're on approach for Heathrow.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be a while before you get to try this new culinary
adventure. The new terminal's September 26 opening has been
postponed for at least six weeks because of construction troubles
and equipment installation delays. For the restaurant owners,
construction costs charged by the airport have tripled because of
the complexities of building in an airport. After a committee of
owners complained to Mayor Willie Brown, the Airport Commission
voted to reimburse the restaurateurs for the extra costs.
</P>
<P>
   When the terminal does open, San Francisco will be trying a
concept that is part of a new movement in U.S. airports: Instead of
giving travelers a motley collection of overpriced and
underwhelming snack bars, the new terminal will have 18
restaurants, all operated by local restaurateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a trend toward doing this,'' said Jordanna Smida,
associate editor of Airport Business, a trade magazine. ``And San
Francisco is definitely in the forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   Smida said airports in such cities as Chicago, Minneapolis,
Philadelphia and Pittsburgh have already installed locally operated
restaurants, but San Francisco airport officials say theirs is the
first to be entirely derived from local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, the Airport Commission selected Pacific
Gateway Partnerships _ a collaboration of airport-retail developer
Marketplace Development of Boston and the San Francisco retail
developer Reininga Corp. _ to start finding food businesses that
might like to set up shop at the new international terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Through a laborious selection process, involving a committee of
local ``hospitality industry'' experts, the airport's new
restaurateurs were culled from a list of more than 256 applicants
who clearly saw the advantage of having a captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a real desire on the part of the airport and the
city to make the restaurants represent the culinary diversity of
San Francisco,'' said airport spokeswoman Lisbet Sunshine,
explaining the motives behind the new venture. (Sunshine has since
left the airport for another job.) ``We didn't want to go with
chain-themed restaurants. We wanted to make them independently
owned.'' There is one chain, however _ Il Fornaio _ but it is based
in Corte Madera and most of its 22 restaurants are in California.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to convince Bay Area restaurateurs they should operate at
the airport, however, was tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a lot of fears,'' said Bob Weinberg, the president of
Marketplace Development. ``If your restaurant is out on a
concourse, you have to take your lettuce through a metal detector.
You don't normally do that on Union Street. And then you have to do
a 10-year background check on all employees, for security.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg said to further whittle down the list, ``every
restaurant we didn't know was visited by one or two (of our)
people. They looked at food quality and service, and at the end of
the visit they would introduce themselves and do an informal
kitchen sanitation inspection. At that point, we did a very fast
cut, and anybody we thought just couldn't handle it, like very
small restaurants or places with no management capacity to do this,
was dropped from the list.''
</P>
<P>
   When the list of prospective restaurants had been chopped to
110, Weinberg started meeting with their owners in small groups,
where he told them ``the good and bad news _ the long hours, the
demand for high quality,'' and explained some of the arcana that
fetch up in leases with the City and County of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Added Weinberg, ``I told them about all the positives _ no one's
going to open a restaurant across the street from you, your market
is likely to grow, and you're going to get a lot of publicity that
will benefit your other restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to get an initial doubter like George Chen, owner
of such hot San Francisco spots as Shanghai 1930 and Xanadu, to
investigate further.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought, `Why would I want to do that?''' Chen
said the other day. ``Airports are not generally known as a place
for fine food _ you hear about the $8 hot dog and the $6 beer.
 &LR; Nobody  &LR; wants to eat at airports.'' Chen also said he had little
interest in ``the potential bureaucracy one would have to deal with
in doing a restaurant in the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Chen made the final cut in the selection process,
Weinberg encouraged him to stay with it. ``After being selected I
did more research,'' Chen said. ``Now I look at this thing as kind
of revolutionary, something that fills a need.'' The result was his
Restaurant Qi and Water Bar, the anchor restaurant in the new
airport eating complex.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said the customer he looks forward to feeding is the
``first-class business traveler who's stuck at the airport a lot''
and has a flight to Asia at 1:30 or 2 in the morning. ``A lot of
these people have to check in at 11 or 11:30 (p.m.) and the last
thing they want to do when they get on these planes is have a meal.
They want to sleep.'' So Chen figures he will feed them, and the
airline will put them to bed. Just to make sure his customers don't
miss their planes after a post-prandial cognac or two, Chen will
have closed-circuit flight information screens in his restaurant's
bar.
</P>
<P>
   There will be three kinds of restaurants at the new terminal,
according to Lorri Vasquez, the airport's concessions czarina _
``fine dining,'' like Chen's restaurant, which means you can sit
down in an upscale place; bars; and ``quick serve.'' The airport
will have two ``food courts, which we're calling food collections,
because they are higher quality than you would normally find,''
Vasquez said. ``We'll have (a version of) Harbor Village and Osho.
These are not your typical food-court lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbor Village will be what the airport calls a ``quick-serve
version of the high-end Harbor Village'' restaurant in San
Francisco's Embarcadero Center. Osho is a spin-off from a
well-known Millbrae restaurant. The new terminal will also have
versions of such well-known Bay Area eateries as Harry Denton's,
Lori's Diner, Emporio Rulli, Andale Mexican Restaurant, Cafe Metro
and the Deli-Up Cafe of San Francisco's Potrero district.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant operators will lease their location for a ``minimum
annual guarantee,'' based on square footage or a percentage of
gross revenues, whichever is higher.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez said that because the airport wants the prices to be the
same as they are in comparable restaurants elsewhere in the city,
``we try to make (the leases) reasonable based on how much they
could afford. We really want these restaurants to provide high
quality at reasonable prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new airport restaurants will be required to stay
open 16 hours a day and Vasquez said the airport, in a concession
to the possibility that business may be slow for some restaurants,
is not charging restaurant owners for maintaining the common areas
around the restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Nidal Nazzal, owner of the Burger Joint, a restaurant under
construction at the new terminal, said that he will open for
business in mid-September despite the delays. He plans on serving
airport employees, construction workers and the occasional charter
flight passengers who are scheduled to come through starting in
early September.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Michael Taylor at  &LR; miket(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
