<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-APPEAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NAPSTER INITIATES APPEAL PROCESS  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Arguing that its members are not copyright
criminals, Napster Inc. on Friday formally asked a federal appeals
court to throw out a preliminary injunction against the popular
online music-swapping company.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining a legal brief filed minutes before a deadline set by
the U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco, Napster lawyers said
they believe a federal judge who issued the injunction
``misunderstood and misapplied'' previous court rulings and case
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our users are not liable,'' said Napster attorney Jonathan
Schiller. ``They are immune from liability under the Audio Home
Recording Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, he said, ``if they're not liable, we're not liable.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo, Calif., startup ignited a digital music
revolution by creating an easy-to-use software program that lets
Napster members share for free MP3-formatted songs stored on one
another's computer hard drives. Napster estimates about 22 million
people have used the program.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the widespread use of Napster will drain revenues, major
record labels represented by the Recording Industry Association of
America sued Napster for copyright infringement last December. The
RIAA contends a vast majority of the music being exchanged by
Napster members are illegal copies.
</P>
<P>
   In an oral ruling July 26, U.S. District Court Judge Marilyn
Hall Patel ordered Napster to halt the sharing of songs owned by
RIAA members. Two days later, and hours before the injunction would
have taken effect, the U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco
issued a stay.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court, finding there were precedent-setting legal
issues that had to be decided before the injunction took effect,
gave Napster lawyers until Friday to file their legal arguments
against Patel's order.
</P>
<P>
   Patel filed a 45-page written version of her ruling last week.
The judge rejected Napster's defense that a preliminary injunction,
to remain in effect until the copyright suit went to trial several
months later, would put Napster out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any destruction of Napster Inc. by a preliminary injunction is
speculative compared to the statistical evidence of massive,
unauthorized downloading and uploading of plaintiff's copyrighted
works, as many as 10,000 files per second,'' Patel wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has every reason to believe that, without a
preliminary injunction, these numbers will mushroom as Napster
users, and newcomers attracted by the publicity, scramble to obtain
as much free music as possible before trial.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schiller said Napster's appeal to the Appeals Court is based
on the assertion that Patel misapplied several instances of case
law, particularly the 1992 Audio Home Recording Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act protects all non-commercial copying by consumers of
digital and analog recordings,'' Schiller said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Rubin, a Chicago attorney who specializes in copyright,
trademark and entertainment law, said the landmark case could be
decided by the U.S. Supreme Court, although he expects ``Napster
will probably wind up on the losing end.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Rubin said that among several legal arguments the
defense will use, Napster will try to convince the appeals court to
focus on the individual acts by Napster members rather than the
cumulative effect of millions of people downloading songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the individual act is not copyright infringement, then you
can't argue that all of these people somehow are collectively
committing copyright infringement,'' Rubin said. ``Napster is
saying that if copying by our subscribers for their own home use is
not copyright infringement, how can we be contributing to copyright
infringement.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry has until September 8 to file its
response, and Napster would have until September 12 to file a
reply. A hearing before the Ninth Circuit judges will be scheduled
sometime after that date, but until then, Napster fans will be able
to download songs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
