<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-NYT     08-18 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWIN GYMNASTS ARE PUSHING TO COMPETE IN SYDNEY TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wis.)   By SELENA ROBERTS   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Just a month or so short of their 18th birthdays, and
newly introduced to the shaving-cream market, Paul and Morgan Hamm
are back to wearing matching clothes.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, when they were into OshKosh overalls and pajamas
with feet, their mom, Cecily, would dress her twin sons alike for
fun. But she always encouraged them to be individuals &UR;  &LR; and pursue
their own paths. Still, somewhere along the way, the Hamm twins
developed identical ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, both walked off the floor of the Fleet Center
after the men's preliminary round of the U.S. Olympic gymnastics
trials, each in red, white and blue warmups, and each closing in on
a trip to Sydney, Australia. Paul Hamm is in the better position of
the two to make the six-man team, which will be named after the
finals on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   By nailing his pommel-horse routine and high-bar performance
with a pair of 9.75 scores, he finished in second place behind
Blaine Wilson. The top four gymnasts, ranked by their combined
scores from the trials and July's nationals, earn a place on the
team. The fifth and sixth places on the team will be decided by a
selection committee through a more subjective process.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Morgan Hamm in a much more precarious position.
Entering the finals, he is sixth among the men, just ahead of
30-year-old John Roethlisberger, a two-time Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can John make the Olympic team just because he made the last
one? '' Olympic coach Peter Kormann said. ``No. He knows he has to
do well in the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Roethlisberger's career on the national team spans more than two
presidential terms. The Hamms aren't eligible to vote yet.
Roethlisberger wears a knee brace, has absorbed as many injuries as
a crash-test dummy, but is looking for one last Olympic team berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as prepared as I can be, and I've trained well, but it's
just not happening for me right now,'' a mystified Roethlisberger
said after several spills in the preliminaries. ``I can't explain
why I'm not hitting my routines. On the vault, I was fine, but I
got lost in the air and then I'm on my butt. On the high bar, I was
in perfect shape and then I ended up landing on my back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is. I mean I'm 30, but with the way I've
been practicing, it's not age. In that respect, that doesn't make
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hamms are newborns in comparison. For men gymnasts, maturing
into your 20s is an asset, as men often gain strength as they exit
from their teens. That makes the Hamms' arrival on this stage _
perhaps nudging out some older, more established gymnasts like
Roethlisberger _ even more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surprising how calm they are in competition,'' Peter
Kormann, the coach of the U.S. men's team, said. ``They look like
seasoned veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the peach fuzz, they are intense and focused, but not
blind to what the other is doing. After Morgan Hamm fell off the
pommel horse during preliminaries, one of the first people to
approach him was his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like, `You're strong, don't' get down,''' Morgan said.
``He really psyched me up. He got me going and was right there to
get me back on track. We want to motivate each other. We want the
other one to do well. That's the way it is with us.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no visible signs of a sibling rivalry. As if to
punctuate their normality, they entered an interview room Thursday
night looking like cast members off the set of a Doublemint
commercial, oozing wholesomeness, dripping Americana. It was a
scene made complete by a couple of quaint facts. They grew up in
Waukesha, Wis., with a father who was once an all-American diver
and a mother who makes candles.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the Hamm twins appear to be a pair of fresh faces to
light up the men's team, two similar soothing voices that come at
you in stereo. No twins have ever made a men's Olympic gymnastic
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like going through this with my twin,'' Morgan Hamm said.
``I think to be in the position we're in is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Even their enthusiasm is equal. As Morgan spoke, Paul finished
his sentence. But there are ways to tell them apart. In
competition, Paul is the more consistent one. In appearance, Morgan
is the one with the slight curve in the bridge of his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both want the same thing,'' Paul Hamm said. ``Right now,
Morgan is on the spot a little bit. He could get in or fall out. I
want to see him hit his routines when I'm watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I made it and he didn't, I'm sure he'd be happy for me, but
we want to do this together. That's what we're here for. That's our
goal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
