<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6343 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-CLEANUP-LADN     08-18 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-CLEANUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANUP CREWS SWEEP BACK INTO CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whew!
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people - from Los Angeles merchants and city
leaders to out-of-town reporters and Democratic officials -
breathed a collective sigh of relief Friday as workers tore down
the convention hall inside the Staples Center a day after the
Democratic National Convention ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank the Lord, it's over,'' said Jack Serna, manager of a
Winston Tires store across the street from the Staples Center that
was damaged in June by rioters after the Lakers won the NBA
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners and city officials had been waiting for this
week for months, many fearing that protests and negative publicity
might grip the city.
</P>
<P>
   But four days later, most are calling the convention a success
and are eager to return to business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went very well,'' said City Councilman Alex Padilla, who
also was a delegate at the convention. ``I talked to people this
last week from all over the country, and they were just blown away
with how great of a time they had here in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Staples Center on Friday, workers vaccuumed confetti,
tore up phone and electrical lines and hauled out materials from
the arena that, only a matter of hours before, was packed with
35,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   In the adjacent Convention Center, workers were dismantling news
organizations' work booths.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's a little bit of a letdown, just because now you
look around and the confetti's just slowly falling to the ground
and it's really over,'' said Staples Center communications director
Michael Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said it will take about 10 days for crews to fully clean up
and move out of the Convention Center and Staples Center. The next
two events scheduled for Staples Center are the Latin Grammy Awards
on Sept. 13 and Barbra Streisand's final two concerts on Sept. 20
and 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a nice feeling to go home,'' said Reuters News
Service cameraman Tipp McClure, who will head back to Washington,
D.C., this weekend after joining 15,000 journalists who converged
on Los Angeles for the convention. ``It's sort of a strange
euphoria when you pack everything up.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Avery of Virginia has been in Los Angeles for a month,
volunteering for the Democratic News Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here at the beginning, I was here during and I am here
after,'' she said, surveying the aftermath of the convention
Friday. ``And they pulled it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Green, director of communications for the DNC, stood
inside the arena and watched crews starting to dismantle the
massive stage below and makeshift television studios in the
skyboxes above.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an arduous process, but I think very successful, and
everyone just wants some time to relax,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Green will go home to Washington, D.C, next week, where she
already has decided what she will do first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleep,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2311EDT &QL; 
