A6345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-NYT &LR;      08-18 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS SHARES SPOTLIGHT, BUT LEAD IS HIS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN, GLF-PGA-INJURY) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tiger Woods did not mind sharing the spotlight
with Jack Nicklaus, but Woods wanted the lead for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Capped by a special moment on the 18th green, where Woods and
Nicklaus both made birdies, the second day of the PGA Championship
ended with Woods in a familiar position, at the top.
</P>
<P>
   While Nicklaus barely missed the cut and probably played his
last round of a PGA Championship, Woods continued his methodical
march toward what would be another historic victory.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, unlike what happened in the U.S. Open and the
British Open, when Woods ran away from the field, the pursuing pack
was not very far back.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was the clubhouse leader at 11 under par (133), holding a
1-stroke lead over Scott Dunlap when second-round play was
suspended by darkness with 11 players still on the course. Davis
Love III, the 1997 winner of the PGA Championship, was tied for
third place at 7 under par, with Fred Funk and J.P. Hayes. And
Nicklaus shot a 71 after an opening-round 77.
</P>
<P>
   So while it has been difficult to play quickly at Valhalla Golf
Club, with some of Thursday's rounds taking more than six hours, it
has not been difficult to make birdies. Perhaps Woods will
ultimately win his third consecutive major, and join Ben Hogan as
the only player to win three professional majors in one year.
</P>
<P>
   But many other players had legitimate reason to hope, and the
weekend had legitimate potential for drama.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a 5-under-par 67, after an opening-round 66, Woods
broke out of a first-round tie with Dunlap (10 under par), who shot
a 68 Friday after an opening-round 66.
</P>
<P>
   But the focus Friday was on Nicklaus and Woods, who were paired
in the first two rounds for the first time, and probably the last
time. Both players finished in style at No. 18, with Nicklaus
nearly making an eagle from the fairway before his tap-in birdie,
and Woods making a beautiful up-and-down birdie from a difficult
position in a green side bunker.
</P>
<P>
   After Woods' final 12-foot birdie putt disappeared into the
hole, Nicklaus smiled approvingly. And after Nicklaus made his
birdie, Woods did the same.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fitting ending to a memorable day, as the gallery
serenaded Nicklaus with affection from tee to green. For Nicklaus,
winner of 18 professional majors, including five PGA Championships,
it was a farewell. But for Woods, the tournament was only
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been quite a two days,'' said Woods, who can become the
first back-to-back winner of the PGA Championship since Denny Shute
in 1936 and 1937. ``I enjoyed playing with Jack and it was great
for me. Nobody even noticed what I was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with where I am because this golf course is very
demanding. You're faced with some difficult shots and some
difficult putts. Any time you shoot 11 under par after 36 holes at
a major, you should be leading.''
</P>
<P>
   When Woods won the U.S. Open by an astonishing 16 shots in June,
he led by six strokes at the halfway mark. When he won the British
Open in July by eight shots, he had a 3-stroke lead after two
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Woods is not entering the weekend with a lead
that looks insurmountable. Dunlap, a 37-year-old who has never won
on the PGA Tour, has been the surprise player of the tournament,
showing the moxie to stay in contention when most people are
waiting for him to fall back.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day tied with Woods at 6 under par, Dunlap nearly
kept pace with the world's No. 1 player, and he continued to make
huge putts.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap made a 35-foot birdie putt at No. 3, he made a 25-footer
for birdie at No. 10, and he almost made a 40-foot birdie putt for
eagle at No. 18, before settling for a tap-in birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Can a player who has never won on tour outplay Woods at a major?
Dunlap was eager to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger will be extremely difficult to beat because you know
that is what he lives for,'' said Dunlap of the pressure facing the
leaders this weekend. ``He actually gets better at that time, much
like Jack did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be many bookies tonight taking bets
on Scott Dunlap. I don't have anyone else's expectations to live up
to, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if anything in his past would prepare him for playing with
Woods in Saturday's final group, Dunlap said: ``No. You never know
when you're ready. At the end of 72 holes, you realize you didn't
choke, you didn't screw up, you won. Who knows? Maybe it will
happen this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Love reached 9 under par after a birdie at No. 16, but he
finished his day with costly bogeys at both No. 17 and No. 18, a
finish Love will regret if he ultimately loses by a shot or two.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of play has been somewhat regrettable already. It has
been very slow at times, particularly on Thursday, when some rounds
took more than six hours to complete. Players grumbled heavily,
unhappy about waiting as much as 10 or 15 minutes between shots.
</P>
<P>
   All four par-5 holes are reachable in two shots, so when players
reached the tee on a par-5 hole, there was often a group standing
in the fairway, waiting for the green to clear so that they could
hit their second shot.
</P>
<P>
   The deep rough, the long walks between some greens and tee
boxes, the humid weather and the severely undulating greens that
often left players with long putts, only added to the slow pace.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing seemed to distract Woods, who remained the man to
beat. His birdie at No. 18 Friday was special, when he hit an
impressive bunker shot from a buried lie that cleared a high ridge
and settled 15 feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' lie in the bunker was so bad, and the ridge was so steep,
that he considered hitting out of the bunker sideways. But after
his skillful bunker shot, Woods ended the day by making his putt to
take the outright lead over Dunlap, who was already in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend should be intense. But once again, Woods is the man
to catch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
