<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED BULLET WILL MISS A DIMINISHED TRAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ After reeling off their respective
victories in the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness in May, Fusaichi
Pegasus and Red Bullet were being counted on by many to help
reinvigorate the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Now, neither colt will run in the summer's biggest race for
3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Orseno, who trains Red Bullet, announced Friday that he
would hold his colt out of next Saturday's Travers Stakes here
because of the lingering effects of the same viral infection that
caused Red Bullet to skip the Haskell at Monmouth on Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus finally back in
training but still having yet to race since losing the Preakness,
the Travers, Saratoga's signature race, is without the two biggest
3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing needed a horse like Red Bullet and a horse like
Fusaichi Pegasus to run against each other,'' Orseno said Friday.
``It's good for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   What has not been good for the game is the prolonged absence of
either, much less both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' Orseno said, ``because I think the Travers
needs a big name.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the race known as the Midsummer Derby will feature a
field of nine less distinguished colts, led by the surprise Belmont
winner Commendable, who finished last in the Dwyer and second to
last in the Haskell his last two times out. Also missing will be
Graeme Hall, the upset winner of the Jim Dandy last month at
Saratoga. His trainer, Todd Pletcher, said Friday that the horse
had sustained a hairline fracture of his left knee during that
race.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Red Bullet and Fusaichi Pegasus keep missing each
other, as a once-budding rivalry has all but fizzled. The colts
have raced head-to-head only twice, with Fusaichi Pegasus winning
the Wood at Aqueduct before Red Bullet returned the favor, and
dashed Fusaichi Pegasus' Triple Crown hopes, in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, who was syndicated for a reported $60 million
last weekend, began working out again in Southern California this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet last raced on July 9 at Belmont, where he finished
third in the Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cautious approach, Orseno and the colt's owner, Frank
Stronach, had held Red Bullet out of both the Kentucky Derby and
the Belmont, hoping not to overtax the horse. But Friday, Orseno
conceded that the colt ``seems to come up with excuse after
excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least there's next year. Orseno said Friday that Stronach
was committed to racing Red Bullet as a 4-year-old. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
