<HEADLINE>
GORE'S SPEECH SATISFIES HIS SUPPORTERS IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add 2nd `n' to Georgianna in 7th graf.)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPLEWOOD, N.J. _ As the confetti fell and the delegates
thundered in Los Angeles Thursday night, there was a far more
modest eruption of glee at the Fabrizio home here, where three
generations of women were watching Al Gore's long-awaited televised
pitch to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore promised that his administration would serve the
people, not the powerful, Lois Corcoran, 39, just home from her
nursing job, whooped along with the ecstatic throng at the Staples
Center. Her daughter, Amanda Orem, 18, who will vote for the first
time this year, cheered, as well.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of doubting Gore and his ability to wow a crowd,
Orem and her mother said they were pleased by his speech _ and
relieved. ``I was kind of worried he'd be a dud, but he came off
great,'' said Orem, a sophomore at the College of New Jersey who is
a registered independent. ``His words seemed heartfelt. As a
struggling middle-class family, we felt like he was talking to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's presidential coming out Thursday night may not have won
over any rock-ribbed Republicans, but interviews with New Jersey
voters found that he had carried enough zest to turn them, at
least, from tepid supporters into veritable stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   Until Gore mounted the stage, many Democrats and independents
spoke of the vice president as if he were a kindly, if somewhat
insufferable, uncle. ``I wish he wasn't so stiff and didn't seem so
distant,'' said Jo Allen Henry, 44, a fourth-grade teacher from
Plainfield, voicing a common refrain. ``He needs to be more
lively.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Davis did not look entirely mesmerized as he sat in his
living room watching Gore jab the air with his hands. Still, at
least he did not join his wife, who dozed through the entire
52-minute speech. ``Obviously Gore doesn't compare to Clinton, but
he was much more dynamic than I expected,'' said Davis, 36, a
medical recruiter from Bloomfield. ``There were a couple of times
where he threw in some fake laughter, but everyone does it. Except
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Gore is succeeding in crafting an
identity separate from that of his charismatic boss. After watching
him speak, Georgianna Walsh, 55, an elementary school teacher from
Montville, said she was satisfied that he would be his own man. But
most of all, she thought he had shown Americans that he would spare
them from the indignities of the Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said that unlike the president, whom she called a
disappointment, Gore seemed ``wholesome and honest.'' ``We've been
through enough,'' she said. ``You can't imagine what it's like to
have a bunch of fifth-graders asking you about the cigar and the
blue dress.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Walsh has been sold, her husband, Mike, has not. A
construction worker, union loyalist and National Rifle Association
member, Mike Walsh, 55, is a registered Democrat who usually
hopscotches his way through a ballot without regard to party
affiliations. He voted for Ronald Reagan and George Bush, but he
also voted for Clinton the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what he termed a decent performance by the vice
president, Walsh said he had not been entirely impressed by Gore.
``I still might pick Bush or even Ralph Nader,'' he said. ``We'll
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many voters seemed swept up by the news media's endless
dissection of Gore's public persona and his lack of razzle-dazzle,
others were more focused on his politics and his positions. Orem,
who opposes the death penalty and supports gay marriage and
abortion rights, said there was no way she could vote for Gov.
George W. Bush. She is not thrilled by Gore's support for capital
punishment, but she said she appreciated his defiant words on Roe
v. Wade; his reference to Matthew Shepard, the young gay man who
died after being beaten in Wyoming in 1998; and his promise to make
college tuition tax- deductible.
</P>
<P>
   In a swing state like New Jersey, where half the voters are
independents and recent polls show the two candidates to be neck
and neck, pulling in voters like Orem will be critical. But in his
effort to play to the middle and the left, Gore runs the risk of
turning off voters like Mike Walsh, who sees Gore as too liberal.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, die-hard progressives like Steven Cherry, 44, of
Wayne, said that Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman, were too conservative. Despite the vice president's
populist proposals for working-class America and Lieberman's
efforts to recast his positions on affirmative action, Cherry was
not swayed. ``Lieberman is too moralistic and Gore doesn't have any
moral fiber,'' said Cherry, who edits engineering publications on
the Internet. ``I'll vote for them, but I'll be holding my nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Allen Henry, who is black, complained that the Democrats were
not doing enough to ease racism, joblessness and the despair in her
community. ``Everyone keeps talking about this great era of
prosperity, but in the black community, you just don't see it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any thoughts Henry had of voting for Bush were vanquished
as she watched the Republican National Convention, with its
strategic splashes of minority color. ``I found their convention
scary,'' she said. ``But on the other hand, I feel like the
Democratic Party takes the black vote for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, she will swallow her cynicism, vote for
Gore and hope for the best. ``I liked a lot of what he said,
especially on education and campaign finance reform,'' she said,
``but I've seen too many candidates make promises they don't
keep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
