<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-DEMS-L.A.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION AND THE CHANGING FACE OF LOS
ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
   (CHANGES ``of the old'' to ``powerful'' in 7th graf)  
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For Democrats this week, a flood of nostalgia
evoked a bygone time in politics when Lew Wasserman, head of MCA,
Frank Sinatra and other figures in the old Hollywood establishment
hobnobbed at the 1960 convention with John F. Kennedy. Back then,
the entertainment industry supplied the glamour for a political
party trying to look hip and committed. But the real power in Los
Angeles resided elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The convention this week showed how the entertainment industry
has moved from the gilt-edged periphery of the Democratic Party to
its financial and cultural center. For Los Angeles that transition
has come with a striking geographical twist. Forty years ago the
power center was downtown. This Democratic convention, though it
took place downtown, reflected how much the center of power has
shifted to the city's west side, where the entertainment and
fashion industries are rooted.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ronald Reagan was a son of Hollywood, he had no interest
in engineering such a transition when he ran for president in 1980.
Reagan's financial backers were not from show business, but from
the other Los Angeles business establishment _ men like Justin
Dart, Holmes Tuttle, Henry Salvatori and Alfred Bloomingdale. Many
of them had earlier recruited Reagan to run for governor after
making fortunes in the oil, aerospace and real estate industries.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1960 convention the new and largely Jewish Democratic
political establishment on the west side and the San Fernando
Valley was beginning to hit its stride. But it was a time when
Jews, blacks and other minorities were still excluded from the
California Club, the Jonathan Club, the Los Angeles Country Club
and other precincts where Los Angeles' movers and shakers virtually
ran the town. Indeed the downtown and west side establishments when
I was growing up here hardly even knew each other.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The Powers That Be,'' David Halberstam spoke of
the time in the 1960s when Dorothy Chandler, doyenne of the family
that owned The Los Angeles Times, then a conservative Republican
paper that Jews looked on with disapproval, tried to bridge the gap
between downtown and West Los Angeles. She realized that to raise
money to save the old Hollywood Bowl and build a new music center,
she had to go where the money was, to men like Wasserman of MCA and
to Paul Ziffren, the top lawyer in west Los Angeles and a stalwart
of the Democratic Party. Chandler, Halberstam wrote, ``knew what
was happening in the world of the arts, and there the changes were
taking place much faster than they did in the world of the
California Club.''
</P>
<P>
   The coming together of new and old money occurred so fast that
by the 1980s, when the Reagan team reached its zenith of power in
the nation, the old guard was becoming increasingly irrelevant in
its own home town. Mayor Tom Bradley, an African-American, had put
together his own coalition of minorities, Jews and moderate
business leaders. He barred city officials from attending meetings
in the California Club and even got an ordinance passed banning
discrimination in any private club where business is conducted.
Mayor Richard Riordan, a Republican, has kept the Bradley coalition
going and tried to expand it.
</P>
<P>
   Today the old-line conservative Republican business
establishment has largely disappeared from view. Many powerful
banks and financial businesses have died or been bought by
outsiders, just as The Los Angeles Times has been. The oil and
aerospace industries are ailing, and the Mojave Desert to the north
of the city, where the stealth bomber was tested and the space
shuttle still lands, is now being torn up for residential
communities by developers like Eli Broad, the tycoon from the west
side who is a close supporter of Riordan and was instrumental in
bringing the Democrats to town this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The exciting thing about Los Angeles now is the emergence of new
elites, most notably in the Asian and Hispanic communities. Instead
of being dominated by a handful of wealthy barons, it is a city
laced with entrepreneurs striving to reinvent the city. The next
mayor could be either Assemblyman Antonio Villaraigosa or Rep.
Xavier Becerra, two rival leaders of the Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   The new concern in Los Angeles is that it has lost its cohesion
and sense of purpose provided by the old elite. Even the
entertainment industry has fragmented into dozens of power centers
outside the shadow of giants like Wasserman. Some fear the loss of
support of the city's central cultural institutions. Others worry
that without a new identity, places like the San Fernando Valley
and the harbor district to the south may secede. For anyone
fascinated by how the city has changed from 1960 to now, what it
will be like in 2020 is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly a different city today, but you wouldn't
expect it to be the same,'' says Betsy Bloomingdale, the widow of
one of the pillars of the old Reagan inner circle. ``You've got to
go forward or you die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
