<DOCNO> NYT20000818.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; kan-z
r n BC-DIAL-KAN &LR;      08-18 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAL-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Gore speech gets mostly positive results in reaction test  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   LOS ANGELES _ In a cavernous
television studio, parked in rows of folding chairs and clutching
pager-size gadgets each topped with a single dial, three dozen
voters embody the pulse of America's undecideds.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On two televisions in front of them, Vice President Al Gore is
declaring that ``I stand here tonight as my own man,'' and most of
them are lapping it up.
</P>
<P>
   They are making $350 each for four evenings of watching the
tube. They have strict orders to turn their dials clockwise when
they like what they hear, back when they are displeased.
</P>
<P>
   Their composite scores _ split into three groups to represent
those leaning Republican, those leaning Democrat and those who are
independents _ chart three lines across a television monitor they
cannot see. A neutral score is 50. One hundred means they love what
they hear. Zero means they hate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have cut the welfare roles in half and moved millions into
good jobs,'' Gore says.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' reaction leaps to the mid-80s, the independents
to 70, and even the Republicans inch up to 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just wrong for seniors to have to choose between food and
medicine while the big drug companies run up record profits,'' the
vice president tells his convention, the nation and this collection
of Southern Californians.
</P>
<P>
   The lines go up again _ the Democrats to 90, the independents
past 70, and the Republicans into the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore declares support for affirmative action and promises
an end to racial profiling, the lines go their separate ways.
Democrats top 90. After his story about a family advised to give up
a son for adoption because an HMO would not pay for the nursing he
needed, one woman broke down in tears. Half the group later
confessed to becoming teary-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Luntz, the boyish, 30-something polling guru running the
focus group for MSNBC-TV, has moderated more than 500 such
gatherings. Rarely have people so adored what they heard, the
longtime Republican pollster says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This'll move people,'' he whispers out of earshot from his
political guinea pigs. It will win over a sizable lump of voters
the way George W. Bush's acceptance speech did at the Republican
convention two weeks earlier, Luntz says. Bush hit nearly the same
highs, according to a similar Luntz dial-a-pulse group assembled in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But the high scores measure the responses of just 36 persons in
a country where more than 100 million vote. And polling
professionals note that results of a national telephone poll reach
a reasonable margin of error only when about 1,000 randomly chosen
folks have been surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz found these Southern Californians by combing through voter
registration rolls and by telephoning hundreds of people, searching
for those who had yet to make up their minds. From there his staff
attracted a fraction willing to share their feelings for some cash
and for the chance to appear on MSNBC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that this group and the one in Philadelphia
could have regional biases.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to say that a traditional telephone poll is a like a
table of contents and that ``dial groups'' like this fill out the
chapters. In general, though, pollsters warn that such focus groups
are far from science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing it gives you is real-time response to what
people think as they're watching the speech,'' said Charles
Franklin, a specialist in public opinion, at the University of
Wisconsin-Madison. ``You can see what these 36 people responded to.
That's fine. But by definition, those people can't be
representative of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Neil Newhouse took Luntz to his first focus
group years ago, before Luntz helped the GOP craft its ``Contract
with America'' and worked for Reform Party founder Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   The groups do far better at testing a winning phrase than
figuring out what direction an election is heading, Newhouse said.
``It's not science, but it's not at all worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's camp uses the technique. Gore meets almost every morning
with pollster Harrison Hickman to learn what focus groups had to
say the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the currency of the dial group that rated Gore, Luntz
said the Democrat could not have expected better.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the speech, the group members' average prediction of
how much they will like it scores 62 on Luntz's dials. Afterward
they rate it 80. ``This is incredible,'' Luntz says when told of
their review.
</P>
<P>
   Later he declares to his cable audience that Gore has belted a
``home run. No doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Between speeches throughout the week, Luntz administers a sort
of oral inkblot test to the ostensibly undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I need you to tell me one word or short phrase you think
of to describe George W. Bush,'' Luntz commands and then begins
pointing to one voter after the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conniving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich and powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very civil...''
</P>
<P>
   After polling the group on that question, Luntz says: ``Now
describe Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trustworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Negative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A politician above all else...''
</P>
<P>
   When Hillary Rodham Clinton spoke Monday night, the scores
regularly scaled toward 80 and even 90 when she called for
increased adoption rates, a higher minimum wage and improving
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not beating up on Republicans,'' Luntz observed. ``The
voters want these guys to shut up about the other guy and tell us
what you'll do....This is a very smart speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, both vice presidential candidates scored lower in
their speeches, especially when criticizing their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton followed, the scores were especially high
when he talked about the spunk in America's new economy and a need
for sturdier gun control and when he cracked that Harry Truman was
right when he said, ``If you want to live like a Republican, you
should vote for the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Clinton praised his wife, the scores tumbled. The
voters in this laboratory said it only made them think of his
affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even the Republican dialers expressed gratitude toward
Clinton, and to a lesser extent toward Gore, for the country's
booming economy. And although many held doubts before his speech
about Gore's ability to lead, all but a handful said they saw him
as a dynamic man afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost brought me to tears,'' said Mike Evans, a
32-year-old carpenter. ``He convinced me he's going to work hard to
help regular people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the man,'' said Diana Cuevas, a 40-year-old who
voted for Clinton in 1996 but who was unsure about Gore until
Thursday night. ``I'd like to see him be president for two terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, some Republicans were won over. Gore spoke about paying
teachers more. That made a skeptical Paula Schoppe, the daughter of
two educators, a believer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see me changing my mind away from him now,'' said the
29-year-old personal trainer. ``I'm going to call my parents and
try to get them to vote for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not unanimous. Pretty words delivered with enthusiasm
made one 62-year-old Republican think Gore was merely well-coached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Santa Claus tonight,'' he said. ``He promised the world
but didn't say how he'd pay for it.'' The focus group was made up
mostly of lemmings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His skepticism was shared by Democrat Melinda Moore, a
34-year-old secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said everything Clinton did eight years ago,'' she said.
``He told everybody want they wanted to hear, but he won't follow
through.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, more than two-thirds were in Gore's camp.
Seven who started the week leaning toward Bush said they were solid
Gore backers now.
</P>
<P>
   Will that show up on the national scene?
</P>
<P>
   Don't bank on it. For starters, few Americans watch a convention
with the motivation of this group. They read newspapers, watch
television and talk with friends about the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If minds were changed, they can be changed again. More than two
months of political commercials, debates and campaign news
developments are yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   A focus group can focus on only so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just more art in the interpretation than something you
can take to the bank,'' Newhouse said. ``But it can tell you what
works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
