<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GATLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVA GATLING, 87, ART CURATOR, LED THE HECKSCHER MUSEUM  
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Va., Ala., N.C., Mich., Iowa)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eva Gatling, an art historian and curator who for many years was
the director of the Heckscher Museum in Huntington, N.Y., died on
Tuesday in Virginia Beach, Va., where she had lived in recent
years. She was 87.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the museums in America are small,'' Gatling
once wrote. ``They have a potential for greatness that often
escapes public attention.'' As head of the Heckscher from 1962 to
1978, she turned it into a valuable suburban museum.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald G. Pisano, an art curator, said, ``She had an unerring
eye for art, and was responsible for enriching the Heckscher
collection with significant acquisitions, and elevating its
reputation to that of one of the finest regional museums in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   August Heckscher founded the museum in 1920. In the 1950s it
showed works from its permanent collection on a limited schedule.
Under Gatling's leadership, the museum expanded the collection and
held four or five major exhibitions each year. She rediscovered the
work of the painter Helen Torr and was instrumental in acquiring
many paintings by Arthur Dove, Torr's husband. George Grosz's
``Eclipse of the Sun'' became the centerpiece of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Ingersoll Gatling was born in Mobile, Ala., and graduated
from the University of Alabama and Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the Heckscher, she was director of exhibitions at
Duke University, curator at the Museum of the Cranbrook Academy of
Art in Bloomfield Hills, Mich., and assistant director of the Des
Moines Art Center in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   When Gatling retired, the Heckscher honored her with an
exhibition, ``The Art of the Director: Eva Gatling's 15 Years at
the Heckscher Museum.'' In 1996, another exhibition, ``A Founding
Director's Legacy,'' was a tribute to her.
</P>
<P>
   There are no immediate survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
