r f BC-CHURCH-KAN &LR;      08-18 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Mixing religion and investing  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ On any given
weekend 5,000 people _ out of a membership of 8,000 adults and
children _ stream into the United Methodist Church of the
Resurrection in Leawood, Kan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Founded a decade ago in a Kansas City funeral home, the church
is one of the fastest-growing in United Methodist history, its
membership exploding by 50 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years ago it dedicated a 1,700-seat sanctuary at
its 137th Street and Roe Avenue location. Now the church plans to
break ground in 2002 for a sanctuary seating from 5,000 to 7,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the Rev. Adam Hamilton, its 36-year-old senior pastor,
United Methodist has never done things by the book, although it
manifestly takes its inspiration from the Book.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a pastor who's extremely gifted and has an immense
desire of what this megachurch can and should become,'' said member
Ben Craig, chairman of Metcalf Bank and a longtime Johnson County,
Kan., booster. ``He is the driving force _ no ifs, ands or buts.
He's absolutely fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   So fearless, in fact, that when the church decided to buy 47
acres of bean fields immediately north of 44 acres it bought in
1997, it came up with a rather unorthodox way to finance the
purchase: selling investment units in a company it formed to
develop the property.
</P>
<P>
   The company, COR Development LLC, recently filed a registration
statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission proposing to
raise $16 million through the sale of 1.6 million units _ akin to
shares of stock _ for $10 apiece. Church members are expected to be
the main purchasers of the units, which will be sold in minimum
lots of 100.
</P>
<P>
   Church members ``approved the concept even though it's kind of
way out there,'' Hamilton said, quickly adding: ``I personally have
no interest in being a commercial real estate mogul. It's just a
means to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   That end is severalfold: to accommodate the church's need for
additional space, to give it much-needed parking, to control
development around the church and to generate a profit for the
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Because the church would get less than a third of the land and
the rest would be developed commercially, COR Development and the
investors would stand to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The Leawood church is not the first United Methodist church to
embark on a commercial venture. Decades ago the First United
Methodist Church of Chicago erected a 21-story high-rise in that
city's downtown. The church occupies the first four floors and
leases most of the rest to lawyers and other commercial tenants.
</P>
<P>
   SEC officials, however, said they could not recall any
church-affiliated organization filing a registration statement with
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offhand we can't come up with any that has filed,'' said SEC
press officer Carol Patterson, who has been with the agency 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC filing was triggered by the Leawood church's decision to
make the investment units available to ``nonaccredited'' investors,
whose annual incomes or net worths fall beneath a certain
threshold. The minimum investment in COR Development is $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started out, we were asking people to give a lot more
than $1,000,'' said church member Greg Walton, owner of Walton
Construction Co. and one of the prime movers behind the project.
``But people who were less well off said, `Hey, don't leave us
out,' and we decided to open it up.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, close to 750 congregants have made financial commitments
ranging from $1,000 to $600,000. ``People believe that much in Adam
and his vision,'' Walton said.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial venture will not jeopardize the church's
tax-exempt status, because COR Development and the church are
separate entities. Though church members will make up most or all
of COR's investors, and church members will volunteer their time to
run the business, the church itself will not be an investor in COR.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's no legal relationship between the two, it's just a
normal LLC (limited liability company) subject to federal taxes,''
said tax lawyer Stanley Weiner of Shook, Hardy &AMP; Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The church decided to go the investment route because
congregation members had already pledged money for the 1,700-seat
sanctuary and the 44-acre parcel just a few years ago. Asking them
to pledge an additional $12 million _ the approximate cost of the
proposed purchase at $250,000 per acre _ would have been too much,
Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   The church does not need all 47 acres that will be acquired, but
the property's owner _ L&AMP;F Land Co., a partnership managed by
developer Harlan Laner _ had plans to put up a big-box retailer
just north of the church. That would have created parking problems
on Sundays, when United Methodist holds no fewer than five
services. (Hamilton preaches at all five, as well as one the night
before.)
</P>
<P>
   So Hamilton and some church members, including Walton and
developers Estel Hipp and Dennis Eskie, began mulling over the idea
of setting up a for-profit venture to buy all the land. The venture
would donate 15 acres to the church _ which investors could deduct
as a charitable contribution _ for the new sanctuary and an exit to
135th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the land, they figured, could be developed
commercially: retail shops facing 135th Street and office space
between the shops and the new sanctuary. The church could share
parking with the office buildings on Sundays, when they were little
used. And COR Development, and its investors, could make money by
leasing the property and, eventually, selling the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In short, a chance for investors to do well by doing good.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the 20 acres it acquired before it moved to its
current location in 1995, and the 44 it acquired in 1997, the 47
acres COR Development proposes to buy will give the church control
of more than 100 acres. That is 100-plus acres of prime space in
the heart of one of the area's fastest growing commercial
corridors. The area sits immediately east of the LionsGate
residential development, which includes a Jack Nicklaus-designed
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like a lot of land, said Hamilton, but other
megachurches around the country have gobbled up even more. Hamilton
visited more than 20 such churches on a summer sabbatical in 1998
and found that ``once you get 10,000 Sunday worshippers'' _ the
number United Methodist projects it will have in a few years _
``all of them were looking at 80, 100, 120 acres,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not the stuff that excites me. This is a means to
an end. And the end is to have enough space for ministries that can
happen here in the future. The end is the opportunity to reach
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
