<SLUG> BC-MCDONALDS-BAN0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge won't give this guy a break today
 &HT;    By John Lynch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Did someone say McDonald's?
</P>
<P>
   The golden arches are off the menu for a 21-year-old Longview
man Friday after he admitted to scuffling with a police officer.
Judge David Brabham told Quintal Miller that if he goes to a
McDonald's restaurant, he faces prison time.
</P>
<P>
   Brabham ordered Miller to stay out of the restaurants after he
pleaded guilty to assault on a public servant in the 188th District
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all McDonald's,'' Brabham said as he sentenced Miller
to eight years in prison for the third-degree felony assault April
23 on Longview police Sgt. Sean Pendleton. Brabham suspended the
prison time to five years of probation, plus a $100 fine, anger
management counseling and 240 hours of community service. Miller's
McDonald's ban is for the duration of his probation.
</P>
<P>
   Miller also must pay at least $298 in restitution, which
includes the officer's medical bills, the judge ordered. Miller
knocked Pendleton down and scuffled with him during a disturbance
at the McDonald's Family Restaurant at in Longview.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant, who suffered minor injuries in the scuffle, agreed
that the sentence is appropriate punishment for the man, said Gregg
County Assistant District Attorney Joe Black, who prosecuted the
case. Miller could have been sentenced to between two and 10 years
in prison for the assault.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was one of several people on the restaurant grounds to
use a pay phone who got into an argument with restaurant security
guards, Black said. Pendleton was called to quell the disturbance,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs appeared to be at the root of Miller's problems, the man
revealed during questioning by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you feel like you have a drug problem, Mr. Miller?''
Brabham asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' Miller replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize, if you don't beat your drug problem, you won't
complete probation,'' the judge said later.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he had skipped an earlier treatment program because
he couldn't get a ride, but promised to comply with the judge's
order for continued drug testing during his probation even if he
had to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
