FOUR KILLED IN MEXICAN POLITICAL PROTESTS   (SUBS to update number
of dead in 1st, 3rd grafs) 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMALHUACAN, Mexico _ At least four people were killed and
dozens wounded Friday as political protests swept across Mexico
state, shattering the euphoria from last month's elections and
dashing hopes for a peaceful political transition.
</P>
<P>
   The protests erupted on Thursday in cities like Ecatepec and
towns like Huixquilucan as local party leaders in Mexico's most
populous state clashed during ceremonies to swear in new mayors and
town councils. But the worst demonstrations occurred Friday in this
town 20 miles east of Mexico City between rival factions of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   As supporters of the PRI mayor-elect, Jesus Tolentino Roman,
gathered in the main plaza here for the ceremony, shots rang out.
The state attorney general reported that at least four people had
been killed and 40 others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The violence, according to reports by witnesses, was started by
armed followers of a local political boss, Guadalupe Buendia, who
has coerced politicians in Chimalhuacan for years in support of the
PRI. But last year when her choice for mayor lost in the PRI
primary, Buendia turned against her party, leading protests that
turned into riots outside the town hall.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general said a warrant had been issued for
the arrest of Buendia.
</P>
</TEXT>
