<SLUG> BC-VACCINE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Flu vaccine may be in short supply this fall, government warns  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. - Health
departments throughout the country are being warned that flu
vaccine may be in short supply this fall _ a warning that comes as
some officials worry that a major outbreak is due.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta say a shortage of vaccine is possible because it has proved
unusually difficult to produce and because production by two of the
four suppliers was delayed after the Food and Drug Administration
ordered plant renovations to meet federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   Health departments are expected to know by September whether
there will be a shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get all of our information from the CDC, and what they are
telling us is that we should expect delays and a possible shortage
of flu vaccines,'' said Sue Denny, public information and education
coordinator for the Missouri Department of Health's immunization
program.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Hanley, director of health education for Johnson
County, Kan., said: ``We don't want to panic people. But we want to
give John Q. Public a heads-up that this may be a problem this flu
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal centers are uncertain how much of the vaccine will
be produced this year. Last year as many as 85 million doses were
produced for distribution in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers are having a difficult time producing one of three
strains of the flu virus needed to create this year's vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Because viruses are constantly changing, the strains used in the
vaccine must be updated each year. The World Health Organization
recommends which strains to include, based on the most prevalent
varieties from last year's flu season in the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   From January through March of each year, U.S. public health
officials select the virus strains for the vaccine for the United
States for the upcoming fall.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's vaccine, two new strains, the
A-Panama/2007/99-like (H3N2) and the A-New Caledonia/20/99-like
(H1N1), were recommended for inclusion. The third strain,
B-Yamanashi/166/98-like virus, is unchanged from last year's
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the companies growing the Panama strain are
having difficulties. They have discovered that it is harder to grow
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Food and Drug Administration has cited two of the four
companies _ Parkedale Pharmaceuticals of Rochester, Mich., and
Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories of Marietta, Pa. _ for problems.
According to the federal centers' Web site, both manufacturers
indicated they would correct the problems.
</P>
<P>
   The other two manufacturers are Aventis Pasteur of Swiftwater,
Pa., and Medeva Pharma Ltd., in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the vaccine could increase this year because the
centers had lowered the recommended age for the flu vaccination to
50 from 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are backing away from that recommendation now because of
the potential shortage,'' said Denny of the Missouri Health
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Denny said, the federal centers recommend that people in
high-risk groups and those older than 65 should get the vaccine.
Also, health care workers and people who take care of high-risk
groups should be immunized.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, most people should not get their vaccines until late
October or early November to make sure that they are still immune
to the viruses in March.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials are being urged to proceed as normal with
immunizations for the elderly and others who are at risk, including
people with chronic illnesses such as asthma, diabetes and
respiratory conditions.
</P>
<P>
   According to American Health Line, researchers at six hospitals
are testing the effectiveness and safety of using half-doses of the
vaccine as a way to stretch supplies. Results of the study are not
expected until October.
</P>
<P>
   How big the problem is and how severe the winter flu bug will be
are still wild-card factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems the flu season starts earlier and earlier each
year,'' said Hanley of Johnson County. Last year the first
confirmed case of flu in the county came in early December.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, major flu epidemics hit about every 30 years, said
Bill Schmidt, administrator of the Jackson County Health
Department. The last one came in 1970, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you believe in history, we are probably due to have
another flu epidemic pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what health officials thought in 1999, and they made an
all-out effort to pump up education campaigns to increase the
number of people receiving flu shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we thought it was our time. But since the flu didn't
hit big, it increases the likelihood that something will happen
this year,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, health departments are being urged to develop
contingency plans that put at-risk populations at the top of
priority lists for vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is: People should stay tuned and be alert and
stay away from people with respiratory symptoms,'' said Hanley.
``Wash your hands, cover your mouth, and a lot of these problems
can be avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt is anxious to get more information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to make people paranoid,'' he said. ``Life has
to go on. But we do have to give people a warning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-00 2336EDT &QL; 
