<SLUG> BC-NJ-COP-SHOOTING-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY OFFICER KILLS SUSPECTS IN EXCHANGE OF GUNFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   By GEORGE JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Jersey police officer shot and killed a man before dawn
Friday after the man reportedly fired a gun at him in a wooded area
of Hunterdon County, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred while dozens of police officers were
searching the woods for the suspect, one of five men who had fled
from a Clinton police officer who had stopped their car for a motor
vehicle violation. Two men in the car reportedly fired shots at the
officer, the police said, and the officer returned fire, and all
then got out of the car and fled the scene on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The car, a Plymouth Horizon with Pennsylvania license plates,
was stopped about 3:40 a.m. on Route 513, south of Interstate 78 in
Franklin Township. The police would not specify the violation that
prompted the officer to stop the car.
</P>
<P>
   None of the police officers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Police would not release the names of anyone involved. They said
they had not yet positively identified the men, but believed that
they were from the Allentown, Pa., area.
</P>
<P>
   After the men fled from the car, the police, using dogs and a
helicopter, searched an area at the juncture of Clinton, Franklin
and Union townships.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter found three of the men in the woods surrounding the
Hunterdon Developmental Center, a 600-patient facility for the
mentally retarded. Officers found the fourth man, the car's driver,
on a road behind a nearby Wal-Mart store.
</P>
<P>
   But the fifth man eluded capture until shortly before 6:30 a.m.
As dawn was breaking, the helicopter reported spotting the suspect
in the woods in Union Township, about an eighth of a mile from the
abandoned car.
</P>
<P>
   There the suspect was confronted by an officer from the New
Jersey Department of Human Services assigned to the Hagedorn
Gero-Psychiatric Hospital in nearby Glen Gardner. The officer
called for the suspect to surrender, the police said, but he
instead fired several shots at the officer.
</P>
<P>
   The officer returned fire, the police said, striking the man. He
was pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said it was not clear Friday night whether the
dead man was one of those suspected of firing on the Clinton police
officer who had stopped the car.
</P>
<P>
   Police recovered one gun, said John Hagerty, a spokesman for the
state police, but he said he could not reveal the make of the
weapon or the number of shots exchanged, because the investigation
was continuing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Police said that when the men's car was stopped, as it entered
Franklin Township, the Clinton officer asked the driver for his
license and registration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young man was unable to produce any identification, so the
police officer asked him to get out of the car and then moved
forward with a pat-down search for safety,'' Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was at this point where the passenger jumped out and
started to fire,'' Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   As the man ran away, Hagerty said, the driver, who had been
facing the car, backed up suddenly and knocked the officer to the
ground. He also shot at the officer before fleeing, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police officer returns fire toward the passenger and the
driver,'' Hagerty said. ``At the same time, the other three people
get out and they start running.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
