<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-PRIVATIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC GETS 14 PROPOSALS TO PRIVATIZE ITS FAILING SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mich., Pa., Mass.)   By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fourteen companies and nonprofit organizations from
around the country have submitted proposals to manage some of the
worst-performing New York City schools under a privatization plan
outlined last month by Schools Chancellor Harold Levy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the submissions received by Friday's deadline was a
sweeping proposal by Edison Schools, the Manhattan company that is
the country's largest commercial manager of public schools, to take
over 45 low-performing elementary and middle schools by the fall of
2003. Under the plan, Edison would take over 12 elementary schools
in September 2001 and the remainder only if students at the initial
12 schools outperformed their peers at similar schools on
standardized tests by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Edison's proposal was submitted, the program
outlined by Levy and approved by the Board of Education had the
potential to be one of the country's largest educational
privatization efforts. In his plan, Levy appeared to be addressing
two constituencies: minority families and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the schools eligible for privatization under Levy's plan
are in neighborhoods with large black and Hispanic populations;
nationwide, minorities have supported charter schools and other
alternatives to public schools. Giuliani set aside $60.8 million of
the Board of Education's $11 billion budget for the current fiscal
year to pay for private management of some of the worst-performing
city schools.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Edison, seven other organizations in New York
state submitted proposals, including Victory Schools, a Manhattan
company that this fall will run three charter schools in New York
City and on Long Island, and Boys Harbor Inc., a nonprofit Harlem
group that last year tried and failed to secure a charter school
license from state authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Six groups from outside the state made bids as well, including
National Heritage Academies, a Grand Rapids, Mich., company that
will begin operating a charter school in Rochester this fall.
National Heritage has attracted criticism for its plan to make
students aware of _ but not teach, the company insists _
creationism and other theories that company officials say are
alternatives to the theory of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other companies that submitted proposals were Nobel
Learning Communities of Media, Pa., and Advantage Schools of
Boston, which recently gave up management of the troubled New
Covenant Charter School in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crowe, a spokeswoman for the New York City Board of
Education, said board officials would begin reviewing the
submissions this weekend to see if they fulfilled the board's
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Under Levy's plan, some of the roughly 50 struggling schools
that are both on the state's list of ``schools under registration
review'' and are part of the special Chancellor's District would be
converted into charter schools beginning in the fall of 2001.
Though the schools would still receive money from the city and
state, their conversion to charter status would free them of many
state and city regulations and allow their managers to renegotiate
some union contracts. Last month, board officials said they
expected five to seven schools to be privatized in the program's
first year, although one official said as many as 20 could be
converted.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proposals received Friday were quite modest. Victory
Schools, for example, proposed converting and managing one or two
schools, and Advantage Schools requested management of two schools.
By contrast, beginning this fall, Edison will manage more than 100
schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Under its proposal, Edison would invest $80 million in New
York's program, recruit 1,000 highly qualified teachers, distribute
about 25,000 IBM computers to teachers and students, and start a
$50 million philanthropic campaign to support its schools, company
officials said Friday. They also suggested a collaboration with the
Board of Education to bring one of Edison's planned Teacher
Colleges to New York City. In addition, Edison said it wanted to
work with the city teachers' union, the United Federation of
Teachers, in developing the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Benno Schmidt, the chairman of Edison, said he believes that in
order to determine whether this type of experiment will work, many
schools must be privatized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
