<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-YANKEES-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      08-18 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEES-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES LOSE TO ANGELS, 9-8 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Darin Erstad waded through teammates wanting to
congratulate him in the Anaheim dugout after his game-saving catch
in the bottom of the 10th inning Friday night at Yankee Stadium,
and his expression never changed before he reached the bat rack. He
had business to tend to in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad followed his spectacular catch with a home run in the
11th against the Yankees' Mike Stanton, capping a wild comeback
victory by the Angels in which the Yankees blew a five-run lead in
the ninth and lost, 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Yankees blew a five-run lead in the ninth and
lost was on May 16, 1968, in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led Anaheim, 8-3, into the ninth, with Roger Clemens
working on a complete game and his 258th career victory. But
Clemens allowed back-to-back singles and was relieved by Jeff
Nelson, walking off to a standing ovation, tipping his cap and
raising a gloved hand.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, he had thrown 122 pitches and been charged with
only three runs. But after Nelson retired Adam Kennedy on a fly
out, Nelson walked Kevin Stocker and manager Joe Torre replaced
Nelson with Mariano Rivera, who had converted 10 of his last 11
save chances.
</P>
<P>
   The air of invincibility has not surrounded Rivera this year,
however. One run scored on a fielder's choice, and then Orlando
Palmeiro pulled a double inside first base and down the line. There
were two outs, two on, and Vaughn was coming to the plate as the
tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn fouled Rivera's first pitch off the right toes of the
catcher Jorge Posada, who limped away from the plate and slumped to
the ground, where he remained for a couple of minutes, waiting out
the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Posada stood up, returned to his position, called for a fastball
_ and Vaughn launched a high drive that landed in the right field
stands, sucking all emotion other than disappointment out of Yankee
Stadium. Tie game, on Rivera's fifth blown save of the year; he
converted 45 of 49 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Glenallen Hill, who hit two homers earlier in the game, led off
the Yankees' 10th by topping a slow roller to the left side against
Shigetoshi Hasegawa, and there was no play. Luis Polonia ran for
Hill, and advanced to second on Luis Sojo's bunt. Jose Canseco
batted for Jose Vizcaino and hit a deep fly ball; Polonia tagged up
and moved to third.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter was walked intentionally, and Posada blistered a
drive to left-center that appeared destined for the gap and
game-ending hit. But Erstad charged back and to his left, dived,
stretched his body and back-handed the liner, saving the game.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton relieved Rivera for the 11th, and Erstad drove a high
homer into the first rows of the right field stands, his 21st homer
and 189th hit of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee collapse took the hero's mantle from Hill, who has
been with the Yankees for less than a month, and is already known
to his teammates as something of an eccentric personality. He plays
music loudly _ ``All kinds,'' said Jeter _ and speaks softly. He
wears eye black in night games, and in the day. He dresses
elegantly, but swings his bat viciously, quickly, powerfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Muhammad Ali's left jab,'' said Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there are ways to get him out. He came into this
season with a .271 batting average, striking out an average of once
every four and a half at-bats. But so far, he is dominating
American League pitching.
</P>
<P>
   He would probably not have played Friday night, except for the
fact that he smashed a soaring homer on Thursday against the Angels
and Torre wanted to keep him in the lineup, to stay with a hot
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hill led off the fourth for the Yankees, after Tim Salmon
homered in the top half of the inning for the Angels and reduced
Clemens lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of Hill in the count no balls and one strike, Anaheim's
Ramon Ortiz floated a change-up, a pitch he aimed outside, at the
target set by the catcher Bengie Molina. Ortiz was off target,
however and Molina reached back to retrieve the ball after it
crossed the plate; except it never got to Molina.
</P>
<P>
   Hill jabbed, one side of the ball caved in, and Hill's eighth
homer with the Yankees disappeared over the left field wall, on a
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored once more in the inning. Luis Sojo was on
second and Jose Vizcaino on first and Jeter singled to right. Sojo
turned at third and was held up by Willie Randolph, the Yankees'
third base coach. But Vizcaino, far past second, slipped and fell
when he tried stopping, and soon he was in a rundown.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim third baseman Troy Glaus took a throw and ran
Vizcaino back toward second, where Jeter already was stationed _
and Sojo bolted for home. Inexplicably, the Angel never looked
homeward, and Sojo scored uncontested, giving the Yankees a 5-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the top step of the Anaheim bench, manager Mike Scioscia, who
had seen his team make two brutal base-running mistakes Thursday,
complained with exasperation to Alfredo Griffin, one of his
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels picked at Clemens in the fifth, scoring after Adam
Kennedy and Kevin Stocker opened with singles. But Hill flexed
another muscle in the bottom of the fifth. With two out, Tino
Martinez smacked a single to left. Hill moved slowly to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz threw a fastball. Hill snapped his bat at the ball, that
massive 35-ounce bat. There was a line drive to right and the ball
was quickly gone.
</P>
<P>
   The fans stood and screamed, beckoning for Hill to come out to
take a bow. After a pitch to Sojo, Hill moved onto the top step of
the Yankee dugout and waved his helmet with his right hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
