<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-18 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-MCQUIDDY-AMSOU     08-18 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MCQUIDDY-AMSOUTH-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
  
 INVESTING WITH: DEAN McQUIDDY OF AMSOUTH SMALL CAP FUND  
(For release Sunday, August 20) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE TANNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ In 1983, fresh from the University of
Florida with a finance degree, Dean McQuiddy went to work for
Barnett Banks, then the state's largest bank, as an analyst
recommending stocks to portfolio managers. Soon, he helped create
Barnett's Emerald Small Cap fund, and in 1994 took over management
of the portfolio, consistently outperforming the benchmark Russell
2000 growth index through the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But then Barnett, an old-line Florida bank, was swallowed in a
wave of mergers. First, NationsBank of North Carolina took over
Barnett, and Bank of America later merged with NationsBank.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, McQuiddy and four key members of his Barnett team
turned down offers of NationsBank jobs in Charlotte, N.C., deciding
that it was time to take a risk by opening their own firm, Sawgrass
Asset Management, in Jacksonville, the former home of Barnett. This
summer, Sawgrass hit $1 billion under management, including the
$162 million that McQuiddy manages in AmSouth Small Cap, a growth
fund offered by AmSouth Bancorp in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   In his move from employee to investment entrepreneur, McQuiddy
jettisoned most of his dark bankers' suits in favor of khakis and
short-sleeved golf shirts. More significantly, he and his
colleagues installed networked personal computers with a variety of
professional investment programs to obtain real-time quotations and
analysis. Back at Barnett Bank, when they had to wait their turn
for the mainframe computer, it sometimes took days to get reports.
The ability to upgrade technology without the struggle for
budgetary approval has been liberating. ``We literally were able to
leapfrog a couple of generations in technology,'' McQuiddy said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, McQuiddy, 39, has five computer monitors glowing in his
office, and reports cover his desk and spill over onto chairs and
the floor. Technology is crucial to his quantitatively driven
style. ``We spend a lot of time and effort and brain cells,
tinkering with and improving our modeling system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He started the fund in March 1998. After a slow start, it ranked
39th out of the 266 small-cap growth funds tracked by Lipper Inc.
for the six months ended July 31 of this year, with a return of
15.27 percent, compared with an average of 4.36 percent for the
group.
</P>
<P>
   From its inception until July 31, the fund had an annualized
total return of 10.10 percent, compared with 27.82 percent for the
group. McQuiddy's explanation for the turnabout is his criterion
that a company must be profitable before he will invest in it. Last
year, when stocks of money-losing technology companies were
soaring, momentum players could chalk up gains with timely trades.
But since the luster of the dot-coms has worn off, his conservative
approach has proved sounder.
</P>
<P>
   McQuiddy, working with Patrick Riley and Martin LaPrade, who
were also portfolio managers at Barnett, starts with the 1,400
growth-sector companies in the Russell 2000 and quickly weeds out
any foreign or unprofitable concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Then they apply a series of models to measure companies on three
key factors: earnings momentum, positive changes in analysts'
estimates of future earnings and a value analysis. An exacting
attention to upticks in analysts' estimates is a hallmark of
McQuiddy's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   McQuiddy likes to buy stocks with price-to-earnings ratios of 30
to 40, but he has found high-earning bargains at lower multiples.
Companies are ranked by ratios including price to earnings, price
to book, price to sales and price to cash flow.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The number-crunching typically turns up 150 to 200 stocks, of
which 50 or 60 are selected. ``This is a consistent discipline that
has worked for us over the years _ we don't stray from that,''
McQuiddy said from his office in the booming southern end of
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   When comes the personal touch. McQuiddy, Riley and LaPrade and
other associates read analysts' reports about a company, talk with
analysts, interview company principals, look at the company's
rivals and study profit margins. They focus on companies with high
market share and an ability to defend it with patents, high budgets
for research and development or unique technology _ all to find
companies that are likely to post better-than-expected earnings
that will send their stocks higher.
</P>
<P>
   The fund tends to hold a rising stock six to nine months; after
that, it tends to get out. Turnover averages 150 percent a year.
``That sweet spot is the two or three quarters that the company
does better than the street expects, and the market rewards the
positive surprise,'' McQuiddy said.
</P>
<P>
   Just over half of the fund's holdings are in technology.
McQuiddy likes profitable stocks that feed the backbone of the
Internet, not flashy retail Web stocks. ``I like to use the
analogy, and it's not original with me, that the people who made
money in the gold rush weren't the people who mined for gold,'' he
said. ``It was the people who supplied pickaxes, shovels and
pans.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His behind-the-scenes Internet holdings include Hall, Kinion &AMP;
Associates, a staffing firm in San Francisco that specializes in
engineers, systems analysts and programmers. McQuiddy bought the
stock at $26.70 on May 15, and later added to his holdings, for an
average cost of $30.31. It closed Friday at $39.25. The company's
revenue has been growing 70 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Silicon Valley Bancshares in Santa Clara, Calif.,
the parent of Silicon Valley Bank, a lender to Internet start-ups.
``They take warrants for their services, and a lot of their clients
have gone public or are in the pipeline to go public,'' McQuiddy
said. Earnings this year will double, to $2.40 a share, he
predicted. He bought the stock in April at an average cost of
$33.90 a share. It closed Friday at $53.4375.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McQuiddy doesn't turn his back on low-tech companies. In April,
he bought shares of the Shaw Group, which fabricates piping
primarily for electric generating plants, at an average of $41.31 a
share. Shaw recently scooped up assets of a bankrupt peer operation
and is expected to benefit from the proposed merger of the Entergy
Corp., a Louisiana utility, with the FPL Group of Florida. ``I
don't think the market has yet focused on this,'' McQuiddy said.
The stock, which closed Friday at $44.75, has been selling for less
than 20 times analysts' expected earnings for next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
